<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-10 00:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4911 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BKN-BARKLEY-HNS &LR;      12-10 1100
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-BARKLEY-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JONATHAN FEIGEN  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
BOSTON _ His body couldn't move, but his mind raced. And then it
crawled. But it never rested.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Charles Barkley's friends and family finally left him to his
thoughts, but there were too many to cover in one night. He lay
awake all night, the pain in his heart throbbing worse than his
damaged left knee.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last night was hard,'' Barkley said Thursday. ``After all my
friends left and it was me by myself in the middle of the night, it
was very hard. I didn't sleep at all last night.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, I'm disappointed and frustrated. But last night was
really hard about 3, 4, 5, 6 in the morning. Not much pain.
Obviously I'm in some pain, but the depression No. 1, the
depression of knowing it's over, and the depression of knowing the
next six months I'm going to have of rehabilitation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very sad, and it's hard. I cried for like three hours
straight last night. It's still hard, and I know it's going to get
harder. My heart is broken. My spirit is broken. I can't sit here
and sugarcoat it. I'm just real down and depressed right now. I
know I have to go on. But it's hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Barkley, for so long an irrepressible, jovial, celebrated lover
of life, was sullen on the day after.
</P>
<P>
   He told himself to remember the good times, to focus on 16 years
in the NBA rather than the end. He heard from friends Michael
Jordan and Tiger Woods, from NBA players John Stockton, Karl Malone
and Patrick Ewing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Scottie (Pippen) is on my voice mail,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But no amount of quips or good wishes changed the facts, or his
mood.
</P>
<P>
   Barkley ruptured his left quadriceps tendon in the first quarter
of Wednesday's game in Philadelphia, ending his career where it
began. Surgery is scheduled for Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew it was over immediately,'' Barkley said. ``You could
just look at it. I said, `Ugh.' I thought when it first happened I
had one of those compound fractures, but I knew it was bad.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have not seen the replay. I was thinking about that. I'm not
sure I want to see it. It does me no good.
</P>
<P>
   ``My No. 1 priority now is to rehab. This is an injury that is
really serious. You can't mess around with the rehab. I know for
the next six months I have to dedicate myself totally to that. I
want to be able to do things, normal things. This is a very serious
injury.''
</P>
<P>
   Barkley spoke about the diligence his rehabilitation will
require. But he said the work he must put in would not give him any
thought about playing again. If anything, he said the stunning
events in Philadelphia convinced him the time was right.
</P>
<P>
   ``I stand by what I said last night,'' Barkley said. ``I am a
religious person, even though I might not show it or act like it
all the time. I think the big fella is always protecting me and put
me in situations to be successful. There's no doubt in my mind just
the way everything happened last night.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a really good game in Phoenix last week. I had a really
good game in Houston. They're the last memories of me. I played
good games. Then for it to happen with my mom and grandmother
there, I think it just can't be coincidence the way things
happened.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is profound it started there and ended there.''
</P>
<P>
   Few players have enjoyed the game and NBA life more. But for
Barkley, that made losing it that much more difficult.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing prepares you for retirement,'' he said. ``It's hard.
All those years I thought about retiring, I could never get the
words out. This year, I forced myself to say it because I knew my
game was coming down and it's important for me not to disrespect
the game. It's very important for me to play at a high level.
</P>
<P>
   ``It took me about a week to say those words publicly. I called
all my friends, hoping one of them would say something to talk me
out of it. They all said, `That's a great decision, good luck to
you.' That lets you know they think you should retire too.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to miss the guys. There's nothing like the
fraternity of players,'' Barkley said.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I'm going to miss the fans. Man, the fans are really good.
People judge the fans by one or two bad people. They should not be
judged by that. I met the most unbelievable people in my lifetime.
Some of them I will never forget.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of all, he said, he will miss the games. The public and the
friends will remain. His celebrity will endure, and he will
continue to meet the kind of people he has so enjoyed. But he said
he could never replace the 48 minutes on the court.
</P>
<P>
   ``I started playing basketball when I was 9, and I played almost
every day since then,'' Barkley said. ``One sad thing about being
an athlete, when you retire, you don't play anymore. I'm not one of
those guys (who's) going to join the church league for faded glory.
I know I'm not going to play basketball anymore. That's the thing
I'm probably going to miss the most.''
</P>
<P>
   But Barkley said his career is complete. Even the lack of a
championship that so many may use to temper his accomplishments
does not detract from his happiness with a sweet, 16-year run. Even
his four seasons in Houston, he said, were more than he had hoped.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really enjoyed playing in Houston,'' Barkley said. ``I loved
my coaching staff. They've been terrific. The fans accepted me from
day one. It's just been a blast. I'm glad I got a chance to play
there.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was more, more than I thought it would be. We were older.
We weren't the best. We had one realistic shot at it, the first
year, when Utah beat us in the conference finals. After that, we
were on the downhill of our careers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was more than I expected the way I was appreciated and
respected. It was a unique situation. We had two seven-game series
(when Barkley was with the Phoenix Suns) the years the Rockets won
the championships. They were all-out wars, and I was the villain.
But from the first day I came to Houston, they treated me
unbelievable. That's what I'll remember the most.''
</P>
<P>
   The more he contemplated his career and its turns, the more he
found to remember and to comfort him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basketball has given me everything in the world,'' Barkley
said. ``I'm going to be 37 in a couple of months. I've never had a
real job. I've got great things. I've been all over the world. I
met the most fantastic people.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what I'm going to miss. If I could tell the young guys
anything, I hope they appreciate the game. You can take one wrong
step, and it's over. I'm glad my wrong step came after 16 years.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
