<SLUG> BC-FBN-RAIDERS-TITANS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TITANS TOP RAIDERS, 21-14 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By THOMAS GEORGE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NASHVILLE _ The Tennessee Titans found themselves in a battle
with the Oakland Raiders where the offenses looked worn, and the
defenses appeared pumped with enthusiasm. All night, big plays, and
points, would be scarce.
</P>
<P>
   It was the perfect setup for running back Eddie George.
</P>
<P>
   They call him the Beast. He has always loved cracking open tough
games and tough defenses. Ride me, he demands. Fifty carries is too
little for him, he insists. And on a night like Thursday night,
where George felt it, sensed it, running with direction and purpose
and authority through the Raiders' defense, 28 carries would prove
just enough.
</P>
<P>
   That got him 199 total rushing yards and the Titans three
rushing touchdowns (two by George) in the second half. Tennessee
jumped to a 21-7 lead with 8 minutes 1 second remaining and wound
up winning, 21-14, before 66,357 fans at Adelphia Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee improved to 10-3. Oakland fell to 6-7, a big loss for
a team confident that it is of playoff caliber.
</P>
<P>
   George scored on runs of 8 and 19 yards that helped fend off
Oakland's comeback. He hit the holes, read the defense, ran low and
fast and with such force that by game's end, he had nearly matched
his career-best rushing day of 216 yards. He also caught six passes
for 50 yards.
</P>
<P>
   It was a monstrous game from the Beast.
</P>
<P>
   The final quarter served as the final push that would separate
these teams. It was set up by the Raiders finally figuring out a
way to get into the end zone in the third quarter, on a 10-play,
90-yard drive. The critical play was a 50-yard run off a swing pass
by Napolean Kaufman. He ran up the left sideline and in blinding
speed down to the Tennessee 2-yard line, where he was tackled by
cornerback Denard Walker. Zack Crockett then scored from the 1-yard
line and the score was tied at 7-7 with 2:36 left in the quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee had scored a touchdown on the previous possession.
</P>
<P>
   Back-to-back scores in the third quarter? That was a complete
turnabout from the game's first 30 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The teams were scoreless at halftime, despite big plays by the
Oakland offense. Too many of the plays were bungled. Tennessee did
not have to worry about blown scoring chances _ for the entire
half, it never moved the football past the Raiders' 41.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Husted is a seven-year place-kicker from Virginia who
could be in his last season with Oakland unless he rediscovers his
consistency.
</P>
<P>
   Husted entered the game having missed at least one field goal
attempt in each of his last four games. Make it five. And two
misses in the first half in this one. The first came after Oakland
had driven from its 37 to the Tennessee 14. Husted tried a 32-yard
field goal with 25 seconds left in the quarter. It hooked wide
left.
</P>
<P>
   Early in the second quarter, the Raiders took the ball at their
21 and drove to the Tennessee 27. They took nearly 7 minutes
getting there. With 4:47 left before halftime, Husted tried a
45-yard field goal. That attempt missed short and to the left.
</P>
<P>
   The worst of the missed chances for Oakland, however, was Rich
Gannon's fumble at the Tennessee 8. It came with only 35 seconds
left in the half, with the Raiders ready to leave for halftime
ahead. But Gannon scrambled on a second-and-4 play, was sacked by
Jevon Kearse and lost the ball to cornerback Samari Rolle.
</P>
<P>
   Oakland dominated in the first half in first downs (9 to 4),
total yards (204 to 99), passing yards (133 to 44) and in
possession time (17:25 to 12:35). The Raiders knew they would
regret the lost chances. They simply hoped they could overcome
them.
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee, though, made the Raiders pay with a touchdown drive
to open the third quarter.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
