<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-MURRAY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MURRAY BACK TO KICK, NOT TO CARRY TORCH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RAY BUCK 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ Eddie Murray isn't the least bit interested in
carrying a torch for all you middle-aged males out there.
</P>
<P>
   He is not a modern-day George Blanda. He's much too young for
that.
</P>
<P>
   At 43, Murray is merely the oldest player in the NFL (three
months older than Kansas City quarterback Warren Moon) and tied for
the fifth-oldest player in NFL history.
</P>
<P>
   But his fortysomething mind is strictly set on helping the
Cowboys change what has become an old storyline this season.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys, 6-6, have lost four games in which they've held the
opposition to 13 points or less. Richie Cunningham, who was waived
Tuesday because of his inconsistency, missed five field goals in
those four low-scoring losses and missed 10 of 22 altogether.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not here to prove that 43-year-olds should be able to do
something, and I'm not on the bandwagon for people in their 40s,''
Murray said. ``I've come back into the league, hopefully, to add
some stability and help this team get into the playoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   It has been 24 years since Hall of Famer Blanda retired as the
NFL's all-time leading scorer. He was 48. He also was an national
icon for millions of middle-aged males in this country through the
first half of the '70s.
</P>
<P>
   Murray, who was known as Eddie Money when he kicked for the
Cowboys in 1993 and helped win a Super Bowl, has not kicked
competitively for 23 months. His last NFL job was with the 1997
Minnesota Vikings.
</P>
<P>
   He officially retired this past June with Detroit, after signing
a day earlier just so he could retire with the team for whom he
spent two-thirds (1980-91) of his 18-year career.
</P>
<P>
   ``The desire was always still there to kick,'' Murray said. ``I
was 41 when I last played. I'm 43 now. I can't do anything about
that. I can't change my age.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Besides, I don't know what a 43-year-old is supposed to kick
like ... because I see younger (kickers) out there who are having
problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Murray is six years older than the next-oldest player on the
Cowboys (Dale Hellestrae, 37) and two years older than his position
coach, Steve Hoffman. Murray and Hoffman have remained close
friends from their days together in '93, talking as often as twice
a month.
</P>
<P>
   It was Hoffman who told Murray that if any kicking change was to
be made with the struggling Cunningham that the Lions would have to
give Murray his release.
</P>
<P>
   Watching Cunningham miss a potential game-tying field goal from
43 yards in the Cowboys' 13-6 loss at New England on national
television Sunday night, Murray phoned Hoffman on Monday morning.
Then he phoned Chuck Schmidt, the Lions' VP/chief operating
officer, and received his release. All that was left was for Murray
to clear waivers, which he did on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Murray, who has continued to live in the Detroit area, has been
a sideline radio reporter for Lions games.
</P>
<P>
   He was contacted by Washington and Cleveland before training
camp this summer to see if he was interested in coming out of
retirement, which motivated him to start an indoor kicking regimen
at his home gymnasium.
</P>
<P>
   Leg strength? No problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm still kicking 50-yard field goals,'' said Murray,
dismissing questions about distance with his own philosophy about
success. ``My thought has always been in ``making'' field goals,
not on how far they are.
</P>
<P>
   ``Besides,'' he added, ``there aren't that many 50-yard field
goals being attempted these days in the NFL, with the rule change
and the ball being put back at the spot of the (missed) kick. That
puts a premium on making the kick.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm here because the Cowboys want me to make those kicks from
43 yards and in.''
</P>
<P>
   Holder Eric Bjornson worked with Murray and long-snapper
Hellestrae on Thursday and, in spite of gusting winds, everything
looked right.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not picky about the laces or anything,'' said Bjornson,
adding, ``neither was Richie. We should be smooth Sunday.''
</P>
<P>
   Murray ranks third all-time in the NFL in career field goals of
50 yards and more. He has 21. Yet, if the Cowboys need to launch a
55-yarder at the end of a half, it will probably be punter Toby
Gowin who will try it.
NFL OLDIES
</P>
<P>
   At age 43, Cowboys kicker Eddie Murray becomes the oldest player
in the NFL (three months older than Kansas City QB Warren Moon).
Only four players in the history of the NFL have played at an older
age. Here's the list: Age Pos. Player Last season/Team 48 QB-PK
George Blanda 1975 Oakland Raiders 45 PK Ben Agajanian 1964 San
Diego Chargers 45 OT-G John Nesser 1921 Columbus Panhandles 44 QB
Steve DeBerg 1998 Atlanta Falcons 43 PK-OT Lou Groza 1967 Cleveland
Browns 43 PK Jan Stenerud 1985 Minnesota Vikings 43 PK Eddie Murray
1999 Dallas Cowboys 43 QB Warren Moon 1999 Kansas City Chiefs nn
</P>
</TEXT>
