<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-10 00:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4919 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-RUSSIA-SPY-ARREST1STL     12-10 0528
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-SPY-ARREST1STLD-WRITETHRU-470(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. EXPELLING RUSSIAN DIPLOMAT IN BUGGING OF STATE DEPARTMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (Subs for new 12th graf providing additional details on
counterintelligence operation) 
(jw) 
By DAVID JOHNSTON and JAMES RISEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The State Department said Thursday that it had
ordered the expulsion of a Russian diplomat who was apprehended
outside the department's headquarters with electronic equipment for
monitoring a listening device hidden in a conference room used by
senior American diplomats.
</P>
<P>
   The order to expel Stanislav Borisovich Grusev, an employee of
the Russian Embassy here, came after a long investigation that also
uncovered a tiny sophisticated transmitter on the top floor of the
State Department, law enforcement officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Government officials said their investigation had uncovered a
``very aggressive'' Russian intelligence operation that represented
a serious penetration of the State Department. The FBI and the
department are still trying to determine the extent of the damage
to national security from the eavesdropping operation, which may
have been running for months before it was detected early this
fall.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. officials said the case marked the first time that the
State Department headquarters was known to have been successfully
penetrated with listening devices by a foreign intelligence
service.
</P>
<P>
   FBI counterintelligence agents detained Grusev on Wednesday in a
public park across the street from the State Department. Grusev,
identified by the federal authorities as an embassy attache, was a
technical expert from the SVR, or Russian foreign intelligence
service, officials said. He was not charged with any crime, and was
quickly turned over to Russian officials after he invoked
diplomatic immunity.
</P>
<P>
   Russian officials were later directed to remove Grusev from the
United States within 10 days.
</P>
<P>
   Neil Gallagher, a senior FBI official in charge of
counterintelligence operations, told reporters at the State
Department that investigators first became suspicious of Grusev
almost by accident early last summer when an FBI surveillance team
working on another case noticed him outside the department. The FBI
agents recognized him from their surveillance of Russian Embassy
employees.
</P>
<P>
   ``They made an observation that Stanislav Grusev was standing in
the vicinity of the State Department, and it took them as a little
bit odd, and they just remembered that very brief observation and
came back and developed a surveillance strategy,'' Gallagher said.
</P>
<P>
   But other officials said the FBI had information before Grusev
was detected that led them to suspect a Russian operation was under
way at the State Department.
</P>
<P>
   Over time, FBI agents watched how Grusev often drove up to the
department, got out of his car and walked around in the surrounding
streets and parks. Gallagher said that Grusev always parked his car
_ with diplomatic license plates _ in the same location, and that
that action had attracted the attention of surveillance agents.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Agents documented his movements around the State Department, the
frequency of his visits and the activity surrounding his car, and
concluded that the Russians had planted an electronic eavesdropping
device inside the department. After a search lasting several weeks,
a transmitter that Gallagher said was a ``very sophisticated'' and
``sensitive technical'' piece of espionage equipment was found this
fall.
</P>
<P>
   American counterintelligence agents had been controlling the
operation for the last few months, making sure that no important
and sensitive meetings were held in the conference room and that
some misleading statements were made so they could be detected by
the device.
</P>
<P>
   ``This episode should be a stark reminder to all of us in
government that despite the thawing of tensions between competing
nations, government facilities and personnel remain a desirable
target for foreign intelligence services,'' Assistant Secretary of
State David Carpenter told reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Law enforcement officials said the investigation of Grusev began
months before the recent espionage incidents that evoked the Cold
War practice of retaliatory expulsions. In late November, the
Russian authorities expelled an employee at the American Embassy in
Moscow after they said they had found her carrying spy
paraphernalia, including a device designed to detect signals of
electronic surveillance gear.
</P>
<P>
   And just before that, a Navy enlisted man who had worked at the
super-secret National Security Agency was arrested and charged with
passing secrets to Moscow about American submarine espionage
operations.
</P>
<P>
   Law enforcement officials said they did not know how long ago
the listening device had been installed at the State Department or
who might have planted it. Officials said they had no suspects
under investigation who might have aided the operation from the
inside.
</P>
<P>
   Some officials described the potential damage as serious, but it
was unclear what conversations might have been monitored by the
Russians. Officials said that 50 to 100 meetings might have been
held in the conference room since the time that Grusev was thought
to have begun his activities.
</P>
<P>
   Grusev entered the United States in March, but officials said
the listening device could have already been in place by that time.
He may have been sent to Washington to continue an eavesdropping
operation already under way.
</P>
<P>
   One official said the FBI would study the listening device to
look for clues about when it was installed. Officials are also
studying logs of meetings held in the conference room to determine
who had access there.
</P>
<P>
   The sophisticated eavesdropping device was carefully installed
in a hidden location that was not visible, officials said Thursday.
They said the installation required tools and a high level of
technical skill and could not have been completed in a short time.
</P>
<P>
   Officials theorized that whoever planted the listening device
had probably entered the conference area more than once, and
probably at a time when the State Department allowed authorized
visitors to move throughout the building without an escort. The
department tightened its policy on allowing unescorted visitors in
August.
</P>
<P>
   Grusev's visits to the State Department did not appear to be
timed to eavesdrop on particular meetings, which the officials said
suggested that the Russians did not have inside information in
advance about high-level meetings. The device could work only when
activated from close range, and could not store previously recorded
conversations, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   When he was caught, Grusev had hidden in his clothing a remote
switching device that turned on a receiver and tape recorder in his
car and a device designed to detect electronic surveillance
signals.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
