<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-10 00:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4923 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-FBC-HOUSTON-PRUETT-HN     12-10 0883
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-HOUSTON-PRUETT-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY WIZIG  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
Bob Pruett, who produced a Division I-AA national championship and
some of the nation's most explosive offenses in Division I-A in
four seasons at Marshall University, will be the next head football
coach at the University of Houston.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Two sources close to the university said Thursday night that
Pruett has agreed to leave Marshall, his alma mater, to succeed Kim
Helton as coach of the Cougars.
</P>
<P>
   Pruett, 57, who was in Orlando, Fla., on Thursday night with his
quarterback, Heisman Trophy finalist Chad Pennington, for a college
football awards program at the Walt Disney World Resort, would not
comment on reports of his hiring at UH.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will not have any comment on the situation until the Heisman
Trophy ceremony on Saturday,'' he told television station WSAZ in
Huntington, W.Va. ``That's the most important thing with Marshall
football right now. I won't comment until I talk with the
administration, my coaches and my team on Sunday.''
</P>
<P>
   UH athletic director Chet Gladchuk was unavailable for comment
Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   Pruett is expected to receive a multiyear contract, probably at
least five years, for an estimated $500,000 annually. He recently
agreed to a seven-year contract at Marshall with a $1 million
annuity after turning down an invitation to interview for the
then-vacant job at Louisiana State.
</P>
<P>
   Marshall is ranked No. 11 in the nation by the Associated Press
and will play BYU in the Motor City Bowl on Dec. 27. In four
seasons under Pruett, Marshall is 49-4 with a Division I-AA
national title, three Mid-American Conference Eastern Division
titles and two MAC titles.
</P>
<P>
   Today is the first day under state hiring policies that the new
UH coach could be announced.
</P>
<P>
   UH's ninth head coach, Pruett will succeed Helton, who was
dismissed Nov. 21 after seven seasons with two years remaining on
his $300,000-a-year agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Pruett arrived at Marshall after serving as a defensive
coordinator at Florida when Jim Donnan was hired away from Marshall
by Georgia. Marshall currently has a 16-game winning streak and has
won 31 in a row at home.
</P>
<P>
   Entering the MAC title game, which the Thundering Herd won 34-30
over Western Michigan, Marshall's offense ranked fourth in the
nation in total offense at 471.4 yards per game. Pennington was
fifth in the nation in total offense at 326.2 yards per game.
</P>
<P>
   Marshall's most prominent player of the Pruett era was wide
receiver Randy Moss, now with the Minnesota Vikings. Teaming with
Pennington in 1997, Moss caught 90 passes for 1,647 yards and 25
touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to two years at Florida, Pruett was defensive
coordinator at Tulane in 1992-93 and an assistant at Mississippi,
Wake Forest and Marshall.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Perry, Marshall's interim president, announced Nov. 24
that Pruett had signed a new seven-year contract, quelling
speculation that the coach would leave.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was concerned that rumors about him considering another
position would damage his recruiting efforts,'' Perry said. ``He
asked that I make today's announcement to try to put an end to such
rumors.''
</P>
<P>
   Pruett was to be paid $132,000 per year at Marshall, including
incentives based on game attendance and promotions. An annuity was
established for him through the private Marshall University
Foundation Inc., but he would have had to remain at the school
through the 2002-03 school year to qualify.
</P>
<P>
   West Virginia state law prevents the university from issuing
multiyear contracts, but additional payments to Pruett were to be
guaranteed by the private foundation.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, Pruett downplayed reports that he would seek to
leave his alma mater.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since I've been here, I've always looked for reasons to stay
at Marshall,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Pruett's arrival at UH will end a week of rumors that only
seemed to accelerate Thursday. In the latest round, Kansas State
officials denied a broadcast report that Wildcats coach Bill Snyder
was headed to UH.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Max Urick, K-State's athletic director, said of
the Snyder report: ``There is no truth to the rumor.'' Snyder was
at a Holiday Bowl function preceding the Wildcats' Dec. 28 date
with Washington, then was going to Orlando for the same awards show
attended by Pruett and Pennington.
</P>
<P>
   New Mexico State coach Tony Samuel also surfaced in speculation
for the job. Samuel, who had been a candidate for the Texas Tech
job until withdrawing Dec. 3, never mentioned interest in the
Cougars position, but his status as a former assistant coach at
Nebraska for Tom Osborne led to the speculation.
</P>
<P>
   Osborne made a brief stop at UH last week at the request of
Gladchuk in a consultant's role. Gladchuk then denied on Tuesday
that the job would be offered to Osborne after a Nebraska radio
station reported that Osborne was headed to UH to accept a $1
million-a-year offer.
</P>
<P>
   New Mexico State athletic director Brian Faison said Thursday
that UH never requested permission to talk to Samuel, who just
completed the third season of a four-year contract. Faison said the
school and Samuel are in the process of working out a contract
extension.
</P>
<P>
   Staff writer David Barron contributed to this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
