<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KINGS OF THE ROAD _ AT LEAST FOR NOW
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ The Dodgers haven't had roommates on the road since
the late '70s. By his own admission, Wilt Chamberlain had a lot of
roommates during his NBA career, but none of them were Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   In the NHL, things are a little different. Los Angeles Kings
captain Rob Blake bunks with Matty Norstrom. Luc Robitaille rooms
with Glen Murray.
</P>
<P>
   Salary and status don't matter. Only goalies get their own
rooms. Goalies and veteran defenseman Garry Galley. He could win a
Stanley Cup for snoring.
</P>
<P>
   Tradition is king in the NHL and this season the Kings have
taken this togetherness and built a winner by playing well out of
town. At home there is distance and distractions, players living
anywhere from Encino to Hermosa Beach.
</P>
<P>
   On the road, every minute is choreographed from a mandatory
mid-day team meal to a pregame nap back at the hotel. There even is
time set aside for a snack before everyone leaves for the arena.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, all that bonding goes out the window if you
snore,'' Galley said with a grin. ``It's something we've all grown
up with in hockey. There is a compatibility. When you're running
with somebody on the road, it helps on the ice. It's nice to have
someone to talk to. All that builds a team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year it didn't work. But this year, I think everyone knew
if we were going to be as good as we're capable of being, we had to
play well on the road.''
</P>
<P>
   It is the place where this once-fractured team began bonding
opening night in Nashville on Oct. 2 and really jelled during a
seven-game trip to start the season. The Kings are 8-3-3 on the
road entering tonight's game against the Detroit Red Wings at Joe
Louis Arena.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, they were 14-25-2 away from home and missed the
playoffs for the fifth time in six seasons.
</P>
<P>
   A tightly knit schedule created by tightly wound coach new coach
Andy Murray has provided structure. Victories are enjoyed, losses
are dissected. And the night before every game on the road, a
scouting report is slipped under the door of each player.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is very thorough,'' general manager Dave Taylor said of
Murray. ``He not only has broken down tendencies about the other
team, he has the team already thinking about the game the night
before.''
</P>
<P>
   After replacing Larry Robinson, Murray brought in a new coaching
staff and had seven new players. He stressed accountability as much
as fundamentals. There were motivational tapes and uptempo
speeches. It has been a hands-on approach and so far the players
have responded.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings played well in training camp, but Taylor knew it would
be a long season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we got a great opportunity to come together by opening
the season with those games on the road,'' he said. ``The Staples
Center wasn't open. It was a good chance for everyone to get to
know each other.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the new faces were Ziggy Palffy and Bryan Smolinski, who
came over from the New York Islanders last summer. Defenseman Aki
Berg returned from a season playing in Finland. Norstrom came back
after missing all of training camp because of a contract dispute.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't ignore that we really improved talentwise,'' Blake
said. ``We have a lot more ability to get out of losing streaks.
But that first trip was a huge confidence builder. It made us
believe we could win anywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   On the road, game days begin around 10 a.m. with a bus ride to
the arena or a practice facility.
</P>
<P>
   After 45 minutes of stretching, players hit the ice for what is
aptly termed the ``morning skate.'' It was designed years ago to
keep players from carousing the night before. Now it allows players
to get loose and often is optional as the season wears on.
</P>
<P>
   Then it is back to the hotel, where a meal is catered for the
club in one of the ballrooms. There is an afternoon nap built into
the schedule and a snack that helps players build reserves for the
night ahead. Off to the rink at 5 p.m. with game time at 7 or 7:30.
</P>
<P>
   ``The schedule is very important,'' Murray said. ``It gives
players focus that they might not have at home.''
</P>
<P>
   But does it really build a winner? They did all that last year,
but it didn't help.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of training camp, I really keyed on that first game in
Nashville,'' Murray said. ``All through camp we had Nashville signs
all over the dressing room. We had their lineup up about 10 days
before the game. This was a measuring stick for our team. We wanted
to be a harder-working team.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what playing on the road is all about. Hard work.
That's why Nashville was the perfect place to open the season. Last
year, they outworked us and beat us three times. We felt that might
be as important a game as we play all year.''
</P>
<P>
   The Kings opened the season 3-1-1 before taking a week break and
heading to Calgary and Edmonton. Another impressive stretch came in
late October during a three-city swing through the East and
Midwest. The Kings beat the Pittsburgh Penguins, then tied Detroit
the next night.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you eat together, sleep together and go to meetings
together, it's easier to focus,'' Galley said. ``On the road,
that's your life.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
