<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LeBRETON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NBA LOSES RASCAL, GEM WHEN BARKLEY RETIRES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GIL LeBRETON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   There was not enough notebook paper to cover Charles Barkley.
</P>
<P>
   And so he retired Wednesday night. A knee injury in Philadelphia
brought a sudden end to one of the most colorful careers since,
well, Redd Foxx. Charles might chuckle at the comparison.
</P>
<P>
   He was crass and yet he could be so disarming. He could be
``Outrageous,'' as his autobiography is titled, and yet his words
could be so profound.
</P>
<P>
   Like the time _ on NBC _ when he railed about TV _ namely, NBC _
showing ``too many Lakers games.''
</P>
<P>
   Or like the frequent answer he would give when it appeared that
his remarkable, 16-year NBA career would not be crowned by a
championship ring.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing that a ring would do,'' he said, ``is make me
not have to answer that question anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   He came so far, from a corpulent college kid that Southeastern
Conference crowds used to taunt as ``Fat Albert'' to Sir Charles,
one of the 50 greatest NBA players of all-time, as named in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Lest anyone forget, Indiana scoundrel Bobby Knight cut Barkley
from the 1984 Olympic team. And it's just as well. Eight years
later in Barcelona, Spain, early in the Dream Team's opening game,
Charles threw an elbow to the chops of an Algerian forward _ ``to
let him know we weren't here on any vacation.''
</P>
<P>
   Barkley had a way of saying what was on his mind, whether David
Stern had the fine meter running or not. He could be cruel, but the
people who know him quickly add that he could be kind.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody, they say, nobody in the NBA signed more autographs for
kids than Charles Barkley.
</P>
<P>
   And nobody did as much with so little.
</P>
<P>
   Officially, Barkley was listed as 6 feet, 6 inches, and 252
pounds. Unofficially, his bald pate never reached the 6-5 mark. Yet
Barkley scored more than 20,000 NBA points, grabbed 10,000 rebounds
and had 4,000 assists, and the only others to do so were Wilt
Chamberlain and Kareem Abdul-Jabbar, both 7-foot giants.
</P>
<P>
   Coaches like to say that rebounding is 10 percent height and 90
percent desire. On the basketball floor, Sir Charles was a blazing
furnace of desire. For a guy who wasn't good enough for Bobby
Knight, Barkley did just fine, making the All-NBA team 10 times.
</P>
<P>
   He was the fifth pick in the 1984 draft, a memorable talent pool
that included Michael Jordan, Hakeem Olajuwon and John Stockton.
The irony shadowed him to the end.
</P>
<P>
   When Barkley was with the Philadelphia 76ers, making the
playoffs six times in eight years, there were always the Bulls and
Michael. When Barkley was with the Phoenix Suns, there was always
Hakeem and the Rockets. And when he joined Houston three years ago,
the unscaled hurdle became Stockton's Utah Jazz.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I have no regrets,'' Barkley said in Philadelphia after
his final game. ``I have nothing but 16 years of great memories.
I've been all over the world. I've met unbelievable people who I
would never have gotten the opportunity to meet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I met some of the best actors in the world. I met some of the
best athletes in the world. I met presidents, Bishop (Desmond)
Tutu. I met just regular people who made an impact on my life. I
played in two Olympics. I've exceeded all my expectations, all of
them.''
</P>
<P>
   He was cast by his critics as selfish and disruptive. Yes, he
could be all of that. But nobody, maybe not even Jordan, wanted to
win more.
</P>
<P>
   He was, like his book said, outrageous. He was, as far as
commissioner Stern was concerned, the anti-Jordan in some ways. He
once tossed a heckler through the window of an Orlando night spot.
He broke the nose of a drunk who wouldn't shut up in a bar in
Milwaukee.
</P>
<P>
   But life, for Charles Barkley, clearly was a participation
sport.
</P>
<P>
   It was Barkley, wasn't it, who spilled the beans about golf
partner Jordan's retirement? And when it was time to sign his last
contract, Sir Charles inked his at the Tamarisk Country Club, where
he couldn't bear to leave the Bob Hope Classic. Barkley had his
agent meet him with the contract on the 10th hole.
</P>
<P>
   It was so right that his mother and grandmother were with him
Wednesday night, flown in from Alabama to Philadelphia for the
franchise's final farewell.
</P>
<P>
   Leaving the postgame press conference in a golf cart, Barkley
sighed and observed, ``Just what America needs _ one more
unemployed black man.''
</P>
<P>
   Basketball just got a lot duller.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
