<SLUG> BC-BKN-MAVERICKS-NOTES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNION HEAD HOPES SMITH CAN PLAY SOON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DWAIN PRICE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ NBA union leader Billy Hunter is devising a plan to get
Mavericks rookie Leon Smith back on the basketball court as soon as
possible.
</P>
<P>
   But first, Hunter is making sure Smith stays in the National
Basketball Players Association after-care players assistance
program.
</P>
<P>
   Smith is at an undisclosed Dallas hospital receiving psychiatric
treatment. Hunter would not identify the facility.
</P>
<P>
   ``The kid is doing well, and we're going to continue to monitor
his situation and help manage his affairs,'' Hunter said. ``I have
had some discussions with the league and with the team, and
hopefully we're going to be able to work this thing out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our ambition is to make sure Leon is well. And once Leon has
been given a clean bill of health, the idea is to make sure he's
able to put himself in a training program that we're going to
monitor and set up for him in consultation with the league, and at
least keep them and the Mavericks aware of what we're doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Hunter said he doesn't know when Smith will be ready to go
through such a program.
</P>
<P>
   ``It might take the remainder of this season,'' he said. ``I'm
hoping it doesn't take that long. Hopefully, from the first day of
the program, Leon will be able to demonstrate that he's ready to
come back to the NBA.'' TRENT UPDATE
</P>
<P>
   The Gary Trent watch continues.
</P>
<P>
   Trent tore his hamstring during an Oct. 21 preseason game
against Toronto, and the Dec. 2 target date for his expected return
has come and gone.
</P>
<P>
   The Mavericks medical staff still doesn't know when Trent will
play. But they're hoping he will return during the five-game
homestand, which starts Saturday against Jason Kidd and the Phoenix
Suns.
</P>
<P>
   Trent practiced for the first time since his injury on Monday,
and a fitness test he took Tuesday indicated that the leg has
healed. Now it appears it's just a matter of Trent getting in
basketball shape. FINLEY IN MINI-SLUMP
</P>
<P>
   After averaging 30.3 points per game recently against Chicago,
Minnesota and Milwaukee, Michael Finley has slipped a bit.
</P>
<P>
   In the past two games against Vancouver and Utah, Finley has
scored 17 and 11 points, respectively. That's just the second time
this season he has scored fewer than 20 points in consecutive
games.
</P>
<P>
   During consecutive games earlier this season, Finley followed a
19-point effort against the Los Angeles Lakers with a season-low
4-point outing against the Miami Heat. BRIEFLY
</P>
<P>
   _ Mavericks coach/general manager Don Nelson has used nine
different starting lineups this season. The lineup of Michael
Finley, Dirk Nowitzki, Sean Rooks, Robert Pack and Erick Strickland
is 3-5.
</P>
<P>
   _ The 79 points the Mavericks scored in Wednesday's six-point
loss to Utah was their lowest-scoring game of the season. It also
was only the second time the Mavericks have been under 90 points
this season _ the other time being a 107-82 shellacking at the
hands of the New York Knicks.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Mavericks scored 100 or more points in six of their first
eight games, but have topped the century mark only three times in
the past 13 games.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Mavericks lead the NBA in free-throw shooting at 79.6
percent, but are last in the league in points allowed at 103.7 per
game. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
