<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARS HOPE TO IMPROVE ON PAIR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JENNIFER FLOYD 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ The Dallas Stars' third defensive pair is Jamie
Pushor and Brad Lukowich, but you aren't likely to see them on t together too often.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see it being a pair right now. There are too many
errors there,'' Stars coach Ken Hitchcock said. ``If they can play
better, they are going to get more minutes and it's going to help
us. If this is as good as they can play, then from that pair we're
going to need more.''
</P>
<P>
   With rookie defenseman Richard Jackman sent down to their
minor-league affiliate Thursday, the Stars are going to find out
how good the two can be.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars have only six defensemen on the roster. They have
compensated by having their top defensive pair of Derian Hatcher
and Richard Matvichuk play their shift and then an extra shift
alongside either Pushor or Lukowich.
</P>
<P>
   But Hitchcock acknowledges that their top four defensemen can't
keep playingthat many minutes without wearing out. Hatcher is among
the leaders in the NHL in ice-time.
</P>
<P>
   So it's sink or swim for Pushor and Lukowich.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope me and Push can become a pair together and not worry
about having Hatch or Matty being out there,'' Lukowich said.
``It's almost like they're a dad or a babysitter. I don't want to
be a guy that has to be babysat on the ice.''
</P>
<P>
   If Lukowich and Pushor can prove they don't need to be
``babysat,'' Hitchcock said he'll send them out together and
increase their minutes. If not, the Stars may have make a trade to
solidify that third defensive pair, Stars general manager Bob
Gainey said.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a situation we'll give more time for a couple of
reasons,'' Gainey said. ``No. 1, give some players time to get
comfortable and show improvement and also give (injured defenseman)
Shawn Chambers a little more time. We'll have a clearer idea a
month or so from now.''
</P>
<P>
   Chambers, of course, is the missing piece in the puzzle.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars didn't begin the season planning to depend on Pushor,
in his first season with Dallas, and Lukowich, in his first full
season period, as their third pair. Pushor, Lukowich and Chambers
were supposed to be the fifth, sixth and seventh defensemen, but
Chambers has missed most of the season after having knee surgery in
October.
</P>
<P>
   ``If somebody said Shawn Chambers is a definite player on the
15th of January, I'd feel great. But we can't tell that and neither
can Shawn,'' Hitchcock said. ``He's right now a big question
mark.''
</P>
<P>
   Chambers admits as much, saying that he has ``no idea how it's
going to be.''
</P>
<P>
   So, for now, the Stars have to bank on Pushor and Lukowich
developing into a strong, third defensive pair.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd take that bet,'' Pushor said. ``Brad and I are ready for
that role. That's what we want. I know that Brad is capable of it,
and I'm capable of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Pushor also realizes that his play early on didn't show that.
The fourth-year player struggled from the get-go until finally
finding himself among the healthy scratches for a couple of games
in late November and early December.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think when you get out of the lineup that's kind of, for any
athlete, I don't want to say rock bottom, but it makes you take a
hard look,'' Pushor said. ``You realize you have to come back and
do the things you are supposed to do. I know I can definitely
improve and become the player they want me to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Hitchcock: ``I think he lost some confidence and we lost
some confidence in him.''
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock's confidence in Pushor has been growing lately,
though. He has played back-to-back strong games, and teamed with
Lukowich for seven or eight shifts in Monday's game against
Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you noticed in the Phoenix game, until Luke got hurt, we
were using them as a pair,'' Stars assistant coach Rick Wilson
said. ``We'd like to see them get up to a point where they can give
us a very sound 10 minutes of even-strength hockey.''
</P>
<P>
   Pushor and Lukowich would like nothing more.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it helps in the long run if he and I can be a
consistent pair together,'' Lukowich said. ``Right now, Hatch is
playing 30 minutes, leading the league I think, but maybe if we
take four of those minutes ... ''
</P>
<P>
   He didn't finish the sentence. He realizes the way to get those
minutes is to prove that he and Pushor can do the job _ by
themselves. The time is now. The chance has presented itself.
</P>
<P>
   Can they become a pair in more than name only?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know,'' Hitchcock said. ``I guess it's a matter of how
much they can improve.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
