<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-10 01:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4928 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BKN-ROCKETS-HNS &LR;      12-10 1121
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-ROCKETS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JONATHAN FEIGEN  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
BOSTON _ Charles Barkley's will is sure to contain a passage asking
that those attending his funeral smile, tell jokes openly and laugh
loudly.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Barkley's playing career ended Wednesday in Philadelphia. After
surgery and a long, painstaking rehabilitation, his life will go on
pretty much as he has planned. And as mourners will someday be
expected to laugh, his teammates now will be called on to play.
</P>
<P>
   In a season of injuries to their stars, fines, a suspension and
Wednesday's painful irony, the Rockets find themselves trying to
move on. Again.
</P>
<P>
   Barkley stayed with the team and will attend tonight's game in
Boston against the Celtics. Meanwhile, Hakeem Olajuwon is more than
a month from returning after hernia surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Only three players from last season's team _ Matt Bullard,
Cuttino Mobley and Bryce Drew _ will take the court tonight.
</P>
<P>
   But life will go on. It just won't be the same.
</P>
<P>
   ``With every negative, you have opportunity,'' coach Rudy
Tomjanovich said. ``I heard something the other day: Stumbling
blocks and steppingstones can be the same thing. It depends on
attitude.
</P>
<P>
   ``Next year came early.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets are not conceding this year, Tomjanovich and the
players say. But the team is not likely to seek stopgap solutions.
Asked if he would consider picking up a player whose age made him a
short-term fix, Tomjanovich said, ``Probably not.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets' immediate move was to add Devin Gray, a rookie
forward who has been playing in the Continental Basketball
Association after showing great promise with the Rockets' summer
team in Salt Lake City.
</P>
<P>
   But without Barkley and the multitude of ways he led the
Rockets, the transition will be significant, even if the roster
remains relatively unchanged.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be 62 games of experience for these guys,''
Tomjanovich said of the rest of the regular season. ``It's almost a
bonus for the young guys. They're going to have to learn to grow up
quickly and mature quickly.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we put the ball in Charles' hands, almost 50 percent of
the time the team scored. That's a big security blanket that's no
longer there.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some things will change,'' Tomjanovich said. ``We've got to
get some easy baskets. We can't run all the time. We don't have
enough firepower. We have to be a better-executing team. We have to
run more five-man plays, not just `iso.'
</P>
<P>
   ``Our offensive rebounds have to go way up because our
(shooting) percentage is not going to be as good.''
</P>
<P>
   But before anything can happen, the Rockets must retool
emotionally. They have had only three players available for every
game, fewer than any team in the league. They have only two players
_ Shandon Anderson and Walt Williams _ who have started every game,
matching Seattle for the league low.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody feels for Charles,'' Tomjanovich said. ``The good
thing is his attitude about the whole deal. He almost made them
feel (as if he was) fortunate, that that (a major injury) could
have happened a long time ago, before he had a chance to do all the
wonderful things he's done.''
</P>
<P>
   Through each test, Barkley provided the booming voice and
outsized leadership capacity to continue to push the team. With so
many new players and so few veterans, Barkley's leadership was as
important as his rebounding or his command of the offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where's the leadership going to come from?'' Tomjanovich said.
``These guys are basically young. The older guy (Matt Bullard) is
basically a reserve. Walt (Williams) is older. But everybody is
going to have that responsibility. I'm asking them to grow up
early.''
</P>
<P>
   The first step, Rockets players said, is to get over the shock
of Wednesday's events. The Rockets played much of their loss to the
76ers in a daze.
</P>
<P>
   They took a three-game winning streak, a season best, to
Philadelphia. But when Barkley left, any intensity and precision
the Rockets had showed in recent days went with him.
</P>
<P>
   One of the team's few veterans, Williams, said: ``Last night was
damn near impossible to concentrate on the game. It was just a bad
situation. It really made you think about other things, more
important things, like, Is he going to be all right? It was a bad
situation to try and concentrate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every professional knows injuries are part of the game and
that injuries can end a career. At the same token, he's not only
one of the 50 greatest ballplayers to play the game, he's a good
person, a good locker-room guy, a fun guy to be around.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think leadership doesn't automatically come because of how
old he is. It's going to have to come from everybody. I definitely
have to be more vocal. But I'm not going to say I'm going to
replace Barkley. That's something all of us have to do, to step up
and make contributions. Everybody has to be leaders.''
</P>
<P>
   That said, more burden than ever may fall on rookie Steve
Francis. Barkley already had said the Rockets are Francis' team.
The Rockets will certainly reshape themselves around his talents.
</P>
<P>
   But without Barkley, and while the Rockets wait for Olajuwon's
return, it is more important than ever that Francis serve as a
facilitator.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just know I'm going to continue to try to do what I'm doing
and stay aggressive,'' Francis said. ``With Dream and Charles out,
everybody's scoring is important, not just one person.
</P>
<P>
   Of Barkley's contention that the Rockets are Francis' team, the
rookie said: ``I really can't see it. I'm just a member of the
team. I'll shoulder leading the team. But I don't want them to look
at me as a leader until I display that on the court.''
</P>
<P>
   He will, however, have increasing control of the offense.
Barkley drawing double teams in the low post had initiated much of
the Rockets' offense. Now, much of it must go through Francis _ a
role he said he welcomes, particularly as the Rockets attempt to
run more.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not just me. We have a lot of guys that get up and
down,'' Francis said. ``The first thing for me is to be the
starter. I'm the ignition that starts the car. Then everybody runs.
The main thing is we still want to be a good team this year. We
don't want to wait for next year. I still think we can be a good
team.''
</P>
<P>
   Tomjanovich insisted he would have his team ready.
</P>
<P>
   ``The goal is always to win,'' he said. ``I'd be cheating the
guys if I didn't coach to win and have them focused. That's the
worst thing that could happen. I don't want to lose, but I don't
care if we lose every game if our mentality is every possession,
every minute out there we're trying to win the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't let them get into playing this thing out.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-10-99 0107EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
