<DOCNO> NYT19991210.0016 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-10 01:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4929 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BKN-BARKLEY-NBA-HNS &LR;      12-10 0758
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-BARKLEY-NBA-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MURPHY  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
``It's over.''
<TEXT>
<P>
   With those two words, Charles Barkley announced the end of a
16-year NBA career. Barkley had just ruptured a tendon in his left
knee in Wednesday's game against the Philadelphia 76ers, ending his
days as an NBA player.
</P>
<P>
   How much more ironic can it get?
</P>
<P>
   Not only because Barkley had ended his career in Philadelphia,
the city where it all began in 1984, when the Sixers made the 6-6,
300-pound ``Round Mound of Rebound'' the fifth pick in the draft.
</P>
<P>
   But there further is irony in the brevity of his comment.
</P>
<P>
   From the moment he landed in the NBA, Barkley has been to words
what blizzard is to snow _ one nonstop comedic stream of
consciousness, with Richard Pryor's awareness and Sam Kinison's
irreverence mixed in with the superb timing of Groucho Marx.
</P>
<P>
   There is further irony in that with that statement, Barkley used
the same number of words to announce his retirement that his good
friend _ ``brother,'' even _ Michael Jordan used to announce his
return after his self-imposed exile _ ``I'm back.''
</P>
<P>
   Utah's Karl Malone used one word to sum up Barkley's career.
</P>
<P>
   ``Underappreciated,'' Malone said.
</P>
<P>
   Even Scottie Pippen, with whom Barkley shared a rivalry, a
locker room and _ finally _ a war of words, was moved by Barkley's
injury. Pippen shrugged off the differences between himself and
Barkley, and spoke about his one-time friend.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel bad for him,'' Pippen said. ``I didn't want to see him
end his career like that. I wanted to see him go out as a fighter
and a warrior, the type of player he's been his whole career.
Things happen like that. You don't wish that on anybody. I just
hope he's able to get himself back to where he was before he
suffered the injury.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're always going to miss not having Charles out there. The
fact he's been such a competitor his whole career, he's tried to
win and take over games and do things. He's going to be missed.''
</P>
<P>
   By many.
</P>
<P>
   Barkley's career path often crossed those of Malone and John
Stockton. Barkley, Malone and Stockton were selected as three of
the 50 greatest players during the league's 50th anniversary
celebration at the 1997 All-Star Game.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole league,'' said Stockton, ``will miss him and his
personality.''
</P>
<P>
   Malone agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``What he brought to the game, how he prepared to play the game
and how hard he played trying to win,'' Malone said, ``all that
makes Charles part of a dying breed, in my opinion.''
</P>
<P>
   And it was Utah that eliminated the Rockets from the 1997
Western Conference finals, the closest Barkley came to a title
since advancing to the NBA Finals in 1993, when his Phoenix Suns
lost to the Chicago Bulls in six games. But that, said Phoenix
coach Danny Ainge, who teamed with Barkley for three years with the
Suns, should not detract from Barkley's career.
</P>
<P>
   ``The things that stand out to me are just the daily things he
does to make you laugh,'' Ainge said. ``You can talk about him
being a comedian and entertainer and all those things, but those
things can go a long way with a team. Being loose and playing loose
is a lost art, in some ways.''
</P>
<P>
   Malone, Stockton and Pippen were just a few who spoke Thursday
about the end of the Barkley era.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people put in that nonsense that because he doesn't
have a (championship) ring, he's not a great player,'' Lakers
center Shaquille O'Neal said. ``I find that not true. He played
with a lot of enthusiasm. He played with a lot of heart and never
backed down from anybody. That's what I liked the most.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Needless to say, I was disheartened by the turn of events in
his life,'' said former Sixers teammate Julius Erving, now the
executive vice president of the Orlando Magic. ``Him having been a
former teammate of mine and a friend of my family, we are all sad
that his career had to end on the note it did.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I hated to see it,'' said Seattle forward Chuck Person, a
teammate of Barkley's at Auburn. ``Nobody will ever forget what
he's meant for the game. I'm telling you right now, for one game,
he's the best power forward I've seen in the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Pippen said he is considering a phone call to his one-time
teammate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Charles is a great player, he's a legend, a Hall of Famer,
he'll be remembered like all great players who played the game,''
Pippen said. ``You don't have to label him that he didn't win a
championship; he's still great in his own way.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
