<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-MEETINGS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANGELS BRACE FOR BUSY MEETINGS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Baseball's annual Winter Meetings begin here
today, a five-day gathering of the major leagues' general managers
during which trades often involving big names are made.
</P>
<P>
   The Anaheim Angels are expected to be as active as any team,
with new general manager Bill Stoneman having made it clear there
is no such thing as an ``untouchable'' Angel.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are going to be a lot of discussions,'' Stoneman said.
``We'll push toward doing something from a player standpoint if we
can do it. We haven't kept any secrets about what we are trying to
do. We're trying to improve our pitching.''
</P>
<P>
   It's also no secret what the Angels will give up to get
pitching. One of their four outfielders is almost certain to go.
</P>
<P>
   In recent seasons, center fielder Jim Edmonds and Garret
Anderson, who has played all three outfield positions, have been
mentioned in trade rumors the most. Now, though, even Tim Salmon
and Darin Erstad could be dealt.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bill's doing his best to acquire starting pitching,'' said
Paul Cohen, Edmonds' agent. ``Through conversations I've had with
other general managers, Bill's statement to the press that anyone
could be traded is correct. I can say with certainty one of the
outfielders will be dealt.''
</P>
<P>
   Because Edmonds and Anderson can become free agents at the end
of the 2000 season, they are more likely to go. But even the
mention of his name in trade speculation is a little strange to
Salmon.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's new for me,'' Salmon said. ``If I got traded it would be
for the short term. After my contract is up (after the 2001
season), I'll exercise my rights as a free agent and look for
greener pastures around home (Paradise Valley, Ariz.). The
Diamondbacks would love to have me there.''
</P>
<P>
   Salmon, though, said he hasn't given up on the Angels and said
he hopes the team isn't torn apart.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year was a bad year, there was a lot of turmoil inside
the clubhouse,'' he said. ``But that doesn't take away from the
talent we have. We need pitching to put us over the top.''
</P>
<P>
   With the Angels lacking pitching, many including Salmon didn't
see the point in letting Chuck Finley go. Stoneman, though, said he
couldn't compete with the offers that other teams were making.
</P>
<P>
   The loss of Finley will be felt throughout the organization, and
not just on the field. Tim Mead, the Angels' vice president in
charge of communications, developed a close friendship with Finley
during the pitcher's 14 seasons in Anaheim.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think everybody in the industry sees enough to know that you
may not always like things, but it's not a matter of agreeing or
not agreeing with what might happen,'' Mead said. ``When I look at
Chuck Finley, the things I will think about have very little to do
with pitching.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bus crash (in '92). Chuck was in the back of the second
bus playing cards. When the other bus crashed, he was hopping over
seats. He was the second one out of the bus. By the time I got out
of the bus, he was reaching into the first bus pulling guys out of
windows.... He's the last of Mr. Autry's boys. And that's as
symbolic or meaningful as anything.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
