<HEADER>
A4936 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKN-LAKERNOTES-LADN     12-10 0599
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAKERS GETTING WISE TO JACKSON'S PLOYS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ A Los Angeles Lakers winning streak that ended
with a thud Wednesday in Sacramento began in mid-November with a
bit of pop psychology, Phil Jackson style.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers' cerebral coach chided his team after a disappointing
Nov. 18 loss in Denver and warned them, prior to a home date
against the hot Toronto Raptors, that trouble might loom.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's some good teams coming up,'' Jackson recalled telling
his team, ``and (we) might just go 2-6.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I just didn't think we were playing good enough.... We'd lost
to Denver, we were kind of fiddling around there in that period of
time. That's when I mentioned, before the Toronto game, that maybe
there's a chance we were going to end up eating our lunch a little
because we had to get better. We got better.''
</P>
<P>
   A lot better, in fact. They did lose to the Raptors on Nov. 21,
but recovered to win seven straight _ beating Utah, Seattle and
Portland _ before watching the string end against the upstart
Kings.
</P>
<P>
   A product of Jackson's calculated mind ploy? Maybe, but
Shaquille O'Neal scoffed at the idea, and mocked the coach's
earlier predictions that his team, now 15-5, might struggle to a
.500 record in the first month of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``You didn't think I believed that (garbage), did you?'' said an
indignant O'Neal. ``First 15 games, .500? Please.''
</P>
<P>
   But did the ``psychology thing,'' as O'Neal called it, work? Or
was it recognized for what it was?
</P>
<P>
   ``I always recognize it,'' he said. ``I guess we used it as
motivation. We won seven straight.... I don't listen to what people
say, especially you guys (reporters).''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the week, O'Neal seemed quite affected by Jackson's
modest predictions, saying testily, ``Some people, including you
guys, including some guys in this locker room, didn't expect us to
go this far. But I expected to do this.''
</P>
<P>
   Of his players appearing to respond to the ploys, Jackson said,
``It's good,'' but smiled at the realization they might be catching
on.
</P>
<P>
   ``They know, they're starting to learn a little bit,'' he said.
``I'm going to have to do some different things.''
</P>
<P>
   Behind the numbers: O'Neal's MVP campaign is strong in large
part because he's improved his stats in nearly every category when
comparing this season to last. But his average minutes are also up,
by 3 to 4 per game, so is he really playing that much better?
Actually, yes.
</P>
<P>
   When O'Neal's numbers are boiled down to a per-minute basis,
it's clear he's greatly improved in rebounding and blocked shots,
and slightly in assists.
</P>
<P>
   Last season he averaged 26.3 points, 10.7 rebounds, 1.67 blocks
and 2.3 assists in 34.8 minutes. This season he's averaging 28.2
points, 13.7 rebounds, 3.26 blocks and 3.1 assists in 38.4 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   But recalculating O'Neal's current averages based on last year's
minutes still shows improvement. At 34.8 minutes per game this
season, he would average 12.4 rebounds (up 1.7), 2.96 blocks (up
1.29) and 2.81 assists (up 0.51). Only his points would decline, to
25.5, but he also is taking fewer shots on a per-minute basis.
</P>
<P>
   Ouch report: Kobe Bryant briefly left Wednesday's game to go to
the locker room and on a couple of occasions seemed to wince after
getting hit on his right arm. But Bryant said his right hand,
recently healed from a broken bone, was OK. Beefy Kings guard Nick
Anderson had simply slammed Bryant's upper arm a couple times, he
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
