<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-10 01:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4939 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-10titansroll-HNS &LR;      12-10 0737
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-10titansroll-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN McCLAIN  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
NASHVILLE, Tenn. _ After being humiliated by Baltimore in their
worst game of the season, the Tennessee Titans were desperate for a
victory Thursday night at Adelphia Coliseum.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Running back Eddie George answered the distress call with his
most impressive game of the season, rushing for a season-high 199
yards and scoring two touchdowns in the Titans' 21-14 conquest of
the Oakland Raiders.
</P>
<P>
   Before a crowd of 66,357, the Titans recovered from the Ravens
debacle to improve their record to 10-3. They have 10 days to rest
before they host Atlanta and Jacksonville, the latter for what
could be the next big game in the AFC.
</P>
<P>
   George wasn't the whole show Thursday night; it just seemed like
it.
</P>
<P>
   He carried 27 times for 200 yards, but he lost a yard on his
final attempt, finishing with 199. He also led the team with six
catches for 50 yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eddie's been possessed since Sunday night,'' coach Jeff Fisher
said, alluding to the 41-20 blowout at Baltimore. ``He got that
look in his eye and kept it. It was a great effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our plan was to run the ball because you have to run the ball
successfully to win in December.
</P>
<P>
   ``The blocking was outstanding. The defense made so many big
plays against a very good offense.''
</P>
<P>
   Rookie defensive end Jevon Kearse continued his assault on
quarterbacks with two sacks, the same number as linebacker Eddie
Robinson.
</P>
<P>
   With three games left, Kearse has 11{ sacks, one behind the NFL
rookie record shared by Leslie O'Neil and Simeon Rice.
</P>
<P>
   The Raiders finished with 364 yards. They entered the game
ranked first in rushing, but they generated only 111 yards on the
ground. They committed three turnovers to Tennessee's one.
</P>
<P>
   The Titans accumulated 307 yards, including 204 rushing.
Quarterback Steve McNair, who scored the first touchdown on a
one-yard run, completed 12 of 20 passes for 114 yards. He was
intercepted once when the ball was deflected at the line.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you want to be a championship team, you have to find a way
to win,'' George said. ``You can't be embarrassed like we were in
Baltimore. You have to fight through adversity, and we did.''
</P>
<P>
   Both offenses struggled in the first half, and there was no
score at halftime. George, who rushed for 55 yards on 11 carries in
the first half, exploded in the last two quarters.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a mindset to run the ball, and that's what we did,''
George said. ``After the Baltimore game, it was time for the
leaders to stand up and be counted. I wanted to provide some
leadership. I got into my rhythm the longer the game went. I felt
fresh even though I got a lot of carries.''
</P>
<P>
   The Raiders had no answers for George, who gained yards inside
and outside. He broke tackles like Earl Campbell and kept his
balance like Barry Sanders.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I finally found that game where I can just cut it
loose,'' George said. ``And I wanted it tonight. I wanted the win.
I think everyone in this room wanted to win.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were quite upset. We wanted to come out and prove something
not only to the fans and the nation but ourselves that we're a good
team. We can bounce back from a defeat like that.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We tried several things to stop Eddie, but we couldn't do
it,'' Raiders coach Jon Gruden said. ``When a back is running hard
like that, there aren't a lot of adjustments you can make. We did
try to move some guys around and play eight- and nine-man fronts,
but he still made some good plays.
</P>
<P>
   ``He just got stronger as the game went on. I tip my hat to
Eddie George.''
</P>
<P>
   The Raiders never led. After the scoreless first half, McNair
gave the Titans a 7-0 lead. Oakland tied it on Zach Crockett's
one-yard run for a 7-7 game entering the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Then, George erupted and scored on eight- and 19-yard runs for a
21-7 lead.
</P>
<P>
   The Raiders scored their last touchdown on Rich Gannon's
two-yard pass to tight end Rickey Dudley.
</P>
<P>
   The Raiders had a chance to tie the score with 59 seconds left,
but Darrien Gordon fumbled a punt and Donald Mitchell recovered for
Tennessee, allowing the Titans to run out the clock.
</P>
<P>
   ``We needed to get the big guy (George) down, but we didn't,''
Raiders defensive tackle Russell Maryland said. ``We just weren't
up to par. They put the ball in No. 27's hands, and we give our
respect to them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
