<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-10 01:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4945 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-RAC-PINCAY-LADN     12-10 0795
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-PINCAY-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PINCAY TIES SHOEMAKER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRANK C. GIRARDOT  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ On a day that contained moments as truly
exciting, moving and frustrating as any in all of sports, Laffit
Pincay Jr. nearly became an immortal.
</P>
<P>
   Falling momentarily short of that however, Pincay achieved the
status of legend at Hollywood Park Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The 52-year-old jockey, once thought to be on his way out of
racing because of weight problems, picked up his 8,833rd career win
and moved into a tie with all-time leader Bill Shoemaker.
</P>
<P>
   `It's very good,'' Pincay said. `I feel very proud and content
that I've done this. I just need one more winner and my dream will
come true.''
</P>
<P>
   The win, aboard I Be Casual in the fourth race was Pincay's only
trip to the winner's circle in five mounts Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   He's scheduled to ride five horses this afternoon at the
Inglewood track.
</P>
<P>
   As he has been throughout his pursuit of Shoemaker's record,
Pincay has maintained a casual and calm demeanor. Just before his
only win of the day, the 5-1, 117-pound Pincay relaxed comfortably
on an soft couch in the jock's room. He focused his attention on a
crossword puzzle in the back of a glossy magazine, stopping
occasionally to adjust a pair of oversized reading glasses.
</P>
<P>
   After leaving the jock's room, Pincay somehow found the edge to
ride a perfect race aboard I Be Casual. The three- year-old gray
colt had to mount a powerful stretch run between horses and
overcome a strong early leader.
</P>
<P>
   Even Pincay, once known as `the Pirate` among fellow jockeys,
wasn't sure he would do it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was hoping that (David Flores') horse would die on the turn
and he did die on the turn,'' Pincay said. ``That other horse was
very tough inside and for a while I thought he was going to come
back and beat me. I was lucky I had enough horse left to prevail.''
</P>
<P>
   Pincay, a native of Panama who began riding in the United States
in 1966, has five chances today to prevail. Just one more win will
place him atop an unparaled pinnacle.
</P>
<P>
   In the sport of Thoroughbred horse racing the accomplishment is
on a par with Cal Ripken's consecutive games played streak in
baseball or Wilt Chamberlain's 100- point game in basketball.
</P>
<P>
   `You cannot understate by use of adjectives this guy's
accomplishment,'' said rider Chris McCarron. `The English language
to describe this ... it blows everything away.`
</P>
<P>
   `The average racegoer; there's no way he can grasp how much
skill it takes to ride a race horse like Laffit Pincay Jr. ''
</P>
<P>
   Just because Pincay tied the Shoemaker's record and didn't break
it Thursday, didn't mean there wasn't cause for celebration.
</P>
<P>
   Immediately following the race, a moving tribute in the winner's
circle honored both Pincay and Shoemaker. The only blemish of the
day was a faulty sound system that kept fans from hearing much of
what was said.
</P>
<P>
   Surrounded by his proud family and smiling friends, Pincay,
waving a Panamanian flag, was hoisted on the shoulders of his
fellow riders. They then paraded from the winner's circle to the
track.
</P>
<P>
   `I didn't know somebody was going to hand me a flag, but
somebody gave it to me and I took it and it was nice,'' Pincay
said. `There are a lot of people in Panama watching and I think
it's nice to show that I still remember Panama and all my family
and friends that I have over there.''
</P>
<P>
   Pincay can also number Shoemaker among his many friends. The
former jockey had nothing but kind words for the man who shares his
record and will soon break it.
</P>
<P>
   Shoemaker watched the race in the jock's room and cheered on
Pincay.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was very exciting for me,'' he said. ``I know it was an
emotional for Laffit because he's been trying hard to get this
done.''
</P>
<P>
   Pincay had been scheduled to ride just four horses Thursday, but
got an extra mount in the second race. Jockey Emile Ramsammy took
ill with stomach flu and was taken off heavy favorite De Witt.
</P>
<P>
   On short notice, trainer Bob Baffert elected to put Pincay
aboard the horse. Although the horse was in contention for the
entire 6{-furlong sprint, he ultimately finished second.
</P>
<P>
   After winning the fourth race, Pincay finished sixth aboard
Finally in the fifth. In the sixth he finished seventh on Justice
Bold. The seventh race saw Pincay finish fifth aboard Alert to Go.
All of his horses were contenders and most were heavily bet by
gamblers looking to take home a piece of history. A slip with the
right horse in the right race could become a collector's item.
</P>
<P>
   Pincay's five mounts today include Demidoll in the first; Flying
Journey in the third; Irish Nip in the sixth; Storm Dog in the
seventh and I Gotcha Covered in the eighth.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-10-99 0138EST &QL; 
