<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL _ (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST-ASSESS (Jerusalem) _ Analysis: A feeling that change was
imminent swept through Israel Thursday after President Clinton's
surprise announcement on Wednesday that Israeli-Syrian talks would
be resumed after nearly four years. Almost palpably, the national
pulse seemed to quicken _ for some with elation, for others with
anxiety. Even the Israeli right-wing, so uninspired these last few
months, girded up for a real opportunity. By Deborah Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   EUROPE-SUMMIT (Helsinki, Finland) _ Curtain-raiser on the
European summit conference, which is set to open Friday with
unexpected rancor. By Warren Hoge.
</P>
<P>
   ITALY-TV-HOLYYEAR (Rome) _ Italy, the country that perfected
housewife strip-tease quiz shows, is better known for pizazz than
piety on television. But on Dec. 25, a Roman Catholic Holy Year
begins, one that coincides with the 2,000th anniversary of the
birth of Jesus. So even on television, there will be little respite
from the Jubilee celebration. By Alessandra Stanley.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   WELFARE-WORKERS (Milwaukee) _ Lots of people consider themselves
experts on this city's war on welfare, but few have ridden its
highs and lows as intensely as Michael Steinborn. Eighteen months
ago, Steinborn was an unemployed jack of the building trades, down
on his luck and in need of a job. Improbably enough, he is now one
of the system's most popular caseworkers _ and a de facto authority
on the nation's most famous welfare experiment. By Jason DeParle.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-MARS-OCEAN (Undated) _ Scientists at Brown University say
they have found tantalizing evidence that the northern lowlands of
Mars once bore a wide ocean that, until it dried up, had waves,
hidden depths and long beaches. The findings are hailed as making
the best case yet for the existence of a sea on primordial Mars. By
William J. Broad.
</P>
<P>
   KING-TRIAL-ASSESS (Atlanta) _ With key players long dead, with
confessions recanted and altered, and with a vast conspiracy
alleged but not proven, Wednesday's verdict in the civil trial
connected to the assassination of Dr. Martin Luther King Jr. may
ultimately do little to demystify the tangle of fact and theory
surrounding one of the century's most traumatic events. By Kevin
Sack.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CAMPAIGN _ (Moved in ``p'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   GORE-BRADLEY (Washington) _ In his relentless attacks on Bill
Bradley, Vice President Al Gore is following closely to the script
written by his mentor, Bill Clinton. By Katharine Q. Seelye.
</P>
<P>
   TRUMP-ASSESS (Los Angeles) _ Is Donald Trump serious? In
interviews over a few days, a reporter tries to determine whether
the New York real estate tycoon really wants to be president. By
Adam Nagourney.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON _ (Moved in ``w'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   NTSB-CHALLENGES _ A look at the challenges faced by the National
Transportation Safety Board as it seeks to carry out its mandate.
By Matthew L. Wald.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS DAY _ (Moved in ``f'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   U.N.-CORPORATE-DONORS (Undated) _ Across the world, huge
companies that once shrugged off the United Nations as a worthy, if
often ineffectually bureaucratic, do-good agency are now viewing it
as a valuable partner. And the United Nations, for a change, is not
only welcoming their help but seeking it out. By Claudia H.
Deutsch.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   COCACOLA-NORRIS-COLUMN (Undated) _ Do you remember what a
two-liter bottle of Coke cost five or 10 years ago? Have prices
gone up? The answers to those questions go a long way toward
explaining why M. Douglas Ivester is leaving his job after little
more than two years as Coca-Cola's chief executive. It's hard to
sustain the stock price of a growth company when the company can't
raise prices. By Floyd Norris.
</P>
<P>
   EMAIL-AD-COLUMN (Undated) _ You usually don't want to stand in
the way of agencies rushing to complete deals before the end of the
year. That is even more true this month because the urge to
capitalize on the frenzy for interactive advertising, marketing and
media is spurring deal makers to finish up in, well, Internet time.
By Stuart Elliott.
</P>
