<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEN-KRIKORIAN-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
 
MEMORY STILL BITTER FOR McCULLOUCH 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DOUG KRIKORIAN  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   One of Poly High's more famous graduates, Earl McCullouch, plans
to be at Edison Field Saturday night to root for his alma mater
against Mater Dei in the CIF championship match.
</P>
<P>
   ``At least this Poly team has a chance to win it all,'' says
McCullouch wistfully. ``Unfortunately, we didn't. They took it away
from us for something we didn't even know was against the rules. We
were kicked out of the playoffs. That was 36 years ago, and I still
haven't forgotten it. It still hurts when I think about it. We were
deprived of an almost certain title because of a silly rule that no
one knew about.''
</P>
<P>
   Historians of Poly High athletics never will forget that the
Bill Mulligan-coached 1963 Jackrabbits were disqualified from the
playoffs after it was revealed that they had watched film of their
quarterfinal victim, El Rancho, before the game.
</P>
<P>
   What a crime!
</P>
<P>
   Imagine, Poly actually had to forfeit its victory over El Rancho
for such a dastardly indiscretion.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a rule the CIF put in for just that one year, and it
was a rule that I wasn't even aware existed,'' says Mulligan, who
was head football coach only that one season at Poly and who went
on to coach basketball at both USC and UC-Irvine. ``Aaron Wade
(then coach at Centennial) offered the film to me. His team had
faced El Rancho earlier in the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I watched it with the then-Poly athletic director, Sam
Iantorno, and then I watched it with my team. I know Iantorno
didn't know it was against the CIF rules, or he'd have never
allowed me to show it to my players.
</P>
<P>
   ``A few former Poly High players saw the film, and told some El
Rancho graduates who were attending Long Beach City College that
Poly was going to beat El Rancho. Well, the CIF got wind of it, and
all hell broke out after we did beat El Rancho. The CIF director,
Ken Fagans, waited until Monday to disqualify us. El Rancho took
our place.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What is so aggravating is that we would have beaten El Rancho
had we not watched the film,'' says McCullouch.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to McCullouch, a receiver who averaged more than 20
yards a carry on double reverses and ends-around, the Jackrabbits
had another future NFL star performing at quarterback in Gene
Washington and a slew of exceptional running backs in Marvin
Motley, Elwood Steward, Oscar Brown and Al Nichols.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a pretty good team,'' says McCullouch, who would go on
to become a world class 110-meter high hurdler and extraordinary
receiver with USC and then have an exceptional career with the
Detroit Lions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the team we had was even better than that legendary
Poly one of 1959 that had Willie Brown, Dee Andrews and Alonzo
Irvin,'' says the 69-year-old Mulligan, now a scout for the
Portland Trail Blazers and a resident of Irvine.
</P>
<P>
   Mulligan would gain a measure of solace later that season when
his Poly basketball team, led by Chuck Moore, Trent Gaines, Gene
Washington and a promising reserve named Mack Calvin, would win the
CIF title.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our fans booed Ken Fagans at the presentation of the
championship trophy,'' recalls Mulligan.
</P>
<P>
   Earl McCullouch isn't surprised that Poly High has maintained
its dominance on the football field across the years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Poly High kind of reminds me of how USC was in the 1960s and
1970s,'' says McCullouch. ``There's just such great tradition
there, and it's carried on from one generation to the next.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember when I moved here from Bakersfield, and heard all
about Dee Andrews, Willie Brown, Alonzo Irwin and all the other
great Poly stars. A lot of us young guys wanted to be like them,
and I think that inspired us. I honestly think Poly is the best
high school in the United States in scholarship and athletics.''
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, McCullouch's youngest child, Dawn McCullouch, is
currently attending Wilson High, where she's good enough of a
basketball player to already have earned a scholarship next year to
Rutgers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was Dawn's choice to go to Wilson,'' explains McCullouch.
``I've always let my kids make their own decisions about what high
school they want to go to. My other four all chose Poly.''
</P>
<P>
   The 54-year-old McCullouch these days is a night manager at the
Federal Express facility at LAX, and on his off days can be found
handicapping horses at Los Alamitos with old pals like Alonzo
Irvin.
</P>
<P>
   ``Naturally, I'm picking Poly to beat Mater Dei this time,''
says McCullouch. ``I hear the defense they have is pretty mean. At
least they're getting a chance to play for the title. I wish we had
been given such a chance.'' ...
</P>
<P>
   After watching a special screening the other night in Westwood
of Ron Shelton's ``Play It To The Bone'', I'll be surprised if this
comic-drama boxing yarn featuring Woody Harrelson, Antonio
Banderas, Lolita Davidovich, Robert Wagner and Tom Sizemore isn't a
huge hit and a recipient of a few Academy Award nominations.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, this is the most entertaining fight film I've ever seen,
and, yes, I've seen ``Raging Bull'', ``Rocky'', ``Body &AMP; Soul'',
``The Champ'', etc.
</P>
<P>
   I think this is Shelton's best film, exceeding even his much
acclaimed ``Bull Durham'', as well as ``White Men Can't Jump'',
``Tin Cup'', and ``Blaze''.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, I might be slightly biased since I do make a couple
of appearances I'm one of the ringside sportswriters in the film,
as do a couple of my pals, Johnny (The Downey Flash) Ortiz and Bill
(Bozo) Caplan.
</P>
<P>
   But Shelton trusted Ortiz and Caplan enough to give them a few
lines of dialogue. Me? Well, at least I got my name in the credits.
...
</P>
<P>
   When Magic Johnson was 21, he knew how to play basketball and
never made all those vexing turnovers that continue to haunt Kobe
Bryant. . .
</P>
<P>
   I'll be surprised if Charles Barkley doesn't attempt to play in
the NBA again. ...
</P>
<P>
   When I covered Bill Bradley as an NBA player, I always found him
to be remote and even arrogant. ...
</P>
<P>
   The ring record book will show that Fernando Vargas beat Winky
Wright for the IBF junior middleweight title last Saturday evening
in Lincoln City, Ore. Don't believe it.
</P>
<P>
   This was just another example in boxing where a deserving
veteran who can fight is sacrificed by the establishment for a
heralded youngster with a more promising future.
</P>
<P>
   But what Winky Wright did do was expose Fernando Vargas for what
he is and what he is is not another Oscar De La Hoya. ...
</P>
<P>
   One of Southern California's most talked about bodyguards, Mike
(The Hammer) DiMarzo, is on the mend after breaking his left leg in
a mysterious golf cart accident in the hills of Bel Air. None of
the people DiMarzo was protecting were injured. . .
</P>
<P>
   Where are the laws of compensation when it comes to Georgia
Frontiere? ...
</P>
<P>
   I'm sure the person who thought up mute buttons on TV remotes
had in mind Dick Vitale, the Most Irritating Man In America.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
