<SLUG> BC-SOC-UCLA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOURNEY NO WALK IN THE PARK FOR UCLA SOCCER DUO
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LEE BARNATHAN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ As UCLA and Indiana compete in Friday's NCAA men's
soccer semifinal in Charlotte, N.C., the Indiana players will
survey the Bruins defense, taking note of Steve Shak and Adam
Cooper's locations and tendencies.
</P>
<P>
   They'll see Shak and Cooper are solid players. What they won't
see, however, is they began as walk-ons.
</P>
<P>
   Rarely does a nonscholarship player start on a team playing in
the national semifinals. UCLA has Cooper. Shak was a walk-on his
first two seasons before winning a scholarship.
</P>
<P>
   Here they are, joining the rest of the unseeded Bruins (19-2) in
the College Cup at Ericsson Stadium. They play second-seeded and
defending champion Indiana (19-3) at 3:30 p.m. PST.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've proven it as seniors they can play soccer at this
level,'' UCLA coach Todd Saldana said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always take a step back and say, `I'm playing for one of the
best programs in the nation, that's in the top five every year,'''
said Cooper, a Calabasas graduate. ``It's a dream come true.''
</P>
<P>
   At least Cooper was a recruited walk-on, having impressed
then-assistant coach Saldana at a UCLA summer camp. No one knew who
Shak was.
</P>
<P>
   Shak was academically accepted to UCLA but loved soccer enough
to consider a tryout. He impressed then-coach Sigi Schmid enough to
earn a spot.
</P>
<P>
   But he never saw a minute of playing time. He came in 1996 with
an eight-member recruiting class that includes current seniors
Sasha Victorine (who won the Missouri Athletic Club's Player of the
Year award this week), Pete Vagenas, Nick Paneno, Martin Bruno and
Shea Travis.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was the ninth guy, so I was the only guy without a soccer
roommate,'' Shak said.
</P>
<P>
   His game days were practices, so he practiced like he would
play. The next season, Schmid put him in the first match for a few
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The next match, Shak started.
</P>
<P>
   ``My goal was to make the practice squad,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   That season, UCLA's defense shut out 14 opponents and won the
national championship. Shak earned the Bruins' Most Improved Player
award.
</P>
<P>
   Things have improved since. Shak has played in the U.S. Soccer
Festival and on the national under-23 team that won a bronze medal
at the 1999 Pan American Games.
</P>
<P>
   Cooper's road has been longer but no less rewarding, especially
when it's revealed he played just one year of club soccer.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, Cooper's an AYSO graduate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know one single person in Division I who didn't play
club,'' Cooper said, ``except myself.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That really inspires younger kids,'' Shak said. ``They think
they have to play club to reach the highest level. Sometimes,
that's not the case.''
</P>
<P>
   Cooper redshirted the 1997 season with an torn abdominal muscle.
Because he felt pain in his groin, doctors first misdiagnosed the
problem as a groin injury, so it took time to find the tear was
higher in his body.
</P>
<P>
   But Cooper, who played all of 53 minutes in his first season and
never more than 48 in any match his sophomore season, was so eager
to return he aggressively rehabilitated.
</P>
<P>
   By 1998, his minutes had tripled, and he had scored his first
goal.
</P>
<P>
   This season, he has excelled as a marking back, in part because
Saldana switched to a more standard defense.
</P>
<P>
   If the unseeded Bruins beat Indiana, they'll play either
unseeded Santa Clara or No. 4 Connecticut on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Saldana, while pleased with his two walk-ons, isn't surprised.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're put in the toughest environment. It's either sink or
swim,'' Saldana said. ``Steve Shak and Adam Cooper have stepped
forward.''
</P>
</TEXT>
