<HEADER>
A4972 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a BC-BREAKUP-LAUSD-LADN     12-10 1233
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BREAKUP-LAUSD-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCHOOL DISTRICT BREAKUP PETITIONS FILED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By Greg Gittrich  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- After two years of collecting signatures, a group
working to break up the Los Angeles Unified School District has
filed petitions to force hearings that could lead to a public vote.
</P>
<P>
   Finally Restoring Excellence in Education, based in Los Angeles'
San Fernando Valley, announced on Thursday it has more than the
21,000 signatures needed to push its plan to split the district
into North Valley and South Valley school districts. The dividing
line would run across Saticoy Street and Roscoe Boulevard.
</P>
<P>
   FREE officials said their plan would create two racially and
ethnically diverse public school systems that are large enough to
win state and federal funds, but small enough to improve public
education in the Valley.
</P>
<P>
   ``This plan will give San Fernando Valley parents neighborhood
schools. Schools where parents can partner with teachers and local
administrators to meet the educational needs of every child,'' said
former state Assemblywoman Paula Boland, chairwoman of FREE.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a wonderful holiday present to the people of the
Valley,'' Boland said, adding that her group collected more than
30,000 signatures. ``We're in good shape. I'm sure any and all
groups that care about kids will support us.''
</P>
<P>
   The county Office of Education and state Board of Education must
approve the plan to cut up the nation's second-largest school
district, and voters would have to endorse it in a special
election.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles school board President Genethia Hayes said the
breakup movement is ill-timed because it does not take into account
sweeping administrative and curriculum-based reforms in recent
months.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the things they want are possible now, and all they can do
is bitch and gripe,'' said Hayes, one of four board members elected
on a reform platform earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   Board member Julie Korenstein, who has often found herself at
odds with the new board majority, said she supports a Valley
breakaway, but would endorse only the creation of one new district.
</P>
<P>
   Carving the Valley into two new public school systems would
create too much new bureaucracy, said Korenstein, who represents a
large portion of the potentially affected areas.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'd have two superintendents, two school boards. There would
be major duplication,'' she argued.
</P>
<P>
   Incoming Superintendent Ramon C. Cortines declined to express
his position on attempts to dismantle Los Angeles Unified, which
has an enrollment of more than 710,000 students. Through a
spokesperson, Cortines referred to the matter as political and
therefore not something he intends to get involved in.
</P>
<P>
   Board member Caprice Young, one Los Angeles Unified's three
newly elected board members, said she has confidence that the new
regime's changes will have improved the district substantially
before FREE's plan makes it to the polls.
</P>
<P>
   ``My sincere hope is the day this hits the ballot,'' Young said,
``people will vote no because we will have fixed the district. We
have made a lot of progress.''
</P>
<P>
   FREE sees it differently.
</P>
<P>
   Stephanie Carter, a former teacher and co-chairwoman of FREE,
said Los Angeles Unified's ``current one-size-fits-all mentality''
of delivering programs ``has proven not only ineffective, but
alienating.''
</P>
<P>
   ``New, smaller districts will redirect the focus to the
educational needs of all the children,'' Carter said.
</P>
<P>
   FREE's petition comes as momentum builds among legislators and
activists fed up with Los Angeles Unified's low test scores,
shortage of qualified teachers, downtown administrative upheaval
and botched construction projects.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the movements are much younger than FREE's, having been
formed only in recent months out of outrage to the district's
handling of the Belmont Learning Center scandal and the board's
decision to oust Superintendent Ruben Zacarias.
</P>
<P>
   State Sen. Richard Polanco, D-Los Angeles, expects to submit
legislation in the new year to launch a breakup study, and other
area lawmakers have signaled their support for the measure.
</P>
<P>
   Breakup groups in the Valley, Los Angeles, Carson, Lomita and
Garden Grove have formed a coalition and begun drafting a single
plan uniting their efforts, hoping to gain clout by working
together.
</P>
<P>
   The Coalition to Break Away from LAUSD includes Valley Voters
Organized Toward Empowerment, which recently rolled out an
exploratory committee to examine the idea of forming a Valley
school district.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, the Los Angeles City/County Latino Redistricting
Coalition has backed a plan to divide the public school system into
six autonomous districts, including an east-west split of the
Valley.
</P>
<P>
   Activists in the South Bay also jumped into the fray this year,
pursuing a secession study in the Wilmington and San Pedro sections
of Los Angeles Unified. They hope to join with neighboring Lomita
and Carson to create a district that would still be large enough to
pull some weight in Sacramento.
</P>
<P>
   The state's Little Hoover Commission weighed in on the matter,
issuing a harshly critical report on LAUSD in October that called
for a breakup study.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike other movements, the Latino Redistricting Coalition's
plan would slice up Los Angeles Unified based upon socioeconomic
factors, regional identity and race, according to Allan Clayton,
the movement's regional chairman.
</P>
<P>
   Such a plan raises legal questions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm worried about the resegregation of many little districts
in this city,'' Hayes said.
</P>
<P>
   The state's education code requires that the reorganization of a
school district not promote segregation. The code, however, does
not specify what ratios among races and ethnicities are acceptable,
creating a judgment call for legislators.
</P>
<P>
   Even with attempts like FREE's to create new districts with
diverse student populations, the school board president argued
``you would still be left with the possibility of some districts
that would be comprised mostly of communities of color.''
</P>
<P>
   The Los Angeles County Office of Education must verify the
signatures on FREE's petition by Dec. 29.
</P>
<P>
   If the petition is valid, the Los Angeles County Committee on
School District Organization would discuss the plan at its Jan. 5
meeting and hold public hearings in the affected areas within next
60 days.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the county committee, which consists of 11
elected members, would conduct an independent study into the
benefits and drawbacks of FREE's plan.
</P>
<P>
   The commission would review the plan based upon nine conditions
and four other criteria, including the number of pupils in the
proposed district, the resulting distribution of school property
with the original district, and racial diversity.
</P>
<P>
   By March 6, the commission would be required to make a
recommendation to the state Board of Education, which would then
review the plan. The state could take as much time as it needed to
act.
</P>
<P>
   If the state board agrees, a special election would be held in
the area that state education officials determine would be affected
by the breakup.
</P>
<P>
   If a majority of voters back the plan, the Los Angeles County
Board of Supervisors would implement the creation of the two new
Valley districts over an unspecified period of time.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-10-99 0158EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991210.0036 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-10 02:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4973 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-RAC-HORSE-COLUMN-LADN     12-10 1149
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-HORSE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HAPPY FOR NOW WITH DEAD HEAT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ The mountain came equipped with a wheelchair
ramp.
</P>
<P>
   That way, Laffit Pincay could share the summit with Bill
Shoemaker on Thursday, the two winningest jockeys in history
basking in the rarefied air of mutual admiration.
</P>
<P>
   Something felt so right about this, about Pincay calmly
answering reporters' questions from behind a dais in a tunnel
outside the Hollywood Park jockeys' room, about Shoemaker sipping
and puffing his electronic wheelchair up a wooden ramp to sit
beside him.
</P>
<P>
   If only they could have stood side by side. If only Shoemaker
hadn't lost the use of his arms and legs in a 1991 freeway
accident.
</P>
<P>
   But at least in spirit, they did stand together.
</P>
<P>
   Pincay will break the Shoe's record as early as today, but until
that happens, the two old friends and rivals seem pleased and proud
to be tied, each with 8,833 victories.
</P>
<P>
   Outside, in the winner's circle ceremony, Shoemaker had referred
to Pincay reaching ``the top of the mountain.'' Later, at the press
conference, he said he's happy to have company there.
</P>
<P>
   ``It feels good only because it's Laffit Pincay,'' said
Shoemaker, the living icon of American thoroughbred racing, dressed
in a blue blazer, white turtleneck shirt and red wool scarf. ``He's
been a good friend of mine for 35 years, ever since he came from
Panama.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, I didn't know then that he was going to break my
record. I didn't even know I was going to break the record.''
</P>
<P>
   They met four years before Shoemaker took the record from Johnny
Longden with his 6,033rd winner on Sept. 7, 1970 at Del Mar. They
became buddies, competed shoulder to shoulder during the day at
Hollywood Park, Santa Anita and Del Mar, in some of the greatest
races of the 1970s and '80s, and celebrated each other's victories
together at night.
</P>
<P>
   Shoemaker, 68, watched Pincay's record-tying victory aboard I Be
Casual in the fourth race on television in the jockeys' room.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's where I'm most comfortable, I think,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody (the idle jockeys) was rooting for him very hard,
including me,'' Shoemaker said of the scene in the jockeys' room.
</P>
<P>
   It was a nip-and-tuck race as I Be Casual, a maiden gelding,
needed every tap of Pincay's left-handed whip and nearly the length
of the stretch to win the 6-furlong sprint by a head.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looked like he was going to get up,'' Shoemaker said,
``then it looked like he wasn't, then it looked like he was ...''
</P>
<P>
   Which also describes Pincay's pursuit of Shoemaker, the only
thing that has kept the 52-year-old Hall of Famer riding into his
35th season.
</P>
<P>
   Shoemaker said he first considered the possibility Pincay would
break his record when the younger man drew within 300 or 400
victories. At that point, though, Pincay was struggling without
choice mounts and had worried he might have to leave the
major-league Southern California circuit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew if he could stay healthy, he could do it,'' Shoemaker
said.
</P>
<P>
   Back in 1970, on the verge of Longden's record, Shoemaker went
into a slump and needed a week to break it. He was asked if he had
any advice for Pincay.
</P>
<P>
   ``He doesn't need any advice from me or anybody else,''
Shoemaker said. ``The only thing I want him to do is get to
9,000.''
</P>
<P>
   The weekend: Defending champion Manistique (ridden by Corey
Nakatani) is assigned 124 pounds, six to 13 more than his
opponents, in the Bayakoa Handicap for fillies and mares at
Hollywood Park on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, General Challenge (Chris McCarron) is the 123-pound high
weight for the Native Diver Handicap, the 3-year-old Pacific
Classic winner's first start since his 10th-place finish in the
Breeders' Cup Classic.
</P>
<P>
   The Native Diver, only a Grade III race according to the
national committee that decides such things, has an impressive list
of winners in the 1990s, including major-stakes winners Twilight
Agenda, Sir Beaufort, Slew of Damascus, Best Pal, Alphabet Soup,
Gentlemen and Puerto Madero.
</P>
<P>
   __The United States will be represented in the rich races at
Hong Kong's Sha Tin on Sunday by two California horses, Big Jag in
the $700,000 Hong Kong Sprint and Self Feeder in the $900,000 Hong
Kong Mile.
</P>
<P>
   __Pincay said he'll ride his six scheduled mounts at Hollywood
Park Saturday whether or not he has already broken the record.
There had been a chance he'd go to Turf Paradise in Phoenix for a
stakes race.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
A WEEK AT THE RACES &QL; 
Hollywood Park leaders: Jockeys (through Wednesday): Laffit Pincay,
20 wins; Pat Valenzuela, 19; Alex Solis, 16; Corey Nakatani, 14;
Isaias Enriquez, David Flores and Martin Pedroza, 9. Trainers: Bob
Baffert and Richard Mandella, 9; Jack Carava, 8; Wesley Ward, 6;
Paul Aguirre, Bobby Frankel and Mike Mitchell, 5. &QL; 
Handicapper helper: Unless you're a souvenir hunter, a wager on
Laffit Pincay offers poor value these days. Pincay's horses were
bet down from their morning line odds by a factor of nearly 40
percent Wednesday and Thursday. &QL; 
On the stakes schedule: At Hollywood Park: Saturday, $150,000
Bayakoa Handicap, fillies and mares 3 and up, 1 1/16 miles; Sunday,
$100,000 Native Diver Handicap, 3-year-olds and up, 1 1/8 miles. At
Sha Tin Race Course, Hong Kong: Sunday, $1.3 million Hong Kong Cup,
3-year-olds and up, 1 1/4 miles on turf. &QL; 
Mileposts: Eoin Harty, the assistant trainer who deserves some
credit for Bob Baffert's success, has been hired by Godolphin
Racing to prepare its young horses for the Triple Crown. The
Irish-born Harty, 37, will split the year between Dubai and the
United States. Sheikh Mohammed's Godolphin operation made its first
try at the Triple Crown this year when Worldly Manner finished
seventh in the Kentucky Derby.... Pat Valenzuela recorded his
3,000th victory aboard Sexy Too last Saturday. Valenzuela,
sidetracked by suspensions, is 37. Laffit Pincay won his 3,000th at
28.... A Jan. 1 national riders' strike apparently has been averted
with a reported three-year contract agreement increasing the
amounts tracks pay to the Jockeys' Guild insurance program....
Breeders' Cup Juvenile winner Anees returned to trainer Alex
Hassinger at Santa Anita after a 20-day freshening, and could begin
his Derby preparations with the Jan. 30 Santa Catalina Stakes....
Hollywood Park will play host to a 10-race, $1.2-million program of
stakes for California-breds April 30, 2000 _ sort of a midterm Cal
Cup. The card, headed by the $250,000 Snow Chief for 3-year-olds,
will combine existing stakes previously held on separate days....
Hollywood Park's summer Shoemaker Mile has been moved up from Grade
II to Grade I. Silic won the race this year on his way to a
Breeders' Cup Mile triumph.... Canadian International winner
Thornfield was voted Canada's Horse of the Year.
</P>
</TEXT>
