<SLUG> BC-GEN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNLIKE SHAQ, TRACK STAR ARNOLD RELISHES OLYMPICS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Shaquille O'Neal would sooner see Greg Ostertag
come after him than his country.
</P>
<P>
   That all-expenses-paid trip to the other side of the world that
Uncle Sam is dangling in front of the Lakers center like a Krispy
Kreme doughnut? O'Neal has made it abundantly clear he's not at all
tempted.
</P>
<P>
   Heck, no, he won't go.
</P>
<P>
   The other day O'Neal sounded like a man who'd burn his passport
rather than get on that chartered airplane to Sydney to serve his
country as part of the basketball battalion in the 2000 Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've already got (a) gold medal,'' O'Neal said, making it
sound more like a battle wound than a badge of honor.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, he explained, summer is his time for relaxing and
rapping. Why should he sacrifice all that to spend a few weeks in
one of the most desirable destinations on the planet, working up a
sweat against the likes of Lithuania?
</P>
<P>
   It's a tough life, being one of the few, the chosen; a
prospective Olympian.
</P>
<P>
   But don't ask O'Neal about it. A better person to consult would
be Dominique Arnold, a track athlete who has the 10th-fastest time
in the world this year in the 110-meter high hurdles.
</P>
<P>
   You can find Arnold on the Cal State Northridge track most
mornings and at The Home Depot in Canoga Park in the afternoons.
His job there, secured through the Olympic Job Opportunities
Program, is nothing like O'Neal's dabbling in rap during the
off-season.
</P>
<P>
   Arnold is not moving plywood off the shelves as some kind of
lark. It's the way he makes ends meet while clearing the hurdles,
both real and metaphorical, that stand between him and the
Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   When we caught up with the 25-year-old Arnold Thursday morning
at CSUN, he was none too pleased to hear O'Neal talk about dodging
the Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   ``It definitely bothers me to hear him say those things,''
Arnold said, ``because I've been through hell and back trying to
get there. To miss out on an opportunity to represent your country
in an event of that magnitude, I don't understand that at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Our purpose here today is not to pick on O'Neal, who was just
being honest. The truth is, the sentiments he expressed aren't
anything we haven't heard before from tennis-playing millionaires
and puckish hockey players.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal mumbles and his words rumble like an avalanche down theon
down _ are on the take these days, the symbol of the Games ought to
be changed. The five concentric rings should be replaced by a line
of zeroes broken only by commas.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the cash is even exchanging hands above the table.
</P>
<P>
   John Godina, a former UCLA standout who is among the world's
best shot putters and discus throwers, will make more money this
year in endorsements and prize money than quarterback Kurt Warner
will clear with the Rams.
</P>
<P>
   'Twas not always so.
</P>
<P>
   The pursuit of sporting excellence long has been a full-time
job. Until recently, it wasn't much help paying the bills. The
reconfiguring of amateur guidelines over the past 20 years has made
it possible for world-class athletes to have their Olympic dreams
and eat, too.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, for every Godina there continues to be many more
Arnolds.
</P>
<P>
   Arnold, a graduate of Long Beach Wilson and Washington State,
came late to the hurdles (he was a junior in high school when he
first started racing) and retired early, in 1997 after suffering a
groin injury that was slow to heal.
</P>
<P>
   CSUN coach Jeff McAuley coaxed Arnold back onto the track and
the hurdler since has gained a lot of ground on the world's best.
He placed fourth in the 110-meter high hurdles at this year's Pan
American Games after missing a berth on the U.S. team that competed
in the World Championships in Spain by one spot.
</P>
<P>
   Arnold was improving despite keeping a schedule only an
insomniac could love. Until just recently he worked behind the
registration desk at a Howard Johnsons from 11 p.m. until 7 a.m.,
grabbed two hours of sleep, then practiced at CSUN for another
three.
</P>
<P>
   The Home Depot job affords Arnold a much more sane schedule. And
yet there remain obstacles even after he leaves the track.
</P>
<P>
   Ask him why he continues to chase a finishing line so few reach
and Arnold talks about maximizing his God-given talent. He speaks
eloquently of ``feeling the wind blowing through my head when I'm
running fast.''
</P>
<P>
   And he talks about honoring the country that has given him the
freedom to chase all his dreams, on and off the track.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was in Europe racing this summer I understood why
people get on planes and come over here and kiss the ground,''
Arnold said. ``Being over there made me appreciate the privileges
and opportunities we have in the United States. It made me want to
wear USA on my chest.''
</P>
<P>
   For Arnold _ and for swimmers and wrestlers and gymnasts and
fencers and archers like him _ the Olympics is Mount Everest. It's
the ultimate sporting experience, unlike the tennis players who
have the Grand Slam, the hockey players who have the Stanley Cup
Finals and the basketball players who have the NBA Finals.
</P>
<P>
   If a hockey player such as Keith Tkachuk or a basketball player
like O'Neal is eligible to compete in the Olympics, so be it. If
they choose to pass on the event, that's their prerogative.
</P>
<P>
   We just wish they'd step away from the mirror long enough to see
the Olympics through Dominique Arnold's eyes. Then maybe they'd
recognize its allure.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-10-99 0206EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
