r s BC-BKC-GONZAGA-LADN     12-10 0789
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-GONZAGA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GONZAGA TRIES TO RECAPTURE MARCH MAGIC
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ It's time for a name change for those lovable
gunners from Spokane.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzaga.com seems appropriate, considering expectations of the
No. 24 Bulldogs have risen faster than Internet stocks.
</P>
<P>
   This time last year, after a loss to Detroit Mercy, the Bulldogs
were 4-3 and wondering if they'd make the NCAA Tournament. They
did, of course, vanquishing Minnesota, Stanford and Florida before
a five-point loss to eventual champion Connecticut in a riveting
West Regional final.
</P>
<P>
   This season, with three starters back, the Bulldogs (4-2) are
being compared to the best teams nationally, not the best in the
West Coast Conference.
</P>
<P>
   ``We beat Montana by 15, and people said we should have won by
more,'' Gonzaga coach Mark Few said. ``We battle back against
Cincinnati and lose by seven, and everyone wants to know why we had
to battle back. Expectations are way, way out of whack.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we can't control what the polls say, or what a guy from
Redondo Beach thinks, or what a physics major on campus thinks. We
can't get caught up in the expectations. And so far, we haven't.
The kids still have their perspective.''
</P>
<P>
   That's not all. They still have savvy point guard Matt
Santangelo, who's considered an NBA prospect. They have super
shooter Richie Frahm. They have powerful, athletic forward Casey
Calvary. And they have the same precision offense that sliced up
Stanford and is bound to frustrate No. 11 UCLA when the teams
collide Saturday in Pauley Pavilion.
</P>
<P>
   ``They put on an offense clinic every time they take the
floor,'' Bruins coach Steve Lavin said. ``They're similar to
Princeton. They play at a higher speed and shoot it quicker, but
they're like Princeton.''
</P>
<P>
   That's not good news for UCLA. Not now, not ever. But the Bruins
(3-0) will have one grand advantage Saturday: rest. They haven't
played since a 61-point victory over Morgan State nine days ago
while Gonzaga has twice traveled long distance in that span.
</P>
<P>
   The Bulldogs lost to Cincinnati in Cleveland last weekend,
returned to campus for two days, lost to Temple in Chicago on
Wednesday in the Great Eight, then returned to campus again for two
days for final exams. They are scheduled to arrive in Los Angeles
tonight. Will their legs make the trip?
</P>
<P>
   ``Those games are good for us, it just happened that they all
ended up one on top of another,'' Few said. ``It would have been
nice to have a week to prepare for UCLA, instead of a day. They
have a week to prepare for us.''
</P>
<P>
   But these are not the same Bulldogs the nation embraced last
spring _ not in personnel or performance.
</P>
<P>
   They're defending well and rebounding well, but something's
amiss on offense. Perhaps its a rhythm thing that will develop over
time. Perhaps it's a change in dynamics they won't ever correct _
March Magic lost forever. Whatever the reason, the Bulldogs are
shooting 26.1 percent from 3-point range after a 6-of-37
performance against Temple. Frahm, the chief bombadier, is shooting
20.5 percent. Santangelo isn't much better at 28.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not playing that well,'' Santangelo said. ``We're not
doing the little things that made us successful. I don't know when
we'll start clicking. As good as we are offensively, I'm sure we're
not far away.''
</P>
<P>
   No doubt, the Bulldogs are adjusting to the departure of coach
Dan Monson, who took the Minnesota job in July after signing a
10-year extension with Gonzaga. Few, a longtime assistant,
recruited many of the Bulldogs and has kept Monson's motion offense
intact, but no coaching change is seamless.
</P>
<P>
   First-team all-West Coast Conference center Jeremy Eaton is
gone, along with his leadership and 12 points per game. (Axel
Dench, a 6-11 senior, has replaced Eaton as the starting center.)
</P>
<P>
   But the most significant loss _ bigger, even, than Monson _ is
point guard Quentin Hall. He teamed with Santangelo to provide a
double-dose of ballhandling. He collapsed defenses with
penetration, which created open 3-point attempts for Frahm. He gave
Gonzaga its speed and its nerve.
</P>
<P>
   ``Quentin got a lot of easy shots for everybody,'' Few said.
``He was fearless, and we fed off that. He was the guy who, if
(Cincinnati center) Kenyon Martin says something, he'd say it right
back.''
</P>
<P>
   Hall also would have known what to do about those darn
expectations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Teams are coming after us, and we need to be able to hold
serve,'' Santangelo said. ``But this is what we all hoped for when
we decided to play college basketball. Whether we win or lose,
we've got stories to tell our grandkids.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
