<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-WORLD-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. BEATS WORLD ALL-STARS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED J. ROBLEDO  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM _ The screams sounded more like it was an 'N Sync or 98
Degrees concert, but the red-white-and-blue painted faces revealed
who was really in town.
</P>
<P>
   Sports Illustrated's sportswomen of the year, the Women's World
Cup champion Team USA squad, brought its ``Toys R US,'' Victory
Tour to The Pond on Thursday, beating a group of World All-Stars,
9-7, in front of 11,613.
</P>
<P>
   Kristine Lilly scored five goals for Team USA, which visited the
Southland for the first time since beating China in the Women's
World Cup final last July at the Rose Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the U.S. is nearing the end of what feels like an extended
victory lap, completing the final leg of the 12-city indoor tour
this month.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. team has three stops left, heading north to San Jose
(Saturday), Tacoma, WA. (Sunday), and then Portland Dec. 15.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do only have three games left, but I think the enthusiasm
is still building,'' said defender Brandi Chastain. ``It's
exciting, from the opening whistle the crowds have really been into
it and that get's us going.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the U.S. team finished its final training camp for
1999 in San Diego, saying goodbye to coach Tony DiCicco. The former
U.S. coach guided the U.S. to the 1996 Olympic Games gold medal as
well as this summer's World Cup. DiCicco, who retired in October,
leaves as the all-time winningest U.S. coach, compiling a 103-8-8
record in five years.
</P>
<P>
   Aaron Heifetz, press office for the U.S. Soccer Federation, said
he expects a successor to be named by mid-January, but wouldn't be
surprised if a new coach was named in the next few weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. team learned Tuesday that it will not have four years
to call itself world champions. FIFA, international soccer's
governing body, announced that the next Women's World Cup will be
held in 2002 instead of 2003.
</P>
<P>
   FIFA made the change to avoid using the Women's World Cup as a
qualifying tournament for the Olympics, as it did with this year's
World Cup. By moving the World Cup to 2002, FIFA can now have an
Olympic qualifying tournament in 2003 for the 2004 Olympic games in
Athens.
</P>
<P>
   The problem with the switch, however, is that the men's World
Cup also competes in 2002, leaving the women wondering if that's
too much soccer for the American public to handle in a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``This summer was an indication of how well this tournament can
do on its own,'' said Chastain. ``There's no need to piggy-back it
with the men's tournament, even if they're giving some excuse that
teams need to qualify for the Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's ludicrous. The tournament needs to be a
stand-alone event for the very fact that it stood alone this summer
and drew greater crowds than playoff football and almost as many
people as the Pope (when he visited here).''
</P>
<P>
   Even Marla Messing, President of this summer's Women's World
Cup, was a little skeptical.
</P>
<P>
   ``Initially, I was surprised and I think I'm still digesting the
decision,'' said Messing. ``I've heard they made the decision to
promote women's soccer which I'm a strong proponent of. But I think
it's difficult and will bring significant challenges.''
</P>
<P>
   The women will likely lose media coverage, with most news
organizations spending their resources on the men, rather than the
women.
</P>
<P>
   ``FIFA is a smart organization and they have done wonders for
men's soccer, but I hope what they're doing will bear fruit for the
women's game,'' said Messing. ``Hopefully, people will look at this
as a really big year for the sport of soccer. I just hope FIFA
preserves their resources and spends wisely that year.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
