<SLUG> BC-MINIMED-SHARES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MINIMED PRICE DIPS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By Jason D. Cohen  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- As they witness the slide of their stock price,
officials at insulin pump maker MiniMed struggled Thursday to find
reason in the market's fickle ways.
</P>
<P>
   The company, based in the Los Angeles-area community of Sylmar,
has absorbed two recent body blows. Rival Cygnus Inc., a Redwood
City, Ca.-based medical products developer, is nearing approval on
a product that will rival one of MiniMed's main lines. And the
company found a flaw in its newest insulin pump and had to notify
customers of this development.
</P>
<P>
   But neither should have driven down MiniMed's stock by half,
chief financial officer Kevin Sayer said. The stock price has
fallen 51.8 percent from its 52-week high of $108.25.
</P>
<P>
   The slide continued on Thursday, with shares losing 7.73 percent
to close at $52.25 per share.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our business is fine. I really don't have an explanation for
what's going on,'' Sayer said. ``Cygnus' approval (of a rival
glucose monitor) has created some confusion among our investors.''
</P>
<P>
   Kurt Kruger, medical devices analyst for Banc of America
Montgomery Securities, said the real issue among investors is
figuring out just how quickly the company will grow in the next
year or so.
</P>
<P>
   Kruger said the Cygnus issue is not the real problem but that
the investment community is re-evaluating MiniMed's growth.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are all scratching our heads, wondering what the company's
underlying growth rate is in the next few quarters,'' Kruger said.
</P>
<P>
   Kruger still recommends the stock as a buy and has not
downgraded his earnings estimate of 21 cents per share for the
fourth quarter, but he believes the company might not grow as
rapidly as previously thought.
</P>
<P>
   Cygnus has designed a glucose monitor and a U.S. Food and Drug
Administration panel has recommended its approval.
</P>
<P>
   MiniMed already has a monitor on the market.
</P>
<P>
   These devices continuously measure blood glucose levels.
MimiMed's is inserted under the skin and Cygnus' is external.
</P>
<P>
   MiniMed says its monitor takes more measurements per day than
the Cygnus product and does not require a finger prick test for
calibration.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, MiniMed hopes to marry its continuous glucose
monitoring system with its insulin infusion pumps to create a
product that both monitors and adjusts a diabetes patient's blood
sugar levels.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
