<HEADLINE>
VERTEL SHARES GET MAJOR BOOST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By Jason Z. Cohen  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- A day after introducing its new product to the
telecommunications market, Vertel Inc. saw its shares rise sharply
for the second consecutive session Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The company's shares increased 179.6 percent a day after
announcing the company has secured a major purchaser for its e-ORB
technology.
</P>
<P>
   New Jersey-based optical switch maker Tellium will install
Vertel's e-ORB in its newest product, a switch for fiber optic
networks on which much of the Internet's traffic travels.
</P>
<P>
   Vertel spokeswoman Sandy Christopher said the market's response
to the new product has been outstanding.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is very significant for us because it is a technology
that's taking us into the future,'' Christopher said.
</P>
<P>
   E-ORB is an object request broker, a piece of software that
manages the movement of data. It is designed to work under various
software platforms, including Linux and Microsoft NT.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're really happy because this is the area we wanted to get
into as we move into the future,'' Christopher said.
</P>
<P>
   Vertel introduced e-ORB at a telecommunications conference in
Las Vegas on Wednesday, Christopher said. The response was
immediate, with the company's stock gaining more than 40 percent in
afternoon trading. The increase continued Thursday until the stock,
which was lingering around $2 per share before the announcement,
closed at $9 per share.
</P>
<P>
   More than 24.4 million shares traded hands Thursday, a stunning
amount considering the company has only 25.5 million shares
outstanding.!dlim!!end!
</P>
