<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SEX-HARASS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 STATE JUSTICES LIMIT SCOPE OF SEX HARASS LAWSUITS  &HT;     By HARRIET CHIANG 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The California Supreme Court limited the scope
of sexual harassment suits Thursday, ruling that victims can sue
their employers but not the co-workers who harassed them.
</P>
<P>
   By a unanimous vote, the high court said the state's harassment
laws apply only to employers who know or should know about the
offensive conduct and do not stop it.
</P>
<P>
   If an employer fails to take ``immediate and appropriate
corrective action,'' Justice Ming Chin wrote in the court's
opinion, ``there may be an unlawful employment practice, but it is
by the employer, not the co-worker.''
</P>
<P>
   In a side note, the court made it clear for the first time that
if a supervisor is doing the harassing, the employer is
automatically liable, whether it knew about the conduct or not.
</P>
<P>
   However, it did not address whether supervisors can be held
personally liable if they harass people who work under them.
</P>
<P>
   In Thursday's decision, the court ruled against a female
employee of the state Department of Corrections who sued both the
department and the co-worker who she said harassed her over a
seven-month period in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Maryann Carrisales, who worked in a warehouse at the California
Institute for Men in Chino, claimed that co-worker Dave Selkirk
touched her on the buttocks and around the breasts and would come
up from behind her and touch her between the legs. She complained
to her bosses but said that he was let off with a warning.
</P>
<P>
   In Thursday's ruling, the court rejected the woman's argument
that holding the co-worker liable would help deter future
harassment. The law applies only to management, the court said.
</P>
<P>
   However, the justices said the Legislature can always change the
harassment law if it wants to.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling does not mean that a harasser can escape unpunished.
The justices said the co-workers can still be held responsible
under other statutes, including battery and intentional infliction
of emotional distress.
</P>
<P>
   The decision is a setback for plaintiffs, who routinely sue both
the employer and the employee under the state's sexual harassment
law. William Quackenbush, the lawyer who argued the appeal for
Carrisales, said victims now will have to sue under statutes that
have largely been untested in harassment suits.
</P>
<P>
   But Quackenbush said he was relieved that the court didn't rule
out personal liability if a supervisor is doing the harassing.
``The bottom line is that supervisors are still on the hook,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Carrisales' trial lawyer, Mark Tundis, said the decision will
not hurt his client's case because she can still pursue her suit
against the department. But he said juries in general may wonder
about the strength of a case if the victim is suing only the
employer for harassment and not the co-worker.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling was also a setback for the state Fair Employment and
Housing Commission, the agency in charge of implementing sexual
harassment laws and which had backed Carrisales' suit against her
co-worker.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're of course disappointed that the court decided to
eliminate this deterrent,'' said Sandra Michioku, a spokeswoman for
state Attorney General Bill Lockyer. She said the only way to
change the law is through the Legislature.
</P>
<P>
   Selkirk's lawyer, Kathleen Stosuy, said Thursday's decision
brings California in line with federal law and most other states.
</P>
<P>
   She said the harassment law ``is directed at employers, who have
the best resources and incentive available to prevent any sort of
conduct or deal with it when it occurs.''
</P>
<P>
   Carrisales had originally sued the department, Selkirk, and two
supervisors who she said did nothing to stop the harassment. A
trial judge threw out her suit, but a state appeals court said she
could pursue her harassment charges against the department.
However, the appeals court said that neither the supervisors nor
the co-worker could be sued under the law.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-10-99 0242EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
