<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-10 02:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4984 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BKN-BARKLEY-BOS     12-10 1087
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-BARKLEY-BOS </SLUG>
 
Charles gets the last laugh 
(For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL HOLLEY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The funniest man in the NBA limped into the Ritz-Carlton
Thursday night and said he was depressed. He wore a symbol of his
depression on his left leg: a bulky brace that, remarkably, made
Charles Barkley look vulnerable.
</P>
<P>
   You looked at the brace. You looked at its 36-year-old owner's
face. You knew it would be a while before Barkley would be able to
joke about his career ending five months earlier than he expected.
But there was never any doubt that the comedy would come. Remember,
we're still talking about Charles Barkley.
</P>
<P>
   Barkley's days as a pro ended Wednesday night in Philadelphia,
the city where he developed his unusual playing _ and saying _
style. Before this season began, he said he would retire. Thursday,
he said he has no plans to renege on that promise. His mother and
grandmother were in Philly's First Union Center when he ruptured
his quadriceps tendon, an injury that provided the ironic
punctuation for a 16-season career. He said maybe the ``Big Fella
who has always protected me'' is trying to tell him this is the
time to stop playing. Because of his injury, he also won't be able
to play his beloved golf for the next six months.
</P>
<P>
   ``Golf and sex are the only two things you can be bad at and
still have a blast doing them,'' he said. He followed that
statement with some additional comments that cannot be repeated in
a newspaper. Barkley did not whisper those words or say that they
were off the record. He was merely being himself.
</P>
<P>
   When he enters the FleetCenter Friday night and is given a
tribute at halftime, some people will applaud that aspect of
Barkley. In a society of timid speakers, he is fearless. He is
unafraid to speak about race, religion, sex, or politics.
</P>
<P>
   As he was checking into a 1994 game at the old Richfield
Coliseum in Ohio, he looked at Burt Graeff of the Cleveland Plain
Dealer and quipped, ``You know, you are still one of the ugliest
white men I have ever seen in my life.'' It was a running joke he
had with Graeff from the previous season, when he scanned a huge
crowd of reporters, paused to look at Graeff, and then broke
everyone up with the line.
</P>
<P>
   He targeted reporters of all shades. I saw him in Houston in
1996 and told him I worked for the Globe. He then smiled and
shouted to Clyde Drexler, ``Hey, Clyde! They've got a brother
covering the Celtics in Boston . . . and he ain't the mascot! Can
you believe this?''
</P>
<P>
   I laughed. And that was the point. Barkley can be contradictory
at times, but, essentially, he loves hearing and seeing people
laugh. Unlike many players in the current NBA, he understands that
it isn't exactly normal to make $9 million a year playing
basketball.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see how my life could be any better,'' he said. ``I'm
telling you, it has been a blast. And it's very hard right now, I
ain't gonna lie. I tell you, I cried for like three hours straight
(Wednesday) night. It's hard and I know it's going to get harder. I
was 9 when I started playing basketball and I've played every day
since.''
</P>
<P>
   The hardest part? No more games. He won't play basketball again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not one of those guys who is going to join the church
league,'' he said. ``I'll be 37 in a couple of months and I've
never had a real job.''
</P>
<P>
   Barkley made his job sound easy, but it wasn't for him. He
played most of his 16 seasons at power forward, a position that is
usually manned by those who stand anywhere from 6 feet 8 inches to
7 feet. Barkley is not quite 6-5, but he dominated his position for
years because he had two things going for him: a very big backside
and a big heart. He once said that rebounding is nothing but
desire, so he was able to set goals of leading the league in
retrieving missed shots.
</P>
<P>
   You never knew what to make of Barkley, the man or the player.
He has said that he would like to run for governor of Alabama, his
home state. He would run as a Republican. He once joked that he
hated white people, a comment that caused a furor. He once called
himself a ``1990s nigger,'' another comment that got a lot of
attention. He received feel-good phone calls Thursday from Michael
Jordan, Tiger Woods, Karl Malone, Patrick Ewing, Rod Thorn (a man
who has fined him several times), and John Stockton. He was asked
if he heard from ex-teammate Scottie Pippen, who recently
criticized him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Scottie is on my voice mail,'' he said with a grin.
</P>
<P>
   It is tough to see Barkley leave so abruptly. He is an original
in today's NBA, kind of like a classic bodega surrounded by Stop &AMP;
Shops and Star Markets. Obviously the league will survive without
Barkley and Jordan and Ewing and Malone. There are players such as
Gary Payton, Tim Duncan, Kevin Garnett, Shaquille O'Neal, and Jason
Kidd who would have been great in basketball's Golden Age (the
early 1980s). But who among them will speak so honestly? That's
what I'll miss most about Barkley.
</P>
<P>
   What will he miss? Boston, probably.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew when we came to Boston, the old guys on (the 76ers)
changed their whole disposition,'' he said. ``It wasn't just
another game. When we came to play the Celtics, you would see Moses
(Malone), Doc (Julius Erving), Maurice (Cheeks), Andrew Toney,
Bobby Jones . . . their whole demeanor changed. We would go into
other cities and would want to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Barkley learned about the parquet floor, Bill Russell, and the
banners hanging in the rafters. Red Auerbach once gave him a
compliment and ``I was on Cloud Nine.'' He still thanks Larry Bird
and Magic Johnson when he sees them because he believed they helped
make him who he is. Since Barkley likes to talk so much, it won't
surprise you to learn that he also chats with fans and thanks them,
too. He said he knew he was a good player after his trade to
Phoenix. The Suns were in Boston and he got a nice ovation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was out somewhere, and a fan came up to me and said, `Did
you enjoy the game?' I said, `Every bit of it. That was a nice
ovation.' He said, `We couldn't cheer for you when you played for
the 76ers; we thought you were a good player but you played for the
76ers.' And that let me know that they know their basketball and
they appreciated what I was doing. That made me feel good.''
</P>
<P>
   Barkley will be back Friday night as a Houston Rocket. A retired
Rocket. He'll be limping. He'll also be telling a few jokes, but it
will still be sad to hear them this way.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-10-99 0243EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991210.0046 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-10 02:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4985 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-HKN-BRUINS-BOS     12-10 0881
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRUINS PAY THE PRICE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by New York Times News Service cients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sixty-five minutes. One point. No detention.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins extended their winless streak to five games with a
2-2 tie against Edmonton Thursday night. It was a boring game, but
the Bruins were cnsderably better than last Saturday night when
they dropped a 9-3 decision to the Blackhawks, and coach Pat Burns
lifted the mandatory postgame media grilling that was in effect
after the rout.
</P>
<P>
   ``We played well. We played hard right to the end,'' said the
coach. ``That's all I'm asking. It'll come if we stay and work the
way we're working now.''
</P>
<P>
   The Boston locker room was empty when officials threw open the
doors to the media. Players eventually drifted in for commentary,
but it was nothing like Saturday, when they were forced to face the
Fourth Estate. After the Saturday massacre, Burns told his players
to stay at their lockers until the local media had no more
questions. There would be no hiding, no trainer's room cowardice,
no back-door exit. Making it sound like reporters would be wielding
pickaxes instead of notepads, Burns ordered his players to ``sit
there until they are done with you.''
</P>
<P>
   Explained Burns, ``I told them I wasn't going to sit there and
make excuses for them. I wasn't trying to embarrass them. But it's
like, `You want the money? You want the contract? You want the
respectability? Well, you've got to be accountable.' I closed the
gym they sometimes use after games. I didn't want guys off in the
trainer's room sitting on ice bags. I told them to be respectful,
shut off the radio, and explain what happened. I wanted to hear
their version.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are highly paid athletes, and they should explain to the
guy who paid 95 bucks or 65 bucks why his night was spoiled. I
think the guys were all right with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Imagine a coach in another sport getting away with this. Imagine
Pete Carroll telling the Hell's Angels Patriots to siin front of
their lockers and engage the media after their latest stink bomb.
Who'd be the first member of the Kraft A.C. to tell Pete to
(expletive)? Players would be beating a path to the Foxy Lady
before traffic cleared on Route 1. (Come to think of it, how about
a special access road that'll get players from the new stadium to
he Foxy after games?)
</P>
<P>
   Accountability. It's a hockey thing. It's a word we don't use
enough in a world gone mad with excuses and diagnosed disorders.
It's a word that still exists in skating circles.
</P>
<P>
   Why are hockey players more accountable than Major League
Baseball players or the mastadons of the NFL and NBA?
</P>
<P>
   Some of it has to do with unions and contracts. Baseball's
Players Association runs that sport more than the commissioner.
Players have guaranteed contracts, and it's OK for Bobby Bonilla to
play cards in the clubhouse while his teammates are losing the
final game of the playoffs. The NBA is similarly smothered by
long-term deals, and few coaches have the hammer that Rick Pitino
wields in Boston (but who'll win the ultimate showdown between $50
million Rick and $70 million Antoine Walker?). In theory, pro
football coaches can be as powerful as hockey honchos, but only a
few flex the muscle _ think it's a coincidence Terry Glenn was most
productive in his one year under Bill Parcells? _ and the athletes
aren't as respectful.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe it's the way we're all brought up,'' said Bruins goalie
Byron Dafoe, who was mercifully pulled from the pipes in the middle
of the Saturday debacle. ``The coach has the authority. Guys make
more money than the coach, but he's the authority figure and we
respect that. may not be happy with all his decisions, but we
follow them.''
</P>
<P>
   Even Ray Bourque. The Bruins captain has been skating at the Old
and New Gardens for 20 years now. He is the consummate professional
hockey player and he's still not too big or old to be spanked by
his coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we respect authority,'' said Bourque. ``The coach is
the coach and we respect the game. We weren't accountable on the
ice the other night, so after the fact we've got to be accountable.
That wasn't one or two guys the other night. It was a total team
collapse.''
</P>
<P>
   And so they sat in front of their lockers and took the heat
(``Take your best shot,'' volunteered Steve Heinze). Then they
skated until their blades flattened during training camp-type
practices Monday and Tuesday. There were no public complaints, no
Terry Glenn saying that being on time won't make them champions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Regardless of what happens, we have to answer to it,'' said
veteran Dave Andreychuk. ``We're all adults. We've got to live up
to the responsibility.''
</P>
<P>
   Thursday night, the Bruins skated harder and it showed. They
outshot the Oilers, 13-7, in the first period and 14-9 in the
second, 37-21 overall. The coach was pleased. It was the first of
six games in 10 nights and Burns said, ``The way we're working now,
everything's coming into place.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Saturday was god-awful,'' admitted veteran Don Sweeney. ``We
took it to heart. All of us realized we'd let everybody down.
(Thursday night) we got back to playing the way we want to play,
the way we need to play to win.''
</P>
<P>
   They were accountable.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
