<SLUG> BC-BKN-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BARKLEY WILL STILL BE HEARD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA VECSEY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ His former coach knows for sure this is the end of the
line for Charles Barkley.
</P>
<P>
   ``Say anything you want about the guy,'' Paul Westphal said
Thursday. ``Charles is not going to rehab.''
</P>
<P>
   Long live the Chuckster, who now says he wants to be turned
loose on national TV, where he wants a basketball analyst job.
</P>
<P>
   Guess it's better news than ``Barkley for Governor.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, no. I don't think that's a very good idea,'' Westphal
said, laughing, about Barkley's old declaration that he would make
a run in his native Alabama.
</P>
<P>
   Hey, but considering some of the candidates on the political
horizon, is Barkley really a worse choice than, let's say, Donald
Trump?
</P>
<P>
   One day after Barkley ruptured a tendon in his left knee and
fell to the floor in Philly _ his old Round Mound of Rebound
stomping ground _ the NBA was taking notice of its hefty loss.
</P>
<P>
   And Barkley, like Michael Jordan, Larry Bird and Magic Johnson,
was one of the big reasons why, during the '80s, the NBA surged to
become the standard-bearer for the wild success pro sports could
achieve.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, commissioner David Stern did his share to turn the NBA into
a sports/corporate juggernaut. But like the other Mount Rushmore
figures (Bird, Magic and Michael), Barkley _ all 6-foot-4 of him,
with two Olympic gold medals, the 11 All-Star appearances and his
inclusion as one of the NBA's 50 greatest _ did more than his
share.
</P>
<P>
   When Barkley wasn't throwing fellow bar patrons through plate
glass windows; when he wasn't skewering referees such as Mike
Mathis by saying they belong in jail; when he wasn't trading
put-downs with Scottie Pippen; when he wasn't spitting on
spectators; when he wasn't clotheslining opponents; when he wasn't
making hysterically funny but racially charged jokes; when he
wasn't out playing hooky and golfing with Jordan during NBA
All-Star media days; when he wasn't getting summoned to New York to
visit with Stern about his boorish behavior ...
</P>
<P>
   Well, in other words, Barkley still had the time and the talent
and the personality and the inclination to turn the NBA on its ear
_ hard.
</P>
<P>
   He set a standard for competitiveness, for rebounding, for
playing the game to full-tilt boogie. And he did it while
entertaining fans as if he were playing for the Harlem
Globetrotters instead of NBA title-chasing teams.
</P>
<P>
   He sold tickets. He played the game to win. He lamented the
changing times that has given rise to too many agents, cell phones
and players as individual heads of corporations.
</P>
<P>
   In October, on the day Barkley announced this would be his last
season, he kicked off his farewell tour by giving away $3 million
to three different organizations in Alabama.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure, it's a loss,'' said Westphal, whose time with Barkley in
Phoenix resulted in a tough Game 6 loss to the Bulls in the 1993
NBA Finals _ the closest Barkley ever came to the ring he wanted.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't artificially make someone be Charles Barkley. It's
like when Sandy Koufax retired, Major League Baseball lost
something. Or when Bill Russell retired or Larry Bird or Michael
Jordan,'' Westphal said.
</P>
<P>
   We're not trying to take anything away from Shaquille O'Neal,
who has probably only begun to show us what sort of force he will
be over the course of his career.
</P>
<P>
   And we're not taking anything away from Tim Duncan, a super
player who stepped up when David Robinson stepped back and led the
Spurs to the 1999 NBA championship.
</P>
<P>
   And we're not depriving Allen Iverson of his props for being a
star attraction and even listening to coach Larry Brown once in a
while.
</P>
<P>
   But when it comes to the NBA and its links to its heyday,
Barkley was the lone ranger out there this season.
</P>
<P>
   Hakeem Olajuwon, David Robinson, Karl Malone and John Stockton
are active testaments to the beauty of the game when played at its
greatest level.
</P>
<P>
   But Barkley did that and more ... in his own, inimitable
fashion.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's one of the funniest people alive. And he's also a very,
very kind-hearted person who also has a temper. And he's
competitive. So how many people do you know like that?'' Westphal
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anyone who he thinks has been dealt a tough break in life or
who are hurting, he cares about. And the people who he thinks are
trying to get something from him, well, he's got a saying for them,
too.''
</P>
<P>
   It seemed perfectly fitting that while Jordan retired (twice) to
whirring tape recorders and TV cameras in well-orchestrated news
conferences, Barkley's last NBA moment came with a hard hit to the
floor. He landed on his infamously large backside and knew right
away what was to come.
</P>
<P>
   His basketball days are over, Barkley said as he headed to
surgery.
</P>
<P>
   But, certainly, we have not heard the last of Sir Charles. Not
hardly.
</P>
<P>
   P-I columnist Laura Vecsey can be reached at 206-448-8011
</P>
<P>
   or lauravecsey &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
