<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GASOLINE-ADDITIVE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 AIR BOARD OKs MTBE-FREE GAS FORMULA  &HT;     By LYNDA GLEDHILL 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO _ The California Air Resources Board unanimously
approved Thursday a new formula for the state's gasoline that will
eliminate the additive MTBE while maintaining strict air quality
requirements.
</P>
<P>
   The new gasoline formula, which could increase gas prices
anywhere from 1 cent to 15 cents per gallon, will be required by
the beginning of 2003.
</P>
<P>
   The board's 10-to-0 decision satisfied neither environmentalists
nor oil industry representatives, who testified before the board
for more than eight hours Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Oil industry representatives charged that the new formula is too
costly.
</P>
<P>
   Jay McKeeman, executive vice president of the California
Independent Oil Marketers Association, said he expects a 10- to
15-cent-per-gallon increase in gasoline costs as a result of the
approved regulations.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have very significant concerns that this will turn into a
situation that equals this summer's price conditions, if not
worse,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But environmentalists argued that the formula does not go far
enough to reduce emissions.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Coleman, a spokesman for Bluewater Network, an
environmental group in San Francisco, said he does not believe that
the air board recipe will maintain existing air quality standards.
</P>
<P>
   ``They basically handed over the keys to the oil industry,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Alan Lloyd, chairman of the air resources board, said, ``Today's
action will enable us to further clean our air without putting our
drinking water at risk.''
</P>
<P>
   MTBE (methyl tertiary butyl ether) is an additive that was
intended to reduce emissions. Studies have shown that it has leaked
into groundwater and can cause cancer in animals.
</P>
<P>
   In March, Gov. Gray Davis ordered a phaseout of MTBE by the end
of 2002, while at the same time maintaining current air quality
standards.
</P>
<P>
   Under Davis' directive, the air resources board was required to
remove MTBE from the current gasoline formula. However, federal
regulations still require the use of either MTBE or ethanol in the
worst-polluted areas of the state.
</P>
<P>
   ``That makes a very narrow path for us,'' said air resources
board spokesman Jerry Martin.
</P>
<P>
   Davis is asking for a waiver from federal regulations to allow
the use of additives other than ethanol that would give the oil
companies more flexibility.
</P>
<P>
   An original air board staff report on the changes suggested that
gas prices would go up as much as 7 cents a gallon to make up for
the reduced capacities the refineries would have as they switched
to non-MTBE gas.
</P>
<P>
   But another study by the California Energy Commission and
statements by one oil refinery, Tosco Inc., suggest that there may
no price increase at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are pretty much resolved that their predictions are more
accurate,'' Martin said. ``We notoriously overestimate things. If
everything else remains same, then there will be less than a cent a
gallon increase.''
</P>
<P>
   But that is not the view held by Dave Fogarty, a spokesman for
the Western States Petroleum Association, a group that represents
the oil industry. He said the air resources board formula goes
beyond just maintaining current standards.
</P>
<P>
   ``The option we are suggesting has the least consumer risk in
it,'' he said. ``It would remove MTBE and would provide emissions
reduction equivalent to the gasoline we have in California today,
which is the cleanest in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   The oil industry laid out a proposal that would still remove
MTBE but would not alter the formula as much, thereby providing
greater flexibility in how the gas can be made.
</P>
<P>
   Fogarty said he expects the new regulations to decrease oil
refinery capacity by 10 to 15 percent, raising prices about 7
cents.
</P>
<P>
   But Tosco said it fully supports the California Air Resources
Board regulations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tosco is pleased to unconditionally support the staff's
proposal,'' said company representative Duane Bordvick. ``They will
eliminate MTBE, provide the flexibility needed to minimize the
potential reduction in supply, and minimize the economic impacts of
the MTBE phaseout. In addition, they provide some additional air
quality benefits.''
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Tosco announced that it will phase out all MTBE by
the end of 2000, two years ahead of schedule, if the federal
Environmental Protection Agency grants a waiver of its requirement
to have an oxygenate in the fuel.
</P>
<P>
   Davis has pledged to push for the waiver, which all oil
companies said would greatly lessen the burden of eliminating MTBE.
</P>
<P>
   ``(The waiver) would certainly mitigate the problems to a large
degree,'' said McKeeman. ``It basically gives refiners a lot more
flexibility in trying to figure out how to make compliant
gasoline.'' &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
