<SLUG> BC-NURSES-SHORTAGE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 SEVERE NURSING SHORTAGE AHEAD IN CALIFORNIA, REPORT SAYS  &HT;     By SABIN RUSSELL 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Without a substantial boost in public university training,
California will face a serious shortage of nurses in the coming
decades, according to a new federally commissioned report.
</P>
<P>
   The study by researchers at the University of California at San
Francisco estimates that by 2010, California will need 43,000 more
registered nurses.
</P>
<P>
   Current training programs would add only 9,000, and another
13,000 registered nurses are expected to move to California from
other states. That still leaves a shortage of 21,000 nurses.
</P>
<P>
   There are an estimated 183,000 California registered nurses in
active practice today.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our recommendation is for an increase in the number of RNs
educated at public colleges and universities. It would require an
increase in state funding,'' said Janet Coffman, associate director
of the UCSF Center for California Health Workforce Studies, and
lead author of the report. She estimates that 3,600 more nurses
need to be trained in the state each year, two-thirds more than the
5,400 who graduate from current programs.
</P>
<P>
   More than 8 out of 10 registered nurses in California were
trained in either community colleges or the California State
University system.
</P>
<P>
   The university system, however, does not track the cost of
training a registered nurse, so there are not definitive estimates
on the cost of training 3,600 new nurses.
</P>
<P>
   John Richards, director of budgeting for the California State
University system, notes that nurse training requires about twice
the number of faculty per student as most programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one of the most expensive,'' he said. Overall, California
spends about $10,000 a year on each student in the state university
system.
</P>
<P>
   The study, underwritten by the federal Health Resources and
Services Administration, is published in this month's issue of the
journal Image: Journal of Nursing Scholarships.
</P>
<P>
   Coffman's forecast of a nursing shortage is based on projections
of a 23 percent increase in the state population by 2010, and
assumes that the ratio of registered nurses per state resident will
remain constant.
</P>
<P>
   Coffman concedes that the estimates are conservative. A new
state law requiring the Department of Health Services to set
staffing ratios for nurses in hospitals could increase the demand
for nurses.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the current labor force is aging, and large number
of nurses will be retiring. ``Just as Baby Boomers begin to need
more care, Baby Boomer nurses are going to start leaving the
workforce,'' said Coffman.
</P>
<P>
   Kay McVay, president of the California Nurses Association, said
there is already a shortage of nurses, and puts the blame for it on
the legacy of layoffs and mistreatment of the profession by
California hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to do something to make nursing extremely attractive.
You can't mistreat nurses and expect them to continue on,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Study co-author Joanne Spetz, a fellow of the Public Policy
Institute of California, said wages for nurses in the state have
not kept up with inflation. Average hourly earnings in 1997 were
$25.46, two dollars less, when adjusted for inflation, than nurses
made in 1994.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-10-99 0306EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991210.0051 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-10 03:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4990 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-VALINUX-STOCK-SFCHRON     12-10 0966
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VALINUX-STOCK-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 SAN FRANCISCO BAY AREA TECH FIRM'S STOCK SOARS A RECORD 697%  &HT;     By HENRY NORR 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ In the hottest initial public offering in Wall
Street history, shares in a little-known Sunnyvale, Calif., company
Thursday soared from an offering price of $30 to a close of $239.25
_ a record 697.5 percent jump.
</P>
<P>
   VA Linux Systems Inc., which sells computers, software and
services based on the upstart Linux operating system, ended the day
with a market capitalization of $9.5 billion _ even though it has
lost $29.9 million over its six years of existence and declared in
official documents accompanying the IPO that it ``expects to
continue to incur net losses for at least the foreseeable future.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There's just a huge general surge of momentum around Linux
companies,'' said Gail Bronson, a startup strategist based in Palo
Alto, Calif., and senior analyst at the IPO Monitor. ``They're
riding the crest of a wave of euphoria about the idea of an
alternative to Microsoft.''
</P>
<P>
   Linux is ``open source'' software _ programmers all over the
world work cooperatively to extend and improve it, and their work
is available free for anyone to download from the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, the software has gained popularity as an
alternative to Microsoft's Windows NT and other heavy-duty
commercial operating systems, especially for Internet server
computers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Linux has the potential to become a major industry over the
next few years, and this is probably the strongest of the Linux
companies we've seen,'' said Irv DeGraw, a Florida professor who
earned his doctorate in economics by studying IPOs.
</P>
<P>
   Linux ``could be almost as big as Microsoft (Windows),'' added
DeGraw, an assistant professor at Eckerd College in St. Petersburg,
Fla., and research director of WorldFinanceNet.com, a Web site that
focuses on IPOs. ``I'm not saying that's going to happen, but it
could.''
</P>
<P>
   Investors Thursday seemed to think that prospect was worth
betting on. The banks underwriting the VA Linux sale had originally
set a target offering price of $11 to $13 for the 4.4 million
shares they planned to sell. In the face of strong demand they
raised it several times over the past month, up to a final figure
of $30.
</P>
<P>
   But when the shares hit the market Thursday morning, the first
trade took place at a staggering $299. Over the course of the day
the price soared as high as $320, then dropped all the way back to
$233, before closing at $239.25 on the Nasdaq. At that price, the
179-person company is now worth slightly more than Best Buy,
Staples Inc. or Estee Lauder. VA Linux closed at $250 in
after-hours trading.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's 697-percent single-day jump shattered the old record
of 606 percent, set last year by TheGlobe.com, a Web site that
allows people to build personal home pages.
</P>
<P>
   ``These outrageous jumps between the offering price (set by the
underwriters) and the opening trade are something new,'' DeGraw
said. ``Historically, until recently, it's averaged around 15
percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has us academics all screwed up,'' he acknowledged. ``We
really don't know what's making it happen.''
</P>
<P>
   VA Linux is not the only Linux-related company to enjoy a huge
post-IPO bump. Red Hat, the first company in the field to go
public, sold its first share on August 11 at $14 and closed
Thursday at $286.25. Andover.net, a company that runs a complex of
Web sites aimed largely at Linux programmers, sold its first shares
on Tuesday at $18 and closed Thursday at $77.50.
</P>
<P>
   Even though Linux is available free and runs on conventional
PCs, among other kinds of computers, installation is sometimes
complex, and some PC hardware components are not compatible with
the system _ which is why companies starting to use it are often
willing to pay for professional assistance.
</P>
<P>
   VA Linux got its start in 1993 selling computers with the
operating system preinstalled and tested. Over the past year it has
expanded its business to provide consulting and support to
corporations running Linux. It also acquired the coveted Linux.com
domain name and used it to set up what has become a heavily
trafficked informational site for Linux users and developers.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's IPO brought the company a capital infusion of $132
million. At the closing price, company chief executive and
president Larry Augustin and his wife, who own 6.6 million shares,
are now worth about $1.6 billion, at least on paper. Augustin, who
was one of the company's founders, already has some experience with
runaway Internet success: As a Stanford graduate student, he helped
write the business plan for Yahoo.
</P>
<P>
   Intel, the chip giant and an investor in VA Linux, also made a
handsome gain: Its 3.5 million shares are now worth about $837
million.
</P>
<P>
   The company's backers also include Silicon Valley venture
capital firm Sequoia Capital, which holds a 23 percent stake valued
at $2.16 billion.
</P>
<P>
   For the year ending in July, VA Linux had a net loss of $14.5
million on revenues of $17.7 million. For the quarter ending in
October, its net loss totaled $10.2 million on revenues of $14.9
million.
</P>
<P>
   VA Linux apparently made an effort to share its bounty with the
community of programmers who helped create the operating system it
now sells. According to reports posted last week at several
Linux-related Web sites, the company offered some 3,000 Linux
programmers outside the company the opportunity to purchase up to
140 shares each at the opening price.
</P>
<P>
   Eureka Endo, a spokeswoman for VA Linux, declined to confirm the
report, saying the company's lawyers had insisted that all
employees respect the government-mandated ``quiet period.''
</P>
<P>
   ``All I can say,'' she said, ``is that it's been a really high
day.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
