<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Walker, Texas Ranger' star quits to run for Congress
 &HT;    By Glenn Evans
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONGVIEW, Texas _ Noble Willingham, who portrays C.D. Parker on
the television show ``Walker, Texas Ranger,'' says he will leave
the show at the end of the year to concentrate on his run for
Congress from East Texas.
</P>
<P>
   He announced here this week that he has laid out the $2,500
filing fee to enter the race for Texas's District 1 congressional
seat. Willingham will run as a Republican against incumbent
Democrat Max Sandlin.
</P>
<P>
   Willingham told supporters that his final episode is the
Christmas show. Writers tentatively plan to have his character win
the lottery and take off to see the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not a bad idea,'' he said before describing his
departure from the show after seven years. ``We had a mutual deal.
They wanted to know what I thought they should do about it. They
were amenable to me leaving, and they wanted me to stay.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's time to get to what's really important, and that's this.
I wouldn't want to stretch myself too thin.''
</P>
<P>
   Willingham contrasted himself with Sandlin as ``about like
daylight and dark.''
</P>
<P>
   Sandlin, he said, has veered too far to the liberal side of the
political spectrum by linking himself with President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Willingham said he would return to his California residence this
week, planning to catch the annual dog show in Indio, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the first of the year we're going to hit it running,'' he
said. ``And we're going to hit it hard, and we're going to have
blood in our eyes.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
