r a BC-CONNERLY11-COX     12-10 0589
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONNERLY11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Connerly still plans to change Florida law
 &HT;    By Brian E. Crowley
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Ending affirmative action in Florida has
become tougher than Ward Connerly expected. Delays in the Supreme
Court are forcing him to postpone his petition drive and dimming
the chances of getting the issue on the ballot next year.
</P>
<P>
   Supreme Court justices will not hold hearings until March 6 on
whether Connerly's proposed changes to the state constitution meet
the legal requirements for getting on the November ballot.
</P>
<P>
   After the hearing, it could take months for the court to make a
ruling. The seven justices must determine if the amendments are
clear, easy to understand and address only a single topic. Connerly
has offered four versions of his amendments hoping the court will
be unable to reject all of them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have no intention of stopping our campaign,'' Connerly said
Thursday from California, where he is a member of the state
university board of regents. ``We certainly need to reevaluate how
the campaign needs to be organized in light of the Supreme Court's
timetable.''
</P>
<P>
   Getting on Florida's ballot to change the constitution is not
easy in the best of circumstances. First, 43,500 signatures must be
collected from registered voters. Those signatures must be verified
by elections supervisors in each county where they are collected.
Then, the proposed amendment must go to the state Supreme Court for
its approval. If a majority of the justices give it the nod,
another 391,500 signatures must be collected by August. All of
those signatures must be verified by county election supervisors.
</P>
<P>
   It is not only time consuming, but expensive, with the cost
estimated at $1 million. Connerly said he doesn't want to spend the
money collecting signatures now in case the court tosses out the
amendments. If he wins approval, Connerly says there simply won't
be enough time after the court's decision to collect the necessary
petitions.
</P>
<P>
   While the slowness of the process here is frustrating to
Connerly and his supporters, he said he is determined to see it
through. If Connerly continues the effort, the earliest he could
get on the ballot after 2000 would be November 2002.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am pleased that Mr. Connerly has decided to slow things
down,'' said Florida Gov. Jeb Bush. ``I don't support the
initiative and if this means there won't be a divisive ballot
initiative, I believe that is a good thing.'' Bush has his own plan
to do away with affirmative action, which he calls the One Florida
Initiative.
</P>
<P>
   Connerly, who succeeded in passing state amendments in
California and Washington, is coming to West Palm Beach next Friday
to speak at the Forum Club of the Palm Beaches luncheon at the
downtown Sheraton Hotel.
</P>
<P>
   Called divisive, disruptive and a traitor to his race, Connerly
has received blistering criticism for his nationwide effort to
force state and local governments to abandon affirmative action
practices.
</P>
<P>
   Connerly, who is black, argues that affirmative action does more
harm than good. He contends that blacks should be given
opportunities based on merit. He says the role of government is to
help those in need regardless of race or gender.
</P>
<P>
   Recent polls have indicated that if Connerly's amendment were to
get on the ballot it would pass overwhelmingly.
</P>
<P>
   ``One way or another,'' he said, ``we are going to get on the
ballot.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
