<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MINTER-COLUMN11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Obituary sweepstakes
 &HT;    By Jim Minter
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   FAYETTE COUNTY, Ga. _ We had finished a delicious breakfast of
Eggbeaters, low-fat jelly and seven-grain toast dabbed with
margarine made from yogurt. I was starting on the sports section
and a second cup of coffee dosed with Sweet 'n' Low when she looked
up from her end of the table.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've changed the way they write about people when they
die,'' my wife said. ``Why did they do that?''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just the way things are,'' I explained. ``Everything gets
changed. Like what we have for breakfast.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What do you mean by that?'' she asked, somewhat irritably, I
thought.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't mean anything,'' I lied. ``I was just thinking how
lucky we are now that we aren't clogging our arteries with terrible
stuff like real eggs, sausage, cheese grits, hot biscuits, butter
and gravy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You're lucky to have me looking after your diet,'' she
replied. ``If you ate like you want to, you would weigh 300 pounds
and have a heart attack.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Thanks a lot,'' I answered. ``What do you find so different
about newspaper obituaries?''
</P>
<P>
   ``They're mostly about ordinary people,'' she said. ``They used
to be mostly about prominent people.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes,'' I agreed. ``I've noticed that.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I wonder why they changed to ordinary folks,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's because of the egalitarian age,'' I explained. ``Used to
be you had to run a big company, be rich and live in Buckhead, or
be in the Legislature to get a big headline on the obituary page.
That wasn't fair.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What do you have to do now to qualify for a nice obituary?''
she asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mostly you have to just die,'' I answered.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of ordinary people die every day,'' she said. ``How do
they pick the ones they write about?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know,'' I admitted. ``Potluck, I suppose.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I've noticed men who liked to have gardens and go fishing get
nice write-ups,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``A good crop of tomatoes can get you a three-column headline on
a slow day,'' I agreed. ``So can being a good dancer, liking to
play poker and telling funny jokes. If you took up sewing and
started back frying chicken and making gravy you might be a
candidate yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Now that people who aren't rich and famous can get in the
obituaries, do you think they might write something about you when
you die?'' she asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been thinking about it,'' I admitted. ``It could
happen.''
</P>
<P>
   ``How do they get information about ordinary people?'' she
asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mostly, they call the surviving spouse and the children,'' I
explained.
</P>
<P>
   ``What if you died and they called me?'' she asked. ``What in
the world could I say?''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's something we need to think about,'' I replied,
``especially since I've just had another birthday I really didn't
expect to have.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And with the way you keep slipping off on the tractor and
smoking those cigars,'' she added.
</P>
<P>
   ``Have you ever heard of an advance obituary?'' I asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``You mean one that's written before you actually die?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Exactly,'' I said. ``The newspaper sends a reporter to
interview old people who ran big companies, or who are rich and
live in Buckhead, or have been in the Legislature. They get to tell
about their notable achievements and list all the exclusive clubs
they belong to.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reporter goes back to the newspaper and writes it all down
and puts it in a computer. When the person dies all the newspaper
has to do is call up the story and punch in age and time of the
funeral.''
</P>
<P>
   ``How is that going to help me?'' she asked. ``They don't do
advance obituaries on ordinary folks, do they?
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought we could do one ourselves,'' I replied. ``If you
were to get a call, you could just read it off.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What would it say?'' she asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a bit of a problem,'' I admitted, ``but I've done a few
things in my lifetime that ought to qualify under the new rules.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't play golf or poker, and you sure can't dance,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I played poker in the Army,'' I replied. ``That's why we had
to go to the Varsity instead of the Owl Room when we were dating.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd hate for our friends to know about that,'' she said.
``Can't you think of anything that would impress people?''
</P>
<P>
   ``You could mention my longtime membership in the Moose Lodge.
You could say I won a $10 bet from Heyward Owens when Harry Truman
beat Tom Dewey.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Anything else?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Put in that I raised a fabulous tomato crop in 1997.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Can't you think of anything sophisticated?'' she asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can point out that even though I didn't go to Georgia
Tech, I learned how to use e-mail.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope they don't call,'' she said. ``I don't think you'd make
much of a story.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll have to work on that,'' I replied. ``If this starvation
diet you have me on works, maybe I'll live long enough to learn how
to dance and play poker. I might even do something really weird
like getting into organic gardening or turning into a Republican
and running for the County Commission.''
</P>
<P>
   Jim Minter is a former editor in chief of The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-10-99 1102EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
