<DOCNO> NYT19991210.0057 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-10 11:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5098 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-RELIGION-MUSIC11-COX     12-10 1107
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-MUSIC11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Following for contemporary Christian music grows
 &HT;    By James Lloyd
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Gospel music caught fire in the 1990s. At the
beginning of the decade, contemporary Christian music, though it
had been around for about 20 years, tended to be viewed in the
mainstream marketplace as old-fashioned, irrelevant or inferior.
</P>
<P>
   No more. Among the acts that have climbed pop, modern rock,
adult contemporary and R&AMP;B charts in the decade are Amy Grant,
Michael W. Smith, BeBe and CeCe Winans, Jars of Clay, Kirk Franklin
and Sixpence None the Richer. dc Talk's 1998 rock release,
``Supernatural,'' debuted at No. 4 on Billboard's top 200, and Bob
Carlisle's ``Butterfly Kisses (Shades of Grace)'' album reached No.
1, the first Christian album to do that.
</P>
<P>
   Mainstream media haven't missed this phenomenon. Entertainment
Weekly, in its Dec. 3 and 10 issues, looks at the rapid growth in
Christian music, fiction and film, calling it ``The Greatest Story
Ever Sold.''
</P>
<P>
   For the purposes of this story, ``gospel'' music is a
broad-based term encompassing a wide range of musical styles from
Southern Gospel to black gospel to praise and worship and pop,
rock, R&AMP;B, hip-hop, swing, reggae and so forth. Contemporary
Christian music has a slightly narrower focus, generally speaking
more in terms of pop, rock, R&AMP;B, hip-hop and other genres that
reflect popular culture.
</P>
<P>
   According to SoundScan Inc. figures reported by the Gospel Music
Association in July, 20.5 million units were sold in the first six
months of 1999, a 21 percent increase e same period in 1998.
This was on top of increases of 30 percent, 32 percent and 1.4
percent in 1996, '97 and '98.
</P>
<P>
   SoundScan numbers placed Christian music fifth in size in 1998,
behind R&AMP;B, rap, country and soundtracks and ahead of metal, jazz,
classical, Latin and new age.
</P>
<P>
   Ten years ago, someone wanting to buy a release by a Christian
artist, other than Grant and Smith, perhaps, probably would have
had to go to a Christian retailer. That's no longer the case.
According to a study by the GMA, which is dedicated to educating
the public and music industry about gospel music, as well as
producing the annual Dove Awards telecast, Wal-Mart, the nation's
biggest retailer, devotes more than 20 percent of its selling space
to Christian music.
</P>
<P>
   And those wanting to listen to the music on the radio had an
even tougher time in the '80s, unless they preferred the more
conservative inspirational or Southern gospel genres. A dozen years
ago, the GMA study said, fewer than 200 stations nationwide played
gospel music, but by 1998, that had grown to more than 1,600.
</P>
<P>
   A variety of factors have influenced this change. A few are
listed below, as well as a couple other issues or developments that
got a lot of attention in the '90s.
</P>
<P>
   1. Big business: Mainstream entertainment conglomerates saw the
potential and they bit, buying Christian music labels and
distributing their products. They've settled into the big three:
</P>
<P>
   _ Gaylord Entertainment Co. owns Word, Myrrh, Squint and other
labels, and it distributes for independent labels such as
Maranatha!, Rocketown and B-Rite/Gospo Centric.
</P>
<P>
   _ Zomba Music Group created Provident Music Distribution Inc.
and owns Brentwood, Benson, Reunion and Essential.
</P>
<P>
   _ EMI Christian Music Group counts among its labels Sparrow,
ForeFront, EMI Gospel, and it distributes for smaller labels such
as Gotee, 5 Minute Walk, Springhill and Vineyard Music.
</P>
<P>
   2. SoundScan: When Billboard magazine began counting Christian
retailers in its SoundScan charts in 1995, it had an immediate
impact _ half or more of the sales occur there.
</P>
<P>
   3. Diversity: Christian music is the only genre defined by its
lyrics. Stylistically, you can find just about anything in gospel
that you can in mainstream _ hip-hop, pop, R&AMP;B, country, adult
contemporary, reggae, Latin, modern rock. And, of course, Southern
and black gospel haven't faded away.
</P>
<P>
   4. Worship and praise music: In the beginning, there was the
hymnal. Then came Bill and Gloria Gaither. Then the Maranatha! and
Vineyard labels. In the past two years, virtually every major label
has added praise and worship labels; even Toby McKeehan of dc Talk
and Gaither himself teamed up on a worship label this year. The
guitar- and drum-based music is causing a generational tumult in
the church that hasn't been seen since the beginnings of ``Jesus
music'' 30 years ago. It's too shallow, it's too loud, it's too
emotional. Or, it speaks to the heart, it's relevant, it's bringing
people into the church.
</P>
<P>
   5. Growing pains: Such expansion doesn't come without some worry
and debate. What is Christian music? Can a love song to your spouse
be ``Christian''? Both Sixpence None the Richer and Michael W.
Smith had songs eliminated from Dove competition by the Gospel
Music Association judging last year because the content wasn't
specifically focused on Jesus. (Rules have been relaxed for 2000.)
To be fair, GMA was only reacting to the discussion going on by
those in the industry, including singers Steve Camp and Charlie
Peacock.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the decade, great fear was expressed over whether
mainstream corporate owners would pressure artists to tone down
mention of Jesus to sell more records. So far, that doesn't seem to
be a huge concern.
</P>
<P>
   And, of course, there have been scandals, involving Michael
English's and Sandy Patti's infidelities and broken marriages.
English, one of the most promising artists in the early '90s,
returned his Dove awards and disappeared from public eye for an
extended time. He's been returning gradually, and you can expect to
see more of him in 2000. Patti has not regained her former
prominence either. It remains to be seen what the fallout will be
for Amy Grant, who was divorced from singer Gary Chapman earlier
this year and is now seeing country artist Vince Gill.
</P>
<P>
   _ A trend to watch out for in the '00s: The growing
internationalization of Christian music. The Newsboys, Rebecca St.
James and Michelle Tumes _ all from Australia _ caught on in the
'90s, and Delirious, from England, came on strong at the end.
Expect this to expand in the next 10 years. The Christian Latin
market, with Jaci Velasquez as its poster child, is beginning to
blossom, and Newsboys front man Peter Furler helped launch a new
label, inpop, to focus on artists from outside the States. Its
first band, a fellow Aussie group called beanbag, recently released
its first stateside CD, ``Free Signal.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
