<DOCNO> NYT19991210.0059 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-10 11:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5100 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s BC-FBN-REEVES-AIDE11-COX     12-10 0960
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-REEVES-AIDE11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Falcons assistant admired for his personality, football
knowledge
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ After intercepting a pass in practice, Falcons free
safety Eugene Robinson ran down the sideline. Robinson had one man
to beat, and he figured it would be a cinch. After all, Marvin Bass
is 80 years old, and the last time he played he was wearing a
leather helmet.
</P>
<P>
   As Robinson approached, he yelled, ``You ready for me, coach
Bass?''
</P>
<P>
   The white-haired gentleman, a college All-American 55 years ago
at William &AMP; Mary, assumed a would-be tackling stance, clipboard in
hand, and replied, ``Lemme tell you something; I'm still doing
it.''
</P>
<P>
   And so Bass is.
</P>
<P>
   As perhaps the senior member of any NFL staff, Bass has given
the majority of his life to football. Falcons coach Dan Reeves
brought his former college coach to Suwanee soon after he was hired
by the Falcons in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The lives of the two have been interwoven for more than four
decades; it is a father-son relationship between two people who
aren't related.
</P>
<P>
   When the Broncos hired Reeves in 1981, the coach said, Bass
``was the first person I called about joining my staff, because I
respect him so much.'' Bass had been Reeves' college coach at South
Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   Bass, who has coached throughout North America, said he would
join Reeves, but he wanted to finish his commitment as defensive
coordinator of the Calgary Stampeders of the CFL. So he showed up
in the Mile-High City in 1982. He stayed on Reeves' staff, mostly
as a special assistant, until Reeves was fired in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Bass could have gone to New York when Reeves was hired as coach
of the Giants in 1993, but he wanted to remain with his wife,
Audrey, who had suffered a stroke. After moving Audrey back to
Columbia, his life revolved around caring for her. Nothing more.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt like I needed to spend more time with her,'' Bass said.
``In Denver, I could get home in 10 or 15 minutes. I didn't think
I'd be able to do that in New York.''
</P>
<P>
   Friends say Bass was crushed in 1996 when his wife died. Reeves
called soon after about joining the Falcons, and Bass had a chance
to turn back the clock. He couldn't get to team headquarters in
Suwanee fast enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll do this as long as I can do it,'' he said. ``It keeps you
young. I don't know what I would be doing if I wasn't messing
around with football in some way.''
</P>
<P>
   Reeves doesn't know what he'd do without Bass around. Reeves'
father died years ago, and Bass has become a substitute of sorts.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of times as a head coach you worry about whether coaches
will tell you what you want to hear, rather than what you need to
hear,'' Reeves said. ``You don't have to worry about that with
coach Bass.''
</P>
<P>
   Bass is popular with all the Falcons coaches. They love his
stories and have a few of their own. A couple of years ago, the
staff was in Indianapolis for the scouting combine and went to
dinner. The bill came, and Reeves was surprised when he saw the
drinks tally. He went to every coach, more than half sitting at
Bass' table rather than at Reeves', and said, ``Did we have this
much wine?''
</P>
<P>
   After a succession of, ``Nope. Nope. Nope,'' Reeves approached
coach Bass. ``Coach Bass, did we have this much wine?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coach, I reckon we might have,'' Bass said.
</P>
<P>
   The room erupted in laughter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Marvin has a way of getting you back to reality quickly with
down-to-earth language,'' passing game coordinator Jack Burns said.
``He's a common-sense thinker. When a lot of people overlook the
obvious, Marvin will punch you right in the face with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Bass charts the practice work of kicker Morten Andersen and
punter Dan Stryzinski. He also sits in on staff meetings,
especially on offense.
</P>
<P>
   After he graduated from William &AMP; Mary in 1945, Bass coached
there, and then stopped at several places. He became an assistant
at South Carolina in 1956. After a one-year stop at Georgia Tech as
Bobby Dodd's defensive coordinator in 1960, he returned to South
Carolina as coach and athletics director, 1961-65 _ one year after
Reeves left. His record was 17-29-4.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, USC named its weight room for him. Former
players raised $100,000 for the facility on the condition that it
be named for Bass.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a great guy,'' offensive line coach Art Shell said. ``He
gives you the levity when you need it. We can be sitting in a room,
down, and all of the sudden he'll say something, and we'll all
crack up.''
</P>
<P>
   Bass wouldn't have it any other way.
</P>
<P>
   He still has the home north of Columbia, and his only son,
52-year-old Randy, and two grandchildren live near there. But he
rarely visits. Instead he stays close to work. Real close.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcon Inn hotel closed 15 months ago, but Bass and Falcons
intern Mark Olson each live in one room.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's convenient.'' Bass is laughing now. ``You don't have to
battle traffic. You can sleep a little longer because you don't
have to go very far to get to work.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked what he does on holidays, Bass chuckled again. ``Nothing.
Every day is a holiday. I stay here.''
</P>
<P>
   After persistent questioning, he said, ``I see my son when I
can, for Christmas. But when I'm here _ like Dan asked me over for
Thanksgiving dinner. I do things like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Bass loves the game, but he says the thrill is helping to find
the winning edge.
</P>
<P>
   ``Facing a challenge has always been something I liked, and I
hope it will be until my last day on this earth,'' he said.
``Football is a hobby. People ask me why don't I retire, but you
don't retire from hobbies; you retire to hobbies. What else would I
do?''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
