<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-10 11:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5101 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-WARNER-ON-WOOD11-COX     12-10 0679
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WARNER-ON-WOOD11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Setting up shop
 &HT;    By Jack Warner
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A reader sent me an e-mail a while back asking for
recommendations and books on setting up a home shop; not so much, I
gather, on what to buy, but how to lay it out.
</P>
<P>
   I have seen various articles on this over the 18 years I've been
in the craft, but I can't recall where they were. The best advice I
can give on books and articles is a trip to a good woodworker's
store.
</P>
<P>
   However, there are certain things that should always be
considered when setting up a shop.
</P>
<P>
   Most of us have to play with the hand we have been dealt, by
which I mean we can't afford to construct a shop, or remodel
existing quarters.
</P>
<P>
   In many respects, I have been very lucky, living in a house with
a full basement, two sides of which have windows. It certainly
beats a windowless one-car garage.
</P>
<P>
   However, it isn't all gravy. While it is a big area, it is
broken into small areas by the positioning of load-bearing posts
under the upstairs walls. This makes power tool and machine
positioning very critical.
</P>
<P>
   The first tool to position is always the table saw, because you
need a lot of room fore and aft, and on one side. For instance, if
you are going to rip an 8-foot plank _ a pretty common occurrence _
you need an absolute minimum of 18 feet, nine in front of and
behind the saw arbor. If you intend to work with manufactured
goods, such as plywood, you'll need more than that, especially in
front of the arbor.
</P>
<P>
   By the same token, if you're going to square up the end of an
eight-foot plank, you need about nine feet on one side or another
of the arbor.
</P>
<P>
   We're using 8-foot lengths here simply by example; it's no magic
number. I just want to show you how injudicious positioning can
leave you incapable of dealing with a big board or a piece of
plywood.
</P>
<P>
   The jointer and planer need the same kind of space fore and aft,
although they don't need any at all on the off side and just a few
feet on the working side.
</P>
<P>
   I've seen some cramped shops set up so that ripping, planing and
jointing operations are carried out in front of a window that can
be opened so the workpiece can be run through it.
</P>
<P>
   Some newcomers have the idea they'll put the workbench up
against a wall. This isn't a good idea; you'll often want access to
all four sides of the bench for clamping and other operations.
</P>
<P>
   Another option for cramped spaces is to have all the heavy
equipment on rollers so each piece can be brought out into an open
space as needed. It's an option, but a last-ditch one, as far as
I'm concerned. Unisaws are heavy suckers, even on rollers.
</P>
<P>
   The next thing to consider is ventilation and dust control.
Young people are a lot more concerned about their environment than
people of my generation, and it's a good thing. It's especially a
good thing in a basement shop, and doubly so in a basement that
also houses the furnace/air conditioner.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, home shop dust control is an art still in its
infancy. Manufacturers tend to stick vacuum ports on their machines
and then advertise them as ready for dust control, when in fact the
port is just put on wherever possible, without regard to how much
dust it will encounter.
</P>
<P>
   Take my Unisaw, for example. It has a big port on it for a
4-inch hose. But the cabinet is not enclosed, so whatever dust is
sucked out through the port is more or less accidental. One has to
mess around with a roll of duct tape to try to create anything like
a closed space within the cabinet.
</P>
<P>
   Even then, you get only the dust thrown downward. At least an
equal amount is thrown upward, especially during ripping
operations, and the port on the cabinet isn't going to do anything
about that.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, imposing serious dust control on a home shop is an
expensive proposition, and certainly not one I have even come close
to solving. Just do the best you can, live with what you can't
control, and wear a good dust mask.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-10-99 1103EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
