<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-10 11:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5103 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-Y2K-WORRY11-COX     12-10 1207
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Y2K-WORRY11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Preparing for Y2K: Is it really necessary?
 &HT;    By Stephen J. O'Brien
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ Waco resident Carole Hague admits the supplies she
and her husband are stockpiling in case Y2K computer foul-ups cause
problems on Jan. 1 look part strategic reserve and part romance.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last few weeks, the Hagues have been putting extra
canned food, flashlights, batteries and bottles of drinking water
in their supply closet.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's the stack of candles, blankets, firewood and a
radio _ battery powered, of course.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the lights really do go out, I'd like to see how much the
birth rate goes up in September 2000,'' Hague said. ``I think most
people will just light a couple of candles and get under the
blankets to stay warm.''
</P>
<P>
   Already proud grandparents, the Hagues probably wouldn't figure
into any birth-rate figures next fall, but they are part of the
group of Americans who plan to prepare for power outages and other
inconveniences when the millennium hits.
</P>
<P>
   The Y2K glitch could cause computers to misfire when the first
two digits of the year change from ``19'' to ``20.'' It's a problem
most programmers did not foresee years ago when the computer
industry was still in its infancy and systems were hard-coded with
``19'' in datelines.
</P>
<P>
   The Hagues say they are not ``going nuts.'' Their supplies do
not include piles of ammunition or gas masks. They'll have things
people should have on-hand year-round, Y2K or no Y2K, they say. In
the event that major flooding, tornadoes or some other natural
disaster hits the area, survival and first-aid supplies, along with
a little cash, will come in handy.
</P>
<P>
   As a diabetic, Carole Hague has had to address a more serious
issue than whether the canned beans in her closet are of the baked
or chili variety. She will have three month's worth of insulin on
hand New Year's Eve, something her doctors recommended. Since
insulin and other life-saving drugs are sometimes shipped into the
United States from overseas, medical experts warn that problems
abroad could disrupt supplies even if glitches are minimal
stateside.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it's life-threatening, doctors say you should have extra
on-hand,'' she said. ``My grandson was asking, but I told him I
don't know that you need to stockpile acne medicine.''
</P>
<P>
   Like the Hagues, Woodway resident Dr. F. Clay Weekley will
prepare for potential Y2K problems by taking a few simple
precautions. Weekley has fueled up his motor home with 60 gallons
of gas and filled the truck's 40-gallon water tank. His RV has a
generator that can run the refrigerator and radio. A propane tank
can run the stove and heater. Weekley figures he could survive at
least three weeks if things got chilly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really don't think there'll be any problems, but I'll be
ready just in case,'' Weekley said. ``I'll have the motor home
stocked just like I was going on a trip. I could see some
businesses having problems if their computer systems go down, but
for me, it wouldn't matter too much.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of those storing extra supplies argue that the supplies
they'll have on hand New Year's Eve won't go to waste if no Y2K
problems arise.
</P>
<P>
   Waco resident Barbara Collier has canned fruit, peanut butter,
food for her dog, a camping stove and six gallons of drinking water
for her and her son. Collier also plans to have plenty of gas in
her car.
</P>
<P>
   Collier figures she could last at least a week if utility
services and modern conveniences were interrupted.
</P>
<P>
   ``There don't seem to be too many people who are taking this
seriously,'' she said. ``I think it's a little foolish not to do
something. The things you stock up on you will use eventually. You
can eat canned vegetables later in the year if you don't need them
because of Y2K. And it's not like you're incurring a lot of debt to
buy these extra supplies.''
</P>
<P>
   According to research by the Grocery Manufacturers of America,
the vast majority of Americans are not going on canned-food and
bottled-water shopping sprees.
</P>
<P>
   About 70 percent of respondents to a GMA survey earlier this
year said they don't plan to purchase extra food in anticipation of
Y2K problems. Almost 80 percent said they were not concerned at
all, or only somewhat concerned, about possible food shortages.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're urging consumers to be reasonable,'' said Bill James,
senior vice president of the Grocery Manufacturers of America.
``While it's never a good idea to have an empty pantry, there's
also no need to overbuy food in preparation for Y2K. We think it's
prudent to have enough food on hand for a long holiday weekend and
not to wait until the last minute to go grocery shopping.''
</P>
<P>
   The survey revealed that 57 percent of shoppers usually have
enough food in their refrigerators, pantries and cupboards to last
about seven days.
</P>
<P>
   According to a Gallup poll conducted earlier this year, about 21
percent of Americans think the Y2K computer bug will cause major
foul-ups, 65 percent expect minor problems, and 12 percent expect
no problems at all.
</P>
<P>
   When respondents were asked how the Y2K glitch will affect them
personally, only 9 percent said they expected major problems, and a
third said they expect no problems at all.
</P>
<P>
   At the Heart of Texas Area Chapter of the American Red Cross,
preparations for 12:01 a.m. Jan. 1, 2000, have been made, but Bruce
Bennett, director of emergency services, said his organization is
always ready for disasters.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the way the Red Cross is approaching it, as you would
any other disaster,'' Bennett said.
</P>
<P>
   About 50 customers a day come through the doors of Hewitt Guns
'N Gold. Sharif Sidarous of Hewitt Guns 'N Gold said ammunition and
gun sales have picked up slightly in the last three months, but the
upswing in sales has been slight.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're talking about maybe one person a week who comes in here
and mentions Y2K,'' Sidarous said.
</P>
<P>
   At Waco Army/Navy Supply Store Inc. overall sales are up 20
percent, manager Cliff Emmons said. Water jugs, water purification
tablets, Meals Ready to Eat and flashlights have been selling at a
brisk pace since the beginning of the year, Emmons said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Y2K business has been good all year,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   For those concerned about civil unrest, flak jackets sell for
$75 apiece; double mantle propane lanterns cost $24.95; an Army
issue sleeping bag runs $59.95; and a ``chopped beef steak and
components'' MRE or escalloped potatoes with ham meal is about $8.
A 6.5-gallon water jug costs $10.88.
</P>
<P>
   As owner of Mack's Camper Sales Inc., Jerry Harrison figures
he's got at least 50 potential places to stay in his business'
parking lot alone if things go south Jan. 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the propane gas, which can run the stove and heater, and
a full tank of gas, you could survive for awhile in an RV,'' he
said. ``But I really don't think there will be that many problems.
I'm sure there will be some minor glitches, but I'm not too
concerned.''
</P>
<P>
   Harrison does admit to stockpiling propane at his home to ensure
he can still cook if the power goes out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to be sure we have enough propane for our grill
outside,'' he laughed.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
