<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COX NEWS SERVICE COMMENTARY BUDGET
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   These columns for release Saturday, December 11 and Sunday,
December 12, 1999 are moving today to clients of the New York Times
News Service.
</P>
<P>
   All columns have moved, in the commentary (k) category. If you
have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the Cox News
Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   NETHAWAY-COLUMN _ WACO, Texas _ Gov. George W. Bush opposes a
standardized national test for public school students. That's a
shame. (Rowland Nethaway is senior editor of the Waco
Tribune-Herald) MOVED TUESDAY FOR SATURDAY
</P>
<P>
   MINTER-COLUMN _ FAYETTE COUNTY, Ga. _ Talking over an advanced
obituary with my wife. (Jim Minter is a former editor of The
Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED FOR SATURDAY
</P>
<P>
   TEEPEN-COLUMN _ The U.S. Supreme Court has, dangerously, decided
to revisit the historic 1966 Miranda ruling. Dangerously, because
it will be a close call in the current conservative court whether
this fundamental protection against coerced confessions can
survive. (Tom Teepen is national correspondent for Cox Newspapers.)
MOVED THURSDAY FOR SUNDAY.
</P>
<P>
   KLEINBERG-COLUMN _ What do you get the person who has
everything?, is the wail of many holiday season shoppers. I have a
suggestion: A can of Dole's Pineapple Chunks and perhaps its
Pine-Orange-Banana juice. You see, you've got to have two UPC bar
code proofs-of-purchase of Dole's products to be eligible to win a
trip to ``outer space.''(Howard Kleinberg is a columnist for Cox
News Service.) MOVED THURSDAY FOR SUNDAY.
</P>
<P>
   GLASS-COLUMN _ The brainy fellow engaged with the legal fate of
Microsoft's Bill Gates is Chicago's Richard Posner, who was named
to the U.S. Court of Appeals during the Reagan era and who has been
cited by American Lawyer magazine as ``the most brilliant judge in
the country.'' (Andy Glass is a columnist for Cox News Service in
the Washington bureau.) MOVED THURSDAY FOR SUNDAY.
</P>
<P>
   WALKER-COLUMN _ LONGVIEW, Texas _ On Dec. 12, all who have even
the slightest connection to Mexico celebrate Guadalupe's day. The
event is an official feast day in the Catholic Church but on the
day when ``La Virgen'' is honored, Mexican people of all faiths
claim her. (Walker, Longview News-Journal). MOVED FOR SUNDAY
</P>
