<P>
   LOOK ON THE WEB: Stories marked as a CoxNet layout are available
for purchase in paginated form: http://nytsyn.com/syndicate/pageex
</P>
<P>
   SCIENCE/MEDICINE
</P>
<P>
   MEDICAL-MISTAKES _ Your step-by-step guide to what you can do to
prevent medical mistakes, from prescription mixups to misteps by
doctors, nurses or hospitals. (Lore, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
MOVED MONDAY.
</P>
<P>
   MEDICINE-MEDIA _ Books on pill reference guides, internet site,
awareness days. (Kim, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). MOVED MONDAY.
</P>
<P>
   COXNET SCIHEALTH PAGE
</P>
<P>
   EDs: This is the CoxNet SCIHEALTH page for the current week.
This layout will be available Friday by 1 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Art includes two color photos and two color illustrations
</P>
<P>
   COXNET SCIHEALTH 1211: HOLIDAY BLUES -- Mental health therapists
say the added pressures of the new millennium could lift holiday
anxiety levels to new heights, leading to more cases of holiday
depression. (Lamb, Dayton Daily News) Art includes 4-column color
illustration of holiday depression.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: BATTLING THE BLUES BOX -- A list of ways to help lift the
holiday blues. (Lamb, Dayton Daily News)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: DIET PLANS -- When the holiday season comes to an end,
those who have found themselves carrying an extra few pounds will
be looking for diet plans. Many will be looking for the quick fix.
These diets are among the most popular, but all have drawbacks.
(Guthrie, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: HEALTH AND MEDIA -- Publishers offer numerous books on
pills and medications. (Lee Kim, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) Art
includes two 6-pica color photos of book jackets and 1 6-pica color
illustration of a computer.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE
</P>
<P>
   WARNER-ON-WOOD _ ATLANTA _ Arranging your woodshop work space.
(Warner, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   Y2K-WORRY _ WACO, Texas _ Most people say they are not stocking
up for Y2K, but experts suggest a few precautions just in case.
(O'Brien, Waco Tribune-Herald)
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION-MUSIC _ Gospel music caught fire in the '90s. At the
beginning of the decade, contemporary Christian music, though it
had been around for about 20 years, tended to be viewed in the
mainstream marketplace as old-fashioned, irrelevant or inferior. No
more. Among the acts that have climbed pop, modern rock, adult
contemporary and R&AMP;B charts in the decade are Amy Grant, Michael W.
Smith, BeBe and CeCe Winans, Jars of Clay, Kirk Franklin and
Sixpence None the Richer. (Lloyd, Dayton Daily News). 27. WITH
PHOTOS. MOVED
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION-GUSHEE _ Marketing Christ is as old as Christianity.
Entrepreneurs, tour guides and churches have cashed in on Jesus
since soldiers threw dice for his clothing after the crucifixion.
That may not be pious, but it's profitable _ and ubiquitous. That's
because most pilgrims are tourists spending the coin of one realm
to find a more spiritual kingdom. (Gushee, Palm Beach Post)
</P>
<P>
   SISTER _ Profile of Sister Gertrude Levy, a nun who ministers to
the ill and dying: and who also plays the saxophone and bongo
drums, is friends with composer Marvin Hamlisch and former Supreme
Mary Wilson, and had an Elvis impersonator at her 80th birthday
party. Sister comes from a large New Orleans family. Her
grandfather was Jewish. She has three siblings who are also in
service. (Santos, Austin American-Statesman). WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   HONDURAS-GIFTS _ SAN PEDRO SULA, Honduras _ Two students from
Heritage High School in Conyers, Ga., have come to this
poverty-stricken country with the minister-son of Billy Graham to
hand out small gifts to poor children and others living in squalor
after a recent hurricane. The Heritage kids were chosen because
they endured an attack at their school last spring in which six of
their classmates were wounded. (Hendrick, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT-ARTS
</P>
<P>
   MUSIC-HALLOFFAME _ MACON, Ga. _ When the Georgia Music Hall of
Fame opened three years ago in Macon, analysts predicted a wild
success with high attendance. They were just a bit optimistic,
although it could be argued that the museum is a quiet success. We
visit the hall to check it out with our own eyes, talk to its
director, patrons, someone from the Macon-Bibb County tourism
bureau, similar museums and the GSU prof who argued that the museum
should have been built in Atlanta. Lots of good staff art shot for
this story. (Janich, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 40. WITH
PHOTOS. EMBARGOED FOR SUNDAY.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
