<DOCNO> NYT19991210.0068 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-10 11:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5123 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-ISRAEL-EXTREMISTS-$AD     12-10 1296
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-EXTREMISTS-$ADV11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ISRAEL BRACING - MAYBE TOO MUCH - FOR MILLENNIUM SECURITY
 &HT;    (750&AMP;ADD).
 &HT;    With Photo.
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (l) Lifestyle categories.
 &HT;    For Use Sat., Dec. 11 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ One was clad in robes and preached in the streets of
Jerusalem, calling himself the Prophet Elijah. Another came from
upstate New York as Brother David and brought others to worship in
Christ's Bethany.
</P>
<P>
   Another was a successful Detroit chiropractor who came with his
family to live in caves and raise goats in the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
   They appeared harmless, but posed too much of a risk for Israel
at the dawn of a new millennium. All three were either made to
leave or refused re-entry into the country.
</P>
<P>
   Nervous about policing an event unprecedented in the modern age,
Israeli authorities are scrambling to prevent violence in the
millennial ground zero _ the land where Christianity started 2000
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   They have been accused of both over-reacting and under-reacting.
Experts have predicted everything from a gathering of only
harmless, if eccentric, believers, to violent acts that could start
regional wars.
</P>
<P>
   Assessing the danger is difficult. Millennium security is a new
field. But, fears of fanaticism should be kept in perspective.
</P>
<P>
   In any year, religious zealots are practically mainstream in
Jerusalem, a holy city for Christians, Jews and Muslims.
</P>
<P>
   It's the kind of town where the Christian waitress in a pizza
restaurant will say she moved here from Latin America at God's
command. Or, where a small museum displays replicas of the third
Jewish Temple and tools for sacrificing a red heifer _ the
cleansing ceremony for when God sweeps away the Muslim mosque now
on the temple site.
</P>
<P>
   The Jerusalem mental hospital that treats people suffering
religious delusions, called ``Jerusalem Syndrome,'' was this year
only about 10 patients over its annual average of 40.
</P>
<P>
   But the year 2000 is fraught with extra significance. For many
groups _ including at least one Jewish group _ it is the beginning
of the end of the world, coming of the Messiah or return of Jesus
Christ.
</P>
<P>
   Many Christians see it as the start of the prophecies in the
Book of Revelations. It is the time for the battle between good and
evil, and the final judgement of the end of days.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think ever in history there has been such a fantastic
staging of a messianic moment,'' said Moshe Halbertal, Israeli
researcher of messianic groups.
</P>
<P>
   The danger, Halbertal said, comes when Jan. 1 passes like any
New Year's Day. While many Jews long for the rebuilding of the
temple and many Christians believe in Revelations, Jerusalem could
host a few fanatics bent on speeding up the end of the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Jerusalem in the year 2000, we won't have only one
frustrated mass movement, we'll have two _ one Jewish and one
Christian,'' Halbertal said.
</P>
<P>
   So, Israel's highly reputed security services are faced with
preserving the peace in one of the most hyped and unpredictable
events of our time.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of video cameras and three new police stations are
going up on the narrow stone streets of Jerusalem's walled Old
City, home to the holiest sites. Hundreds of extra police will be
on duty.
</P>
<P>
   And, fueled by information from FBI agents working with the
Israeli Mossad intelligence agency, the deportations began months
ago. They have included about 40 people.
</P>
<P>
   The geographic center of concern is the hilltop campus area that
is now home to the Al-Aqsa Mosque. Al-Aqsa is the third most holy
site in Islam, where the Prophet Mohammed is believed to have
prayed before ascending to heaven. More than 400,000 Muslims are
expected there at noon Friday, Dec. 31, in prayer for the Ramadan
holiday.
</P>
<P>
   But, Jews also consider the area holy. It was the location of
the ancient Jewish temple where it is believed that God told
Abraham to sacrifice his son.
</P>
<P>
   Police have uncovered dozens of plots over the last 20 years by
Jewish terrorists planning to storm or blow up the mosque.
</P>
<P>
   Some Christians believe the area must be returned to the Jews,
and the temple rebuilt, before Jesus returns. The fear is that a
fanatic _ Christian or Jewish _ could attack the mosque. The
attacker might hope the assault could be blamed on Israel and touch
off a worldwide confrontation between Judaism and Islam.
</P>
<P>
   It's worth noting that Al-Aqsa has been attacked before and the
world has not descended into war.
</P>
<P>
   An Australian set it on fire in 1969, saying he sought to speed
up Christ's Second Coming. An American Jew shot four people there
in 1982.
</P>
<P>
   Neither attacker was activist in any organized group, showing
that it could be difficult to spot troublemakers before they act.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   So far, though, the focus has been on groups.
</P>
<P>
   One group, arrested and deported early this year, apparently
came from a Denver, Colo.-area religious organization called
Concerned Christians. They are headed by Monte Kim Miller, who
authorities speculate intends to die in some sort of violence at
the end of the millennium.
</P>
<P>
   Others were less threatening. Brother David, from upstate New
York, had been in Israel for most of 20 years and was a prayer
leader of a band of apparently peaceful, if unorthodox, people.
</P>
<P>
   Police have kept quiet about their moves, but apparently David's
efforts to bring others to the Holy Land, was too much to allow.
</P>
<P>
   The self-styled Elijah had also been here for years but may have
recently drawn too much attention. Someone started an Internet Web
page for his followers, and he was told by authorities to leave
Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Mark White, the Detroit chiropractor, who brought his family to
live in linen robes and without technology in the rural West Bank,
has not been allowed to return since going home a few weeks ago to
tend to his ill mother.
</P>
<P>
   His wife and children remain. They say Israeli authorities have
offered to let White back if they then all leave the country. They
have refused.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli authorities note many of those deported had let their
visas expire or, apparently in a belief that God forbids the making
of images, destroyed their passports and identification.
</P>
<P>
   But, some fear the police actions might create martyrs for other
zealots.
</P>
<P>
   ``It may actually help to verify the fundamentalist beliefs and
biblical prophecies,'' said David Katz, Israeli author on Christian
fundamentalism. ``The Israeli tendency to jump on the bus and kill
all the terrorists might actually prove counterproductive in this
case.''
</P>
<P>
   But, Israeli authorities want to eliminate the uncertainty.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not going to take risks and maybe we might make some
mistakes,'' said Israeli Minister of Tourism and Retired Gen. Amnon
Lipkin-Shahak. ``I don't think it will always be 100 percent right
or fair.''
</P>
<P>
   Some local Jews are also expecting big things from the
millennium. A Jewish group called Operation Homeward preaches that
2000 is the start of the worldwide persecution of Jews.
</P>
<P>
   Director Avraham Sheinman, originally from Philadelphia, cites
computer Y2K problems as part of the upheaval that will take place.
</P>
<P>
   Sheinman was a follower of the late Rabbi Meir Kahane, who was
twice suspected by Israeli security officials of plotting actions
on the Al-Aqsa mosque.
</P>
<P>
   Sheinman said he does not advocate violence. His job, he said,
is only to convince Jews that they will be safer in Israel once
everything falls apart.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do know one thing,'' Sheinman said. ``We are on the eve of
the end of days and things are very volatile.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
