 Friday, Dec. 10, 1999      The Hearst News Service will file these stories for Saturday. If
you have questions, please call Tim Spence at 202-298-6320.
    (All sluglines end with ``HNS'' tag.)
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BELL-RINGERS (Albany, N.Y.) _ The jingle of Salvation Army bells
has become a ubiquitous reminder of the holiday season, but a
shortage of volunteers at area Salvation Army corps this year has
left many outposts silent and raised concerns about meeting
fund-raising goals. By THEOLA S. LABBE.
</P>
<P>
   N.Y.-TAXES (Albany, N.Y.) _ New York Gov. George Pataki seeks a
22-cent-per-pack increase in cigarette taxes, a $100 million cut in
graduate medical education and a much more aggressive investment in
child health insurance, according to a confidential draft of his
proposed Health Care Reform Act plan. The draft appears to be a
compromise on ways to finance the state's health care system that
would neither make conservatives or health care advocates
particularly happy. By JAMES M. ODATO.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   COMPUTER-COLUMN (Undated) _ Fans of the Death Match _ and we're
talking computer games here, not professional wrestling _ are in
heaven this Christmas season. They've got not one, but two highly
anticipated titles that focus on multiplayer mayhem: id Software's
Quake III Arena and Epic Games' Unreal Tournament. But which is
better? Let's take a look. By DWIGHT SILVERMAN.
</P>
<P>
   COMPUTER-HELPLINE (Undated) _ A reader asks, ``I've managed to
put all my icons on the Windows 98 toolbars/trays at the bottom of
the screen except My Computer and the Norton Recycle Bin. I've
tried without success to remove them from the wallpaper portion on
the screen.'' Assorted Q&AMP;As. By DWIGHT SILVERMAN.
</P>
<P>
   COMPUTER-COLUMN (Houston) _ A few companies are doing something
a little different this holiday season. And you can forget the
office party. One Houston company whisked its seven employees in a
limousine to an area mall and gave each worker instructions: Here's
a couple hundred dollars. Now go buy something for yourself. By
L.M. SIXEL.
</P>
<P>
   COMPUTER-Y2K (Undated) _ The so-called Y2K computer glitch will
mostly leave things OK. Most experts predict relatively smooth
sailing in the United States, but they still recommend that people
take some precautions. By DWIGHT SILVERMAN.
</P>
<P>
   ACUPUNCTURE-INSURER (Albany, N.Y.) _ A new program by Blue
Shield of Northeastern New York will offer member discounts on
everything from acupuncture to personal trainers. The cost of the
discount will be picked up by the providers themselves in exchange
for the benefit of being part of Blue Shield's network with access
to more than 100,000 members in the region. By SYLVIA WOOD.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLES (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   TREESTANDS (Albany, N.Y.) _ Tree stands have come a long way
from a cross of wood nailed to the base of the tree. Now on the
market is the patented Swivel Straight tree stand by Country Line
Limited of Solon, Ohio. Simply by stepping on a pedal, you can
swivel the tree into place. To keep the tree in position, just
release the pedal. No more crawling around on the floor readjusting
screws. By FRANCES INGRAHAM HEINS.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SKI-EXERCISES (Albany, N.Y.) _ Only fools believe they can ski
their way into shape. It doesn't happen in the real world without
creating sore muscles, pulled ones or even worse. Harald Harb,
coach and trainer of the U.S. National Demonstration Team, offers
some advice on how to prepare for the season. By BUZZ GRAY.
</P>
<P>
   RAC-NY-STAKES (Saratoga Springs, N.Y.) _ The New York Racing
Association is delivering some early Christmas presents to
horsemen, unveiling its richest stakes program in history. Saratoga
Race Course will be the site of some of the largest increases as
the historic Whitney will be bumped up to $750,000 this summer from
last year's mark of $600,000.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BARLOW-COLUMN (Undated) _ Amtrak, the government-owned rail
passenger service, has a drop-dead date in 2002. That's when the
system is required by Congress to meet its operational costs. And
Amtrak has made substantial progress toward that goal, says the
General Accounting Office. But there's no assurance that it's going
to actually make that goal. By JIM BARLOW.
</P>
