<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-10 12:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5156 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-SCHOOL-VIOLENCE-$ADV1     12-10 1258
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHOOL-VIOLENCE-$ADV12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SCHOOL VIOLENCE HURTS THE SURVIVORS TOO
 &HT;    840&AMP;add. With SCHOOL-VIOLENCE-DATA for release Sunday, Dec. 12.
 &HT;    By ANDREW MOLLISON
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The pain from a murder lingers long after the last
scrap of yellow crime-scene tape is gone from the grounds of the
school.
</P>
<P>
   Brenda Muhammad and Gregory Carter learned that the hard way.
Muhammad's son was murdered in Atlanta. Carter, a former teacher,
was shot in Richmond, Va.
</P>
<P>
   They empathize with the bewildered families of both the victims
and the victimizers whenever a multiple-victim school shooting
dominates the network news.
</P>
<P>
   But they stress that even more students, families and witnesses
suffer physical and emotional damage from the routine, one-on-one
violence that doesn't make headlines around the world.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody died in the much-publicized school shootings in Fort
Gibson, Okla., last week. But since August, at least a dozen people
have died in one-on-one assaults like the ones that transformed
Muhammad and Carter into volunteer crusaders for community-based
anti-violence efforts in schools.
</P>
<P>
   At a school violence seminar this month in a suburban Washington
hotel, Muhammad reminded education writers that families in suburbs
or small towns are not the only ones who ask themselves, ``Why did
it happen here, and to this child?''
</P>
<P>
   She said her 16-year-old son was shot in the back of the head in
1989 by an ``emotionally challenged'' young friend who had argued
with him over a New England Patriots jacket that cost $89. Her son
died two days after he was attacked in front of the school in
southeast Atlanta where Muhammad had been president of the PTA.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a wailing that comes from the parent. Not crying; I'm
talking about something more than that,'' she said. ``It is from
the pit of that parent's stomach. Your knees weaken, your body is
like water. I can't explain it to you. Just hope you never
experience it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I am far beyond the anger I felt in 1989 toward the young man
who committed this crime,'' said Muhammad. ``I hurt for him and
others like him, because we have millions like him out there who
are not receiving the kind of treatment they need if we are going
to lower the level of violence.''
</P>
<P>
   She finally channeled her grief into founding a national support
group, MOMS, an acronym for mothers of murdered sons and daughters.
She also directs a local assistance program for victims and
witnesses and has served on the Atlanta school board since her
election in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Carter's troubles began in June 1998, one day before the end of
his 21st school year as a teacher of American history at Armstrong
High School in Richmond, Va.
</P>
<P>
   From the window of his second-floor classroom, he spotted two
students whom he once had in class struggling for control of a gun.
</P>
<P>
   ``Naturally, I ran down to stop them,'' said Carter. He was too
late.
</P>
<P>
   ``They say there were 10 shots,'' Carter said. ``I went into the
wrong direction for cover, and as I re-routed myself, that was when
one shot hit me in the side and lodged in my abdomen.''
</P>
<P>
   Less than a week later, while he recuperated in a hospital, he
turned on the TV news. That is how he learned that a recent
graduate whom he had coached in basketball had been shot to death
in a similar situation: trying to mediate a fight between two young
men.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had lived,'' he said. ``I felt blessed.''
</P>
<P>
   Fellow educators, old students, church members and neighbors
rallied around at first. But several expressed deep disappointment
after he visited his assailant and then helped to have him treated
as a juvenile, rather than prosecuted as an adult.
</P>
<P>
   Uncomfortable at the thought of returning to Armstrong, he began
teaching at a new school last fall. There were occasional
flashbacks, surges of anger, trembling and other signs of
post-trauma stress. But Carter continued doggedly to teach until
</P>
<P>
   he glanced at a TV set one day last April and learned about the
shootings at Columbine High School in Littleton, Colo.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tried to go back to school, but I could not,'' he said. He
is retired now, with a full disability pension. His marriage has
collapsed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Physically, the doctor says I'm lucky, and I say I am
blessed,'' Carter said. ``But do you see? This kind of thing can
have an effect on a personal life as well.''
</P>
<P>
   He can see one positive result: ``The Richmond public schools,
hopefully by next year, will have telephones or some signal device
in every classroom from elementary through high school, so teachers
won't have to run to the office for help.''
</P>
<P>
   In this school year, public attention has once again focused
most tightly on a spectacular incident: millions know that at a
middle school in Oklahoma, one student shot four others.
</P>
<P>
   ``But that ended pretty quickly because they were 'only'
wounded,'' said Bill Modzeleski, director of the U.S. Education
Department's program for safe and drug-free schools. ``How bizarre
that we are becoming so immune to school violence that we would put
it like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, murders, suicides and fights in and near schools
since August have taken the lives of at least eight children and
four adults.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows)
</P>
<P>
   Ten died in one-victim incidents; two others died in a
murder-suicide.
</P>
<P>
   Eight victims shot themselves or others with guns, and one was
stabbed with a screwdriver. The other three were killed without
weapons: a high school sophomore hit his head twice on the
cafeteria floor while involved in and being dragged away from a
fight in Omaha, and two school security officers _ one in East
Point, Ga., and the other in Brooklyn _ had heart attacks after
breaking up a fight.
</P>
<P>
   The youngest victims were both 13. A boy was stabbed in the head
as he walked from home room to his first-period class in a middle
school in Houston and a girl was shot in the lobby of her middle
school in Deming, N.M.
</P>
<P>
   The two oldest were old enough to join the AARP. A 57-year-old
former school bus driver at a high school in Lincoln County, W.Va.,
shot himself after slaying a 66-year-old janitor whom he mistakenly
thought was carrying on with his wife.
</P>
<P>
   Police arrested another janitor's husband in Dayton, Ohio, after
she was shot as she left a school to go home at the end of her
shift.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Trump of Cleveland, a school security consultant who helped
compile that sample of recent school fatalities, said deaths are
only ``the tip of the iceberg.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Think of the families and victims of the lesser crimes _
assaults, shoving, pushing, extortion, sexual offenses and so on _
which occur in school,'' Trump said. ``Many go unreported by
educators who are afraid that full disclosure will damage their
chances for promotion or for passing a school levy the next year.''
</P>
<P>
   You can write to MOMS, 1405 Woodland Ave., Atlanta, Ga., 30316
or e-mail momsII(at)aol.com.
</P>
<P>
   For links to many Web sites on school violence, click on ``Safe
&AMP; Drug Free Schools'' at the Education Department home page
(http://www.ed.gov).
</P>
<P>
   To find out how your local public school can get a free
satellite dish in order to participate in six violence-prevention
teleconferences sponsored by virtually every major national
education group in 2000, try another site (
http://www.nea.org/issues/safescho/echostar/).
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Mollison's e-mail address is andym(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
