<DOCNO> NYT19991210.0074 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-10 12:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5168 &Cx1f; tic-z
r k BC-CUBANBOY-EDIT-AZR &LR;      12-10 0393
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUBAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CUBAN BOY NEEDS DAD, NOT POLITICS  
 (THIS EDITORIAL APPEARED IN FRIDAY'S EDITORIAL REPUBLIC) 
</HEADLINE>
 BOY-EDIT-AZR   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - A 6-year-old boy should not have to turn to strangers
to mourn the death of his mother. Not when his father's arms are
waiting to hold him.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone with a heart would tell you that reuniting a grieving
child with his father is simple human decency.
</P>
<P>
   But leaven in some political opportunism, and that child's pain
becomes currency to be spent for a cause.
</P>
<P>
   Witness the case of Elian Gonzalez. Fate left him afloat in the
ocean after his mother and stepfather were killed trying to cross
illegally from Cuba to the United States.
</P>
<P>
   He was rescued Nov. 25. But his ordeal isn't over yet. He
remains in a strange land.
</P>
<P>
   Mourning his mother. Without his father.
</P>
<P>
   The adults both in the land of his birth and the land that his
mother died to reach have disgraced themselves in the name of
self-righteousness.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. authorities placed the boy with his mother's relatives and
announced that Florida courts would decide where he should live. He
celebrated his sixth birthday in Florida, riding a pony, swinging a
new baseball bat, marveling at the wonders of a plastic Minnie
Mouse.
</P>
<P>
   Mourning his mother. Without his father.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. relatives who want to prevent his return to Cuba coaxed
this confused, overwhelmed, grieving little boy into making a
public statement that he wants to stay in the land of plenty. He
wants to help fulfill their anti-Castro political aims.
</P>
<P>
   Mourning his mother. Replacing his father with material goods.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Cuba's government demonstrated its legendary lack of
decency. Fidel Castro put up billboards in Havana with the child's
face, ordered up thousands of protesters and warned of dire
consequences if the boy was not returned.
</P>
<P>
   Boy became symbol.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, blistered from the bright light of public
criticism, the Immigration and Naturalization Service told the
father it ``would be interested in hearing from him about the
boy.'' The INS says it will act in the best interests of the child.
</P>
<P>
   It's about time everybody involved started acting in the best
interests of a little boy who faces the tough job of mourning his
mother.
</P>
<P>
   And needs his father. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-10-99 1242EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
