<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-10 13:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5183 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e BC-TIM-ALLEN-IN-GALAXY-Q     12-10 1029
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TIM-ALLEN-IN-GALAXY-QUEST-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIM ALLEN, LIGHT YEARS FROM `HOME' 
</HEADLINE>
  (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to Inside Trek, a
weekly science-fiction column with color and black-and-white art.)
 (Includes a color slide and a black-and-white photo of Tim Allen
with Robin Sachs in a scene from ``Galaxy Quest.'') 
 By IAN SPELLING  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    One of the biggest sci-fi fans on the planet is ... Tim Allen.
 &HT;    Who'd'a thunk it?
 &HT;    The former star of television's ``Home Improvement'' grew up
reading Galaxy magazine. He collects ``Alien'' memorabilia, and can
quote chapter and verse from the works of Larry Niven.
 &HT;    ``It started when I was a kid,'' he says. ``Sci-fi books and
films stimulated my world. I loved space ships and the adventure of
space travel, the technical stuff and the ray guns.
 &HT;    ``What I liked most _ and still like _ is that sci-fi stimulated
my imagination to go to worlds totally different from the one I
lived in.''
 &HT;    Allen boldly goes to one of those fantastic worlds on Christmas
Day, with the release of Dean Parisot's sci-fi comedy ``Galaxy
Quest,'' starring Allen, Sigourney Weaver and Alan Rickman.
 &HT;    Allen plays Jason Nesmith, a cocky actor best known as Commander
Taggart, the Kirk-esque hero of ``Galaxy Quest,'' a sci-fi series
that ran for four years in the 1970s. These days, however, Nesmith
and his co-stars live off the convention circuit, endlessly signing
autographs and recounting their glory years for the ``Galaxy
Quest'' faithful.
 &HT;    One afternoon, real aliens _ who for years have been picking up
reruns of ``Galaxy Quest'' and mistake them for actual events _
draft Nesmith and company for their bona-fide space battles.
 &HT;    ``When I first read it, I said, `This could be really silly and,
no offense to Mel Brooks, it could be `Spaceballs,''' Allen says by
telephone from his Los Angeles home. ``Instead, Dean Parisot set
the story up as a documentary with layers that get peeled away as
you get deeper into the film. It's very clever and so subtle.
 &HT;    ``He lets it run so it feels like you're watching a slice of
life with these people and then, when it gets into high gear, it
becomes a wonderful sci-fi adventure,'' the comedian says. ``But,
all the while, you've got the fake and the real being twisted
around.
 &HT;    ``You've got fake actors acting like real space heroes and
aliens that are obviously real, in a situation that's not real in a
whole movie that's not real,'' he concludes. ``It's essentially a
big sci-fi action movie with humor.''
 &HT;    Allen cracked jokes aplenty on the set, but strove to suppress
his inner comedian when he faced the film's more dramatic moments.
 &HT;    Weaver had her own problems, he notes: She had to keep her
formidable ``Alien'' alter ego out of the way in playing blonde and
buxom Gwen DeMarco _ aka ``Galaxy Quest's'' seductive leading lady,
Tawny Madison.
 &HT;    ``Boy, it was hard for Sigourney, when we were running down
hallways and fighting aliens who were shooting at us, not to grab
the gun from my hand, push me out of the way and go, `I'll take
care of this,''' Allen says, laughing. ``More than once I said,
`You're not Ripley here. I'm the hero.'
 &HT;    ``It eventually became a test of wills,'' he says, ``even as two
people, not really actors, as to who would go first through the
door. But it came out wonderfully.''
 &HT;    Moviegoers can judge for themselves how ``Galaxy Quest'' turned
out, but if the film is half as wonderful as ``Toy Story 2,''
Allen's other December launch, it'll be cause for celebration.
Allen once again provides the voice of Buzz Lightyear in the
acclaimed sequel to Disney/Pixar's 1995 digitally animated
blockbuster.
 &HT;    This time around Buzz, along with Andy's other playthings,
mounts a rescue mission to save Woody (the voice of Tom Hanks) from
the sweaty clutches of a toy collector (the voice of Wayne Knight).
Along the way, the group encounters the evil Zurg and a new-edition
Buzz (also Allen) who doesn't comprehend that he's merely a toy.
 &HT;    ``I love `Toy Story 2,' but I'm loyal to the first movie,''
Allen says. ``It's like `Aliens' to `Alien': `Aliens' was clearly a
better piece of entertainment, but I won't say it was a better
movie.
 &HT;    ```Toy Story 2' is a much better piece of entertainment than the
first one,'' he says. ``It's not better, though, because the first
one was the first one.''
 &HT;    Allen would welcome a third ``Toy Story'' installment, but in
the meantime he's plenty busy. His line of Tim Allen Signature
Tools helps raise funds for children's-education charities, while
his production company, Boxing Cat, develops film projects.
 &HT;    Truth be told, where Allen would most rather be right now is on
a Hollywood sound stage, starring in a feature entitled
``Graviton.''
 &HT;    ``It's a script I've been writing and tweaking for nine years,''
the comedian says. ``It's a good sci-fi story, but it's not
supposed to be _ nor will I let it become _ a comedy.
 &HT;    ``I want to play the lead,'' Allen says, ``but I'll be the old
man in it if I keep putting it off. I am going to do it, even if I
have to finance it myself.''
 c.1999 Ian Spelling  
<TEXT>
