<HEADLINE>
HEALTH STUDY DATA DEMANDED IN US CHAMBER SUIT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By AARON ZITNER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Picking a legal fight with universities and
hospitals, a major business group is demanding that researchers at
Harvard University and elsewhere turn over data from health studies
that the researchers say is personal and confidential.
</P>
<P>
   The demand by the US Chamber of Commerce is designed to provoke
a lawsuit that would test a new law that allows anyone to request
data produced under federal research grants. Business groups had
pushed for the law, saying federal agenciese tightening clean air
rules and setting other policies on the basis of research data that
remained secret.
</P>
<P>
   The law, which Congress passed last year with little notice,
allows anyone to obtain ``all data'' produced with federl money by
filing a request under the Freedom of Information Act. The
22-year-old act gives citizens access to government documents, but
until now generally could not be used to reach beyond ederal
agencies to obtain information from individuals or organizations.
</P>
<P>
   University and hospital researchers reacted with alarm to the
new law, saying it would force them to break confidentiality
agreements with research subjects and business partners, stifling
future research.
</P>
<P>
   Many said the real intent of the law was to allow businesses to
harass scientists working in controversial fields, such as air
quality and tobacco.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers were cheered, however, when the White House Office
of Management and Budget ruled in October that the law would apply
to a limited range of research and that sensitive medical and
business records would not be released.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the Chamber of Commerce is trying to overturn the White
House ruling, which it said illegally narrowed the scope of the
law.
</P>
<P>
   ``OMB decimated the congressional intent by limiting the
information that has to be made available,'' William Kovacs, vice
president for environmental and regulatory affairs at the Chamber
of Commerce, said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The law, known as the Shelby amendment, took effect last month.
</P>
<P>
   The business group Thursday filed three requests under the
Freedom of Information Act, asking the US Environmental Protection
Agency to turn or data produced by university researchers. Kvacs
said he expected the EPA to reject the requests, and that the
chamber would likely respond with a lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   In two requests, the business group asked for data produced by
the Harvard School of Public Health, Cambridge-based Abt Associates
Inc., and other institutions that were later cited by the EPA in
proposing tougher clean-gasoline and clean-air regulations.
</P>
<P>
   Kovacs said these requests are designed to challenge the White
House ruling that the Shelby amendment covers only data produced
under new grants, not grants handed out before the law took effect
last month.
</P>
<P>
   In its third request, the Chamber of Commerce asked for any data
the EPA cited in formulating ``environmental justice'' decisions.
These are EPA rulings that block states from issuing permits to
businesses that want to build plants in minority or low-income
areas that already have a disproportionate number of plants.
</P>
<P>
   Kovacs said this request is designed to challenge the White
House ruling that the Shelby amendment covers only research used in
setting federal policies that have the force of law. The chamber
says agencies set many policies that are costly or affect business
practices, but which do not have the force of law.
</P>
<P>
   Joel Schwartz, an associate professor at the Harvard School of
Public Health, said the chamber appeared to be requesting data from
him that he had drawn from public sources and was already in the
public domain.
</P>
<P>
   But Schwartz said the chamber was also asking for health data
from his colleagues that they collected only afterromising
confidentiality to their research subjects.
</P>
<P>
   If that information is released, ``the biggest problem is that
no one would ever be able to do a study again,'' he said. To
persuade people to join studies, ``you have to convince them that
you're really going to keep (the material) confidential.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very effective way of preventing any future air
pollution research from getting done ... I think industry thinks
that's just fine, because these studies keep coming up with answers
they don't like,'' Schwartz said.
</P>
<P>
   The Harvard research concluded that thousands of people die each
year from inhaling soot and other airborne particles. The EPA drew
on those findings in developing tougher air quality standar, which
are awaiting Supreme Court review.
</P>
<P>
   Harvard researchers offered their data to the Health Effects
Institute, which is funded jointly by industry and the EPA. But the
chamber says the data should still be made public.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
