<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-PRIDE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TACKLING A COMPLEX AMERICAN ICON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
WHEN PRIDE STILL MATTERED 
A Life of Vince Lombardi 
By David Maraniss 
Simon &AMP; Schuster, 541 pp., illustrated, $26 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Winning isn't everything, it's the only thing,'' Vince
Lombardi's famous (and infamous) credo, was uttered first by an
11-year-old actress in a forgotten 1953 movie. And when Lombardi
did say it, he was talking about the National Football League, not
about life.
</P>
<P>
   He was not an honor student, as profilers suggested, but a C
scholar who dropped out of law school after a semester. Though
Lombardi gave patriotic speeches, he avoided serving in World War
II and pulled strings to keep his star player from being called up
during the 1961 Berlin crisis. And while he preached the importance
of family, he virtually ignored his wife, son, and daughter and
adopted his players as surrogates.
</P>
<P>
   Myth busting is at the core of ``When Pride Still Mattered,'' an
exhaustively researched (and, at times, exhaustively written)
biography of the famed Green Bay Packers coach who still stands as
an American icon three decades after his death from cancer in 1970.
</P>
<P>
   David Maraniss, the Pulitzer Prize-winning journalist for the
Washington Post who explicated Bill Clinton in ``First in His
Class,'' grew up in Wisconsin during the '60s, when Lombardi was so
revered by the citizenry that he was dubbed ``The Pope.'' Now,
writes Maraniss, at a time when professional sport's grace has
largely given way to greed, ``Many yearn for Lombardi out of a
sense of longing for something they fear has been irretrievably
lost. . . . Why isn't there anyone like the Old Man out there
anymore?''
</P>
<P>
   It's not as if there wasn't anyone like Lombardi after Lombardi
_ Don Shula of the Miami Dolphins, Chuck Noll of the Pittsburgh
Steelers, Tom Landry of the Dallas Cowboys, and Bill Parcells of
the New York Giants (then the Patriots, and now the New York Jets)
all stressed the same virtues: discipline, consistency,
selflessness, resilience, confidence, pride. But Lombardi, who
coached the Packers from 1959 to 1967, captured the nation's
imagination at a time when pro football was beginning to displace
baseball as the national game and American society was in
transition from conformity to division.
</P>
<P>
   Lombardi was demanding, charismatic, energetic, obsessive _ and
his Packers won, five championships in his final seven years. He
was documented in snapshot form during his heyday, by W. C. Heinz
in ``Run to Daylight!'' and (indirectly) by player Jerry Kramer in
``Instant Replay.'' But Maraniss is decidedly more ambitious and
definitive. He traces Lombardi from beginning to end, re-creating
his milieus along the way _ the immigrant Brooklyn of the '20s, the
Fordham of the '30s, the exurban New Jersey of the '40s, the West
Point and New York of the '50s, the Green Bay of the '60s.
</P>
<P>
   Maraniss's research is daunting, with dozens of interviews
(including Lombardi's son, Vince; daughter, Susan; and brother
Harold) supplementing more than 50 books, sheaves of newspaper
clips, even hospital records. And though his writing can be
digressive (the 1951 West Point cribbing scandal which involved
Lombardi only marginally, is given more than a dozen pages), he
gets his man down fully and finally.
</P>
<P>
   Lombardi was the oldest son of an Italian-born butcher who had
W-O-R-K and P-L-A-Y tattooed on his fingers. Harry Lombardi taught
his boy about the importance of duty, respect for authority, and
discipline. The Jesuits at Fordham (where Lombardi was one of the
football team's famed Seven Blocks of Granite) taught him the
exercise of free will within a hierarchy.
</P>
<P>
   In football, Lombardi found one place where all the lessons came
together. Though his short, blockish build kept him from playing
stardom, his relentless perfectionism and his knack for motivation
made him a superb coach. ``There are other coaches who know more
about X's and O's,'' Lombardi conceded. ``But I've got an edge. I
know more about football players than they do.''
</P>
<P>
   Lombardi knew when to push them and when to back off and how to
keep them off balance by dispensing praise and scorn unpredictably.
He was harsh (``Defy me! Defy me!'' he screamed in practice) yet
fair. Lombardi brooked no prejudice (``If I ever hear'' racial and
ethnic slurs, he told his players, ``you're through with me'') and
quietly rooted for homosexual players (his brother is gay) to make
his team.
</P>
<P>
   His Packers loved him, his Packers hated him. But for the nine
years he coached them, they played _ and won _ for him as no team
did for anyone else. It was, Lombardi preached, a matter of team
love: The Packers were a family. Yet the sad truth, Maraniss
writes, is that Lombardi felt closer to them than he did to his own
family, which pined for his attention.
</P>
<P>
   His wife, Marie, who died of cancer in 1982, turned to alcohol
and pills. His son and daughter craved a share of the attention he
lavished on his team. ``You know what?'' Lombardi once confessed to
the team broadcaster. ``I was a terrible father.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet he was, and to some still is, an American father figure, a
complex and contradictory mix of intimacy and aloofness, rigidity
and compassion. A week into their marriage, Marie Lombardi told
herself it was the biggest mistake of her life. Three decades
later, she sang her torch song to him over cocktails: ``You're
Nobody 'Til Lombardi Loves You.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-10-99 1341EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991210.0083 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-10 13:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5194 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k BC-NYHAN-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      12-10 0906
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYHAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BATTLE-TESTED CLINTON MAKES RIVALS LOOK LIKE MINOR LEAGUERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID NYHAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   No one is big enough to be president of this country right off
the bat. It's all about growing. The time, experience, and scars
are essential ingredients. And the president who traveled to
Worcester Thursday to honor six fallen firefighters grew into the
job these past seven years, crafting a persona and record that his
enemies cannot diminish no matter how much they denounce and deny.
</P>
<P>
   The televised news conference Clinton unrolled the day before,
his summing-up of his seventh year in office, was indisputable
evidence of Clinton's skills, unrivaled on the contemporary
political scene. Put that Clinton into the mix of the six
Republican presidential candidates whose debate was televised from
Arizona this week, and it's no contest.
</P>
<P>
   Nor do Vice President Gore or Bill Bradley, the two Democrats
out for the job, match Clinton's ability to deliver a flawless
speech, fence with reporters for an hour of live televised
repartee, and connect with the public.
</P>
<P>
   The incumbent's well-advertised moral flaws notwithstanding, his
leadership skills are apparent to all but the ost obtuse critics. A
president with what appears to be an inordinate desire to be loved
flashes his talents before an audience often dulled to his
brilliance. But there remains that huge chasm between Clinton's
performance and the skill level of those who would replace him.
Able men in their different ways, they have yet to commandeer the
public's interest or the critics' esteem in the way Clinton did
before he crashed into disgrace.
</P>
<P>
   Running the gauntlet of a presidential campaign is the way we
test the mettle of those who would lead. Every campaign cycle
offers a different combination of quirky coincidences and
developments that cannot be anticipated. Events rush at a candidate
with accelerating speed. The  &UR; morning  &LR; after Paul Tsongas won the
New Hampshire primary over Clinton in 1992, I told Tsongas that he
would feel like an Olympic skier, hurtling down a sheer slope on
the slickest ice, gates slapping him in the face, aware that any
second could bring calamity. No one knows what it's like till he
gets there.
</P>
<P>
   Sizing up his audience and tailoring his remarks, decisions, and
body language to the group is what made Clinton president, and made
him the president he became. He learned. Like Bill Bradley, he's a
Rhodes scholar. No one ever said he wasn't smart. A voracious
reader, still, no one doubts he's devouring all those books on race
relations he's scanning as he writes his own.
</P>
<P>
   Put that up against George W. Bush's clumsy defense of his own
reading habits, and it's no contest. Forging bonds of empathy with
mass audiences is what sustains presidentilleadership. Even before
Clinton landed in Worcester Thursday, I had no oubt he would
connect with the audience, and families left with 17 fatherless
children in a way that would be appropriate to the occasion and
memorable.
</P>
<P>
   Queen Elizabeth II told of her annus horribilis in 1992, a
particularly grim year for the Windsor clan. Clinton just survived
his Year of Kenneth Starr. But he keeps on, talking up his
achievements, wooing public opinion with artful asides and sly
strategems. On health insurance, Social Security, economic policy,
Clinton knows what to say, and what not to say.
</P>
<P>
   He is the sole colossus on the world stage, the man who
strong-arms Israel and Syria into renewed peace talks, who brokers
Northern Ireland's grudging, ripening resolution, who tiptoes
nimbly between the two Chinas, who alternately cajoles and ignores
the bumbling Boris Yeltsin, managing the diffcult relationship with
Russia like a worldly wise uncle handling an unruly drunk at the
family gathering. Clinton wins more respect abroad than at home,
where his enemies are dug into impregnable positions in the media
and political office.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clinton fatigue'' is the popular label. ``Clinton
exasperation'' is what his critics suffer. Which is why they give
him zero credit for anything that was done right or well in the
last seven years, the greatest economic boom ever.
</P>
<P>
   Talk of his ``legacy'' preoccupies those in the Republican Party
and news media _ it is often hard to distinguish between them _ who
deem it their role to call Clinton perpetually to account. They
have dogehim and denigrated him to the point of diminishing
returns. If Clinton could run for a third term, there are millions
who would vote for him.
</P>
<P>
   His rivals talk of him as though he was already comatose, a big
mistake when the most skillful pol in the land has almost 14 more
months in office. Say what you will, about his priapic
propensities, hairsplitting or truthfulness, he has demonstrated
the capacity to grow in office.
</P>
<P>
   Can you say the same of the man most likely, in the polls, to
succeed him? Is Bush growing in his capacity to lead? John McCain
gets bigger before our eyes, but Bush seems to be shrinking under
the relentless spotlight. All to date is mere fund-raising,
polling, and a couple of patty-cake debates. It gets tougher every
day, and there are 11 long months to the verdict. Despite the worst
hammering any politician has endured since Nixon, Clinton does not
shrink. Let us see which of his would-be successors grows.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(David Nyhan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
