<HEADLINE>
SECOND-YEAR COLT QB WILL KEEP PATRIOTS ON THEIR TOES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK BLAUDSCHUN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ Different week, different game, different
quarterback. From Dan Marino to Troy Aikman to Doug Flutie to
Peyton Manning, the Patriots are getting an up-close look at the
marquee quarterbacks of the National Football League, past,
present, and future.
</P>
<P>
   Manning, the second-year man whose Colts are Sunday's foe, is
the leading passer in the AFC in yards, touchdowns, and completion
percentage. He's got the attention and respect of the Patriots.
</P>
<P>
   ``Peyton's playing great football,'' said quarterback Drew
Bledsoe, who is not playing great football right now. ``The
attention he is getting is well deserved and I don't begrudge that
with him one bit. He is playing in a good offense and he's the
linchpin. He's making it happen for them. This is a big matchup
with the quarterbacks. He was able to go down to Miami and take a
win from Mrino and the Dolphins, but he hasn't bt me yet and I
don't intend to let them start.''
</P>
<P>
   One of Manning's strengths is his ability on play-action passes
to conceal the ball until the last instant, a talent the Patriots
are well aware of.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to be careful,'' cornerback Ty Law said, ``because he
can hide the ball and all of a sudden set up and go downfield to
(wide receiver Marvin) Harrison.
</P>
<P>
   Manning came into the league out of Tennessee as a No. 1 pick,
and after a year of adjustments, he's playing like one. The
difference is clear, said Patriots coach Pete Carroll.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year when we played him in the first game we made a
highlight film,'' Carroll said. ``His numbers weren't great in that
game, but in that highlight film we saw 15 to 18 extraordinary
throws that rarely would you see a top-flight quarterback make in
the course of a year. You could see the high end he had, and this
year he's doing it on a regular basis.''
</P>
<P>
   Carroll says the Colts have fiddled with their offense to take
advantage of Manning's skills. ``I attribute a lot of it to the
style of things that they're doing with him,'' said the coach. ``I
think (offensive coordinator) Tom Moore has done a remarkably good
job of putting together things that he can execute right off the
bat as a first- and second-year guy. They do a very nice job using
their players in ways they can really complement each other. Marvin
running across the field, the play-action stuff with Edgerrin
(James), the style of quick rhythm, that ball is out so fast from
Peyton. Even on the play-actions.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of these things added together, with Peyton being able to
control it all in his mind and handle it, it's a tremendous job
coaching. Without Peyton's ability, none of this would be
possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Carroll has seen the early skepticism around the league about
Manning's arm strength die down. ``There were times when people
would question it,'' he said. ``But coupled with the style and the
release, it's an excellent arm. He can throw the ball on a line
40-50 yards and hit guys in creases. He throws very well on the
move. He throws well when he's in trouble and has to find a second
and third receiver.''
</P>
<P>
   Manning is where Bledsoe was before his slump. A young
quarterback with an offense that can seemingly score points against
any team in the league.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots hope they can put the same kind of pressure on
Manning as they did on Aikman Sunday night, when the defense, led
by Willie McGinest, harrassed and hammered the Dallas quarterback
throughout the game.
</P>
<P>
   But the bottom line is that Manning is a cut above the rest
right now.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's better than anyone,'' said Carroll.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
