<SLUG> BC-COMPUTERS-BOMBAY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WACKO KEYBOARD HAS TURNED INTO `CONTROL' FREAK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DR. EMILIO BOMBAY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DEAR DR. BOMBAY: I'm using a Microsoft ``ergonomic'' keyboard on
a machine running Windows 98. Occasionally, the keyboard goes into
a ``control mode.'' When you hit the ``E'' key, Windows Explorer is
launched, when you hit the ``R'' key, the Run box is launched, etc.
I seem to be the only person around this office having this
problem.
</P>
<P>
   _ Keyboard Kaper
</P>
<P>
   DEAR KEYBOARD: Don't get all paranoid on me. Microsoft messes
with everybody, not just you. If it's not this keyboard thing, it's
``illegal operations'' or ``fatal exceptions'' or disappearing
cursors or that deal that records every single keystroke and relays
it back to world domination headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   Windows tends to get silly at times, especially when it's
keeping track of a lot of stuff going on in the background, and
this keyboard weirdness is a perfect example. Somehow, Win98 thinks
you're pressing one of the two Windows keys, which, when combined
with regular keys, ordinarily provide shortcuts to certain Windows
features. For example, Windows-E starts Explorer and Windows-D
minimizes all open applications.
</P>
<P>
   Many times the culprit confusing Windows is System Agent (or
Task Scheduler, as it's now known). Ordinarily, it's loaded by
default, and most people don't even realize it's running. Try
disabling it: Go to Accessories/System Tools in the Programs menu,
where it's probably listed as ``Scheduled Tasks.'' Open it up and
go to the Advanced menu, where you have the option of turning it
off.
</P>
<P>
   If that doesn't work, see which other things you can turn off.
In Windows 98, open the Run dialog from the Start menu (or use
Windows-R) and type in Msconfig (Enter). You'll find a little
utility that lets you control exactly what starts up when you turn
things on.
</P>
<P>
   When none of that works, ask your company's support tech for a
regular keyboard without the extra keys. I only hope you can keep
it a secret from Microsoft. Watch your back.
</P>
<P>
   DEAR DR. BOMBAY: I don't know what happened, but my sound has
stopped in Windows. It does OK in DOS. My sound card is not listed
in the Device Manager.
</P>
<P>
   _ Sounds of Silence
</P>
<P>
   DEAR SOUND: Ah, another silly thing Windows does: lose track of
its peripherals. Ordinarily, anything that disappears from the
Device Manager _ but that you know still works _ will be
rediscovered if you run the Add New Hardware Wizard in the Control
Panel. Even if Windows misses it, you'll get the opportunity to
specify exactly what you want reinstalled.
</P>
<P>
   But rather than put your trust in Windows, go to the sound card
maker's Web site and download the latest driver. It should come
with installation instructions and, if you're lucky, an automated
setup program.
</P>
<P>
   DEAR DR. BOMBAY: I am being continually ``dropped'' when online.
My Internet Service provider has assured me that their system is
working perfectly.
</P>
<P>
   _ Unhooked
</P>
<P>
   DEAR UNHOOKED: Well, what did you expect them to say? Assuming
your equipment and software haven't changed and the dog hasn't been
chewing up the phone lines, that sort of narrows it down. If your
ISP keeps dropping you, drop them. There are plenty of other
providers in the phone book.
</P>
<P>
   (Dr. Emilio Bombay recently changed Internet providers, but it
wasn't voluntary. Apparently, several restraining orders were
involved. However, you still can reach him at
drbombay(at)star-telegram.com (snail-mail: Fort Worth
Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort Worth, TX 76101). Fax: (818)
390-7257. In real life, he is Michael Gerst, editorial systems
manager for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
