<SLUG> BC-TV-SPORTS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATRIOTS, THE JAMES VERSION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HOWARD MANLY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Craig James readily acknowledges that his observation is not a
revelation.
</P>
<P>
   But when players quit playing for a coach, said the CBS analyst
and former Patriots running back, a coaching change is bound to
occur. And in his mind, the Patriots fit into that category.
</P>
<P>
   ``I watched the Buffalo game and, in my opinion, there were
several plays that could have been made that weren't,'' James said.
``Those plays were purely an effort question.''
</P>
<P>
   James couldn't cite specific plays, but explained that it was a
``general feeling.''
</P>
<P>
   James went on ``The NFL Today'' pregame show last Sunday and
told viewers that the Patriots and New York Giants would be looking
for new coaches if their players quit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Quitting is not just not running to the ball,'' James
explained. ``N nning to the ball is just the most glaring
observation. But quitting occurs Monday through Friday. The players
are not really into doing all the things that they are supposed to
do. They stop taking care of the personal things. They stop eating
right. They don't get enough sleep. The Patriots are in a tough
division, and every little thing matters. There is not one thing
that they can overlook.''
</P>
<P>
   Rest assured, James added, that the Buffalo Bills and
Indianapolis Colts are taking care of business every day.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, coach Pete Carroll responded by taking a swipe at
James, saying James doesn't know his team or his players.
</P>
<P>
   Don't get James wrong, though. He is one of the Patriots'
biggest fans. The problem, he says, is that he has to tell the
truth.
</P>
<P>
   ``What makes it hard is that I have several friends on the
coaching staff,'' James said. ``Pete Carroll is a good football
coach. But he has known that he would be watched this year. He also
knows that he has to succeed. But I can't be a homer. I have to be
a straight-shooter.''
</P>
<P>
   True, indeed. And that's why he likes the Patriots against the
Colts on Sunday. ``The Pats are in a good position to knock off the
Colts,'' James said. ``The Colts have had to get up two weeks in a
row, first against the Jets, then against Miami. Now they have to
get up again, for the Patriots. The law of averages says they will
not be able to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   But James offered a final warning. ``Thirteen points won't get
it done against the Colts,'' he said. ``The Pats have got to score
21, 24, or 28 points to beat them.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Golden opportunity
</P>
<P>
   peaking of the Colts, HBO will air a good feature on Peyton
Manning Tuesday at 10 p.m. on ``Real Sportswith Bryant Gumbel.''
</P>
<P>
   Frank Deford asks Manning if he was sick of the image that he
had or if he was irritated when San Diego quarterback Ryan Leaf
called him ``the perfect nerd.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah,'' Manning said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Golden boy?'' Deford asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't really know what that is,'' Manning said. ``I don't
know what a golden boy is. I'm certainly not perfect. I make
mistakes. People are looking at me and I have a chance to send a
good message to kids, and help kids make the right decisions in
life. So I choose to do that. I think as an athlete, people are
looking at you, so you might as well give them something good to
look at.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The old college try
</P>
<P>
   Billy Packer has some ideas about how the NCAA should spend some
of the $6.2 billion CBS agreed to pay for rights to the NCAA
basketball tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``The NCAA needs to understand that men's college basketball
accounts for more than 90 percent of its total revenue,'' said
Packer, a CBS analyst. ``Therefore, it needs to have special
attention given to it and should be run as a separate division
within the NCAA. The money should be used to clarify what is a
college player, which should be separate from what is a
professional player. There is a tremendous opportunity for
intercollegiate athletics to provide an avenue where sports fans
can have a real role model, people that represent what they'd like
their sons and daughters to be, instead of trying to emulate what
they have moved towards, which is to be another division of
professional sports.''
</P>
<P>
   Clark Kellogg also talked about the potential thet of the CBA to
lure the nation's top 100 high school players. ``The CBA is much
like some other things that have gone on in college basketball
(such as Proposition 48 and allowing athletes to work part time),''
said the analyst and former NBA player. ``In theory, these things
sound like they might be feasible, but in practice you get into all
kinds of crazy dynamics and logistics trying to make them work. How
much the CBA could benefit young kids bypassing college completely
or leaving college after a year or two is open to wide debate. I
don't know if it's a viable alternative.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Howard Manly covers the sports media for The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
