<SLUG> BC-BKC-NOTEBOOK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EARLY TESTS DON'T MAKE THE GRADE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times Ne rvice clients)  
 By MARK BLAUDSCHUN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   You're a college basketball coach. Say you're Tom Brennan at
Vermont. You eagerly await a new season because that is what you
do, other than host a radio show in Burlington, of course.
</P>
<P>
   You look at your team. Middle of the pack, with the chance to
win some games in the mid-major America East Conference.
</P>
<P>
   And then you look at the first four games of your schedule.
Connecticut. Yale. Boston College. Ohio State.
</P>
<P>
   Whoa. What's wrong with that picture?
</P>
<P>
   You're a college basketball coach. Say you're Tom Izzo at
Michigan State. You eagerly await a new season because that is what
you do. And you know you're good. Very good, even when your best
player, point guard Mateen Cleaves, is out with an injury for the
early part of the season. So good that you figure you can do better
than last season's Final Four appearance by winning the national
championship.
</P>
<P>
   You look at the early part of your schedule. A tournament in
Puerto Rico that will include a loss to Texas as well as games
against North Carolina, Kansas, Arizona, and Kentucky.
</P>
<P>
   Whoa. What's wrong with that picture?
</P>
<P>
   In the case of Vermont, everything. In the case of Michigan
State, nothing.
</P>
<P>
   December is the first real month of the college basketball
season, despite the nonsensical creeping up of the beginning of the
season closer to Hlloweeen than Thanksgiving.
</P>
<P>
   Those early games constitute the nonconference part of the
schedule, in which top teams either go out and play each other or
don't play each other, as the case may be.
</P>
<P>
   Georgetown, in the heyday of John Thomps,ever played annWhat
Vermont is doing is ridiculous.
</P>
<P>
   And it's not entirely by choice. Vermont needs the money that
can be gained by playing schools such as UConn and Ohio State on
the road. Also, Brennan and his America East coaching brethren are
following a dictum issued by the league office. The schools in
their nonconference schedules must have a minimum Ratings
Percentage Index, which is a key factor in the NCAA and NIT
tournament selection committees' deliberations.
</P>
<P>
   The feeling is that if the schools in America East play a
schedule with a fairly high RPI, they have a better chance of
getting at-large postseason bids.
</P>
<P>
   Nice idea, but totally misguided. America East is what it is, a
good mid-major conference with decent coaches and a fair quality of
basketball. The NCAA and the NIT won't give its teams a second
look, no matter what their RPIs say, no matter who they play.
</P>
<P>
   So the coaches are taking hits for what? All they are doing is
piling up losses, which could affect their job security in the long
run.
</P>
<P>
   The NCAA will fill out its tournament field from among
major-conference also-rans, and the NIT will pick its teams from
among schools with the biggest television markets, e biggest fan
support, and the biggest conferences.
</P>
<P>
   A team such as Boston Univrsity can win 20 games as an America
East runner-up and be virtually assured that it is done for the
season unless it wins the conference tournament. On the other hand,
a team such as Notre Dame or Georgetown can finish a game over .500
and in the second division of the Big East, and be virtually
assured it will get an NIT bid.
</P>
<P>
   Such is life.
</P>
<P>
   Now, for a team su as Michigan State, playing a
toughnonconference schedule makes sense. Nothing is at stake, other
than meaningless spots in the weekly polls.
</P>
<P>
   All Izzo's team has to do is prepare itself for March, when it
will be playing tournament games that count. For the Spartans,
playing a tough nonconference schedule does help, because it
toughens them up. It gives them more exposure for recruiting
purposes and allows Izzo to test his young players, knowing that
even if the team loses a game or two, it will be a no-harm, no-foul
situation, unless it suffers a total colllapse.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Chemical reaction
</P>
<P>
   BU and Northeastern have gotten off to slow starts, but there is
a difference between the directions the programs are taking. BU was
plagued by bad chemistry last season, a prime reason for the
Terriers' fall from first to eighth in the America East standings.
But Dennis Wolff has brought in some new faces who should freshen
the air, if not the attitude at BU . . . Boston College gave its
best shot at landing 7-foot-6-inch Neil Fingleton. No question
Fingleton would have been the foundation for future hoop success at
the Heights, but when North Carolina put on its full-court
recruiting press, sending up its Lear jet and wining and dining
Fingleton, with the DeanDome as a backdrop, BC had no chance . . .
Gonzaga, which has made a living (and nearly made it to the Final
Four last season) on 3-point shooting, ran into Temple the other
night at the Great Eight in Chicago, and the results were
predictable. The Zags shot 6 of 37 from 3-point land and lost to
the Owls, 64-38. Even with the win, Temple is still struggling
without senior point guard Pepe Sanchez, who habeen out for a
couple weeks with an ankle sprain. Without Sanchez, the Owls lost
to Indiana and Wake Forest and nearly lost to Florida State. ``I'm
praying hard for Sanchez to come back,'' said coach John Chaney.
``If he's not, we're going to struggle a lot.'' . . . Not many
players have had a rougher trip through college than Luke Recker.
He started at Indiana, decided he had had enough of Hoosiers coach
Bobby Knight, and transferred to Arizona. But last summer Recker
was involved in an automobile accident in which he suffered minor
injuries but his girlfriend, Kelly Craig, was left partially
paralyzed. This week Recker decided to transfer again, this time to
Iowa, so he could be closer to Craig, who remains hospitalized in
Chicago. ``I have been contemplating this ever since my arrival in
Tucson,'' said Recker. ``The decision is based soley on personal
reasons.'' Recker will have a new Indiana connection, since Iowa is
coached by former Hoosier star Steve Alford . . . Massachusetts's
win over Villanova Monday was a big boost for Minutemen coach
Bruiser Flint, who is under a lot of pressure to produce this year.
A combination of not winning as many games as in the past and a
suddenly soft fan base s not the best way to maintain job security
. . . With UConn coach Jim Calhoun getting a new contract that puts
him in the $2 million-a-year range, the bar on coaches' salaries
has been raised again. Now that there are no guarantees that the
top high school recruits will even make it to college _ opting
instead for the NBA _ and the best of players stay only a couple of
years in many instances, college basketball has become even more of
a game of coaches . . Kentucky's three-game losing streak last week
has the critics and wolves coming after Wildcats coach Tubby Smith
harder than ever . . . Unless things turn around quickly, the
legacy that Jim Harrick left at Rhode Island will be just what the
critics of the move to hire Harrick three years ago predicted: a
one-year run in the NCAA tournament with Al Skinner's players, and
then a program in turmoil, filled with moody, unpredictable players
who are difficult to control. From their early-season results, the
Rams may be in for a long season unless first-year coach Jerry
DiGregorio can settle things down.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
