<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-10 13:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5201 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-YAC-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      12-10 0941
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YAC-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIME FOR NYYC TO SINK OR SWIM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TONY CHAMBERLAIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   By Sunday, the Christmas Crunch will have shred its debris all
over the Aukland waterfront.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of this weekend, the top six boats inAerica's Cup
trials willtep up to the semifinals while five others will be, as
that old crooner Perry Como says, ``home for the holidays.''
</P>
<P>
   To say Young America of the New York Yacht Club is making the
Christmas Crunch interesting is understatement in the extreme. It
was just one month ago that Young America hull No. 53 fell off a
pair of steep waves, cracked like an eggsell, and sent 17 sailors
diving for their lives. It's the second time we have seen this
routine, and that we should never see it again would dictate some
new design and construction standards, though that is a column for
another day.
</P>
<P>
   Just over a month ago, the question was whether Young America _
New England's home team, if you will _ could outgun Italy's Prada
campaign and Paul Cayard's AmericaOne from San Francisco to top the
leader board going into the semifinals that begin Jan. 3.
</P>
<P>
   Now, amazingly, Young America fans are going through an
agonizing sort of death watch, as each race in this round has
brought this once lustrous campaign closer to elimination. Who
would have thought in October that Young America would be fighting
in December to make the top six? Home for Christmas might be a
reality _ no, not just for the Swiss and French but for the New
York Yacht Club.
</P>
<P>
   A look at the matchups ahead still seem to favor Young America's
chances to make it into the semis, and yet a subtle shift has taken
place. Rather than where Young America will end up in the top six,
the question is if it'll be there?
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel pretty good,'' said John Marshall, president of Young
America. ``We're still two races ahead in the loss column, and we
have half the races to salhis round. It's still in our hands to
make the semis. We don't need help from anyone.''
</P>
<P>
   Brave talk. And still, on paper there's no reason Young America
should not be talking big. They are still a well-heeled, two-boat
(hull No. 53 is ready to sail again), highly evolved racing
campaign with fast boats and good sailors. So why are they below
the top six line on the leader board? No. 8, in fact?
</P>
<P>
   In the November Round, when Young America was rocked on its
heels by the boat breaking, it was understandable that the team
could never quite get itself going again. In fact, it seemed a
remarkable recovery that they (and the boom from Hall spars)
managed to save hull No. 53 at all, then start right up with their
new boat, No. 58. No one would expect that to be a smooth
transition.
</P>
<P>
   It was also understandable that windy round when the weather got
rough that skipper Ed Baird decided to sail cautiously and eat a
couple of 4-point races rather than risk breaking the other boat
that, like all this generation of IACC 75-footers, creaks and
groans scarily in the 20-plus-knot range.
</P>
<P>
   But that was then. This is now. Time to claw for every 9-pointer
on the board. After all, these $4 million techno-yachts have few
enough useful days in their lives. If there were ever a time to
push the limits, there is _ in that most famous sports cliche _ no
tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   But for Young America, this round has not been about pushing the
limits in big winds. This has been strange from the very start, the
race in which it led Prada (then leader of the pack) into the
second downwind mark by 20 secnds, then, incredibly, failed to
cover.
</P>
<P>
   New Zealanng analyst Chris Law, once the second-ranked
match racer in the world, said:
</P>
<P>
   ``I watched with amazement as the two boats went off on opposite
tacks. In front of me the instruments read a slight right-hand
shift. And I could only assume Young America was holding onto this
lifting breeze in the hope that it might go back to the left so
they could bank a substantial gain.
</P>
<P>
   ``But this is speculative,'' said Law. ``This is leaving the
keys in your car while it's parked. This is leaving the back door
open. This is invitng someone to steal your well-earned gains. This
is overconfidence.''
</P>
<P>
   Baird admitted as much, explaining: ``In match racing, you can
either sail on the paranoid side or the overconfidence side. Today,
we chose overconfidence.''
</P>
<P>
   OK, that was one race. But the news for Young America got worse.
They stood still, going from seventh to eighth, while some real
onetime dark horses came on at a gallop.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco's Cayard holding the No. 1 spot with 90 points is
no surprise, but how about his cross-waterfront rival, Dawn Riley,
standing in second with 83 points (before today's races)?
</P>
<P>
   Prada in third with 82 points is understandable, but Japan
fourth with 75 points? Dennis Conner is never to be counted out of
any regatta, so it's no surprise that he, Ken Read, Tom Whidden, et
al, have Stars &AMP; Stripes in the thick of it, fifth with 55 points.
But Spain in sixth with 44oints?
</P>
<P>
   Behind these top six, Abracadabra from Hawaii is in seventh with
43 points, and Young America is eighth with 42 points.
</P>
<P>
   So the odds still favor NYYC getting into the top six, at least
on paper. But as Cayard was saying before Round Robin 3, the
9-point round is scary because on any given day, luck can pair you
with a boat you should beat, but a weather wrinkle can beat you out
of a 9-point race.
</P>
<P>
   Again, for Young America, this is survival weekend. Who would
ever have thought it would come before Christmas?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Tony Chamberlain covers the outdoors for The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
