<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A MATTER OF STYLE FOR ALL-DECADE TEAM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE AND CHARLES STEIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dan Miller doesn't hesitate when you ask him to put a finger on
the prevailing investment theme of the spectacular stock market of
the past decade.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being aggressive is what has worked in the '90s,'' said
Miller, manager of the $21.5 billion Putnam New Opportunities fund.
</P>
<P>
   He's half right from where we sit. The All-Decade Team of
hometown mutual fund managers who stood tallest during the 1990s
fall into two distinct styles: aggressive stockpickers who scored
the biggest gains and managers who gambled less with a mainstream
approach but may have produced the best risk-adjusted results of
all.
</P>
<P>
   Miller, John Ballen of MFS Emerging Growth and Fred Kobrick of
Kobrick Capital have all invested aggressively and made the most of
the decade's technology stock boom.
</P>
<P>
   A foursome of experienced managers at Fidelity Investments took
the mo instream approach: Steven Kaye, Will Danoff, Beth Terrana
and Robert Stansky.
</P>
<P>
   The lone exception was specialist Jim Schmidt of the John
Hancock Regional Bank fund, who capitalized on the nation's huge
banking industry consolidation of the 1990s like no other money
manager.
</P>
<P>
   Our conculsion: there has been more than one way to the top for
managers who excel at their particular style.
</P>
<P>
   All the managers on our team have generated returns of more than
500 percent between the start of the 1990s and Nov. 30 of this
year, according to data prepared for us by Lipper Inc. The Standard
&AMP; Poor's 500 index earned 410 percent during the same period.
</P>
<P>
   Miller's fund had by far the largest cumulative return, gaining
994 percent. Bill Dougherty of Boston mutual fund consulting firm
Kanon Bloch Carre argues Fidelity Growth &AMP; Income, a fund run by
two of our managers at different points in time, was actually the
best performer.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was the real winner based on unit of return for unit of
risk it took,'' said Dougherty.
</P>
<P>
   A few managers stayed at the helm of one fund through the entire
decade. We tracked others from one fund to another and,
occasionally, from one investment company to the next. We looked
for Boston investors who managed public money through the entire
decade but made a couple of exceptions: Will Danoff took over
Fidelity's Contrafund in June 1990 and Miller began running New
Opportunities in August of that year (a bit of fortuitous timing,
missing most of the drubbing small stocks suffered early in 1990).
</P>
<P>
   We don't attempt to ra the eight members ofour team for several
good reasons, besides the different investment objectives of their
funds. Return figures can be skewed slightly by different methods
of factoring expenses into results. Some managers, particularly
Stansky and his current Fidelity Magellan fund, are investing
vastly larger sums than others and can face market problems caused
specifically by their size.
</P>
<P>
   For all their differences, our team of managers repeat a couple
of leading investment themes that helped them make money in the
'90s. They point to innovation and enormous gains in efficiency
through technology and consolidation.
</P>
<P>
   The same themes often led them to different stocks. Ask Miller
what stocks worked best for him through the '90s and he will cite
EMC Corp., Clear Channel Communications Inc. and especially America
Online Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Kobrick also rode America Online and EMC, but also cites Cisco
Systems Inc. Ballen'sbest include Cisco, Microsoft Corp. and Oracle
Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Kaye used the same themes to buy different kinds of stocks,
including General Electric Co. and Fannie Mae ``I've made multiple
billions on General Electric for my shareholders,'' said Kaye.
``They have improved their margins every year under the Jack Welch
era.''
</P>
<P>
   They all have favorite stocks but most of our managers
emphasized that individiual stories and even sector investments
emerged and often changed through the years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Technology sounds pretty obvious today but I'm not sure it was
so obvious in 1990,'' said Miller. ``Microsoft looked alotlike
Lotus. EMC was a turnaround.''
</P>
<P>
   The lesson of the 1990s, said Ballen, is not to assume today's
answers will work very far into the future. ``You shouldn't decide
the environment you're in is the paradigm going forward,'' he said.
``Eyeballs are all the rage on the Internet today. But you can wake
up a year from now and that may not even be a factor in people's
investment decisions.''
</P>
<P>
   For all their big scores, many of our managers recall a '90s
mistake or two that sticks in their minds. Ballen bought the
management story at Mentor Graphics Corp. for too long, Kobrick
didn't see problems building at Sunglass Hut International Inc.
Miller should have unloaded some of his health care stocks, like
Total Renal Care Holdings Inc. Kaye wishes he bought more
technology.
</P>
<P>
   So what do the managers who performed best in the 1990s think
about the stock market of the decade ahead? They are cautious about
predicting a repeat of the '90s big years, but most said the solid
growth and low inflation of today's economy combined with other
advantages will make for a strong start.
</P>
<P>
   ``The new economy, (American) leadership in key growth areas and
an increasing amount of money coming into financial growth
instruments,'' said Kobrick. ``That's a decent backdrop, isn't
it?''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Steven Syre and Charles Stein can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
