<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FINANCE-HOOKER-$ADV12-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INVESTOR NEEDS TO TAKE RISK OUT OF HIS PLANNING 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, December 12, 1999)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KENNETH HOOKER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. I am 47 and my wife is 45. I've worked for the same company
for 27 years in various positions and now earn $80,000 a year, with
10 percent of this going into my 401(k) plan, which has a $130,000
balance invested in an index fund. My wife operates her own
preschool business and earns $15,000 a year, with $1,500 going ino
SEP-IRA invested in Alger Aggressive Growth fund, and with a $4,000
balance. We also save $1,000 a month in a taxable account invested
in Firstar Equity Index, with a current balance of $30,000. We were
risk averse with our investments for the first 25 years of our
marriage. Now that our daughters are in college -- one a senior and
the other a freshman on a full-tuition scholarship -- we are
looking at retirement. This year we moved our money from CDs into
mutual funds. In addition to the holdings above, we have $20,000 in
common stocks, $20,000 in Hartford Stock fund, Class B, $10,000 in
Putnam Voyager fund, $10,000 in Firstar Special Growth, $20,000 in
Firstar Growth and Retail, $20,000 in Firstar Growth and Income,
$5,000 in Firstar Bond Index, $15,000 of my employers common stock,
representing employer matches for my 401(k) plan, $120,000 in a
pension accumulation, and $10,000 in savings and CDs. We would like
to retire in four to six years. Our house is debt free and we have
no other debts. We anticipate needing $50,000 a year in living
expenses. Can we retire and replace earnings with this mix? I'm
contemplating moving everything to Vanguard, considering its Index
500, Growth Index, Mid-Cap and Small-Cap Indexes, and its
Lifestrategy Moderate Growth funds. What type of mix would you
suggest among these?
</P>
<P>
   D.H., Waunakee, Wis.
</P>
<P>
   A. Well, the short answer is probably yes, but the longer
approach is that you would be taking a lot of chances that you'd
encounter rough times in the later years of your retirement.
</P>
<P>
   If we take the mid-point of your four-to-six-year range and if
your total portfolio averaged 10 percent average investment
returned, your current balanceplus your contributions at the
current rate would take you to $804,029. If such a pool were then
invested in fixed-income securities to provide an income stream, it
would indeed supply the $50,000, but not the $59,384 which you
would need to buy what $50,000 buys today if inflation averages 3.5
percent annually. Worse, you would hav no money which would be left
in stock to build a capital pool to protect against the ravages of
inflation on your income stream in the later years of inflation.
Having such a pool is especially important to people who retire
early, and the earlier they retire, the more they need to think
about post-retirement inflation.
</P>
<P>
   The choices, I guess, are three: To step up the savings pace, to
delay your anticipated retirement date for a few years, or to
reduce your expectations of the income your savings pool should
produce.
</P>
<P>
   As to whether you should sell out of your current fund positions
and move to Vanguard, you should first calculate what the tax
implications of the move would be. Certainly it would make sense to
move your ongoing contributions to Vanguard, given that you are not
only paying a sales load of up to 4.5 percent on your investments
in the Firstar Equity Index fund, but it has an expense ratio of
.58 percent, compared to .18 percent for Vanguard Index 500. I'd
suggest a mix of 40 percent in the Index 500 fund and equal
positions in the other four funds.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I fear that I have too many mutual funds in my retirement
portfolio. I am a 38-year-old single female and a police detective.
I will retire with a pension representing two thirds of my lary of
$60,000. In addition, I add $8,000 a year to my deferred
compensaton plan, which has $22,277 in Janus fund, $15,177 in
Fidelity Contrafund, $15,885 in American Century Ultra fund, $2,608
in Dreyfus Mid Cap fund, $2,866 in Oppenheimer Global, and $3,948
in a money market account. I also have two Roth IRAs, with $17,287
in Fidelity Growth and Income and $8,176 in Scudder European Growth
fund. I add $100 a month to the latter account. I have a 403(b)
account from a previous employer with $6,921 in Scudder Global,
$22,083 in Scudder Large Value, and $3,935 in Scudder European
Growth funds. Finally, I have taxable accounts of $18,083 in
Scudder Young Investors and $14,726 in American Express New
Dimensions. I plan to retire in 2016. What will my retirement
income be? Most important, how should I consolidate and yet
diversify my portfolio? I tend to be toward the aggressive side.
</P>
<P>
   L.A., Portland, Ore.
</P>
<P>
   A. My best estimate is that you can retire comfortably with
about the same buying power as you have now, and with some extra
money put aside to protect you from the effects of inflation in
future years.
</P>
<P>
   If you achieve average 10 percent portfolio returns and maintain
your current saving schedule, you would have a pool of $950,791
after 16 years. If your retirement pension were $40,000 and if you
invested that pool in fixed income securities, you would have an
income stream of $101,801, which would have the buying power of
$56,322 in today's money.
</P>
<P>
   But let's approach it a different way -- assuming that you
realize salary increases that match that presumed rate of inflation
during the next 16 years. Thus, you would retire at a $4,039
salary, and be entitled to an annual pension of $68,655. Using the
same approach as before, between the pension and the yield from
your investments, you could bring in an income stream of $130,466,
equivalent to $72,696 in todays money. Rather than doing that,
though, you could leave about $185,000 of your money in stocks at
that point, with that pool designed to provide capital appreciation
to protect you against the inflation of later years of your
retirement.
</P>
<P>
   That latter figure may not seem terribly large, given that you
would be retiring at age 54. But if you increase your contributions
to the deferred compensation fund every time you get a raise,
maintaining the contribution at the current 13.3 percent, your
accumulation would be larger. Also, if you could add another $66 a
month to max out your Roth IRA contributions, that also would add
to the likely accumulation.
</P>
<P>
   As for your investments, the only thing I definitely suggest you
do is lose the money market account in your deferred compensation
plan. I would suggest that the balance there and any contributions
going there, be put into the Dreyfus Mid-Cap position. If you want
to consolidate for the sake of simplicity, you could calculate that
Janus, Fidelity Contrafund and American Century Twentieth Century
Ultra are all fishing in the same waters, so you could switch your
core position to any one of the three; on the other hand, I see no
good argument for doing that, and unless tracking three funds
bothers you, I would leave the investments as they are. You could
make much the same argument for consolidating the Stein Roe Young
Investors and American Express IDS New Dimensions hodngs.
</P>
<P>
   But there's an extra incentive not to do so, since both holdings
are taxable accounts, and whichever move you made would doubtless
generate in unpleasant tax bill. So with the exception of getting
rid of the money market account, I see no good reason to make any
change in this nicely balanced portfolio.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Send letters, including your name, address and telephone number,
to: Kenneth Hooker, The Boston Globe, Boston, Mass. 02107.)
</P>
</TEXT>
