 &HT;    This is a test. This is a test. This is a test  (EDS: Repeating
for all needing)    U.S. AND RUSSIA WORK TO PREVENT THE ULTIMATE
Y2K PROBLEM    (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ERIC ROSENBERG    c.1999 Hearst Newspapers   WASHINGTON _ A
<TEXT>
small group of U.S. and Russian military officers won't be doing
much New Year's Eve cork-popping as the millennium arrives at
midnight on Dec. 31. Instead, they will be guarding against the end
of the world. Their concern is the ultimate Y2K catastrophe:
Computer glitches causing the launch of nuclear-tipped ballistic
missiles. The U.S. and Russian governments have been working to fix
the potential Y2K glitches in their missile systems and early
warning defense equipment. And officials from both countries stress
that the likelihood of a mistaken Y2K missile launch is extremely
remote. But to reassure a jittery world public and further cut the
risk of a Y2K accident, the governments of the two nuclear
superpowers have set up a joint command center at Peterson Air
Force Base at Colorado Springs, Colo., to help protect against such
an accident. The year 2000 problem, commonly called Y2K, refers to
the possibsian military, are due to arrive at the Air Force
facility on Dec. 21 and begin training on the equipment Dec. 23.
The center is expected to be up and running no later than Dec. 30.
The center also has a certain public relations mission. ``The
bottom line is that it's important for the U.S and Russia to show
the rest of the world that former Cold War adversaries can come
together and work as a team,'' said Wicklund. The warm relations
only extend so far. Partly for security reasons, the Russians won't
be allowed inside Cheyenne Mountain, the heart of the U.S.
missile-warning network, buried 1,800 feet underneath the Front
Range of the Rocky Mountains. In an assessment last year of
Russia's potential Y2K problems, the Pentagon singled out for
particular concern the Russian early warning system designed to
detect incoming missiles. But even before Y2K worries took hold,
U.S. officials were worried about the capability of Russia's
missile defense system. In 1995, Russia initially interpreted the
launch of a Norwegian scientific rocket as the onset of an U.S.
nuclear attack. President Boris Yeltsin activated his ``nuclear
briefcase'' in the first stages of preparation to launch a
retaliatory strike before the Russian armed forces realizllion in
upgrades to deal with the problem. The U.S. military has 2,107
so-called ``mission critical'' systems _ those considered essential
for waging war _ deployed on weaponry and command posts. Defense
Secretary William Cohen vowed that all will be ``Y2K compliant'' by
the New Year. Lt. Col. Gary Warren, the Y2K program manager for the
Air Force's Space Command, which is responsible for maintaining
U.S. missile-detection radars and satellites, said the service has
worked three years on updating its computers. ``We've checked them,
we've rechecked them. They're ready,'' Warren said.  &UR; --- &QL;  &LR;  (Eric
Rosenberg can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail address
eric &LR; hearstdc.com).
</TEXT>
