<HEADER>
A5209 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MOVIE-TUMBLEWEEDS-BOS     12-10 0760
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-TUMBLEWEEDS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A MOTHER AND DAUGHTER'S COMPELLING JOURNEY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
TUMBLEWEEDS 
Directed by: Gavin O'Connor 
Screenplay by: O'Connor, Angela Shelton (based on Shelton's
memoir) 
Starring: Janet McTeer, Kimberly J. Brown, Jay O. Sanders, Gavin
O'Connor, Michael J. Pollard, Laurel Holloman, Lois Smith 
Running time: 100 minutes 
Rated: PG-13 (language, sensuality and a scene of domestic
discord) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Tumbleweeds,'' Gavin O'Connor's sweet, embraceable
mother-daughter movie, makes every moment count. It immediately
clarifies the reason for its title when Janet McTeer's earthy Mary
Jo Walker has what you feel isn't her first blowup with a husband.
``Pack yer bags, we're leavin','' she shouts to her 12-year-old
daughter, Ava, named after Mary Jo's fellow North Carolinian and
role model, Ava Gardner. Off they drive in a cloud of road dust.
They are leaving West Virginia, after having come from North
Carolina. They're headed to California, but only after a detour in
Missouri.
</P>
<P>
   There, Mary Jo discovers to her horror that the onetime suitor
on whom she had pinned her hopes has turned into a fat salesman of
used cars that blur the line between clunkers and junkers. As,
indeed, does he. This time, Mary Jo doesn't need to say a thing.
They don't even get out of the car. Mary Jo just floors it and
heads west. So, tumbleweeds. Until they hit the end of the road at
a quiet California coastal town, where Mary Jo hopes her daughter
doesn't notice the uncertainty in her eyes as she bravely announces
the new game plan. The twist is that Kimberly J. Brown's observant
Ava brings more clarity of vision to the situation than her mother
does.
</P>
<P>
   Whenever Mary Jo thinks she's failed, she has only to look at
Ava, and realize that she's done something right. Ava is the
well-adjusted one, rich in self-esteem, bolstered by her mother's
love and belief in her. Ava good-naturedly plays parent to her
warm-hearted but scattered mom who isn't terribly interested in
self-analysis, and just keeps repeating the same old coquettish
Southern belle routines that attract the same initially easygoing
but eventually sullen and controlling men. But even here, the film
reminds us that one of its strengths is that it knows the score
when it comes to human behavior. It allows for uncommon degrees of
texture and complexity.
</P>
<P>
   Director O'Connor doubles as an initially gentlemanly truck
driver into whose house they move in San Diego. He's not a bad guy,
or even an abusive one. He's just wrong for Mary Jo, who begins
feeling hemmed in by his insistence that she do things his
conservative way. When the stresses escalate, Mary Jo feels the
same old panic. The question is whether she'll revert to the same
old pattern. Or whether she's going to try to stay put and solve
her problems instead of fleeing from them, factoring into the mix
the fact that her daughter is growing older, becoming more her own
person, and reluctant to uproot the social life she's making for
herself.
</P>
<P>
   You'll care what happens in this film with more than enough
freshness and originality to avoid succumbing to girls-on-the-run
cliches. McTeer is delivering one of the year's richest
performances as a warm woman with little talent for planning and
decision-making, but a strong woman nonetheless whose love for her
equally strong but more self-confident daughter is boundless. If
British actress McTeer's performance as a dislocated Southern earth
mother weren't as appealing and compelling as it is, Brown would
steal the film utterly as the precocious Ava, who thrives in the
slight degree of stability she feels, quickly takes root and
breezes through school. It doesn't occur to her that she can't try
out for _ and get _ the role of Romeo in her school play.
</P>
<P>
   Time and again ``Tumbleweeds'' impresses with its freshly
considered action and total avoidance of the stale and routine,
even in lives that are largely unexamined. O'Connor brings
dimension to the role of the truck driver. Jay Sanders convincingly
occupies what for him is new filmic territory as a nice guy with
whom Mary Jo just might make a go of it. And as the boss of the
security company where they both work, Michael J. Pollard convinces
us he's not just caricaturing paranoiac weirdness, but living it.
Based on a memoir by O'Connor's onetime wife and current
scriptwriting colleague, Angela Shelton, the unassuming, homespun,
large-hearted ``Tumbleweeds'' is going to make a lot of friends.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
