<HEADER>
A5211 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-ENTERTAINMENT-NEWYEAR     12-10 1185
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ENTERTAINMENT-NEWYEARS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RINGING IN Y2K _ AND GETTING GOUGED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE MORSE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Stories of greed dominate the New Year's Eve pop scene, with
some stars asking up to $1,500 a ticket for shows that usually sell
for a fraction of that. The Eagles and Jimmy Buffett in separate
Los Angeles sites, Barbara Streisand in Las Vegas, and a package of
Andrea Bocelli, Sting, and Aretha Franklin in New York. All with
stratospheric ticketprices.
</P>
<P>
   Others are keeping prices low _ such as Vermont's Phish in an
unlikely date at the Cypress Seminole Indian Reservation
in &UR;  &LR; Florida; and Boston's Godsmack at the ``Smackfest.''
</P>
<P>
   But many other entertainers, like the general public, have mixed
feelings about going out at all this New Year's Eve.
</P>
<P>
   Garth Brooks is staying home and ``ordering a pizza.'' Yoko Ono
is staying home because ``it's the safest place to be . . . I just
said no to everything.'' Melissa Etheridge is spending the night at
her New Mexico ranch with friends and family. And Tori Amos expects
her husband to ``cook something delicious for me.''
</P>
<P>
   The FleetCenter in Boston will be dark, partly because of
skepticism that audiences would pay high ticket prices. There may
be a public skate that afternoon, but that's all, says FleetCenter
president Richard Krezwick, who expects to be home with a TV
controller in his hand when the clock strikes midnight.
</P>
<P>
   The FleetCenter had its chances for a concert, but nothing
worked out.
</P>
<P>
   Bocelli was offered a reported $2.5 million to headline, but
took $3 million instead to play the Jacob Javits Center in New York
with Sting and Franklin. And Puerto Rican pop star Ricky Martin was
offered $1.5 million to reprise ``Livin' la Vida Loca'' at the
Fleet, but reportedly insisted on $2 million, so no deal. At the
moment, Martin doesn't have any New Year's Eve gig, according to a
spokeswoman who says ``he'll stay home unless he finds something
worthwhile.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There wasn't the right act at the right time at the right
price,'' says Dave Marsden, vice president of the Don Law Company,
which tried to find an act for the FleetCenter. ``And when you look
at what's going on with First Night and look at the high guarantees
that artists want, those are difficult things to overcome. We also
believe that a lot of people will have private New Year's Eves and
aren't even going to go out.''
</P>
<P>
   Some Boston-identified acts are going elsewhere. Aerosmith will
play in Osaka, Japan, the J. Geils Band in Detroit, and James
Taylor in North Carolina. But most shows, no matter who is playing
where, are not selling out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we did right by the ticket-buying public to not have a
show,'' says Krezwick. ``A lot of promoters are losing tons of
money. . . . Hey, the Eagles aren't sold out. And neither is Barbra
Streisand in Las Vegas, Gloria Estefan in Miami, or even Billy Joel
at Madison Square Garden in New York. Many people are looking at
these New Year's shows as stiffs.''
</P>
<P>
   Pop entertainers often call New Year's Eve ``amateur night,''
but this one is ``the ultimate amateur night,'' says Buffett. He's
playing the Universal Amphitheatre in LA for up to $1,500 a ticket,
but promises ``the most bang for the millennium dollar,'' even
planning to give videos of the show to people who buy the
top-priced tickets. But he admits that the show is not sold out and
says one reason he's playing it is because his wife wanted to visit
friends in LA.
</P>
<P>
   ``I talk to a lot of people who have no clue as to what they're
going to do on New Year's Eve,'' says Buffett. ``I just decided to
go play. I was offered one gig in Guam, where I'd then be put on an
Air Force jet to go play in Hawaii. That way I'd be playing the
first and last place on American soil of the millennium. . . . But
then the Universal Amphitheater made me an offer that I couldn't
refuse.''
</P>
<P>
   Some musicians, however, view the high-priced New Year's Eve
shows with the same disdain as some fans do. Grateful Dead veteran
Bob Weir, who is playing San Francisco's Warfield Theater with his
band Ratdog for a modest ticket price, is pleased to see the more
expensive shows struggling. ``As well they should,'' he says.
``They're cases of impossibly ugly opportunism. It looks bad and
smells bad and I don't want to be a part of that.''
</P>
<P>
   The most high-powered, but not highest-priced, rock show that
night is a triple bill with Metallica, Kid Rock, and Ted Nugent at
the Silverdome in Pontiac, Mich. It's nearly sold out.
</P>
<P>
   Many acts are playing more low-key shows _ away from the glare
of arenas. Bonnie Raitt, Huey Lewis and the News, and Asleep at the
Wheel are booked to play in a tent in San Rafael, Calif., as a
benefit for that town. Shawn Colvin and Lyle Lovett are playing
outdoors in front of the state house in Austin, Texas, not far from
where Colvin lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be nice to be near home in case Y2K hits,'' Colvin
says, adding in jest, ``We'll just drive home in the SUV and drive
over the bodies.''
</P>
<P>
   Blondie, which reunited in the past year, is set to play on
South Beach in Miami. ``The millennium actually had something to do
with us getting back together,'' says Blondie drummer Clem Burke.
``We didn't want to let our music go by the wayside, so playing on
New Year's Eve means something to us.''
</P>
<P>
   Representing the opposite extreme is Chrissie Hynde and the
Pretenders. They're in San Francisco that night, but Hynde can't
tell you where. ``I don't know anything except that we're part of a
show with a bunch of artists and that we're going on at 12:15. But
I thought the band would rather be playing than getting drunk,''
she says.
</P>
<P>
   Some artists who feel that audiences might not go out that night
are instead being lured to MTV's New Year's Eve bash, which will be
broadcast from MTV's Manhattan studios. Playing two songs apiece
that night for the country's couch potatoes are Bush, Christina
Aquilera, and the Goo Goo Dolls.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're playing for sandwiches,'' jokes Bush singer Gavin
Rossdale.
</P>
<P>
   The Chieftains have an unlikely New Year's Eve lined up. Along
with Art Garfunkel and Diana Krall, they're playing on a cruise
ship headed to the South Pole. Talk about your Y2K paranoia.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're flying to Chile and then taking a cruise to
Antarctica,'' says Chieftains leader Paddy Moloney. ``The cruise is
being booked by a bunch of multimillionaires who wanted to get
away, but we're able to bring our families, so that should be
good.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet, despite so many performing options, many acts are still
sitting it out. ``I hope I don't have a gig. I hope I just get to
have a party or something,'' says singer Fiona Apple. ``I'm just
going to hang at a friend's house and have some hors d'oeuvres,''
adds Dean DeLeo of Stone Temple Pilots.
</P>
<P>
   As for Chris Robinson of the Black Crowes, he's headed to
Jamaica for three weeks to hide out from all the fuss.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll just play dominoes and catch up on reading some novels,''
he says. ``I don't need kids doing Jell-O shots. I need Thomas
Wolfe's `Look Homeward Angel.' ''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-10-99 1357EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991210.0097 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-10 13:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5212 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MUSIC-STEREOLAB-BOS &LR;      12-10 0810
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-STEREOLAB-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STEREOLAB MIXES IT UP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM SULLIVAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The title of Stereolab's latest CD doesn't exactly trip off the
tongue: ``Cobra And Phases Group Play Voltage In the Milky Night.''
Does the linkage of these words make any sense?
</P>
<P>
   ``It means whatever you want it to mean,'' says Stereolab
singer, lyricist, and synthesist Laetitia Sadier. ``You have to
make it mean something. (To me) it has got a very subtle meaning
inside, which I associate with the music but it's something that
can probably be destroyed by words.''
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to the cryptic but enchanting retro-futurist world of
Stereolab, a band formed by the French-born Sadier and English
guitarist-songwriter Tim Gane in 1991. Various players have passed
through the group, including the High Llamas' Sean O'Hagen. The
current lineup includes guitarist-singer Mary Hansen, keyboardist
Morgane Lhote, bassist Simon Johns, and drummer Andrew Ramsay. For
``Cobra . . .'' the London-based band relocated to Chicago, as it
did with its previous CD, ``Dots and Loops,'' and recorded with
Tortoise's John McEntire and producer Jim O'Rourke.
</P>
<P>
   Stereolab started out playing what might be called drone-rock _
layers of hypnotic guitars, synthesizers, and vocals climbing to
glorious plateaus. Minimalist but adventurous pop that was neatly
summed up by the title of an early song, ``John Cage Bubblegum.''
``It served a purpose at the time,'' explains Sadier, of that
sound, ``but it was sort of limiting.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, you'll hear in Stereolab an exotic lounge-and-beyond music,
airy pop, jagged time signatures, an ever-shifting mix of
mellifluous and dissonant sounds. Stereolab is both easy on the
ears and challenging _ a rare combination. If, however, you're
looking for linearity, you'd do well to look elsewhere. Same thing
if you're looking for lyrics that tell a story or have a clear,
emotional impact.
</P>
<P>
   You get the impression that the members of Stereolab, and their
guest musicians, are these mad musical alchemists, busying about
the studio searching in search of new sonic ingredients, every now
and then yelling ``Eureka!'' (Their moniker, of course, suggests as
much.) Sadier doesn't look at it quite that way, but admits there
is ``a mathematical playfulness'' to their sound. She adds, ``You
don't have to be completely out there to do something new; it is
about connecting ideas that have never been connected before.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still rooted in the same areas,'' she continues. ``We've
just developed. I don't feel it's a radical taking off in different
directions. The melodic pop _ you still hear some Brazilian
influences; some people think jazz is most accentuated on this
record.''
</P>
<P>
   Sadier is happy to answer questions about Stereolab's music, but
she often takes off from a discussion of music and ventures into a
politicized real-world context.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tim's music is about breaking ground,'' Sadier says, ``being
exploratory, taking a few risks in the sense that it is going to go
off the deep end and no one gets hurt. I think people are happy
with that. And my lyrics also, I think, are about exploring. Yes,
you may fall or make a mistake or you may come across an obstacle,
but when one has a brain we usually can overcome obstacles.
Humanity always has. We live in times that are very alarming, the
greenhouse effect, mad cow disease. I can confront it and engage in
the outside world, coming (to terms) with the private fear and
personal fear.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet, she adds, the attempt to be strong is undermined by
authorities who ``see us as children, as potential dangers to
society and therefore are not to be trusted.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, Stereolab has become noted for its pro-socialist
leanings and lyrics. But Sadier sings in French, English, and what
might be her own made-up language of sound. The band hardly
emphasizes polemics in song.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is best is something that is subtle and open-ended,''
Sadier suggests, of words and music, ``but at the same time not
completely abstract.''
</P>
<P>
   Where Sadier does get polemical is during interviews. She
believes America regards England as its toy poodle; she's angry at
attempts to censor the Internet; she's fearful of Big Brother
watching.
</P>
<P>
   So, after all of this, is Stereolab a rock band?
</P>
<P>
   ``I would say more of a pop band,'' says Sadier, adding that one
of the last terms she'd use to describe Stereolab is ``rock band.''
``Maybe, I have an issue with that,'' Sadier says, because of the
macho connotations of rock. ``I think sometimes we `rock' and it is
kind of nice to rock, but we kind of turn our back on that.'' As to
the equal mix of women and men, she says, ``It is very clear, to
everyone in the band at least, that this band would not sound like
this band if it was six guys playing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
