<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-GREEN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`GREEN MILE' GOES THE DISTANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
THE GREEN MILE 
Written and directed by: Frank Darabont (based on Stephen King's
novel) 
Starring: Tom Hanks, David Morse, Bonnie Hunt, Michael Clarke
Duncan, James Cromwell, Michael EJeter, Graham Greene, Doug
Hutchison, Sam Rockwell, Barry Pepper, Jeffrey DeMunn, Patricia
Clarkson, Harry Dean Stanton, Dabbs Greer, Gary Sinise 
Running time: 187 minutes 
Rated: R (violence, language and some sex-related material) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As a filmmaker, Frank Darabont may have staked out a pretty
specialized patch of turf _ Stephen King prison novels. But with
``The Shawshank Redemption'' and now ``The Green Mile,'' he's got
them covered. The title of the new film, from a novel King
serialized in six parts, refers to the linoleum floor of a
Louisiana prison's death row in 1935, when most of the story
unfolds. There's almost too much there, but the three-hour-plus
film permits the kind of detailing that not only brings the
storytelling to life, but sometimes persuades us we're breathing to
its rhythms. The performances _ especially the Oscar-nomination
caliber work of Tom Hanks as a death row guard and Michael Clarke
Duncan as a remarkable prisoner _ mesh handsomely. Only the fact
that the film contains several horrific electrocution scenes keeps
one from overstressing the point that for Darabont, lightning, at
least of the filmic variety, has struck twice.
</P>
<P>
   While the film could have benefited from tightening, it must be
said that Darabont knows how to fill the time with the kind of
absorbing detail that specifies a world and populates it vividly
with mostly decent prison guards keeping things as calm as possible
among mostly reasonable condemned men. The perhaps predictably
colorful prisoners are allowed human dignity with the exception of
Sam Rockwell's psychopathic loose cannon, who must be restrained at
regular intervals. His counterpart among the guards is Doug
Hutchison's newcomer. In a performance that gets under your skin
and stays there, he loses no opportunity for sadistic
power-tripping, convinced he can abuse prisoners with impunity
because he's related to the governor's wife.
</P>
<P>
   At this stage in movie history, Hanks is as much an icon of
American decency as Jimmy Stewart was. His top-ranking prison
guard, Paul Edgecomb, is determined to run the cell block in as
humane and civilized a fashion as possible. He tries to do the
right thing. Star though Hanks may be as regulator of a small
corner of the prison, the job of Hanks's character essentially is
to react to the figure who serves as the film's heart, Duncan's
muscular black giant. He's on death row to be electrocuted for the
murder of two little girls. But Hanks and the others find it hard
to reconcile his purity, gentleness, and spirituality with murder,
especially when events pose the question of whether he might
possess some unusual powers.
</P>
<P>
   The film is certain to attract criticism for putting at its
center a black man who is strong and so immense that his cell can
barely contain him, but also submissive and afraid of the dark.
Even though it's difficult to imagine a black prisoner behaving in
anything like a defiant manner in a Southern prison in 1935, the
man named John Coffey (obvious initials and all) will be perceived
as too infuriatingly childlike and even slavelike in his
unquestioning acceptance of white authority, even though it may be
tied to a massive injustice. But politically incorrect as he may
be, he's enormously moving all the same, and seems a shoo-in for a
controversial Oscar nomination. The racism that includes black
presence as a sort of cure-all for white ills is soft-pedaled, yet
still horrifying, just as the film's electrocutions are.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Green Mile'' doesn't shrink from portraying several
executions in grisly detail. Except for vengeful relatives of
murder victims and the sadistic guard, nobody enjoys them. The fact
that their savagery is so much a part of the film can leave no
doubt of the film's anti-capital-punishment sentiments long before
Hanks's guard denounces it as an old man we see at the film's
beginning and end. In the context of the film, racism seems merely
one facet of the psychopathic killing that plays no small part in
the story. Yet Hanks's guard isn't the only one trying his best to
make moral choices in a bad situation. His fellow prison guards
played by David Morse, Jeffrey DeMunn, and Barry Pepper, are
well-motivated, too. So is the prison's warden, nicely
dimensionalized and humanized by James Cromwell.
</P>
<P>
   Arriving at complexity and human dimension is the big job here.
Hanks and the others achieve it. So does gentle giant Duncan, who
does an astonishing job of slipping out from under a pall of
sentimental beatification to seem a benevolent force of nature with
a healing touch _ and then some. They and Darabont hang in there,
overcoming the story's tendency to move from character to
caricature as it aligns itself along opposing but too often
conveniently schematic poles of good and evil. You can't help
noticing certain parallels between ``The Green Mile'' and ``Of Mice
and Men,'' especially between Duncan's sensitive hulk and
Steinbeck's Lenny and between the two sawed-off power-tripping
sadists. Cast and director override the structural and conceptual
shortfall of ``The Green Mile,'' but you're never unaware that the
shortcomings are there, even as you feel yourself being hooked by
the film and you exit feeling that all the holiday releases should
_ but won't _ be as absorbing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
