<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-ROCK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GREGG ALLMAN KEEPS HIS FOCUS ON THE SIDE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE MORSE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Gregg Allman used to be addicted to drugs and alcohol. He left
those behind three years ago, but there's one addiction he can't
kick _ and that's having a side band to go along with his main
occupation as singer/keyboardist with the Allman Brothers.
</P>
<P>
   ``For almost my whole career I've had another band on the
side,'' he says. ``And you can cover all the bases you want to
cover. I just feel a certain freedom from that. We sort of do
things my way, you know? Let me put it a different way _ there's
only one leader.''
</P>
<P>
   While the Allman Brothers are known for their wide-open,
democratic jams, Allman runs a tighter ship as his own bandleader.
``I'm more into (song) arrangements than anybody else in the Allman
Brothers is,'' he says, noting that tighter arrangements will be in
evidence at his Orpheum Theatre engagement in Boston. He'll again
be backed by the Alameda All-Stars (with whom he toured two years
ago), as well as Floyd Miles and Danny Chauncey of 38 Special.
</P>
<P>
   It's common for keyboardists to like their arrangements more
defined _ and Allman is no exception.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, (keyboardists) wind up being a litle more concerned
about everybody's else's parts and how they fit together. I'm a
real stickler about what's being played behind a solo, for
instance,'' he adds.
</P>
<P>
   The repertoire will include tunes from his solo discs, as well
as some Allman Brothers songs _ ``but only the stuff I wrote,'' he
says. ``You'll hear some Brothers' tracks rewritten and redone,
like `Midnight Rider' and `Whipping Post' are two examples of that.
The way `Whipping Post' was on the last record, and the way
`Midnight Rider' was, is the way they were written.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that Allman isn't enjoying his enduring relationship with
the Allman Brothers, who tour every summer (with two annual dates
at the Tweeter Center in Mansfield). He particularly enjoyed the
way Derek Trucks _ the 20-year-old nephew of Allmans drummer Butch
Trucks _ joined the Allmans last summer and boosted the energy
level.
</P>
<P>
   ``He got us kind of straightened up,'' says Allman. ``You know,
certain people, as they get older, tend to get a little sloppy. In
the event that happens, then bring on some new lightning, dude.''
</P>
<P>
   That new lightning (Trucks) has also just been touring with Phil
Lesh and Friends _ a gig that Allman didn't even know about. ``Was
he just in town with Phil? Wow,'' he says. ``He's a glutton for
punishment, but I was, too, at his age. . . . He's really dedicated
to music . . . and who ever had chops that good at that age?''
</P>
<P>
   These days, Allman is a very contented man, after turning his
life around thanks to AA. Next year, he plans to marry the woman
he's been dating for five years. He's even moved back from
California to a waterfront pad in Georgia not long ago. ``I got a
big dock that goes out and there's moss hanging off these huge
300-year-old oaks in my yard. It's beautiful. I'm in the Deep South
now. I love it down there, man.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Amusia a band to watch: The Boston scene has spun out some
terrific records this year, not least of which is Amusia's recent
CD, ``Forever Ends.'' It revels in dreamy, hypnotic music sung by
Nashville emigre Ruth Peterson, who sounds like a soul sister to
Sarah McLachlan.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been a fan of hers since 1979,'' admits Peterson, who
works as a legal secretary when she's not working the clubs with
Amusia.
</P>
<P>
   The band's album showcases acoustic-driven rock-pop with
Peterson elegantly singing about the subtleties of relationships,
backed intoxicatingly by Todd Russell and David Sella on guitars,
Matthew Russell on drums, and Johnny Rosenfeld on bass. Peterson, a
'80s fan of the Smiths and Cocteau Twins, originally came to Boston
to attend Emerson College. Her dad teaches sociology and pop
culture at Vanderbilt University.
</P>
<P>
   Amusia started two years ago and is just coming into its own
now. And, oh yes, the name Amusia means the inability to produce or
comprehend music. ``If you're not a fan of irony, you're not a fan
of us,'' Peterson says with a laugh.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
