<DOCNO> NYT19991210.0102 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-10 14:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5221 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MOVIE-DEUCE-BOS &LR;      12-10 0568
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-DEUCE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`DEUCE BIGELOW' A NOT-SO-BAD SANDLER CLONE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOAN ANDERMAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
DEUCE BIGELOW: MALE GIGOLO 
Directed by: Mike Mitchell 
Screenplay by: Harris Goldberg and Rob Schneider 
Starring: Rob Schneider, Oded Fehr, William Forsythe, Arija
Bareikis, Eddie Griffin 
Running Time: 85 minutes 
Rated R (language, crude humor, strong sexual innuendo) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Admit it: just saying the name of this movie makes you feel
stupid. I suspect that's the desired effect. This movie is stupid _
the sort of aggressively brainless cinema that honors the inherent
humor in flatulence, falling down the bus steps, and
rhinestone-studded men's briefs. Adam Sandler executive-produced;
need more be said?
</P>
<P>
   But ``Deuce Bigelow...'' is something more, too. There's a
sweetness to both the characters and the plot that fleshes out the
film's stock antics. SNL alum Rob Schneider plays the title
character, a hapless, horny fish-tank cleaner who dreams of moving
to the beach and living near his finned ``friends.''
</P>
<P>
   After losing his job at the Los Angeles Aquarium for cleaning a
public tank naked (exactly why Deuce elects to squeegee in his
birthday suit is inexplicable, as are most of the plot
developments), Deuce finds work cleaning a koi pond at a luxury
Malibu apartment complex. One of the residents is world-class
gigolo Antoine Laconte (the dashing Oded Fehr), who is also the
proud owner of a state-of-the art aquarium. When Antoine's Chinese
tailbar lionfish comes down with a potentially fatal gill disorder
on the eve of Antoine's European ``business'' trip, Deuce is
persuaded to fish-sit.
</P>
<P>
   And we're off. A grilled-cheese incident sets off a chain of
events that virtually destroys Antoine's apartment, aquarium
included. To raise funds for the repairs Deuce is forced to launch
a 3-week career as replacement gigolo _ or man-whore, as newly
acquired pimp-with-a-heart-of gold T.J. (Eddie Griffin) calls him.
First-time feature film director Mike Mitchell's previous
experience on the animated series ``Ren and Stimpy'' serves the
film well. He sprints, sketch-like, through scenes that a leisurely
pace would have rendered painful: Deuce services (not, however, in
the way you might expect) clients who include a giantess, women
with narcolepsy and Tourette syndrome, and _ in an unbilled cameo _
Marlo Thomas as a fetishist who dresses Deuce as a German tourist.
</P>
<P>
   Sounds pretty tasteless and exploitive. And yes, they want you
to laugh when the woman with narcolepsy falls asleep mid-throw at
the bowling alley. On top of that, there's a heap of gross-out
humor that seems geared toward adolescent males who theoretically
aren't this R-rated movie's target audience, plus a romance that's
nearly derailed, predictably, by Deuce's temp job.
</P>
<P>
   But Schneider's mild-mannered fish-lover is genuinely likable,
and a good-natured foil to the crude jokes. Deuce massages the
giant woman's aching feet, and takes the girl with Tourette's to a
baseball game, where her profane outbursts fit right in. And, of
course, Deuce makes everything come out right in the end. It's not
a new story: dim, fumbling nebbish winds up as the moral center in
an unfair, mean-spirited universe. Neither is the
nice-guy-who-sugarcoats-the-bathroom-humor device. One need only
refer back to the latest Adam Sandler movie.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
