<HEADLINE>
HOW BIG SHOULD ATTIC VENTS BE? 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, December 12, 1999)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER HOTTON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. What's the formula for the size of vents in an attic to
assure adequate ventilation?
</P>
<P>
   CHARLES CARTER, Bedford, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. The vent formula for an attic is: One square foot of free air
space (no screens or louvers) for every 300 square feet of attic
floor area. If you put in vents, add 20 percent to the size to
compensate for the screens and louvers.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. My 100-year-old house has storm windows that seem as old as
the house. They are triple track, and many are missing screens. I
was thinking of replacing the windows (and getting rid of the
storms). A company suggested vinyl, but my father said to use
vinyl-clad wood windows or wood windows that are clad on the
outside. What kind should I get?
</P>
<P>
   M.R., Medway, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. I'm with Dad. If you replace the main windows, get only the
movable sash, not the entire window, which will be a lot more
expensive, and use the vinyl-clad or clad on the outside.
</P>
<P>
   And, you might not even have to do that, if the windows are in
good shape, fairly tight and well-weatherstripped. Keep them,
weatherstrip them if necessary to make them tighter, and put in new
storms. You can buy a high-quality, airtight storm for about $100
installed. One such storm is True Channel, made by Harvey
Industries and generally contractor installed. With those tight
windows, plus the storms, you will have virtually the same thing
you would get if you installed the new sash.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. My 15-year-old Gibson washing machine makes a terrible racket
on the spin cycle. It sounds as if a couple of lead balls are in
there, clattering away. I thought it might be an unbalanced load.
Is it worth checking?
</P>
<P>
   F.Q., Cambridge, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. It is worth checking with an appliance repair shop. These
shops are all over, and I have found them very helpful with all my
problems. But don't expect too much because the handyman's list of
the expected life spans of appliances shows that a washing machine
has a life expectancy of 11 years. That means that your machine is
way over its life limit. But go ahead with the appliance repairman.
If the fix is over $100, it is time to buy a new washing machine.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. My bathroom floor is covered by sheet vinyl. I'd like to put
in ceramic tile. Is it OK to put mortar over the vinyl?
</P>
<P>
   JOHN SEYMOUR, Hopkinton, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Yes, you can mortar over the vinyl; but you have to put down
steel mesh first; this will act as a reinforcement for the mortar,
which should be fairly thick ( 1/2 to 1 inch). After this bed sets,
tiles are set with thin-set mortar. This is a true mud job, which
is the best way to handle ceramic tile.
</P>
<P>
   As for setting tile directly on the vinyl with thin-set mortar,
I don't think it is a good idea because the thin-set might not
stick to the vinyl very well.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When Etha Indeck of Beverly, Mass. had trouble with rust that
would not come off her Spring Ram plastic sink, the handyman
suggested several ways to try to remove the rust, and suggested
that the sink might be at fault, and that the company might be out
of business since she could not locate the manufacturer.
</P>
<P>
   Here's how Elizabeth A. Genisol of Charlotte, N.C. responded by
e-mail: ``Shame on you for trashing a good product which you
obviously know nothing about! I am writing this letter as an
enraged reader because I Love my Spring Ram sink and think that you
owe Spring Ram an apology. . . .
</P>
<P>
   ``I have had a Spring Ram sink for seven years and it looks as
good as it did the day I got it, so I don't know what your reader's
problem is other than the way they take care of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your reader may have a special problem with rust. I don't know
how they got the rust there unless they didn't use the recommended
drain parts &AMP; covers, or they're leaving rusting cans and/or pots
in the sink overnight. Hardly any product/material can be resistant
to rust without staining, so I think you're harsh in assuming it's
the product's fault.
</P>
<P>
   ``The company can be reached at www.springram.co.uk and I found
their American distributor to be at www.astracastusa.com. I'm sure
they can be more helpful in solving the problem than you were.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope that this has educated you on a product that I will
certainly buy again and look for in my next home. I have no
connection with the company, I'm just a loyal fan who usually
thinks you have good advice and a good column which I read weekly.
This time you were just way off base! Thanks for listening.''
</P>
<P>
   Whew! Thanks for telling me. I stand corrected, and will put
your information in my file for future use.
</P>
<P>
   Thinking further, I wonder if the rust occurred on metal pipes
coming through the sink and the drain cover, due to faulty
materials and/or installation. At any rate, Etha Indeck, the owner
of the sink in question, can contact the manufacturer or
distributor through its Internet address you so thoughtfully
provided.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Globe Handyman on Call Peter Hotton will answer reader questions.
Write him at the Boston Globe, Boston, Mass., 02107.)
</P>
</TEXT>
