u k BC-JACKSON-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      12-10 0895
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JACKSON-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHY, SWEET, AND NEARLY DEADLY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DERRICK Z. JACKSON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Seth Trickey fit no popular profile for destruction. He had been
a straight-A student in Fort Gibson, Okla. He was in a Christian
youth group. Schoolmates said of Trickey:
</P>
<P>
   ``He's just a normal kid. He's smart, always on the honor roll,
very polite. I've known him sice preschool.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He's kind of cool, never acting weird or being a threat to
anyone. He is a nice guy. He loves the outdoors and playing soccer
and basketball. He loves Michael Jordan.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Seth is my friend. He's got lots of friends 'cause he's cool,
funny, friendly, and smar   One friend called Trickey ``the perfect student.''
</P>
<P>
   On Monday morning, the perfect 13-year-old student went to his
middle school with a backpack loaded with a 9mm handgun and scores
of bullets. Almost immediately upon reaching the grounds, he
randomly fired away, emptying a 15-round clip. He wounded four
people. Since Trickey fit no profile, everyone was shocked.
</P>
<P>
   ``He doesn't even know who it was he shot,'' said Muskogee
County Sheriff's Deputy Terry Cragg. ``This was not a hate thing. I
asked him why. He said, `I don't know.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, no one was killed. Unfortunately, the fact that no
one was killed means that the school shooting in Fort Gibson can
easily be put aie s a reason to roil the nation's conscience. By
the numbers, Trickey's act was less tragic than the April massacre
at Columbine High School or the rampage last year at Thurston High
School in Springfield, Ore.
</P>
<P>
   But the shooting by this child should be of particular note.
Trickey did not seem haunted by the Hitleresque demons that drove
the killers at Columbine or ``voices'' that Kip Kinkel claimed told
him to fire awy in Springfield. Trickey did not seem to be enraged
by lost love or by a teacher he hated.
</P>
<P>
   He had no criminal history of violence, although in the
aftermath some students now realize that Trickey had a temper. When
he lost at arcade paint ball, Trickey apparently splattered the
winners in the back with paint. One student recalls that his sister
told him that Trickey ``joked around in class about shooting
people. He acted like he had a gun, but no one took him
seriously.''
</P>
<P>
   Even now, few in power take Trickey seriously. President Clinton
_ not thinking for a moment how it was only through dumb luck that
no one was killed _ made just a brief mention of the shooting,
saying, ``There are no fatalities, only people who are wounded.''
</P>
<P>
   Governor Frank Keating of Oklahoma, a robot for the National
Rifle Association, said: ``Obviously, the debate will always turn
to guns. But guns are not the issue.'' He also said: ``This could
have been committed . . . with a rock, with a knife. If a child is
hellbent on an act of evil, that child will do it.''
</P>
<P>
   This is rock-headed, since it is nearly impossible for a student
to duplicate the mass carnage of our school shootings with a bag of
rocks or a knife. Such politicians ignore the facthat Trickey
actually does fit the profile of a school shooter more than one
would think.
</P>
<P>
   In a study of 15 school shootings since 1993, James McGee,
director of psychology and forensic services at Baltimore's
Sheppard Pratt Hospital, found the assailants to be ``usually good
students, maybe on the honor roll, and are not well-known to school
officials. They're able to blend in with the woodwork until they
actually go ballistic.''
</P>
<P>
   McGee, who wrote the study with Caren DeBernardo, said school
shooters are usually white, male, 11 to 17 years old, come from a
blue-collar or middle-class background, and are from families that
seem normal but are ``subtly dysfunctional.''
</P>
<P>
   McGee said guns are part of the family culture of school
shooters, and the weapons used in the shootings are usually
family-owned. The gun Trickey allegedly used was purchased by his
father at Wal-Mart in 1993, the year before the laggard chain
joined other mass merchandisers in halting such sales.
</P>
<P>
   The family of Seth Trickey and, to some degree, Trickey himself
are so far receiving the benefit of the doubt in Fort Gibson, even
though Trickey's parents have refused to let police grill their son
in depth. ``Those are good kids,'' said neighbor Karen Hobbs. ``I
can't imagine what was going through his mind, but I just know it
wasn't to murder someone. He's just a baby.''
</P>
<P>
   America will go nowhere on youth violence if we can't imagine
our ``good kids'' doing wrong. Seth Trickey reminds us that
violence is not due solely to guns or values, nor is it isolated in
black ghettos or among white suburban ``goths.'' He reminds us that
a culture that glorifies violence and continues to make ns so
readily available can tempt any child with the least bit of temper
to make a tragic choice.
</P>
<P>
   In talking about Seth Trickey's neighborhood, the Tulsa World
wrote: ``Seth Trickey lived in one of the newer, bigger houses, in
a little valley where deer graze at dawn and the setting sun
silhouettes the water ower. Oklahoma has thousands of Seth
Trickeys. Shy. Friendly. Sweet.'' We should always try to view our
children as sweet babies. We also must remember how easy we have
made it for them to turn into sour adolescents.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Derrick Z. Jackson is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
