<SLUG> BC-BEAM-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`A CIVIL ACTION'; TAKE TWO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX BEAM  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jan Schlichtmann, the lawyer who litigated the Woburn, Mass.
toxic wells trial depicted in the best-selling book ``A Civil
Action,'' is back in court _ this time as a defendant.
</P>
<P>
   Schlichtmann has spent the past few days in front of a jury
arguing Cadle Co. v. Schlichtmann, a complex suit arising from his
old law firm's declaration of bankruptcy after the eight-year-long
Woburn case. Cadle, an Ohio-based company that buys up bad debt,
says Schlichtmann owes it a portion of his post-Woburn earnings. He
disagrees. The case has dragged on for several years, and motions
for summary judgment from both sides have been turned down.
</P>
<P>
   They say Schlichtmann has mellowed, but I didn't get that
impression when I bumped into him in the corridor of the new
federal courthouse. (Architectural note: Henry Cobb's buildings
sure look nice from the inside . . .) He has retained the energy,
the charm, and the penchant for rhetorical excess aptly imitated by
John Travolta in the ``Civil Action'' movie. ``These people are
trying to destroy me,'' he said. ``They're notorious for pursuing
these cases all over the country.'' Later, he congratulated himself
on his own ``brilliant'' cross-examination of a Cadle executive.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the post-Wobur emns still seem to haunt him. When I
registered surprise that he was back in front of a jury, he shot
back: ``Do you think I'd put my fate in the hands of a federal
judge?'' Ghost from the Past 1: The trial judge, George O'Toole, is
a former colleague of Jerome Facher, the Hale and Dorr lawyer who
represented W.R. Grace in the Woburn trial. Ghost from the Past 2:
Retired Judge Walter J. Skinner, who bedeviled Schlichtmann during
the Woburn trial, was conducting a mediation just two floors above
where we were standing.
</P>
<P>
   Thus informed, Schlichtmann just rolled his eyeballs. ``New
building, same old story,'' he sighed.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Gift idea
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   What is the worst movie ever made? I always thought it was a
tossup between John Sayles's ``Piranha'' and the insufferably
precious ``Vanya on 42nd Street.'' But a new candidate has emerged:
``Dinosaur Valley Girls,'' a 1997 release from B-movie genius
``Dinosaur'' Don Glut, who has nurtured such memorable celluloid
outings as ``Bikini Drive-in'' and 1971's ``Schlock.''
</P>
<P>
   Glut is a hard man to pigeonhole. He is the co-author of a
well-regarded dinosaur encyclopedia, a dinosaur dictionary, and
``novelizations'' of the Star Wars movies. ``Valley Girls,''
occasionally featured on USA Network's ``Up All Night'' show,
remains his magnum opus. He tells me he is now raising money for
two movie projects, ``Dinosaur Valley Girls II'' and a vampire
movie called ``Blood Justice.''
</P>
<P>
   How bad is ``DVG''? So bad that it circles the categoryand
almost reemerges as wonderful. The plot, such as it is, contrives
for Hollywood action sr Tony Markham to be transported back in time
to Dinosaur Valley, where scantily clad starlets wander around
chucking spears and mumbling ``for sure.'' Think: ``Quest for
Fire'' meets ``The Vixen,'' minus Anthony Burgess, who penned the
caveman grunts for ``Quest.''
</P>
<P>
   B-stars abound: William Marshall of ``Blacula'' fame, has a
small role, as does onetime Oscar nominee Karen Black. Glut filmed
the lush outdoor scenes near Devil's Punch Bowl in Pearblossom,
Calif., and at Bronson Canyon in Los Angeles. Does the cave mouth
where Bam-Bee and Bar-Bee disport themselves look familiar? It
should; it was used in John Ford's ``The Searchers,'' ``Mighty
Morphin' Power Rangers,'' the Batman TV series, and countless
movies and shows in between.
</P>
<P>
   ``DVG'' is available from frontlinefilms.com. I recommend the
Family Edition, not the mildly spicy ``Director's Cut.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The arguably watch
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sightings of ``arguably'' in its current usage, as a synonym for
``not'': The New Yorker calls Al Gore ``arguably the most active
and influential Vice-President in history.'' The New Times of
Phoenix writes of John McCain: ``His connections to the banker
arguably ran deeper than those of any other member of the Keating
Five.'' And a Globe colleague recently wrote: ``The Public Garden
is arguably the most beautiful, most open park in the nation.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Alex Beam's e-dress is beam(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
