<P>
   NY-TRANSIT-STRIKE (New York) _ With the prospect of a transit
strike looming, New Yorkers are faced with trying to prepare for a
holiday season without public transportation. (THIS STORY MAY BE
HELD IF IT DOES NOT MAKE PAGE ONE.)
</P>
<P>
   IND-MORALCODE-DISPUTE (Scottsburg, Ind.) _ Given its druthers,
the school board here would post the Ten Commandments in
classrooms. But since that would violate the First Amendment, the
board decided to carve its own tablet of moral behavior: the 11
Common Precepts. If the strategy was intended to appease civil
libertarians, it has not worked. By Dirk Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   TENN-FOSTER-FEAR (Memphis, Tenn.) _ A journal about the child
who spent a month living with his mother's corpse out of fear that
if he told anyone, he'd be placed in foster care. By Emily Yellin.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POLITICS &LR;  (Moving in ``p'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   MCCAIN-CAMPAIGN (Washington) _ John McCain seems to be running
with great glee against all the conventions of modern politics. He
is not polling, he has no stump speech, he's practically stalking
journalists instead of fleeing from them. Audiences in New
Hampshire are lapping it up. He has surged into the lead there,
according to polls. The question is: will this style of personal
politicking work beyond New Hampshire? By Alison Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   FORBES-IOWA (Des Moines, Iowa) _ A at look Steve Forbes'
campaign strategy and apparatus in Iowa. By Leslie Wayne.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (Moving in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON (Little Rock, Ark.) _ Developments: President Clinton
said Friday that he hopes his planned presidential library will be
a place of healing as well as an economic power for his home state.
By Robert Pear.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COLUMNS &LR;  (Moving in ``k'' news file.)
