   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT &LR;  (Moving in ``e'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   TECH-RISK-RESEARCHER _ Charles Perrow plans to rise early on
Dec. 31 to see what happens as the calendar turns over to the year
2000, first in New Zealand and then, hour by hour, across the
globe. It will be an unusual activity for the Yale sociologist, who
says he rarely watches television. But Perrow sees the planet on
New Year's Day as a giant laboratory for the influential theory he
came up with in the early 1980s about the nature of catastrophic
accidents. By Laurence Zuckerman.
</P>
<P>
   RAILROAD-FEVER _ The building of railroads has begun to get some
unusual attention, including a massive new 797-page chronicle
devoted to the construction of America's transcontinental railroad.
Railroads have always attracted hobbyists and specialists, but the
attention has recently broadened, echoing the energies now being
poured into proliferating books about the Internet. By Edward
Rothstein.
</P>
<P>
   RUBENSTEIN-RECORDINGS _ A caress can sometimes accompany the
chill of death. Or at least so it seemed when I first heard Arthur
Rubinstein play. It was some 30 years ago; the pianist was in his
80s and said to be frail. That experience has been coming to mind
again as I have been immersing myself in ``The Rubinstein
Collection,'' the pianist's complete recorded legacy, just released
by BMG classics in a sumptuously produced set of 94 compact disks.
By Edward Rothstein.
</P>
<P>
   OBOE-DREAM-PERFORMANCE (New York) _ A young oboist, battling
Hodgkin's disease, will play with the New York Philharmonic on
Friday night. By Ralph Blumenthal.
</P>
<P>
   SISTINE-FRESCOES (Rome) _ The Vatican unveils the Sistine
Chapel's final refurbished frescoes. By Alessandra Stanley.
