<HEADER>
A5263 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s BC-SKI-EXERCISES-HNS &LR;      12-10 0480
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SKI-EXERCISES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SIMPLE EXERCISES MAKE THE SKI SEASON MORE RELAXING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By BUZZ GRAY  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Only a fool believes he or she can ski themselves
into shape. It doesn't happen in the real world without creating
sore muscles, pulled ones or even worse.
</P>
<P>
   So take the advice of such experts as Harold Habra, coach and
trainer of the U.S. National Demonstration Team, author of ``Anyone
Can Be An Expert Skier'' and columnist on the popular web site
www.OnTheSnow.com.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rarely does anyone I know ski longer than a minute or two
before stopping,'' Habra said. ``Judging from that, ski muscles
need to be conditioned for many repetitions in short bursts.''
</P>
<P>
   One of Hare's basic exercises for would-be skiers who already
are in relatively good shape is the one-legged squat.
</P>
<P>
   The exercise, which should be started at least two weeks before
you hit the slopes, builds quad strength (muscles on the front of
the upper leg) and endurance. It also increases balance and can be
done anywhere without equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Here's what to do: Stand sideways to the back of a chair. Hold
the top of the chair with your right hand for balance. Pick your
right leg off the floor and try to hold it out straight.
</P>
<P>
   Flex your left leg until you lower your rear end to
approximately two inches above a sitting position.
</P>
<P>
   Repeat this movement as many times as possible and record the
number. Turn around and exercise the other leg. Ten repetitions is
a starting number.
</P>
<P>
   The degree of flex (how far you bend the leg for each rep)
should depend on your level of present fitness. If you rarely
exercise, it is recommended you bend to only half the amount of
flex it takes to come to a full seated position. This range of flex
is minimal and will allow you to do more reps. The deeper you flex,
the fewer repetitions you'll be able to perform.
</P>
<P>
   If you are at the beginning phases of physical conditioning, use
the chair for support. As you become comfortable with the exercise,
try to be less dependent on the chair. Use only a finger to touch
the chair lightly.
</P>
<P>
   ``A sore butt, not from falling but from pulling yourself over
your skis and maintaining your balance, is one of the consequences
for not being in shape,'' Habra said.
</P>
<P>
   A way to avoid such discomfort is to try split squats. Step
forward with one leg. Move and stretch the back leg behind your
body until your legs are split. Now you are in the starting
position.
</P>
<P>
   From here, lower the back knee until it touches the floor by
flexing the front leg. In your lowest position, the front shin
should be at a 90-degree angle to the floor.
</P>
<P>
   Repeat this movement 10 or more times.
</P>
<P>
   You may want to use a chair for support. As balance and strength
increase, you can hold hand weights for added resistance.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-10-99 1430EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
