<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK RACING ASSOCIATION BOOSTS PRIZE MONEY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MATT GRAVES  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SARATOGA SPRINGS, N.Y. _ The New York Racing Association is
delivering some early Christmas presents to horsemen, unveiling its
richest stakes program in history.
</P>
<P>
   Saratoga Race Course will be the site of some of the largest
increases as the historic Whitney will be bumped up to $750,000
this summer from last year's mark of $600,000.
</P>
<P>
   In all, the record stakes purse total for Saratoga's 35
added-money events will be $8,725,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Whitney has always been one of Saratoga's greatest
attractions, and it seems to get better each year,'' NYRA racing
secretary Mike Lakow said Wednesday. ``Victory Gallop's nose win
over Behrens in 1999 is regarded by many as the race of the year.
The year before Awesome Again won the Whitney en route to winning
the Breeders' Cup Classic.''
</P>
<P>
   The trend for larger purses has increased steeply for the past
two years.
</P>
<P>
   For the first meet of the new millennium, eleven of the Spa
stakes have been boosted by a total of $1,125,000, including the
Alabama ($750,000 up from $400,000), the Diana Handicap ($500,000
up from $300,000), the Sword Dancer ($500,000 up from $400,000) and
the Jim Dandy ($400,000 up from $300,000).
</P>
<P>
   ``The Alabama has long been one of the most important races in
the country,'' Lakow said. ``With a $350,000 boost in its purse, it
will take its place as the richest race for 3-year-old fillies in
the country.''
</P>
<P>
   Saratoga's showpiece event ... the Travers ... will remain one
of NYRA's three $1 million stakes along with the Belmont Stakes and
the Jockey Club Gold Cup.
</P>
<P>
   In all, NYRA will feature 180 stakes worth $34.1 million at its
three tracks (Belmont, Aqueduct) for the year 2000. Thirty-six of
those stakes are Grade I events, including a dozen at Saratoga in
its meeting from Wednesday, July 24, through Monday, Sept. 4 (Labor
Day).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-10-99 1433EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
