<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-10 14:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5266 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-BELL-RINGERS-HNS &LR;      12-10 0680
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BELL-RINGERS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHORTAGE OF BELL RINGERS HURTS SOME SALVATION ARMY CHAPTERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By THEOLA S. LABBE  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ The jingle of Salvation Army bells has become a
ubiquitous reminder of the holiday season, but a shortage of
volunteers at Salvation Army corps this year has left outposts
silent and has raised concerns about meeting fund-raising goals.
</P>
<P>
   In suburban Cohoes, where a dearth of downtown businesses has
curbed foot traffic from shoppers, Salvation Army administrator
Glenda Larcombe has had to redeploy her four workers. While
normally they might be found on downtown street corners, she has
sent her troops this season to malls in other communities and still
fears she may miss her $28,000 fund-raising goal.
</P>
<P>
   On the surface, the Salvation Army of Schenectady seems to be
doing better, with 10 volunteers for 10 stations.
</P>
<P>
   But the average during bell-ringing season is 20 workers, said
Maj. Clyde Jones, supplying a cadre of replacement workers to fill
in as needed. Since Nov. 18, when volunteers in Schenectady donned
their blue ``I am a Bell Ringer'' vests and stood next to the red
kettles, shaking hand bells, absent volunteers have left some spots
uncovered.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've gone out to help out,'' Jones said.
</P>
<P>
   With volunteers coming forward in droves to help other agencies
or to serve meals at holiday events, the Salvation Army has been
struggling here and in other regions of the country. The problem is
more acute during the week than on weekends, officials say. But
beyond that, they cannot say what is driving the shortage.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't even pay people to help me,'' said Capt. Luva Blakely
of the Albany Temple corps. She is responsible for 10 stands in
Albany County, including the world's largest kettle at Crossgates
Mall.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was hoping to make at least $60,000,'' she said of the
agency's goal, ``but that's become a joke.''
</P>
<P>
   The annual bell-ringing campaign from Thanksgiving to Christmas
is lucrative for the organization, an evangelical Protestant church
best known for its charity work. Last year bell ringers collected
about $79 million in 20,000 kettles nationally.
</P>
<P>
   Maj. Ronald Lee, the Salvation Army coordinator in the Albany
area, said finding competent volunteers is always a challenge.
</P>
<P>
   `'There's a lot of people who want to do it, but they're there
for the wrong reasons, and instead of helping they're turning
people off,'' Lee said.
</P>
<P>
   Not all of the Salvation Army Corps in the region, 12 in total,
are in such dire straits.
</P>
<P>
   The Troy Salvation Army actually has a waiting list for bell
ringers, said Capt. Raymond Patrick. A group of 19 Bible students
has helped boost volunteers to staff the 24 kettles throughout
Rensselaer County, and the group expects to meet its $70,000 goal,
Patrick said.
</P>
<P>
   Some chapters supplement volunteers with paid bell ringers. That
may have helped in Saratoga Springs, where Capt. Mary Fitch said
she was unaware that other corps were struggling.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are doing very well this year,'' said Fitch, who is
coordinating shifts at 14 stands throughout Saratoga County. Eight
workers are paid $5.15 per hour, and six are volunteer, but the
corps averages about 9 to 10 stand workers every day.
</P>
<P>
   Even without full coverage, the corps is $7,000 ahead compared
to last year and expects to meet its $60,000 goal. As a result, she
expects the corps will be able to beef up its programs next year.
</P>
<P>
   The kettle campaigns are almost as old as the Army itself.
Salvationists arrived in New York from Britain in 1880 and the
kettles appeared 11 years later at a San Francisco Christmas dinner
for needy people.
</P>
<P>
   Nickels, dimes and quarters fed 1,000 people that first year.
</P>
<P>
   The kettles, in the Army's well-planned strategy to provide
``soup, soap and salvation,'' were a deliberate attempt to
capitalize on the commercialization of the Christmas season.
Historians say kettles were placed outside department stores and
were meant to evoke warm feelings of hearth and home.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
