<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-10 14:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5271 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-VIEQUES-PROTEST-2TAKE     12-10 1064
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIEQUES-PROTEST-2TAKES-$ADV12-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BATTLE OVER TARGET RANGE RAISES FEAR OF UNREST IN PUERTO RICO
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, Dec. 12)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.) 
 By STEWART M. POWELL  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   VIEQUES, Puerto Rico _ Weary but determined protesters have
weathered isolation, uncertainty and lashing hurricanes to thwart
resumption of 58 years of naval bombardment on a remote target
range at the eastern tip of this impoverished island.
</P>
<P>
   But now, after eight months of peaceful civil disobedience that
forced an aircraft carrier battle fleet to divert elsewhere for
amphibious warfare training, encamped trespassers and Puerto Rico's
political leaders are bracing for their greatest challenge yet.
</P>
<P>
   Puerto Rico Sen. Ruben Berrios, head of the Puerto Rico
Independence Party and the party's candidate for governor in 2000,
has lived a Robinson Crusoe life of civil disobedience on Vieques'
Yellow Beach since May 8.
</P>
<P>
   The scholarly lawmaker _ who has degrees from Georgetown, Yale
Law School and Oxford University _ sees signs that Washington is
waging a more determined offensive to undercut a people-power
campaign to oust the Navy from Vieques after a Marine warplane
accidentally bombed a range observation post in April, killing a
Navy contract security guard from the island and wounding four
other civilian workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope our unity will hold,'' Berrios said in an interview in
his beach-front encampment, one of eight protest camps located
about an hour's boat ride from the civilian sector of the island.
``The Clinton administration must break us apart if they hope to
prevail in this struggle. I just hope they don't succeed.''
</P>
<P>
   Far from the beach, ensconced in the majestic fortress-style
governor's mansion in San Juan that dates back to the Spanish
colonial era, Gov. Pedro Rossello expresses related concerns.
Strains are beginning to develop over strategy and tactics within
the improbable coalition of rivals that united to demand an end to
Navy bombardment and fixed-date withdrawal from Vieques while
continuing to disagree about statehood, commonwealth or
independence for Puerto Rico.
</P>
<P>
   ``The consensus is based on peace _ any sort of demonstration
within the boundaries of nonaggression and no violence,'' Rossello
said in an interview in La Fortaleza, a stronghold built in 1540 to
cement Spain's hold in the Caribbean. Some factions in the
coalition now ``have in their interest changing this into a
confrontation and into violence,'' Rossello warned. ``That is the
one thing that I think we have to be very careful about.''
</P>
<P>
   The plan outlined by Clinton 10 days ago failed to resolve a
bitter dispute between Puerto Rico and the Navy over the future of
the target range. Clinton bought time for additional negotiations,
by diverting the USS Dwight D. Eisenhower battle group from
scheduled training on the island before Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   The commander-in-chief ordered an end to live-fire combat
training on Vieques, requiring the Navy and Marines to use inert,
non-explosive weapons during the amphibious assault exercises that
are scheduled here in March, led by the aircraft carrier USS George
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton told the Navy to return 8,000 acres of Navy land that
has been used as an ammunition storage site; withdraw completely in
five years; and provide $40 million in economic development
assistance to Vieques, which has 9,300 civilian residents.
</P>
<P>
   Rossello, the popular pro-statehood Democrat with close
political ties to Clinton, Vice President Al Gore and First Lady
Hillary Rodham Clinton, rejected the president's blueprint because
it failed to set a firm date for Navy withdrawal, lacked legal
enforcement to bind future presidents and held open the possibility
of the Navy negotiating resumption of live-fire training.
</P>
<P>
   But the failure to reach an agreement after widespread
expectations that Puerto Rico would be able to protect its
territory from unwanted Navy training has dramatically changed the
political landscape.
</P>
<P>
   Anti-Navy demonstrators have defiantly expanded their peaceful
occupation of the target range in the wake of Clinton's
announcement to impose a contentious, round-the-clock blockade at
the entrance to Camp Garcia. Demonstrators have prevented supplies
from entering the Navy reservation that contains an 11,000-acre
maneuver and buffer zone, the hilltop range observation post and
the 899-acre shell-impact area.
</P>
<P>
   Puerto Rican authorities have helicoptered a team of riot police
to stand by on Vieques. Navy authorities have beefed up security on
the Navy-side of the gate, with U.S. Marshals.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Rabin, a former school who leads the Committee for the
Rescue and Development of Vieques, said the blockade is designed to
``send a message to Washington that the people of Vieques are
standing firm.'' Rabin added: `We will not tire of this issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Some protesters living on the impact area are now talking tough.
Jorge Farinacci, of the Socialist Front, says that ``any type of
resistance is legitimate'' to protect Vieques from resumption of
Navy bombardment.
</P>
<P>
   Fugitive Puerto Rican guerrilla leader Filiberto Ojeda Rios used
a television interview from a clandestine location to warn that his
Macheteros, or Cane Cutters, may resume terrorist attacks if the
Navy resumes operations on Vieques.
</P>
<P>
   Anti-Navy Puerto Rican sympathizers in New York staged a
demonstration at the United Nations that led to 10 arrests last
Tuesday, including former world boxing champion Jose ``Chegui''
Torres. Singer Ricky Martin, the Puerto Rican heartthrob,
electrified his receipt of an honor at the Billboard Awards
ceremony on Wednesday by dedicating his award to the ``children of
all militarized zones,'' before adding in Spanish: ``Vieques, I'm
with you.''
</P>
<P>
   On the beach, Berrios vows to remain encamped on the target
range until the Navy permanently ends amphibious combat training or
until he is arrested to make way for resumption of training with
inert ammunition next spring. The thoughtful, white-bearded scholar
savors the potential political clout offered by Puerto Rican voters
in the New York Senate race being waged by Mrs. Clinton and by
Hispanic voters who are influential in large electoral states
crucial to Vice President Al Gore, including, California, Florida,
New York and Texas.
</P>
<P>
   (MORE ... MORE)
</P>
<P>
   ``If the Navy leaves without one more bomb, we win,'' said
Berrios, whose civil disobedience on Navy-owned Culebra and
imprisonment in 1971 helped set the stage for the Navy's turnover
of the nearby island in the mid-1970s. ``If they arrest us, they
lose. If they imprison us, you can jot down the defeat of the
Democratic Party in the next election.''
</P>
<P>
   Rossello said Thursday that he expects to resume personal
negotiations with Clinton before Christmas, either by telephone or
during a trip to Washington, in a continuing effort to reach a
settlement.
</P>
<P>
   But Rossello warned that as a compromise nears, other
participants in the political partnership of convenience may harbor
other goals. Rossello, who favors statehood, said that Berrios was
``begging to be arrested'' to bolster his campaign to win Puerto
Rico independence.
</P>
<P>
   ``If that's one of his goals, he will do anything to accept
nothing,'' Rossello said. ``But again, that's his goal. That's not
our goal.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On Vieques, the dispute lives side-by-side with a fledgling
tourist trade that lures mainland Americans to a quiet Caribbean
getaway and islanders who are largely dependent on a social safety
net financed by San Juan and Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Unemployment exceeds 50 percent on a wind-swept island where the
Navy has owned two-thirds of the 52 square miles since buying up
sugar cane fields and residents' small plots for $47 an acre in
1941 to make way for combat training for World War II. Today, many
families rely on food stamps, part of the $11 billion in federal
payments to Puerto Rico's 3.8 million U.S. citizens who reside in
the commonwealth, which lacks the clout of a state or a nation.
</P>
<P>
   Many homes and businesses are dilapidated, built from cinder
block, wood and corrugated metal sheeting that have been torn and
tattered by passing hurricanes. Packs of dogs roam overgrown sugar
cane fields. Limited air and ferry services contribute to an air of
isolation on the island 8 miles from Puerto Rico.
</P>
<P>
   Carmelo Belardo, 60, a retired high school Spanish teacher who
served in the U.S. Army in Alaska, blames Navy occupation for
stemming economic development and sowing chronic dependency.
</P>
<P>
   ``People should not receive something for nothing,'' Belardo
said, as he chats with a half dozen friends on the beachfront.
``But people have no hope. Why finish school, the wonder, if their
only choice is to go on the dole or leave the island they love.''
</P>
<P>
   For the family of David Sanes Rodriguez, the 35-year-old Navy
security guard who died in the errant bombing on April 19, the
Christmas season approaches with an air of dread.
</P>
<P>
   Sanes, devoted to his well-paying job with the Navy, died one
month before his planned wedding as he stood on an observation
platform watching Navy and Marine aircraft drop bombs from 10,000
feet. Two 500 pound bombs exploded nearby, inflicting mortal
wounds.
</P>
<P>
   The incident became a rallying point for islanders' frustration
with the Navy. But the Sanes family has shunned the limelight and
the crusade that his death inspired.
</P>
<P>
   Rumors circulate that negotiations are under way between the
Sanes' lawyer and the Navy on a compensation package in excess of
$1 million. But no one is talking.
</P>
<P>
   Victor Ortiz, a cabinet maker who has two brothers married to
sisters of the victim, said the family ``doesn't want to take part
in the protests,'' adding: ``They have suffered a loss. They have a
lot to deal with.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (Stewart Powell can be reached via e-mail at
stewart(at)hearstdc.com.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
