<HEADER>
A5285 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r d BC-FROZEN-FOOD-HNS &LR;      12-10 0257
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FROZEN-FOOD-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FROZEN BAKED GOODS DON'T LAST FOREVER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RUTH FANTASIA  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Perhaps the most common inquiry I had this season is, ``Can I
freeze (enter any baked good here)?''
</P>
<P>
   The answer, according to the National Food Safety Database and
the University of Georgia Extension Service, is yes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any food can be safely frozen. However, the quality might not
be acceptable when thawed,'' writes the extension service's Carolyn
J. Lackey.
</P>
<P>
   For best results, use packaging materials that are made for use
in the freezer to minimize changes. Also, package everything in the
freezer airtight so flavors and odors don't travel from food to
food.
</P>
<P>
   The longer the foods are frozen, the more likely the quality
will diminish, but since the holidays are close, that shouldn't be
a problem. Just in case you don't use them all this Christmas, date
the packaging and use within three months for best results.
</P>
<P>
   Thaw precooked breads, cakes and cookies in their wrapping at
room temperature.
</P>
<P>
   Unbaked yeast breads are best if they are frozen before the
final rising period. Thaw in the refrigerator overnight. Let the
dough then stand at room temperature about 15 minutes to warm
slightly before shaping. Bake as directed in recipe.
</P>
<P>
   Even choux pastry, which is used for making cream puffs and
eclairs, can be frozen. Bake as usual, cool and remove the moist,
inner parts, but do not fill. Package and freeze. Thaw at room
temperature.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
