<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-10 15:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5294 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k BC-EDITORIAL-WORCESTER-B     12-10 0622
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-WORCESTER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`MY OWN BROTHER PASSED AWAY' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The procession and memorial service for six Worcester
firefighters who died last Friday in a ghastly blaze was, at heart,
a family gathering. If a banner could be sewn large enough to
stretch over these public servants, it would best depict a passage
from the Book of Proverbs: ``A brother helped by a brother is like
a fortified city.''
</P>
<P>
   Firefighters began to muster at dawn on Grove Street. Within a
few hours an estimated 30,000 of them formed a human lifeline
almost 3 miles long. It was meant to reunite them with their six
brethren, four of whom are still buried beneath the rubble of the
Worcester Cold Stog and Warehouse building.
</P>
<P>
   The firefighters, who traveled here from as far away as
Australia, accept the dangers of their profession. Each is equipped
to deal with the harshest realities. Yet each also knows how
quickly one or more of their number can succumb to the deadly
caprices of fire. Only light smoke was showing on the upper floors
of the warehouse when Worcester firefighters searched for homeless
men and women. Within a few seconds, cork paneling and polyurethane
coating ignited, turning the building's cubicles into crypts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like my own brother passed away,'' said firefighter
Nick Fahs of the Mehlville Fire Department District near St. Louis.
It was an oft-repeated sentiment.
</P>
<P>
   Worcester firefighters, in their time of sorrow and exhaustion,
needed every member of the family there.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is our extended family, and it extends around the
world,'' said Jim Cassidy, a Worcester firefighter who was
bleary-eyed from the previous night's efforts to recover bodies.
``And it's a good thing, too, given this devastation.''
</P>
<P>
   The deeper the sorrow of these men, the less they had words to
describe it. Before the procession stepped off, it appeared that
one member of the Worcester Fire Department's honor guard, Steven
Raffa, would collapse if he had not been able to lean on his M1
carbine. Yet when a fire officer called hoarsely for ``Rescue One,
Ladder Two, and Engine Three'' _ the first responders to the blaze
_ to take up the lead position, Raffa led them ramrod straight.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the firefighters wanted the public to understand that it
is not just the shared peril of the job that unites them.
</P>
<P>
   Martin O'Reilly, who travel to Worcester with five other members
of the Dublin Fire Brigade, was almost dismissive of the dangers of
a job where a flickering glow can suddenly turn deadly.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always dangerous,'' he said. ``That's just what we do.''
</P>
<P>
   The real point, said the Irish firefighters, is the profession's
abiding belief in ``humanitarian service'' and ``preservation of
human life.'' That sense of common obligation and value binds the
firefighters together, regardless of geography or department
strength.
</P>
<P>
   Even the youngest Worcester residents who lined the march route
seemed to understand that sentiment. Hardly a sound could be heard
along the way other than pipes and drums. Schoolchildren, many
teary-eyed, held signs with the hand-drawn message, ``May God
protect our heroes, always.'' The message would be taken up later
by Bishop Daniel Reilly, who told thousands of assembled mourners:
``We ust recognize the transcending goodness of their actions. Love
like theirs, heroism like theirs, sacrifice like theirs, cannot go
unrewarded.''
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of people came to Worcester on is day of lamentation
to say that noble purpose defined the lives and times of Worcester
firefighters Paul Brotherton, Timothy Jackson, Jeremiah Lucey,
James Lyons, Joseph McGuirk, and Thomas Spencer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-10-99 1528EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
