<DOCNO> NYT19991210.0129 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-10 15:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5295 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l BC-NYHAN-COLUMN-$ADV12-B     12-10 0976
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYHAN-COLUMN-$ADV12-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RAYTHEON'S PICARD A SELF-MADE MAN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, December 12, 1999)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID NYHAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dennis Picard was not born with a silver spoon anywhere handy.
</P>
<P>
   More like a brass screwdriver. As a working class kid in North
Providence, R.I., he arrived at the Christian Brothers' doorstep at
LaSalle Academy. ``I was a punk kid, and the Christian Brothers let
me know I was a punk kid,'' said the retired Raytheon CEO, now 67.
``They straightened me right out.''
</P>
<P>
   Then the Air Force got hold of him. As an 18-year-old airman
with a knack for electronics, he began as a Korean-era radioman,
and began lapping up correspondence courses. Until he became
bedazzled by electronic gizmos, he'd been pointing to a career in
wildlife management.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Air Force turned me around from running a duck marsh,'' he
said, though a lifelong interest in fishing finds him still heading
out for deep water on his fishing boat based on Cape Cod. ``I
learned a great deal about leadership in the Air Force, about the
kind of people who should be leaders, and the people who should not
be inedership positions.''
</P>
<P>
   Discharged, he set up shop in his father's cellar, fixing broken
TV sets. By the time he had the first two of his five children,
``my wife was telling me to go get a real job, so I got in my car
and drove from Rhode Island to Waltham,'' looking for the Sylvania
plant to file a job application.
</P>
<P>
   ``This very gruff, tough Irish cop pulled me over near Route 20
in Waltham, asking me what the hell I was doing holding up traffic.
I was trying to read the map. I didn't know where I was.'' The cop
wanted him to move his car, and pointed him toward a nearby
Raytheon factory. Following the hand of fate, and the stern finger
of that flatfoot, Picard got hired at Raytheon, in the lowest-level
engineering job the company offered.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was going to Northeastern three nights a week and some
weekends, and moved the family to Oak Square in Brighton. We lived
there till the ceiling caved in. The trolley went right by the
house, and over the years, it loosened the plaster, till the whole
thing came down. So we moved.''
</P>
<P>
   And he didn't stop moving until he became the boss, an engineer
who rose through all the technical ranks till a stubborn mentor
overcame Picard's reluctance and shoved him onto the management
track. There he presided over the aggressive acquisition strategy
that turned Raytheon into the number three defense contractor. But
after Picard turned the CEO job over to Daniel Burnham, the current
chief, Raytheon stock was hammered, triggering a critical article
in Business Week that challenged Picard's management style.
</P>
<P>
   ``. . . the accusation fromanonymous sources that (Picard) had
`not just a hot temper but was unpredictable' is simply untrue and
obviously a venomous accusation by someone with an ax to grind,''
replied former US Senator Warren Rudman, a Picard booster who
points out that many defense companies have had problems digesting
the acquisitions that Pentagon downshifting forced them into.
Burnham also leaped to the defense of his predecessor, as did
former CIA chief John Deutch, another Raytheon board member, who
called Picard ``one of the most impressive leaders I have ever
met.''
</P>
<P>
   The fallout from the consolidation in the defense industry is a
short-term problem; to Picard the long-term problem is getting a
higher quality of public education. America's economic strength
rests ultimately on the quality of public education. ``I've been
active in charter schools, to get the public schools to work in
competitive ways. Bill Bulger got me started _ his roots and my
roots were similar. We're not doingall that well with public school
kids, particularly in math and science.''
</P>
<P>
   ``All these engineering and Internet companies are having
trouble getting the right kind of people,'' Picard said over lunch
Monday. ``The problem really begins in secondary school. That's
where you can lose the work intensity, the desire, for the hard
subjects like math and science.'' He says too many bright young
people believe that ``other kids seem to have more fun than those
taking math and science, where they're doing twice as much
homework.''
</P>
<P>
   Picard put in 44 years aRaytheon, Massaachusetts' largest
employer. ``I've worked with great engineers over the years, and
the greater they are, the more pronounced they are.'' He says you
can't lead a giant corporation without facing tough decisions.
``I'm not a bully, but I'll agree with you that I'm a tough guy, a
forceful guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Picard saw the handwriting on the wall about defense spending
cutbacks at a now-famous dinner in Washington in 1993, dubbed ``The
Last Supper,'' where top officials of the US government informed
contractors the fall of the Berlin Wall would mean severe slicing
in some kinds of military spending.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no panic, no frenzy,'' claims Picard of Raytheon's
reaction to the news. In the race to adapt to changing conditions,
he said, ``Lockheed Martin went forward quickly, we hung back.''
There were other corporations ``that came in and wanted to buy
Raytheon'' in the merger derby that unfolded.
</P>
<P>
   He described the Raytheon merger with Hughes as an example of
two cultures clashing. ``Hughes was tough. They were our
arch-rivals. It was like the Red Sox and Yankees suddenly having to
work together.'' Experiences like that convinced him America needs
business leaders who can bridge gaps.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a need for a better mix of business and liberal
education with technology skills,'' he said. ``With the Internet
and the amount of information flow, you can't be just a technocrat
anymore. You're not allowed to be just a technocrat.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(David Nyhan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
