<HEADER>
A5308 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-RUSSIA-CHECHNYA-1211-     12-10 0916
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-CHECHNYA-1211-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MOSCOW BACKS OFF FLEE-OR-DIE DEADLINE, BUT WAR GRINDS ON
 &HT;    (600 &AMP;ADD).
 &HT;    By CHARLES W. HOLMES 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ The Russian government appeared to ease a flee-or-die
deadline Saturday for residents of the besieged Chechen capital,
Grozny, but vowed to pursue its punishing military offensive in the
breakaway republic despite intense international criticism.
</P>
<P>
   Russia offered to negotiate safe passage for the thousands of
civilians trapped in Grozny, said a senior Russian official,
Emergencies Minister Sergei Shoigu. He denied that a target date
existed for the city's annihilation.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no deadline. Everything will be all right. What
deadline? Is it the end of the world tomorrow?'' Shoigu asked
reporters.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Russian forces dropped leaflets over the Chechen
capital warning residents that they had until Saturday to escape
through a designated military corridor or face death from a Russian
onslaught.
</P>
<P>
   The United States and others condemned the threat. President
Clinton said Russia risked international isolation and Germany
called the ultimatum ``barbaric.''
</P>
<P>
   The United Nations refugee agency, UNHCR, estimates as many as
40,000 people _ many of them elderly and disabled _ are pinned down
in Grozny amid Russia's ongoing artillery and air bombardments.
</P>
<P>
   Russia forces have occupied the northern two-thirds of Chechnya
and are poised to overrun Grozny, as the remaining pocket of
resistance from Islamic guerillas in the central plains appears to
be evaporating.
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Vladimir Putin revealed Friday that he has
conducted secret, and thus far fruitless, contacts with an envoy of
the Chechen president in an effort to seek a peaceful settlement of
the three-month-long conflict.
</P>
<P>
   But with broad support for the war from the Russian people,
there seems little motivation for Russia to make concessions.
</P>
<P>
   The Chechen campaign is causing diplomatic strains with the
United States and the European Union, but the offensive is a
political winner at home for the Kremlin as Russia prepares for
national parliamentary elections one week from Sunday. The election
will signal the political mood in advance of the race to replace
President Boris Yeltsin. The vote for a new president is scheduled
for June 2000.
</P>
<P>
   The war is widely popular among Russians, who blame Chechen
guerrillas for a series of fatal apartment-building bombings that
killed about 300 people in Moscow and other cities last summer.
Putin, virtually unknown when he was appointed by Yeltsin in
August, is now the country's most popular politician because of the
war he has waged.
</P>
<P>
   The capture of Grozny would be an important symbolic victory,
coming three years after Russian troops, bloodied and humiliated,
retreated from the city following a war with Chechen rebels from
1994-96.
</P>
<P>
   When the capital may fall is uncertain. Analysts suggest that
the Kremlin is weighing the political dividends of securing Grozny
before the Dec. 19 elections versus the political fallout should
Russian ground forces face fierce resistance and suffer casualties.
</P>
<P>
   But there appears to be little standing in the way of the
100,000 Russian troops now amassed in Chechnya and the border
regions. The current Russian campaign, and the damage left from the
1994-96 war, have decimated about 80 percent of Grozny, according
to media and eyewitness reports.
</P>
<P>
   Shoigu, the Russian Emergencies Minister, said Friday that the
military would temporarily halt its siege and establish six
corridors to allow civilians to leave Grozny for Russian-controlled
territory in northern Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   UNHCR spokesman Ron Redmond said in Geneva that ``confusion
reigned'' over the Russian offer for safe passage and that few had
fled via using the single route suggested Monday after the military
dropped its do-or-die leaflets.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Russia has displaced the guerrillas, but has not
conquered them.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week, some 5,000 Chechen guerrillas held positions
in Grozny and its southern outskirts, according to reports. But
wire services quoted Chechen guerrilla commanders Friday saying
that many fighters have now retreated to the southern mountainous
region to regroup.
</P>
<P>
   Russia has vowed to pursue the rebels into the highlands and
destroy them there. Yet the ground forces would be vulnerable to
hit-and-run attacks, analysts say.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin and Putin need a swift, successful conclusion to the
conflict, or risk becoming mired in a war of attrition like that of
'94-'96, said a political commentator in Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a paradox. The Russian economy remains weak; people's
lives have not changed. And the outcome of this war is unclear. But
for now the nation feels good,'' said Boris Makarenko of the Center
for Political Technologies, a think tank.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian government has demanded that Chechen authorities
hand over the ``terrorists'' and disarm warlords and armed groups
in the lawless province. Shoigu, who is running at the head of the
Kremlin-backed list of candidates for parliament, said he would be
willing to meet and negotiate with Chechen President Aslan
Maskhadov.
</P>
<P>
   But Putin said later on Friday that Maskhadov ``keeps sending
new people (to negotiate) but we have not been given clear answers
to our questions.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
