<HEADER>
A5310 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-TEXACO-OPERA-TEX     12-10 0665
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXACO-OPERA-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OPERA AND RADIO LOVERS REJOICE AT TEXACO TRADITION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WAYNE LEE GAY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   For opera fans across America, Texaco means more than big oil.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to one of the country's most enduring and far-reaching
cultural institutions _ the weekly Texaco Metropolitan Opera
broadcasts _ thousands who could only dream of going to New York to
see a live performance at the Metropolitan Opera have experienced
opera in their own living rooms, becoming familiar with the
masterpieces of the repertoire and with the unique qualities of the
great singers of the century. As of 1999, opera is more popular
across America than ever, and the Texaco Metropolitan Opera
broadcasts can take at least part of the credit for making America
an opera-friendly nation.
</P>
<P>
   The tradition begins its 60th season Saturday, with broadcasts
that will be aired on more than 600 stations in the United States
and Canada _ from Nome, Alaska, to Miami _ and on almost 60
stations overseas.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the ongoing success of the Saturday-afternoon broadcasts
is due to the intelligent, but adamantly nonsnobby intermission
commentary of Peter Allen, who often includes quizzes and trivia
questions from listeners.
</P>
<P>
   Allen, who had his first radio experience while majoring in
English at Ohio State University, will celebrate his 25th
anniversary as host of the program Jan. 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``My main goal is to communicate,'' he said in a recent
telephone interview.
</P>
<P>
   Allen has hosted over 500 broadcasts and says that only three
were operas he doesn't like. He declines to say which three operas,
but says he strove to help the audience enjoy those works anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ``Virtually every opera has a fascinating background,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   That fact helped Allen through one of the most difficult moments
in his career early on, when, during a performance of Verdi's
``Macbeth,'' a man committed suicide by jumping from a balcony.
Allen and his guest commentators had to improvise two hours of
intermission features while the situation in the Metropolitan Opera
House was cleared up.
</P>
<P>
   This year's broadcast schedule has an unusually rich variety of
repertoire, including _ along with the Met's usual heavy dose of
standard Franco-Italian repertoire _ a complete performance of
Wagner's monumental four-opera ``Ring'' cycle, Shostakovich's
``Lady Macbeth of Mtsensk'' and a broadcast of the premiere
production of American composer John Harbison's ``The Great
Gatsby.''
</P>
<P>
   The schedule this year, a definite clip-and-save item, is as
follows (all times CST):
</P>
<P>
   11:30 a.m., Dec. 12: Donizetti's ``Lucia di Lammermoor''
</P>
<P>
   11:30 a.m., Dec. 18: Wagner's ``Tristan und Isolde''
</P>
<P>
   12:30 p.m., Dec. 25: Mozart's ``Le Nozze di Figaro''
</P>
<P>
   12:30 p.m., Jan. 1: Harbison's ``The Great Gatsby''
</P>
<P>
   12:30 p.m., Jan. 8: Puccini's ``Tosca''
</P>
<P>
   12:30 p.m., Jan. 15: Verdi's ``Rigoletto''
</P>
<P>
   12:30 p.m., Jan. 22: Mascagni's ``Cavalleria Rusticana'' and
Leoncavallo's ``Pagliacci''
</P>
<P>
   Noon, Jan. 29: Richard Strauss' ``Der Rosenkavalier''
</P>
<P>
   Noon, Feb. 5: Verdi's ``La Traviata''
</P>
<P>
   12:30 p.m., Feb. 12: Offenbach's ``Tales of Hoffmann''
</P>
<P>
   12:30 p.m., Feb. 19: Boito's ``Mefistofele''
</P>
<P>
   12:30 p.m., Feb. 26: Puccini's ``Madama Butterfly''
</P>
<P>
   12:30 p.m., March 4: Lehar's ``The Merry Widow''
</P>
<P>
   12:30 p.m., March 11: Rossini's ``La Cenerentola''
</P>
<P>
   12:30 p.m., March 18: Shostakovich's ``Lady Macbeth of Mtsensk
''
</P>
<P>
   12:30 p.m., March 25: Wagner's ``Das Rheingold''
</P>
<P>
   11:30 a.m., April 1: Wagner's ``Die Walkure''
</P>
<P>
   12:30 p.m., April 8: Debussy's ``Pelleas et Melisande''
</P>
<P>
   11:30 a.m., April 15: Wagner's ``Siegfried''
</P>
<P>
   11:30 a.m., April 22: Wagner's ``Gotterdammerung''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Wayne Lee Gay is classical music critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call him at (817) 390-7756, or e-mail:
wlgay(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
