<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-10 15:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5311 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-FBN-COLTS-MORA-BOS &LR;      12-10 1401
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COLTS-MORA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MORA'S OFFENSE MAKES COLTS ONE OF THE BEST 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating for all needing)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ The day in America's heartland is cool, December
dank, and dark. The Colts are leaving the field after a midweek
practice and the media are seated under a giant old tree, sturdy as
the Midwest. Jim Mora walks over and begins talking about a
phenomenon rarely seen in this area.
</P>
<P>
   Time spinning faster than it does on the coasts.
</P>
<P>
   A new rage exploding first in Indiana and only then fanning
across the country.
</P>
<P>
   The Colts stomping.
</P>
<P>
   A year earlier than expected.
</P>
<P>
   Mora is tanned. There is a glint to his eye. His smile is quick.
That image from New Orleans when he fell apart at a news conference
after his Saints lost their sixth game in eight and Mora resigned
after 11 seasons with New Orleans seems long gone.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be honest, I hadn't been asked that question before,'' Mora
said when an outsider asked when he realized his Colts were not
just a team on the upswing but one of the best in the National
Football League. ``I don't know if I can say there was any one
moment.''
</P>
<P>
   It's happening so fast. The Colts now have an offense that even
draws in neutral fans for a look at how football should be played.
The Colts now have a quarterback, Peyton Manning, and a running
back, Edgerrin James, and a wide receiver, Marvin Harrison, that _
in their potential _ seem capable of being more exciting than, or
as good or even better as, any of the last generation.
</P>
<P>
   And it happened so fast.
</P>
<P>
   ``You never know in this business,'' said Mora. ``I've been in
this business long enough to know that crazy things happen. No, I
didn't think we'd win this many games . . .''
</P>
<P>
   Mora exhaled a deep breath. ``You saw this potenial in this
team, especially offensively, and yet you never know what's going
to happen next year. You know you're an injury away, a key injury
away, from going the other way.''
</P>
<P>
   So fast.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nice that it's happening,'' said Mora, struggling to put
into words this sudden rise from the ashes of the Colts _ and
himself. ``It gives you a nice feeling . . . it's better than not
having it.''
</P>
<P>
   Two games with the Patriots, both in Foxborough, stand out as
benchmarks on the trek upward. The first, early in the 1998 season,
was perhaps Manning's worst game in his short career, the rookie
quarterback confused, lost, bewildered, and inept, throwing
interception after interception. ``That was maybe Peyton's worst
game,'' said Mora, as the Colts struggled to a 3-13 year.
</P>
<P>
   But, significantly, Manning was not scarred as so many rookie
quarterbacks are scarred by sudden ineptitude when they take that
last giant step to professional football (``That Patriots game was
tough,'' said Manning. ``I was worried that I might be scarred'').
Late last season, said Mora, ``he made it over the hump'' when he
went out to San Francisco and fired three TD passes against the
49ers in a 34-31 loss.
</P>
<P>
   The next benchmark, early in this season, came when the Colts
scored 28 points against New England in the first half as Manning
checked off at the line scrimmage on play after play, testing Ty
Law as no other QB had tested Ty Law, throwing three TD passes to
Harrison over Law. ``That showed how much I'd learned about
defenses since that other game in Foxborough,'' Manning said of the
audibles at the line of scrimmage.
</P>
<P>
   But the Colts blew that lead, as Mora's teams in New Orleans,
good as they were, so often blew leads and lost games they should
have won. Mora so often would go conservative with a lead, but a
hard, hard lesson was learned in Foxborough by these young Colts.
They learned their offense was too good to ever be set in neutral,
that their offense could suck all momentum from opposing teams.
</P>
<P>
   Mora also learned that he had a quarterback ``who was a
competitor, one who could handle pressure, one who _ like a Larry
Bird or Michael Jordan _ wants the ball in pressure, critical
situations, one who handles adversity and doesn't let it put him in
the tank.''
</P>
<P>
   Mora has ever been known as a defensive coach, deep in his core
the football truism that defenses win games. But now, as the Colts
defense is still being built, Mora has a true offensive power, one
that can win games now with its sheer explosiveness.
</P>
<P>
   The defensive guru (``Oh, nobody is a guru in this business,''
he countered) was asked to look at his offense from a defensive
coach's eyes. Mora complied, but the essential defensive nature of
his soul told him that no offense, not even his Colts, is
unstoppable.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody is unstoppable,'' said Mora. ``We fought for our lives
twice against the Jets. We fought for our lives . . . I mean, we
scored 16 points in one game and 13 in the other. Nobody in
unstoppable; I guarantee that. I coached against the 49ers every
year for many years when they had a great offensive machine and
there were times they had trouble scoring points. Everybody
struggles.''
</P>
<P>
   And Mora knows so well the cycle of NFL football. A team can
spring suddenly upon the scene, but as that team enjoys more and
more success, opposing coaches devote more of their attention, and
their schemes, to stopping it. It is the way of life in the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then, when you are doing good in this business, when you
really are doing good on offense, then everybody is really bearing
down to put the clamps on you to stop that offense,'' said Mora.
``It makes it even tougher.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But there is one element to this Colts team that makes it so
different from Mora's New Orleans teams. Beyond the quarterback,
beyond the running back, beyond the wide receiver, there is Tom
Moore. He is 60 years old now, has spent 22 years coaching in the
NFL, and, for most of the years, has been the offensive coordinator
for some very good offenses.
</P>
<P>
   From the Steelers of Terry Bradshaw and Lynn Swann in the late
1970s to the Lions of Barry Sanders in the 1990s, the offense that
led the league and was the first to have two receivers (Herman
Moore and Brett Perriman) catch more than 1,000 yards in passes,
Moore has been excellent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year, Tom Moore more or less called the plays,'' said
Manning. ``As he's gained confidence in me and as I have a better
understanding of what we're doing, it's gotten better. Last year,
I'd just listen to the play. But now I have a pretty good idea of
what he's going to call before he calls it and that's what you want
to have between a quarterback and a coordinator.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, the bond is total between the wise and savvy Moore and
Manning. They think the same _ they think the worst epithet for an
offensive game plan after the last play ``is to be one play away,''
as Manning put it. ``The worst thing is to think, `I just wish we
had the post call when they were in that defense.' ''
</P>
<P>
   (For Patriot fans who no longer remember what a post pattern or
quick slant pass play entails, the receiver cuts diagonally to the
inside. Despite the Patriots' reluctance to use the patterns, they
still are most effective against some blitzes.)
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to use that last play,'' Manning said. ``If they're
showing blitz, hey . . . we want the post route and we know we can
get to it. That's kind of a result of how much confidence I have in
Tom and Tom has in me. We never want to leave the field thinking of
that one last play we should have called but we didn't call.''
</P>
<P>
   These Colts of Mora, unlike those Saints of Mora who just
couldn't take the final step, do not think offense is merely what
happens when the defense is not on the field. Blowing that 28-7
lead to the Patriots taught them all a lesson _ keep scoring
points.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   So fast.
</P>
<P>
   The Colts are now among the best in football, and unlike last
year's Falcons, who also made a sudden rise, it is clear this team
will be very good for several years. And if it happened so fast
that Mora doesn't realize exactly when the Colts went from a team
on the uptick to a team that must be feared, his decades in pro
football have taught him one lesson. Seize the moment.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to take advantage of the opportunity when you've
got it,'' Mora said. ``All coaches learn that. It's really
important. You've got to . . . you've got to . . . you never know
when it's going to come again.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
