<HEADER>
A5314 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k BC-EDITORIAL-INDIA-BOS &LR;      12-10 0865
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-INDIA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INDIA'S DEMOGRAPHIC FRONTIER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By Renee Loth  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   KERALA, India  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The numbers are so dizzying in the world's second-most-populous
country that demographers have borrowed words from Hindi to help
express their vastness: ``lakh'' for 100,000; ``crore'' for 10
million. So, for example, India's teeming population of 1 billion
is increasing by 1.6 crore (16 million) every year.
</P>
<P>
   Gement programs to manage the population, especially in the
cities, where the slums are a dispiriting sink of pollution,
squalor, and disease, have not been successful. In the mid-1970s,
Indira Gandhi imposed emergency restrictions on civil liberties
that included a coercive two-child policy for each family.
Vasectomies were forced upon men. Women found to have reached their
limit were packed off to hospitals for sterilization, then sent
home with a transistor radio as an ``incentive.'' In 1996 India
officially dropped birth-control quotas in favor of a more holistic
approach to reproductive health care, but government efforts at
family planning remain deeply suspect.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is compounded by the pitifully low status of most
women in India. Sixty-three percent of the female population is
illiterate. Girl children are not valued, and many are abandoned as
infants. Although the Qutb Minar tower in Old Delhi is closed now
for security reasons, women without dowries routinely flung
themselves off it rather than face a life of ostracism, begging, or
marrying beneath their caste. Women who fail to produce sons can be
banished from their homes. Widows in some areas still immolate
themselves upon their husbands' funeral pyres in the Hindu ritual
of suttee. All of these practices are officially banned but seldom
prosecuted.
</P>
<P>
   Further impeding progress is the nation's diversity: Indians
speak 18 languages and belong to at least six major religions, each
with its own civil code. India is, of course, the world's larget
democracy, but it is also the most chaotic. Each sprawling state is
barely manageable. In Uttar Pradesh (population 157 million), the
impression is of disorder bordering on anarchy: Fires for cooking
or incinerating garbage burn everywhere; pigs, dogs, and the
ubiquitous cows root about in the streets, picking through trash
with men who have little to do but squat on their heels and trace
idly in the dirt with sticks. The most optimistic UN projection
does not foresee India's population stabilizing until it
nearlydoubles, to 1.8 billion. To consider that prospect is to
court despair.
</P>
<P>
   Just visible through the gloom is Kerala, a green and languid
state on the southwest coast, where literacy even among females is
90 percent, education is compulsory, health care is free, and
infant mortality rates are 12 per 1,000, compared with 85 per 1,000
in Uttar Pradesh. Since 1957, with some interruptions, Kerala has
had a democratically elected communist state government that
nonetheless exists with vigorous religious expression, especially
among Christians, and a bustling economy of rubber, cashews, coir,
and, increasingly, tourism.
</P>
<P>
   Officials estimate that nearly a third of educated Keralites are
working abroad, mostly in Kuwait and Dubai. So-called ``Gulf
houses'' are springing up amid the palms and jasmine thanks to the
wealth returning to India from the Gulf states. Kerala reached zero
population growth 15 years before the target date set by the UN.
</P>
<P>
   Kerala is thus a laborory for the thesis that family size
naturally decreases when women are educated, children survive
infancy, and economic opportunity nurtures hope for a better life.
During a visit to the Vadavucode Community Health Center organized
by the Population Institute, a US-based nongovernmental
organization, we met Leela Yohannan, who explained that she had a
tubal ligation at the center after her second child and already
tells her daughters about the benefits of a small family.
</P>
<P>
   It is difficult to tell in this stew of factors which holds the
secret for Kerala: Is it the religious or political differences,
the fact that the state is a traditional matriarchy, or the system
of industry cooperatives and strong local ``panchayats,'' or
district councils, that make Kerala easier to organize? Officials
cannot hope to replicate Kerala's success until they figure this
out, but free compulsory education for boys and girls alike would
be a good place to start.
</P>
<P>
   There is a political conundrum as well; in a democracy, states
like Kerala that have stable populations lose out against the
growing states. And India itself is not above rattling one billion
sabers against its enemies. In recent border clashes with Pakistan
the government in New Delhi ran patriotic ads saluting India as
``100 Crore strong.''
</P>
<P>
   India will need to reconcile these competing imperatives in
favor of a sustainable population or it will lose power in the
world despite its nuclear capacity and its grwg middle class.
Mohandas Gandhi said poverty is the worst form of violence. Surely
the father of his country would not support creating more savagery
on such a scale.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
