<DOCNO> NYT19991210.0147 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-10 16:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5324 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-BIO-WAR11-COX     12-10 0510
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIO-WAR11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ROGUE NATIONS SAID TO RECRUIT FORMER SOVIET WEAPONS EXPERTS
 &HT;    By JEFF NESMITH
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Developed countries have failed to block efforts by
rogue nations and terrorists to recruit chemical and biological
warfare scientists in the former Soviet Union, a weapons
proliferation expert said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   More than seven years after the Soviet collapse, no one in the
U.S. or Russian governments seems to even know the identities of
scientists whose brains hold key information on how to build and
use chemical and biological weapons, said Amy E. Smithson.
</P>
<P>
   They are ``conservatively'' estimated to number more than 10,000
persons, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Reporting on a recent tour of the sprawling network of chemical
and biological weapons labs in Russia and other former Soviet
states, Smithson said scientists confirmed to her that some of
their former colleagues had left to work in Iran, Iraq and North
Korea.
</P>
<P>
   She added that no one knows if others are ``moonlighting by
modem'' _ using computer networks to transfer critical facts across
borders.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. leaders have known since the collapse of the Soviet Union
that suddenly impoverished weapons scientists likely would be
recruited for their expertise.
</P>
<P>
   ``The festering concerns of U.S. leaders have not yet translated
into meaningful resources to address the chemical and biological
brain drain threat,'' said Smithson, who works for the Stimson
Center, a national security analysis group.
</P>
<P>
   Financial research support and joint commercial ventures with
U.S. companies have been the chief means of keeping the chemical
and biological weapons experts in their laboratories, working on
peaceful projects.
</P>
<P>
   But these grants -- from the United States, the European Union
and Japan _ have been ``glaringly insufficient,'' Smithson said.
</P>
<P>
   She recommended ``at least doubling'' funding of collaborative
research grants for former biological weaponeers and ``at least
tripling'' the grant support of former chemical weapons scientists.
</P>
<P>
   The entire cost of those increased expenditures, about $19
million year, would be only about seven one-thousandths of 1
percent of the annual Pentagon budget, she said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, she said, Russia must ``clean its own house'' and
get rid of those who are determined to maintain the Cold War
practice of developing these weapons.
</P>
<P>
   ``An ounce of prevention, applied via collaborative research
grants, security enhancements and training programs to steer the
weapons institutes toward commercial self-sufficiency, could
short-circuit biological and chemical weapons proliferation,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   The text of Smithson's report, entitled ``Toxic Archipelago:
Preventing Proliferation from Former Soviet Chemical and Biological
Weapons Complexes,'' can be downloaded from the Stimson Center's
Internet site, www.stimson.org.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Nesmith's e-mail address is jeffn(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
