<SLUG> BC-HEARST-NEWS-BUDGET-2NDLD-WRITETHRU-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 Friday, Dec. 10, 1999   Editors  
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Hearst News Service has filed or will file the following for
Saturday and Sunday. If you have questions, please call Susie McBee
or Tim Spence at 202-298-6920.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Adds: SF-MAYOR-POLL; CLINTON-PLANS; MEAT-SAFETY;
DAY-CARE-SHOOTING; and FBC-HU.)
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (The ``HNS'' tag appears in all sluglines.)
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For Saturday:
</P>
<P>
   POLITCAL NEWS (``p'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SF-MAYOR-POLL (San Francisco) _ A new poll shows that Mayor
Willie Brown has a comfortable lead over Board of Supervisors
President Tom Ammiano heading into Tuesday's run-off election. The
San Francisco Examiner and KTVU-TV survey shows that 48 percent of
likely voters support the incumbent, while 34 percent favor
Ammiano, who staged an electoral coup last month by finishing
second with a write-in campaign. By ZACHARY COILE.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-PLANS (Little Rock, Ark.) _ President Clinton travels to
Arkansas and Tennessee and talks about plans for his library and
about his years as president. By GREG McDONALD.
</P>
<P>
   MEAT-SAFETY (Dallas) _ Officials of a Texas meatpacking company
and an expert in food microbiology testify that a Dallas meat
processing plant is being unfairly targeted by the Agriculture
Department for failing federally mandated salmonella tests. But the
government says its new food-safety program is at risk unless a
judge allows the shutdown of the Supreme Beef Processors Inc.
plant, which supplies about 15 percent of the department's beef for
school lunch programs. By JIM HENDERSON.
</P>
<P>
   DAY-CARE-SHOOTING (Pleasanton, Texas) _ A day care center worker
is gunned down at a South Texas nursery, just hours before parents
started dropping off their children. By JIM PINKERTON.
</P>
<P>
   For Sunday:
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   VIEQUES-PROTEST (Vieques, Puerto Rico) _ Weary protesters here
have weathered isolation and lashing hurricanes to stop U.S.
bombing at a remote target range on this impoverished island. But
now the encamped demonstrators and Puerto Rico Gov. Pedro Rossello
face their greatest challenge: reaching a long-term compromise with
Washington that avoids violent protests on the island. By STEWART
M. POWELL. (Filed Friday.)
</P>
<P>
   POLITICAL NEWS (``p'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-DEBATE (Washington) _ The third Republican debate in Iowa
Monday will give Texas Gov. George W. Bush yet another chance to
ward off commentary that he is an empty suit. Bush is losing ground
to Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., in New Hampshire and could use a
positive debate performance to shore up his frontrunner status. By
DAN FREEDMAN.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MILLENNIUM-CLINTONS (Washington) _ Hollywood star power will
meet Washington political power on New Year's Eve as some of the
world's biggest celebrities join President and Mrs. Clinton for a
glitzy, patriotic celebration to usher in the millennium. By MARK
HELM.
</P>
<P>
   MILLENNIUM-TIMELINE (Washington) _ Times when main events occur
on New Year's Eve. By the Hearst Newspapers. With
MILLENIUM-CLINTONS.
</P>
<P>
   Y2K-NORMAL (Washington) _ If your bank's ATM machine isn't
working on Jan. 1, don't assume it's a Y2K problem. As many as
3,000 of them can be down under normal circumstances. On any given
day flights are delayed and people lose their electricity. The
federal government is trying to determine what doesn't normally
work so it won't blame a Jan. 1 problem on the year 2000 computer
glitch when the real cause may be a snowstorm. By JENNIFER CORBETT
DOOREN. (Filed Thursday.)
</P>
<P>
   Y2K-TIPS (Washington) _ with Y2K NORMAL _ While experts say
banks, electricity distributors and transportation companies are
ready for the New Year, they're offering tips to consumers just in
case there are Y2K computer failures. By The Hearst Newspapers.
(Filed Thursday.)
</P>
<P>
   REDISTRICTING-WONKS (Washington) _ Dueling Republican and
Democratic statisticians, cartographers and demographers will play
key roles in the redistricting of the House of Representatives, a
huge political upheaval that occurs once every decade and can
determine which political party controls the House. By JUDY
HOLLAND. (Filed Thursday.)
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   THOMPSON-COLUMN (Washington) _ It is astounding to learn that
George McGovern, the Democratic presidential candidate in 1972 and
a leading critic of the Vietnam War that President Lyndon B.
Johnson escalated in the 1960s, now judges LBJ as one of the
greatest presidents since Abraham Lincoln. But as a reporter
covering Johnson in those days, I know what McGovern means. By
ROBERT E. THOMPSON. (Filed Wednesday.)
</P>
</TEXT>
