<HEADER>
A5334 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-MEXICO-VIRGIN-1211-CO     12-10 1596
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-VIRGIN-1211-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MEXICO'S RELIGIOUS FAITHFUL STUNNED AT PRIESTS' QUESTIONING
EXISTENCE OF INDIAN MESSENGER OF THE VIRGIN OF GUADALUPE
 &HT;    (1200&AMP;ADD)
 &HT;    With Photos.
 &HT;    By SUSAN FERRISS 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ It's one of the most fundamental, beloved stories
of Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   In 1531, during the Spanish Conquest, a brown-skinned,
Aztec-speaking Virgin Mary is said to have appeared before an
Indian peasant named Juan Diego. The Virgin who became known as
Guadalupe asked Diego to build a church on the site where she
appeared, and to prove her miraculous apparition she left an
imprint of herself on Diego's cloak for him to show to Spanish
priests.
</P>
<P>
   For centuries, this story has nurtured Mexicans' strong faith in
the Catholic Church as well as Mexican and Mexican-American pride
in their indigenous heritage. But just as Mexicans prepared to
celebrate the apparition of their patron saint 468 years ago this
Sunday, the country was stunned to discover some of their own
priests doubt the miracle ever occurred.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the three Mexican priests _ all of whom have worked at
the Virgin's basilica here _ wrote a letter to the Vatican in
September objecting to an effort to make Juan Diego a saint. They
say that so far no requisite proof has been produced to confirm
that the Indian was a real person.
</P>
<P>
   The dispute has thrown canonization for Diego into question and
is testing the strength of faith in Mexico, the second largest
Catholic country in the world and a naiton vital to the Vatican's
influence in this hemisphere.
</P>
<P>
   ``We never said anything about this to the people before, and we
never intended to hurt anyone,'' said Carlos Warnholtz, who
ministers at the Virgin of Guadalupe Basilica and signed the
letter, which was supposed to be confidential but was leaked to a
reporter in Rome.
</P>
<P>
   Upset because some top church officials have ordered the three
to repent, Warnholtz said the dissident priests embrace the
``tender, beautiful and very Indian story'' of the Virgin's
appearance. But without proof of Juan Diego's existence they regard
the encounter as a symbolic legend that helped convert Mexico's
Indians, who _ not coincidently _ worshipped the Aztec mother
goddess Tonanztin on the same hill where the Virgin appeared to
Juan Diego.
</P>
<P>
   The legend was fueled by priests eager to win converts and
evolved over the centuries into a cult of worship for the Virgin
that is valid, Warnholtz said. But that doesn't mean it merits
canonization.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have doubts in the tradition,'' he said. ``But where
is the proof? Where are Juan Diego's remains? Where is his tomb?
</P>
<P>
   At Mexico City's massive Virgin of Guadalupe Basilica, where as
many as 6 million were expected to pour in from all parts of Mexico
for Sunday's fiesta, pilgrims appeared disturbed by the priests'
doubts but unshaken in their faith.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the church, the second most visited shrine in the
Catholic world, they gazed with reverence at the cactus fiber cloak
Diego supposedly wore with the miraculous image of the Virgin. The
cloak hangs high on a wall inside a glass case.
</P>
<P>
   Juana Medina, a 30-year-old Mexico City mother, carried her own
statue of the Virgin to the church to be blessed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will continue to believe until Juan Diego and the Virgin
come and tell us not to believe,'' she said indignantly.
</P>
<P>
   Rosa Soriano, 23, who sells corn cakes outside the church, said
of the priests, ``If they don't believe, why do they work here?''
</P>
<P>
   Candida Portilla, a Veracruz state construction worker, was
equally firm in his faith.
</P>
<P>
   ``He existed and he still exists in our hearts,'' Portilla said
of Juan Diego, grimacing and sweating with pain as he showed his
devotion by hobbling toward the church on his knees.
</P>
<P>
   Believer Antonia Garcia, a Mexico City housewife who visits the
shrine whenever she needs comfort, said, ``Juan Diego was very
important. The Virgin doesn't just appear to just anyone. She chose
him because he was one of the humble. That was a message.''
</P>
<P>
   When the story about the internal church squabble over Juan
Diego surfaced in Mexico last week, the press and radio shows
gobbled it up.
</P>
<P>
   The Pope last visited Mexico in January and repeatedly expressed
veneration for the dark-skinned Virgin of Guadalupe, announcing
that she should be a symbol for evangelization throughout the
Americas. The pope beatified Diego in 1990, a step that must be
taken before a candidate can be considered for sainthood.
</P>
<P>
   Top church officials here, who reportedly hope to see Diego
canonized next year, were swift and harsh in their condemnation of
the dissident priests' opinions.
</P>
<P>
   The letter's primary author was Guillermo Schulenburg, 83, who
is now retired but for 33 years served as abbot of the Virgin's
basilica. Three years ago, Schulenburg angered Catholics here when
he called the apparition of the Virgin ``a symbol, not reality'' in
a Catholic publication. He was retired shortly afterward.
</P>
<P>
   Last week Norberto Rivera, Cardinal Primate of Mexico, said
Schulenburg was effectively excommunicating himself by questioning
the canonization.
</P>
<P>
   Bishop Onesimo Cepeda, a church spokesman, told a newspaper,
``This is what you might expect of someone older than 80. Logically
all old people become a bit capricious and lose lucidity in their
thinking.''
</P>
<P>
   Papal Nuncio Justo Muller, the Vatican's ambassador here, called
for Schulenburg to ask for forgiveness.
</P>
<P>
   For good measure, Muller also said Schulenburg had ``no right''
to his opinion because he owns several houses and lives in
excessive luxury. The retired Mexican priest has avoided the press
since the squabble erupted into the public light.
</P>
<P>
   Warnholtz said he and another priest who also works at the
basilica haven't been fired or pressured so far to leave their
posts. ``We didn't commit a crime or a sin by expressing our
doubts,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The church allows for confidential debate over naming saints,
Warnholtz said, and since it requires ``scientific'' proof of a
candidate's existence the priests felt it was their duty to point
out shortcomings.
</P>
<P>
   Warnholtz said his doubts were heightened when he saw the image
of the Virgin on Juan Diego's cloak up close in 1980.
</P>
<P>
   ``People say it's supernatural. But I've seen it and it is a
painting,'' he said. ``We agree, though, that it is mystical
because it remains so well-preserved.''
</P>
<P>
   Warnholtz acknowledged that many saints in the Middle Ages were
named without sufficient proof they existed, including Saint
George, the legendary dragon slayer and patron saint of England.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the modern world is more critical,'' he said and the
church should protect its reputation by following its own more
modern, strict standards.
</P>
<P>
   Jose Luis Guerrero, a priest who spent four years in Rome
promoting sainthood for Diego, said worshippers he knows burst into
tears and were deeply wounded when they heard about the priests'
letter.
</P>
<P>
   He insisted, too, that hundreds of pounds of documents he
presented to the Vatican add up to adequate historical record of
Diego's existence. Not long ago, he said, a piece of paper was
discovered in an archive with Diego's Aztec name on it and a
certification of his death in 1548.
</P>
<P>
   The document bears the authenticated signature of a famous
priest who ministered to Indians at the time, Guerrero said.
Apparently, however, there are disagreements over the authenticity
of the document, the cloak and other evidence.
</P>
<P>
   Guerrero said he fully accepts that it was no accident that the
Virgin supposedly appeared on the same site where the Indians
worshipped their mother goddess.
</P>
<P>
   ``God adapted to that by sending his mother to be the
evangelizer,'' he said. ``It was an indispensable way to show the
Indians that the Christian faith was for them.''
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Alfonso Vietmeier, director of the Center for Religious Studies
here, said he thinks that the dispute over Juan Diego is rooted in
power struggles within the Mexican church and the Vatican. Someone
leaked the priests' confidential letter to the press, but no one is
saying who or exactly why, except to suggest it was to harm
Schulenburg.
</P>
<P>
   But one thing is certain, Vietmeier said. The fight has touched
a popular nerve because of the Virgin of Guadalupe's powerful image
unifying Mexico's European and Indian heritage, which violently
collided with the Spanish Conquest.
</P>
<P>
   ``The experience of Mexico is of a people conquered, violated,''
Vietmeier said. ``Yet they recovered their dignity through their
religion.''
</P>
<P>
   Independence fighters in the 19th century went to battle against
the Spanish carrying banners of the Virgin of Guadalupe.
</P>
<P>
   In the United States, Mexican-Americans and Mexican immigrants
marched for the rights of Hispanic farmworkers in the 1960s
carrying images of the Virgin.
</P>
<P>
   Playing Juan Diego in plays celebrating the Virgin is an honored
role for little Mexican boys, who paint on mustaches and don cloaks
like Juan Diego's.
</P>
<P>
   Even Mexican rock musicians have penned odes to the Virgin
because she is a symbol of national hope as much as religious
conviction.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, said Warnholtz, ``We don't have to believe in
private apparitions of the Virgin until the Pope says we do.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If the Pope canonizes Juan Diego,'' he said, ``then we will
have to accept it. He will be giving us the gift of an Indian saint
whose example we can follow.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
