<HEADER>
A5336 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r k BC-LABBE-COLUMN-TEX     12-10 0875
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LABBE-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAWLESS IN SEATTLE: A TALE FROM THE FRONT LINES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By J.R. LABBE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Mary Ann Lockhart never in her 53 years imagined that she would
one day find herself in the middle of one of the biggest news
stories to hit the United States in the waning days of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   A grandmother of 12 who cares for an 80-year-old mother-in-law
in her home in Yakima, Wash., Lockhart volunteers what free time
she has to help glean local orchards and farms for area food banks
and assist in Habitat for Humanity and Union Gospel Mission
projects.
</P>
<P>
   Yet there she was on Nov. 30, standing at Pike Street and Third
Avenue in downtown Seattle, when the black-hooded anarchists
arrived to disrupt what had been peaceful civil disobedience
against the World Trade Organization conference.
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart's reason for being among the throng of protesters
raising a din outside the city's convention center wasn't sea
turtles or labor standards or worldwide minimum wages, although she
said the stories about working conditions for children in some
countries had tears streaming down the face of her 26-year-old
daughter.
</P>
<P>
   Nope, Lockhart's issue was U.S. sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to being a wife, mother and grandmother, Lockhart is
a captain in the Yakima County Militia.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was never really involved in world or global relationships
until I read about Bob Dole saying back in '94 or '95 that he did
everything he possibly could to save this nation's sovereignty
during GATT negotiations,'' Lockhart said in a telephone interview
last week. ``That got my attention.''
</P>
<P>
   The word ``militia'' in Washington state apparently isn't the
indictment for lunacy that it has become in other parts of the
country. Lockhart said her group works in cooperation with the
local parks and recreation department to hold public awareness
classes on preparedness, constitutional rights and firearm safety.
They have a good working relationship with the Sheriff's Department
_ one deputy is even a member.
</P>
<P>
   ``We love our country and want to help keep it free,'' Lockhart
said. ``It's a shame the term has become so negative. After all,
our founding fathers were militiamen.''
</P>
<P>
   E-mail from like-minded people alerted Lockhart to the planned
protests during the WTO convention, so, gas mask in hand, she and
eight members of the militia loaded up in a van and headed into
town that Tuesday morning. What better way to exercise one's First
Amendment rights than to peaceably protest what they believe is
America trading away its rights?
</P>
<P>
   ``The gathering at the stadium was made up of a broad spectrum
of people,'' she said. ``The Communist party, China Out of Tibet
protesters, the Farmers Union and labor groups. For two hours we
listened to speakers from Europe, Mexico, Canada, Japan, Africa and
Australia.''
</P>
<P>
   Around noon, more than 50,000 protesters began their march
downtown. Lockhart said she was unaware that other people were
already at the convention center, linked arm in arm around the
building to block entry by delegates from the WTO's 135 member
nations.
</P>
<P>
   As they neared Pike Place Market, Lockhart said she could hear
concussion grenades several blocks away. Once at the market, the
newly arrived protesters saw windows bashed out and shattered eggs
covering the exterior of the Nike building. Things had turned
nasty.
</P>
<P>
   About 2:30 p.m. _ with nary a police officer in sight, Lockhart
said _ a group of athletically built men marched up Pike in
formation, banging on drums. Their heads covered in black hoods,
the men turned over garbage bins and set the spilled contents on
fire, all the while shouting profanities.
</P>
<P>
   The anarchists had arrived.
</P>
<P>
   ``We weren't about to intervene because we didn't know what they
might do to us,'' Lockhart said.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't until after the masked men had left the area that the
police showed up.
</P>
<P>
   ``All around me were college-aged students sitting and talking
about people power,'' she said. ``Without provocation, with no
signs of trouble, the police used concussion grenades, rubber
bullets and tear gas on the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't believe what I was seeing. There were no acts of
vandalism, no stealing. Just young people with no protection being
fired on.''
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart admits that the street cops were caught in a hot spot,
having to follow orders from ``higher up,'' but the use of pepper
spray, tear gas and rubber bullets on citizens horrified her.
</P>
<P>
   ``From my position, what I saw, there was no attempt to make
peaceable arrests.''
</P>
<P>
   The announcement this week that Seattle Police Chief Norm
Stamper plans to step down from the job in March underscores
Lockhart's assessment of the situation: His department did not
handle the demonstrations well at all.
</P>
<P>
   So what will Lockhart do now that the gas has drifted away from
Seattle?
</P>
<P>
   ``One of those dangerous militia activities,'' she said with a
chuckle, ``cracking nuts.''
</P>
<P>
   (Jill ``J.R.'' Labbe is senior editorial writer and columnist
for the Star-Telegram. She can be reached via e-mail at
jrlabbe(at)star-telegram.com or by phone at (817) 390-7599. Visit
the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
