<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOCIAL SECURITY AND CLINTON: HE'S AT IT AGAIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILL THOMPSON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   There is no end to Bill Clinton's chicanery.
</P>
<P>
   You'd think that after all this time, Clinton would occasionally
lapse into forthrightness _ for variety's sake, if nothing else. No
such luck. The president's aversion to the truth _ and his audacity
in disseminating deception _ is constant and consuming.
</P>
<P>
   It should not have come as a surprise, then, when Clinton looked
America straight in its collective eye Wednesday and declared
himself ``profoundly disappointed'' that nothing was done this year
to secure the long-term viability of Social Security. He said this
as if the preservation of Social Security were an issue floating
somewhere in the stratosphere, far beyond the reach of the
president.
</P>
<P>
   The comment came at the end of his response to a question posed
by a reporter during a rare presidential news conference:
</P>
<P>
   ``You're ending a tumultuous year that began with impeachment
and that closed with tear gas in Seattle; could you tell us what
you're proudest of this year and what events or accomplishments of
yours that you're the least proud of?''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton nearly broke his arm patting himself on the back for
legislative and foreign policy achievements ranging from money for
teachers and cops to his war in Kosovo. When he got to the ``least
proud'' part of the question, needless to say, he broke the other
arm tossing blame at Republican members of Congress for failing to
embrace his entire domestic agenda.
</P>
<P>
   Last, but not least, he got around to Social Security:
</P>
<P>
   ``And I'm profoundly disappointed that we still haven't done
anything to take the life of Social Security out beyond the baby
boom generation and extend the life of Medicare and add a
prescription drug benefit.''
</P>
<P>
   The reporter immediately saw that something was awry in
Clinton's assessment of the Social Security problem. She reminded
the president that he hadn't even offered a proposal for protecting
the nation's most cherished entitlement program.
</P>
<P>
   His response to the follow-up question was classic:
</P>
<P>
   ``I gave them ... first of all, I asked them ... there's no
point in putting forward ... look, I tried it the other way; with
health care. I put forward a plan. And everybody said you put
forward a ... I remember Sen. Dole saying you put forward your plan
and I'll put forward my plan and we'll get together and we'll agree
and we'll pass a plan ... and, uh, so, you know, I've had
experience with that ... that didn't work out too well. ...''
</P>
<P>
   Besides, he said, he did put forward a plan to use interest
savings from paying down the national debt to bolster Social
Security, and the Republicans wouldn't go along with it.
</P>
<P>
   So. Clinton didn't offer a comprehensive plan to save Social
Security because Congress shot down the health-care plan he
proposed way back in 1993. Is this the guy who is famous for his
perseverance?
</P>
<P>
   Maybe that legendary persistence only comes into play when
Clinton's personal political survival is at stake.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's attempt to wash his hands of the Social Security
problem is infuriating for the obvious reason that his lack of
involvement ensures that the problem won't be solved any time soon.
Adding insult to injury, though, is the mind-boggling hypocrisy of
a politician who portrays himself as the guardian of Social
Security when he's running for election and then makes no effort
whatsoever to guard it once the election is over.
</P>
<P>
   It's a shame, too, because Clinton really could have been the
savior of Social Security if he'd been willing to expend some
political capital after winning re-election in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Preserving Social Security, as Clinton and every other
politician knows, will require unpopular choices and considerable
sacrifice by the American people. A Democratic president who
claimed to feel our pain might have been able to sell those choices
and sacrifices to the public.
</P>
<P>
   He isn't the first president to shrink from the challenge, of
course, and he probably won't be the last. But he at least ought to
have the decency to tell the truth about his failure.
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Thompson is a columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can reach him at (817) 390-7787. Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
