<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-10 16:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5342 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-FILM-HANKS-TEX     12-10 0835
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-HANKS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOM HANKS, OUR GENERATION'S JIMMY STEWART IS STILL BEST WHEN HE
SURPRISES US
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ELVIS MITCHELL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Is Tom Hanks this generation's Jimmy Stewart? When he was
younger, he had a lean ranginess like Stewart; he was as slender as
a question mark. Like Stewart, audiences seem to be eager to
overlook his failures, movies like ``Bonfire of the Vanities,''
where he's so miscast that he disappears. Or a whole stretch of
movies such as ``Every Time We Say Goodbye'' and ``Nothing in
Common'' and ``Dragnet.'' And like Stewart did for most of his
career, Hanks is now settling into the role of elder statesman
whose core of common-sense decency can be seen in everything he
does.
</P>
<P>
   But when he was younger, he threw off sparks in a way that
Stewart never did. One of Hanks' best performances came in the 1984
raunch-comedy ``Bachelor Party,'' where he does everything _
including burst into song _ to keep the movie alive. It's hard to
imagine Stewart, even in his youngest days, triumphing over an
underwritten ``Animal House'' rip-off by peppering the picture with
gleeful riffs. It's as if he's surviving the cinematic equivalent
of a hazing.
</P>
<P>
   Part of Hanks' charm is that he may be the most generous actor
of his generation. He may be more engaging when he has to work off
another actor _ or, as in the case of ``Turner &AMP; Hooch,'' another
species _ than any other performer. Often, stars either tend to
look for a way to upstage other actors when doing ensemble work, or
submerge themselves so deeply that they no longer exist. In the
big-cast dramas ``Apollo 13,'' ``Saving Private Ryan'' and his
newest, ``The Green Mile,'' Hanks underplays and yet clearly pays
attention to the other actors.
</P>
<P>
   The boy/man phase of his career, when his whiny voice spiraled
into the high registers, was tremendously enjoyable. His work
during this period includes his stint on the TV series ``Bosom
Buddies'' as well the fantasy comedy ``Splash'' and, of course, the
definition of boy/man roles, ``Big,'' for which he won his first
Oscar nomination in 1988. And his gift for playing off other actors
was first realized in ``Splash,'' in which he and the late John
Candy play brothers. Candy is all appetite and Hanks the calmer,
more rational of the two until he meets his dream mermaid. Then,
he's transformed into a pleasure machine himself, bouncing off the
walls with happiness.
</P>
<P>
   Hanks was so likable during this period because he got the
chance to show off an almost lethal smart-aleck quickness. In fact,
Bob Hope comes to mind more than Jimmy Stewart. Hanks, with his
long jaw and suggestion of a ski-jump nose, even resembles Hope a
bit. And he's moved into a relaxed self-confidence very close to
Hope, though with a commitment to acting that Hope never showed an
interest in developing.
</P>
<P>
   Hanks' smart-mouthed impetuousness is gone now. And it would
probably be rather untoward for him to continue along that line.
Comedy releases something in him, though. In ``Punchline,'' where
he plays a struggling stand-up comedian with a restless, angry
streak, he mutters a throwaway line about a bouncer with one of
those carved-out-of-stone pompadours _ ``Nice hair'' _ that sums up
the character perfectly. Even more so than when he pours on the
juice for the rest of the picture. His real talent is for the
gesture, the moment that gives an insight into his character. Hanks
can provide the small, telling moment that lingers after the rest
of the picture has drifted out of your memory.
</P>
<P>
   He's not as insubstantial physically anymore, and he uses his
presence judiciously. In the only high point of the forgettable
``You've Got Mail,'' he turns on the charm to seduce a hostile
cashier into letting Meg Ryan through an express line. He's all
polish and masterful cool here; this is a grown man showing that he
knows exactly what his place is in the world, and when to employ
the resources at his command.
</P>
<P>
   He's similarly composed in ``Ryan'' and ``Apollo 13,'' hunkering
down to give adult, movie-star performances. In his more
well-regarded dramatic roles, his need to please can make him come
off as bland, although he still shows enough skill to move an
audience in the way he wants.
</P>
<P>
   He has cut back on the energy, which he now works up for
talk-show appearances. When he isn't acting like he's running for
office, his comic reflexes can still get the best of him _
thankfully. On a recent ``Today'' show appearance, he was asked
about the beard he's grooming for an upcoming movie. ``Just
something I'm working up for all the Stonewall Jackson movies
they're doing for TNT,'' he said, a remark that even seemed to
surprise him slightly. And that's still when Tom Hanks has the most
to offer, when he has caught others _ and himself _ off-guard.
</P>
<P>
   (Elvis Mitchell is film critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
