<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KING-GREENMILE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIVING THE HORROR KING HIS DUE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JEFF GUINN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Casual readers who associate Stephen King only with the grisly
likes of ``The Shining'' and ``Cujo'' will be surprised when they
see ``The Green Mile,'' which is based on a King novella.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Green Mile's'' emphasis is on people _ warmblooded
characters drive the story instead of lurking, scaly monsters
dribbling blood from munching on recent victims. In fact, ``The
Green Mile,'' and a surprising number of other King titles,
represents a softer, more humane approach to storytelling that may
well identify King to future generations far more than his gorier
tales.
</P>
<P>
   This trend really began in 1982, when Viking published
``Different Seasons,'' a collection of four King novellas. Since
1974, when ``Carrie'' hit bookstore shelves, King had established
himself as America's favorite horror writer, although not a writer
of ``quality'' literature.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, in ``Different Seasons,'' story emphasis shifted from the
stomach-churning occult to more human quirks. There were still
bodies discovered in strange places, but story protagonists were
identifiable as real people in a way Carrie, for instance, never
was. In fact, a popular movie, ``Stand by Me,'' was based on ``The
Body'' from ``Different Seasons.''
</P>
<P>
   Ever since, Stephen King has defied categorization. Since
``Carrie,'' he has written 27 novels under his real name, another
six as ``Richard Bachman,'' and 19 collections of short stories,
essays or singly published novellas. Such feverish output
guarantees a certain literary unevenness, and when King is sloppy
(''Insomnia,'' especially) the results can be atrocious.
</P>
<P>
   The signal King sent with ``Different Seasons,'' though, has
been followed by several books that, along with telling good
stories, capture a sense of modern-day America. Perhaps better than
any other mega-selling author, many of King's characters genuinely
reflect ``us.'' In ``Hearts in Atlantis,'' for instance, his latest
novel, King uses wonderfully tiny elements of ordinary American
lives _ silly top 10 songs like ``Incense and Peppermints,'' a
boy's natural nervousness reading ``The Lord of the Flies'' for the
first time _ as well as epochal events like the Vietnam War _ to
create a sense of time and place that is dead-on. ``The Green
Mile,'' in both print and on film, is more of the same.
</P>
<P>
   King will never win a Pulitzer Prize _ critics still harbor too
many ``Carrie''-era grudges for that. But his overall body of work,
considered objectively by scholars of the next generation, may well
be evaluated as a lot more important, and lasting, than most of us
currently realize.
</P>
<P>
   (Jeff Guinn is books editor for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
