<HEADLINE>
INSURER OFFERS DISCOUNT PROGRAM FOR ALTERNATIVE THERAPIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SYLVIA WOOD  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Michael Wayne of the Center for Natural Wellness
in Albany has a growing acupuncture practice but he could always
use more business.
</P>
<P>
   So he is willing to pay for the privilege of participating in a
new program by Blue Shield of Northeastern New York that will offer
member discounts on everything from acupuncture to personal
trainers.
</P>
<P>
   The cost of the discount will be picked up by the providers
themselves in exchange for the benefit of being part of Blue
Shield's network with access to more than 100,000 members in the
area.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of acupuncture, the discount amounts to 25 percent.
</P>
<P>
   That means Wayne will reduce the cost of a regular visit from
$60 to $45 for any Blue Shield members.
</P>
<P>
   ``I figure it can't hurt to be part of it,'' Wayne said.
</P>
<P>
   Blue Shield unveiled details of its new program earlier this
week.
</P>
<P>
   Officials with the health insurance company hope the new
discounts will appeal to a growing number of people who are
interested in alternative therapies. According to recent survey by
the Journal of American Medicine, 42 percent of adults used some
form of alternative medicine in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hope it would be a very positive incentive for people,''
said Dr. Cynthia Ambrese, Blue Shield's chief medical officer.
</P>
<P>
   Blue Shield members who want to take advantage of the discounts
will make appointments directly with practitioners. The savings
include 25 percent for acupuncture and massage therapies, 15
percent for personal trainers, fitness clubs and on healthy meals
from certain restaurants.
</P>
</TEXT>
