   CHINA-SPYING-RDP (Washington) _ A federal grand jury in New
Mexico Friday indicted a government physicist on 59 counts of
stealing highly classified nuclear data from secure computers at
the Los Alamos weapons lab where he worked, government officials
said Friday. The physicist, Wen Ho Lee, was arrested Friday
afternoon at his home outside of Los Alamos. By James Risen and
David Johnston.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-SPYING-SECRETS (Washington) _ What is the evidence
presented in the indictment, and what does it show, beyond what we
already know, about the larger allegations on the one side of
espionage and on the other side that this is selective prosecution?
By James Risen and David Johnston.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``p'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   MCCAIN-CAMPAIGN (Washington) _ John McCain seems to be running
with great glee against all the conventions of modern politics. He
is not polling, he has no stump speech, he's practically stalking
journalists instead of fleeing from them. Audiences in New
Hampshire are lapping it up. He has surged into the lead there,
according to polls. The question is: will this style of personal
politicking work beyond New Hampshire? By Alison Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL-GENERAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   NY-TRANSIT-STRIKE (New York) _ In the event of a transit strike
midnight Tuesday, New York City will ban cars carrying only one
occupant from entering Manhattan, will reserve major avenues for
buses and taxis, and will cancel school on the first day of the
strike. By Elisabeth Bumiller.
</P>
<P>
   (THIS STORY MAY BE HELD IF IT DOES NOT MAKE PAGE ONE.)
</P>
