<DOCNO> NYT19991210.0165 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-10 16:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5359 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-RUBINSTEIN-RECORDINGS     12-10 1021
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUBINSTEIN-RECORDINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEAUTY AND GRANDEUR IN `THE RUBINSTEIN COLLECTION' 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By EDWARD ROTHSTEIN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   A caress can sometimes accompany the chill of death. Or at least
so it seemed when I first heard Arthur Rubinstein play. It was some
30 years ago; the pianist was in his 80s and said to be frail. And
the presence of Chopin's Sonata No. 2 on the program, with its
familiar ``Funeral March,'' did not lighten concerns that he might
never be heard again. In fact when he began that often hackneyed
march (linked by popular culture with the words ``pray for the dead
and the dead will pray for you''), it seemed as if a shroud had
been cast over the audience. A swift, silent intake of breath was
held almost without exhale until the movement's final dying chord.
</P>
<P>
   The sound of that dirge still remains in the porches of my ears.
Rubinstein was sitting upright, his face stonily impassive. But his
hands, having lived with the nuances of hammers and felt and ivory
as long as any human ever had, molded each chord's overtones,
creating otherworldly vibrations. The sound was like death's shadow
passing overhead, its cold breath somehow mixed with sensuous
affection. I have not heard its like since.
</P>
<P>
   But that sound has been coming to mind again as I have immersed
myself in ``The Rubinstein Collection,'' the pianist's complete
recorded legacy, just released by BMG classics in a sumptuously
produced set of 94 compact discs containing 706 recordings of 347
compositions (retailing at about $1,300). They range from the first
78s he made in the 1920s when he was already in his 40s, to his
final, nearly nonagenarian meditations. It is an extraordinary
testament, its remastered sound bringing Rubinstein's own sonic
mastery to life. And now that recording companies have abandoned
such long-term commitments and have finished plundering their
vaults of such riches, this set may also be one of the last
testaments to an era of Old Worldly pianism, cultivated and
confident in its mastery.
</P>
<P>
   It is tempting, in fact, to linger over each achievement: the
Franck Violin Sonata, perhaps, recorded in 1937 with Heifetz, or an
electrifying Chopin Polonaise recorded live at a 1964 Moscow
concert and never before released; the two lilting sets of Chopin's
Mazurkas, perhaps, or the autumnal grace of late Rubinstein playing
late Brahms.
</P>
<P>
   Such detail, though, can wait for another time. Right now, I am
swept away by the set's preternatural energy. The quantity, sonic
beauty and grandeur of these recordings (and even their occasional
sloppiness, fragmentation and frailty) are expressions of a life
force. The playing can seem so natural that it is startling how
different it is from much of this century's pianism. Rubinstein was
not preoccupied with structural drama (like Rudolf Serkin or Artur
Schnabel), or limpid tone color (like Walter Gieseking), or poetic
rubato (like Alfred Cortot) or ecstatic excavation (like Glenn
Gould).
</P>
<P>
   He was, instead, preoccupied with the sensuous power of lived
experience. For Rubinstein, music was lived through, not observed
or dissected. It was as if he were himself always startled and
entranced at the course of its unfolding. This is why his concert
performances, however flawed, have long seemed the apotheosis of
his art (some are offered in this set). Music comes, it speaks and
then is gone, relished in its presence, honored in its passing.
</P>
<P>
   There is a risk, of course, in this kind of immediacy.
Rubinstein had an almost childlike devotion to the pursuit of
pleasure. ``I loved women, cards and brandy too much,'' he once
said of his youth, ``and I almost never practiced.'' This might
have turned Rubinstein into a salon pianist, a highbrow version of
Eddie Duchin, which is what his memoirs suggest with their tales of
love affairs and formal dinners with faded European royalty. ``Do
you know what I like best?'' he said to a Madrid interviewer in
1919. ``To make a collection of happy moments, eternities, without
ever stopping, so that they could replace the moments of
disappointment...I would like to take leave of every woman and of
every friend at the highest moment of affection, and never wait
until the disenchantment comes.''
</P>
<P>
   But if his music had remained at this level _ a collection of
happy moments punctuated by abandonments _ it would hardly be worth
hearing. Is it possible instead that the power of Rubinstein's
playing later in his life comes from his having tempered this
devotion to sensation with an almost tragic understanding of its
limitations? For how can a string of happy eternities ever satisfy
if they are always scarred by transience? Yet how can they be
abandoned when the desire for them is so strong? Perhaps it is only
in music that the pleasures of experience and the sorrows over
their passing can be fully reconciled: the sybarite is also a
tragedian. This spirit haunts Rubinstein's best Chopin recordings,
which mix immediacy and regret, pleasure and melancholy.
</P>
<P>
   That tension is also intertwined with another memory I cherish
of Rubinstein, this one from his last New York concert, in March
1976 at Carnegie Hall. The nearly blind 89-year-old strode
purposefully to the keyboard and played with voluptuous intensity.
But there was no doubt that he would never be seen on stage again.
After a series of encores, Rubinstein, declining demands for more,
shook his head at the cheering audience and, with a sigh of
resignation, held up his hands as if displaying their frailty.
</P>
<P>
   Still no one left, and a roar erupted from the hall's belly.
Rubinstein raised yet again his broad hands and spread his fingers.
Silence fell. ``You listened with marvelous affection for me,'' he
said of his decades of concerts at the hall. ``I love you.'' And
the cries came back, ``We love you!'' Rubinstein put his hands to
his heart, sadly smiled and extended them to his listeners, the
instruments of his music-making offered in a gesture of farewell.
Then he left the stage.
</P>
<P>
   And thus did mortality merge with pleasure and the shadow of
death pass with a caress.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
