<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-10 16:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5366 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l BC-STYLE-BUDGET-NYT &LR;      12-10 0615
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STYLE-BUDGET-NYT </SLUG>
  
 Attn: Style and Leisure Editors:  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service plans the following articles
from the Style section for use Sunday, Dec. 12, and thereafter. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   VAGINA-MONOLOGUES-AUDIENCE (New York) _ ``The Vagina
Monologues'' now playing at the Westside Theater by Eve Ensler and
based on her interviews with more than 200 women, is drawing
various women's groups. The show is a candid talk about a body part
that is a source of sexual pleasure as well as an object of sexual
violence, and whose mere naming causes many people embarrassment.
By Liz Welch. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NY-KNIT-FASHIONS (New York) _ A handful of yarn stores around
the city are doing a brisk business in teaching kniting classes.
Most of their students are in their 20s and 30s, a few of them men.
And they are not using ugly acrylic yarns, but soft skeins of
cashmere and mohair. Women dressed in business clothing can be seen
knitting away on the subway and in airports, lost in their work as
others juggle newspapers and books. It is not unique to New York,
either. Membership in the Knitting Guild of America has increased
by 10 percent in three years. By Amanda Hesser. Photo.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MRSCLINTON-GALA (New York) _ One of the week's big gala was the
rollicking Costume Institute party at the Metropolitan Museum of
Art. It was debatable just how many billionaires were at the gala,
which was a benefit for the Municipal Art Society of New York, a
preservation group whose patrons _ Anne Bass, Veronica Hearst,
Cecile Zilkha and Marie-Josee Kravis, among others _ are hardly
what anyone would call slouches. But with so much else going on,
the rich food, couture dresses that cost $50,000 and then some, not
to leave out an appearance by Hillary Rodham Clinton, well, it
seemed a case of exquisite overkill. Mrs. Clinton, wearing a black
pantsuit, arrived shortly after 7 p.m. and stayed for about an hour
before going on to another engagement. By Cathy Horyn. Photo. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   HOLIDAY-SHOPPING (New York) _ The ritual of Christmas shopping
is upon us. But is the advent of e-commerce killing the traditional
hustle and bustle of the season? By Dany Levy. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NITEOUT-MCCARTNEY-DAUGHTER (New York) _ A fleet of town cars
were parked three deep in front of Pastis, Keith McNally's hopping
new bistro. With all eyes on the famous faces of Minnie Driver and
Puff Daddy, no eyebrows were raised by Stella McCartney's entrance
on a recent Saturday night. Slipping into a corner banquette in the
back, Ms. McCartney, 28, the designer for Chloe, seemed unimpressed
by the marquee crowd. The daughter of Paul and Linda McCartney may
not elicit the same stares and elbow nudges as the stars who grace
the covers of In Style magazine. But as far as those stars are
concerned, she is one of them. By Elizabeth Hayt. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   GARDEN-COLUMN (Undated) _ A good garden tool doesn't strain the
body. It does the job right. It is easy to clean and sharpen. It
endures, even improves with age. So if you are thinking of giving a
tool as a holiday gift, choose a high-quality one _ with the return
slip in case it doesn't suit the person's hand or height, is too
heavy or too light. By Anne Raver. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
