<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLIDAYS-LIGHTS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
READY TO HANG YOURSELF WITH CHRISTMAS LIGHTS?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PETE ALFANO 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It sounded like a great idea at the time: We could put up a
Christmas tree and not have to deal with all those lights.
Stringing Christmas lights, as you probably know, is the reason
some people are hopeful Y2K disasters DO occur. It means we won't
have to worry about taking them down.
</P>
<P>
   In many houses, Christmas lights are responsible for provoking
colorful phrases, with ``Bah humbug'' being about the only one that
can be printed in a newspaper. They are the acid test of a
marriage: Often, the children are crying, the phone is ringing, the
dog is barking and the Cowboys are driving for the game-winning
touchdown when the lights are being strung. Joy to the world,
indeed.
</P>
<P>
   If your Christmas lights are like mine (and I believe all lights
are created equal), they either magically tangle during the summer
or become entwined when you're stringing them on the tree, which
itself requires contorting your body like a 12-year-old gymnast.
When the ordeal is over, you flip a switch and invariably one of
the strands that worked when they were tested earlier has suffered
a catastrophic malfunction. Honey, I fried the tree.
</P>
<P>
   So you can imagine my euphoria upon learning that our local
Christmas store (which sells pool supplies and flotation devices
most of the year), would string the lights on our new 9-foot
artificial tree for a mere sum of $294. Now, it did occur to me
that this was cheating (not to mention expensive) and not exactly
in the spirit of the season, but I felt more in tune with the times
after learning this store alone had pre-lighted more than 100
trees.
</P>
<P>
   Still, I also remember ranting one morning after spying a small
homemade sign at an intersection that read, ``Will hang X-Mas
lights. Call ...'' And I was troubled watching a neighbor direct
two men who are not members of his immediate family setting up his
elaborate light display, which took the entire day.
</P>
<P>
   There also was the revelation that students at Martin High
School in Arlington, Texas _ members of the Key Club _ rent
themselves out to hang lights and decorate trees, with proceeds
going to charity.
</P>
<P>
   That's very noble, but I began wondering, what's up with that?
Does anyone do anything themselves during the holiday season? Are
all those shoppers in the malls on retainer?
</P>
<P>
   This trend may be the single biggest reason why it looks as if
there are more and more lights on people's houses this season. They
are simply hiring others to live their nightmare. There are entire
neighborhoods glowing like Chernobyl. And while icicle lights are
the rage, some people are lining their driveways and lawns with
runway lights, lending an aesthetically nonpleasing D/FW Airport
aura to the surroundings.
</P>
<P>
   This next bit of information also explains the phenomenon.
According to Ray Granado, a spokesman for TXU, Christmas lights are
more energy-efficient than ever. A string of 100 miniature lights
is the equivalent of a 50-watt light bulb and costs only 45 cents a
month on your utility bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nowadays, you can run four times as many lights at half the
cost,'' Granado says.
</P>
<P>
   All of this is great news for would-be Clark Griswolds. You can
celebrate the holiday tradition without actually taking part in any
of it. And Ray Granado's words echoed in my ears when the
Christmas-store guy says that we need 28 sets of lights on our new
artificial 9-foot tree; more lights, I'm guessing, than are strung
on the tree in downtown Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   But why not go for it? A complete stranger is doing all the
work. It took him 10 hours, he says.
</P>
<P>
   There's more. Another complete stranger from the Christmas storewill come to your house to ``set up your tree'' for another mere
sum of between $50 and $75. And you don't even have to leave him
cookies and milk, like you do the big fella in the red suit.
</P>
<P>
   Now, I don't recommend that people with small children abandon
the time-honored tradition of this festive season: Go ahead and
decorate the tree and the house yourself and by all means, let the
kids help. Stress is as much a part of the holiday season as
eggnog, sugar cookies and mistletoe.
</P>
<P>
   But with two boys in college, I felt we could be cut some slack.
Until, that is, we arrived home with our new artificial 9-foot
tree. It came in four sections _ like an Atlas booster _ each
weighing more than I really cared to lift. There were three
extension cords leading from those 28 sets of pre-strung lights,
but no written instructions about how they were to be plugged in.
</P>
<P>
   So we did it by trial and error. And blew out two fuses in the
process.
</P>
<P>
   There must be someone I can hire to figure this out.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
