<SLUG> BC-SF-MAYOR-POLL-1STLD-WRITETHRU-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLL GIVES SAN FRANCISCO MAYOR EDGE OVER CHALLENGER 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDs: Subs 3rd graf, The San Francisco Examiner, to add undecided
vote; pickup: The poll.)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ZACHARY COILE  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Mayor Willie Brown has a comfortable lead over
Board of Supervisors President Tom Ammiano heading into Tuesday's
run-off election, according to a poll released Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Brown's message that he is the best leader to shepherd San
Francisco's red-hot economy seems to be trumping his opponent's
message of open, honest government.
</P>
<P>
   The San Francisco Examiner and KTVU-TV survey showed that 48
percent of likely voters support the incumbent, while 34 percent
favor Ammiano, who staged an electoral coup last month by finishing
second with a write-in campaign. Eighteen percent were undecided.
</P>
<P>
   The poll also showed that more people who supported Brown's
opponents in the Nov. 2 general election _ former Mayor Frank
Jordan and Clint Reilly _ now will vote for Brown.
</P>
<P>
   But analysts and Ammiano's supporters say the election could be
much closer because the poll did not reach some of the groups drawn
to the supervisor's maverick campaign _ new, young and occasional
voters.
</P>
<P>
   While those surveyed see Ammiano as honest, principled and more
understanding of their everyday concerns, they question his
leadership and ability to sustain the economy and create jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Ammiano ``is seen as a kind of rabble-rouser, a man of great
integrity, but someone who could rock the boat in good economic
times,'' said Del Ali, pollster with Research 2000 of Rockville,
Md., which conducted the random telephone poll of 630 registered
city voters Monday through Wednesday. The margin of error is plus
or minus 4 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor won about 39 percent of the vote in the Nov. 2 general
election. Ammiano, who joined the race as a write-in candidate
three weeks before the election, finished second with more than 25
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Though a recent Newsweek article described Brown as ``in the
race of his life,'' the new poll shows the powerful former state
Assembly speaker with solid support in the race. An Examiner/KTVU
survey of 627 people conducted Nov. 9-11 showed Brown with a
10-percentage point advantage, at 43 percent to 33 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Although both men are Democrats, Brown is viewed as more
moderate and more pro-business than Ammiano.
</P>
<P>
   The new Examiner/KTVU poll shows more than half of those
surveyed view Brown as arrogant, but the mayor has gained leverage
over his opponent in what have become the key issues of the race.
</P>
<P>
   Those surveyed were much more likely to trust Brown to manage
the city's economy and budget, spur development and create jobs.
Forty-four percent said Brown would provide the ``best leadership''
for San Francisco, compared with 30 percent for Ammiano.
</P>
<P>
   On the issues of public transportation, homelessness and
affordable housing _ problems Ammiano had hoped would fuel his
effort to topple Brown's bid for a second four-year term _
respondents were largely split over which candidate would do a
better job.
</P>
<P>
   Ammiano had the edge on integrity, which he has made a top
issue. Fifty-one percent of those surveyed said they believe
Ammiano would do a better job of instilling honesty and integrity
at City Hall, compared with 34 percent for Brown.
</P>
<P>
   Respondents also thought the challenger would do a better job in
generating affordable housing than the mayor would, by a margin of
39 percent to 34 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The Examiner/KTVU poll surveyed registered voters who said they
vote ``always'' or ``most of the time'' in city elections. About 94
percent of those surveyed said they had voted in the Nov. 2
election.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
