<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-10 16:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5372 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l BC-VAGINA-MONOLOGUES-AUD     12-10 1204
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VAGINA-MONOLOGUES-AUDIENCE-$ADV12-720&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FROM DARING MONOLOGUES TO DARING DIALOGUES 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, Dec. 12.) 
(js) 
 By LIZ WELCH    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In the lobby of the Westside Theater the other night,
Mei Kai Chin, the chairwoman of the New York chapter of the
American College of Nurse-Midwives, smiled in greeting 17 midwives
who'd come to see ``The Vagina Monologues.''
</P>
<P>
   Nurit Kahane, 50, in a red shearling, waited in the lobby for 19
friends gathering for what she called ``a night out for married
women.''
</P>
<P>
   And 35 Hunter College students in a Sexuality Across the Life
Cycle class clustered, denim clad, in a corner.
</P>
<P>
   All three parties had come to see an off-Broadway hit that,
since it opened on Oct. 3, has acquired something of a cult
following among groups of women, who come with friends or
professional colleagues. The delegations range in size from two or
three to as many as three dozen, and they have included parties
from the Center for Reproductive Law and Policy, Geraldine
Laybourne's women-oriented Oxygen Media and a bachelorette party at
which the bride-to-be was blindfolded and didn't know what she was
being taken to. (When the show's title was announced, there was a
scream.)
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not your usual Broadway tour-bus affair,'' said Eric
Schnall, who arranges group sales at the theater, on West 43rd
Street. ``Each group is attracted to the word vagina.''
</P>
<P>
   Bluntly stated, perhaps. But that, in simplest terms, is what
the evening is about _ candid talk about a body part that is a
source of sexual pleasure as well as an object of sexual violence
and whose mere naming causes many people embarrassment. The show is
written and performed by Eve Ensler and is based on her interviews
with more than 200 women. The dozen or so monologues are by turns
humorous _ corporate lawyer turns dominatrix _ and disturbing _ a
Bosnian rape victim speaks.
</P>
<P>
   Since the show was first performed, in 1996 at Here, a Soho
theater, it has run in Washington, London and Athens, and it was
staged by A-list celebrities at a Manhattan fund-raiser on
Valentine's Day 1998. Though not everyone falls under its spell, it
often stirs up strong reactions. Ms. Ensler is often asked to stay
and lead group discussions after performances.
</P>
<P>
   The run at the 250-seat Westside Theater, extended twice, until
Jan. 23, is selling at 96 percent of capacity _ and some nights,
the other obstructed-view 4 percent sells out as well. Group sales
generally make up 10 percent of all ticket purchases, said David
Stone, the show's producer. Other groups that have booked blocks of
seats this month include a support group for incest survivors and
women from a White Plains synagogue.
</P>
<P>
   At the Dec. 2 show, in addition to the midwives, ``married
women'' and students, there were two famous actresses, Amy Irving
and Heather Locklear, looking like sisters, both blonde and
beautiful.
</P>
<P>
   Beth Dozoretz, who had organized the 19 married women, had
earlier brought a group to see Ms. Ensler's performance in
Washington. ``Eve says what we all feel but are unable to
articulate,'' said Ms. Dozoretz, a former finance chairwoman of the
Democratic National Committee. ``She touches a chord that's deep,
private and that needs to be voiced _ that's why it's so
compelling. It raises a woman's consciousness.''
</P>
<P>
   ``For some of my friends,'' she predicted, ``it will be
shocking, for others moving and for others eye opening.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Kahane, an executive who lives in Manhattan, found it
daring. Taking her front-row seat, she said, ``I told my 5-year-old
daughter that I was going to see a play called `The Vagina
Monologues' and she said, `Mommy, don't be silly, they don't show
that on the stage.'''
</P>
<P>
   The lights dimmed. Ms. Ensler, 46, appeared barefoot in a black
spaghetti-strap dress, her dark hair cut in a bob. ``I was worried
about vaginas,'' she began, acknowledging the sqeamishness that she
too felt.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Ensler clearly sees herself on a crusade to banish the shame
some women feel about their bodies and sexuality, as well as to
raise awareness about the effects of sexual abuse. If in interviews
she talks of the show in terms that are reminiscent of '60s-era
consciousness-raising, her view of performing also has a bit of the
old Living Theater utopianism. ``From the beginning, `The Vagina
Monologues' happened to me,'' she said in an interview. ``If it
were about me, I'd get nervous. It's about us.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   She described passing groups of women in Le Madeleine, a nearby
restaurant, all wearing the ``Vagina Friendly'' buttons sold in the
lobby and discussing the show. ``To have people translate your art
into changing consciousness is the most exciting thing possible,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite her dour-sounding theme of sisterhood-is-powerful, much
of Ms. Ensler's message onstage is conveyed through humor. There
are monologues sending up the indignity of pelvic exams and the
silliness of workshops teaching women to navigate their genitalia.
Several of Ms. Dozoretz's friends laughed during Ms. Ensler's
demonstration of sexual moans, a bit that is reminiscent of Meg
Ryan's deli orgasm in ``When Harry Met Sally.''
</P>
<P>
   Several of the graduate students sniffled during the rape
monologue. Most of the midwives were silent, neither laughing nor
tearful.
</P>
<P>
   Kathryn Rolland, an associate professor at Hunter College, who
had invited the 35 students and graduates of the Urban Public
Health program, later said: ``The next day, the overwhelming
response was: `I'm bringing my sister! I'm bringing my friend!' I
spoke with one graduate who went out with a friend until the early
hours of the morning because they couldn't stop talking about it.
That's what I hoped for.''
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, Ms. Ensler led a discussion for the three groups. The
midwives seemed the least impressed. One, Jeanette Breen, who
specializes in home births in Baldwin, N.Y., said that the final
monologue, describing a hospital birth Ms. Ensler had witnessed,
``missed truth and beauty about birth.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Ensler said she was simply recounting her own experience. A
woman next to Ms. Breen whispered, ``She should've had a midwife.''
</P>
<P>
   A woman thanked Ms. Ensler: ``My mother died in childbirth and
had a stillborn son. In a way, you gave my mother back to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Adele Mora di Puma, one of the Hunter students, raised her hand
and said, ``Where I come from, in Spanish Harlem, the word vagina
is taboo.''
</P>
<P>
   Others had lighter reactions. Swept up, apparently, in the mood
of giddy sisterhood evoked by the evening, Ms. Irving pointed to
Ms. Locklear as both left the theater and said, ``My vagina was
talking to her vagina throughout the show.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Locklear pronounced the show ``awesome.''
</P>
<P>
   Later that night, the midwives gathered at Le Madeleine. Few had
found the monologues funny. Pixie Cram Elsberry, the director of
midwifery at the North Bronx Health Care Network, explained, ``We
didn't laugh because we could relate everything she said to someone
we know.''
</P>
<P>
   No one, it seemed, had been embarrassed or shocked. Ms. Chin
said, ``We talk about vaginas all day long.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-10-99 1659EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991210.0171 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-10 17:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5375 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-BONFIRE11-COX     12-10 1069
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BONFIRE11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Engineering faculty doubted bonfire's stability
 &HT;    By Ralph K.M. Haurwitz
 &HT;    and Laylan Copelin
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLLEGE STATION, Texas _ Several faculty members in structural
engineering at Texas A&AMP;M University regarded the design of the
Aggie Bonfire as unstable but did not speak up because warnings by
one of their most highly regarded colleagues were ignored for
years, according to records released Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I suppose we all have some regrets now that we kept quiet,
even though we thought it futile to speak up,'' Loren Lutes, a
professor of civil engineering and associate head of the civil
engineering department, said in an e-mail to Ray Bowen, president
of the university.
</P>
<P>
   Lutes e-mailed Bowen on Nov. 19, one day after the four-story
stack of logs for the annual bonfire collapsed, killing 11 students
and one recent graduate and injuring 27 students. The university
released about 1,400 e-mails to or from Bowen in response to
requests under the Texas Open Records Act.
</P>
<P>
   A special commission has been appointed to investigate the
collapse, and questions about the design and stability of the giant
woodpile are expected to be central to the inquiry. Several
engineers unaffiliated with A&AMP;M or the investigation have suggested
that the layers of logs might have become unbalanced, causing the
structure to topple.
</P>
<P>
   Lutes told Bowen that T.J. ``Teddy'' Hirsch, formerly head of
the structural engineering section of the civil engineering
department, had expressed the view ``for years'' that the stack
design was fundamentally flawed.
</P>
<P>
   Hirsch took his concerns to the university's Office of the Vice
President for Student Affairs, probably before 1994, and proposed a
more stable design, but the university administration ignored the
recommendations, Lutes said.
</P>
<P>
   Bowen, who holds bachelor's and doctoral degrees in mechanical
engineering from A&AMP;M, said in an interview Thursday evening that
such information could be important.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm trying to keep at arm's length of the necessary analysis
that is taking place,'' Bowen said. ``I hope that professor will
provide that information to the commission and they will decide
whether it's relevant or not. I have a lot of confidence in their
ability to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Lutes was traveling Thursday and could not be reached for
comment. Hirsch, who is retired, declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   Despite A&AMP;M's reputation as a leading engineering school, the
A&AMP;M engineering staff has no responsibility for the bonfire. A
faculty adviser, who is not an engineer, helps students, but the
Aggie tradition is for students to take the lead in building the
structure. No blueprint for the structure exists; each class is
expected to teach the next one how to build the bonfire.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many structural engineering faculty members are well aware of
Teddy's unsuccessful attempt to have the design of the stack
altered,'' Lutes told Bowen in the e-mail. ``I think there has been
a widespread feeling that if he couldn't do it, none of the rest of
us had a chance of having any effect.''
</P>
<P>
   Lutes also said he had spoken with several faculty members and
found ``general agreement'' that the stack had been built in an
unstable way in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   ``In that situation it does not really matter whether the
immediate triggering effect on Thursday (Nov. 18) was due to soil
problems, the splice in the center pole or some other detail. As
evidence of instability, I point out the fact that the stack has
fallen very quickly in recent years. ... To me this is a clear
indication that the structure was only marginally stable before it
was lit.''
</P>
<P>
   Just hours before the bonfire collapsed, there were questions.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after the midnight shift change, some students thought
something was wrong with the stack _ and it was a topic of
conversation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just didn't look sturdy at all,'' said a sophomore crew
chief who asked that his name not be used. ``When I looked at it,
it looked a little shifted. It didn't look quite right.''
</P>
<P>
   The crew chief, who was responsible for a student crew wiring
logs in place, said he thought the stack leaned slightly in the
direction it eventually fell. Although each log in the 40-foot
stack must be wired to three other logs with heavy baling wire, the
crew chief said there were too many loose logs.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were tightening loose logs all night,'' the chief said of
his crew.
</P>
<P>
   The student, who had worked on the bonfire the year before,
blamed a lack of training for the loose wiring. Unlike cutting or
loading the logs, he said, there is no class to teach wiring. Each
crew chief teaches his group on the stack. He said there were just
too many workers _ A&AMP;M has estimated 70 students on the stack that
night _ to train adequately. A&AMP;M officials also have admitted that
many freshmen and sophomores were on the upper stacks, a violation
of university policy.
</P>
<P>
   The crew chief said a majority of the workers from his dorm
``just went out there and just started wiring'' this year. He
added, however, ``Most of them caught on.''
</P>
<P>
   Under A&AMP;M's military-style organization for building the
bonfire, 18 seniors and juniors _ called ``red pots'' for their
helmets _ are responsible for safety. But they work in shifts, so
only a few were there that night.
</P>
<P>
   ``The red pots check for sturdiness,'' the crew chief said of
the wiring. ``I don't think there is any way you can check every
single log, especially when the stack gets really big. People just
need to learn how to wire.'' Another student with experience on
past bonfires is Bill Theissen, 22, a senior management major from
Bedford.
</P>
<P>
   He said he thought the first stack, the base for the structure,
was narrower than in previous years: ``There wasn't much room to
stand.''
</P>
<P>
   Theissen said he climbed up to the top at one point and thought
the structure seemed fine. But he said others complained that the
stack did not have enough cables supporting it.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago when Theissen was a bonfire leader from his dorm,
he said, they cinched the first two stacks with cables, much like a
belt, at least twice before the stack was completed.
</P>
<P>
   ``People were talking about how they didn't do that this year,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Both Theissen and the crew chief escaped injury when the bonfire
collapsed.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
