<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-10 17:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5379 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l BC-HOLIDAY-SHOPPING-RITU     12-10 1115
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLIDAY-SHOPPING-RITUALS-$ADV12-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
E-COMMERCE BRINGS AN END TO THE CHICKEN-SCRATCH CHRISTMAS LIST 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, Dec. 12) 
(mk) 
 By DANY LEVY    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Call me a sap. But one of my favorite Christmas presents was a
purple velour sweat suit my father gave me from Saks Fifth Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   It was ugly, almost aggressively so. I don't think Richard
Simmons would have touched the thing. Of course I returned it, got
a store credit and bought myself some pretty underpants and a
woolly scarf.
</P>
<P>
   This is a ritual of Christmas. I almost kept the thing _ and
maybe I should have, because I will always smile at the thought of
my father darting around Saks, mauled by the barrage of other
holiday shoppers, trying to pick a Christmas gift for his
14-year-old daughter, who, admittedly, changed her style every
other week.
</P>
<P>
   Needless to say, when I flipped open the business section of the
paper recently and read about the new thing going on in the mad
world of e-commerce _ a series of online registry sites designed to
allow users to post their holiday gift wish lists online _ I got a
bit sad.
</P>
<P>
   OK, I got really sad. There is OhIWish.com, Wishlist.com,
Wishclick.com, Wishbox.com, even IveBeenGood.com. My curiosity was
piqued. I logged onto Domains.com, a site that records all
registered domain names, and did a search. I plugged in Gimme.com.
Taken. GimmeGimme.com. Taken. MineAllMine.com, CoughItUp.com,
ForkItOver.com. All taken.
</P>
<P>
   Was the little chicken-scratch Christmas list really dead? Is
this what my future children will be using to inform me what they
want? (Or, from the sound of it, expect.) The downright demanding
nature of it made me uneasy.
</P>
<P>
   Don't get me wrong; I like to have my wishes granted as much as
the next person, but the materialistic, matter-of-factness of this
format made me squirm. I could already see my mother and sister
haggling on Priceline.com over who would get the best price to
satisfy my request for a Hanro undershirt.
</P>
<P>
   I had always thought this product-specific ``I want it!''
brattiness was supposed to be confined to a bride and bridegroom
setting up house. Did anyone and everyone now deserve a personal
registry?
</P>
<P>
   And, if you had a registry at age 10, what would be the use of
rejiggering one for your nuptials?
</P>
<P>
   I started poking around some of these sites, much surprised by
the fact that I didn't need a password of any sort to view the
contents of, say, a little girl named Ally's wishbox in Ohio. Each
time I perused some unsuspecting child's list of wishes, I felt
vaguely as though I were lurking around a schoolyard.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, it made me queasy to behold all the things
these children wanted. One 13-year-old wanted a Jaguar. Another
teenager had composed a list of no fewer than 110 items, including
a Hewlett-Packard flatbed scanner, Bye Bye Blemish drying lotion, a
Mir space station model, multicolored hair butterflies, a hand-held
color television set with a TFT Active matrix screen and a Fisher
slim stereo.
</P>
<P>
   She didn't stop there. She wanted English Cheddar cheese, the
new Limp Bizkit album, a Thinkpad 240 computer, Emotion Potion, a
clear-brain yo-yo and Mega cargo pants from the Gap. The first item
on her list? The Cosmo magazine makeover software. These kids were
asking for it, and for a lot of it.
</P>
<P>
   Which seems, as it turns out, the general concept that much of
this trend hinges on.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kids from Generation Y are much more comfortable asking for
exactly what they want,'' explained Lou Weiss, a founder of
Wishbox.com, a site that specifically targets the ages 10 to 20
demographic (and heavily promotes charity donations). ``They are
meant as a place where you can put something in that you might not
otherwise have the guts to ask for.''
</P>
<P>
   Emily Birnbaum, a chirpy fifth-grader at the Dalton School in
New York, confirmed this theory. ``I feel OK asking for more in my
Wishbox because that way I don't have to really ask and get an
answer,'' she said. ``My mommy and daddy can just look in there and
know, and they don't have to say `no' to my face. I don't think
there is anything I wouldn't feel comfortable asking for.''
</P>
<P>
   By the way, Emily would like, among other things, some ``Polar
tech feety pajamas'' (read: pajamas with feet) and ``for Daddy to
set up the Nintendo.''
</P>
<P>
   Kind of cute, no? There's another twist.
</P>
<P>
   ``This other weird thing goes on,'' Weiss said. ``Parents are
warning their kids not to have a lot of things in their Wishbox
because they think it will make them look greedy.''
</P>
<P>
   So, if I am getting the gist of this correctly, you can ask for
a lot, just as long as you do it under a pseudonym. Mindy Birnbaum,
Emily's mother, considers the need for anonymity more of a safety
issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``Parents don't want their kids using their real names. It's too
much exposure,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Not a bad point, when you note the teasers written by the sites
on these sites, for example: ``So you want to peek in someone
else's Wishbox? Why not? It's fun...it's even legal.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, I made the leap. I embraced my inner brat and got myself a
Wishbox, filled it with some fairly by-the-book items (``a CD
player that won't skip when I run,'' ``a Polaroid I-Zone sticker
camera.'')
</P>
<P>
   Then, I decided to go to town. I asked to have six calla lilies
delivered to my house once a month (I almost asked for them
weekly). I commanded a Vespa, an antique pocket watch, ``free reign
at Agnes B.'' And anything else over the top I could come up with.
</P>
<P>
   Web-site address in hand, I went to Thanksgiving dinner, where
much of the wish-list bartering goes down in my family.
</P>
<P>
   I announced to the table that I had gotten myself a Wishbox
online, and if anyone had any questions about what to get me for
the holidays, they could just check www.getthere.com. There was a
moment of silence and some clinking of forks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It saves trees?'' asked one guest.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I don't know how to use my computer,'' my mother
protested.
</P>
<P>
   Uncle Rodger, perched at the head of the table, was quite taken
with the concept. ``It's simple,'' he said. ``It makes the whole
thing really easy.''
</P>
<P>
   My mother persisted. ``It certainly takes the romance out of
Christmas,'' she said as she pushed her sweet potatoes around her
plate. She mulled the concept a bit further and piped up: ``I guess
it's a good idea, because every year I ask you and your sister what
you want and you both are always like, `I don't know.' I find that
frustrating.''
</P>
<P>
   She smiled. ``In any event, it certainly is a good excuse to not
have to talk to your mother,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe these sites really do understand their customer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
