 (Attn: Britain, France)  
 A NIGHT OUT WITH STELLA McCARTNEY   By ELIZABETH HAYT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ On the dark streets of the meatpacking district, a
fleet of town cars were parked three deep in front of Pastis, Keith
McNally's hopping new bistro. With all eyes on the famous faces of
Minnie Driver and Puff Daddy, no eyebrows were raised by Stella
McCartney's entrance on a recent Saturday night. Slipping into a
corner banquette in the back, Ms. McCartney, 28, the designer for
Chloe, seemed unimpressed by the marquee crowd.
</P>
<P>
   ``This isn't that inspirational to me,'' she said, smoking a
cigarette and chewing gum at the same time. ``I'm not famous, but I
know a lot of famous people because of my upbringing.''
</P>
<P>
   The daughter of Paul and Linda McCartney may not elicit the same
stares and elbow nudges as the stars who grace the covers of In
Style magazine. But as far as those stars are concerned, she is one
of them. As Jerry Seinfeld was escorted to a nearby table, he
recognized Ms. McCartney and offered a familiar, ``How ya doin'?''
Charlie Rose and Amanda Burden took their places at the banquette
alongside Ms. McCartney. ``How long will you be in town for?'' Rose
asked.
</P>
<P>
   The designer, who divides her time between London and Paris, was
visiting for the VH1/Vogue fashion awards and the Costume
Institute's gala at the Metropolitan Museum of Art and to rummage
in vintage clothing shops for inspiration for her next collection.
</P>
<P>
   Shrugging off her jacket _ a used denim embellished with
rhinestones and a Black Sabbath logo found in the East Village
earlier in the day _ Ms. McCartney unwound a colorful wool crochet
scarf from her neck. It looked like something her grandmother might
have crocheted but was in fact designed by Ms. McCartney for
Chloe's fall 1999 collection. Underneath, she wore a black
strapless jump suit with jet black beads, also her design. The
entire outfit, along with her unstyled hair, had a thrown-together
feeling, an eclectic mix of glamour and grunge.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have never believed in the philosophy of the outfit,'' Ms.
McCartney said. ``I have always believed in one beautiful piece,
and then you build around it with, let's say, something
secondhand.''
</P>
<P>
   Rose's unbuttoned shirt cuffs caught Ms. McCartney's eye. ``I
like that,'' she whispered. ``It proves he's either too lazy or
he's got vibe.''
</P>
<P>
   She was picking at a plate of potatoes and carrots. Ms.
McCartney is a vegetarian, as her mother was. Calvin Klein, whose
sleek, minimal aesthetic couldn't be more different from the
frilly, vintage-inspired Chloe look, worked his way to the back of
the restaurant. ``You are doing such creative things!'' Klein said.
``Look at you!'' he added, admiring the granny scarf. ``Who
wouldn't want to look like you!''
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, when Ms. McCartney was just 25, the Vendome Group,
Chloe's parent company, named her to succeed Karl Lagerfeld at the
venerable French label. Her legendary last name, coupled with her
inexperience, raised doubts that talent was the reason she was
offered such a plum job.
</P>
<P>
   As a student in London at Central St. Martin's College of Art
and Design, where she studied fashion, Ms. McCartney had enlisted
her supermodel pals, Kate Moss and Naomi Campbell, to model her
1995 graduation collection. Her parents applauded from the front
row. The hype made it easy to dismiss her as a
spoiled-little-rich-girl.
</P>
<P>
   In retrospect, that student collection, which Ms. McCartney
sewed in her garage in Notting Hill, foreshadowed the style that
has made Chloe hot again, especially with younger women. Customers
have snapped up her sexy dresses and tops adorned with antique
buttons and lace. The feminine touches are in step with today's
antiminimalist moment. The rumor du jour in fashion is that Ms.
McCartney's rapid rise will be capped by her appointment to take
over from Tom Ford as Gucci's designer. With Gucci's recent
acquisition of Yves Saint Laurent, the speculation has been that
Ford will be elevated to creative director overseeing both houses,
leaving the Gucci post open.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. McCartney refused to comment directly, confirming only that
she and Ford had discussed the matter, after first meeting at a
party given by Madonna several months ago. ``Don't you think I want
to tell the whole world the job offers I've had?'' she said. ``But
I can't. It's unprofessional.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Tom's a Virgo,'' she added. ``I'm a Virgo. And we both drink
vodka.''
</P>
<P>
   In the ladies room at Pastis, Ms. McCartney disapprovingly eyed
a reporter dressed in a Chloe gray herringbone skirt with a ruffled
hem. The designer was unhappy that the skirt didn't fit as snugly
as she had shown it on the runway, and she grabbed a handful of
fabric at the seat. ``This is a woman's best part,'' she
instructed. ``A skirt has to scoop under the booty.''
</P>
<P>
   By 10:30, she was ready to make a break for her town car waiting
outside the restaurant, declaring she wanted to make a quick stop
at Double Happiness, a basement bar in Chinatown, to meet a friend.
</P>
<P>
   The friend turned out to be the actress Liv Tyler. ``You're
wearing a good T-shirt,'' Ms. McCartney said, snuggling up to the
actress, who flaunted her Chloe top emblazoned with a gold Playboy
bunny. Marveling at Ms. Tyler's kooky ensemble _ which included
fuzzy red earmuffs, a red beaded choker, a long red skirt over a
pair of khaki jeans and black Jack Purcell sneakers _ Ms. McCartney
said, ``She has great style!''
</P>
<P>
   At nearly 11 o'clock, Ms. McCartney was joined by a childhood
friend with no star pedigree: Hope Webster, who works in
communications at Estee Lauder, and her husband, Rob Robles, a
musician. Everyone piled into the car and, sounding like a female
Austin Powers, Ms. McCartney prodded the driver, ``Put the pedal to
the metal, baby!'' They headed to Rockefeller Center to take in a
performance of ``Saturday Night Live,'' which was to have Christina
Ricci as the host.
</P>
<P>
   En route, Ms. McCartney accepted a Jolly Rancher candy from Ms.
Webster and spit her gum out the window. ``Spitting gum out the
window is a good feeling,'' she said. ``It's just like sneezing.''
</P>
<P>
   At Studio 8H in the GE Building at Rockefeller Plaza, where
``Saturday Night Live'' is broadcast, Ms. McCartney and her
entourage were escorted through various smoke-filled rooms, where
dozens of VIPs lounged, drank and watched the show on television.
Ms. McCartney took a few minutes to flirt with Chevy Chase.
``You're looking very dashing,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. McCartney spent most of the evening at the side of Lorne
Michaels, the show's producer. But when Beck, the musical guest
that night, performed, she dashed to join the audience. ``He's
fly,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   It was nearly 2 a.m. when Ms. McCartney left the set to head
back downtown for the ritual afterparty. As she was leaving the
building, a photographer snapped her picture. The usual swarm of
fans outside the show descended upon her, asking for autographs,
pictures, assuming she was famous even if they weren't quite sure
how.
</P>
</TEXT>
