<HEADLINE>
THE HOLLY, THE IVY, AND A TOOL TO TRIM THEM 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sun., Dec. 12) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(jt) 
 By ANNE RAVER    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   A good garden tool doesn't strain the body. It does the job
right. It is easy to clean and sharpen. It endures, even improves
with age. Such a tool engenders loyalty, not as fierce as the love
of a dog but about as close as an inanimate object can get.
</P>
<P>
   So if you are thinking of giving a tool as a holiday gift,
choose a high-quality one _ with the return slip in case it doesn't
suit the person's hand or height, is too heavy or too light. Like
all tools, pruning shears are intensely personal items.
</P>
<P>
   ``For my hands, I like the No. 2 Felcos,'' said Mike Ruggiero, a
senior curator of the New York Botanical Garden. ``They're flexible
and they give a nice sharp cut for the rose canes. The rotating
ones slip in my hand.''
</P>
<P>
   I swear by Felco No. 7, with the rotating handle, which eases
the twinges in my wrist.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since I prune about 2,000 roses in the spring, I like to start
the year with a new blade,'' Ruggiero said. ``But I don't throw the
old one away; I use it on dead wood, which can nick any blade.''
</P>
<P>
   When the blades get dull, sharpen them on the bevel side, using
a stone and a bit of oil. ``But don't use motor oil, which is toxic
to plants,'' Ruggiero said. ``I use olive oil. But it doesn't have
to be extra virgin.'' I found Felco No. 2, for $39, and Felco No.
7, for $56, in the Smith &AMP; Hawken catalog: (800) 776-3336 or
www.smith-hawken.com
</P>
<P>
   As for pruning knives, Wayne Cahilly, a venerable pruner at the
botanical garden, has an old Victorinox, with a rosewood handle and
a slightly curved three-inch blade. ``It has a bit of a reverse
curve to the handle and fits your hand nicely,'' he said. ``I like
a wooden handle, because you can take sandpaper and make it fit
your hand, so you don't get blisters.''
</P>
<P>
   The blade should be high-carbon steel, not stainless steel,
which doesn't hold an edge. Victorinox knives, for $22, are sold by
A.M. Leonard, which has great tools; (800) 543-8955 or
www.amleo.com.
</P>
<P>
   As for saws, I'm partial to my Japanese pruning saw, which has
an eight-inch blade that slips into a slim oak carrying case that
attaches to my belt. The curved handle fits nicely in my hand.
Smith &AMP; Hawken sells it for $26.
</P>
<P>
   Cahilly prefers the folding Felco saw, with a six-inch blade,
that is 14 inches long when open and only 8 inches when closed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has a nice locking mechanism that doesn't come loose,'' he
said. ``And everything is replaceable.''
</P>
<P>
   The diamond-shaped tooth design, excellent for cutting, makes it
difficult to sharpen, so when the blade gets dull, he just throws
it away and buys a new one, for about $12. Stillbrook Horticultural
Supplies sells the saw for $20; (800) 414-4468.
</P>
<P>
   As for loppers, Felco and Sandvik are old standbys. And I'm
intrigued by a pair of loppers made by Fiskars, which has a gear
design that increases leverage and reduces stress, as well as
lightweight aluminum handles (about $30 at retail centers); for
information, (800) 500-4849 or www.fiskars.com.
</P>
<P>
   Stanley Tools sells lightweight hedge shears with cushion grips
and high-carbon steel blades, and other ergonomically designed
tools, though I can't attest to how they wear; for information,
(800) 782-6539 or www.stanleytools.com.
</P>
<P>
   And spades? Ruggiero has two, one 30 years old, the other 15,
and he keeps them razor-sharp.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have stainless steel blades, which don't pit or rust,''
he said. ``I sharpen them with a file, just the bevel side. You
don't have to use oil with stainless, but I do because it keeps
them clean.''
</P>
<P>
   My favorite spade is an English-made Bulldog forged-steel spade
with a 44-inch D-handle, which is now $49. It's four inches longer
than the regular model and easier on my back. You have to try on
your spade. Seeds of Change sells it; (800) 762-7333 or
www.seedsofchange.com.
</P>
<P>
   Ames makes good spades, too, especially the Iowa Pattern, which
has a slightly tapering 11-inch blade and weighs about five pounds.
It sells for $53 at A.M. Leonard.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't want a handle socket that's been wrapped around the
handle,'' Cahilly said. ``When you pull back on it, you're pulling
against the weak spot.'' So look for a handle that's one piece of
steel _ or a half-strap spade, which has a handle strap that's part
of the blade. It comes up the front and back and is riveted through
the handle.
</P>
<P>
   As for trowels, Ruggiero treasures his $30 Wilkinson's stainless
steel trowel with the wooden handle. ``The blade is one piece
that's welded into the handle,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   I love my Ho-Mi tool, a curved hand digger that can weed, plow
or scare burglars. The label says Ho-mi means ``little ground
spear'' in Korean, and it feels like one. Available at Womanswork,
for $18; www.womanswork.com or (800) 639-2709.
</P>
<P>
   You won't find most of these tools in the average hardware
store, so order the catalogs or look up the Web sites, and choose
carefully.
</P>
</TEXT>
