<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-10 17:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5389 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l BC-MRSCLINTON-GALA-$ADV1     12-10 0916
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MRSCLINTON-GALA-$ADV12-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OVERDRESSED FOR OVERKILL: VIVE LA FRANCE! 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, DEC. 12) 
(af) 
 By CATHY HORYN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ What with all the white-gloved waiters, the caviar,
the lobster and truffled veal for 650 guests, the cases of Chateau
Cheval Blanc (at $135 a bottle), and last, but by no means least,
all the women decked out in haute couture feathers and silk,
Wednesday night's gala to open the new LVMH Tower in Manhattan was
certainly a French affair.
</P>
<P>
   Dinner was served across the street in the atrium of the IBM
Building, which was big enough to hold it. The musicians in the
orchestra, who kept flailing away despite the poor acoustics, also
lent a distinctly French note of surrealism to the evening.
</P>
<P>
   ``I mean, you can see them, but you can't hear them,'' Kenneth
Jay Lane, the fake-jewelry king, said. ``It's very French, a rather
nice antidote to rock and roll,'' he added, alluding to the week's
other big gala, the rollicking Costume Institute party at the
Metropolitan Museum of Art.
</P>
<P>
   It was debatable just how many billionaires were at the gala,
which was a benefit for the Municipal Art Society of New York, a
preservation group whose patrons _ Anne Bass, Veronica Hearst,
Cecile Zilkha and Marie-Josee Kravis, among others _ are hardly
what anyone would call slouches. Bernard Arnault, the chairman of
LVMH Moet Hennessy Louis Vuitton, the luxury conglomerate, which
owns Christian Dior, Celine and a lot of wine and spirits brands,
as well as the auction house Phillips, sat between Mrs. Bass and
Mrs. Hearst. John Richardson, the writer and Picasso biographer,
was also at the main table, and so was Henry Kravis, the financier.
</P>
<P>
   Helene Arnault, the chairman's wife, who was wearing a black
Dior dress with leather straps, did her best at her table to
entertain Gwyneth Paltrow, who arrived in a clingy, plum-color Dior
slip dress, which matched her lipstick; the designer John Galliano;
and Judy Taubman, a chairwoman of the evening, who wore an Yves
Saint Laurent dress with a diamond broach.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we have one billionaire at our table,'' Lane
said, not sounding the least bit sulky. ``But we've had fun.'' His
dinner partners were Deeda Blair, the Washington couture stalwart
and fund-raiser, and Aileen Mehle, the gossip columnist. The
novelist and Vanity Fair writer Dominick Dunne was at their table,
too.
</P>
<P>
   If the Costume Institute party was about looseness and rap stars
with half-moon slivers of dollar bills lacquered on their
fingernails, the LVMH gala was about grandeur. And the French know
how to pile it on.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the claret and Champagne, which mostly came from
Arnault's vineyards, all the embroidered table linen was brought
from France, and so were the 5,000 meters of white fabric used by
the building's architect, Christian de Portzamparc, to drape the
walls of the dinner area. De Portzamparc also staged a light show,
involving, among other things, images of the French and American
flags fluttering on the LVMH Tower and a parachuting dress with a
60-foot train.
</P>
<P>
   But with so much else going on, the rich food, couture dresses
that cost $50,000 and then some, not to leave out an appearance by
Hillary Rodham Clinton, well, it seemed a case of exquisite
overkill.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton, wearing a black pantsuit, arrived shortly after 7
p.m. and stayed for about an hour before going on to another
engagement at the Plaza. Ms. and Mrs. Arnault held a private
cocktail reception for her, with about 50 VIPs, nearly all of whom,
in surreal contrast to Mrs. Clinton, were sensationally attired in
haute couture. Mrs. Hearst's Dior gown resembled a filigree of red
cobwebs on a nude lining. ``It feels like nothing,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The couture-clad Ms. Paltrow entered the reception looking as if
she were desperately trying to dislodge a caramel or something from
her teeth and then glowed as she greeted Mrs. Clinton and the
Arnaults.
</P>
<P>
   Brooke Astor was the ever-unflappable Mrs. Astor. She had on a
long white silk suit, many emeralds at her throat and ears and
white kid gloves. The crowd seemed to part when she entered, and
Mrs. Clinton stepped forward to greet her.
</P>
<P>
   Across the room, Suzy Menkes of The International Herald Tribune
fell into a discussion with Mouna Ayoub, probably the world's most
acquisitive couture client, about her latest jewels.
</P>
<P>
   ``I sold $26 million worth of jewelry, and I bought $10
million,'' Ms. Ayoub explained in her straightforward manner. ``I
wanted something younger.''
</P>
<P>
   From a social point of view, the night was certainly a success
for Arnault.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's fun,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He scored even more points at dinner when, sensing the acoustics
problem, he stuffed into his pocket the two-page speech he had
planned to give and spoke briefly off the cuff.
</P>
<P>
   Harvey Keitel heard Arnault while sitting at Marc Jacobs' table.
It wasn't clear what the tough-guy actor's connection was to the
glamorous evening, but he seemed to be enjoying himself. He took
out a cigar and was lighting it as the model Giselle was brought
over to meet him.
</P>
<P>
   Someone remarked that he seemed to be the kind of guy who never
let a good cigar wait for a beautiful woman, and he laughed.
</P>
<P>
   ``You got that right,'' he said. Then he looked up at the
towering Giselle.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
