<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-DEBATE- </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IOWA DEBATE MAY PROVE CRUCIAL TO BUSH 
</HEADLINE>
 ADV12-HNS  
 (For release Sunday, Dec. 12)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 (News analysis)  
 By DAN FREEDMAN  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Texas Gov. George W. Bush, a little less sure of
his front-runner status in the Republican presidential field after
two debates with his challengers, needs a solid showing _ maybe
even a clear victory _ in the final debate of the year Monday night
in Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   The debate at the Des Moines Civic Center before an expected
2,400 Republicans will be televised on local stations in Iowa and
nationally on the MSNBC cable channel. It gives Bush yet another
forum to battle a question that has bedeviled his campaign lately:
Does he have what it takes to be a world leader or is he an ``empty
suit,'' as late-night TV comics Jay Leno and David Letterman have
suggested?
</P>
<P>
   ``Bush has to prove he's as good as his (poll and campaign
contribution) numbers tell us he is,'' says Charles O. Jones, a
political scientist who recently retired from the University of
Wisconsin. ``He has to show he lives up to what those numbers
represent.''
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, Bush's greatest challenge may be the numbers rather
than any individual GOP opponent. Whit Ayres, an Atlanta-based
Republican pollster unaffiliated with any candidate, says, ``The
only damage (Bush sustained in the two prior debates) is the
comparison to sky-high expectations. I'm not sure anybody could
have met such expectations.''
</P>
<P>
   With more than $60 million in the bank and the lead in most
national polls, Bush has been the front-runner and presumptive GOP
nominee since well before declaring his candidacy this summer.
</P>
<P>
   But lately he has seen a surge in New Hampshire of his closest
rival, Sen. Charles McCain, R-Ariz., plus a rising chorus of
questions about his own intellect.
</P>
<P>
   After the first Republican presidential debate Dec. 2 in
Manchester, N.H. and a second in Phoenix, Ariz. on Dec. 6, Bush is
dead-even with McCain or behind him in several polls in New
Hampshire, which holds the nation's first primary on Feb. 1.
</P>
<P>
   The importance of New Hampshire is open to a debate of its own.
</P>
<P>
   Bush is way ahead in Iowa, which holds its caucuses Jan. 24, and
McCain is bypassing that state altogether. Bush is well-organized
in larger states such as California and New York, which are among
the 16 states holding primaries on March 7, ``Super Tuesday.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, because its primary is the traditional starting gate for
presidential candidates, New Hampshire maintains an aura of
importance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we have the earmarks of a possible McCain landslide in
New Hampshire,'' says pollster John Zogby, whose latest poll in the
state reflects the impact of the Dec. 2 debate there. Asked who won
the debate, 30 percent said McCain and 16 percent said Bush. Asked
whose performance impressed them, 79 percent said McCain and 44
said Bush.
</P>
<P>
   In the New Hampshire debate, Bush defanged his most ardent
attacker, publisher Steve Forbes, by serving up a Forbes magazine
column from 1977 in which he suggested a rise in the Social
Security retirement age of 65 might be the only way to save the
beleaguered system.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes had just begun airing commercials accusing Bush of a
``betrayal'' for saying he would consider a rise in the retirement
age to shore up Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   To demonstrate intellectual heft, Bush said he was reading a
biography of Dean Acheson, an architect of U.S. Cold War policy as
secretary of state under President Truman.
</P>
<P>
   In Phoenix, Bush raised some eyebrows on the intellect question
when he was asked what lessons he drew from reading the Acheson
biography. His response in large measure was lifted from his
foreign policy speech: ``Our nation's greatest export to the world
has been, is and always will be the incredible freedoms we
understand in America.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain, a retired Navy flier and former POW in Vietnam, offered
his own unscripted comments about Acheson a little later and won
praise from several pundits. Post-debate commentary compared the
two responses in ways that were unflattering to Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Wayne Fields, director of the American studies program at
Washington University in St. Louis and author of a 1996 book,
``Union of Words: A History of Presidential Eloquence,'' said he
doubts Bush is the kind of candidate who can ever thrive amid the
verbal jousting of a debate.
</P>
<P>
   ``The emphasis is on glibness, and he's the target of everyone
else,'' Fields said. ``What he needs is a one-on-one with a major
television interviewer, where he can sustain a discussion for some
time.''
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts discount the idea that Bush is in any danger. As
the front-runner, they say, he needs more to avoid a devastating
gaffe than to win a clear victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``Others with little to lose can go for the grand slam every
time they step to the plate,'' said Stephen Hess, a senior fellow
at the Brookings Institution, a think tank here. ``Bush can afford
to strike out a few times and not lose anything.''
</P>
<P>
   (Dan Freedman can be reached at 202-298-6920 or by e-mail at
dan &LR; hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
