<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-10 17:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5392 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k BC-BARLOW-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      12-10 0778
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BARLOW-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONGRESS EXPECTS AMTRAK ON TRACK 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JIM BARLOW 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Amtrak, the government-owned rail passenger service, has a
drop-dead date in 2002.
</P>
<P>
   That's when the system is required by Congress to meet its
operational costs. That doesn't mean Amtrak would have the same
burden as your business or mine.
</P>
<P>
   The federal government would still pay for Amtrak's capital
costs _ locomotives, cars and all the other physical objects it
needs to operate. Amtrak will be allowed to survive, according to
Congress, if it can simply take in enough revenues to pay its
operating costs _ fuel, rail rental, salaries, maintenance and the
like.
</P>
<P>
   Amtrak has made substantial progress toward that goal, says the
General Accounting Office _ the nonpartisan investigative and
accounting office that audits government entities. But there's no
assurance that it's going to actually make that goal.
</P>
<P>
   Since Amtrak took over intercity rail passenger service from the
private railroads in 1971, taxpayers have picked up $23 billion of
its costs.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1999 federal fiscal year that just ended, Amtrak's net
loss was $907 million _ $23 million less than projected and down
from $930 million the year before. That $930 million was, however,
the highest operating net loss in 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
EXPRESS TRAIN COULD HELP _ FAST &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In order to meet the 2002 deadline, in the next two years it
must cut costs five times as much as it has done in the prior four
years, the GAO reports. And part of the savings looks awfully
suspect. For example, the rail corporation says it plans to save
$160 million a year in productivity gains and other reforms that
will be explained at a later date.
</P>
<P>
   The rail passenger corporation says it can meet its goals
primarily by increasing revenues. It has two main programs to do
just that.
</P>
<P>
   The first is a series of high-speed trains that Amtrak is
calling Acela Express. The trains, capable of reaching 150 mph, are
due to start first on the Washington, D.C.-New York-Boston route.
Other Acela routes are planned south from Washington to Virginia,
North and South Carolina and Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   Additionally, high-speed routes are planned between California
cities and Las Vegas and a nine-state hub and spoke train system in
the Midwest centered on Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Amtrak believes these routes will pull people from airplanes
since _ adding in the time it takes to go to and from airports and
mandatory airline check-in time _ they will take less time than
flying.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, the hyped Acela service, due to start in December
on the East Coast, has been pushed back to next spring. Tests of
the train found excessive wheel wear. Amtrak won't be able to use
the trains until that problem is solved.
</P>
<P>
   The rail company also is counting on increased revenues from
attaching freight cars to its passenger trains to haul high-value
goods, such as fresh fruit and flowers.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
DEADLINE MAY BE PUSHED BACK &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But to enter that kind of freight business, Amtrak is going to
have to buy specialized equipment that has yet to be tested in the
marketplace, the GAO says. Even if the system works, the GAO adds,
Amtrak is going to have trouble finding the money to buy that
equipment. Congress has given Amtrak $1.6 billion for equipment in
the next three years. But Amtrak has already announced it will wind
up using $1 billion of that money for routine maintenance.
</P>
<P>
   So what's going to happen if Amtrak doesn't reach break-even by
the deadline? The best answer comes from a recent hearing before
the U.S. House ground transportation subcommittee. After hearing
the gloomy report from the GAO about Amtrak's finances, much of the
questioning of Amtrak representatives was along the lines of how
soon could the rail corporation start running trains in their
congressional districts.
</P>
<P>
   If Amtrak doesn't meet its deadline, then in all probability new
deadlines will be set.
</P>
<P>
   What Congress doesn't want to face is that none of the 42
national rail services worldwide breaks even. All are subsidized by
their governments.
</P>
<P>
   The private railroads couldn't compete head-to-head with the
airlines for passengers and not lose money. Neither can a
government rail corporation.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, airports and air traffic control systems also receive
money from taxes. But there is a great difference. The air system's
subsidy comes overwhelmingly from taxes paid by airline passengers
and on aviation fuel. Amtrak's subsidy comes out of the general
fund _ primarily made up of income taxes paid by individual
taxpayers.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
