<DOCNO> NYT19991210.0183 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-10 17:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5395 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u f BC-COMPUTER-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      12-10 1339
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTER-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRAGGING BRAGGING RIGHTS GO TO QUAKE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DWIGHT SILVERMAN 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Fans of the Death Match _ and we're talking computer games here,
not professional wrestling _ are in heaven this Christmas season.
They've got not one, but two highly anticipated titles that focus
on multiplayer mayhem: id Software's Quake III Arena and Epic
Games' Unreal Tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the fact that there are two also means that the
hard-core gaming community, which can be more partisan than
Republicans and Democrats, now has something new to argue about.
Which is the better game?
</P>
<P>
   This seems to happen every year that id puts out a title in its
vaunted Quake franchise, generally considered the pinnacle of the
3-D, first-person shooter genre. In 1996, the challenger to the
original Quake was Duke Nukem 3D. And in 1998, it was Quake II vs.
the original Unreal.
</P>
<P>
   Both of these new games have the goal of bringing new blood _ so
to speak _ into the ranks of death-match players. In a death-match
game, combatants hunt each other down in surreal environments using
over-the-top weapons, trying to score the most kills, or frags, and
avoid being fragged themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, these games are violent, and yes, they're politically
incorrect. But they're also a lot of fun.
</P>
<P>
   Quake III Arena and Unreal Tournament are similar. Each has a
single-player component that uses computer-generated enemies _
called bots _ to simulate an online competition between human
players. This gives newcomers to the genre a chance to get used to
its conventions and develop some skills before hopping online and
taking on the real thing.
</P>
<P>
   Both games also make it easier to find free Internet servers on
which to play, considered crucial if online gaming _ regardless of
the type of game _ is to grow. In the past, it's been frustratingly
difficult for novices to figure out how to get into a contest.
</P>
<P>
   The argument over which game is better has been playing out for
weeks in chat rooms and Internet discussion forums since the games
were released. It's time to add my voice to the cacophony.
</P>
<P>
   _ Graphics: Advantage, Quake III. If you've got a powerful
enough graphics card, nothing will prepare you for the visual
beauty of Quake III. The artists and 3-D modelers at id Software
have done an astounding job, creating worlds that will make your
jaw drop. In fact, the game is so beautiful, you're tempted to quit
fighting and just wander around, gawking. That, of course, would be
a fatal mistake.
</P>
<P>
   John Carmack, the genius programmer at id who creates the main
3-D software, or engine, for the company's titles has outdone
himself. Quake III Arena is filled with rich, organic textures that
pulse and throb. Gone are the dull reds, browns, yellows and greens
that characterized the past Quake games _ the levels here are
filled with color and detail. The engine allows for curved
surfaces, which make a remarkable difference in how realistic its
environments appear.
</P>
<P>
   Unreal Tournament, while also visually impressive, just doesn't
match up. It still looks like a Quake II-era game, boxy and static,
with relatively muted colors. Programmer Tim Sweeney has done some
interesting things with lighting and texture, but overall it pales
in comparison. Unreal Tournament does have one leg up on Quake III
_ it doesn't require as powerful a graphics card to look good.
</P>
<P>
   _ User-friendliness. Advantage, Unreal Tournament. In the past,
you've had to be a knowledgeable computer user to set up
first-person shooters. Although some configuration choices have
been available in menus, most of the ``good stuff'' has been hidden
in arcane commands you must type in manually at a hidden command
prompt known as the console.
</P>
<P>
   Unreal Tournament changes all that. It uses a slick,
Windows-style menu that lets you tweak almost every aspect
imaginable.
</P>
<P>
   While Quake III does have a much better interface than previous
games in the series, there are still dozens of commands that must
be entered via the console. Even worse, id doesn't document these
commands _ users are left to search for them on fan Web sites. If
the company isn't going to tie them to a menu, it should at least
include a detailed list in the box.
</P>
<P>
   _ Newbie-friendliness. Advantage, Unreal Tournament. Both games
are trying to appeal to two audiences: longtime fans of death
matches and novices. This is not easy to do, since what works for
one often frustrates the other. Unreal Tournament does a better job
of walking the line.
</P>
<P>
   Both games have an initial training area, but Unreal
Tournament's provides much more information, and in fact spreads it
out over four levels. It presumes the player knows nothing, even
explaining the term ``frag.''
</P>
<P>
   Also, I think id made a big error by forcing all players to use
what's known as freelook, in which mouse movement is used to look
around, as opposed to moving back and forth. This can be
disorienting for those who've never played a first-person, 3-D
game. In older Quake games, and in Unreal Tournament, you can turn
this off with a menu item, but in Quake III Arena it requires the
aforementioned, arcane console commands.
</P>
<P>
   _ Playability _ Advantage, Quake III. This is the category of
most dispute among fans of these games, but I have to come down
squarely on the side of Quake III Arena.
</P>
<P>
   I define playability as the feel of the game _ its smoothness,
3-D ease of movement and how well its worlds are designed. These
factors, combined with graphics, contribute to immersion _ whether
you can truly get lost in a game.
</P>
<P>
   Quake III's movement is silky, whether you're playing online or
in single-player mode, and its physics very realistic. Its 30
levels are smartly laid out and full of surprises. Although you
could fault the levels for sameness _ there are plenty of
castle-like mazes and platforms suspended in space _ they have
become id's signature. It's what players expect and want in a Quake
game.
</P>
<P>
   Although Unreal Tournament's 50 levels have more variety _
players compete in environments ranging from a ship at sea to an
asteroid _ they're difficult to navigate, and the game's overall
movement seems choppy and harder to control.
</P>
<P>
   _ Bots. Tie. In both games, you can adjust the skill level of
the computer-generated players. At the lowest level, the bots in
Quake III and Unreal Tournament are ridiculously bad opponents. As
you move up the skill ladder, they become tougher, and the top
level for both games is a serious challenge even for the best human
players. In fact, at the highest settings, the bots almost never
miss, making them less realistic.
</P>
<P>
   I think the bots in Quake III behave more realistically in
general death-match play, while the bots in Unreal Tournament
really shine when playing cooperative games, such as Capture the
Flag.
</P>
<P>
   _ Variety. Advantage, Unreal Tournament. While I'm more a fan of
simple free-for-all and one-on-one death-match games, I have to
hand it to Unreal Tournament in this category. Its developers have
included many kinds of game types, from the familiar Capture the
Flag to cooperative variants such as Assault and Domination.
Besides free-for-all and one-on-one, Quake III Arena only offers
team death-match and Capture the Flag. And for the latter, there
are only four levels included.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, I find myself favoring Quake III Arena just for its
sheer eye candy and smooth play. I like my death-match games simple
and uncomplicated, and Quake III is the ultimate death-match game.
However, Unreal Tournament may be a better choice for newcomers, or
for those who have grown weary of the simplicity of just shooting
everything that moves.
</P>
<P>
   You can try out both for free and decide for yourself. Both are
available in playable demo versions. Get Quake III Arena's demo for
Windows, Macintosh and Linux machines at www.quake3arena.com.
Unreal Tournament's Windows-only demo is at
www.unrealtournament.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
