A5396 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u f BC-COMPUTER-HELPLINE-HNS     12-10 0681
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTER-HELPLINE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GETTING ALL ICONS WHERE YOU WANT THEM IS POSSIBLE, BUT IT MIGHT
SLOW YOU DOWN 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DWIGHT SILVERMAN 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: I've managed to put all my icons on the Windows 98
toolbars/trays at the bottom of the screen except My Computer and
the Norton Recycle Bin. I've tried without success to remove them
from the wallpaper portion on the screen.
</P>
<P>
   A: It never fails to amaze me the lengths some folks will go to
get their desktops just the way they like them.
</P>
<P>
   I imagine your taskbar is quite cluttered with icons, something
I can't stand. My desktop is covered with icons, which you
obviously dislike. This is why they're called ``personal''
computers.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, I have bad news for you. Some icons have to stay
where they are, and those are two of them. However, there is a
virtual sleight-of-hand you can try if you're willing to put up
with a more sluggish machine.
</P>
<P>
   If you have Windows 98, or are running Internet Explorer 4.0 or
later on top of Windows 95, you can have the Windows desktop
displayed as a Web page. Among other things, this lets you use
HTML, the language in which Web pages are written, to display
useful things on your desktop.
</P>
<P>
   This is how some PC makers create some of the fancy desktop
effects often seen when you first bring home a computer from the
store.
</P>
<P>
   You can turn on the feature by right-clicking on the Windows
desktop and clicking on Active Desktop from the menu that appears.
Next, click ``View as Web page.''
</P>
<P>
   If you want to make your remaining desktop icons vanish, open
any folder, click View and then Folder Options. Click the View tab,
and scroll down to the Visual Settings category. You'll see ``Hide
icons when desktop is viewed as Web page.'' Check it, click Apply
and OK, and presto! Your remaining icons will vanish.
</P>
<P>
   However, so will the zippy performance of your computer. Viewing
the desktop as a Web page slows down your display, particularly if
you run at a high resolution _ say, 1,024-by-768 or above _ and
with a high color depth, such as 32-bit color.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I've just discovered the Usenet news groups, and I am really
hooked! There's a lot of junk in a lot of the groups I'm reading,
and someone suggested to me I can clean some of it out with my
``killfile.'' What is a killfile? I use Netscape Messenger to read
Usenet, and I don't see anything in the menus or in the Help file
that mentions anything about a killfile.
</P>
<P>
   A: A killfile is a term derived from Unix software used to read
Usenet groups in the early days of the Internet. Although most
modern-day Windows and Macintosh news group readers have the
ability to do what it does, few of them call it that.
</P>
<P>
   A killfile is basically a filter. When your news reader sorts
the messages in a Usenet group, the filter can hide messages you
don't want to see. When you're going through the list, trying to
pick out messages to read, you don't see messages that fit the
criteria in your filter.
</P>
<P>
   In Messenger, you can get to the filters through the Edit menu
item. In Outlook Express, look under Tools, then Message Rules,
then News.
</P>
<P>
   Why would you want to do this? You might not want to read the
posts of a particularly obnoxious individual _ and, unfortunately,
Usenet is full of 'em _ or you might want to try to filter out the
spam that clogs many of the groups. You could probably avoid half
the spam on Usenet by filtering for the phrase ``make money.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: Do you know of a program that can move a Windows 95
application from one drive letter to another, and make all the
necessary registry changes, etc.?
</P>
<P>
   A: Symantec's CleanSweep (originally developed by Quarterdeck)
has a transport option that will do this, but I've found it doesn't
always work as it should. It often misses a registry entry or two.
</P>
<P>
   If you have the original installation disks for the program, the
best thing to do is back up the data generated by the software,
uninstall it and then reinstall it on the new drive.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
