<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-10 17:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5408 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u f BC-WORKING-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      12-10 0769
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORKING-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOVE THE WORKERS? SAY IT WITH CASH 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By L.M. SIXEL 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Employees at the Tate Agency expected to spend Monday
afternoon coming up with a new design of the public relations
firm's sales brochure. After ordering lunch, they settled into the
conference room with their notepads and sharp pencils.
</P>
<P>
   Before anyone got too intent on strategizing, Judy Katrana, the
firm's president, announced the brainstorming story was just a ruse
and they were going to a mall for the next two hours. A limousine
was downstairs ready to whisk everyone away. And then Katrana
passed out $200 in cash to each employee with the directive: Spend
it on yourselves. No gifts for anyone else.
</P>
<P>
   The seven employees looked as surprised as if a naked man had
lept into the conference room.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wow!'' several stunned employees said.
</P>
<P>
   They tucked their new stash of $20s into their purses and
pockets and filed into the waiting limo, which was complete with
champagne. It was a bit like suddenly winning big on the hit TV
show ``Who Wants to be a Millionaire?''
</P>
<P>
   Many companies reward their employees for hard work at this time
of year. But some employers such as Katrana are going beyond the
traditional holiday party.
</P>
<P>
   Holiday parties are often stressful, Katrana said. Instead, she
wanted to be creative in the way she rewarded her hard-working
employees by getting them something that they normally wouldn't buy
for themselves.
</P>
<P>
   And it doesn't hurt that the employees feel special _ which
tends to happen when you're cruising through Houston in a stretch
limo drinking French champagne.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
A CHEAP LUNCH BEFORE THE SPREE &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   After a quick lunch at Chick-Fil-A _ after all, they were out of
the office to shop, not to eat _ the group fanned out to buy shoes,
leather jackets and a food processor.
</P>
<P>
   Catherine Wenske wasn't having any of that _ she was on the hunt
for major jewelry. She started at Tiffany's, Wenske's favorite
store, where she perused the mid-range jewelry collection. Nothing
struck her fancy, so she pulled out her cell phone and called her
friend _ an accountant with a fabulous jewelry collection _ and
asked where to look.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to find a totally lasting piece of jewelry, not just a
shirt or anything,'' she explained.
</P>
<P>
   Her friend suggested a jewelry line at Neiman-Marcus, so Wenske
was off in a flash.
</P>
<P>
   Except for a $595 necklace, nothing caught her eye, so Wenske
called another friend, who suggested a trip to Saks Fifth Avenue.
Forty-five minutes later, Wenske was agonizing again in front of
the jewelry counter at Saks.
</P>
<P>
   You'd be surprised how stressful _ and how hard _ it is to spend
$200 cash in two hours.
</P>
<P>
   With the money burning a hole in her pocket and with only 30
minutes remaining, Wenske chased back to Neimans and finally found
the ring she had been looking for: a blue topaz creation. Wenske
kicked in an extra $95 and it was hers.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
`BETTER THAN A TRADITIONAL PARTY' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The shopping extravaganza was a little easier for Darren K.
Craig, the only man in the group. After he discovered it would take
two weeks before he would receive a $195 stereo from the Sharper
Image (``I want instant gratification''), Craig went to J. Crew,
where he chose a suede jacket and wool sweater.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is much better than a traditional party,'' said Craig, as
he slipped on the jacket in the dressing room. ``Everybody has done
those,'' he said, ``so it makes sense to do something more
creative.''
</P>
<P>
   Lou Moore, manager of marketing, bought the Raymond Weil watch
she has had her eye on for quite some time. It cost more than
$1,000, so the $200 helped quite a bit. The remainder will come
from family gifts that she expects to receive this Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   Tina Boutros, operations manager at the Tate Agency, spent her
windfall on a $220 Emanuel Ungaro jacket and another $120 for
matching pants at Neimans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why buy odds and ends when I can make an investment?'' she
reasoned.
</P>
<P>
   The group collapsed in the white stretch limo, where there was
another bottle of champagne waiting.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is my first time in a limo,'' said account supervisor
Dottie Roark, who ran her hand across the leather upholstery.
</P>
<P>
   Boutros and the others modeled their new ensembles when the
group got back to the office. Everyone oohed and aahed as they
dived into a plate of Christmas cookies and showed off their
purchases.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thanks, Judy,'' they shouted. ``You're welcome, kids,'' said
the Santa in the business suit.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
