<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-10 18:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5426 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-ABOUT-CARS-FERRARI-2T     12-10 0911
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ABOUT-CARS-FERRARI-2TAKES-$ADV12-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
2000 FERRARI 36 MODENA: INSIDE, ROOM TO MOVE, (AND, YES, IT
MOVES)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, DEC. 12) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By DAN NEIL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   If there were a Nobel Prize for sports cars, the motor heads who
designed the Ferrari 360 Modena could start packing their bags for
Stockholm right now.
</P>
<P>
   Alas, there is no such award, despite the fact that the Modena _
named for the central Italian city where Enzo Ferrari, the
company's late founder, was born 101 years ago _ will spread
infinitely more joy around the world than the latest hermetic
dissertation on economics. After all, what teen-ager puts a poster
of Milton Friedman on the wall?
</P>
<P>
   Annually, only about 2,000 souls worldwide will be allowed to
pony up $150,000 to enjoy the Modena firsthand. That sounds like a
lot up to the moment you twist the aluminum key in the ignition.
The first contralto strains of the 395-horsepower engine set loose
butterflies in your stomach and you think, ``Ah, that's why it's so
expensive.''
</P>
<P>
   Running through the gears at full throttle, the Modena slams you
back like a great ocean wave, squeezes you breathless in corners
taken flat out, jams you against the shoulder belt with its mighty
brakes. Alighting passengers are reduced to dumbfounded utterances
like ``wow'' and ``awesome.''
</P>
<P>
   The Modena replaces the F355 as the company's midengine
V8-powered supercar, and it surpasses the F355 in all the
predictable ways. The Modena accelerates, brakes and corners harder
than the F355.It is even more savagely beautiful, more sullen and
sloe-eyed, menacing and concupiscent _ qualities the more
surprising if you consider that the styling was largely dictated by
the blind eye of aerodynamics.
</P>
<P>
   The 360 also advances the trend of user-friendliness established
by Ferrari's chairman, Luca Cordero di Montezemolo, in the last
decade. With a longer wheelbase and body, the 360 is much better
packaged than the F355. The cabin is larger, even spacious, with
excellent outward visibility _ the better to see yourself being
envied.
</P>
<P>
   Getting in and out is far easier than in the broad-silled F355.
The thickly padded steering wheel is adjustable for reach and rake;
the Connolly leather seats adjust to accommodate even Bill
Bradley-sized drivers. The controls and instruments are simple and
elegant, trimmed in brushed, anodized aluminum.
</P>
<P>
   Not only is there a generous trunk (in the nose), there is a
shelf behind the seats to accommodate the Connolly golf bag (a
$1,500 option). For a midengine car, this is the ergonomic
equivalent of the triple lutz.
</P>
<P>
   But the biggest improvement in functionality is the F-1 gearbox,
a $9,500 option. Introduced on the F355 three years ago and since
refined, it uses paddles mounted behind the steering wheel at the 6
and 9 o'clock positions to shift gears. To upshift, the driver tugs
on the right paddle; to downshift, on the left. There is no clutch.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Porsche's Tiptronic transmission (and its many
imitators), which is essentially an advanced automatic transmission
that can be shifted manually, the F-1 gearbox uses Ferrari's
standard six-speed synchromesh fitted with an electronic
gear-changing mechanism.
</P>
<P>
   To engage neutral, the driver pulls back on both paddles; a
luminescent ``N'' appears on the tachometer's gear selection
window. Under way, the paddles engage gears sequentially, the
crispness of the shift determined by the throttle position. Under
hard throttle, the car upshifts at the 8,500 rpm red line with a
sudden jarring BANG! _ which under certain conditions can upset the
balance of the car. For this reason, the paddles do not move with
the steering wheel, to discourage shifting in midcorner.
</P>
<P>
   In performance driving, the main advantage of the F-1 box is
that the driver can downshift quickly under hard braking, and the
car's central computer _ controlling the throttle with electronic
drive-by-wire technology _ will instantly match the engine speed
with the selected gear faster than the best drivers can. This
technology was perfected in Formula One racing, and Ferrari plans
to license it to unidentified American companies next year.
</P>
<P>
   For those not in the mood to shift gears, there is a fully
automatic mode, activated by a switch on the console; a T-shaped
switch nearby engages reverse.
</P>
<P>
   The suspension underneath consists of all-aluminum A-arms, hubs
and anti-roll bars. Keeping the wheels steady are aluminum shocks
and springs with an electronic damping control.
</P>
<P>
   The Ferrari knows when you are pitching it into a hard corner
and will stiffen the damping to reduce body roll. When you are
cruising in sixth gear on the interstate, it will automatically
relax the suspension for a smoother ride.
</P>
<P>
   The suspension has two settings: normal and sport, which is
stiffer; various other functions, like the degree of intervention
in the traction control and antilock brakes, also respond to the
choice of modes.
</P>
<P>
   Bucking the supercar trend, the Modena has relatively narrow
tires (215/45 ZR 18 in front, 275/40 ZR 18 in back). Smaller tires
improve driving quality _ great slabs of rubber tend to hunt along
every crack and crevice in the road and will cause a low-slung car
to hydroplane like a low-slung boat. Smaller tires also enhance
fuel economy _ still a profligate 14 miles per gallon in mixed
city-highway driving _ reduce aerodynamic resistance and hush road
noise.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   But in corners, smaller tires don't hang on quite as long as big
ones. To compensate, Ferrari again dipped into its bag of Formula
One racing tricks. The body shape of the Modena generates what is
known as down force. The bottom of the car is flat, like a Hot
Wheels car, with twin cavities at the rear channeling air that
would otherwise get trapped under the car, causing it to lift and
become unstable at speed.
</P>
<P>
   This is ground-effects technology straight out of racing. At
around 120 mph, the Modena's body shape generates 400 pounds of
down force, clamping the car to the track with an invisible
aerodynamic hand.
</P>
<P>
   The Ferrari's steering is laser sharp and telepathically quick.
If you can think your way through a hairpin, the Modena will stay
with you like Deion Sanders covering a deep pass. When the limits
of tire adhesion are finally reached, the car gives up traction
with gently progressive oversteer, rotating the rear toward the
outside of the turn. The Modena dashes from zero to 60 in just 4.3
seconds, and is a very safe car to drive hard.
</P>
<P>
   It may also be the quickest-stopping road car on the market: the
nearly 12-inch Brembo disc brakes bring the Modena to a chattering
stop in an incredible 110 feet from 60 miles an hour, according to
Road and Track magazine.
</P>
<P>
   For that, you can credit the car's fairly light weight, around
3,000 pounds. The porpoise-tight skin of the Ferrari is fashioned
out of aluminum. The chassis, a high-tech confection of extruded
and welded aluminum beams and cast aluminum joints, is light and
enormously stiff _ no rattles or squeaks and no untoward shaking of
body parts when you hit those forgotten railroad tracks at 70 mph.
This thing feels as if it were built by Boeing.
</P>
<P>
   The most important part of any Ferrari is the engine, and this
all-aluminum V8 is gloriously displayed under the broad rear
window. The engine bay is dominated by huge intake tubing connected
to two manifolds painted in the traditional red wrinkle finish.
</P>
<P>
   This 3.6-liter, 40-valve V8 reaches its peak horsepower at 8,500
rpm and 275 foot-pounds of torque at 4,750 rpm. Equipped with
variable valve timing and variable geometry intake _ all fairly
high-tech means to improve power and driveability _ the Ferrari
motor is tractable enough around town to satisfy a loafing Sunday
driver.
</P>
<P>
   While relatively mellow at lower rpm, when the valves open up
and the throttle throat clears, the Ferrari engine barks out a
spine-tingling song of naked force.
</P>
<P>
   Such are the joys of a six-figure sports car. Yet the 360's
greatest pleasure isn't limited to its owners or even to the
tifosi, the company's fans. Ferraris are important additions to the
visual world. Unlike ordinary cars, whose destiny lies in the
cubism of the car-crusher, Ferraris are perpetual, living to
advanced age in museums and collectors' garages. The 360's styling
is appropriately timeless, a lovely way to mark the end of the
Century of the Automobile. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   INSIDE TRACK: 21st-century Italian renaissance.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-10-99 1800EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
