<SLUG> BC-PANAMA-ALBRIGHT-475&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PANAMA SEES A COLD SHOULDER IN SHUFFLE OF U.S. DELEGATION 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By DAVID GONZALEZ    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PANAMA CITY, Panama _ With the symbolic hand-over of the Panama
Canal just days away, Panamanian officials were given a
disheartening preview of their rapidly changing relationship with
the United States when they learned that Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright would skip Tuesday's ceremony in order to attend
Mideast peace talks in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Panamanian officials were told Thursday of the change. U.S.
officials said the U.S. delegation will instead be headed by former
President Jimmy Carter, who signed the canal treaty with Panamanian
leader Gen. Omar Torrijos. He will be accompanied by some 40
others, including Secretary of Transportation Rodney Slater.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the end, are they going to send us a messenger from the
White House?'' said Roberto Eisenmann, an adviser to President
Mireya Moscoso. ``What a way to mess up something beautiful.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Albright was named the head of the U.S. delegation last
week, after President Clinton had said that scheduling conflicts
prevented him from attending the concluding acts of the 1977
treaties that gave Panama control over the canal and thousands of
acres of military bases. But the perception among many here and in
Washington was that the administration was loathe to revive
conservative resentment over the handover during the presidential
campaign next year.
</P>
<P>
   Although U.S. officials were trying to downplay any slight to
Panama, political leaders and commentators here were pained to see
their nation's most historic event be eclipsed by campaign worries
and more pressing foreign policy concerns.
</P>
<P>
   ``It shows that the United States has lowered their estimation
of us even more,'' said Ricardo Arias Calderon, a Christian
Democrat and former vice president in the administration of
Guillermo Endara. ``And it evidently reveals the low priority not
only of Panama, but Latin America. The special relationship between
Panama and the United States is disappearing.''
</P>
<P>
   The last-minute change was just the latest in a series of
delayed decisions surrounding the handover ceremonies. Panamanian
officials had moved the original date of the diplomatic ceremony
from December 31, when they will actually receive the canal, to
December 14 at the urging of U.S. officials who said that few
high-ranking officials would be able to attend because of
millennium parties and Y2K fears.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, despite Panamanian entreaties, Panama was not told until
last month that Clinton would be unable to attend. It was only last
week that Ms. Albright was officially named to lead the delegation,
triggering a scramble to make arrangements in keeping with
protocol. Throughout, the Panamanians accommodated a wearying
series of requests.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now this,'' said one person involved in planning the aborted
visit. ``This is going to leave a bad taste in everybody's mouth.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   While U.S. officials were said to have tried to make some
hurried replacements to the delegation Friday morning, they did not
have much success.
</P>
<P>
   ``No big names, no midlevel, nothing,'' said one person involved
in the planning. ``No rock stars. Madeleine Albright is the Bruce
Springsteen of foreign affairs. It looks like we're ending up with
Barry Manilow.''
</P>
<P>
   Some Panamanians have wondered whether or not the change of
plans was payback for their government's lack of progress in
reaching a security and intelligence sharing agreement with the
United States. Efforts last year to establish a multinational
counterintelligence center failed in the wake of Panamanian
opposition to keeping U.S. troops on their soil.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Pastor, a political scientist at Emory University, who
was unsuccessfully nominated as ambassador to Panama by Clinton,
said the handling of recent events was typical of the
administration's failure to forge new partnerships in Latin
America.
</P>
<P>
   And Miguel Antonio Bernal, a political scientist, said of
Washington, ``Their attitude is absurd. Fine. Until the 31st of
December, they are the boss. But after that, no.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-10-99 1802EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991210.0195 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-10 18:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5430 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-HARRY-SHEARER-INTERVI     12-10 0760
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HARRY-SHEARER-INTERVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WAY MORE THAN MR. BURNS
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: For release Saturday, Dec. 11. Fact box at bottom.) 
By FRED SHUSTER 
c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Harry Shearer _ actor, radio host, political commentator _ may
be a little bit of everywhere these days but one place he won't be
on New Year's Eve is out on the town.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel about the millennium the way I do about New Year's Eve
generally _ it's a holiday for civilians,'' he said. ``Like most
people in show business, if I'm not working that night, I'll be
home. In this case, entertaining my in-laws.''
</P>
<P>
   You may not immediately recognize the name, but you will the
voice and maybe the face. Shearer, you see, is one of those
ubiquitous talents who gets around.
</P>
<P>
   Creator and star of the seminal fake rockumentary ``This Is
Spinal Tap,'' Shearer voices Mr. Burns and 19 other characters on
TV's ``The Simpsons,'' hosts public radio's weekly ``Le Show'' and
has appeared in such feature films as ``Godzilla,'' ``The Truman
Show,'' ``edTV'' and ``The Right Stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   How does he find the time?
</P>
<P>
   ``I wonder that myself sometimes,'' he says. ``It's a pretty
full week. But with the radio show, I've always believed I could do
it way into the future, as long as I can make room for it in the
rest of my career.''
</P>
<P>
   A former writer and cast member on ``Saturday Night Live,''
Shearer unbuckles the Beltway in ``It's the Stupidity, Stupid''
(Random House; $16.95), a shrewd look at the Clinton administration
and why it has inspired such fervent hatred in some quarters.
</P>
<P>
   In the book, Shearer debunks Hillary Clinton's ``vast right-wing
conspiracy,'' arguing that ``a conspiracy by its nature should be a
fairly tightly controlled operation, like the Mafia or
Scientology.''
</P>
<P>
   Shearer _ whose long-running ``Le Show'' airs on KCRW-FM (89.9)
at 10 a.m. and 6 p.m. Sundays _ will appear in conversation with
humorist and fellow curmudgeon Fran Lebowitz tonight at UCLA's
Royce Hall.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be Fran and Harry having a good old-fashioned
conversation,'' Shearer explained the other day. ``When Fran gets
into town, we'll have a pre-chat about what bees are under our
particular bonnets. Life is preparation.''
</P>
<P>
   Lebowitz is author of two collections of humorous essays,
``Metropolitan Life'' and ``Social Studies,'' which have recently
been collected in the ``Fran Lebowitz Reader'' (Vintage Books;
$14).
</P>
<P>
   In a recent interview with Mirabella, the irascible Lebowitz was
at her mordant best. On Bill Clinton: ``He's a prom king. He's a
boy. He wants to be really popular, in a teen-aged sense. ... And
this is not what you'd call presidential material. You don't want a
president who liked high school.''
</P>
<P>
   The short, soft-spoken Shearer, too, frequently targets the
Clintons on his weekly radio program, currently in its 15th year on
KCRW. A recurring ``Le Show'' feature is the slickly produced
``Clinton-something,'' a ``Friends''-type takeoff of daily life at
the White House, which alternates with readings from obscure trade
journals and New Orleans r&AMP;b music.
</P>
<P>
   ``I get many things out of the show,'' says the Santa
Monica-based Shearer, who turns 56 on Dec. 23. ``It scratches an
itch. It's a place where I have access to a large audience each
week without any interference or censorship. That's rare and
valuable, even though I sometimes curse the fact I have to do it
every week.''
</P>
<P>
   Shearer's radio days actually began in the mid-'60s at KRLA-AM,
where he was part of the Credibility Gap comedy troupe, which
offered an irreverent daily look at current events. A child actor
in ``Abbott and Costello Go to Mars'' (1953), Shearer also played
the role of Eddie Haskell in the pilot episode of ``Leave It to
Beaver.''
</P>
<P>
   And Shearer _ who has been dubbed a calmer James Carville or a
liberal P.J. O'Rourke _ has long been involved in parody. He quit
``Saturday Night Live'' twice because his skits were getting
produced less frequently, and he played dim-bulb bassist Derek
Smalls in the classic ``Spinal Tap'' (1984).
</P>
<P>
   As for the future, Shearer is working on another book and plans
to shoot a digital film.
</P>
<P>
   ``With digital cameras, it's possible to do a movie for much
lower cost,'' the humorist explained. ``It tends to be more
actor-friendly. Plus, you can shoot in smaller spaces and be more
flexible.'' &QL; 
____ &QL; 
Who: Harry Shearer and Fran Lebowitz. &QL; 
Where: Royce Hall, UCLA campus, Westwood. &QL; 
When: 8 p.m. Saturday. &QL; 
Tickets: $15 to $25. &QL; 
Information: (310) 825-2101.
</P>
</TEXT>
