<HEADER>
A5431 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-FUNCTIONAL-FOODS-$ADV     12-10 1350
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FUNCTIONAL-FOODS-$ADV12-ART-1275(3TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`FUNCTIONAL FOODS' STRADDLE LINE BETWEEN NUTRITION AND MEDICINE 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, Dec. 12) 
(ART ADV: Photos NYT 14, 15 are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By DAVID J. MORROW   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Americans, who have always looked at supermarkets as cornucopias
of calories, are increasingly finding fare of a different kind in
the grocery aisles. Stacked in the rows of margarines, breakfast
cereals, salad dressings and snacks are elixirs that promise to
fight heart disease, osteoporosis and other ailments. And in some
cases, the products are billed as alternatives to medicine.
</P>
<P>
   Concerned about cholesterol? McNeil Consumer Healthcare, a
division of Johnson &AMP; Johnson, recently introduced a margarine that
contains an ingredient shown to lower it by about 10 percent with
two weeks of use.
</P>
<P>
   Worried about bacteria that can upset your digestive system?
Snap up a ``digestive biscuit'' or hot chocolate drink that
Novartis plans to introduce in the United States next year.
</P>
<P>
   And how about your aging bones? For them, Mead Johnson &AMP; Co., a
subsidiary of Bristol-Myers Squibb, has a little caramel (or
chocolate) candy snack fortified with calcium and Vitamins D and K.
</P>
<P>
   Children, too, will soon have their choice of health-promoting
treats. The Gerber Baby Food Co. plans to introduce a snack for
preschoolers with a compound that is supposed to improve their
concentration. The agent, docosa hexaenoic acid, is already being
fed to Japanese schoolchildren to improve their grades.
</P>
<P>
   After some initial stumbles, the world's largest drug and
consumer-goods companies are back with plans to introduce a growing
number of these products, known as functional foods.
</P>
<P>
   Defined broadly as items that provide an enhanced health
benefit, functional foods go far beyond the low-fat, no-fat,
organic and sugar-free products that have been sold for years as
healthier alternatives to regular food. With claims to remedy some
widespread ailments and ward off others, functional foods are seen
by their makers as natural grub for aging baby boomers intent on
living long, robust lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``Consumers are linked now by one common interest,'' said John
Troup, the head of worldwide nutritional research and development
at Novartis. ``Everybody wants to live longer but nobody wants to
grow older.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, however, functional foods have raised far more
controversy than they have lowered cholesterol levels. Critics
contend that some manufacturers exaggerate the products' health
benefits, especially when the brand may contain ingredients that do
as much harm as good. For example, some products intended to lower
cholesterol can reduce the body's vitamins, according to some
nutritionists.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a lot of quackery,'' said Michael Jacobson, executive
director of Center for Science in the Public Interest, a consumer
group in Washington. ``Some companies are making outrageous claims
that probably don't provide any benefit other than to their
shareholders.''
</P>
<P>
   Prices are another issue. The functional foods that have come to
market are so expensive _ sometimes five or six times more than
their nonfortified competitors _ that they may not be worth the
benefit.
</P>
<P>
   Some manufacturers are having a difficult time rousing sales for
their brands. After selling Benecol brand cholesterol-reducing
margarine, snack bars and salad dressings in the United States for
only seven months, Johnson &AMP; Johnson backtracked this month,
trimming consumer ad spending for the line by two-thirds, according
to analysts' estimates. The analysts attributed the cutback to poor
sales, perhaps a result of high prices _ the Benecol spread sells
for $7.29 for 5.9 ounces at a Food Emporium in New York _ but the
company said the cutback figure was ``way off base,'' adding that
it wanted to redirect its resources to promoting Benecol to
physicians.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the functional-food offensive is just beginning. Drug makers
see the foods as a way to parlay their laboratory discoveries
beyond the pharmacy and into grocery stores, while packaged-goods
companies see hot-selling, high-margin products that can foment
stagnant food sales and improve their earnings.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street has bought into the idea. Consumer-goods analysts
estimate that sales of functional foods in the United States should
top $3 billion this year, or 1 percent of the country's annual
expenditures on food.
</P>
<P>
   ``The profits are very strong in our grocery segment,'' said Al
Piergallini, the head of worldwide consumer health at Novartis,
which owns Gerber Baby Food and the Ovaltine brand and sells
Sunkist products. ``It's a high-margin business, so it's inviting
to expand our product offerings. We think we can do very well
against our competition.''
</P>
<P>
   Such confidence in the market may be wishful thinking, though,
given the market obstacles that loom _ even aside from price.
</P>
<P>
   Though many functional foods are still being sold in test
markets, some brands that have already been introduced have come
without much explanation of how they work, leaving consumers
without an understanding of how to use them. In general, they are
not simply foods. Like pills that treat a chronic illness, most
functional foods have to be used several times a day for weeks to
get the promised benefit.
</P>
<P>
   Benecol, for example, must be taken three times a day as a
spread, snack bar or salad dressing for about two weeks to reduce
cholesterol levels by 10 percent; a sporadic user has little chance
of reducing cholesterol by that amount. The same goes for Take
Control, a similarly fortified spread from Unilever that costs a
little less than Benecol. A prescription drug, meanwhile, like
Lipitor, has been proven to lower cholesterol by 40 percent within
a few weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Other functional foods have similar problems. EnfaGrow, a Mead
Johnson snack for toddlers, provides a battery of vitamins not
found in some cereals. The EnfaGrow box boasts that zinc is
necessary for cell function, but toddlers had best be pretty hungry
to get their recommended daily allowance of the vitamin. They have
to eat about 3.5 cookies a day to get the benefits.
</P>
<P>
   The proliferation of health-fortified products has baffled
federal regulators. Any company can make a reasonable claim about
the structure or function of a product's ingredients _ that fiber,
for example, promotes digestive health. But if a manufacturer wants
to assert that its product prevents stomach infections, it would
need approval from the Food and Drug Administration.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the FDA review for foods is far less thorough than its
approval process for new drugs. There are no requirements for
clinical trials, except for some food additives like sweeteners,
and many compounds used in functional foods do not require
pre-approval from the agency. Usually, makers of functional foods
have to prove to the FDA only that an ingredient is ``generally
recognized as safe.'' That typically means that it has been
consumed without incident or is widely known among scientists.
</P>
<P>
   To set market criteria for functional foods, the FDA has
established 12 ``health claims,'' based on the ingredients, that
manufacturers can use in marketing their products as potential ways
to reduce the risk of diseases. Products high in calcium, for
example, can state that they help reduce the risk of osteoporosis,
while others rich in folic acid can say that they can help reduce
the risks of brain or spinal-cord birth defects.
</P>
<P>
   Lacking a legal definition of functional food, the FDA has
acknowledged having trouble weighing the nutritional benefits of
some new products. ``We were all once sure what food was,'' said
Dr. Christine Lewis, assistant to the director of the Office for
Special Nutritionals at the FDA. ``Now we're just not sure when a
food becomes functional. It's not anyone's fault. It's a reflection
of the times.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
