<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-10 18:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5433 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-FUNCTIONAL-FOODS-$ADV     12-10 0988
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FUNCTIONAL-FOODS-$ADV12-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: the times.'' 
<TEXT>
<P>
   But the manufacturers' rush toward functional foods is becoming
intense. Some established products are being recast, even to
include some unlikely brands. Campbell's Pork &AMP; Beans, hardly
healthy cuisine, carries a label stating that it meets American
Heart Association guidelines for low saturated fat and cholesterol.
Yet one half-cup serving of the product contains 8 grams.
</P>
<P>
   Any new functional foods, meanwhile, from yogurt to breakfast
bars to milk shakes, will soon be trundling down the assembly lines
and into grocery delivery trucks. ``Functional food is becoming a
sort of fad,'' said Bill Leach, a food analyst at Donaldson Lufkin
&AMP; Jenrette. ``I'm not sure people are just going to go out and
start eating soybeans.''
</P>
<P>
   If the past is a good predictor, Leach may well be right. Last
year, Campbell Soup dropped its Intelligent Quisine line of frozen
foods _ aimed at people with diabetes and heart conditions _ after
test-marketing it for 15 months in Ohio. Kellogg, meanwhile, had
planned to sell Ensemble, a line of 22 health-fortified products,
including cereals and pastas, that purported to lower cholesterol,
but scrapped the line in November because of poor sales in a
southwest Michigan test market.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said Campbell Soup and Kellogg had invested millions of
dollars developing functional foods but did not know how to sell
them. Kellogg had boasted that Ensemble was rich in fiber, an
ingredient so familiar to consumers, critics said, that many were
unimpressed. Intelligent Quisine was a marketing disaster.
</P>
<P>
   ``What happened with Intelligent Quisine was that these frozen
meals would be delivered to someone's home,'' said Dr. Paul
Lachance, executive director of the Neutraceutical Institute at
Rutgers University. ``The problem was that most people didn't have
enough freezer space to store the meals. People just didn't know
what to do with it all.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, though, makers of functional foods believe that they have
developed a successful formula. Instead of selling full meals,
manufacturers are devising single products. They are basing their
product assertions not on common things like fiber but on more
unusual ingredients like plant stanols, the ingredient in Benecol
that is said to lower cholesterol, and acid compounds said to
address particular ailments (and thereby warrant premium prices).
And manufacturers are also stressing the products' taste.
</P>
<P>
   ``People want positive things in their diet, but taste is No.
1,'' said Guy Johnson, vice president of nutrition at Kellogg USA,
which plans to introduce a soybean cereal next year. ``Functional
foods will prosper because they are convenient and taste good. Our
soy cereal will taste so great people will want to eat it just for
that reason.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, companies plan to spread the risk, selling functional
foods in many forms, including beverages.
</P>
<P>
   Novartis, a pharmaceutical company best known for cyclosporin, a
drug used in organ transplants, took that approach last month in
introducing Aviva, its functional food line, in Switzerland and
Britain. The line includes muesli, juice drinks, cereal bars,
biscuits and hot chocolate to provide heart, bone and digestive
benefits. And the company said it would soon license several of its
compounds for functional foods to makers of dairy products.
</P>
<P>
   The potential profit from the new brands is exciting the
manufacturers. Novartis expects Aviva's worldwide sales to reach
$500 million in five years, including fees from licensees.
</P>
<P>
   While most of Johnson &AMP; Johnson's competitors have heavily
criticized Benecol _ usually for its lofty price _ most have noted
the brand's sales. In its first months on the market, ending Sept.
26, Benecol spread had $12.3 million in sales in the United States
and a 2 percent share of the margarine market, according to
Information Resources, which tracks sales in supermarkets. Johnson
&AMP; Johnson, however, heavily promoted Benecol with coupons and ads.
</P>
<P>
   While that 2 percent share may seem small _ the leading
margarine, Shedds Country Crock, had a 15.8 percent share _
Benecol, made for Johnson &AMP; Johnson by a Finnish company, the
Raisio Group, has been available only since May. The packaged-goods
market in the United States is so mature _ margarine sales have
increased just 2 percent so far this year and cereals 1 percent _
that companies must ``steal'' share from their competitors to
bolster sales.
</P>
<P>
   Novartis executives have watched Benecol's introduction closely,
trying with its Aviva line to sidestep Johnson &AMP; Johnson's
marketing mistakes. Several Novartis executives have publicly
chided Johnson &AMP; Johnson for placing Benecol in the refrigerated
section of the supermarket alongside other margarines. Consumers
had little trouble comparing prices _ and being shocked by the
multidollar difference. That pound of Benecol spread at a Food
Emporium in Manhattan costs $17.22 a pound, while Shedds Country
Crock goes for $1.79.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we plan to do with Aviva in Europe is to group the
products together on one shelf,'' said Thomas Ebeling, the chief
operating officer of Novartis' drug unit. ``That way, we can
maintain our price premium. In Europe, products that are on a
special shelf always sell at a premium. Consumers can't compare
products if they aren't side by side.''
</P>
<P>
   Novartis said it planned to use the same game plan for Aviva in
American supermarkets, but analysts have expressed doubts. To get
separate shelf space in the United States, they calculated,
Novartis could have to pay up to $20 million in fees _ eroding the
brand's profits.
</P>
<P>
   Still, some analysts believe the expense might be worth it. If
the Aviva orange drink were placed in the refrigerated section, for
example, it would compete with Tropicana and Minute Maid and their
titan corporate parents, PepsiCo and Coca-Cola.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-10-99 1806EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
