<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991210.0199 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-10 18:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5436 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-FUNCTIONAL-FOODS-$ADV     12-10 0983
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FUNCTIONAL-FOODS-$ADV12-ART-3RDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: and Coca-Cola. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   But executives at Novartis do not appear too concerned. Like
other manufacturers of functional foods, the company is confident
that its products will dazzle consumers. To market Aviva in the
United States, Novartis will rely heavily on its Gerber Baby Food
subsidiary, which will soon introduce functional foods under its
own label.
</P>
<P>
   Piergallini, who is on a pound-shedding diet that he proudly
announced includes martinis and steak, is especially excited about
a Gerber snack for preschoolers that will contain the compound
docosa hexaenoic acid, or DHA. The Japanese routinely feed DHA, in
pill form and as an ingredient in snacks, to school-aged children
so they will get better grades. Recent studies in Japan have also
shown that the compound may improve eyesight.
</P>
<P>
   ``The science with these products will be sound,'' Piergallini
said. ``But with any of them, they have to taste good and be fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Aviva will be marketed mostly to women, who tend to spend more
than men on preventive health care. But Novartis may also make a
subtle pitch to anyone eager to balance their overindulgences. One
Novartis executive said he thought prime users would be people who
regularly devour chocolate sundaes and would reach for Aviva
chocolate drinks to help balance out their snacks.
</P>
<P>
   While the market research for Aviva appears to be thorough, it
is not known how closely the brand's managers will follow it. The
company recently began a regional introduction in 114 Boots
drugstores and 30 Safeway stores in Britain, but preliminary
results were mixed.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Sinclair, Safeway's commercial director, who is conducting
the test for Novartis, gave Aviva only a 30 percent chance of
success. An Aviva orange drink, which provides bone benefits, is
being sold at Safeway for about $5.25 for a liter. By contrast,
that amount of Tropicana orange juice sells for about $3.65, a
Novartis executive said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, I'd say that it costs too much,'' Sinclair said,
adding that people will not pay enormous premiums. ``Aviva would be
far more successful if it were priced at about 10 percent to 20
percent above what it costs for similar items.''
</P>
<P>
   Novartis executives disagreed. ``We're talking about a food
category that nobody has been in before,'' said Alastair Paton,
marketing director in Britain for Novartis' health and functional
foods. ``Jack has experience with low-fat products, but Aviva goes
well beyond that by supplying a health benefit. People will pay
more to be healthy.''
</P>
<P>
   But Sinclair had other reservations about Aviva. Novartis, he
noted, has hinged the line's success largely on the company's
ability to sell Aviva separately from similar items. Essentially,
it hopes that consumers will go automatically to the Aviva shelf in
the store, bypassing all competitors.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure that selling Aviva together in one place in the
store will work,'' Sinclair said. ``The women who buy the
groceries, they know how much everything they want costs,
regardless of where it is in the store. With Aviva, they're going
to know that they're paying a lot. And if they pay six times as
much for a margarine, they're only going to use it on special
occasions. That's not a way to get to the mass market.''
</P>
<P>
   After Benecol's stumbles during its introduction, some
packaged-goods experts say they think functional foods will never
enjoy widespread appeal. When Benecol and Take Control are measured
in unit sales, not dollars, each has less than a 1 percent share of
the market. Take Control has only a 1 percent share of margarine
sales, measured in dollars, according to the report by Information
Resources.
</P>
<P>
   Functional foods also do little to countermand trends that have
stymied the packaged-goods market for decades. Americans are eating
out more than ever before, hurting sales of groceries and consumer
goods products in general.
</P>
<P>
   Some consumers have begun to think of functional food as
medicine, abandoning it once the benefit is achieved, several
packaged-foods analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   Many makers of functional foods are counting on doctors'
recommendations to drive sales. But that strategy is showing signs
of backfiring.
</P>
<P>
   ``Benecol is a nice way to add something positive to your
diet,'' said Dr. Tu Nguyen, director of the cholesterol disorder
program at the Mayo Clinic and a researcher in plant stanols. ``But
people who only use it occasionally may not receive any of the
effects.'' Doctors and health professionals also know that the
wonder biscuits and drinks are not substitutes for drugs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, Benecol is a good product but I wouldn't go out and
tell someone to eatall the Benecol they could,'' said Deena Fox, a
clinical dietitian at New York Presbyterian Hospital. ``Anyone can
go anywhere and get an apple and orange and pop it in their mouth.
And they're much less expensive.''
</P>
<P>
   And there may be outright resistance. The Center for Science in
the Public Interest is known for crusading against controversial
foods, though Jacobson said it was too soon to say how it would
react to functional foods. Meanwhile, he said, consumers should
carefully scrutinize the ingredients in these foods, since some
compounds are not tested by regulators.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts have said that consumers may not bite, anyway. Many
already eat large amounts of fiber and calcium to reduce their risk
of colon cancer and osteoporosis. Why pay extra for more?
</P>
<P>
   ``Consumers do have an interest in eating healthier foods,''
said David Schmidt, the senior vice president of food safety at the
International Food Information Council, a Washington-based advocate
for nutritional safety. ``But Americans are just so
price-conscious. When it comes to buying packaged foods, they
always seem to go for the cheaper price as long as the item meets
their standard of quality.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
