<HEADER>
A5441 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-HARRY-SHEARER-INTERVI     12-10 0761
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HARRY-SHEARER-INTERVIEW-CORRECTION-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WAY MORE THAN MR. BURNS
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: inserts dropped comma in lede; removes embargo) 
By FRED SHUSTER 
c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Harry Shearer _ actor, radio host, political commentator _ may
be a little bit of everywhere these days, but one place he won't be
on New Year's Eve is out on the town.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel about the millennium the way I do about New Year's Eve
generally _ it's a holiday for civilians,'' he said. ``Like most
people in show business, if I'm not working that night, I'll be
home. In this case, entertaining my in-laws.''
</P>
<P>
   You may not immediately recognize the name, but you will the
voice and maybe the face. Shearer, you see, is one of those
ubiquitous talents who gets around.
</P>
<P>
   Creator and star of the seminal fake rockumentary ``This Is
Spinal Tap,'' Shearer voices Mr. Burns and 19 other characters on
TV's ``The Simpsons,'' hosts public radio's weekly ``Le Show'' and
has appeared in such feature films as ``Godzilla,'' ``The Truman
Show,'' ``edTV'' and ``The Right Stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   How does he find the time?
</P>
<P>
   ``I wonder that myself sometimes,'' he says. ``It's a pretty
full week. But with the radio show, I've always believed I could do
it way into the future, as long as I can make room for it in the
rest of my career.''
</P>
<P>
   A former writer and cast member on ``Saturday Night Live,''
Shearer unbuckles the Beltway in ``It's the Stupidity, Stupid''
(Random House; $16.95), a shrewd look at the Clinton administration
and why it has inspired such fervent hatred in some quarters.
</P>
<P>
   In the book, Shearer debunks Hillary Clinton's ``vast right-wing
conspiracy,'' arguing that ``a conspiracy by its nature should be a
fairly tightly controlled operation, like the Mafia or
Scientology.''
</P>
<P>
   Shearer _ whose long-running ``Le Show'' airs on KCRW-FM (89.9)
at 10 a.m. and 6 p.m. Sundays _ will appear in conversation with
humorist and fellow curmudgeon Fran Lebowitz tonight at UCLA's
Royce Hall.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be Fran and Harry having a good old-fashioned
conversation,'' Shearer explained the other day. ``When Fran gets
into town, we'll have a pre-chat about what bees are under our
particular bonnets. Life is preparation.''
</P>
<P>
   Lebowitz is author of two collections of humorous essays,
``Metropolitan Life'' and ``Social Studies,'' which have recently
been collected in the ``Fran Lebowitz Reader'' (Vintage Books;
$14).
</P>
<P>
   In a recent interview with Mirabella, the irascible Lebowitz was
at her mordant best. On Bill Clinton: ``He's a prom king. He's a
boy. He wants to be really popular, in a teen-aged sense. ... And
this is not what you'd call presidential material. You don't want a
president who liked high school.''
</P>
<P>
   The short, soft-spoken Shearer, too, frequently targets the
Clintons on his weekly radio program, currently in its 15th year on
KCRW. A recurring ``Le Show'' feature is the slickly produced
``Clinton-something,'' a ``Friends''-type takeoff of daily life at
the White House, which alternates with readings from obscure trade
journals and New Orleans r&AMP;b music.
</P>
<P>
   ``I get many things out of the show,'' says the Santa
Monica-based Shearer, who turns 56 on Dec. 23. ``It scratches an
itch. It's a place where I have access to a large audience each
week without any interference or censorship. That's rare and
valuable, even though I sometimes curse the fact I have to do it
every week.''
</P>
<P>
   Shearer's radio days actually began in the mid-'60s at KRLA-AM,
where he was part of the Credibility Gap comedy troupe, which
offered an irreverent daily look at current events. A child actor
in ``Abbott and Costello Go to Mars'' (1953), Shearer also played
the role of Eddie Haskell in the pilot episode of ``Leave It to
Beaver.''
</P>
<P>
   And Shearer _ who has been dubbed a calmer James Carville or a
liberal P.J. O'Rourke _ has long been involved in parody. He quit
``Saturday Night Live'' twice because his skits were getting
produced less frequently, and he played dim-bulb bassist Derek
Smalls in the classic ``Spinal Tap'' (1984).
</P>
<P>
   As for the future, Shearer is working on another book and plans
to shoot a digital film.
</P>
<P>
   ``With digital cameras, it's possible to do a movie for much
lower cost,'' the humorist explained. ``It tends to be more
actor-friendly. Plus, you can shoot in smaller spaces and be more
flexible.'' &QL; 
____ &QL; 
Who: Harry Shearer and Fran Lebowitz. &QL; 
Where: Royce Hall, UCLA campus, Westwood. &QL; 
When: 8 p.m. Saturday. &QL; 
Tickets: $15 to $25. &QL; 
Information: (310) 825-2101.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
