<HEADER>
A5445 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-MILLENNIUM-CLINTONS-$     12-10 0933
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MILLENNIUM-CLINTONS-$ADV12-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOLLYWOOD AND WASHINGTON MIX ON NEW YEAR'S EVE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, Dec. 12)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK HELM  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Hollywood star power will meet Washington political
power on New Year's Eve as some of the world's biggest celebrities
join President and Mrs. Clinton for a glitzy, patriotic celebration
to usher in the millennium.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to create something worthy of the ringing in the Year
2000 in the nation's capital,'' said Toby Graf, a spokeswoman for
First Lady Hillary Rodham Clinton, whose office is spearheading the
planning for the celebration.
</P>
<P>
   The first lady will open a three-day festival entitled
``America's Millennium,'' at 11 a.m. eastern time on Friday, Dec.
31, with the unveiling of a time capsule, which will be stored at
the Smithsonian Institution.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is going to be a different kind of time capsule in that
we're trying to find things that define the whole 20th century as
well as what life is like right now,'' said Graf. But she declined
to reveal what will be in the capsule.
</P>
<P>
   While the three days will include parades, dozens of parties and
an array of exhibitions highlighting American history, the focus of
the celebration will be on CBS's nationally televised New Year's
Eve show at the Lincoln Memorial.
</P>
<P>
   Actor and rapper Will Smith will host a three-hour show, which
starts at 10 p.m. eastern time. Joining Smith will be fellow actors
Robert Duvall, Sam Waterson and Diane Keaton, opera stars Jessye
Norman and Kathleen Battle, along with gospel singer Bebe Winans,
country singer Trisha Yearwood and 25 New York cast members of the
musical hit ``Stomp.''
</P>
<P>
   Paul McCarthy, executive director of America's Millennium, the
organization coordinating the celebration for the White House,
promised that other celebrities would be at the event but would not
identify any of them.
</P>
<P>
   Still, he said the program, entitled ``America's Millennium
Gala,'' will offer more than just ``another celebrity special.''
</P>
<P>
   McCarthy said the show, created by musician Quincy Jones and
producer-director George Stevens Jr., will be a ``thoughtful
melange'' of 20th century America. ``The show is meant to be moving
rather than just another musical show,'' he said, adding that the
Lincoln Memorial was chosen because it has been the site of many
key moments in the nation's history.
</P>
<P>
   The president and first lady will begin celebrating around 7
p.m. with a black-tie ``Creators Dinner'' at the White House to
honor some of the country's most prominent figures in sports, arts
and sciences. Playwrights Edward Albee, August Wilson, Arthur
Miller and Neil Simon will be among the attendees, as well as
musicians Itzhak Perlman, Pinchas Zuckerman and Marilyn Horn.
Others include dancers Edward Villella and Arthur Mitchell; artist
Robert Rauschenberg; architect Maya Lin; Olympian runner Carl Lewis
and Internet pionier Vinton Cerf.
</P>
<P>
   About 9:30 p.m., a motorcade of limousines accompanied by dozens
of Secret Service vehicles and Washington, D.C. police cars will
take the Clintons and their guests to the Lincoln Memorial, where
they will join a Mall crowd that _ depending on the weather _ is
expected to reach 250,000 people. Last year's temperatures on Dec.
31 ranged from 19 to 28 degrees. Normal temperatures for the day
range from 18 to 36.
</P>
<P>
   About 11:30 p.m., as the so-called ``Midnight Moment''
approaches, a 100-piece orchestra, along with the combined bands,
choirs and marching units of the U.S. Armed Forces, will premiere a
score by award-winning composer John Williams. The music will
accompany an 18-minute movie on America in the 20th century by
academy award-winning director Steven Spielberg that will play on
giant screens on three sides of the Reflecting Pool in front of the
Lincoln Memorial.
</P>
<P>
   Then U.S. poet laureate Robert Pinsky and his predecessors Rita
Dove and Maya Angelou will read from their new works.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want people to be able to see and hear what this country is
about and what makes it so special,'' McCarthy said.
</P>
<P>
   At midnight, organizers say, the Mall will explode into a
spectacular sound-light-and-fireworks show between the Lincoln
Memorial and the Washington Monument.
</P>
<P>
   The show will end with a group of American children _ joined by
the stars of the gala and choruses _ asking the crowd to join in a
sing-along of traditional American songs.
</P>
<P>
   Washington officials are expecting that during the day Dec. 31
as many as 750,000 people will use the city's public transit
system, more than twice as many as last Dec. 31 and easily more
than record crowd of 541,000 on last July 4.
</P>
<P>
   City spokesman Ray Feldmann said bus and train service will be
provided throughout the day. Usually on New Year's Eve, the city
runs trains until 2 a.m. and buses until 3 a.m., but this year, the
city will keep both going an extra hour.
</P>
<P>
   According to Graf, the Clintons plan to leave the Lincoln
Memorial before the ``Midnight Moment'' show ends at 1 a.m. ``The
president and the first lady are still deciding how to spend the
rest of the evening,'' she said. ``They may just decide to go home
and spend some time alone.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether this New Year's celebration will be the largest
under President Clinton, Graf hedged, saying: ``Well, the
millennium doesn't actually start until 2001, and next year's New
Year's Eve will be the last one under the administration. So we'll
see.''
</P>
<P>
   (Mark Helm can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address mark &LR; hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
