<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-SMART-LUXURY-$ADV12-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A LUXURIOUS BRAWL  
(FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, DEC. 12)
</HEADLINE>
  (af) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The luxury-vehicle sales race is coming down to the wire, and
based on the latest figures, it may be a photo finish. Plus, for
the first time ever, the top two contenders are not American
companies.
</P>
<P>
   gh November, Mercedes-Benz led Toyota's Lexus Division by
just 1,294 vehicles. General Motors' Cadillac Division was in third
place, just ahead of Lincoln, which is part of the Ford Motor Co.
Lincoln won the sales race last year for the first time in six
decades, after GM auditors determined that Cadillac had improperly
inflated its figures.
</P>
<P>
   Sales of luxury cars and sport utilities are booming. In 11
months, several brands have surpassed their full-year sales for
1998. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
