<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-10 18:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5481 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-BIZ-SUN-AMERICA-$ADV1     12-10 1050
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-SUN-AMERICA-$ADV12-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COURTSHIP OF VARIABLE ANNUITIES  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, DEC. 12) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Md., Ohio, Calif.)   (af)  
 By JOSEPH B. TREASTER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   By the time Paul Petersen was 21, he had bought 5 new houses, 20
cars and 30 television sets. One of the cars, a stunning gold
Cadillac convertible with a black leather interior, still makes him
sigh.
</P>
<P>
   Petersen made a small fortune as a teenage star on a hit TV
series of the 1960s, ``The Donna Reed Show.'' But when it ended its
eight-year run, he had trouble finding roles. He kept spending,
though, and within four years he was broke.
</P>
<P>
   Three decades later, Petersen, who lives in a modest home in
south-central Los Angeles, one of the city's poorer neighborhoods,
is making financial misfortune work for him. For the last several
months, he and two other former child TV stars who had trouble
managing their money _ Brandon Cruz, who played Eddie in ``The
Courtship of Eddie's Father,'' and Jon Provost, who played Timmy on
``Lassie'' _ have been traveling the talk show circuit for
SunAmerica, a unit of American International Group.
</P>
<P>
   SunAmerica is a leader in the thriving business of variable
annuities, an investment that combines features of mutual funds and
insurance.
</P>
<P>
   In their talk-show appearances, the three are living examples
for SunAmerica's national advertising campaign, which flashes
images of glamorous cars and jewelry on television screens and,
without actually saying so, urges Americans to resist filling their
lives with toys today so that they can build comfortable nest eggs
for tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   That fancy sports car with the $70,000 price tag? The money,
invested instead at a not-too-hard-to-attain 8 percent, could grow
to a staggering $326,267 in 20 years, SunAmerica says, exclusive of
fees.
</P>
<P>
   The message about saving is good, financial experts say. But
they are not so sure about SunAmerica's main product, the variable
annuity, a controversial and somewhat complicated investment that
is never mentioned by name in the advertisements.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you ask me if convincing people to save money in variable
annuities is better than wasting money, the answer is, of course,''
said J. Michael Martin, president of Financial Advantage Inc., a
fee-only financial planning company in Columbia, Md. ``But if you
ask me if I'd advise most people to put their money in a variable
annuity, the answer is no.''
</P>
<P>
   Variable annuities may make sense for some investors, but they
are not for everyone. Their fees, for one thing, are often nearly
double those for comparable mutual funds. Moreover, many financial
planners say the features that make annuities more costly are often
worthless.
</P>
<P>
   One feature is a guarantee that money put into a variable
annuity will be preserved for the investor's heirs, regardless of
market fluctuations.
</P>
<P>
   SunAmerica and other variable annuity companies say this is a
confidence builder for timid investors who might otherwise never
leave bank certificates of deposit to take a chance on stocks,
fearing that they could lose money. But those fears have generally
been unfounded.
</P>
<P>
   Financial planners like David Foster, of Foster &AMP; Motley in
Cincinnati, say there have been few periods even as short as five
years in which a diversified portfolio of stocks and bonds has lost
money.
</P>
<P>
   Many people looking to make their money grow find it difficult
to tell the difference between a variable annuity and a mutual
fund. Both are most often investments in stocks and bonds. Despite
the higher fees for variable annuities, investors are often steered
to them by sales representatives, who can earn higher commissions
on them than on mutual funds.
</P>
<P>
   Five years ago, long before SunAmerica hired Petersen to promote
its retirement savings theme, his wife, Rana, who runs the medical
department at a CBS production center, opened an investment account
with the company. When they spoke about the investment the other
day, neither Petersen, who now spends most of his time running a
foundation called A Minor Consideration, which helps young actors
take care of financial matters, nor Mrs. Petersen was sure whether
it was in variable annuities or mutual funds.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Petersen remembered that she had called SunAmerica and said
she was ``interested in saving for my future.'' They sent her some
brochures. ``I just kind of said, `OK, I'll pick this one,' and
mailed in a check to open the account,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   After checking her records recently, she found that they were
invested in two mutual funds. The Petersens, who also both have
pension funds through their work, say that knowing just what they
had invested in through SunAmerica was less important than knowing
that they were getting steady returns. That, they say, is good
enough for them.
</P>
<P>
   It's also good enough for SunAmerica, which emphasizes variable
annuities but also sells mutual funds. Like other specialists in
variable annuities, SunAmerica contends that partly because of tax
advantages and trading patterns, annuities can be a much better
investment than critics say.
</P>
<P>
   Many financial experts say variable annuities work best for
people with high incomes. But the National Association for Variable
Annuities, an industry trade group, says the average customer makes
less than $75,000 a year.
</P>
<P>
   Variable annuities carry hefty penalties for early withdrawals
and there is an Internal Revenue Service penalty of 10 percent for
withdrawals before the age of 60. The possibility of penalties can
be a plus, financial experts say, for people who would otherwise be
unable to resist squandering money.
</P>
<P>
   Jana Waring Greer, president for marketing at SunAmerica, agreed
that the penalties could have a good effect, but said SunAmerica
did not emphasize them in its promotion. ``You can't lecture to the
baby boomers,'' she said. ``You have to show them that if they
defer spending they're going to have a lot more money to spend in
the future.''
</P>
<P>
   And that is where Petersen's soft sell, harking back to his
youth, comes in. ``If I had just picked up the phone and called any
company _ (italics)any company(end italics) _ and asked for their
advice in planning my future,'' he said in an interview the other
day, ``I'd be miles ahead today.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
