<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-10 18:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5487 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-INVEST-SODA-BOTTLERS-     12-10 0897
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVEST-SODA-BOTTLERS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLA MAKERS LEAVE THEIR BOTTLERS FLAT 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By CONSTANCE L. HAYS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Coca-Cola, the soft drink, is based on a closely-guarded secret
formula. But the arithmetic that results when Coca-Cola, the
company, decides to squeeze more profit from its complex
relationships with its bottlers was laid bare last week.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, shares of Coca-Cola Enterprises, in which Coca-Cola
holds a 39 percent stake, closed at $18.375 a share, less than half
their 52-week high of $37.50. The share price of Coca-Cola
Consolidated, the No. 2 Coke bottler in the United States, closed
at $49.75, down 13.5 percent for the year.
</P>
<P>
   This had been a bad year for the bottling stocks, but it became
worse last month. That was when an executive of Coca-Cola
Enterprises disclosed that Coca-Cola was raising the price it
charges for concentrate _ the powder or syrup that is mixed with
water and carbon dioxide to become soft drinks _ by 7 percent,
twice the usual rate. The move was seen as Coke's attempt to
capture some of the profit that the bottlers were anticipating from
a price increase they initiated earlier this year at the wholesale
level.
</P>
<P>
   For Summerfield Johnston Jr., the chairman and second-largest
shareholder of Coca-Cola Enterprises, a result has been this: In
early June, his 28.6 million shares were worth about $1.07 billion;
the value of that stake has been whittled down to about $525
million.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would say he's not a happy camper on this whole thing,''
said Emanuel Goldman, an analyst at Merrill Lynch. The unhappiness
of bottlers like Johnston _ whose opinions carry some weight at
Coca-Cola _ may have been a factor in the departure of M. Douglas
Ivester, Coca-Cola's chief executive. Ivester stunned investors
last week with the news that he was stepping down in April.
</P>
<P>
   The concentrate price increase was imitated over at Pepsi-Cola a
short time later. For the Pepsi system, it has been the same story:
shares in Pepsi Bottling, the company spun off from PepsiCo earlier
this year, are now at $16, after trading as high as $25.25. The
Whitman Corp., another major Pepsi bottler, now trades at $13.125,
down 48 percent for the year.
</P>
<P>
   The stock prices of the concentrate companies, however, have
fared better. Coca-Cola closed on Friday at $63.25, down just 5.6
percent for the year, while PepsiCo closed at $36.935, down 9.6
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Does all this mean that investors should avoid bottling stocks?
Not necessarily, say some money managers and analysts.
</P>
<P>
   ``The upside isn't limited if you are a long-term value
player,'' said Scott Black, the president of Delphi Management,
which is among the top five stakeholders in Coca-Cola Consolidated
and has a stake in Pepsi Bottling. ``You're getting exclusive
territorial franchises, a business that generates lots of cash, and
very low multiples.'' With cash flow growth of 10 percent or so in
good times, the stocks are attractive.
</P>
<P>
   Goldman said he thought all the bottling stocks had been
oversold. He has 12-month price targets of $40 on Coca-Cola
Enterprises, $31 on Pepsi Bottling and $16 on Whitman.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Pepsi Bottling, which announced the Pepsi-Cola
concentrate price increase last month, said the timing was right as
long as PepsiCo made marketing-support payments to the bottler.
``Consumers have to want what we make, sell and deliver,'' said the
spokesman, Larry Jabbonsky.
</P>
<P>
   The relationship between the concentrate companies and their
bottlers has been a concern on Wall Street. Many investors want to
see a more equitable distribution of profits between the two sides;
historically, more of the profit has accrued to the concentrate
makers, whose margins are extremely high. Returns on invested
capital have also been far higher for the concentrate companies
than for the bottlers.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there seems to be some confusion, said Paul Rissman, a
senior vice president at Alliance Capital Management, who recently
added to stakes in Coca-Cola Enterprises and Pepsi Bottling, both
of which he calls ``incredibly cheap.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If the concentrate companies were to intend to rob some of the
profits from the bottlers, they'd just be cutting off their
noses,'' he said. ``We think they know that. We think they are
trying to reach agreements with the bottlers where they can both
make money.''
</P>
<P>
   Companies like Coca-Cola have urged ever-higher volume from
their bottlers, and stand to benefit from increased concentrate
sales. But there has been a big cost to bottlers around the world,
said Andrew J. Conway, an analyst for Morgan Stanley.
</P>
<P>
   In a note to investors published last week, Conway assessed
Ivester's contributions and generally gave him high marks. However,
he said volume growth targets of 7 to 8 percent _ which Ivester's
successor, Douglas N. Daft, said he planned to pursue _ had a
distinct downside.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ivester's targets have led to an unprecedented rate of bottler
investment in plants, trucks, machinery and coolers,'' Conway
wrote. ``Given the global economic slowdown, this rate of
investment was well ahead of the volume curve that has emerged. In
turn, this has left many global bottlers with subpar returns on
invested capital.''
</P>
</TEXT>
