<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Saturday, Dec. 11, 1999, sent to computer graphics clients of The
New York Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(jt) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST
</P>
<P>
   Chilly, strong winds from the northwest will buffet most of the
Northeast states Saturday in the wake an intense low-pressure
system heading slowly toward the Canadian Maritimes from northern
Maine. Winds will average 20 to 35 mph along the southern and
central New England Seaboards, with gusts over 40 mph possible in
places.
</P>
<P>
   Snow will develop in the mountains of northern New England as
cold Canadian air is moistened by invading Atlantic moisture. Most
of the snow, however, will be light. A few snow showers will fall
farther south and east, but none will survive to the coast, save
northeast Maine, as winds from the northwest rapidly dry on descent
from the Appalachians.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, moderate rains will develop in the Pacific Northwest,
mainly on west-facing high ground of west Washington and northwest
Oregon, where ocean winds are forced to rise up the sloping
terrain. Snow will fall at high elevations in the Cascades.
</P>
<P>
   Scattered rains will develop over parts of east Texas and
western Louisiana as increasingly moist air over the Gulf of Mexico
stream inland ahead of a slow-moving low-pressure system over the
upper Rio Grande Valley. Late Saturday and Saturday night, however,
as the low arrives, rains will intensify over east Texas, raising
the rainfall potential to more than 2 inches in some areas by
Sunday morning. Thunder will accompany some of the rain.
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of the low, strong winds from the northeast will
gradually ease across southern California.
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: MOIST MISSOURI
</P>
<P>
   For the second time this month, Springfield, Mo., had a record
amount of rainfall. Thursday's showers tallied 2.77 inches,
eclipsing the day's record set most recently in 1985. With the
heavy rain that fell last weekend, the monthly total stands at 6.84
inches, compared with a normal month-to-date value of 1.06 inches.
The wettest December in Springfield occurred in 1982 when 8.84
inches fell. With 20 days remaining, it is highly likely that at
least another 2 inches of rain will fall, making December,1999, the
wettest ever. In fact, another rainstorm should arrive on Monday.
</P>
</TEXT>
