<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SISTINE-FRESCOES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VIVID COLORS OF RESTORED FRESCOES BRIGHTEN SISTINE CHAPEL 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By ALESSANDRA STANLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME _ Ending a 20-year restoration of the Sistine Chapel, the
Vatican on Friday unveiled newly cleaned frescoes by Botticelli and
other 15th-century artists that had long been overshadowed by
Michelangelo's masterpieces.
</P>
<P>
   Even after Michelangelo's ``Creation'' and ``Last Judgment''
frescoes were painstakingly restored, it took five years of careful
scraping and wiping to clean centuries of dust, soot and grit off
scenes from the lives of Jesus and Moses that line the walls
beneath Michelangelo's ceiling. At long last, the entire room is
uniformly bright, glittering with vivid blues, rich crimsons and
gold, and long-forgotten details.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most important thing is that the unity of the color
schemes with Michelangelo's work has been refound,'' Arnold
Nesselrath, director of the Vatican Museums' department of
Byzantine, medieval and modern art, said Friday at a news
conference.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, the pope is to preside at a ceremony to celebrate
the full restoration of the Sistine Chapel, where cardinals gather
to elect a new pope. John Paul II's election in 1978 was held there
before restoration work began. Francesco Buranelli, director
general of the Vatican Museums and Pontifical Galleries, said,
``John Paul II will be remembered as the last pontiff of this
millennium, and one who will have put his own `signature' in the
Sistine Chapel _ not as a commissioner of new works but as a
conserver of ancient ones.''
</P>
<P>
   The frescoes, executed in 1481 and 1482, some 25 years before
Michelangelo began painting the ``Creation,'' are by the most
famous artists of their time, Tuscans brought to Rome by Pope
Sixtus IV. They are well known to art historians, but less so to
ordinary tourists.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps only in the Sistine Chapel could biblical scenes by the
likes of Botticelli, Ghirlandaio and Perugino be so easily
overlooked by the thousands of visitors who stream through the vast
room every day, heads tilted back to take in Michelangelo's vast
and overpowering vision of Creation, which includes Adam's arm
reaching out to to touch the hand of God. The restoration of the
ceiling, begun in 1979 and completed in 1990, was surrounded by
controversy as a small but emphatic group of critics complained
that the restorers had rendered the ceiling too bright and almost
vulgar.
</P>
<P>
   There were fewer complaints by 1994, when the restoration of
Michelangelo's ``Last Judgment'' was completed. And few art
historians expect much conflict over the cleaning of the
15th-century frescoes. ``I doubt there will be a fuss this time,''
said Luciano Bellosi, a medieval-art historian at the University of
Siena. ``I've seen some of the frescoes, and they were in fairly
good condition, so most of the restoration work is really just a
cleaning. Of course, any restoration represents a kind of trauma to
the work of art, but really, I think this one is very good.''
</P>
<P>
   The experts who studied, cleaned and gently brought the frescoes
back to their original colors say they discovered new details,
including inside jokes, like a small white dog who makes cameo
appearances throughout the frescoes, rearing back from the sight of
drowning Egyptians in a ``Parting of the Red Sea'' by Biagio
d'Antonio, and begging on its hind legs at a ``Last Supper''
painted by Cosimo Rosselli. Nesselrath said that the dog was
probably a mascot of the artists.
</P>
<P>
   He also suggested that a palm tree in the background of the
``Voyage of Moses in Egypt,'' a fresco by Petro Perugino, was added
by Botticelli. ``The cleaning brought out the beautiful, very
precise botanical details that must have been executed by
Botticelli,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The artists and their apprentices executed their work with
unusual speed: It took 30 restorers and technicians five years to
clean frescoes painted in less than a year. Of 16 scenes from the
life of Moses and 12 of the life of Jesus, fewer than a dozen
survive intact, and many were completely destroyed long ago.
Perugino, whose rendition of Jesus' giving keys to St. Peter is
among the most famous of the works, also executed a fresco of the
Assumption of Mary over the altar. That was summarily destroyed to
make room for Michelangelo's ``Last Judgment.''
</P>
<P>
   Nazzareno Gabrielli, the Vatican Museums' director of scientific
research, was one of several restorers eager to enhance the
reputation of the 15th-century artists _ even at Michelangelo's
expense. ``Ghirlandaio was working in extraordinary shades of blue
at the time,'' he said. ``He didn't even know that Michelanelo
existed.''
</P>
<P>
   He lavishly praised the Tuscan artists for adapting so easily to
materials then found only in Rome. ``For the first time, they were
using plaster made of lime and pozzolana,'' he said, referring to a
form of volcanic ash that was also used in ancient Roman times.
``And they painted on it so naturally _ the same as Michelangelo.
But for Michelangelo, it was normal It wasn't for them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
