<SLUG> BC-INVEST-CLOSED-BONDS-ART-$ADV12-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A BIGGER WINDOW FOR BARGAIN MUNIS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Fla., N.Y.)   (ART ADV: Graphic of how $10,000 would have fared in the average
municipal bond fund is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, DEC. 12)  
 (af)  
 By CAROLE GOULD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   December is ordinarily a good month to buy closed-end municipal
bond funds. Tax-related selling by some investors can push down the
funds' prices, creating windows of opportunity for others. And this
year, those windows may be open wider than ever.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is one of the rare opportunities to buy closed-end muni
bond funds at extremely undervalued levels,'' said Thomas J.
Herzfeld, an investment adviser in Miami specializing in closed-end
funds.
</P>
<P>
   The reason, experts say, is unusually heavy tax-loss selling
this year. The bond market has been hit hard by interest-rate
increases by the Federal Reserve, and some investors are selling to
lock in losses for tax purposes. Many investors are also worried
about more rate jumps next year _ a fear that may already be priced
into the market.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is shaping up to be the second-worst year in the bond
market, after 1994, since we started keeping statistics in 1926,''
said George W. Karpus, an investment adviser in Pittsford, N.Y.
``And muni bond funds have done even worse.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike mutual funds, closed-end funds issue a fixed number of
shares that trade in the same way as those of ordinary companies.
As a result, they can trade at discounts or premiums to the value
of their underlying holdings, or net asset value.
</P>
<P>
   Because most closed-end muni funds use leverage, issuing
short-term debt and investing the proceeds in higher-yielding
long-term bonds, the decline in their net asset values and market
prices is magnified.
</P>
<P>
   This year, the decline has been accentuated by a glut of new
funds. Thirty have come to market through November, compared with
just 10 in 1998 and 4 in 1997, Herzfeld said. And some bonds held
by the funds are being called and replaced by lower-yielding
issues. That reduces the fund's net income, resulting in dividend
cuts and putting more downward pressure on prices.
</P>
<P>
   The net asset values of closed-end muni bond funds are down 5
percent this year, on average, through November, according to
Morningstar Inc., the Chicago financial publisher. But their share
prices have fallen further, an average of 15.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, funds are trading at extremely wide discounts to
net asset values; the average discount was nearly 9 percent as of
Nov. 26, versus a premium of 1.4 percent last year. At the start of
2000, as tax selling dries up, those discounts should begin to
narrow.
</P>
<P>
   ``The January effect in closed-end funds generally will be very
pronounced in munis this year because the discounts have gone way
overboard, and will narrow or flip to premiums,'' Herzfeld said.
</P>
<P>
   He added that worries about Year 2000 computer problems, which
may also have held back buyers, should disappear in January.
</P>
<P>
   The recent price decline, of course, has meant rising yields.
Closed-end muni bond funds recently yielded an average of 6.5
percent, tax-free, versus about 6.2 percent for long-term taxable
Treasuries.
</P>
<P>
   Herzfeld likes Van Kampen Strategic Sector Municipal Trust and
Van Kampen Municipal Opportunity Trust II, which yielded 7.0
percent and 7.0 percent, respectively, as of Dec. 8 and traded at
discounts of 15 and 17 percent. He also likes Morgan Stanley Dean
Witter Municipal Premium Income Trust, yielding 7.1 percent on Dec.
8 and trading at a 18 percent discount.
</P>
<P>
   Karpus likes Colonial High Income Municipal Trust, with a yield
of 7.7 percent and a discount of 18 percent as of Dec. 8, and
Blackrock Insured Municipal 2008 Trust, yielding 5.8 percent and at
a 15 percent discount.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
