<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-10 18:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5499 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-FRANCE-MCDONALD'S-NYT     12-10 0981
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRANCE-MCDONALD'S-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Britain, France)  
 THE UNAMERICANIZATION OF McDONALD'S FOR FRENCH CONSUMERS   By JOHN TAGLIABUE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ Say it ain't so, Ronald.
</P>
<P>
   If Ronald McDonald has a naughty side, it burst into full view
in France in recent weeks, where the McDonald's fast-food chain has
come under assault as a symbol of American culinary and commercial
imperialism. The French attack on the burger peaked in August, when
the firebrand head of a farmers union, Jose Bove, was jailed for
organizing the destruction of a McDonald's under construction in a
southern French town.
</P>
<P>
   But now McDonald's France Services, the company that operates
McDonald's restaurants in France, has struck back with a campaign
of full-page newspaper ads that take a potshot at Americans and the
questionable sources of their food _ hormone-treated beef,
genetically modified crops and mass-produced vegetables.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind that a Big Mac in France is made the same way as
elsewhere and tastes pretty much the same, too. The point is that
McDonald's France may have been ``born in the United States,'' as
the ads read, but is ``made in France,'' with French suppliers and
products sold by French employees.
</P>
<P>
   But McDonald's and the agency that created the ads, Euro RSCG
Corporate in Paris, part of the Euro RSCG Worldwide division of
Havas Advertising, now seem more than a little uncomfortable with
the mocking, anti-American tone of the ads, the last of which ran
this week in leading French newspapers, including Le Monde,
Liberation, and Le Figaro.
</P>
<P>
   Lucas Auffret, a spokesman for McDonald's France, said the
company would not discuss the ads, except to quote from a
five-line, prepared statement that says they are part of a ``local
campaign'' whose purpose is to ``reinforce the message that
McDonald's in France is a local French company with local
employees, local franchisees, local suppliers and products.''
</P>
<P>
   The ads' creators at Euro RSCG, under orders from McDonald's,
were not much more informative, though equally defensive.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a completely French campaign; it was not meant as an
attack on Americans,'' said Charlotte De Sereville, who created the
ads together with Marie-Noelle Brouaux. She said it was a
McDonald's decision not to comment.
</P>
<P>
   So how had Ronald been naughty?
</P>
<P>
   The ads, black and white except for a red and gold McDonald's
logo, picture fat, unkempt American men, in cowboy hats or overalls
and camouflage jackets, complaining about the food at McDonald's
France restaurants. One, a grizzled cowboy standing under a snippet
of American flag, moans, ``What I don't like about McDonald's
France is that it doesn't buy American beef.''
</P>
<P>
   Part of the reason for the attacks on McDonald's has been to
protest what many French see as the unfairness of an American
decision to tax French gourmet foods in retaliation for a European
ban on American hormone-treated beef.
</P>
<P>
   The text goes on to say that only by using French beef can
McDonald's trace its source, and thus guarantee ``maximum hygienic
conditions.'' It concludes, addressing the cowboy's 10-gallon hat:
``In any case _ nice hat, John.''
</P>
<P>
   Another ad depicts an immensely obese American male complaining
that McDonald's France serves salads; a third shows a hog-jowled
American in a cowboy hat proclaiming in disbelief: ``McDonald's
France products come from the farm? And they eat them?'' (Read: and
not from the laboratory.)
</P>
<P>
   McDonald's won't say how much the ad campaign cost, though
full-page ads in Le Monde, the leading national paper, average
about $72,000. Ms. De Sereville said Euro RSCG had been
commissioned in July to create the ads, sharing the McDonald's
account in France with other agencies, like BDDP(AT)TBWA, a unit of
the Omnicom Group, which does McDonald's French television
commercials.
</P>
<P>
   Laurel Wentz, editor of Advertising Age International, called
the ads a ``tongue-in-cheek French thing.'' As for Euro RSCG, she
said: ``It's certainly not part of their international positioning.
They're as American as they come.'' Far from being French
provincials, she said, the agency and its chairman and chief
executive, Bob Schmetterer, have recently emphasized their New York
base and international sweep.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Winogrodzki, director of the Advertising Consultancy in
London, recalled that Ikea, the Scandinavian mass furniture
retailer, had run a similar campaign in Britain not long ago,
``aimed at knocking the English _ You know, `You're so English. Be
more cosmopolitan.'''
</P>
<P>
   But self-parody, he said, was a British thing. ``It's very
French to knock someone else,'' he said. ``They took the Yanks, and
made it a joke.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he was amazed that the McDonald's parent company had not
opposed the campaign, given a company penchant for propriety in
advertising.
</P>
<P>
   For its part, McDonald's, which jealously guards every aspect of
its restaurants, was stressing local independence and denying any
paternity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ad programs are local,'' said Agnete Samdahl, a spokeswoman
for the McDonald's Development Co. in London, which oversees
European activities. Some advertising, she said, like commercials,
was produced centrallyfered to national companies, ``but all
decisions are local.''
</P>
<P>
   To what extent McDonald's impressed the French is questionable.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm saddened for Americans who are depicted in these ads as
overweight farmers,'' said Patrice Vidieu, general secretary of the
Confederation Paysanne, the farmers union that organized the
attacks. ``The ad is misplaced.''
</P>
<P>
   Vidieu, who returned recently from Seattle, where he took part
in the anti-globalization protests at the World Trade Organization
ministerial meeting, denied that McDonald's beef was good because
it was French.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're perfectly capable of making industrial beef here,'' he
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
