<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-10 18:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5500 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-HONDURAS-GIFTS11-COX     12-10 1836
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HONDURAS-GIFTS11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gifts from the heart in Honduras
 &HT;    By Bill Hendrick
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN PEDRO SULA, Honduras _Cary Sanders was trying hard to put on
a brave, happy face. She smiled, cooing ``hola'' _ hello in Spanish
_ as she handed a bright green shoe box stuffed with Christmas toys
to Keimy Mejia, a tiny, emaciated 8-year-old girl at a run-down
orphanage for children with AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is this?'' Cary asked through an interpreter, holding up
a palm-sized Etch A Sketch toy to the amazed but overjoyed child,
who grinned broadly as she rummaged excitedly through the box the
16-year-old student had packed back in Conyers, Ga. ``You are so
precious.''
</P>
<P>
   The two played together like sisters for half an hour or so, but
when Cary walked out of the dark, dingy stucco building in a San
Pedro Sula slum and waved goodbye, her grip on her emotions left,
too. She embraced Tracie Watkins and the two Heritage High School
students wept.
</P>
<P>
   It was the end of a long, gut-wrenching day for the Georgia
teens, who were chosen to take part in Franklin Graham's
``Operation Christmas Child'' crusade in Honduras this week because
he thought it would ``help them heal'' from any lingering trauma
caused by last May's shooting at their school that left six
classmates wounded.
</P>
<P>
   Like Cary, Tracie managed to keep her emotions in check as their
delegation mingled with a dozen abandoned AIDS kids. Tracie, an
18-year-old senior who was in a Christian devotional when the
Heritage High shootings occurred, bounced Sandra Martinez, 7, on
her knees, caressing the child's black hair and singing ``Feliz
Navidad,'' the popular song that means ``Merry Christmas.''
</P>
<P>
   Sandra yelped in delight as Tracie pulled a pair of purple
sunglasses out of the gift box she'd packed and put them on the
child's face, then showed her how to style her hair with a
barrette.
</P>
<P>
   The teens had been troopers, traipsing from one orphanage to
another, sloshing through muddy fields to deliver Christmas boxes
to dozens of other destitute children. But the Hogar Amor Y Vida
(Home of Love and Life), their last stop after a long day, proved
too much.
</P>
<P>
   It was enough to make grown men cry, and some did, like Cary's
father, the Rev. Preston Sanders, who came as his daughter's
chaperon. He dabbed at his eyes with a white handkerchief as he
watched with obvious pride as Cary tried to explain her emotions to
people outside. She regained some composure, but lost it when
someone asked how it felt knowing that it was unlikely little Keimy
would be alive this time next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess I just feel blessed to have met her,'' Cary said,
trying unsuccessfully to choke back tears. ``It makes me realize
how fortunate we are in the United States where we don't even see
poverty. This is really powerful. I hope I can give my friends even
a taste of what we have experienced. I want them to know that if
you send a gift box, you have no idea how much it really means to
these kids.''
</P>
<P>
   While Cary, Tracie and others on the mission played inside with
the dying children, healthy ones with muddy bare feet rushed up
from nearby shanties to peer through white metal bars at what was
going on. Graham's organization, Samaritan's Purse, which runs the
annual Operation Christmas Child program, brought more than 300,000
gift boxes to Honduras, but they were given only to the neediest in
one of the poorest countries in the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``You feel almost as sorry for the ones outside as those
inside,'' said Cary's dad, nodding at the kids looking in. ``It's
sensory overload. You can't believe how poor these people are
unless you see it.''
</P>
<P>
   Honduras, known as the original ``banana republic,'' is a
beautiful country with towering mountains of mahogany and cedar
trees, but per capita income in this nation of about 6 million is
less than $700 a year. Most families get by on no money at all,
said Rene Fonseca, who has helped Graham's international relief
group, based in Boone, N.C., aid the poor since Hurricane Mitch
killed an estimated 13,000 Hondurans 14 months ago.
</P>
<P>
   Fonseca, an American-educated former presidential candidate in
Honduras who plans to run again, said Graham's assistance was
sorely needed and will be for years. He has been helping the
47-year-old evangelist _ the son and already-appointed successor of
his father, Billy Graham _ organize a project to build homes for
tens of thousands whose mud or thatched huts were washed away by
floods from the hurricane.
</P>
<P>
   Standing outside another orphanage visited by the Heritage kids,
about 35 miles south of San Pedro Sula, Fonseca walked down a muddy
road to a cluster of 30 cinder block houses, each 15 by 20 feet in
size. So far, Samaritan's Purse has built nearly 4,000 of the
houses in areas all across the Tennessee-sized country.
</P>
<P>
   Tracie and Cary walked into many of the homes and were quickly
surrounded by grateful residents. One man said he saved his four
children and wife by tying them to a tree when flood waters in the
valley swept everything away. Tracie, who took off her mud-caked
sneakers before entering one of the homes, marveled that the owner
insisted on tying her shoes as she left.
</P>
<P>
   Graham, in daily morning devotionals during the weeklong trip,
cautioned Cary and Tracie and the rest of their delegation _ about
a dozen people, one of several Samaritan's Purse groups making
concurrent visits _ to be careful but polite. The water is not safe
to drink, he said, so they should decline token offerings of
thanks. And even in San Pedro Sula, a city of more than 330,000,
the streets are not safe. Men armed with pump shotguns make
themselves visible in front of banks and other businesses. In
Balsamo, where the cinder block home village is located, soldiers
of the National Police in camouflage fatigues tote M-16 rifles with
long curved ammunition clips.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. State Department has warned tourists that
machete-wielding bandits roam the countryside, often hijacking
passenger cars, cabs and even buses, sometimes between San Pedro
Sula and its airport about 10 miles away.
</P>
<P>
   Tracie and Cary looked out of their bus windows in amazement as
peasant women washed clothes by hand in a muddy stream down a steep
hill from their shantytown village, where homes look like
clubhouses built in American back yards by kids using scrap lumber.
Buses and cars dodged mule-drawn carts hauling firewood or small
batches of bananas.
</P>
<P>
   Graham, an energetic man who'd sent an army of employees of
Samaritan's Purse to pave the way for gift-bearing Americans, was
upset that the pilgrimage, which began Monday in Atlanta, started
out on a sour note. Just before the Conyers teens and their
delegation boarded their plane in Atlanta, rumors flew about the
latest school shooting spree in Oklahoma.
</P>
<P>
   Few details were available here until Wednesday, and Graham, who
piloted a twin-engine Samaritan's Purse jet from Atlanta to San
Pedro Sula, was clearly upset.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our country has become so violent,'' he said during an
interview between stops. ``Everything is blood. The movies. The
video games. We have a generation of kids who know nothing but
violence. As long as we have this stuff, it's just going to get
worse. I'm just glad Cary and Tracie have a chance to come out and
show the good we do have in our schools.''
</P>
<P>
   But no one in the delegation had time to think too much about
the incident. After arriving late Monday, they spent the rest of
the week visiting orphanages and sick children and helping Graham's
paid staff and volunteers distribute Christmas shoe boxes.
</P>
<P>
   Each day began and ended with a devotional and short sermons by
Graham and other preachers in his ministry, which has 307
employees, most based in Boone. Buses ran on a tight schedule on
narrow roads where anarchy appeared to be the main traffic rule. It
was clear each stop had been carefully planned, because everything
went off like clockwork.
</P>
<P>
   The pilgrimage climaxed at a run-down hospital in San Pedro
Sula, where the delegation gave gifts to stunned-looking children,
victims of accidents or parental neglect. Most children didn't even
muster a smile when handed gift boxes and hadn't seen toys before.
</P>
<P>
   After opening a box, Reina Orbelina, 4, didn't seem to know what
to do with a doll inside, but Judy Pressley Hauck, a 47-year-old
Heritage counselor who served as Tracie's chaperon, quickly showed
the malnourished girl, whose arms weren't much bigger than a garden
hose.
</P>
<P>
   The Heritage girls stayed busy handing out gifts piled high on
metal carts that were pushed by Samaritan's Purse staffers. Though
the children in the crammed wards didn't seem to know what to make
of the commotion, their parents did. Adults came out of rooms to
beckon gift-givers in to make sure their children received
something for Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   Cary, Tracie, Hauck and Preston Sanders opened boxes of crayons,
then showed the sick kids how to use them in cartoonish coloring
books.
</P>
<P>
   ``This picture is going to be so pretty,'' Cary said to
Esperanza Vasquez, 7, who showed little emotion.
</P>
<P>
   Graham's organization has delivered shoe box gifts to more than
80 countries around the world since 1993. In a week he leaves for
Kosovo and will be accompanied by Crystal Woodman, a 17-year-old
senior at Columbine High School in Littleton, Colo., where students
killed 13 people a few weeks before the shootings at Heritage.
</P>
<P>
   Graham, who concedes he was once a Scotch-guzzling ``hell
raiser,'' gave up smoking after he ``accepted Christ'' while in
Jerusalem at age 22. A sincere man given to black lizard skin
cowboy boots and bluejeans, he talks fondly of his father and
ailing mother, whom he said he regrets disappointing during his
years as a ``rebel.''
</P>
<P>
   His mother ``got on me good,'' he laughed, after he drove a Land
Rover from London to the Middle East with a bottle of Scotch in one
hand and the other on the steering wheel.
</P>
<P>
   He gave up drinking 10 years ago and has been running
Samaritan's Purse, which has a $110 million annual budget, since
1979. He said he can relate to kids in trouble, even those who're
driven to ``crazy'' acts, because he spent so much time on a
wayward path.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a sinner,'' he said. ``The Bible says we have all sinned.
I'm still a sinner. I've been to hell on earth, Rwanda, Beirut,
Kosovo.''
</P>
<P>
   And many other places, he said, ``that are even worse off than
Honduras.''
</P>
<P>
   For now, until his father passes the mantle of the Billy Graham
Evangelistic Association to him, he said, he'll devote his time to
aiding the poor and helping American kids like Tracie and Cary
understand ``how much need is out there and what they can do.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope for these young girls it gives them a whole
appreciation for what they have, and to make others see it, too,''
Graham said. ``Bad things happen. But things aren't hopeless. Now
Tracie and Cary know that, too, and they will bear witness.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
