<HEADLINE>
&HT;     CUBA CAPITALIZING ON REFUGEE BOY'S PLIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds.: Accents on A in Elian, A in Gonzalez and second O in
Broton.)  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE FAINARU  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
<TEXT>
 &QL;
<P>
   CARDENAS, Cuba _ The first-grade classroom at Marcelo Salado
Primary School contains a single green desk, on top of which rests
a folded Cuban flag, six neatly stacked books and a pencil holder.
</P>
<P>
   A message is taped to the back of the tiny chair: ``Elian, your
seat is untouchable.''
</P>
<P>
   The 6-year-old pupil, Elian Gonzalez, was discovered over
Thanksgiving, clinging to an innertube off the Miami coast. He had
been separated from his 30-year-old mother, Elizabet Broton, a maid
who apparently perished along with several others who had hired an
ill-fated powerboat to take them to the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The Cuban government has organized daily demonstrations to
demand Elian's return, in the most heated showdown with Washington
since Cuban fighters downed two unarmed planes belonging to a Miami
exile group in 1996. In Cardenas, where the boy's father and four
grandparents still live, Elian has been turned into a kind of
living martyr. His innocent face is plastered everywhere _ in
doorways, on billboards and street banners _ and yet his friends
and relatives have no idea when they might see him again.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been so long, I can't take this anymore,'' said Mariela
Quintana, Elian's paternal grandmother. ``I don't understand why
it's taking them so long to bring him home. It's just too much to
take.''
</P>
<P>
   Quintana burst into tears while standing in her son's living
room and asked to postpone the interview. A family friend, who
identified himself as Gustavo, said Thursday that the family had
been under additional stress because they had been unable to talk
to Elian the past two days. The boy has no legal status in the US
but remains under the temporary custody of a great uncle in Miami.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes they call and the line is always busy,'' said
Gustavo. ``Sometimes they call and they just hang up on the other
end. It's inhuman.''
</P>
<P>
   A few blocks away, in the apartment where Elian's maternal
grandparents live above a pharmacy, an elderly man who identified
himself as an uncle said the boy's other grandmother, Raquel
Rodriguez, had required medical attention earlier in the day
because of the stress. He said she had gone to stay with her
sister.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's terrible, she hasn't slept much in five days,'' said the
man, who declined to give his name and said he had been asked to
watch over the apartment.
</P>
<P>
   Elian's immediate fate appeared to revolve around his father,
Juan Miguel Gonzalez, a Communist Party member who works at a plum
job as a bellman in Varadero, a nearby beach resort. US officials
said they have been negotiating with the Cuban government to have
the Immigration and Naturalization Service interview Gonzalez to
prove that he is Elian's natural father and would like to see him
returned.
</P>
<P>
   Although the custody arrangement is still unclear, Elian
apparently spent as much time with his father, his stepmother and
his three-month-old half brother as he did with his mother. Yosbel
Perez, 27, a cook who lives across the street from the family, said
Elian ``lived with both sides'' and was often seen playing baseball
in the street with his father.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is very much a hands-on father,'' said Perez.
</P>
<P>
   US officials requested to interview Perez Wednesday evening but
said they received no response from the Cuban goverment. The next
day, President Fidel Castro said in an open letter published in
Granma, the Communist Party newspaper, that Gonzalez had decided
not to subject himself to an interview with any US government
official, a position that Castro said he supported. Later, US
officials said they hoped that the issue was still open.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Gonzalez's relatives said he had traveled to
Havana, about 90 miles west of Cardenas, but declined to say what
his mission was or where he could be located. The sequence of
events has suggested that Washington may be slowly preparing to
return Elian to his father.
</P>
<P>
   ``Would you just send back a kid without knowing this is his
father?'' said one US official when asked why the process has taken
so long. ``The issue has been spotlighted and you don't want to
make a mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Elian only continues to grow as a symbol. After
more than 100,000 people marched Thursday past the US Interest
Section on the Malecon, the curving road that runs along the Havana
beachfront, thousands more people turned out Friday in Santiago,
Havana's second largest city. There were other sizeable protests in
other cities around the country.
</P>
<P>
   The protests have been promoted and organized by the government,
which has used state-owned buses to ferry people to the
demonstrations. A US official derided the protests as staged events
that offered ``a rallying point'' for Cubans despite the ``rather
sad state of the revolution at this point.''
</P>
<P>
   But the sentiments behind the protests appeared to be real,
fueled by Elian's close relationship with his father and the way
Cuban exiles in Miami have showered the boy with toys, as if to buy
his allegiance. Sylvio Rodriguez, the folk singer, drew a huge roar
from a crowd earlier this week when he sang two songs to Elian and
announced: ``I am here as a father, and, of course, a a Cuban.''
</P>
<P>
   In a poem posted on a bulletin board in Elian's classroom, a
woman wrote:
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(poetry style) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   To see your mother die
</P>
<P>
   Is a pain that never leaves
</P>
<P>
   And now, to be with your own,
</P>
<P>
   You cannot, cannot even cry
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   How is it possible that there exists
</P>
<P>
   So much egoism and cruelty
</P>
<P>
   This little one is a child
</P>
<P>
   He is not a toy to be played with
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(end poetry style) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Elian's classroom essentially exists now as a shrine to the
little boy. On the wall is a picture if Elian wearing his his
school uniform _ red shorts, a white shirt and a blue kerchief _
and a pair of Nikes. A table is strewn with letters and poems
written to him from all over the country. On another table is a
book signed by hundreds of Cubans, including Castro, who visited
the school Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the freedom of Eliancito,'' wrote Castro, referring to the
boy by his nickname. ``Fatherland or death.''
</P>
<P>
   Near the door is an easel on which the boy was apparently just
learning to assemble words. On top of the easel, E-L-I-A-N is
spelled out in cardboard squares covered with letters written in a
black marker.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had just learned to write his name,'' said a teacher
supervising the shrine. ``That's all he could write.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
