<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-10 19:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5509 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-CHECHNYA-SIEGE-BOS &LR;      12-10 1637
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHECHNYA-SIEGE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOT MANY USING `SAFE CORRIDOR' OUT OF GROZNY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID FILIPOV  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHECKPOINT SEVER, Russia _ High on a wind-swept hill overlooking
Chechnya's burning, bombed-out capital of Grozny, a small crowd of
haggard-looking civilians crowded at a checkpoint Friday, held back
by heavily armed Russian riot police.
</P>
<P>
   The checkpoint straddles the ``humanitarian corridor'' the
Russian military command has opened to allow Chechen civilians to
leave Grozny and avoid a massive assault on the city the army has
threatened to unleash Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   But the only people who reach Checkpoint Sever are those willing
to brave the constant Russian shelling of the besieged capital and
able to walk several miles up a steep moutinroad north of the city.
That ruled out most of the civilians trapped in Grozny, according
to refugees who arrived here Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many people, old people, ill people, Chechens, Russians, many
of them are still there, hiding in their cellars,'' said one woman
who gave only her first name, Malika, as she waited for police to
check her papers. ``They are cut off from the world. They have no
heat or light or food. They cannot even go outside for bread,
because the Russians stop us with their bombardment. They can't
even bury their dead.''
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, the Russian army dropped leaflets saying it would
kill anybody who remained in Grozny after Saturday. The leaflets
also promised safe passage for anyone who left. But by midday
Friday, only 330 refugees had been registered at Checkpoint
Severny.
</P>
<P>
   The ongoing bombardment, and the slow outflow of refugees, have
raised questions about the goals of the Russian commanders'
warning. Independent observers have suggested that the threat to
kill everybody in Grozny was a sign that the Russian generals are
under pressure to finish the war in Chechnya as quickly as possible
after taking three months to occupy half of a republic about the
size of Connecticut. And some have expressed concern that the
military is considering more powerful weapons _ from fuel-air bombs
to gas _ to clear the city of an estimated 3,000-6,000 rebel
fighters.
</P>
<P>
   Russian officers at Checkpoint Sever Friday gave several
explanations for the slow trickle of civilians. One said a computer
that checks each refugee's record for criminal activity failed to
work until Thursday. Another claimed that most of the civilinhad
already left Grozny, but that flies in the face of the Russian
government estimate that up to 45,000 civilians remain. A third
said the Chechen rebels were not letting anyone out, a charge that
refugees and a rebel spokesman denied.
</P>
<P>
   The ultimatum has provoked outrage in the West, and Friday a top
Russian politician, breaking with the generally supportive mood on
Chechnya, joined in the criticism of what the Kremlin calls its
``anti-terrorist operation'' in the separatist republic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Will everyone get out? And if they don't, will they also be
destroyed?,'' asked Moscow Mayor Yury Luzhkov, leader of an
anti-Kremlin political alliance, at a conference in Moscow. ``Thi
is no way to fight terrorism.''
</P>
<P>
   Senior Russian officials are now trying to play down the
ultimatum, saying it was aimed at rebel fighters in Grozny and
designed to save civilian lives. Friday, Emergency Situations
Minister Sergei Shoigu backed away further, saying Russian forces
would interrupt combat operations to let civilians leave.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no deadline. Everything will be all right,'' Shoigu
told NTV television. ``What deadline? Is it the end of the world
tomorrow?''
</P>
<P>
   Shoigu is the leader of a Kremlin-backed party which is vying
with Luzhkov's alliance for seats in the Duma, or parliament, in an
election set for December 19.
</P>
<P>
   In Chechnya, Colonel Alexander Veklich, a Russian military
spokesman, said federal forces had halted their barrage against
Grozny days ago to let civilians out.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not true, they bombed us all last night,'' said Malika
Friday. ``Just like they've been bombing us for the past two
months. They haven't killed any fighters, u they've killed lots of
us.''
</P>
<P>
   Refugees said the bombardment has been so bad the past few days
that many people in Grozny did not know about the ultimatum because
they dared not venture outdoors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today, someone told us about the safe corridor, and we decided
to risk it,'' said Khasan Takayev, who fled with his wife and two
small children.
</P>
<P>
   Colonel Veklich acknowledged that there may have been some
fighting in recent days, but he blamed the rebels for the small
number of refugees. He said the insurgents wanted to use civilians
as ``human shields'' and had shot at anyone who tried to escape the
city.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have not fired at Grozny today,'' Veklich said. As he
spoke, a salvo of explosions erupted on a nearby ridge, sounding
suspiciously like outgoing artillery. Veklich said troops were
using explosives to dig a trench. Another salvo sounded. A reporter
asked some soldiers what it was.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're digging a trench,'' one said.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, that's outgoing artillery,'' said another.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shut up, Sergei!'' said the first soldier.
</P>
<P>
   It was not the only contradiction at this checkpoint, or around
Grozny. Shoigu, the minister, said buses would use six routes to
take refugees safely to Russian-controlled territory in the north.
But there wasonly one open road.
</P>
<P>
   And why was the checkpoint way up on the hilltop, far from the
highway leading out of the city in the valley below?
</P>
<P>
   A military spokesman said the road was the most convenient route
out of the city. But soldiers manning Russian positions on the
mountain offered a different explanation _ despite Russian claims
that Grozny is completely encircled, the military has not been able
to take control of the road, and rebel fighters still command a
village outside Grozny.
</P>
<P>
   ``The 245th brigade tried to take it, but they couldn't,'' said
one soldier, who asked to remain anonymous. ``They were ambushed
and lost eight guys. We still haven't taken it. It is far from calm
here.''
</P>
<P>
   Those losses were not reported by the military _ in the official
version of events, that ambush never happened. In fact, the
official death toll has actually fallen since last month, when the
government information center said 452 servicemen had died and
1,485 had been wounded since Russian troops began fighting Islamic
militants who invaded Dagestan, a region next to Chechnya, in
August.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Russian commanders said their losses totalled 379
dead and 800 wounded for the entire campaign. No explanation was
given for the lower casualty count.
</P>
<P>
   Russian commanders in the field do not talk about their losses,
they talk about successes. Colonel Sergei Skiba, an infantry
commander with a fur hat and white beard, described how his unit
wiped out a rebel force near a train station three miles east of
Grozny last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were well dug-in, but we surprised them,'' Skiba said as
he showed off elaborate trenches he said were dug by the rebels.
``We came in from behind when they expected us to attack head on.
They thought they would hold out for long, but we showed them we
have an army, too.''
</P>
<P>
   He handed a reporter a pair of binoculars, which revealed a line
of Russian tanks and armored vehicles in the distance. Beyond them
stood the battered houses and buildings of Grozny. Thick plmes of
smoke from burning oil wells blackened the sky. The city center,
already badly damaged during the 1994-1996 war that left Chechnya
de facto independent of Moscow, has been totally flattened by
Moscow's campaign to bring he region back under its control.
</P>
<P>
   Russian commanders say the Chechen fighters inside Grozny cannot
cross their lines. But Russian soldiers, and the rebels, say the
separatists move easily at night. Analysts say this means that even
as the numerically and technically superior Russian force takes
towns and territory, they are vulnerable to guerilla attacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let them try,'' said Colonel Skiba.
</P>
<P>
   He said his troops have an advantage the Russians lacked in the
last war _ the support of villagers. Towns that refused to take in
rebel fighters were spared bombardment, a fact made clear by a ride
on a BMP-2 troop carrier through a muddy field just outside Grozny.
</P>
<P>
   To the left was a train station and a cluster of houses, all
destroyed, where Chechens had taken up positions. To the right was
the unscathed village of Tsentora-yurt, which made a deal with the
army.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not fighting them,'' Skiba said. ``They are Russian
citizens like us.''
</P>
<P>
   A few minutes later, Colonel Veklich said the Chechens had blown
up canisters containing toxic chemicals in Khankala, a suburb on
the eastern outskirts of Grozny, and winds were carrying a toxic
cloud northwest over the Chechen capital.
</P>
<P>
   Veklich said the cloud likely consisted of chlorine and ammonia.
He said it was impossible to assess immediately if there was any
danger to civilians, but that the cloud would disperse within two
hours.
</P>
<P>
   ``The rebels are trying any men to keep people from leaving,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   A Chechen spokesman had a different story. He said Russian
artillery had hit a storage tank of chemicals at a former military
factory. The spokesman, Sharip Yusupov, said the rebels had
frequently warned the military not to hit the factory.
</P>
<P>
   Pavel Felgenhauer, an independent Russian military analysts, has
suggested that Moscow might be planning to use chemical weapons to
clear the city of fighters. In an interview last week, he said that
if the weapons were used, the Russians could then easily claim it
was the Chechens who employed them.
</P>
<P>
   Contradictions.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Globe researcher Anastasiya Saschikhina contributed to this report
from Moscow.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
