<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-TALKS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOTE FROM CLINTON LED TO ISRAEL-SYRIA TALKS RENEWAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN DONNELLY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ When Israeli and Syrian leaders meet next week at
the White House to resume negotating a return of the high Golan
plateau for the promise of peace, they will know full well that it
was the third man in the room who got them there.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton, who sees the chance of a peace deal as a
crowning achievement to his two terms in office, pointedly passed a
message to Syrian President Hafez Assad three months ago that time
was running out if he wanted the return of the Golan Heights, said
US officials, speaking on the condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   ``We told him, `The train is pulling out of the station,' ''
said one administration official who works on Middle East issues.
``What just happened was that Assad decided to get on the train.''
</P>
<P>
   The train is Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   By his and others' reckoning, Assad and Israeli Prime Minister
Ehud Barak can either work out a deal now in the last year of
Clinton's presidency, or they can wait for several years _ if then
_ until the next US president is prepared to step in as broker.
Historically, complex foreign policy negotiations, especially
involving the Middle East, are not seriously undertaken until after
a president's first year in office.
</P>
<P>
   The talks, which will open Wednesday with Clinton and then move
to the Blair House, a nearby presidential guest house, will
encompass several issues, including Israel's withdrawal from the
Golan Heights, which was captured from Syria in 1967, security
arrangements, and the nature of peace between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
   If a deal is reached _ a major if _ the repercussions would
reverberate far beyond Golan, which explains the excitement being
felt by so many in the Clinton administration and in the Middle
East. A deal presumably means that Israel would pull its troops out
of southern Lebanon; that the Lebanese army would crack down on the
Hezbollah guerrilla fighters; that radical groups in Iran would
lose an avenue of attack on Israel; and that Israel would be
encircled by old enemies who had made peace with it. That leaves
one negotiation unfinished _ the most difficult one, with the
Palestinians, over the future of Jerusalem, the West Bank, water
rights, and return of refugees.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has long been obsessed with the prospect of putting
together the pieces of a comprehensive peace deal, even spending
most of nine days in the fall of 1998 to wrest several incremental
advances in the Israeli-Palestinian peace track. He also has been
obsessed with getting credit for being the dealmaker and winning
his place in history alongside former President Jimmy Carter, who
brokered the Camp David accords between Israel and Egypt. Clinton
has insisted to his senior aides that he must be the one who
announced any advances _ not subordinates and not Middle East
leaders, either.
</P>
<P>
   In the Israel-Syria talks, Clinton sees the prospect of
breakthrough, but only if the talks begin now.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a clear understanding in Syria that this is the last
chance for the Clinton administration,'' said Shibley Telhami, who
holds the Anwar Sadat Chair for Peace and Development at the
University of Maryland. ``If they didn't do it this time, (the
administration) would move on to other issues.''
</P>
<P>
   Richard W. Murphy, director of Middle East Studies at the
Council on Foreign Relations in New York and ambassador to Syria
from 1974 to 1977, said Assad told him in 1974 that ``there had to
be active American participation before there is any peace deal.''
</P>
<P>
   ``His first words to me were, `You are more than a middleman,'
'' Murphy said. ``I think President Clinton may only have had to
promise him that America would be actively involved in the
negotiation.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said more than that, but the details remain a mystery.
When he announced the resumption of talks, which had broken off
more than three years ago, he said he took a ``blood oath'' not to
reveal his terms of persuasion.
</P>
<P>
   But, said one US official, ``it took a lot of finessing to get
Assad'' to reopen talks.
</P>
<P>
   Assad, whose health has been failing for several years, is
sending Foreign Minister Farouk al-Sharaa to negotiate on his
behalf, while Barak will represent his country. It represents the
highest level talks ever between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
   After the talks shift to the Blair House, they will likely
include Secretary of State Madeleine K. Albright, US officials
said. The discussions, scheduled to last two days, are aimed at
establishing a framework for tackling the outstanding issues.
</P>
<P>
   Further talks could be held either near Washington or at a
Middle East location. Barak, who said when he was elected in June
that he wanted to withdraw troops from Lebanon in a year's time,
has told US officials that he expects difficult negotiations with
Syria but that a solution ``could come fast, and we're talking
weeks, not months,'' the US official said.
</P>
<P>
   Optimism is running so high in some quarters in Israel that
there have already been newspaper articles speculating when Barak
will visit Syria. US officials offer more tempered assessments but
clearly see the talks as a big step forward.
</P>
<P>
   Said longtime US Middle East negotiator Dennis Ross Friday:
``Clearly, both sides have a level of confidence about the
possibility of needs being met, and that's one of the reasons that
they have come to the conclusion that it's important to get back to
the table and try to work things out.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
