<SLUG> BC-FAA-PILOTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAA TO ENFORCE RULES GOVERNING RESERVE PILOT HOURS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW BRELIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Federal Aviation Administration informed airlines Friday
that it will begin enforcing a rule requiring reserve pilots to
have at least nine hours of rest in the last day before they can be
called in to fly an airplane.
</P>
<P>
   Because airlines are worried about having to cancel flights if
crews are not available to fly, some 11 airlines _ including major
carriers American Airlines, Northwest Airlines and US Airways _ had
asked the FAA for an extension. But the agency granted only one
extension, to Comair, a relatively small carrier.
</P>
<P>
   Margaret Gilligan, FAA deputy associate administrator for
regulation and certification, said the FAA had notified airlines in
June that the rule, which in effect requires reserve or ``on call''
status not to be considered rest time, would be implemented in six
months.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they were in noncomplaince at the time, we believed six
months a reasonable period of time for them to make corrections,''
Gilligan said in a telephone conference.
</P>
<P>
   Reserve pilots are full-time airline employees, but much like
substitute teachers, they fill in when a regularly scheduled pilot
is sick or cannot continue to fly. Most pilots are paid only for
the hours they fly.
</P>
<P>
   The reserve rest rule had been in place since at least 1991, but
not enforced. For the most part, airlines interpreted reserve
status or pilots ``on call'' as resting.
</P>
<P>
   ``The airlines have known about this upcoming requirement since
last June,'' said Duane Woerth, president of the Air Line Pilots
Association. ``There is absolutely no excuse for granting any more
leeway. Any extensions would be unfair to the airlines that acted
in good faith to meet the requirement, and unfair to the traveling
public, which expects that existing FAA safety rules will be
enforced.''
</P>
<P>
   Airlines are increasingly faced with pilot shortages as older
pilots retire, and the demand for air travel increases. Hiring and
training pilots is expensive and takes time. The costs will borne
by travelers in the form of higher ticket prices.
</P>
<P>
   The Air Transport Association, the industry's trade association,
has estimated that carriers will have to hire about 3 percent more
pilots to comply with the new regulations.
</P>
<P>
   Gilligan said FAA inspectors will begin on Monday conducting a
comprehensive review of the scheduling of airlines. Once inspectors
have a baseline understanding of the scheduling systems, they will
begin to collect data on the actual schedules of reserve crews used
to see if the FAA requirement is being met, a process that is
expected to take several months.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they find noncompliance, they will bring that to the
carrier's attention and will see if the carrier made a good-faith
effort to comply,'' said Gilligan. The FAA could take action
ranging from written letters to fines.
</P>
<P>
   Comair, a regional airline, was granted an extension until April
1. Gilligan said Comair officials worked with FAA inspectors and
presented a plan to hire and train new pilots and were making ``a
good-faith effort.''
</P>
<P>
   The FAA said the other airlines that asked for extensions but
were denied were American Eagle, Piedmont, Allegheny, Midwest
Express, Air Midwest, Pacific Southwest Airlines, and Skyways
Airlines.
</P>
<P>
   Piedmont, Allegheny and PSA are owned by US Airways. US Airways
spokesman David Castelveter said the airline ``will comply with the
new reserve crew rest rules while making every effort to keep our
schedule intact. Should there be any impact, we expect it to be in
line with the industry.''
</P>
<P>
   Pilot fatigue is a contentious issue in aviation and the
National Transportation Safety Board has made numerous
recommendations to the FAA to improve regulatory oversight of pilot
scheduling to reduce fatigue. The NTSB is scheduled to hold
hearings next month on the June 1 crash of an American Airlines
flight at Little Rock, Ark. that killed 11 people. One issue the
NTSB is examining is flight crew decision-making and its
relationship to fatigue. The crew was approaching the maximum
amount of time it could work for one day.
</P>
<P>
   The FAA proposed new rules in 1995, but received so many
criticisms in the public comment period it withdrew the proposal.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
