<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HANCOCK-IPO-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HANCOCK IPO YIELD EXPECTED TO APPROACH $2.6 BILLION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNNLEY BROWNING  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ John Hancock Mutual Life Insurance Co. could raise
nearly $2.6 billion, one-quarter more than originally expected,
when it sells stock to the public next month.
</P>
<P>
   According to a document Hanockc filed Friday with securities
regulators, the amount would constitute one of the largest initial
public offerings ever for a financial services company.
</P>
<P>
   The Boston insurer originally anticipated raising $2 billion in
its sale, set for Jan. 27. That figure was computed by multiplying
the 102 million shares that Hancock will sell by the estimated $20
per share price indicated by the company in a September filing.
</P>
<P>
   A new document filed with the Securities and Exchange Commission
offered a price range for Hancock of $15 to $25 per share. The
upper end of the scale means the company could raise $2.55 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Hancock, the nation's 13th-largest life insurer, is converting
from a mutual company owned by policyholders to a stock company
owned by shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   While the company's stock will be formally priced the night
before it is sold, the initial price is likely to fall somewhere in
the range indicated by Hancock.
</P>
<P>
   The range is particularly broad _ there is a 66.6 percent
difference between the low and the high price _ because Hancock had
to notify regulatory authorities of its conversion plan months in
advance . The range must be able to accommodate market swings,
which are harder to project further out. Most companies file
initial public offering prospectuses much closer to the actual
offering date and have smaller ranges of around 15 percent.
</P>
<P>
   A price of $25 a share values Hancock at $8.3 billion. And it
gives Hancock a book value of $15 per share. The investment
community will calibrate the initial price against projected
earnings _ still a company secret under SEC rules. Independent
industry analysts have said Hancock could be worth up to $14
billion once in public hands.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to selling shares to the public, Hancock will issue
an additional 231.2 million shares to policyholders who are
eligible for compensation for their ownership rights in the old
company. Hancock will have a total 333.2 million shares of
outstanding common stock. The company has 3.3 million
policyholders, including 2.9 million eligible for compensation.
</P>
<P>
   Hancock will spend the bulk of its sale proceeds, or $1.7
billion, compensating policyholders with cash and policy credits.
It will retain $200 million for internal uses, including paying out
shareholder dividends in 2000. Had the company been public this
year, it could have paid out $607.1 million in shareholder
dividends based on its 1998 financial results, according to
Friday's SEC filing.
</P>
<P>
   The document said Hancock will spend at least $252 million on
the administrative and transaction costs of ``demutualization,'' as
the conversion process is known. About $100 million of the total
will go to the investment bankers and underwriters, led by Morgan
Stanley Dean Witter, who will sell Hancock stock to professional
investors.
</P>
<P>
   The 137-year-old company wants to go public to have stock as a
currency for acquisitions and to better compensate hard-to-retain
talent.
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts insurance regulators and Hancock policyholders
have approved the company's conversion.
</P>
<P>
   Hancock is eager to get its shares out on the market before a
host of other competitors, including Metropolitan Life Insurance
Co. of New York, issue first-time stock next spring.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
