<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEARNINGSMITH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEARNINGSMITH GOING OUT OF BUSINESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS REIDY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Learningsmith Inc., the educational toys-and-games
retail chain founded by entrepreneur Marshall Smith that counted
public TV station WGBH as an early investor, plans to close all 87
of its stores by mid-January and go out of business.
</P>
<P>
   Learningsmith employs about 850 full-time workers and 1,500
part-timers, said Harold B. Murphy of Hanify &AMP; King, the Boston law
firm that represents Learningsmith.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are putting in place a severance package,'' he said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the Bulington, mass. company's senior executives,
including chief executive Janet Emerson, have already ``departed,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The company anticipates liquidating all of its assets, and
store-closing inventory sales are presently under way at the
company's 87 store locations throughout the country,''
Learningsmith said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   The statement was issued Friday shortly after the company filed
for Chapter 11 protection in US Bankruptcy Court in Boston. In
court documents, Learningsmith listed assets of $60.7 million and
debts of $65 million.
</P>
<P>
   Even during the holiday shopping season, fun and games can be a
tough business.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very competitive environment,'' Murphy said.
</P>
<P>
   Presumably, Learningsmith couldn't figure out how to attract
enough of the consumers' toy dollar in a world where everyone from
Wal-Mart to Target and Toys ``R'' Us is selling toys.
</P>
<P>
   As if competition wasn't already fierce enough, brick-and-mortar
toy sellers face new competiton from Internet retailers such as
eToys.com, Amazon.com, and toysmart.com.
</P>
<P>
   Learningsmith attempted to stand out from this crowd by offering
distinct product lines that were available nowhere else. But those
products were believed to account for less than 40 percent of the
store merchandise.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, many items could be found at other stores such as
Zany Brainy or Noodle Kidoodle. Often, larger rivals could sell
items at lower prices than Learningsmith could.
</P>
<P>
   Brio, a Swedish toy company that sold products to Learningsmith,
suggested the chain ``lacked focus.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Only about 10 percent of what they sell are toys,'' said
president Peter Reynolds of Brio's US subsidiary. ``You couldn't go
there as a destination. It was a place for impulse buys.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides toys, Learningsmith sells computer software, art
supplies, books, puzzles, and science projects.
</P>
<P>
   A privately owned company, Learningsmith never disclosed sales
or earnings.
</P>
<P>
   Among the creditors listed on Learningsmith's court documents
were Citizens Financial Group Inc., Brio, and founder Smith.
</P>
<P>
   Smith said he has had no involvement with Learningsmith in
recent years. He said he left Learningsmith in the mid 1990s to
start Cybersmith, a cafe concept with computer terminals wired to
the Internet at almost every table.
</P>
<P>
   Cybersmith also filed for Chapter 11 this year.
</P>
<P>
   Big Learningsmith suppliers such as Brio have insurance to help
cover their losses. But small suppliers can be out of luck.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like I was robbed,'' said Julia Blagden, who runs a
tiny San Francisco firm that supplied CDs of children's music to
Learningsmith. ``This is going to screw me.''
</P>
<P>
   When it was founded in 1991, Learningsmith was believed to be a
new kind of store, one that eschewed violent toys to focus on
educational learning experiences for kids and adults.
</P>
<P>
   WGBH was an early investor, and the chain was once known as WGBH
Learningsmith. Among items sometimes found on store shelves were
videos and companion books of the Nova and Masterpiece Theater
series, two staples of public television.
</P>
<P>
   WGBH incrementally invested about $1 million in Learningsmith in
its early years; none of that money came from member donations or
government funding, said Jeanne Hopkins, a WGBH vice president.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our investment was earned back and then some,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   When Learningsmith made a big push to expand nationally a few
years ago, WGBH opted to play a reduced role, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We essentially licensed our name to the stores in the Boston
area,'' Hopkins said. ``But we never had any involvement in
management.''
</P>
<P>
   WGBH viewers who make donations to the station can qualify for
discounts at Learningsmith stores.
</P>
<P>
   Said Hopkins, ``Whether they will still honor that, I don't
know.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
