<HEADLINE>
SAMSONOV STATISTICS HIGH ON ASSISTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Ts News Service clients)  
 By JIM GREENIDGE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; BOSTON _ It's not very often that Bruins left wing Sergei
Samsonov looks at his season statistics and notices he has more
assists (seven) than goals (six).
</P>
<P>
   But that's the case this season for the third-year right wing,
who was the rookie of the year in 1997-98 with 22 goals and 25
assists in 81 games. Last season, he bettered those numbers
(25-26-51) in 79 games.
</P>
<P>
   Samsonov believes he should be more productive.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could be better than six goals,'' said the 5-foot-8-inch,
184-pound Russian. ``It seems I'm getting chances every game, but
I'm not burying the puck. One day, though, that's going to come.
And then there are the assists _ I've never had more assists than
I've had goals.''
</P>
<P>
   Last season, opponents played Smsonov differently, making sure
that he didn't simply get the puck and scoot by without being
checked. Now Samsonov is getting hit more.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are paying attention to be right now,'' said Samsonov,
who has had only one two-goal game, against the Buffalo Sabres Oct.
30. ``Opposing teams are watching the tapes and they're seeing what
kind of moves I make and I'm trying to adjust to that. I knew that
would happen eventually, so it's not really a surprise to me.''
</P>
<P>
   The start of this special attention started late in Samsonov's
rookie season, as he was en route to leading the league's rookies
in goals and power-play goals, and was second in assists.
</P>
<P>
   Bruins coach Pat Burns wants to make sure Samsonov doesn't lose
the puck in critical areas while ang into traffic. ``He's got to
skate away and let them chase him,'' Burns said. ``He's a dandy
when it comes to handling the puck. He's got a lot of skill. But
with his size, he's got to overcome that in making people run after
him, not running into them.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Samsonov, ``Opponents have been playing physically against
me all the time, but I don't see any difference between my second
year and this season, though.''
</P>
<P>
   Burns has implored Burns to shoot more, and, Samsonov said,
``I'm starting to pick up on that. I'm shooting a little bit more,
I'm thinking more about shooting right now than about making other
moves. It's in my head right now. I'm taking five or six shots, and
you've got to do that _ take more chances _ if you're going to
score.''
</P>
<P>
   When Samsonov was playing for the Detroit Vipers in the
International League (1996-97), he was able to watch quite a few of
the Red Wings' home games on television.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one of the best teams in the league,'' said Samsonov of
the Wings (17-8-3, first in the Central Division), who will visit
the FleetCenter Saturday night. ``We have to be ready for them,
both mentally and physically. We have to start thinking of the game
right now, not just one hour before the game. We have to be ready
when we get on the ice.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins have gone 0-3-2 in their last five, which has
Samsonov puzzled.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know why that's been happening, that we've had those
ties, after we've come back from 2-0 and 1-0 deficits, but we just
have't had enough to come back all the way,'' Samsonov said. ``(In
a 2-2 tie with Edmonton Thursday) we both played similar hockey, we
had good effort and the's nothing wrong with a tie. Sure, you
always want to get that extra point, especially when you outshoot
them (37-21).
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know how to explain why we have so many ties. It just
happens sometimes, we just need that extra effort to win the game.
We had a lot of chances in the overtime and we just have to bury
those chances.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
