<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVEST-INSIGHT-Q&AMP;A-$ADV12-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SLEEPY STEPS FOR JAPAN AFTER A LONG HIBERNATION  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, DEC. 12) 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: The questions may be italicized)  
 (af)  
 By KENNETH N. GILPIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Commodore Perry parked his big black ships at the mouth of
what is now Tokyo Bay nearly 150 years ago and demanded entry,
Japan was still a feudal society.
</P>
<P>
   At the moment, Japan appears to be tentatively emerging from a
more modern version of the Dark Ages, an economic recession that
has lasted for most of the decade. More important, the rigidity
that has been the hallmark of its postwar economic structure
appears to be cracking.
</P>
<P>
   Politicians are talking about doing things that have been going
on elsewhere for years: privatization, deregulation, restructuring,
promoting competition.
</P>
<P>
   Foreign direct investment, never very popular in Japan, is
rising. The banking system is being reformed. And some big
companies that used to guarantee lifetime employment are announcing
layoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Such developments have not gone unnoticed: the Topix stock index
is up nearly 50 percent this year.
</P>
<P>
   P. Nicholas Edwards, a managing director and head of the Warburg
Pincus Japan Growth fund, talked about the Japan that seems to be
emerging from the rubble. Following are excerpts from the
conversation: &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Numbers released in Tokyo last week suggest that after two
periods of very modest expansion, Japan's economy contracted a bit
in the third quarter. After being so weak for so long, are
conditions still that fragile?  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. The numbers were badly reported in the U.S. The headline
number was worse than expected, although that was largely due to
the fact that prices as measured by the gross domestic product
deflator fell more than they had in the second quarter. In real
terms, the economy grew at just under a 1 percent annual rate, up
from 0.6 percent in the previous quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Over the next 18 months, the economy won't show tremendous
growth. It will grind through that period with growth of somewhere
between 0.5 percent and 1 percent. Two years down the road, the
economy should really accelerate.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. What about the Japanese consumer, who unlike his Western
counterparts would rather save money instead of spend it? &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. The consumer is feeling more buoyant than he was, but that is
a relative judgment, because he was very depressed a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Computer sales are up 57 percent year-over-year, and last month
car registrations turned positive for the first time in 32 months.
Consumers don't feel ebullient, but they do feel a bit better and
there is a constructive view going forward. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. That is not exactly the sort of economic outlook that should
excite investors. Yet the stock market is doing better. Why? &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. The story about Japan and the stock market _ and it has been
a tremendous year if you were in the right areas _ is about Japan
feeling its way to the creation of the new economy which surrounds
the Internet and telecommunications and restructuring. Some
companies are working very hard and are very focused on improving
value for shareholders. Others are less focused. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Which companies best symbolize this new Japan? &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. I refer to them as the Three Musketeers _ Softbank, NTT
Mobile Communications Network and Hikari Tsushin. Those companies
symbolize the growth in the telecommunications and Internet sector
in Japan. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Any other companies that come to mind? &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Sony and Fujitsu have done well. But it is really a sector
thing. A number, including telecommunications, electronics,
specialty retailers and securities brokers, have done well. The
rest have underperformed. Fifteen of the 33 groups of stocks in
Japan are down for the year. Steel, mining, foods, &QL; 
warehousing are all the boring old sectors. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. What is your 2000 market forecast? &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. The outlook is not quite as good, but the basic premises of
the thesis remain sound: by continuing to invest selectively in the
winners one should continue to do quite well. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. In the depths of the Asian crisis, it was commonly held that
the rest of Asia couldn't recover without a vigorous Japan. Things
don't seem to be panning out quite that way. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. The fact that the economy has gone from negative to positive
growth, and that the currency is stronger, has been positive for
the region. It may be a while before Japan becomes an engine again,
but Asia looks quite good because Japan looks better. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Japan is a very traditional society with entrenched elites.
What are the chances the forces that represent those elites, and
the old economy, will prevail over those who represent the new
economy? &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. There is validity in the fact that there are forces of
conservatism in the country. But there is zero chance the old will
win out over the new.
</P>
<P>
   Culture is irrelevant. If you compare Great Britain of the 1950s
through the early 1970s to today, it is apples and oranges. At the
moment, Japan is probably halfway through its transformation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-10-99 1935EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
