s f BC-FOODS-TASTE-$ADV12-NY     12-10 0506
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOODS-TASTE-$ADV12-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FUNCTIONAL FOODS: HOW DO THEY TASTE? A FOOD CRITIC ANSWERS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, DEC. 12) 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Precede may be italicized)  
 (af)  
 By WILLIAM GRIMES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   All food is functional. That's why humans eat three times a day.
But unlike animals and insects, they do not eat for function's sake
alone. Somewhere in the tortured mental software that governs
eating behavior, the pleasure principle lives in more or less
uneasy proximity to the efficiency principle. We eat to live, but
we also live to eat, which means that functional foods have to jump
through two hoops at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   Do they taste good? That is the question. In my home test
kitchen, I consumed a generous sampling of functional products,
jotting down my taste impressions and rating them on what might be
called the imperial Roman scale: thumbs up or thumbs down. Here are
the results. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CHOLESTEROL CONTROLLERS
</P>
<P>
   Aviva Apricot and Orange Cereal Bar. Thumbs down. Texture of a
rubber eraser, enlivened by a hideously artificial fruit flavor.
</P>
<P>
   Aviva Deluxe Raspberry Muesli. Thumbs down. Makes you wonder
what the non-deluxe version could possibly be.
</P>
<P>
   Benecol Thousand Islands Dressing. Thumbs down. Like McDonald's
secret sauce, without the finesse.
</P>
<P>
   Benecol spread. Thumbs down. Exhibits absolutely no taste
characteristics other than salt.
</P>
<P>
   Take Control spread. Thumbs down. A slick texture and,
astoundingly, even less flavorful than Benecol, even though it has
more salt.
</P>
<P>
   Take Control Blue Cheese Dressing. Thumbs down. Blue cheese
dressing should taste like blue cheese. This tastes like sugar and
vinegar and has the consistency of paint.
</P>
<P>
   BONE BUILDERS
</P>
<P>
   Aviva Apricot and Almond Cereal Bar. Thumbs down. A notch above
the apricot-orange, but the flavor is medicinal.
</P>
<P>
   Aviva Instant Hot Chocolate Drink. Thumbs up. A little chalky,
but the chocolate flavor is fairly honest and not too sweet.
</P>
<P>
   Aviva Orange Juice Drink. Thumbs up. A good, tangy orange flavor
with apricot notes and the peculiar penicillin-like whiff that
seems to haunt all orange drinks not actually squeezed from
oranges.
</P>
<P>
   Viactiv Soft Calcium Chews, Caramel flavor. Thumbs up. A nice,
salt-water-taffy consistency, with a respectable, dark brown sugar
flavor.
</P>
<P>
   DIGESTIVE AIDS
</P>
<P>
   Aviva Crunchy Wholewheat Biscuits. Thumbs up. Dense and compact,
with a subtle almond flavor.
</P>
<P>
   MULTIFORTIFIED SNACKS (with fiber, anti-oxidants, vitamins)
</P>
<P>
   EnfaGrow Nutritional Cracker Bites (for Toddlers), Cheese
Flavor. Thumbs up. Sharp cheddar flavor comes through before the
cracker disintegrates into an unpleasantly dusty, dry powder.
</P>
<P>
   SUGAR CONTROLLERS (for diabetics)
</P>
<P>
   Choice Nutrition Bar, Fudge Brownie. Thumbs down. Chews like a
plug of tobacco, minus the flavor, except for a haylike aftertaste.
The chocolate coating seems to be for color only. Nuts depicted on
the wrapping fail to show up in the actual bar.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
