<HEADER>
A5537 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-JAPAN-ROYAL-PREGNANCY     12-10 0966
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-ROYAL-PREGNANCY-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JAPANESE EXPECTANT, AND HOPE THE PRINCESS IS, TOO 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By HOWARD W. FRENCH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ By the starchy standards of palace life, theirs has been
anything but a conventional fairy tale. But with an abundance of
patience, and some high-powered medical help, it seems that their
dream has finally come true.
</P>
<P>
   After more than six years of a marriage filled with nervous
speculation over whether Crown Prince Naruhito and his wife,
Princess Masako, were able to furnish a successor to the
Chrysanthemum Throne, the Japanese people awoke to a flood of news
reports Friday that the couple would appear to be bearers of good
news.
</P>
<P>
   If the news must still be stated in the conditional, it is only
because the Imperial Household Agency, the secretive and extremely
cautious bureau that manages the lives of Japan's royalty down to
the way they are allowed to wave to admirers, has not made any
official announcement.
</P>
<P>
   Still, many ordinary Japanese have judged that leaks like these,
about a child reportedly due in August, cannot happen by accident.
And in a country stuck rather gloomily in a decade-long economic
rut, many concluded excitedly that the news of the first pregnancy
of the 36-year-old princess was worth celebrating.
</P>
<P>
   ``As soon as I heard about it, I remembered the words of one of
my friends who once told that she found that Princess Masako seemed
so pitiful without a child,'' said Toshiko Muto, a woman in her 60s
who was waiting to enter a downtown kabuki theater. ``Anyway, we
can pray for her safe childbirth now.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Masahide Koshimuzu, 52, the owner of a real estate business,
said: ``I've heard the news, and it's good, because if the princess
got too old she wouldn't be able to have a baby. The imperial
family is part of Japan's tradition. But I've been worried about
the succession: without boys, who can assure the line?''
</P>
<P>
   The imperial claim to legitimacy stems from the myth of the
nation's founding 2,660 years ago by Jimmu, a descendant of the sun
goddess, Amaterasu. In reality, though, the role of the emperor
today was formed largely from the last century, and it often seems
as if it is still stuck in that time.
</P>
<P>
   Japan's contemporary royal couple _ Emperor Akihito and Empress
Michiko, the first commoner to marry into the royal family _ have
in their own quiet way done much to modernize the institution.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   In ways that are scarcely being discussed in Japan's often meek
press, the drama surrounding the 39-year-old Prince Naruhito and
Princess Masako's efforts to conceive is stripping away much of the
remaining mystery that has traditionally shrouded royalty here, and
perhaps revolutionizing the role of women in the imperial lineage.
</P>
<P>
   The imperial family has been plagued with fertility problems,
and the prince and princess _ and the official handlers, who
usually leave little to chance _ seem to have decided that a touch
of the ultramodern was just what was called for in these
circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   It has been widely reported here that a team of six top
reproduction experts was recently assigned to facilitate the
conception. And everyone here is already wondering whether
artificial insemination was used.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the pressure to conceive has been publicly borne by the
Harvard- and Oxford-educated princess _ just the second commoner to
become crown princess _ even though several of the prince's uncles
and great-uncles were childless.
</P>
<P>
   Making matters worse under a system that requires a male for the
succession, the children of Prince Naruhito's brother, Akishino,
and of the imperial cousins who are also theoretically able to
furnish a successor to the throne, are all girls.
</P>
<P>
   Which leads to the second great modernization under way:
constitutional changes are said to be in the works to allow a woman
to assume the throne.
</P>
<P>
   The Imperial Household Agency initially opposed Prince
Naruhito's choice of a bride, seemingly fearing her as a dangerous
and completely modern precedent setter.
</P>
<P>
   When the prince courted Princess Masako, she was a career
diplomat who spoke French, Spanish and English. Questions were
asked about whether she would keep her eyes downcast in public and
walk five steps behind her husband, as custom demands, and whether
she would be happy abandoning the professional world in favor of a
life full of stiff receptions and obligatory appearances.
</P>
<P>
   But concern over the lack of a child forced the agency to send a
mission to Europe to study legal changes, in countries like Sweden,
that have allowed women to reign. And now it is widely assumed that
if a girl is born, there will be a change in the rules of
succession to allow any child of the couple to ascend the throne.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a son is born, that is best, but even if there is a girl,
that is good news too,'' said Toshiaki Kawahara, the author of
several books about the imperial family. ``If there is a girl,
there is no doubt that in the future the government will change the
rules so that a woman can be an emperor. It is time for us to stop
making a distinction in terms of whether a man or woman can sit on
the throne.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   With such a change, Princess Masako, herself once a reluctant
bride who was nearly spurned by the custodians of the palace, will
have quietly avenged modern women.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference shortly after the couple was married,
Prince Naruhito, asked how many children the couple planned to
have, answered that the stork would decide.
</P>
<P>
   Princess Masako, though, perhaps already sensing her power,
quickly declared, ``Please don't expect enough children to make an
orchestra.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
