<DOCNO> NYT19991210.0250 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-10 19:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5539 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a BC-CLINTON-PLANS-HNS &LR;      12-10 0938
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-PLANS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON HOPES TO GENERATE NEW INVESTMENT IN IMPOVERISHED AREA 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By GREG McDONALD 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST MEMPHIS, Ark. _ President Clinton came home to Arkansas on
Friday to tout his efforts at boosting economic opportunities in
the nation's poorest regions, including this state's impoverished
delta area along the Mississippi River.
</P>
<P>
   But he also used his trip to raise money for the presidential
library he plans to build in Little Rock along the Arkansas River
and to ``take a walk back through memory lane,'' as he put it, of a
presidency rocked by scandal but still able to boast of
accomplishments on the domestic and foreign policy fronts.
</P>
<P>
   At appearances here, in nearby Earle and in the state capital of
Little Rock, Clinton announced a $110 million initiative he hopes
to get funded next year that would create a Delta Regional
Authority to help generate new investment in this struggling
agriculture area, which has failed to keep pace with the rest of
the country's economic boom.
</P>
<P>
   Citing the nation's record prosperity, backed by the first
budget surpluses in 42 years, Clinton said there was no better time
to focus on lifting the country's economically depressed areas.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we can't figure out something to do about this now, when in
the world will we ever get around to it?'' the president asked at
one point during a speech to the Little Rock Chamber of Commerce,
which pledged to give Clinton $1.25 million to help build his
library and policy center.
</P>
<P>
   The poverty initiative, if approved by Congress next year, would
help provide needed education, health care and economic development
assistance throughout the Mississippi delta region. Clinton hopes
that the federal incentives will spur additional financial
investment from the private sector. Clinton made a pitch for
immediate investment from the business world during a private
meeting here with 20 heads of big corporations.
</P>
<P>
   ``We ought to give people the same incentives to invest in poor
areas of America, like the Arkansas Delta, we give them to invest
in poor areas in Latin America, or Asia, or Africa,'' Clinton said,
adding that lifting people out of poverty would help ``minimize'' a
host of other social and cultural problems in the country's poorest
areas.
</P>
<P>
   In his speech to the chamber of commerce, Clinton spent some
time touting his plans to build a sprawling library and policy
center on 26 acres near downtown Little Rock. Clinton hopes to
raise at least $125 million for the project, which will be
affiliated with the University of Arkansas.
</P>
<P>
   He said his library would not only house his presidential
materials, but would be home to a conflict resolution center that
would help bridge ``racial and other divides in our society.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This library can be an energizing force in the life of the
city and the broader community. It will attract people from all
over the world,'' Clinton said, describing what he characterized as
an ``interactive'' museum rather than ``a mausoleum'' used to store
the presidential papers and memorabilia from his two-term
presidency.
</P>
<P>
   While the library and his poverty initiative were at the center
of his trip to Arkansas, Clinton also used his appearances to
summarize the accomplishments of his nearly 7-year-old presidency
and to remind people that he still has 14 months to go in his
second term and still has ``lots to do.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's important to remember that a significant chunk of
the time that I have been given to serve is still out there,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said he hopes to spend next year working on Social
Security and Medicare reform, improving public education, and
continuing to promote peace and stability abroad. He also said his
top priority would be to keep the ``longest peacetime (economic)
expansion in our history'' going.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my lifetime ... there has never been another time, not one,
when our country had this level of economic prosperity, this level
of social progress, this level of national self-confidence, with
the absence of a crisis at home or a threat from abroad,'' Clinton
said in Little Rock.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we stay on the track we're on now ... this country will be
out of debt in 15 years for the first time since 1835,'' Clinton
said, adding that the country has a great opportunity ``on the edge
of the new millennium to really shape the future ... for our
children.''
</P>
<P>
   At each stop in the state where he served as governor for 12
years before winning the presidency in 1992, Clinton thanked the
crowds for their support.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it hadn't been for the experiences you gave me and the
lessons I learned, I wouldn't have been prepared to serve at this
moment in our history,'' Clinton said, adding that his life in
Arkansas helped him decide to run for president at a time ``of
economic distress, social decline and deep political division'' in
the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's impossible to remember what it was like just a few short
years ago,'' Clinton said during one stop. He added that his
``mission'' as president has been to provide ``opportunities for
every American'' and to challenge every citizen to be a
``responsible'' member of their community.
</P>
<P>
   ``We battled through the politics, we battled through a whole
flurry of special interests, we battled through our fair share of
mistakes. But we never forgot who we were working for or what the
mission was,'' Clinton said. ``And I hope that all of you, without
whom I would never have become president, can take some pride in
the results.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
