<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-PHONE-TALKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
3-WAY TALKS COULD LEAD TO JAPAN'S 2ND LARGEST PHONE COMPANY  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By STEPHANIE STROM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ KDD Corp., Japan's largest international telephone
service company, said Friday that it was in talks with its
faltering competitor, DDI Corp., and IDO Corp., a cellular phone
operator, over a possible merger.
</P>
<P>
   The companies stressed that no deal was imminent and that their
discussions were most immediately concentrated on whether they
could jointly develop a new generation of mobile phones.
</P>
<P>
   But the prospect of a merger of the three companies, which would
create Japan's second-largest telephone company after the Nippon
Telegraph and Telephone Corp., is likely to further intensify the
already frenetic realignment of the Japanese telecommunications
industry.
</P>
<P>
   The three companies may do nothing more than band together to
seek one of the three lucrative licenses the government plans to
award next year to allow telecommunications firms to sell cutting
edge cellular phone services like high-speed Internet access and
links to online video services. But even that would be significant.
Together, the three companies would present a more formidable force
than any one of them alone.
</P>
<P>
   A merged company would have revenue of 3 trillion yen, just 30
percent of the 10 trillion yen, or $97.18 billion, in revenue that
NTT is expected to produce this fiscal year on a consolidated
basis.
</P>
<P>
   Still, each of the companies has its problems. For example, a
combined company would have debts of 1.9 trillion yen, or roughly
$18.4 billion at current exchange rates. KDD has had difficulty
finding an international partner, which many analysts regard as
essential, while its competitor Japan Telecom has quickly allied
itself with British Telecommunications, Vodaphone Airtouch and AT&AMP;
T.
</P>
<P>
   DDI alone is struggling with debts of 1.5 trillion yen, roughly
$14.6 billion at current exchange rates. IDO, in which Toyota has a
63 percent stake, is a relative bit player in Japan's mobile phone
market, which is dominated by NTT Mobile Communications Inc., an
affiliate of NTT.
</P>
<P>
   DDI could not even afford to think about developing new cellular
phone technology were it not for a promise from Toyota, which has
ample cash sitting on its books, to help the company raise money.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
