<HEADLINE>
SHORT ITEMS ON PEOPLE AND PERSONALITIES  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, DEC. 12) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Money Managers Aside, She Wanted to Be Alone &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The year was 1959 and a young Brown Brothers Harriman employee
named Richard H. Jenrette was managing Greta Garbo's money when he
learned some valuable lessons about Wall Street. At a dinner last
week to celebrate the 40th anniversary of the founding of Donaldson
Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette, Jenrette told a few tales to show how much Wall
Street had changed.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, he said, it was Ms. Garbo who gave him the idea, then
novel, of providing his clients with more than one money manager.
``Back in those days, for some ridiculous reason, all clients had
only one person manage their money,'' Jenrette said. But, he
explained, Ms. Garbo broke with that practice, hiring three firms _
J.P. Morgan, Bank of New York and Brown Brothers _ and playing one
against another.
</P>
<P>
   When Jenrette founded DLJ, he remembered her approach: ``The
great Garbo was one of the earliest to see the merits of pitting
one money manager against the other. She may have invented the
concept of competitive money managers.''
</P>
<P>
   How different were those times, when Wall Street worked for
fixed 40-cent-a-share commissions. While still at Brown Brothers,
Jenrette recalled, he wrote a letter to a client saying he was
pleased to show that he had outperformed the Dow Jones industrial
average for that quarter. But before the letter was sent, it came
back from Jenrette's boss, with a big black mark through it and the
words: ``Never comment on investment performance. Once you start,
what do you talk about when you underperform?''
</P>
<P>
   Leslie Wayne &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Better Late Than Never &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Five years ago, when Larry Augustin was a graduate student at
Stanford, his friends David Filo and Jerry Yang came up with a
directory to the World Wide Web they ultimately called Yahoo. At
one point, the three, all computer science students, talked about
writing a joint business plan. But Augustin bowed out, going on to
earn his doctorate there in electrical engineering.
</P>
<P>
   Not to worry. Last week, Augustin joined the ranks of Internet
billionaires himself when his company, VA Linux Systems, went
public. At VA Linux's closing price of $218 on Friday, Augustin's
16 percent stake was worth $1.44 billion. Before founding VA Linux,
which sells servers that run the Linux operating system, Augustin,
now 37, was a consultant for Fintronic USA, a provider of software
used for designing chips, and a research associate at Stanford.
</P>
<P>
   Lawrence M. Fisher &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Anyone Can Whistle? &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Being worth more than $5 billion, as Charles Schwab is, means
never whistling off-key.
</P>
<P>
   Schwab appears in a television commercial for his brokerage
firm's new high-speed trading system. The rock anthem ``Born to be
Wild'' blares as Schwab trades behind closed doors. Then he strolls
out of his office, whistling this Steppenwolf tune.
</P>
<P>
   But Schwab acknowledged last week _ in an interview to promote
WebShops, his firm's program of seminars that teach on-line
investing _ that his effort had to be electronically tuned and
enhanced for the soundtrack. Though he put his lips together and
blew, he explained, ``it just wasn't loud enough.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Patrick McGeehan &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Strike or Strikeout? &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If car company publicists ever get together for team bowling,
there will be fierce competition to pick Gerry Spahn. Otherwise,
they would want Spahn, Nissan's spokesman on the East Coast, to
keep his distance.
</P>
<P>
   When Popular Science recently honored recipients of its Best of
What's New awards, from the December issue, at a luncheon at Tavern
on the Green in Manhattan, General Motors set up a display of
innovations including what the magazine had called ``dentproof''
urethane truck fenders.
</P>
<P>
   To demonstrate, GM rigged up a pendulum consisting of a bowling
ball, on a steel cable, that could be slammed into the futuristic
fender of a prototype Chevy truck.
</P>
<P>
   When Spahn took his turn with the bowling ball, ``he picked the
thing up over his head and dropped it,'' said Dan McCosh, the
magazine's automotive editor. Buckled by the impact, the fender was
slashed by the abrasive cable and shattered, he said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   GM officials were not amused, even after Spahn suggested turning
the pickup around to give others a crack at the remaining dentproof
fender. Having left his mark in New York, Spahn is being promoted
to a corporate public relations post in Japan. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   James G. Cobb
</P>
</TEXT>
