<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Navy bombs hurt reef, scientist says
 &HT;    By Rebecca McCarthy
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATHENS, Ga. _ Craters in a coral reef off a Puerto Rican island,
which has a U.S. bombing range on its eastern end, were not made by
hurricanes, as the U.S. government claims, but by bombs dropped by
American forces, a University of Georgia scientist said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The bombs _ along with two sunken ships, possibly naval vessels,
and corroding barrels leaking potentially toxic substances _ were
found by a team of investigators hired by the Puerto Rican
government last July, as it was negotiating the future of the
island with the U.S. Navy. While the Navy owns two-thirds of
Vieques, some 9,000 Puerto Ricans live on the other third, and
their government wants the 58 years of naval bombardment on the
target range to stop.
</P>
<P>
   The investigators include University of Georgia coral reef
expert James Porter, ordnance removal specialist James Barton and
explosives expert Fred Hoverkamp. They were hired in July by the
Atlanta law firm King &AMP; Spalding, which is advising the Puerto
Rican government in its talks with the Navy.
</P>
<P>
   Early this year, a Marine pilot dropped an errant bomb on a
civilian employee at the Vieques range, killing him. Months of
talks between Puerto Rican and U.S. government officials have
followed, as have protests in Puerto Rico on behalf of Vieques'
civilian population.
</P>
<P>
   Federal officials proposed reserving the right to use the site
for 90 days a year, letting pilots drop concrete-filled, inert
bombs _ not live ones _ to practice their bombing techniques. The
Puerto Rican government has rejected that compromise.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the things this discovery does is to call into question
the use of even inert munitions,'' Porter said. ``A bomb might
leave the wing of an aircraft `green,' but if it destroyed the
integrity of these barrels, it could cause environmental harm.''
</P>
<P>
   The team found heavy concentrations of metallic shrapnel in
symmetrical holes, each 12 feet across, confirming that the
indentions were made by bombs, not hurricanes.
</P>
<P>
   The investigative team also has taken samples of the leaking
material from the corroding barrels to determine if they were
toxic. Some appear to contain solid substances, while others hold
liquids.
</P>
<P>
   The team found the two wrecked vessels, both of which contain
numerous barrels, during an exploratory session Nov. 26. A
100-foot-long ship has between 150 and 200 barrels, while near the
broken barge are about 1,000 barrels.
</P>
<P>
   Unexploded ordnance can also be found at both sites.
</P>
<P>
   The investigative team has taken samples of the leaking material
from the corroding barrels to determine if they were toxic. Some
appear to contain solid substances, while others hold liquids.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't know what's in the barrels, but until we do, they
shouldn't be disturbed by either live or inert bombs,'' Porter
said. ``There's been a debate on who does what, but the best course
of action would be for all parties to work together to clean up
that underwater dump site and the remaining underwater ordnance.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
