<HEADER>
A5551 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u p BC-CAMPAIGN-CLINTON-BOS &LR;      12-10 0851
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-CLINTON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`CARPETBAGGER' ISSUE STALKS MRS. CLINTON IN NEW YORK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRED KAPLAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Two questions stood out as Hillary Rodham Clinton
campaigned across Manhattan this week. First, will she ever be
accepted as a New Yorker? Second, does it matter?
</P>
<P>
   It is a more prominent issue than Clinton, who has never worked
or lived here, would like it to be. And it raised its head again
this week in a subtle but still damaging way.
</P>
<P>
   She was appearing Thursday morning at a midtown restaurant
called O'Neill's to accept the endorsement of leading
Irish-American Democrats, all of them grateful for her and
President Clinton's role in the Northern Ireland peace talks.
</P>
<P>
   A reporter asked if she would march in the S. Patrick's Day
Parade, d the First Lady replied, with an eager grin, ``I would
certainly hope so.''
</P>
<P>
   The thing is, most Democrats do not march in that parade because
its organizers prohibit Irish gay-and-lesbian groups from taking
part.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton is hardly insensitive to gay causes. Just a few
minutes earlier, she had criticized her husband's ``don't ask,
don't tell'' policy for gays in the military.
</P>
<P>
   The goof was that she appeared not to know the parade was an
issue. It may seem a small flub, but a telling one, in a city where
one-fifth of the residents are Irish, a fair percentage are gay,
and the parade is a prominent issue for both groups.
</P>
<P>
   Anne Maguire, head of the Irish Lesbian and Gay Organiation,
lashed out. ``The idea that Hillary would march, or even that she
doesn't know the issue, is outrageous.'' She added Friday, more
coldly, ``Clinton needs to make her stand now. She either supports
lesbian and gay men in New York, or she actively supports the
bigots who tell us we can't be Irish and gay at the same time.''
</P>
<P>
   Thus, with a small misstep, the First Lady winds up on the verge
of alienating two groups that she has never remotely offended.
</P>
<P>
   More broadly, the incident serves to reinforce the widespread
perception that she does not know her way around the land mines of
New York politics. The perception first took hold with flaps
involving two other major ethnic groups _ her opposition to amnesty
for Puerto Rican terrorists and her ``kiss of death'' with the wife
of Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat during a Middle East visit.
</P>
<P>
   At moments like these, linton has come off like an
out-of-towner, not a term of endearment here. And the few times
when she has tried to go native _ putting on a Yankees cap, letting
it be known that her great-grandma married a nice Jewish fella _
she has come off as pandering.
</P>
<P>
   The pertinent question, though, is: Does this matter? Judging
from statements made this week, part of her campaign strategy
appears to be convincing New Yorkers that it does not.
</P>
<P>
   ``Political issues should be what campaigns are fought out
over,'' she said at O'Neill's.
</P>
<P>
   At another event this week, on a Wall Street trading floor, she
said, ``I'll ask people to support me on the basis of where I stand
on the issues.''
</P>
<P>
   If this strategy succeeds, she may very well win the election.
All the polls indicate a very close race. She trails her likely
Republican opponent, Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, but only by a few
percentage points, usually within the statistical margin of error.
</P>
<P>
   Her flag of hope in these polls is that they show that she is
viewed much more favorably than Giuliani on issues she has long
cared about _ education, health care, and social welfare. However,
Giuliani comes out ahead when the questions shift to competence,
experience, and knowledge of what makes New York tick. The mayor,
once his campaign gets going, can be expected o emphasize those
themes.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's supporters often talk as if local savvy is an
irrelevant issue. At a Women-for-Hillary fund-raising breakfast
this week, Representative Carolyn Maloney, a Manhattan Democrat,
said, ``We New Yorkers know the only question is who can serve our
interests best, not whee you're from.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, however, in every poll, roughly half of New Yorkers,
including many Democrats, ae concerned about where a candidate is
from. It is because the concern is so widespread that even a small
misstep can cast so huge a shadow.
</P>
<P>
   Some of Clinton's supporters have tried to maneuver around the
``carpetbagger'' issue by placing her in a tradition of senators
from New York _ Robert Kennedy, Jacob Javits, and the retiring
senator she hopes to replace, Daniel Patrick Moynihan _ who have
brought national and international stature to the seat.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton fills that bill, but the program may have changed. ``Al
D'Amato changed the rules,'' said Hank Sheinkopf, a Democratic
consultant. ``He showed that a senator has to bring home the bacon,
too, that it's not just the job of a congressman.''
</P>
<P>
   Charles Schumer, who beat D'Amato in the last election, has paid
no less attention than D'Amato to local concerns. ``That's what
Hillary has to do, too,'' another Democrat said. ``She has to show
she knows the ropes.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
