<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BAD-TEACHER11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ga. teacher bilked students, gets 30 years
 &HT;    By Jingle Davis
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Former high school teacher Vanessa Velez-Cruz was a
hit with her students until she stranded a group in Europe last
summer by bouncing checks to the travel agency that booked their
trip.
</P>
<P>
   When authorities investigated, they learned that Velez-Cruz, 48,
was a one-woman criminal organization who had stolen more than
$200,000 from students and others.
</P>
<P>
   Velez-Cruz pleaded guilty Friday to multiple counts of theft,
bank fraud, forgery, income-tax evasion and racketeering, said
Danny Craig, district attorney for the Augusta Judicial Circuit.
</P>
<P>
   Superior Court Judge Carl Brown sentenced her to 30 years in
prison and ordered her to make restitution of $227,774, Craig said.
</P>
<P>
   Her attorney, Pete Theodocian, declined to speculate about how
much time she would serve but said she could appeal the sentence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm disappointed for her that she got that length of
sentence,'' Theodocian said. ``She's done a lot of good in her
life.''
</P>
<P>
   Velez-Cruz, a native of Puerto Rico, collected about $80,000
this year to take a group of students in her Spanish class at St.
Thomas Aquinas High School in Augusta, Ga., to Europe. Instead, she
diverted the money to her own account. Shortly before the trip, she
paid for airplane tickets with checks that bounced after the group
arrived in Paris.
</P>
<P>
   Even after frantic parents called her in Paris, Velez-Cruz
continued bilking her students, Craig said.
</P>
<P>
   ``She collected money from them for a play and overcharged them
by $900,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Craig said Velez-Cruz had been stealing for years. She arranged
other foreign trips for students that failed to include promised
stops or were canceled, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Velez-Cruz also solicited donations to transport the bodies of
three murder victims back to Mexico about a year ago, but kept the
money.
</P>
<P>
   More than 100 of Velez-Cruz's victims attended the sentencing,
including Cay Hickey, whose 15-year-old daughter and three nieces
went on the June trip to Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Hickey said students at the private Roman Catholic school ``just
loved'' Velez-Cruz, in part because she allowed them to drink
alcohol.
</P>
<P>
   ``We found out later our children had been dancing on the tables
and drinking at Hard Rock Cafes,'' Hickey said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
