<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-F22-11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lockheed to start work on F-22 jets
 &HT;    By Rebecca Carr
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ After surviving a near-death experience in
Congress, Lockheed Martin Corp. has won approval from the Defense
Department to start building its controversial F-22 jet fighters.
</P>
<P>
   The green light comes just one day after a Pentagon review of
the F-22 program determined that the Stealth fighter is the ``most
capable option'' for meeting the Air Force's air superiority needs.
</P>
<P>
   This decision clears the way for Lockheed Martin to receive $1
billion in research and development funds to build six test
aircraft and to purchase raw materials for 10 additional planes.
</P>
<P>
   That spells good news for Lockheed Martin's Marietta, Ga.,
plant, where the aircraft will be assembled. It has been a tough
year for the nation's largest military contractor.
</P>
<P>
   First, the F-22 came under stiff opposition during the
congressional budget process. The House, led by Rep. Jerry Lewis
(R.-Calif.), chairman of the appropriations panel overseeing
military spending, voted to eliminate funds to build the aircraft
until more testing could be conducted.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, the funding was mostly restored. But a few weeks
later, news broke that Lockheed was considering selling off or
consolidating some of its military aircraft business, including the
Marietta plant.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon's decision to move forward is a positive sign for
the plant's future, said members of the Georgia congressional
delegation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We worked very hard to see this important funding appropriated
this year,'' said Sen. Paul Coverdell (R-Ga.). ``Today's
announcement is good news for Georgia and for the future of
Lockheed's Marietta facility.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Max Cleland (D-Ga.) agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm pleased,'' Cleland said. ``I think this augurs well for
the plane and it is a positive straw in the wind for Marietta.''
</P>
<P>
   As a result of the funding, Lockheed laid out a number of goals
for the program for next year.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Rearden, Lockheed Martin's vice president and general
manager for the F-22 program, said that the top goal would be to
get four airplanes flying out of the Marietta factory in the coming
year. Those planes were approved by Congress in 1996 and 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Rearden also said the contractor would send the planes through a
battery of avionics software testing and ground testing.
</P>
<P>
   The Air Force wants to buy 339 fighter jets over the course of
the next decade, so it was more than pleased that work on the
planes would begin immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Air Force Lt. Col. Eric Garvin said the F-22 is superior to
other fighters such as the F-15 because it has the ability to
detect the enemy far in advance of the enemy spotting the plane.
</P>
<P>
   ``As threat continues to evolve, F-15s won't work as well as the
F-22,'' Garvin said. ``If we don't do anything, we will put our
sons and daughters in harm's way. And once you lose air dominance,
you lose American lives.''
</P>
<P>
   The next step for Lockheed will be to secure funding for the
F-22 in next year's budget.
</P>
<P>
   After this year's scrutiny, the Georgia delegation plans to
mount a strong lobbying effort to avoid budget attacks.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Bob Barr (R-Ga.), who represents the congressional district
where the Lockheed plant is located, said that the company should
be rewarded for meeting cost and performance mandates set forth by
the Department of Defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``Despite an undeserved attack by some in Congress on the
program, the men and women who make the F-22 are clearly doing a
great job and keeping their eyes on the ball,'' Barr said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
