<HEADLINE>
SEARCHERS AT BURNED WAREHOUSE OBSERVE MOMENT OF SILENCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOANNA WEISS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WORCESTER, Mass. -- The memorial was over, the VIPs had left,
but the grim search went on Friday, as firefighters continued to
sift through the wreckage of the Worcester Cold Storage and
Warehouse Co. building for four of their lost colleagues.
</P>
<P>
   Salvage crews have worked ceaselessly, 24 hours a day, since the
vacant warehouse caught fire on Dec. 3. But for the first time, the
effort came to a brief halt as firefghters observed a moment of
silence at 6:13 p.m. -- exactly one week to the minute the fateful
alarm went out, sending engines and ladders to the blaze that would
claim six mens' lives.
</P>
<P>
   As a gentle rain fell across the city, crews stood in a line
atop the wreckage, some bowing thir heads, some pacing sadly. All
took off their helmets and held them to their hearts. At the
stations, firefighters stood grim-faced and silent, some raising
their hands in salutes.
</P>
<P>
   It was a striking contrast to the hours before and afterward,
when construction equipment roared and beeped, lifting piles of
brick and dropping them, crashing, to the ground. Crews atop the
piles of debris inside the building hurled charred pieces of wood
and pipe to the ground, and sifted through the mounds of wreckage.
</P>
<P>
   Every day a little bit more of the warehouse disappears, as
construction equipment gnaws away atthe thick brick walls.
Firefighters spent much of Friday preparing to protect the rubble
within, and the walls themselves, fromhwinds and heavy rains
expected this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have literally hundreds of people here working, and we have
all our resources in place,'' District Chief James Callery said.
</P>
<P>
   Weary firefighters, many of whom have had little sleep or rest
since the deadly blaze, made plans to attend the funeral Sunday for
Timothy P. Jackson and another on Monday for James F. Lyons III,
the two firefighters whose bodies have been recovered. Paul
Brotherton, Thomas Spencer, Jeremiah Lucey, and Joseph McGuirk are
still lost beneath the rubble.
</P>
<P>
   Widespread support for fatigued and grieving firefighters
continued to come from near and far, in expressions large and
small.
</P>
<P>
   The Colleges of Worcester Consortium, an umbrella group
representing 15 private and public schools, announced Friday that
its member institutions will provide scholarships to the 17
children whose fathers died in the fire.
</P>
<P>
   Other forms of help and support continued to flood into the
Local 1009 Firefighters Union office. Bags of stuffed animals
shared space with tables laden with donated food, and gestures of
sympathy poured in by mail, from adults and from children, even
those barely old enough to know how to write.
</P>
<P>
   Anthony Mormino, 6, of Quincy, wrote his letter on the thin,
lined paper children use when they are first learning to print. He
penned his thoughts in large, halting letters:
</P>
<P>
   ``Sorry about your Dad that you cant see your Dad at Christmas.
So you can have my Lunch money to buy your Mom a presant.
OXOXOXOX''
</P>
<P>
   In the envelope, he had placed $1.50 in quarters.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
