<HEADLINE>
RICK DANKO, 56; ROCK HALL OF FAMER WITH MANY INTERESTS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (e and a coding)   (For use by New Ykims News Service clients)  
 By STEVE MORSE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Rick Danko, the affable but often troubled Rock and Roll Hall of
Famer who sang and played bass with the Band and had many other
side projects, died Friday in his home in Woodstock, N.Y. He was
56.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Danko reportedly died in his sleep, according to Ike
Phillips, a friend and general manager of Woodstock radio station
WDST-FM.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Danko's deeply soulful voice keyed such Band classics as
``Up on Cripple Creek,'' ``The Weight,'' ``The Night They Drove Old
Dixie Down,'' ``Stage Fright,'' and ``Unfaithful Servant.''
</P>
<P>
   The pink house that Mr. Danko rented near Woodstock in the late
'60s was where the Band recorded its debut record, ``Music From Big
Pink,'' which catapulted the group to fame and is considered one of
the great rock albums.
</P>
<P>
   The Band, which backed Bob Dylan on his breakthrough electric
tour in 1965, played the original Woodstock Festival in 1969 and,
along with the Grateful Dead and Allman Brothers, appeared at the
Watkins Glen Festival in 1973. That fest, with a half-million
spectators, actually drew a larger crowd than came to Woodstock.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from his soulful vocals and steady bass lines, Mr. Danko
played fiddle, which gave an old-timey feel to some Band songs.
That quality helped earn the group its status as leaders of the
Americana roots movement, though four members (including Mr. Danko)
were born in Canada, where they first backed rockabilly singer
Ronnie Hawkins.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Danko, who ws born in Simcoe, Ontario, left school at age 14
to pursue music. He later battled an alcohol problem, which he
discussed in interviews, and two years ago was found guilty of
smuggling heroin into Japan. He was given a suspended sentence.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Mr. Danko was known by many as an eternal optimist. He
defined himself that way and, after the suicide of Band member
Richard Manuel in 1986, Mr. Danko even rationalized in a Globe
interview that Manuel ``was just checking a new, sophisticated
knot. That may sound weird, but that's what I believe.''
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Danko, however, took the death of his close friend Manuel
hard. And he suffered the next year when friend and occasional
touring partner Paul Butterfield died. Still, Mr. Danko dd not
harbor bitterness. Although the Band never reunited with guitarist
Robbie Robertson, Mr. Danko sang backup on Robertson's self-titled
debut album in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Robertson's absence, the Band re-formed (with Mr. Danko,
Levon Helm, and Garth Hudson) for a number of tours through the
years, playing the Newport Folk Festival and hosting New Year's Eve
at the Paradise in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Danko toured relentlessly and was a frequent visitor to
Boston with his own groups. He played the Channel, Jonathan
Swift's, Nightstage, the Middle East, and Ed Burke's, imparting
honky-tonk blues and good times.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Danko found the most peace at his Woodstk home deep in the
woods, by a pond that he stocked with trout. And he always took
pride in how the and's music influenced the next wave of artists.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm really thankful the way our music has been passed down
from father to son, and generation to generation,'' he once told
the Globe. ``I've been influenced, and I have influenced. It's good
to be on both sides of the light.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Wire service material Press was used to prepare this article.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
