<HEADLINE>
DURING ARKANSAS VISIT, CLINTON FOCUSES ON FUTURE BEYOND
PRESIDENCY 
</HEADLINE>
  (mcd) 
 By ROBERT PEAR    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST MEMPHIS, Ark., _ President Clinton still has more than 13
months left in office, but he was clearly focusing on his future
after he leaves the White House on Friday as he made a nostalgic
homecoming trip to his native state.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton sounded more like a governor than a president as he
spoke to the Greater Little Rock Chamber of Commerce and toured
depressed areas of eastern Arkansas, announcing millions of dollars
in federal grants to promote economic development, train long-haul
truck drivers and improve local health care services.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let me just take a minute to walk back through memory lane,''
Clinton said in a mellow, wistful speech to the Chamber of
Commerce.
</P>
<P>
   The whole day followed that pattern as Clinton thanked the
people he credited with making possible his career in national
politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to begin by thanking the people of Arkansas, who gave
me the chance to serve for a dozen years as governor, without which
I could never have become president,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   He observed that his days in the White House were winding down,
and he emphasized this theme so much that it sounded as if his term
would end next month, rather than in January 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton had little to say about his plans for the remainder of
his term. Rather, he boasted of his achievements over the last
seven years and described _ in more detail than ever before _ his
vision of life after the White House, including his plan to build a
presidential library in Little Rock, on a 26-acre site beside the
Arkansas River.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said the library would not only burnish his record but
also attract visitors to Little Rock from all over the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want this to be a museum, but not a mausoleum,'' Clinton
said.
</P>
<P>
   He said his presidential archives would be combined with a
policy center, where he intends to continue the projects he began
as president. He said nothing about the home he and his wife,
Hillary Rodham Clinton, bought recently in Chappaqua, N.Y., or the
career she seeks as a U.S. senator for New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I come home to build the library and my policy center,''
Clinton said, ``I want to deal with a lot of these big questions:
How do you close the digital divide and use these high-tech
advances to benefit every American? How do you create good jobs and
a clean environment? How do you leave behind the ethnic and
religious hatreds, the other kind of hatred that is manifested in
hate crimes in America, and the tribal slaughters in Africa and all
the wars in between? How do you create genuine economic opportunity
and empowerment for people who have been poor a very long time?''
</P>
<P>
   Leaders of the Little Rock Chamber of Commerce used Clinton's
visit as an occasion to encourage donations to the foundation that
is building the library. They said they were trying to raise $125
million.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said he would continue his work as a peacemaker,
mediating racial, ethnic, political and religious conflicts after
he left the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Little Rock and his presidential center can become ``a beacon of
hope for those kinds of people,'' Clinton said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
