<HEADLINE>
KOBE'S ROLE SCALED BACK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   VANCOUVER, B.C. _ Upon further review, maybe Kobe Bryant needs
some time to warm up this season before the Los Angeles Lakers'
nightly fate is placed entirely in his hands. At least, that's
coach Phil Jackson's feeling right now.
</P>
<P>
   While Bryant has shown no physical rust from his seven-week
layoff, he has made some judgment errors in his first five games
back _ witness the six turnovers he committed in Wednesday's loss
to the Sacramento Kings.
</P>
<P>
   So Jackson might scale back some of Bryant's responsibilities,
specifically the burden of orchestrating the Lakers' last
possession of each quarter. It was in those situations, with the
clock running down, when Bryant made the majority of his errors
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's obvious I've put a lot of responsibility on him,''
Jackson said, ``because he's a creative player, he's also a very
talented player, and in that responsibility mode, there's some
things _ end of quarters, time-clock kind of situations _ that
haven't happened for us right yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``He fully understands the role, but I think he doesn't quite
grasp the severity of the situation, really the responsibility of
the whole situation. A lot of games in the NBA you see a team win
(based on) who scores at the beginning of the quarter, who scores
at the end of the quarter. ... And for us in Sacramento, for
example, it was disastrous.''
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the third quarter, for example, the Lakers had a
chance to run one last play and cut the deficit to six points, but
Bryant lost the ball as he made a move toward the baseline. The
Kings took it to the other end, where Derek Fisher fouled Jason
Williams, sending him to the line with four seconds left. The
Lakers entered the fourth quarter down 73-64.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those are the things that Kobe, as a responsible player, will
measure out and know the clock, take the last shot or create the
situation for the last shot, so there's not a turnover,'' Jackson
said. ``It happened the night before against Washington too, at the
end of the first half.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll have to readjust that thinking a little bit and wait
until Kobe (has) that experience to handle those situations. I
might have been a little bit too hasty to put him in that
position.''
</P>
<P>
   Bryant is already working on it. He took one of the game tapes
home to study.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's going to watch it, go through it and grimace, feel the
remorse about it, I know, because that's the kind of kid he is,''
Jackson said.
</P>
<P>
   George returns: The Lakers activated rookie swingman Devean
George on Friday and placed forward Travis Knight on the injured
list.
</P>
<P>
   George went to the injured list Dec. 1 to make room for Bryant
but was activated as soon as he was eligible. Jackson wanted George
to spend some time watching and learning from the bench.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's ready,'' Jackson said. ``He says he's ready to
play. I played him this morning (in practice), he played well.''
</P>
<P>
   Knight, who hasn't left the bench in four of the past eight
games, has never fully recovered from the right ankle he sprained
in mid-October. He's averaging just 5.1 minutes per game.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
