<HEADLINE>
AFTER NFL, ANYTHING BUT PITS FOR NASCAR CZAR GIBBS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILL MCDONOUGH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Years ago, when he was signing off as an NFL pregame analyst
with NBC, Joe Gibbs had a vision.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a natural for me,'' said Gibbs, the Hall of Fame coach
who won three Super Bowls with the Washington Redskns. Gibbs was
just starting a new career as an owner in NASCAR, with one car, one
driver, and 18 employees.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just like pro football,'' said Gibbs. ``You have an
owner, a coach (crew chief), a quarterback (the driver) and and
entire crew with him. I think this sport is great, and is going to
be even bigger.''
</P>
<P>
   That was just a handful of years ago. Now Gibbs has six cars,
six drivers, 130 employees, and two of the sport's hottest drivers,
Bobby Labonte (second overall this year) and rookie of the year
Tony Stewart (fourth overall).
</P>
<P>
   ``This sport is still taking off, it hasn't peaked yet,'' said
Gibbs, trying to explain to your humble servant why NASCAR has
become the second biggest sport in America, ranking only benthe
NFL. ``To start with, this sport is built around something that
everyone knows something about _ cars. People love cars. People
love our drivers. They are good guys. They present themselves well
with the fans and the sponsors. Our guys don't pull some of the
other stuff you see in other sports. We wouldn't let them get away
with it if they did. There's too much at stake. All of the drivers
have a morals clause in their contracts. This is not three strikes
and you are out. This is one strike and you are out.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the nine years I've been in this, there hasn't been a
single driving under (the influence). We won't put up with the
stuff you see in other sports. My three major sponsors are worth
collectively more than $220 billion, and no one working for me is
going to do anything to put that relationship at risk. The
demographics are great. It's very popular with women. The NFL
averages 60,000 people a game, we average 120,000 for a Winston Cup
race. Our sport runs longer than the others. We got 10 months a
year. One of these races is like a football game. It's an event.
Fans tailgate. Corporate America can't get enough of the sport.
This is an upscale crowd. We are very close to having a large track
in every major television market in American.''
</P>
<P>
   According to NBC Sports chairman Dick Ebersol, Gibbs is right on
the money on the growth of auto racing on TV.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is second only to the NFL in producing TV ratings on a
consistent basis throughout the regular season,'' said Ebersol, who
recently signed NASCAR to a major long-term deal.
</P>
<P>
   There are 34 Winston Cup races during the course of a season.
``A wonderful thing happened at our race in Miami, which was their
33d of the season,'' said Jon Miller, vice president of programming
at NBC. ``Everyone of the top drivers was there. All of the stars
were there. They show up every week. This is not like the NFL when
you get toward the end of the season and there is no Steve Young,
no Vinny Testaverde, no Terrell Davis. The stars in racing are
still there going as hard as they have all season.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of popularity:
</P>
<P>
   I wouldn't waste my time going to see it in person, or watching
it on television, but there is no questioning the great impact of
modern pro wrestling.
</P>
<P>
   This week the World Wrestling Federation and CEO Vince McMahon
came to the FleetCenter with ``Smackdown.'' Incredibly, all 17,500
tickets were sold in one day, when you have thousands of empty
seats for Bruins and Celtics game every night.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots offense has been shut down four weeks in a row, but
I don't think Indianapolis can do it, which is why I feel the
Patriots will pull the upset and beat the Colts.
</P>
<P>
   To start with, the Patriots have beaten the Colts seven
straight, and it is not easy to get over the idea that another team
has your ``number'' when they've beaten you seven straight, and
came from 21 points behind last time to do it.
</P>
<P>
   There may be a lot of irony here. Bill Belichick and the Jets
(and Drew Bledsoe has give i credit for this) came up with the
defensive scheme that has haunted the Ptriots for the past month.
That is, press the Patriots' smallish wide receivers to neutralize
their speed, and play a two-deep zone over the top, in case they
break free from quick coverage.
</P>
<P>
   Then the two safeties can move in to take away the big play.
There is only one team in the league that has held the Colts to
fewer than 25 pointsthis year. That's the Jets, and they did it
twice, allowing 16 and 13 points. The irony is that the Jets did it
with the same defensive scheme _ they pressed the receivers and
played two deep.
</P>
<P>
   The difference is, against New England they tried to pressure
Bledsoe, while against Colts quarterback Peyton Manning, they
backed off and played more coverage downfield. Manning eats a blitz
alive. He knows where the pressure is coming from, how to avoid it,
and where the open man is going to be. The Jets took a different
tact, making him opt to throw short, making the big play in the
pssing game difficult, and forcing the Colts to march the ball,
where more mistakes can occur.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots tried to pressure Manning when he came to
Foxborough in the second game of the regular season, and he put 28
points on the board in 30 minutes. Peyton dominated them. In the
second half, the Patriots backed off, and the Colts did not score
again. The Colts do not have a great cast on defense, but play Vic
Fangio's zone blitz scheme very well. However, unlike the Jets,
Bills, Dolphins, and Cowboys, the Colts don't appear to have the
defensive backs to press the Patriot recievers off the line of
scrimmage and get away with it.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   You are a super sleuth if you can come up with the fictitious
name Charley Barkley used at the Ritz when he came to Boston
Thursday night. Answer is below. Don't peek. Here's my own Sir
Charles story. I had dinner with him, Payne Stewart, and Robert
Fraley in the midst of the 1992 Olympics in Barcelona, the first
year of the Dream Team. Charles was being widely criticized widely
that week for elbowing a player from Angola, and we were kidding
him that night.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know why everyone is on me,'' said Charles in defense,
``Karl Malone hit some guy from Croatia so hard with an elbow that
his eyes started watering and he didn't want to play the rest of
the game. Think his name was (Dino) Radja.'' Guess who showed up
with the Celtics the next year? Radja. Barkley said Friday that
Stewart was on the way to see him when the golfer's plane crashed
in October.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got along great,'' he said. ``I loved the guy. He was a
fine man. I had some great times playing golf with him. I spoke to
him the day before (the fatal crash). He was coming to Houston to
play in a golf tournament, so we were going to get together. He was
going to come to our game. I still can't believe it happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Barkley says Kevin McHale was ``the best player I ever played
against. Both ways. He was hard for me to stop on offense. I
couldn't do it. He was too big for me. And he was so good on
defense, it s hard for me to score on him.'' Barkley, inch for
inch, ``I'm 6-4 1/2 in stocking feet'', is the greatest rebounder
in NBA history. ``I just loved to rebound. It's been that way my
whole life. When I first came to pro ball, Moses Malone took me
aside and gave me some tips. Moses was one of the greatest
rebounders ever. When that ball was in the air, I just said to
myself, `this one is mine.' ''
</P>
<P>
   We will miss you, Charles.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The crowd that showed up to vote on the Patriots Stadium issue
in a special town meeting was a Foxborough-record 2,329. The
crucial vote on the access road was 1,731-121, 93.5 percent. What
swayed the town more than anything else toward the stadium was the
Patriots upping the present ante of $400,000 per year to upwards of
$2 million a year when the stadium is finished . . . Consider this:
The Red Sox had 13 pitchers on the disabled list last season and
still finished first in pitching in the American League. Tom
``Flash'' Gordon, prime among that unlucky group, is scheduled for
surgery next week.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The US champion Marlboro Shamrocks thought their season was over
with a fifth national title two weeks ago, but there is another
challenge that they are going to accept for a great reason. ``The
Wichita Drillers have said for years they are better than us and
want to play us,'' said Shamrocks coach Bob Brennan. ``We play in
the USFA. They play in the AFA. It's like the old NFL-AFL days.
We've neer played them before, but we're going to play them now
because we wtto do something for this Firefighter Relief Fund in
Worcester. We're only about 15 miles from Worcester, so what
happened is close to home. Wichita has agreed to come and play us
in Marlboro next Saturday at 1 o'clock. This will be like the first
Super Bowl (of semi-professional football) and we are going to give
all the proceeds to that fund. We're hoping to play a game at
Fitton Field in Worcester next spring to give even more money to
the fund.'' . . . If you want to help in Worcester, here is a way
to do it. Phil Castinetti of Sportsworld in Everett, the largest
memorabilia store in New England, is having his ninth-annual All
Boston Sports Auction and will donate all of the proceeds on a 1939
Ted Williams replica jersey to the Firefighters Fund. The auction
starts Dec. 17. You can get a catalog and other information by
calling 617-387-7220.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Former Patriot defensive coordinator Al Groh is one of the top
candidates for the vacant head coaching job at Princeton. They
couldn't pick a better man. Groh's son, Matt, was the starting QB
for the Princton freshman last year . . . Virginia Tech football
coach Frank Beamer, whose team will play Florida State for the
national championship, said he was a ``house'' away from taking the
head coaching job at Boston College in 1990. Beamer was a top
candidate for the job before Tom Coughlin got the position. Beamer
came to Boston, met with athletic director Chet Gladchuk, accepted
the deal and went house-hunting the same day. When he saw how
expensive houses were in Newton and in surrounding towns, he
decided it wasn't that bad living in Blacksburg, Va., for a lot
less just eight miles from the office, and went back to Tech . . .
Before deciding to go to Boston College, Tim Hasselbeck was pursued
hardest by Northwestern and coach Gry Barnett. ``I thought that was
where Tim was going to go,'' said father Don, a Colorado alumnus.
``But he decided to go to BC and follow in Matt's footsteps.''
Coincidentally, Garnett left Northwestern and is nowthe head coach
of Colorado, which plays against Tim and the Eagles in the
Insight.com bowl in Tucson. On the way, the Hasselbeck clan will
stop in Green Bay to spend Christmas with Matt, who is backup to
Brett Favre on the Packers. ``When we visited Green Bay before to
have Christmas with Matt, the boys decided to have a flag-football
game at a local field,'' said Don. ``One of his brothers whacked
Matt in the nose and broke it, and he had to go back to Lambeau
Field and the trainer to get it taken care of. It's the hardest he
got hit all that year.'' The third Hasselbeck, Nathaniel, a wide
receiver/safety, heads to BC next year.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to all of those who sent money to help Greg Bednarz of
the Weymouth Club travel to Japan in search of the world's light
heavyweight arm wrestling championship. With sizable donations from
John Hancock and Terry Clark and Clark Co., in Boston, plu many of
you, Bednarz raised enough money to make the trip, and didn't let
anyone down. At 42, going against competitors averaging between 25
and 30 years old, Bednarz did the incredible, winning the title on
both arms, which no one had done before . . . Quiz answer: James
Bond.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Will McDonough is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
