<HEADER>
A5575 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-INVEST-WITH-WEISS-ART     12-10 1048
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVEST-WITH-WEISS-ART-$ADV12-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INVESTING WITH RICHARD T. WEISS: STRONG COMMON STOCK 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Ill., Wis., Calif.)   (ART ADV: Graphic of Strong Common Stock is being sent to NYT
graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by
calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, DEC. 12)  
 (af)  
 By CAROLE GOULD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Investors who dabble in smaller-capitalization stocks have had a
lot to grumble about in recent years. But you won't hear complaints
from Richard T. Weiss, portfolio manager of the $1.60 billion
Strong Common Stock and $2.37 billion Strong Opportunity funds,
even though both offerings are laden with small and midcap
companies.
</P>
<P>
   To him, the poor showing last year among smaller stocks was
``the equivalent of a hundred-years storm,'' Weiss said, adding
that the clouds were already breaking up. Calling 1999 a
``transition year,'' he said the large caps' winning streak was
bound to end in 2000: ``The market will shift and small cap will
tend to do much better than larger-cap stocks.''
</P>
<P>
   Weiss commutes from his home in Chicago to the headquarters of
Strong Investments in Menomonee Falls, Wis., near Milwaukee. Fond
of cowboy boots, the theater and the avocado ranch he owns near
Santa Barbara, Calif., Weiss, 48, strikes an independent stance and
often mines forgotten precincts of the market. So the recent poor
performance of the midcap and small-cap issues gives him plenty of
opportunity to find the kind of inexpensive stocks he prefers.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you get beyond the biggest 25 stocks and out of the
technology group, the rest of the market is reasonably priced,''
Weiss said. ``Not dirt cheap, but reasonable.''
</P>
<P>
   His funds have fared well. The Common Stock fund, which has been
closed to new investors since 1993, returned 20.2 percent a year,
on average, for the three years through Dec. 3, compared with 14.9
percent for its peer group of midcap blend funds, according to
Morningstar Inc., the Chicago financial publisher.
</P>
<P>
   The Opportunity fund, which is less risky, returned 21.9 percent
a year, on average, for the three years through Dec. 3, versus 10.3
percent for its category of midcap value funds, Morningstar said.
</P>
<P>
   Weiss is superstitious _ he carries a lucky pen, pencil and
coins and wears an elephant hair bracelet. Soft-spoken, sometimes
laconic, he can sound almost mystical when talking about markets.
</P>
<P>
   He strives to ``listen for the quiet,'' as he puts it, when
searching for neglected stocks. ``Some market segments are simply
ignored, not necessarily because they're bad,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Weiss also likes to ``find areas that may have been hard hit but
are basically sound industries with the potential for higher
P/E's.'' Last summer, for example, when worries about Year 2000
computer problems pushed down second-quarter earnings in the
software sector, ``we were able to buy many good Internet-centric
software companies,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   His preferred valuation method is called private value analysis,
in which he tries to figure out what an entire company would be
worth to a knowledgeable buyer.
</P>
<P>
   The analysis varies, depending on the industry. But for
conventional operating companies, he is willing to pay seven to
nine times cash flow. He will pay more for technology companies.
</P>
<P>
   He might sell a stock when the price reaches 80 percent to 100
percent of private market value _ but not always, he said. ``If
it's a unique asset and the value will grow,'' he said, ``we'll
hold on until the value catches up with the stock price.''
</P>
<P>
   He recently added to his position in Hollinger International,
the Toronto media company owned by Conrad Black. Among its
newspapers is The London Daily Telegraph, which survived a recent
price war with The Times of London, owned by Rupert Murdoch's News
Corp. Should Murdoch raise prices at that paper, The Telegraph
would follow, Weiss said, ``and any price rise would fall directly
to the bottom line.''
</P>
<P>
   At Hollinger's National Post, a new Canadian newspaper,
``circulation has vastly exceeded expectations,'' he said, ``and I
think that will translate into higher revenues, because it has a
lower cost structure than its competitors.''
</P>
<P>
   Weiss expects three-year earnings growth of more than 20 percent
a year.
</P>
<P>
   He bought shares in August at $11; the stock closed on Friday at
$13.1875, or 75 percent of what he sees as its private market value
_ $18 a share.
</P>
<P>
   He also likes Barnes &AMP; Noble, the bookseller. ``The market
thinks the Internet will put booksellers out of business. I
disagree,'' Weiss said, adding that he believes online market share
will increase only modestly going forward.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, the company is using innovative strategies to tie
together its Internet site and its stores, he said _ for example,
by delivering books ordered online in New York City with a
messenger service.
</P>
<P>
   The main offline rival of Barnes &AMP; Noble is the Borders Group,
which trades at 13 times this year's earnings. He calculated that
excluding Barnesandnoble.com, the separately-traded online
affiliate, Barnes &AMP; Noble trades at less half that. ``Any way you
look at it,'' Weiss said, ``it's ridiculously cheap.''
</P>
<P>
   In September, he bought shares at $25.45 each. The stock closed
on Friday at $21.9375, or 63 percent of his estimate of its private
market value of $35 a share.
</P>
<P>
   Another favorite is Seagate Technology, the disk drive maker
based in Scotts Valley, Calif. ``Right now, business is terrible
because there's a lot of pricing pressure,'' Weiss said. ``But
we're at the bottom of the cycle and things should get better from
now on.''
</P>
<P>
   Seagate owns a 30 percent stake in Veritas Software, which
produces software used in storage area networks, as well as
positions in several other software companies. In total, the stakes
are worth $49 a share, Weiss figures.
</P>
<P>
   So Seagate, which closed on Friday at $38.8125, sells for less
than the value of its holdings, ``and you get the largest disk
drive manufacturer in the world for free,'' he said. He expects the
company to become profitable next year.
</P>
<P>
   He started buying shares in July, at an average cost of $25.50
each. The shares now trade for 60 percent of his estimate of
private market value _ $65 a share.
</P>
</TEXT>
