<HEADER>
A5581 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-OBOE-DREAM-PERFORMANC     12-10 1283
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBOE-DREAM-PERFORMANCE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AILING TEENAGER'S WISH: TO PERFORM WITH THE PHILHARMONIC 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., France)  (ART ADV: A photo, NYT8, has been sent. Non-subscribers can
purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By RALPH BLUMENTHAL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Clutching her oboe case and looking for all the world
like any other teenager out with her family to share the merriment
of the season, Johanna Johnson arrived at Lincoln Center on
Thursday and made her way to the Christmas tree at the fountain.
</P>
<P>
   But Johanna, a 16-year-old aspiring musician and soccer player
from Grass Valley, Calif., a suburb of Sacramento, wasn't just any
visitor. Battling Hodgkin's disease, a cancer of the lymph tissue
that in her case appears to have gone into remission, she was asked
this summer by the Make a Wish Foundation, which grants requests to
children with life-threatening illnesses, to pick the thing she
most wanted to do.
</P>
<P>
   Johanna did not ask for a trip to Walt Disney World, or for a
shopping spree or a meeting with her favorite celebrity, the three
most popular requests the foundation receives.
</P>
<P>
   Instead Johanna said, ``I want to sit in the middle of a great
orchestra.''
</P>
<P>
   After some research on the Internet and the New York
Philharmonic's Web page, she zeroed in on the Philharmonic and its
longtime principal oboist, Joseph Robinson.
</P>
<P>
   So it was that Robinson and the Philharmonic not only invited
her to visit the orchestra and receive a lesson from him but also
to play alongside him Saturday night in Avery Fisher Hall when the
orchestra performs Aaron Copland's Third Symphony under Andrew
Litton.
</P>
<P>
   Never has such a young person who is not a featured soloist ever
played with the orchestra, the Philharmonic said. The only guest
appearance by a nonprofessional musician goes back more than 30
years when George Plimpton played the gong, triangle and sleigh
bells with the Philharmonic for a television documentary on NBC in
1968.
</P>
<P>
   The Copland symphony has significant parts for oboe but as
acting assistant principal, Johanna, who has two years on the oboe
and five on the clarinet, will mainly support and reinforce the
louder passages. ``She plays pretty much everything except the
solos,'' said Robinson.
</P>
<P>
   Even before her debut, Johanna emerged from a rehearsal
pronouncing her visit a success. ``I wanted to sit and hear music
all around me,'' she said. ``What can I say? My wish came true.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope I can be somebody's wish some day.''
</P>
<P>
   The Philharmonic was equally delighted.
</P>
<P>
   It was last April, when she was 15, that a lump she had noticed
in her neck months earlier and ignored was diagnosed as an enlarged
lymph node from Hodgkin's disease. The cancer had spread to a
second site. While continuing to play in her high school soccer
league and as principal oboist in the Auburn Youth Symphony, she
underwent chemotherapy and radiation treatment. Her hair fell out
and is now growing back.
</P>
<P>
   The disease went into remission and a recent checkup showed
Johanna to be cancer-free, said her father, Richard, a Lutheran
pastor. Although there is a high recovery rate, the radiation
treatment itself raises the risk of new tumors.
</P>
<P>
   ``With cancer you never know,'' Johnson said, adding that
Johanna was determined to prevail. ``Her attitude was `I'm going to
beat this.'''
</P>
<P>
   In August Johanna was called by a volunteer for the Make a Wish
Foundation, which since 1980 has granted wishes to 66,000 children,
the organization said.
</P>
<P>
   Her wish caught the organization by surprise. ``What's an
oboe?'' the volunteer asked. Johanna was also quizzed to make sure
she was uttering her own request, not her parents'. She convinced
them that sitting in at the Philharmonic and meeting Robinson, a
teacher of prominent oboists, was indeed her wish.
</P>
<P>
   So on Thursday, Robinson was there to greet her as Johanna,
along with her father and her mother, Lois, a kindergarten teacher
and singer, and her 19-year-old brother, Luke, arrived at the
Lincoln Center plaza, their air ticket and stay at the Marriott
Marquis Hotel paid by the foundation. It also gave Johanna $250 to
buy a black dress and shoes for the concert. (Her earrings were a
gift from her English teacher, Mike Cartan.)
</P>
<P>
   Robinson, a 22-year-veteran of the Philharmonic, turned Johanna
around to face Avery Fisher Hall. ``You're playing in there, you
know that?'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Johanna replied quietly, ``Yeah.''
</P>
<P>
   He said, ``You don't seem to be the least bit nervous about
this.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You just can't see because I'm wearing so many clothes,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   He asked her about her oboe reeds and she pulled out an Altoids
tin.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's your case?'' Robinson asked, winking. He had a surprise
in store.
</P>
<P>
   Walking the family to the Shun Lee West restaurant for lunch,
Robinson told Johanna, ``You paid me the greatest compliment of my
life.''
</P>
<P>
   Johanna said, ``It was either you or Mia Hamm,'' confessing that
she had briefly considered asking to meet this soccer star.
</P>
<P>
   She had another admission for Robinson. She had never really
heard him play but learned about him on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   He feigned dismay. ``I thought you must have my picture on your
wall, and all my recordings.''
</P>
<P>
   No, she said. But now that she thought about it, she said, she
had heard him play after all. ``I went to the Internet to see what
you looked like and clicked on a sample of your music,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   After cracking open fortune cookies _ Johanna's said, ``You will
travel both far and wide for business and pleasure'' _ the group
decamped for Robinson's apartment where Johanna was to receive an
oboe lesson.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson rearranged her hands. ``Secret service fingers are no
good on the oboe,'' he said. ``They should move like Prussian
soldiers, goosestepping.''
</P>
<P>
   Urging her to greater passion, he said, ``You get out of your
tone what you put into it, kind of like life itself.'' At another
point he urged: ``More Bloomingdale's tone, less Kmart. More like
mahogany, less like pine.''
</P>
<P>
   Johanna took a deep breath to start again and Robinson stopped
her.
</P>
<P>
   ``Does anyone tell you not to do that?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes,'' she said. ``Everyone.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, he said, without the big breath, ``Do like a karate chop:
kind of hit the cane, blow your brains out.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The best defense is a good offense,'' he said. ``Don't yield.
You have to dominate the cane.''
</P>
<P>
   He regaled her with stories of his teacher, Marcel Tabuteau who,
Robinson recalled, once told him: ```There were a few good notes.
And they're still ringing.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``The hair stood up on the back of my neck,'' Robinson said.
``That was my road to Damascus.''
</P>
<P>
   Then he said with deceptive casualness, ``We got this package
yesterday from Paris.'' He put it in her hands.
</P>
<P>
   She opened it, revealing a new oboe from F. Loreepremier
fabricator of the instrument. Robinson had prevailed on the
company's owners, the Gourdons, to raid one of their outgoing
shipments and substantially cut the usual $5,000 price; the rest
Robinson raised from contributions by himself and other players and
friends.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh My God!'' Johanna said, burying her face in her hands. ``Am
I awake or am I dreaming?''
</P>
<P>
   ``No more plastic, baby'' Robinson said.
</P>
<P>
   Friday morning, Johanna arrived at Avery Fisher Hall for the
rehearsal. The players made a fuss over her. ``Ah, don't be
worried,'' said Mark Nuccio, a clarinettist. ``We're harmless.'' As
the Copland orchestrations swept the hall, and Johanna got the
signal to play for the first time, she lifted her new oboe to her
lips and blew. Then she turned to Robinson, gave a slight smile,
and turned the page.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-10-99 2021EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991210.0279 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-10 20:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5582 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-FBC-ALVIN-HAMILTON11-     12-10 0912
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-ALVIN-HAMILTON11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hamilton puts Alvin `on the map'
 &HT;    By J.C. Clemons
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALVIN, S.C. _ They will be rolling up the rugs and pushing back
tables and chairs in the Low Country tonight. Getting ready for a
Heisman Trophy party.
</P>
<P>
   ``They'd better get the cops from everywhere around here, I mean
it, because we're going to block off the streets and have ourselves
a good time,'' said Iva Beauford, owner-operator of the small
African-American community's lone convenience store.
</P>
<P>
   As hordes of sportswriters and TV crews made their way to Alvin,
home of Georgia Tech quarterback Joe Hamilton, much has been made
about what Alvin does not have.
</P>
<P>
   True, there are no stoplights, McDonald's or movie theaters.
</P>
<P>
   But what the town of about 500, that evolved when former slaves
left plantations to sharecrop after the Civil War before eventually
tending their own land, does have is an abundance of decent,
hard-working, pride-filled people. Just like Hamilton.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's driven, and always wanted to win _ and to be the best,''
says Mark Hamilton, Joe's uncle, who will be among at least 50
family members attending the Gator Bowl in Jacksonville, Fla., Jan.
1.
</P>
<P>
   That high self-regard will be on display tonight when Hamilton
joins other Heisman hopefuls in New York for the presentation.
</P>
<P>
   Already, though, Alvin has hit the big time.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're never going to find Alvin, unless you go there,'' says
Pierson Prioleau, a rookie defensive back with the San Francisco
49ers, who is Hamilton's first cousin. ``You'd always have to say
it's close to Charleston, or something like that. Now it's on the
map.''
</P>
<P>
   College recruiters did find Alvin, where Hamilton, Prioleau and
Penn State star defensive end Courtney Brown played at Macedonia
High. The school has since closed and then was torched by
arsonists, and there are no more blue-chip recruits.
</P>
<P>
   Matters not, the deed has been done. Heisman Trophy or not.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all just wanted people to know that there are good, decent
folks in Alvin,'' Prioleau says. ``Knowing Joe, he's going to be
hurt if he doesn't win the Heisman. Not for himself, but for his
family and the people of Alvin. But he will get over it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Joe's a fighter, and he'll come to realize that he's been
blessed _ truly blessed _ just to be considered for the Heisman.''
</P>
<P>
   It may be a foregone conclusion that Wisconsin running back Ron
Dayne's name will be etched on the trophy. Yet, back home, Lil' Joe
already has been declared a winner.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tell you, I'm so proud of him,'' Silas Hamilton, Joe's
grandfather, says while watching television as Tech's star receives
the Davey O'Brien Award, which goes to the top quarterback. ``I
tried to teach him the right way, and Joe never forgot.''
</P>
<P>
   Silas Hamilton, 79, taught his seven children, and their
children, values. Of religion, family _ and hard work.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting in his modest home warmed by a space-heater, lots of
plants and walls and shelves filled with framed pictures of loved
ones _ all smiling _ Silas Hamilton wears a blue Georgia Tech
sweatshirt. On the front it reads, ``1998 ACC Champions,'' with a
gold helmet and ``No. 14, Joe Hamilton'' on the back.''
</P>
<P>
   There are more telling tipoffs of their connection.
</P>
<P>
   A blue ``GT'' cap, tipped back and to the right, just the way
Joe Hamilton is prone to wearing his. The warm smile, twinkling
eyes that look directly at yours, and the handshake, firm and
wrapped amongst work-worn fingers.
</P>
<P>
   There are nine of them, the middle one on the left hand having
been lost in a mill accident. One of Silas Hamilton's daughter's
also lost part of a finger, at the same mill. They returned to
work.
</P>
<P>
   Silas Hamilton would go anywhere to work _ the Charleston Navy
Yard, the mill in Jamestown, road construction and the Santee River
Dam. Yet, he'd come back every night to his beloved Alvin, his
sweet-potato patch and his hunting grounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a little fella, but I worked all over the place,'' he
says. ``But I stayed here where I was born and raised. I never had
it in my mind to leave Alvin. Back in my day, there wasn't much.
Now, Alvin is picking up pretty well.''
</P>
<P>
   There is a new community center, where the youngsters now play
little-league football instead of the sandlot variety in the field
behind Kinlaw's barbershop that produced Hamilton, Prioleau, Brown
and 18 other Division I football players the past six years.
</P>
<P>
   The shining light, however, may be ``M&AMP;B Community Mart,'' which
opened in January and exhibits the don't-quit spirit around Alvin
that Joe Hamilton has made a hallmark of his career.
</P>
<P>
   The ``M,'' is for Moultrie, Iva Beauford's family name. Her
husband, Jethro Beauford, proved the ``B.''
</P>
<P>
   ``My mother ran a store right next door,'' Iva Beauford says.
``It had a store on one level, a restaurant on another, and then a
club. She named it the `Holiday Inn.' Then one day the other
Holiday Inn sent a letter telling her she couldn't call it that no
more.
</P>
<P>
   ``So, she called it the `Three Roof Inn.' But it burned down.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, the ``Three Roof Inn'' lives on through ``M&AMP;B Community
Mart.'' Just as Alvin lives through its football heroes. Heisman
Trophy, or not.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're thinking about putting up a banner across the road:
Alvin, S.C., Home of Champions _ Joe, Courtney and Pierson,''
Beauford says. ``Wouldn't that be nice?''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
