<HEADER>
A5583 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-FBC-HAMILTON11-COX     12-10 0773
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-HAMILTON11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hamilton again an underdog for Heisman
 &HT;    By Tony Barnhart
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ John Heisman was at Georgia Tech from 1904 to 1919,
longer than any of his eight coaching stops. But in one of the
ironies of sport, no player from Tech has won the Heisman Trophy,
college football's most coveted individual honor.
</P>
<P>
   Quarterback Joe Hamilton, the most prolific offensive player in
Atlantic Coast Conference history, would love to be the first to
bring the Heisman to Georgia Tech when the 65th trophy is presented
tonight at the Downtown Athletic Club.
</P>
<P>
   Will it happen? Probably not. All of the early surveys among the
voting panel of 921 made up of media, former winners and football
officials point in the direction of Wisconsin running back Ron
Dayne. This season Dayne broke the NCAA career rushing record held
by Texas' Ricky Williams, the 1998 Heisman recipient.
</P>
<P>
   But Hamilton, a senior from Alvin, S.C., wants you to know that
for him, it has never been about the trophy. Sure, picking up that
impressive piece of hardware would be nice. The joy Hamilton feels,
he said, comes from the journey. It's a long, long way from
Macedonia Middle School, where he began his football career, to one
of five Heisman finalists. It has been a memorable ride.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who would ever think that somebody from Alvin could wind up in
New York with a shot at the Heisman Trophy?'' Hamilton said. ``And
I can honestly say I have enjoyed every minute of it.''
</P>
<P>
   This has been a big week for Hamilton. On Wednesday, he traveled
to Orlando, Fla., for Thursday night's Home Depot Awards Show on
ESPN, where he was named the nation's top quarterback. Then, it was
off to New York on Friday, where Hamilton and the other four
finalists got to take a big Christmas bite out of the Big Apple.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last week we had the ACC (awards) banquet here, and now I get
to meet all the other guys I've just read about and seen on TV,''
he said. ``To me, that's the most fun _ just hanging out with the
guys.''
</P>
<P>
   During the season, Hamilton said he never allowed himself to
think about the Heisman race. But he confessed that once the
regular season was over, he indulged in some daydreams.
</P>
<P>
   ``Winning the Heisman cannot be one of your goals,'' Hamilton
said. ``It just doesn't work that way. But now that the season is
over, I can say that I did everything that I could do. I feel
really good about the way I played. Whatever happens now is out of
my hands. But, yeah, I can imagine what it would feel like to walk
up there and accept the trophy.''
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton reads the papers and watches television. He surfs the
Net. He knows the score on the Heisman and that his chances of
winning are remote. If he finishes second to Dayne, he will be the
second runner-up from Georgia Tech. Billy Lothridge finished behind
Navy's Roger Staubach in 1963.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know people will find this hard to believe, but I'm not
going to be really disappointed if my name isn't called,'' Hamilton
said. ``I'm there with a lot of great players. Whoever gets it is
going to be a great player.''
</P>
<P>
   The award will be presented in the tiny Heisman Room on the 13th
floor of the Downtown Athletic Club. Only family members and
coaches of the finalists, key Heisman officials and ESPN, which is
televising the event, are allowed in the room. Sitting behind
Hamilton will be his parents, Joseph and Ginger.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've wanted to go to everything,'' Hamilton said. ``I think
they are more excited than I am, and I didn't think that was
possible.''
</P>
<P>
   If Hamilton wins the Heisman, he'll spend two more days in New
York getting the traditional tour that goes to all the recipients.
If not, he returns Sunday, when his attention will turn to a Jan. 1
date with Miami in the Gator Bowl. In February, there will be
another round of awards banquets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some guys think it's a drag, but I think it's fun,'' Hamilton
said.
</P>
<P>
   Tonight, Hamilton said he expects his thoughts to drift back to
middle school, where coach Ken Green saw something special in the
tiny seventh-grader.
</P>
<P>
   He'll think about all of his friends in Alvin, huddling around
TV sets waiting to get a glimpse of the man who put their city on
the map.
</P>
<P>
   He'll think about how he came to Georgia Tech as an uncertain
freshman and how he will leave as the confident, most productive
quarterback in school history.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really only had one goal when I came to Georgia Tech,''
Hamilton said.
</P>
<P>
   ``And that was to get better every year I was in school. I think
I did that.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
