<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATRIOTS RUNNING GAME? DON'T SELL IT SHORT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Servie clients)  
 By SHIRA SPRINGER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ The shoulder shrug was no act. Rookie
running back Kevin Faulk was not trying to feign disinterest.
Friday after practice as he leaned against his locker, Faulk did
not have the time or energy to put up a front.
</P>
<P>
   And the shoulder shrug spoke volumes. Here we go again. Another
week. Another set of rushing statistics. Another reason for hope or
depair. It was not the last time Faulk would hear questions and
criticisms of the running game. The now-you-see-it, now-you-don't
nature of the New England ground attack lends itself to speculation
and conen.
</P>
<P>
   The speculation comes from inconsistency and the inclination to
want to fix it. The concern comes with the cold winter months upon
us and the time-tested football adage that you must have a running
game to survive December. But a long look at the numbers would show
that the running game continues to post respectable gains. The
concern is not unwarranted, but the situation is far from dire.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're improving week by week and it's just something that
we've got to maintain,'' said Faulk. ``(The statistics) are not
something we really keep an eye on. We just need to go out there
and perform. We just need to keep coming out every week and doing
what we're doing. We have to do it even better the next week and
the next week and keep on going.''
</P>
<P>
   Added the Patriots' leading rusher, Terry Allen, ``It's always
going to be iffy, until we get to the point where we stick with it.
With the opportunities that we get, I think we do what we can.''
</P>
<P>
   And Allen has been doing just fine. He ranks fifth among AFC
scoring leaders with eight touchdowns. The veteran also is ninth
among AFC running backs with 690 yards on 188 attempts. While the
Colts' rookie sensation, Edgerrin James, leads all conference
rushers with a 4.3 average and 1,210 yards through 12 games, Allen
averages a creditable 3.7 yards.
</P>
<P>
   The last time New England faced Indianapolis, Allen's
performance gave fans a reason to believe the Patriotsd found their
running game. After Faulk twisted his ankle in the second quarter,
Allen carried the load on his surgically repaired knees and
battered ankles. The veteran gained 74 yards on 15 carries, alowing
the Patriots to run effectively wen they needed to and proving the
benefits of a balanced offense.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday the Colts will again face a healthy Allen, who can't wait
to rack up the carries and the yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``Having not been injured, I don't feel right,'' said Allen.
``Normally, I'm beat up this time of year, so I feel real good
right now. It does give me a bit of confidence, but at the same
time I'd like to feel different. I'd like to have been used more,
but I understand the situations of the game and what we've been
going through. It's a natural thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Allen leads a group of rushers that has posted numbers
comparable to Patriots teams of the past. Through 12 games, New
England has 1,100 total yards, a 3.4 average. Last season, with
Robert Edwards leading the way, the team accumulated just 945 yards
over the same period. And in 1996 behind Curtis Martin, the
Patriots posted 1,138 yards in their first dozen contests.
</P>
<P>
   Along with Allen, LSU-product Faulk hasbeen a large reason why
New England has maintained its level of ground production despite
the absence of Edwards. The rookie has 65 carries for 223 yards
(3.4 average).
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not that I'm feeling more comfortable with the offense,
it's that I'm feeling more confidence in myself and feeling more
confidence in my ankle from when I hurt it,'' said Faulk of his
improving performances. ``It helps me to let my instincts take over
and just run the ball like I have been doing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've learned a whole lot from Terry. Reading defenses.
Predetermining where all the linebackers are going to be or where
all the defensive linemen are going to be or the safeties. It
really was a smart thing, working me in slowly and letting e
develop.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Faulk, the Patriots' running game remains a work in
progress. Yet, it's clear the team needs a successful running game
to win. New England is 7-0 when it runs the ball 26 times or more.
The denizens of Foxboro Stadium are 0-5 when they don't.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look at the teams that run the ball, they've run the
ball 30-plus times and those are the teams that are winning,'' said
Allen. ``We're not running the ball that many times. (The criticism
of the running game) is unjust because we haven't stuck with it
yet, so you never know how it's going o come out.''
</P>
<P>
   And not much time remains to find out.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
