<HEADLINE>
FIGHT IN MISSISSIPPI A CAREER MOVE FOR RUIZ 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TUNICA, Miss. _ This is a long way to come for a tuneup, but
John Ruiz is hoping it's worth the ride.
</P>
<P>
   The Chelsea, Mass. heavyweight has come to this riverboat
gambling center on the Mississippi to put at risk the World Boxing
Council's No. 1 heavyweight ranking. It is a commodity worth more
than most things he's gotten out of boxing the last seven years,
including all his purses.
</P>
<P>
   This is not being done by chance, although, in a sense, it is
taking a chance with a potential multimillion-dollar payday down
the road as a mandatory callenger for undisputed heavyweight
champion Lennox Lewis. If Ruiz is upset Saturday by a former
contender of little note named Jade Scott, he will have blown his
dream and the millions that follow.
</P>
<P>
   It would not be a loss. It would be a disaster.
</P>
<P>
   But Ruiz (35-3) has never seen fights like this that way.
Several weeks ago, it was he who first suggested to his manager to
make a match with No. 2-rated WBC contender Michael Grant, who is
widely seen as the heir apparent to Lewis's throne. Those
negotiations have not reached fruition because Ruiz wants the same
$1.5 million to risk his ranking that International Boxing
Federation No. 1-rated heavyweight David Tua turned down to fight
Grant. This seems reasonable to Ruiz, but boxing is not a
reasonable businesswch only makes his boldness in seeking out Grant
more refreshing.
</P>
<P>
   Te real problem, though, is that a mandatory WBC title fiht is
at least a year away because Lewis's most recent vitory over
Evander Holyfield counted as a mandatory bout, meaning he does not
have to face the No. 1 WBC contender again until November unless he
chooses to. With more pressing engagements looming with both the
World Boxing Association's and IBF's top contenders, the likelihood
of anything breaking the logjam for Ruiz until the end of next year
is unlikely. So he has decided to go back to work.
</P>
<P>
   That comes in the form of Scott, who just a year ago was the
WBA's No. 2 contender, although always a lightly regarded one.
Despite a 25-3 record, he is not considered a threat to Ruiz by
most boxing observers, except for the fact that men as big as these
are always a threat if they land a punch.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Johnny knocks him out in six rounds,'' said Ruiz's
manager, Norman Stone. ``But these are heavyweights. There's always
a risk. We just think it's worth the gamble.
</P>
<P>
   ``Johnny wants to prove to people he deserves to be the No. 1
contender. He's tired of hearing people question him. That's why he
suggested fighting Grant and it's why he's fighting Scott.''
</P>
<P>
   Why Ruiz is fighting is to stay busy and to keep the WBC off his
back. WBC president Jose Sulaiman has been pestering Don King,
Ruiz's promoter, for some time in an attempt to force him to fight
another ranked challenger to keep his rating. Ruiz is not only
willing to do that, he's willing to do it with the No. 2-ranked
fighter, the highly publicized Grant.
</P>
<P>
   This is not unusual in boxing, it's unheard of. No one who gs to
No. 1 puts it on the line against anything but a cadave until his
title shot arrives. When it does, he takes his $1 million or $2
million payday and rolls the dice. But Ruiz is made of sterner
stuff than that.
</P>
<P>
   What he is hoping is that he will look spectacular on the
Showtime telecast in stopping Scott and thus improve his leverage
in trying to force Grant and executives at HBO to accept what he is
offering: a chance for the fighters to decide who should be the
WBC's No. 1-rated heavyweight.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is refreshing,'' said HBO Sports senior vice president for
programming Lou DiBella, whose network has a long-term contract
with Grant. ``I don't believe John is a legitimate No. 1 guy, but I
understand how this works. It's not his doing. But I'm not willing
to pay him nd King $1.5 million when the fight isn't worth it.''
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't worth it perhaps until Grant found himself nose-first
on the canvas two weeks ago in the first round of his fight with
Andrew Golota. Twice he went down, once on his pants and once on
his face, before rising up, taking a terrible beating for most of
nine rounds and then dropping a tiring Golota in the 10th. When
Golota got up, he simply quit, something he's done four times while
taking HBO's money (twice in his foul-plagued losses to Riddick
Bowe and again when he froze against Lewis and was destroyed in two
minutes).
</P>
<P>
   When that fight was over, Ruiz saw HBO analyst Larry Merchant, a
persistent critic of his ability, and told him, ``He wouldn't have
gotten out of the first round if I was in there tonight.'' Merchant
did not reply.
</P>
<P>
   So now Ruiz is hoping to have that chance in April, buthand his
handlers understand all that might be ahead of him is predicated on
avoiding a fate he's already experienced once in this Deep South
state.
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, Ruiz was 14-0 and feeling good about himself when he
journeyed to Mississippi, a place that has never been kind to
Northerners. He was there to fight another up-and-coming fighter
named Sergei Kobozev. There was only one difference between them.
Stone was in Ruiz's corner. Les Bonnano, the fight's promoter, was
in Kobozev's.
</P>
<P>
   Guess who won the decision?
</P>
<P>
   Ruiz believes this shouldn't happen to him again because he is a
better fighter under any circumstance than Scott, who has not
fought since losing to journeyman Marvin Foster 13 months ago. More
important than that belief is the fact that he understands this
tuneup cannot turn into a need for an overhaul if he wants to get
Grant into the ring.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't get the other fights if we don't win this fight,''
Stone said. ``That's why as much as Johnny wants to fight Grant,
he's told us he doesn't want to hear his name mentioned until after
this fight. Even if we make the fight, he doesn't want to hear
Grant's name until he's done with Scott.''
</P>
<P>
   The reason for that is clear because Ruiz knows what can happen
to a kid from Chelsea if he leaves Mississippi without a win again.
</P>
<P>
   ``The memory of that fight in Mississippi is in my mind,'' Ruiz
admitted. ``It happened to me twice (losing controversial
decisions). I understand I have to fight hard from the first bell
to the last bell. There's no such thing as a tuneup for myself. The
Grant fight is something I really want, but this fight with Scott
is t most important fight of my career. Without it, I can't get the
other ones''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
