<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEAT-SAFETY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDGE FAVORS DALLAS MEAT COMPANY IN USDA FIGHT 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JIM HENDERSON 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ A Texas meat processing company that is a major
supplier of ground beef to school lunchrooms won a temporary
injunction in federal court Friday, effectively preventing the USDA
from shutting down its meat grinding business because of salmonella
contamination.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one thinks that salmonella in meat is a good thing,'' U.S.
District Judge Joe Fish said in extending an earlier restraining
order, ``but that's not what this case is about. The question is
whether the Department of Agriculture had the authority to do what
it did.''
</P>
<P>
   A final determination of the issues, he said, will be made at
trial next spring.
</P>
<P>
   Ten days ago, Fish issued a temporary restraining order against
the government after the USDA pulled its inspectors out of the
Supreme Beef Processors Inc., plant near Fair Park in Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   The action was taken after the company flunked three consecutive
salmonella testing programs in the past year. It was the first meat
company in the nation to fail the salmonella test since tougher
standards were imposed in 1996. A slaughter house controlled by
Supreme Beef in Ladonia, Texas, also failed three rounds of similar
testing.
</P>
<P>
   Without the government inspectors, the company could not legally
sell its meat in interstate commerce.
</P>
<P>
   Steven Spiritas, CEO of the company, testified Friday that if
the restraining order were not continued, it would be difficult for
the company to remain in business.
</P>
<P>
   ``It essentially shuts down the backbone of the business,'' he
said. About 180 of the company's 300 employees are involved in the
ground beef operation, which turns out nearly 600,000 pounds of
meat a day.
</P>
<P>
   The injunction hearing mostly centered on testing methods and
the risk to public safety if the plant continues to operate in
spite of the salmonella levels found in USDA tests.
</P>
<P>
   Spiritas told the court that none of his company's beef has ever
been recalled and no illnesses were ever attributed to it. Supreme
Beef has been operating since 1971, he said. It currently supplies
about 15 percent of the 90 million pounds of beef the USDA
purchases annually for its school lunch programs.
</P>
<P>
   From 1907, when the Federal Meat Inspection Act was passed,
until 1996, inspectors worked mainly by touch, sight and smell to
cull potentially hazardous meat. In 1996, following fatal outbreaks
of meat poisoned by the E. coli bacteria, the USDA adopted
regulations that subjected meat to more scientific testing that
could detect harmful microorganisms.
</P>
<P>
   The regulations allow fowl to be sold with higher levels of
salmonella than beef. Chicken passes inspection if salmonella is
found in 25 of 53 test samples; in turkey, the organism can show up
in 29 of 53 tests.
</P>
<P>
   A beef processor flunks if salmonella is found in more than five
of 53 tests, according to testimony at the hearing.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney's for the company argued that salmonella, a one-cell
organism that appears in fruit, animals and humans, is a naturally
occurring substance and not an ``adulterant,'' and is easily
destroyed by proper cooking. Yet, it is estimated that it causes
550 deaths and 1.4 million illnesses a year in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Gordon, an attorney for consumer groups that have sided
with the USDA, urged the judge to withdraw the temporary
restraining order.
</P>
<P>
   ``What Supreme Beef wants to do is shift the responsibility (for
eliminating salmonella) to a 16-year-old kid flipping burgers in a
fast food restaurant,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   On Nov. 30, the USDA withdrew its inspectors from the plant and
canceled its purchasing contracts with Supreme Beef. That same day,
the company obtained a temporary restraining order from Fish so
that it could continue grinding beef until the issues are heard in
court.
</P>
<P>
   In extending the restraining order, Fish noted that prior to
1996, all beef was ``distributed to consumers containing salmonella
because there were no standards'' and ``there were no outbreaks of
salmonella poisoning.''
</P>
<P>
   Lifting the restraining order, he said, would amount to the
``death penalty'' for Supreme Beef, a punishment he considered too
severe in the absence of a clear threat to public safety.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
