<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-10 20:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5591 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-MUSIC-HALLOFFAME12-CO     12-10 1411
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-HALLOFFAME12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hoping to attract more visitors, Georgia Music Hall of Fame in
Macon puts plans in motion
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, Dec. 12.
 &HT;    By Sonia Murray
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MACON, Ga. _ The numbers people must have seen something in
James Brown's red sequined suit that would-be visitors to the
Georgia Music Hall of Fame just haven't.
</P>
<P>
   When the hall opened here a little more than three years ago,
marketing analysts estimated that 250,000 to 350,000 people would
visit each year.
</P>
<P>
   As it turns out, the analysts were optimistic.
</P>
<P>
   Since the $8 million museum opened Sept. 21, 1996, the facility
has drawn about 233,000 visitors total _ an average of less than
78,000 per year.
</P>
<P>
   But the low turnout doesn't seem to worry Hall of Fame director
Rob Blount.
</P>
<P>
   ``Admissions are important,'' he said. ``But fortunately we're
not solely dependent on them. It's a nonprofit business, meaning,
simply, we're not supposed to make money.''
</P>
<P>
   ``All things considered,'' he added, ``I'm fine with where we
are right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Even if the hall hasn't met attendance projections, said Ruth
Sykes, communications director for the Macon-Bibb County Convention
&AMP; Visitors Bureau, the museum is still the No. 1 hook for Macon _
birthplace of Little Richard, home to Otis Redding's widow, former
headquarters for the Allman Brothers Band, and burial place of the
group's Duane Allman and Berry Oakley, both of whom died in
motorcycle accidents there. Said Deborah Robbe, a Georgia State
University business professor who advocated building the hall in
Atlanta: It takes ``a massive amount of marketing to attract
visitors to something like the Georgia museum. Especially because
of where it is'' _ in this central Georgia city 78 miles southeast
of downtown Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Almost half the museum's budget is subsidized by the state,
through direct subsidies, special tax allocations and grants. The
$7.50 admission has covered about 46 percent of the balance over
the three years.
</P>
<P>
   ``The numbers have improved each year here,'' Blount said.
``Where at the Rock and Roll Hall of Fame, it's gone from a first
year of, like, 1.3 million to 500,000 by the third year.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, that far better known museum in Cleveland _ whose
spokesman, Tim Moore, affirms Blount's rough estimates _ has
attracted more than 2 million visitors in its four years.
</P>
<P>
   After 32 years, the Country Music Hall of Fame in Nashville has
passed the 10 million mark in attendance, including the 196,000
people that visited last year.
</P>
<P>
   But a fairer comparison for the Georgia museum may be with the
Alabama Jazz Hall of Fame in Birmingham. About 500,000 visitors _
or 83,000 a year _ have seen the displays on Nat ``King'' Cole and
Sun Ra and His Intergalactic Space Arkestra since it opened in
1993.
</P>
<P>
   Syndicated radio personality Tom Joyner has brought some of his
listeners to the Alabama museum, ``because I know some folks may
not wake up and say, `You know, I need a little excitement today. I
think I'll go to Birmingham.' You may have to be led there.''
</P>
<P>
   Same goes for Macon: It's not necessarily a destination spot
yet; a lot of folks visiting the museum happen to be in town for
something else.
</P>
<P>
   Chris DeVinney of Atlanta came recently for a conference held at
the hall and ventured down to check out the exhibits. ``I didn't
have to walk far to see something great,'' she said, as she
listened to Sam Cooke recordings.
</P>
<P>
   Augusta's Mike Latka and Jim Clark stopped in recently before a
big bikers convention. And 16-year-old Angela Snyder of Augusta
spent a day showing siblings Rebecca, 6, and Donny, 9, the exhibits
while Mom attended a conference.
</P>
<P>
   Snap. Sssnap. Snap-snap.
</P>
<P>
   Rebecca kept somewhat awkward time with her fingers as Lena
Horne played in the headphones. Donny had barely left the museum's
first major stop, the Rhythm &AMP; Blues Revue, before he yelled:
``When are we leaving?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Shhh,'' dad Don advised. He'd read about the hall in the
newspaper, he said. ``It sounded like a good place to go, if we had
to come. I can't say it would be the reason to come'' to Macon.
</P>
<P>
   Londoner Roger Kirkham, in Macon for a cousin's wedding,
endorsed the 42,000-square-foot facility, however.
</P>
<P>
   ``What this museum has should be required viewing. Even though
there isn't a crowd here, it's not because what's here isn't worth
the attention. Georgia should be proud.''
</P>
<P>
   Proud, but apparently not content.
</P>
<P>
   Although Blount said he's not ``disappointed'' with attendance
figures, the Georgia Hall of Fame, with help, has plans to attract
more visitors. Its strategy includes:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  A $1 million children's exhibit that opened in September. In
it, children in preschool through middle school take a musical tour
of the state, compose their own songs and tap on a king-size
keyboard like the one in the Tom Hanks movie ``Big.'' Blount said
the number of children visiting doubled to 2,204 in November
compared with November 1998. Kids do get in free but are usually
accompanied by a paying adult.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Keeps Calling Me Home: A Gram Parsons Retrospective
Exhibit.'' The display about the Waycross singer-songwriter, a
major country rock influence, runs through December. Over
Thanksgiving weekend, 2,002 people visited the hall.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  An online gift shop expected to be accessible on the hall's
Web site (www.gamusichall. com) sometime this month.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  A print marketing campaign in January by the Macon-Bibb County
Convention &AMP; Visitors Bureau. Its tagline will be ``The Song and
Soul of the South.'' The Georgia Music Hall of Fame ``will be
prominently featured, because it is a critical part of our tourism
package,'' said communications director Sykes.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The ``Let Freedom Ring'' exhibit that will open in February
and run for a month. It will include artifacts, text and historic
photographs that detail the Albany Student Non-Violent Coordinating
Committee Freedom Singers and the group's role in the civil rights
movement. It will also depict Georgia musicians who have effected
social change: Bernice Johnson Reagon, an original Freedom Singer
and a founding member of the a cappella group Sweet Honey in the
Rock, and R&AMP;B singer-songwriter Curtis Mayfield.
</P>
<P>
   After a nine-month marketing survey, the independent agency
hired by the visitors bureau found that when people thought of
Macon, they thought of music first.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're proud of what (the museum) is doing and happy it's
here,'' Sykes said. ``Looking at the marketing estimates that were
made before it even broke ground, it's like, `What happened?!' But
that's what can happen when you have an organization come into a
new market and it bases its estimates on historical information
from other markets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, when you compare what the hall has done in its three
years with the other attractions and destinations in the city, it's
done well,'' Sykes said. ``But yes, when you compare its attendance
to the numbers people expected, it does sound really crippling.''
</P>
<P>
   Much like what GSU's Robbe expected when she heard the Hall of
Fame was opening in Macon, not Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``I worked with an event in Colorado that was 2 1/2 hours away
from the major metropolitan city, so I know firsthand how very
difficult it is to pull these things off,'' says Robbe, who teaches
expositions management.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta conventioneers can't hold parties there after meetings,
like they can at the Fernbank Museum of Natural History, she says.
But the hall can hold more performances from established and young
artists. And more traveling exhibits are a plus.
</P>
<P>
   ``It takes different kinds of events at different times to
constantly keep static things in people's minds,'' Robbe said. ``It
absolutely has to keep reintroducing the Georgia Music Hall of Fame
_ the way Disney does.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, she said, she thought about stopping by the Georgia
museum for the first time on a recent trip down I-75 to Orlando.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I had a lot driving to do,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   It seems drag queen RuPaul's pink sequined dress will have to
wait a little longer for Robbe, and others like her, who have yet
to find their way to Macon.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia Music Hall of Fame
</P>
<P>
   9 a.m.-5 p.m. Mondays-Saturdays; 1-5 p.m. Sundays. $7.50. 200
Martin Luther King Jr. Blvd., Macon, Ga. Information: 912-750-8555.
</P>
<P>
   Sonia Murray writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
