<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCAIN11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    McCain lobbies to keep Cuban boy in U.S.
 &HT;    By Brian E. Crowley
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ A presidential order should be signed keeping 6-year old
Elian Gonzalez in the United States, Arizona Sen. John McCain said
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe that this young man should be absolutely assured
that he will be able to live in freedom and not in slavery,'' the
presidential candidate said during a news conference at the popular
Versaille restaurant in Little Havana.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez, who was found clinging to an inner tube in the ocean
off Fort Lauderdale, Fla., on Thanksgiving Day has become the
center of an international struggle. The boy's mother and
stepfather were among 11 people who drowned in their effort to
reach the United States.
</P>
<P>
   His father, Juan Miguel Gonzalez, has demanded that his son be
returned to Cuba to live with him and his four grandparents.
Cuban-American leaders in Miami argue that the boy belongs here
where he is being cared for by his great uncle and great aunt.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if the father has any right to get his son back, McCain
said he is convinced that the father is not free to express his
opinion about what is best for his son as long as he remains in
Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's obvious what the father would say,'' McCain said. ``That
the young man should enjoy democracy and freedom.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain said Cuban President Fidel Castro should allow the boy's
father to come to the United States or ``to go to a neutral
country'' where he can make his feelings known without fear
retribution.
</P>
<P>
   Castro has expressed outrage at the refusal of the United States
to return Gonzalez's son. There have been mass demonstrations in
Cuba against the United States organized by the Cuban government.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Manuel Slabarria said McCain's stand on the young boy
is the right one and it will help him with Cuban American voters.
``The mother made this an issue when she was willing to give her
life for freedom for her son,'' he said. ``This is an important
matter to us.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain did depart a bit from the more strident Cuban Americans
who say they want nothing to do with Castro until he is overthrown.
McCain said the United States should do the same thing it did with
Vietnam, slowly rebuilding relations over a numbers years with each
side taking small but significant steps toward the goal of working
together.
</P>
<P>
   Later in the day, McCain traveled to Pensacola, where he trained
to be a naval aviator after graduating from Naval Academy in 1958,
to attend a dinner to raise money for his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
