<HEADER>
A5593 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-EGYPTAIR-CRASH-NYT &LR;      12-10 0748
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EGYPTAIR-CRASH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRANSPORTATION BOARD TO CONTINUE EGYPTAIR INQUIRY 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By MATTHEW L. WALD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ After appearing eager last month to turn over the
investigation of the EgyptAir crash to the FBI, the National
Transportation Safety Board said Friday that it would hold on to
the case for at least another month and do a thorough
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators said this was partly because they were looking for
a cockpit instrument that could confirm or refute their theory that
a co-pilot deliberately crashed the jet.
</P>
<P>
   American investigators still think that the crash, which killed
all 217 people aboard the New York-to-Cairo flight on Oct. 31, was
a deliberate act. But after weeks of trying to build an unequivocal
case from the flight data recorder and cockpit voice recorder, and
after complaints from Egyptian officials about the idea that the
crash could have been a murder-suicide, the board chairman, James
Hall, said in a statement Friday that investigators would produce a
full set of reports on all aspects of the crash, as is customary.
</P>
<P>
   Hall said the transcript of the voice recording would be
released with the reports. Previously, board officials had
suggested that the transcript might never be released, because the
case would be handed over to the FBI.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said the investigation would take at least until the
end of January.
</P>
<P>
   Hall had said on Nov. 15, soon after the cockpit voice recorder
was retrieved from the water about 60 miles from Nantucket, that
the board was concentrating on whether the investigation was to
remain under its leadership. The board and other federal agencies,
Hall said, were ``committed to an early resolution to this matter
as soon as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   On Friday he said he would not publicly describe the tape,
because ``I do not believe this transcript can be characterized or
further described without adding to the speculation or misleading
the public about the contents of the recording.'' Other officials
said that this was because of disagreements about what the words
meant and differences of opinion about who said which words.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators believe, based on the tape and the flight data
recording, that a co-pilot, Gamil al-Batouti, entered the cockpit
and replaced the co-pilot then scheduled to fly. Then,
investigators say, the captain briefly left the cockpit and Batouti
turned off the autopilot and put the plane into a steep dive.
American and Egyptian investigators are struggling to determine
whether the words exchanged between the captain when he returned
and Batouti represent an argument or an effort to save the plane.
</P>
<P>
   A salvage ship chartered by the U.S. Navy, the Smit Pioneer, is
expected to leave Quonset, R.I., on Sunday or Monday and begin work
at the site for two or three weeks. The investigators are
particularly interested in a part called a torque tube, which is
under the cockpit and connects the controls of the pilot and the
co-pilot.
</P>
<P>
   They are concentrating on the part because the flight data
recorder showed that the elevators, the moveable panels at the back
of the horizontal tail, moved to different angles instead of in
unison, as they are supposed to. Investigators theorize that this
occurred because one pilot was pushing forward, to make the plane
dive, while the other pulled, to make it climb.
</P>
<P>
   The torque tube is designed to break if 50 pounds of force or
more is exerted in opposite directions. If that happened, the tube
should show rivets that were shorn off; if the elevators moved
separately because of a mechanical problem, the rivets would not be
shorn.
</P>
<P>
   ``Almost inevitably, the wreckage will tell a story without a
spin, without a disagreement,'' one aviation official said.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators will also be looking for signs of any mechanical
flaw that could have caused the crash; there was no evidence of any
on the flight data recorder, Hall said. But, investigators say, the
elevators could have split if the controls became jammed, a
condition that the wreckage might reveal.
</P>
<P>
   Hall said Friday that audio engineers were continuing to analyze
the tape, but that ``no sounds have been detected that would be
consistent with mechanical failures or an explosion.''
</P>
<P>
   He added that safety board engineers, working with Boeing, had
programmed a 767 simulator with information from the flight data
recorder of the plane that crashed, to study the plane's movements.
</P>
</TEXT>
