<SLUG> BC-OLY-REFORM-MEETING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IOC ETHICS COMMITTEE DRAWS MANY QUESTIONS
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By JERE LONGMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAUSANNE, Switzerland _ As the International Olympic Committee
prepares to begin changing its procedures in the wake of the Salt
Lake City bidding scandal, serious questions were raised Friday
about the jurisdiction, intent and independence of its commission
to investigate ethical violations.
</P>
<P>
   The eight-member commission, which includes a former U.S.
senator, Howard Baker Jr., and a former secretary-general of the
United Nations, Javier Perez de Cuellar, announced Friday that it
would not initiate investigations of possible wrongdoing but would
require a written complaint before it began a review.
</P>
<P>
   The ethics commission also said Friday that it would not have
the power to discipline any members newly found to have committed
wrongdoing but would pass its findings on to the IOC's 11-member
executive board, which would decide on any punishment.
</P>
<P>
   The commission further indicated that it was unlikely to
consider any future disclosures of impropriety uncovered by a U.S.
Justice Department investigation of the Salt Lake City scandal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are working for the future,'' Perez de Cuellar said. ``We
are not particularly interested in what happened in the past. We
are interested in prevention. We are still discussing the principle
of nonretroactivity.''
</P>
<P>
   In the past year, the IOC has come under criticism for not being
sufficiently active after rumors of corruption in the Salt Lake
City bidding process became widespread. The IOC maintained that it
had no concrete evidence even after Toronto officials years ago
forwarded a lengthy list of improprieties and one of the
committee's own members, Phil Coles of Australia, helped write
dossiers about his colleagues' vulnerabilities that were
distributed to bid cities.
</P>
<P>
   Much uncertainty emerged at an evening news conference about
just how the IOC would handle any new evidence resulting from the
Justice Department investigation. Two indictments have been issued
so far, both related to allegations that Salt Lake City bid
officials arranged a sham job for the son of Kim Un-yong, a
prominent IOC member from South Korea. Kim received a serious
warning from the IOC executive board, which said that the case
could be reopened if new facts emerged.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, the IOC executive board said that the Kim
case would be handed to the ethics commission. In May, the ethics
commission handed the case back to the executive board. Then this
week, Francois Carrard, director general of the IOC, said that the
ethics commission would review any developments in the case. Not
so, said Keba Mbaye, an IOC member from Senegal who is chairman of
the commission.
</P>
<P>
   Franklin Servan-Schreiber, an IOC spokesman, denied that the IOC
was looking to pass the buck on new evidence arising from the Salt
Lake City investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a shell game,'' Servan-Schreiber said. ``Maybe
there is some confusion.''
</P>
<P>
   The ethics commission has also been charged with developing a
code of conduct for the IOC, which did not have one for the first
century of its existence. Mbaye said the IOC's president, Juan
Antonio Samaranch, would still not be subject to the same rules
against accepting gifts from bid cities as other members are.
Samaranch was excluded from gift limits because he does not vote on
cities bidding for the Winter and Summer Games, Mbaye said.
</P>
<P>
   Samaranch, who nevertheless can exercise great influence on the
voting, was criticized for accepting expensive gifts from Salt Lake
City bid officials. They spent millions of dollars on cash
payments, scholarships, shopping sprees and other favors for IOC
members and their families.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether Samaranch should have been included in the limits
on gifts to improve the IOC's tarnished image, Mbaye said, ``It is
up to the president to decide what he must do for his image.''
</P>
<P>
   Mbaye, a vice president of the International Court of Justice,
took issue with the ``culture of corruption'' label placed on the
IOC by American lawmakers. Ten members were fired or resigned in
the Salt Lake City scandal, and another 10 received warnings. The
IOC is currently composed of 102 members.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is more widespread elsewhere than the IOC,'' Mbaye said,
referring to institutional corruption. ``The majority of the
members of the IOC are honest.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
