u a BC-WORCESTER-MEMORIAL-BO     12-10 1193
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORCESTER-MEMORIAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MASSIVE EFFORT CREATED MEANINGFUL TRIBUTE TO FALLEN FIREFIGHTERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TATSHA ROBERTSON AND JOANNA WEISS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was a spectactular scene, perhaps the largest firefighter's
memorial in US history: 30,000 firefighters and honor guards from
around the world, in full dress uniforms, marching in formation
down the streets of Worcester, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   The thousand of spectators who watched them witnessed a somber,
dignified portrait of order: Men and women, in brass-buttoned navy
jackets and formal hats, silently honoring the six fallen Worcester
firefighters with crisp salutes.
</P>
<P>
   But the preparation for the most massive and moving tributes _
which featured President Clinton, Vice President Gore and a host of
dignitaries _ began just hours after news that the firemen had
answered their final alarm.
</P>
<P>
   The procession and ceremony was assembled in part by Boston
firefighters and the national firefighters' union in Washington,
D.C. _ two groups well experienced in the sad task of preparing
tributes for their dead.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was organized chaos,'' said George Burke, spokesperson for
the International Association of Fire Fighters in Washington, the
national union which helped organize the event. ``We did three
months' work in just three days.''
</P>
<P>
   Steve McDonald, spokesperson for the Boston Fire Department and
leaders of the state and national firefighters union were at a
retirement party in Boston when they heard six men were lost in a
fire at the Worcester Cold Storage &AMP; Warehouse Co.
</P>
<P>
   Just more than an hour after traveling to Worcester that night,
McDonald and other firefighters were on the phone with Burke,
planning for a possible memorial _ even as crews continued to fight
the blaze.
</P>
<P>
   As the news of the tragedy spread, McDonald said, professional
wrestlers performing at the Centrum Arena gave checks for $24,000
to officials at the Worcester Fire Department headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   By Saturday afternoon, Burke and two officials from the national
union office were on a flight from Washington to Worcester.
</P>
<P>
   They met with McDonald and his colleagues with a simple yet
monumental task: use their experience to create a stirring public
tribute to the victims.
</P>
<P>
   Between them, the unofficial committee had helped planned
similar events after firefighters perished in Atlanta, Boston and
Stockton, Calif. Burke and his colleagues had coordinated a large
tribute two years ago for nine crew members who died fighting the
Hotel Vendome fire in 1972.
</P>
<P>
   And they knew that the Worcester Fire Department was too
burdened to do it alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``Understand, this is a very taxing situation for the locals,''
said Burke. ``They are hard at work trying to remove their brothers
from that tomb, they have to deal with the families, and in this
case there were six families.''
</P>
<P>
   By Sunday morning, city council members, Mayor Raymond Mariano
and Worcester public works and chamber of commerce officials were
brought into the process along with members of the city
firefighters' union.
</P>
<P>
   Soon, city leaders, the planning committee and local
firefighters agreed that the memorial service should take place on
Thursday in the Worcester Centrum. Six city firefighters were
assigned as liasons to each victim's family, explaining the event
and asking for their permission to stage it.
</P>
<P>
   The families were always involved in the planning, said
McDonald; one of the widows, he said, wanted a memorial service
instead of a full funeral because it would be too painful for her
sons often attend games or concerts in the Centrum.
</P>
<P>
   ``We needed to have all the families in agreement if this is
what they wanted,'' Burke said. ``If just one family member said
no, than we would have never had the memorial.''
</P>
<P>
   Computers and phones, donated from local businesses, were
connected to conference rooms of The Crown Plaza Hotel in
Worcester, which became the nerve center of the operation.
</P>
<P>
   As word of the tragedy spread, it became clear from the flood of
condolence calls that the event would draw thousands of mourners
from across the country and around the world.
</P>
<P>
   By Monday, union officials met with city leaders again to
discuss dozens of details: parking for the hundreds of buses
expected, the procession route, jumbo TV screens for the overflow
crowds, the logistics of shutting down New England's second-largest
city for a day.
</P>
<P>
   Firefighters also began listing what they would need from the
Centrum staff: flowers, audio and visual equipment. The state fire
marshal's office donated radios so all could communicate.
</P>
<P>
   Now it was time to put the word out.
</P>
<P>
   By Tuesday, firefighters from Worcester and across the state
began calling their comrades. Web sites were set up and local
departments relayed information to their firefighters.
</P>
<P>
   Even as the grim search to find four bodies still missing in the
warehouse wore on, Worcester firefighters used donated cellphones
to make more calls, ensuring that every firefighter in every
department they knew of had the opportunity to attend.
</P>
<P>
   By Tuesday evening, the White House had confirmed that Clinton
would speak at the service. Gore, whom the local and national
firefighters' union had endorsed for president, also promised to
attend.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once we knew Clinton was coming, that put a whole other
overlay to the preparation,'' said Burke. ``There were White House
staff and security considerations and all the things that go with a
presidential visit.''
</P>
<P>
   That meant everyone entering the Centrum had to pass through
metal detectors and security checks, and that the national media
would likely attend, too.
</P>
<P>
   On the day of the event, the slate-gray arena stage was adorned
with flowers, polished yellow helmets and large color portraits of
each victim. Clinton and Gore both spoke privately to the families
and firefighters before taking their places on the stage, now fixed
with a podium bearing the presidential seal.
</P>
<P>
   The families took their places, and wave after wave of
firefighters silently filled the seats. As with any massive event,
the orderly appearance belied a few hitches.
</P>
<P>
   McDonald tells of how he had asked 30 honor guard members from
various departments to line the stage. However, 30 entire honor
guards of three to ten men each showed up.
</P>
<P>
   Quick thinking yielded a solution. McDonald directed the honor
guards to line the aisles of the arena instead.
</P>
<P>
   At first, Burke said, officials thought the Centrum would be
large enough to hold the 15,000 firefighters they expected. But at
least that many more were still marching down the streets to the
arena as the ceremony began.
</P>
<P>
   The overflow crowds watched the service on the jumbo TVs.
</P>
<P>
   Though the service started late and ran slightly longer than
planned, things seemed to run like clockwork. ``We were told it
turned out very well, but that is not our purpose,'' said Burke.
</P>
<P>
   Said McDonald: ``It helps the family to know their husband that
died, or son or brother, that their life mattered, that the
community is taking the time to honor them in the right way.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
