<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-U.S.-SPY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIAN SPY BUG WAS PLANTED IN STATE DEPARTMENT'S EXECUTIVE WING 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By PHILIP SHENON    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Russian spies managed to place a sophisticated
eavesdropping device in a conference room on the executive floor of
the State Department by removing a piece of wall molding and
replacing it with a nearly identical piece with the electronic bug
embedded inside, government officials said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Even as they described the installation of a Russian
eavesdropping device in the headquarters of American diplomacy as a
serious breach of national security, investigators said they could
not help but marvel at the Russians' methods and audacity.
</P>
<P>
   With a skill that would do a high-priced interior decorator
proud, the Russians matched the style and paint color of the
molding so well that the bug, in a conference room just down the
hall from the offices used by Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright, was nearly undetectable.
</P>
<P>
   It was found only after a thorough search of the building by
investigators using a device that tracks down radio signals. The
exact location of the bug and how it was hidden were first reported
by ABC News and The Washington Times.
</P>
<P>
   The discovery of the sophisticated bug _ and the elaborate and
presumably time-consuming method of installing it _ have led
investigators to question low-level maintenance workers at the
State Department who may have helped the Russians, perhaps
unwittingly.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to imagine no one noticed when a hunk of the wall
was removed,'' said a department official, speaking on condition of
anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   The official said the bug had been found in a piece of wooden
rail molding about halfway down the wall of a conference room used
by the department's oceans and environment division on the seventh
floor. The wing of offices used by Albright and her senior staff is
also on the seventh floor, although it is several hundred feet away
from the conference room and behind heavily fortified doors.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators said that the conference room may have been
selected for surveillance because it was used on occasion by Russia
specialists who work in offices adjoining the oceans and
environment bureau.
</P>
<P>
   They said they believe that at least two trips were required for
the installation of the bug _ one to inspect and measure the
molding and another to install the new piece.
</P>
<P>
   Although they say it is unclear when the device was installed,
government officials said the bug was powered by a tiny battery,
and that the amount of power left in the battery would give them
clues to the date of the installation.
</P>
<P>
   They theorized that the Russians used the small, low-power
battery in an effort to defeat electronic surveillance equipment
that might have picked up signals from a higher-powered device. The
battery had so little power, however, that a spy was required to
linger just outside the department to listen to conversations going
on inside the building.
</P>
<P>
   In television interviews Friday, Albright insisted that the most
sensitive areas of the State Department were not compromised by the
listening device. ``My office and the most sensitive offices in the
State Department have not been penetrated,'' she said on Cable News
Network. Asked on ABC if anyone inside the State Department might
have helped the Russians, she replied, ``I have no idea.''
</P>
<P>
   She said that the most sensitive areas of the State Department
had been ``very carefully swept'' for bugs and that she had ordered
tighter security in the building long before the device was found.
</P>
<P>
   A Russian diplomat, Stanislav Borisovich Grusev, was arrested on
Wednesday after he was found loitering in a park across the street
from the State Department. Grusev has been identified by federal
authorities as a technical expert for the Russian foreign
intelligence service.
</P>
<P>
   In searching Grusev, officials said, investigators found a
remote switching device hidden in his clothing. The device turned
on a receiver and tape recorder in the car and a device designed to
detect electronic surveillance signals.
</P>
<P>
   Government authorities say that Grusev had been under
surveillance since last summer, when an FBI surveillance team
working on another case noticed him lingering outside the
department near his car.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Russian eavesdropping equipment installed inside
the State Department has been described as highly sophisticated,
Grusev appears to have been less so in his spycraft. He drove a car
with distinctive diplomatic license plates, and made little effort
to hide his presence outside the department.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators say they believe that he used the radio devices in
his car to activate the eavesdropping device, and would wait
nearby, hoping to overhear an important meeting in the
seventh-floor conference room.
</P>
<P>
   The chairman of the Senate Foreign Relations subcommittee that
oversees security at the State Department, Sen. Rod Grams, R-Minn.,
announced that he would investigate the incident.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
