<SLUG> BC-BRADLEY--SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRADLEY CANCELS FUND-RAISERS BECAUSE OF IRREGULAR HEARTBEAT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOEL CONNELLY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Former Sen. Bill Bradley yesterday cut short a West
Coast campaign swing because of an irregular heartbeat, forcing
cancelation of two Seattle fund-raisers and a rally scheduled for
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley was being treated Friday night in California with a
small electric shock to the heart, a common treatment for a
condition called atrial fibrillation, said Tony Wyche, a campaign
spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Wyche, quoting Bradley's cardiologist, described the condition
as an inconvenience rather than a serious problem.
</P>
<P>
   The news about the former New York Knicks forward, who
campaigned Friday in Sacramento, caught his local campaign
organizers by surprise. A total of 80 people were expected at a
$1,000-a-person breakfast in Seattle hosted by technology executive
Keith Grinstein. A second Bradley fund-raiser, a $500-a-plate
brunch hosted by Starbuck's CEO Howard Schultz, was also canceled.
It had been expected to draw as many as 200 supporters.
</P>
<P>
   ``He must be pretty damned sick. I've been with him when he was
ill and he simply plows ahead,'' said Tom Allison, a Seattle
attorney and leading local supporter of Bradley's bid for the
Democratic nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Jim McDermott, D-Wash., one of a half-dozen physicians in
Congress and a Bradley supporter, said the condition is not likely
to hinder Bradley's insurgent campaign for the White House.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not life threatening,'' McDermott said. ``People like
(former President) George Bush have had it. Hakeem Olajuwon plays
basketball every day with it. It is correctable.''
</P>
<P>
   Cancellation of Bradley's visit came just as Vice President Al
Gore's campaign was about to send out a news release designed to
blunt the fast-rising challenge by the former New Jersey senator
and .
</P>
<P>
   The Gore campaign statement announced that 31 Washington state
legislators are endorsing the vice president, including two
representatives who have switched after earlier backing Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley's condition had not been disclosed prior to Friday's
brief hospitalization. ``It's not a major thing. It developed in
1996, in his final year in the Senate, so he's had it for a couple
of years,'' Wyche said.
</P>
<P>
   Friday marked the fourth time Bradley has undergone the minor
electric shock treatment, technically known as cardioversion. The
treatment returns heartbeat to normal.
</P>
<P>
   In May 1998, Bradley was put on an anti-arrhythmic drug called
Procanbid because the irregularity returned several times, as is
common. The candidate's condition was detailed in a letter from
Bradley's doctor, Robert Heissenbuttel, of Columbia Presbyterian
Medical Center in New York, which was released Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Wyche said Bradley would spend the night in a hotel, and then
fly to Florida to resume campaigning.
</P>
<P>
   An estimated 2 million Americans suffer from atrial
fibrillation, a condition which occurs when the upper changers of
the heart (the atria) contract rapidly. They do not pump blood
adequately into the bottom chambers, the ventricles, which speed
up. It the irregular heart beat gets too rapid, people feel
discomfort in their chest.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley felt the condition Thursday night, Wyche said. When it
did not go away yesterday, he decided to seek treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Friday's brief hospitalization marks the first time in months
that Bradley has missed a beat. This week, two polls showed him
running ahead of Gore in New Hampshire, site of the nation's first
presidential primary. A third survey, released yesterday by the
Boston Globe, showed the two candidates in a dead heat.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
