<SLUG> BC-EXCLUSIVE-CHECHNYA-PHOTOS-NYT </SLUG>
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Friday, Dec. 10, 1999:
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-CHECHNYA:
</P>
<P>
   After months of bombing, Russia has opened an escape route for
the thousands of civilians trapped in Grozny.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times is offering 9 exclusive photos from Bruno
Stevens taken in and around Grozny. These photos are available for
sale only at the Wieck Photo Database. (http://www.nyt.wieck.com/)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT109) GROZNY, Chechnya -- Dec. 10, 1999 -- RUSSIA-CHECHNYA-9
-- After two months, Grozny's central market is still in ruins
after a scud missile hit it, killing killed 200. The skeleton
remains of the stalls are filled with personal belongings that
fleeing citizens left behind and never retrieved. (Bruno
Stevens/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT108) UNDATED -- Dec. 10, 1999 -- RUSSIA-CHECHNYA-8 -- This
family of refugees from the village of Satoy, south-west of Grozny,
attempt to reach the georgian border through a high mountain gorge.
Many who try to leave find that the greatest danger comes from
gangs of marauders who cruise around the area, brandishing
automatic weapons and stealing food. (Bruno Stevens/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT107) GROZNY, Chechnya -- Dec. 10, 1999 -- RUSSIA-CHECHNYA-7
-- With dwindling food supplies, tables and stalls at the market
are empty making it difficult for those still trying to lie in and
around the city. An estimated 20-30,000 civilians still live in
Grozny, mainly elderly people and women and children. (Bruno
Stevens/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT106) GROZNY, Chechnya -- Dec. 10, 1999 -- RUSSIA-CHECHNYA-6
-- An older man tries to keep warm with a small fire made from wood
debris. Temperatures are getting well below freezing, especially at
night. (Bruno Stevens/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT105) UNDATED -- Dec. 10, 1999 -- RUSSIA-CHECHNYA-5 -- Adam
was rushed by a neighbor to Shali hospital near Grozny after having
being hit by bomb shrapnel in the head while playing in the
courtyard of his home in the village of Avtoury. (Bruno Stevens/The
New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT104) UNDATED -- Dec. 10, 1999 -- RUSSIA-CHECHNYA-4 --
Sultan, 21, has been rushed to Shali hospital near Grozny after
having been hit by a mortar shell near Gudermes. He lost his left
foot and his left arm is shattered. His loss of blood and lack of
treatment has left him very nemic. (Bruno Stevens/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT103) UNDATED -- Dec. 10, 1999 -- RUSSIA-CHECHNYA-3 --
Mihail, 8, lost his right foot in the midnight bombing of his home
in Mesker-Yurt near Grozny. His 18 year old sister and his 12 year
old brother were killed instantly, his mother lost her left arm and
is in shock. (Bruno Stevens/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT102) UNDATED -- Dec. 10, 1999 -- RUSSIA-CHECHNYA-2 --
Chechen fighters hide a an anti-aircraft gun (Zenitka) coupled with
a 75mm anti-tank gun after retreating from Argun. (Bruno
Stevens/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT101) UNDATED -- Dec. 10, 1999 -- RUSSIA-CHECHNYA-1 --
Russian troops are using grenade launchers to hit the Chechen
defenses. This fighter has lost both hands, both eyes and half of
his face in trying to pick-up and get rid of such a grenade that
had just landed in his trench. (Bruno Stevens/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   The photos will move as part of today's New York Times Photo
Package, moving Friday. Non-clients can make individual purchases
by calling (888) 603-1036 or 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
