</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-CHECHNYA-ART-770(TRIMS)-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEW GROZNY RESIDENTS BRAVE ESCAPE CORRIDOR FROM THEIR BESIEGED
CITY 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: The New York Times is offering exclusive photos from Bruno
Stevens taken in and around Grozny. These photos are available FOR
SALE ONLY at the Wieck Photo Database. (http://www.nyt.wieck.com/)
(ART ADV: A map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By MICHAEL R. GORDON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PERVOMAISKAYA, Russia _ After enduring two months of thunderous
bombardments, a trickle of dispirited refugees straggled out of the
besieged Chechen capital Friday and made their way to the Russian
military checkpoint in the Tersky hills three miles away.
</P>
<P>
   The checkpoint marks the end of an escape route or humanitarian
corridor that the Russians hope will lead to the evacuation of the
thousands of civilians still trapped in Grozny. Russia says it has
stopped bombing the city and has pledged not to attack the escape
route.
</P>
<P>
   To Khasan Dakayev, a 25 year-old who brought his family out of
Grozny Friday, the route out seemed more like a risky gantlet than
a safe passage. He spent weeks worrying that his family might be
shot by Russian soldiers, only to discover that they were
endangered by gangs of marauders who cruise the area, brandishing
automatic weapons and stealing food with impunity.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are afraid of the them,'' Dakayev said. ``They don't
hold anything sacred.''
</P>
<P>
   With Russian troops surrounding Grozny, the predicament of the
city's civilians has become an urgent problem. Nobody knows for
sure how many civilians, who include ethnic Russians, still live in
the city. It was home to almost 400,000 people in the 1980s.
Russian estimates of the current civilian population range from
15,000 to 50,000.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian military has been beseeching them to evacuate so it
can unleash an even more furious barrage against the several
thousand rebels hiding in the city. It has issued warnings and even
an ultimatum _ since postponed _ telling Grozny's defenders and
residents to abandon the city by Saturday or risk death.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian air force stopped bombing Grozny four or five days
ago, when the checkpoint was first installed, in the campaign to
get civilians to leave, Russian officials and Grozny residents said
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   By mid-afternoon Friday, however, around 400 people had passed
through the checkpoint since it was opened earlier in the week,
presenting the Russians and the increasingly anxious international
community with a vexing problem.
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Vladimir Putin said Friday that he was in contact
with the government of the breakaway Chechen republic, led by Aslan
Maskhadov, and that he had met secretly a little more than a week
ago with one of its vice premiers. But there has been no indication
of a breakthrough, and the conditions in Grozny continued to
deteriorate.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Set astride the river Sunzha and between two mountain ridges,
Grozny has long been a strategically important center. A Cossack
general built it as a fort in 1818 when he led one of Russia's
campaigns against the Chechens.
</P>
<P>
   The city sprawls across both sides of the river and was regarded
as one of the Soviet Union's more pleasant cities. During the
1994-1996 Chechen war and the current fighting, however, it has
been a ghastly battleground.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Refugees interviewed at the checkpoint Friday said that a
sizable population still lives in the city, many of them elderly.
They have had to spend long hours hiding in chilly cellars to avoid
Russian bombing, which has been far more intense than in the
1994-1996 war, but they also live in fear of gangs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many of the young people have left, but a lot of older people
have stayed,'' said Baudi Eltamirov, 62, who passed through the
checkpoint Friday. ``There are marauders in the Staropromyslovsky
district in northern Grozny. They call themselves militants, but
they come and confiscate all the food and kick people out of their
houses. They claim they have permission from Maskhadov to take what
they need.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   There are other problems, too. On Friday, a tank full of
chlorine and ammonia exploded in Khankala, a region on the eastern
approach to the city, near the airport. Russian military officials
at the Mozdok air base, northwest of Chechnya, said the blast had
unleashed a poisonous cloud and blamed the explosion on the
militants. They in turn pointed their fingers at the Russians;
there was no way to verify either charge.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   As terrible as life is in Grozny, leaving it is not a simple
proposition. The evacuation corridor runs from rebel-held Grozny
through a neighboring settlement at Pervomaiskaya, which has also
been occupied by rebels, to a kind of no-man's land and then to the
Russian checkpoint in the Tersky hills. Refugees are anxious about
making the journey, and Dakayev asserted that some militants had
fired at a column of refugees Friday.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   (MORE
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Civilians pass through the Russian-controlled checkpoint in two
stages. At the first, the refugees are checked for weapons and
sniffed by dogs for narcotics. At the second, a few hundred yards
up the hill, information from their documents is logged into a
computer.
</P>
<P>
   Then, refugees who do not have relatives to give them shelter
proceed to the northern part of Chechnya, which is under the tight
control of Russian troops. The Russians are erecting two tent
cities in northwest Chechnya to accommodate up to 4,500 refugees
from Grozny and from refugee camps in a neighboring republic,
Ingushetiya.
</P>
<P>
   It might have been easier for refugees from Grozny to travel
west through the lowlands to Ingushetiya. But the Russians do not
want to increase the number of refugees in Ingushetiya; they want
to return them to Chechnya, both for humanitarian reasons and to
demonstrate that the political situation in Chechnya is being
stabilized.
</P>
<P>
   The corridor was inaugurated this week when an elderly man and
his wife walked up the hillside to see if the escape route was
safe. The Russians gave the man a car and told him to spread the
word that the corridor was open. But only four people initially
passed through, Russian officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were ready to receive people on Tuesday, but we really did
not have anything to do until the next day,'' said Col. Sergei
Malyovanny, the Russian commander at the checkpoint. ``A lot of
people in Grozny are really scared. They have been told that
Russian soldiers shoot refugees.''
</P>
<P>
   Gradually, more people began to arrive. On Thursday, the total
was 183, not including children. Friday some 200 had arrived by
early afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Even as refugees pass through the corridor, Russian troops are
preparing to seize Pervomaiskaya, through which the corridor runs.
Russian soldiers were ambushed and suffered heavy casualties in an
early battle there, they say.
</P>
<P>
   Taking the town would enable the Russians to tighten their grip
on Grozny and move the checkpoints down from the hills, which would
make it easier for civilians to leave.
</P>
<P>
   Civilians are not the only ones trickling out. Some militants
have been trying to leave, disguised as refugees, according to a
Russian lieutenant who would identify himself only by his first
name, Andrei. The lieutenant, at Primykaniye, a settlement 3 miles
east of Grozny, said that some militants have shaved their beards
but that the skin underneath is lighter than the rest of their
weather-beaten faces, giving them away.
</P>
<P>
   At the checkpoints, Dakayev said he had not seen any of the
thousands of leaflets dropped by the Russian air force, urging
people to leave immediately. He heard about the corridor on a
Russian-controlled radio station, ``Free Chechnya.''
</P>
<P>
   Dakayev, an ethnic Chechen, said the Russian air and artillery
strikes were terrifying. So were the militants who would
pistol-whip civilians and raid their apartments for food, not that
Dakayev had any to share. He, his wife Larisa and two small
children had been surviving on crumbs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The children did not see bread for three months,'' he said, as
he pulled a stale crust from his pocket.
</P>
<P>
   Having run the gantlet out of Grozny, Dakayev and his family
stood in the frigid winter wind as they waited to board a truck for
northern Chechnya, where they plan to live with his father. Still,
his brow was furrowed with anxiety.
</P>
<P>
   As the family climbed into the truck, Dakayev plaintively ask
his Russian escorts a question: ``Is it safe?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
