<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-10 21:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5622 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-BIZ-EUROPEANS-2TAKES-     12-10 0740
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-EUROPEANS-2TAKES-$ADV12-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HARK! THE SHAREHOLDERS ARE RESTLESS IN EUROPE  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, DEC. 12) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By HILARY ROSENBERG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was a victory for the underdog, and a harbinger of changing
times in Europe's boardrooms.
</P>
<P>
   In November, Telecom Italia found itself having to scrap a plan
to split off its wireless unit, for a reason that until recently
barely made it onto the business radar in much of Europe: Angry
minority shareholders were howling that the plan trampled their
rights.
</P>
<P>
   As recently as a few years ago, Telecom Italia and its
controlling shareholder, Olivetti, would have met little opposition
from shareholders and could have easily rammed the deal through.
But new laws, new pressures and the growing presence of
American-style institutional money management in Europe are
changing the climate in favor of shareholders, who are asserting
themselves as never before.
</P>
<P>
   Telecom Italia learned that after announcing its plan in
September. Large investors objected in person to managers who were
touring Europe; some European and American investors wrote letters
urging Telecom Italia's directors to reconsider.
</P>
<P>
   Peter C. Clapman, chief investment counsel at TIAA-CREF, the
teachers' pension fund, was among those who went even higher. ``We
communicated our views to the Italian government that an action
that disadvantages minority shareholders will cause doubt as to the
credibility of the Italian marketplace,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   When the news media aired the complaints, management was boxed
in. ``Telecom Italia had the majority to vote in favor, but it was
very difficult to damage the minority because of the debate in the
media,'' said Fabio F. Galli, who heads the Milan office of
Assogestioni, the fund managers' association. ``We see that as a
major victory in the new climate.''
</P>
<P>
   The juggernaut known as the global market is responsible, in
several ways, for expanding shareholders' power in Europe. So much
of America's foreign investment capital has poured into equities in
Western Europe _ nearly $1 trillion, twice the total for the rest
of the world, according to the Securities Industry Association _
that American-style reverence for shareholder value and shareholder
rights has inevitably influenced the attitudes and priorities of
investors and companies alike.
</P>
<P>
   The pressure to privatize state-owned businesses has compelled
governments to back away from interfering in corporate affairs and
to create legal environments attractive to foreign buyers. And the
introduction of the euro, the common European currency, makes
cross-border value comparisons easier.
</P>
<P>
   The changes are leading companies like Olivetti to conclude that
they ignore shareholders at their peril. Dario Trevisan, a lawyer
who represents minority shareholders on the Olivetti board, said,
``If institutional investors are not happy, you are not managing
your company well, because access to financial resources is not
easy at the end of the day.''
</P>
<P>
   In several countries, new laws are part of the trend. In 1998,
Italy made takeovers easier and use of defenses more difficult, and
encouraged companies to include an independent member elected by
minority shareholders on their audit boards.
</P>
<P>
   In Germany, new legislation has loosened restrictions on voting
rights, strengthened auditors' independence and required companies
to disclose the existence of any board committees. The French
government is considering compelling the release of more details on
executive pay and requiring shareholder approval each time the
roles of chairman and chief executive are combined.
</P>
<P>
   Shareholder rights groups have sprung up, meanwhile, as have
proxy research services. And European mutual funds and individual
investors, like non-European pension funds, are increasingly
speaking their minds at annual meetings.
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, however, European activism is just beginning. Most
European shareholders still habitually trust the management of
domestic companies and are reluctant to vote against them or their
proposals.
</P>
<P>
   They are even more passive with their foreign holdings, because
they find cross-border voting to be costly and time-consuming,
although many large American investors have found ways to do it
efficiently. Initiatives by shareholders are rare in France and
Germany, because only those with large stakes can propose them.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In France, the asset managers' association adopted a set of
model governance guidelines last year that, among other things,
opposes poison-pill takeover defenses and unequal voting rights for
different classes of stock. The group has begun alerting members
whenever a resolution proposed by a major corporation breaches the
guidelines; this year, that has happened at 21 of the 31 largest
companies in France, the group said.
</P>
<P>
   Shareholders are starting to respond to the activists' call to
arms. The French asset managers' group said 42 percent of its
members had voted against at least one management resolution this
year. American and French shareholders managed to defeat one of
them, a proposal for a poison pill at Rhone-Poulenc, according to
Stephen M. Davis, founder of Davis Gobal Advisors, a Newton, Mass.,
proxy research firm &UR; . &LR;
</P>
<P>
   In Germany, DWS, the retail fund management unit of Deutsche
Bank, has been a leading voice for change among institutional
investors. ``Companies are queuing in front of DWS's door to get a
hearing,'' said Christian Strenger, who was chief executive of DWS
until last summer and now acts as an independent adviser to
corporations.
</P>
<P>
   Pressure from shareholders, especially Deutsche Bank, may have
contributed to the resignation last week of the chairman of the
management board of Philipp Holzmann, the giant Frankfurt-based
construction company that was rescued in November from imminent
bankruptcy. An advocacy group representing individual shareholders
said that it will also press for the ouster of the chairman of the
company's supervisory board at a special shareholders' meeting in
February. Deutsche Bank was said by analysts to be pressing for a
sale or merger.
</P>
<P>
   One European country where shareholder rights have not gained
much traction is the Netherlands. At Dutch companies, supervisory
board members are chosen by the board, not elected by shareholders,
and ``corporations have every possible poison pill,'' said Eric G.
Coppieters, founder of Deminor, a Brussels proxy research firm.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, though, the eight largest Dutch pension funds agreed
to form an association and send a representative to each major
annual meeting. Last October, the eight funds pooled their votes to
block an effort by the management of CSM, a food company, to limit
any single shareholder's vote to 6 percent of outstanding shares.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, CSM agreed to allow voting without restrictions
except in the case of a hostile takeover bid. ``It was a sign to
companies that the pension funds are a sector to reckon with,''
said Rene H. Maatman, general counsel at ABP, the largest of the
funds.
</P>
<P>
   More changes are coming, including simplified electronic voting,
expected to be introduced over the next few years in Britain,
France and possibly Germany.
</P>
<P>
   But most observers expect European corporate governance to
retain significant differences from the American-British model. It
may be impossible for management to focus entirely on shareholder
value in countries like Germany and France, where other
``stakeholders'' like labor unions and local governments have
entrenched influence on boards.
</P>
<P>
   Referring to the outspoken California civil service pension
fund, Strenger said: ``Calpers says shareholder value is the only
thing and the rest will follow for the stakeholders. In Europe,
there are more parties at the table, and they behave better if you
involve them early.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
