u i BC-RUSSIA-POLITICS-1STLE     12-10 0906
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-POLITICS-1STLEDE-WRITETHRU-730&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PUTIN SOFTENS HIS BOSS'S CRITICISMS OF AMERICA 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS 4th graf to CORRECT details on Putin's peace talks.)  (js) 
 By MICHAEL WINES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Boris Yeltsin returned Friday from an official visit to
Beijing sounding more like a recidivist Soviet premier than a
president, having rattled Russia's nuclear saber at President
Clinton on Wednesday and denounced American culture, values and
military dominance before leaving Beijing Friday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   But more intriguing, perhaps, is what Prime Minister Vladimir
Putin was doing in Moscow while he was gone.
</P>
<P>
   As Yeltsin excoriated Clinton and the West for their complaints
about Russia's conduct of the war in Chechnya, Putin was busily
smoothing things over. He said that Yeltsin was not ``ushering in a
period of coolness'' toward Washington, that the United States and
Russia remained friends and that Clinton's criticism was no doubt
spurred by concern, not anger.
</P>
<P>
   While Yeltsin flew home Friday, Putin disclosed that he had been
in secret peace talks with representatives of the Chechen
government, which is led by Aslan Maskhadov. Russian generals
opened a public-relations front, accusing Chechen rebels of
employing chemical warfare.
</P>
<P>
   And the Kremlin's emergencies minister vowed to go to Chechnya
to ensure that civilians trapped in the conflict get safe passage
to Russian-built refugee camps.
</P>
<P>
   Putin's willingness to revise and extend his boss' remarks
underscores his independence in Yeltsin's Kremlin, where two of his
predecessors were dismissed this year alone.
</P>
<P>
   It also suggests that Yeltsin was aiming his words at Russians
as much as foreigners. With a crucial parliamentary election due in
a week, it would not do for Yeltsin to meekly accept Western
dressings-down over a hugely popular war.
</P>
<P>
   But it may also indicate that Western attacks on human-rights
violations in the war are finally starting to sting, and that
Russia's leaders want to mollify their critics, at least with
soothing words, until they can secure a victory.
</P>
<P>
   Europe in particular has seethed over Russia's conduct of the
war and demanded peace negotiations, which Putin now indicates have
occurred, albeit unsuccessfully. The government's newfound concern
over refugees also addresses a major complaint of western critics.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think Yeltsin's remarks in Beijing were scripted,''
said Thomas Graham, a former U.S. diplomat in Moscow who is now a
Russia expert at the Carnegie Endowment for International Peace in
Washington. ``He feels a lot of the pressure. And its sort of the
way Yeltsin's mind works _ he wants to lash out, to remind people
they're an important power.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I think Putin's reaction is a real one, too, that he may
have said things he shouldn't have said, and that we're trying to
walk it back.''
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin erupted in Beijing on Wednesday after Clinton said
Russia could pay a stiff price for the high rate of civilian
casualties in Chechnya. Yeltsin said Clinton seemed to have
forgotten ``what Russia is; that it possesses a complete arsenal of
nuclear weapons.'' And he added: ``It did not happen and will not
happen now that Bill Clinton would alone dictate to the world how
to live, how to work, how to rest. We will dictate how to live, not
him.''
</P>
<P>
   He followed that Friday with a joint Russian-Chinese communique
that fairly bristled with resentment toward U.S. policy. The
document criticized the ``negative momentum'' in international
relations and the ``uni-polar world'' and the ``single model of
culture, value concepts and ideology'' which it said the West was
forcing on the world.
</P>
<P>
   The communique said Russia and China would strengthen their ties
to counterbalance Western dominance, and the nations endorsed each
other's policies in two key trouble spots, Chechnya and Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin's condemnations of the United States resonated here.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeltsin was absolutely correct in his logic, and this logic is
determined by internal political developments,'' Andronik
Migranyan, a political scientist and presidential adviser, said in
an interview Friday. ``The stakes here are already high. Russia is
trying to get rid of these terrorist bandits, to restore law and
order, and it is completely supported by the overwhelming majority
of the people.''
</P>
<P>
   With a major election coming up, he said: ``You cannot respond
another way. Otherwise you are out; nobody needs you. He would have
been viewed as an idiot before his public, his army, his
government.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   It is impossible to tell whether Yeltsin and Putin choreographed
their remarks as a good-cop-bad-cop routine or whether Putin, whose
prosecution of the war has made him a runaway favorite to succeed
Yeltsin, is simply feeling his oats.
</P>
<P>
   And it may not matter. In the wake of the performance, Clinton
revised his own remarks, somewhat softening his attack. The
European Union, opening its own summit meeting in Helsinki, toned
down talk of economic sanctions and diplomatic reprisals over the
Chechen war.
</P>
<P>
   And Putin, in Uzbekistan, made clear that whatever benevolent
impression he had left, the war in Chechnya will continue as
before. ``The goals we set to uproot terrorism in Russia will be
reached,'' he said. ``We do not believe that the chosen tactics
should be changed.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-10-99 2101EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
