<DOCNO> NYT19991210.0309 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-10 21:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5625 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-RAC-PINCAY-2ND &LR;  &UR; TAKE-     12-10 0932
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-PINCAY-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 INGLEWOOD, Calif.: ... any leve.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Along the way, Pincay has accumulated a record-five Eclipse
Awards as the nation's top jockey. His mounts have earned more than
$206 million, trailing only McCarron and Day on the all-time list.
He has led the country in purses seven times. He has won four
Triple Crown races _ the 1984 Kentucky Derby aboard Swale and the
1982-84 Belmont Stakes on Conquistador Cielo, Caveat, and Swale,
respecively _ plus seven Breeders' Cup events. And he has piloted
such Horse of the Year champions as Affirmed in his post-Triple
Crown season of 1979 and Spend A Buck in 1985. He was inducted into
the Thoroughbred Racing Hall of Fame in 1975 at age 28.
</P>
<P>
   But equally impressive are the countless claimers and
nonentities Pincay has somehow coaxed to victory when they probably
should have been pulling hansom carriages in Central Park.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the Lou Gehrig of horse racing,'' said his agent of
nearly a cade, Bob Meldahl, employing an analogy the frustrated
baseball player would savor. ``He rides every day, whether it's
raining or cold, to give the fans every inch he can on a horse.''
</P>
<P>
   He has given much more than that, sacrificed much more than
that, experienced travails and tragedy almost as numerous as his
victories _ and that's not even counting the jockey's inevitable
physical toll: 12 broken collarbones, 10 broken ribs, two spinal
fractures, two punctured lungs, and two broken thumbs.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Those an even footnotes compared to the devastation he
experienced in 1985 when his first wife, Linda, shot herself in the
head at home Jan. 18 and died a day later. A misdiagnosis had led
to a ruptured appendix, and as her intestines became ravaged by the
poison, Linda, 37, steadily deteriorated while seeking solace in
pills, painkillers, and alcohol.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew she was in bad shape,'' said Pincay. ``She'd be up and
down _ fine one day, a wreck the next. She told me a couple of
times that she was a burden to the family, and I kept telling her
that wasn' so.''
</P>
<P>
   But she found no escape, and after she pulled the trigger,
Pincay lapsed into a massive depression punctuated by his own bout
with alcohol.
</P>
<P>
   ``For more than a week, I thought of giving up racing,'' he
said. ``I just couldn't think about riding. But one day I woke up
and said, `I've got to take care of my family' '' _ daughter Lisa,
who last month gave birth to Pincay's first grandchild, and son
Laffit III. `` `I've got to do this for my family and myself.' ''
</P>
<P>
   He was back in the saddle two weeks after Linda's death, and
later that year, he rode Spend A Buck to an epic victory in the
Jersey Derby that sewed up top honors for horse and jockey.
</P>
<P>
   Pincay refused to let tragedy conquer him, just as he had done
two decades before with those intimidating horses. He came out of
the emotional tailspin ``by focusing even more on the job, working
horses, doing different things.''
</P>
<P>
   He has been happily married to Jeanine since 1992. The couple
has a son, 6-year-old Jean-Laff, ``and since then,'' said Meldahl,
``I've never heard him complain about a thing. Not the quality of
mounts, not the number of mounts. Nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, he was waging legendary battles with the scales, for
Pincay is a natural welterweight trapped in a lightweight's
profession.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he wasn't riding, I'd say he'd weigh about 135,'' said
Meldahl, knowing that a jockey can't carry more than 117 pounds,
with gear. ``He's tricked his body.''
</P>
<P>
   But his body has fought back while Pincay has kept it crying for
more than the maximum 113 pounds he allows it.
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1970s, the man universally regarded as the most
gracious and likable in his sport found himself embroiled in
regular fistfights with fellow riders _ not because of temperament
but the combination of diet pills and induced vomiting he employed
to control his weight.
</P>
<P>
   ``The diet pills make you hot-tempered,'' he explained. ``I gave
it up in the mid-'70s.''
</P>
<P>
   Other diets proved less antagonizing but equally unsuccessful.
Pincay became a vegetarian for a while, ``but I didn't like the way
I felt mentally. I was always sleepy. My mind craved proteins.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, two years ago with his career apparently in eclipse, he
struck upon the solution: a diet of 850 calories a day high on
fruit and fiber, and regular workouts in the gym. The noted sports
orthopedic surgeon Robert Kerlan once called Pincay ``the
best-conditioned athlete I've ever seen,'' and there are no
dissenters even now.
</P>
<P>
   Meldahl recalls an encounter at a Del Mar gym, Frog's, where a
fellow client noted Pincay's physique and said, ``You must be on
steroids.'' Pincay responded, ``I've never, ev taken a drug like
that.''
</P>
<P>
   But his career was in need of a boost after he won only 75 times
in 1997. By then, the record that Pincay once had ignored _ ``great
athletes are too busy fousing on the task at hand to think of
long-range goals,'' said Meldahl _ was within reach, and the rider
was eager to get the chase over with. So he considered a move to
racing's Off-Off Broadway _ Northern California or Seattle. But he
decided to stay put, not wanting to cheapen the milestone, and he
has chipped steadily away at Shoemaker's target ever since.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew what people were going to say _ `If he stayed, maybe he
wouldn't have done it,' '' said Pincay. ``Plus, leaving my family,
just seeing them on weekends, would be too hectic.''
</P>
<P>
   And there was one other consideration.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to do it in the major leagues.''
</P>
<P>
   Friday the old ballplayer got his wish.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
