<SLUG> BC-BRADLEY-HEART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRADLEY HALTS CAMPAIGNING TO TREAT HEART IRREGULARITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JILL ZUCKMAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The presidential campaign of Bill Bradley was put on hold
Friday, when he canceled all appearances in California and
checkedhmsf into a hospital because of an irregular heartbeat.
</P>
<P>
   A Bradley aide said the former New Jersey senator ``felt a
little different'' Thursday night from the heart condition. Bradley
hoped the condition, which was first diagnosed in 1996, would
correct itself as it has in the past, and attended a campaign event
Friday morning in Scramento.
</P>
<P>
   But by the afternoon, Bradley checked himself into a hospital
near Palo Alto, Calif., and met with cardiologist Dr. Edward
Anderson. According to a campaign spokeswoman, Bradley expected to
receive a mild electric shock to the heart, a treatment he had
received in the past. But Anderson said that before Bradley arrived
at the hospital, ``he had converted to a normal heart rhythm and no
therapeutic action was needed.''
</P>
<P>
   Voters expecting to see Bradley in nearby Berkeley were instead
read a statement by the candidate. Bradley, 56, was remaining
overnight in California, but not in a hospital, aides said. He has
canceled his appearances in Washington state Saturday, but plans to
resume his schedule Sunday, with a trip to Orlando, Fla., to
address the state Democratic Party convention.
</P>
<P>
   Heart specialists said the condition should not hamper Bradley's
campaign, while the candidate's aides quoted his doctor as saying
the condition ``does not in any way interfere with his ability to
function.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, news of his condition, which had not been disclosed until
now, will bring new scrutiny on the candidate. Political analysts
said voters would be watching Bradley carefully in the coming days,
concerned with whether he can manage the strain of the campaign
trail, let alone the presidency
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a problem anytime a presidential candidate has a
health problem that requires hospitalization,'' said Darrell M.
West, a political science professor at Brown University. ``Voters
will be asking, `Can this guy handle the rigors of the job?' ''
</P>
<P>
   John J. Pitney, a political scientist at Claremont McKenna
College in California, said voters would be concerned only if the
heart problem is a serious one.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it's a minor problem, then it shouldn't have a serious
impact,'' sad Pitney. ``After all, we reelected Dwight Eisenhower
after his health problems in the '50s.''
</P>
<P>
   Eisenhower had suffered a major heart attack. So did Lyndon B.
Johnson, when he was Senate majority leader in the 1950s. Johnson
was elected vice president in 1960 and then president in 1964.
</P>
<P>
   But when former Massachusetts Senator Paul Tsongas ran for
president in 1988, he provided an overly rosy picture of his health
after a serious batle with cancer. Tsongas died after a relapse in
1997.
</P>
<P>
   The Tsongas experience has led many candidates in recent years
to release detailed medical records in order to prove that they are
healthy and physically capable of holding the highest office in the
land.
</P>
<P>
   Just last week, Arizona Senator John McCain released his medical
records in order to refute whispered suggestions that he may have
suffered mental impairment because of his 5 1/2 years in a North
Vietnamese prison camp. He also reported removing a cancerous mole
from his shoulder in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Atrial fibrillation, an irregular beat of the heart's upper
chambers, is a common condition, affecting at least 2 million
Americans. It can be caused by many ftors, such as overactive
thyroid (the cause of former President Geore Bush's atrial
fibrillation), high blood pressure, and some medicines. But most of
the time, specialists said, there is no known cause.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike potentially deadly ventricular fibrillation, which
affects the heart's main pumping chambers and was linked to the
death of basketball player Reggie Lewis, the condition that Bradley
has is usually not life-threatening. The main risk, specialists
said, is that a clot will form within the heart because atrial
blood flow stagnates. Even a tiny clot in the left atrium can cause
a stroke if it migrates to the brain.
</P>
<P>
   For that reason, patients with persistent atrial fibrillation
are routinely put on blood-thinning drugs. Sometimes a short
electrical shock is used if the atrium does not spontaneously
revert to normal rhythm.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Deeb Salem, chairman of medicine at New England Medical
Center, said Bradley's atrial fibrillation is likely to be ``a
minor inconvenience'' for him.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. James E. Muller, director of cardiology research at the
Massachusetts General Hospital, agreed: ``There are many people in
important positions who have atrial fibrillation,'' Muller said.
``If all he has is AF, it is not a significant factor in his
capability to perform the job of president.''
</P>
<P>
   Friday night, Bradley's cardiologist was similarly describing
his condition as ``more of an inconvenience than a problem.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bradley campaign also released results of the recent
physical exam, which showed no ther sign of disease and no
structural damage to the heart. The exam reported about a
half-dozen inciden of atrial fibrillation since 1996, three of
which were treated with a mild electric shock. Bradley was also
prescribed Procanbid to prevent or shorten the duration of the
episodes, without side effects.
</P>
<P>
   ice President Al Gore's campaign had good wishes for a speedy
recovery. ``Our hearts and thoughts and prayers are with Senator
Bradley,'' said Gore spokesman Chris Lehane.
</P>
<P>
   Next week, Bradley is to travel to Claremont, N.H., to meet
McCain and shake hands on the need to overhaul the campaign finance
system. On Friday, he is scheduled to meet Gore in a forum at
Daniel Webster College in Nashua.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Globe medical writer Richard A. Knox contributed to this report.
Wire service material was used in its preparation.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
