<SLUG> BC-CHINA-SPYING-RDP-700&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEE INDICTED IN CASE OF STOLEN NUCLEAR SECRETS 
</HEADLINE>
  With CHINA-SPYING-SECRETS, CHINA-SPYING-TRIAL,
CHINA-SPYING-DEFENSE) 
(rk) 
 By DAVID JOHNSTON and JAMES RISEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A federal grand jury in New Mexico indicted a
nuclear weapons engineer Friday on 59 counts of illegally removing
highly classified design, construction and testing data from the
Los Alamos weapons laboratory where he was employed.
</P>
<P>
   The indictment charged that the engineer, Wen Ho Lee, had
violated the Atomic Energy Act and Foreign Espionage Act,
assembling collections of 19 computer files containing some of the
country's most closely held nuclear weapons secrets.
</P>
<P>
   Lee was arrested Friday afternoon at his home outside of Los
Alamos by agents of the Federal Bureau of Investigation. He made an
initial appearance at the federal courthouse in Albuquerque and,
after prosecutors described him as a flight risk, a federal
magistrate ordered him held without bail pending a detention
hearing on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The indictment accused Lee of transferring classified
information into unclassified computer files at the Los Alamos
laboratory and downloaded other material onto portable tapes. The
indictment said that seven of the tapes that Lee had made,
containing critical nuclear secrets, could not be found.
</P>
<P>
   Although the indictment accused him of mishandling nuclear data,
the charges did not accuse Lee of spying or of any espionage
offenses related to a foreign government. But the most serious
offenses, removing classified nuclear weapons data, are punishable
by a maximum of a life sentence in prison.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, Lee's lawyer, Mark Holscher of Los Angeles, issued a
statement saying that the charges against Lee were ``groundless''
and that federal prosecutors were ``wholly unjustified in
suggesting that Dr. Lee is a flight risk.''
</P>
<P>
   Holscher said that Lee had been unfairly singled out because of
he is a Chinese-American and charged that ``prosecutive decisions
in this case have been influenced by other branches of
government.'' His complaint was an apparent reference to charges by
Lee's supporters that the scientist had been turned into a
scapegoat by law enforcement and energy officials who have been
criticized by Republicans in Congress for security lapses at the
country's nuclear weapons labs.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter Friday to the U.S. attorney in Albuquerque, John J.
Kelly, Holscher said that Lee would submit to a polygraph
examination about what the lawyer said were Lee's repeated
statements that he had not mishandled the computer tapes or turned
them over to any third party.
</P>
<P>
   It is unlikely that prosecutors will accept Lee's offer. In the
past Lee has voluntarily taken government polygraph examinations,
which are not admissable as evidence, and has given some answers
about his activities that appeared to be deceptive, law enforcement
officials said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The indictment did not allege that Lee gave the material to
another country or any unauthorized person or government, but it
did charge that he removed classified nuclear weapons data ``with
the intent to injure the Untied States and with the intent to
secure an advantage for a foreign power.''
</P>
<P>
   The indictment did not explain how the government would prove
Lee's intent and at a news conference in Albuquerque, Kelly
declined to discuss what evidence the government had obtained that
would demonstrate Lee's motives.
</P>
<P>
   For months, Lee's case has been the focal point of a furious
debate within the cloistered worlds of counterintelligence, law
enforcement and nuclear science and Friday's charges are unlikely
to quell that controversy, particularly within scientific circles.
Since Lee was fired from his job in March, some scientists have
said he was selectively punished because other researchers had
sometimes removed classified information without being severely
punished.
</P>
<P>
   But Lee was charged with 29 counts of removing and tampering
with restricted data, 10 counts of retaining restricted data, 10
counts of gathering national defense information and 10 counts of
unlawful retention of national defense information under the
Federal Espionage Act.
</P>
<P>
   With its lengthy list of serious felony charges the government
left little doubt that prosecutors concluded that Lee was
responsible for what some counterintelligence officials regarded as
the most serious breach in security at the weapons labs in the
country's history.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   But in the politically charged debate over U.S.-China relations,
the indictment seemed to further stir the controversy about Lee's
case and whether he could be blamed for what government officials
said was the loss of a vast store of secret data sufficient to
alter the world's strategic balance of power.
</P>
<P>
   But after a security investigation dating back to late 1994,
investigators have been unable to uncover concrete evidence that
Lee passed any nuclear secrets to China or any other government.
</P>
<P>
   The 59-year-old, Taiwan-born, naturalized American citizen who
had worked at the country's weapons labs for 20 years had been
under suspicion in an inquiry into Beijing's suspected theft of
technology known as W-88, the design for the United States' most
advanced miniaturized nuclear warhead. Lee was fired from his job
at the weapons lab in March.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators were unable to determine who was responsible for
the W-88 loss or even whether Chinese scientists might have
acquired the technology on their own. But counterintelligence
authorities continued to investigate Lee on circumstantial grounds
that he had access to some of the information and had traveled to
China on scientific exchange visits.
</P>
<P>
   By early 1997, FBI investigators, anxious to step up their
inquiry into Lee, sought the permission from attorney general Janet
Reno to begin covert electronic surveillance. But Reno's
intelligence aides refused on grounds that investigators had failed
to show that Lee was spying for a foreign power.
</P>
<P>
   In mid-1997, the Justice Department Office of Intelligence
Policy Review found the FBI's justification for electronic
monitoring too nebulous and dated to warrant such intrusive
methods.
</P>
<P>
   But earlier this year when Lee agreed to a voluntary search of
his office and home, agents uncovered evidence that he transferred
weapons data to nonsecure computers _ the first indication of the
massive removal of information at the center of Friday's
indictment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
