u i BC-CUBA-CUSTODY-BOS &LR;      12-10 0892
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUBA-CUSTODY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOY LIKELY TO BE RETURNED TO CUBA, ANALYSTS SAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID ABEL  
 c.1999 The Boston Gobe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The 6-year-old Cuban boy rescued from an innertube and caught in
a raging custody battle since his ill-fated voyage to Miami is
unlikely to remain in the United States, according to immigration
policy analysts and family-law attorneys.
</P>
<P>
   The conflict between Elian Gonazalez's father in Cuba and his
paternal great-aunt and great-uncle in Florida has unleashed an
emotional tug of war between Cubans and Cuban-Americans on the
opposing sides of the Florida Straits.
</P>
<P>
   While hundreds of thousands of people have protested in Cuba,
heeding Fidel Castro's call to support the boy's father, exiles in
Miami have bombarded the city's radio and TV talk shows to urge
immigration officials to let the boy stay with his Florida
relatives.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a child who lost his mother while bringing her child
to freedom,'' said Carmen Morales, one of five lawyers working for
free in support of Elian's relatives in Miami, who said they
believe the boy would be better off in the United States. ``We are
not against the father. We are against Elian growing up under a
totalitarian regime.''
</P>
<P>
   While lawyers for the US relatives petitioned Friday in federal
court to block Elian's return and to file for political asylum for
him with the Immigration and Naturalization Service, their efforts
are unlikely to overcome US law and international agreements that
normally require children to be returned to their closest living
relative, legal alts say.
</P>
<P>
   The US Uniform Child Custody Jurisdiction Act considers the
parental relationship inviolable, so long as the parent isn't
abusive or neglectful, said Bernard Perlmutter, director of the
University of Miami Youth Law Clinic.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as there is no provable claim that the father is not
fit, the child should be expeditiously returned,'' Perlmutter said.
``They should be united without delay. The father's rights under
decades of Florida law, constitutional law, and international law
are clear. His rights are paramount.''
</P>
<P>
   Normal procedure in custody cases of unaccompnied refugees is
that US officials return the children to the living parent or
guardian, said Dan Kane, an INS spokesman in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   US immigration officials in Cuba have already delivered a letter
to the communist-run government, he said, seeking to confirm
whether 32-year-old Juan Miguel Gonzalez is, indeed, Elian's
biological father. ``It's impossible to say what will be the final
outcome of Elian's case,'' Kane said. ``We have to talk to the
father.''
</P>
<P>
   International agreements such as The Hague Treaty, which Cuba
has not signed, support the argument that Elian should be returned
to his father, legal experts say.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of parental abduction, which Cuban officials claim
is what Elian's mother did while trying to escape the island, the
treaty says children should be returned to their native land.
</P>
<P>
   INS officials, however, have not confirmed this was a case of
kidnapping. And this is anything but a run-of-the-mill custody
dispute.
</P>
<P>
   What it is is one more battle in four decades of ideological
skirmishing between the United Staeand Cuba, where emotion and
politics often supersede reason and law.
</P>
<P>
   ``Inside the US government, I can tell you, they're not debating
the law on this, they're debating what this might do to Al Gore's
presidential campaign,'' said Richard Nuccio, a former Clinton
administration adviser on Cuba, who now teaches at Georgetown
University. ``They're worrying what would happen if Castro
unleashed another wave of rafters. They're worrying what would
happen if the immigration accords collapse.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the early 1960s when thousands of Cubans fled as Castro
swerved his revolution toward communism, Cuba has wrangled with the
United States over its policy that nearly automatically awards
Cubans residency if they survive the trip to Florida.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, after Castro gave Cubans a green light to leave and
some 35,000 Cubans set sail for Miami, the United States changed
its policy.
</P>
<P>
   The US Cuban Refugee Act, commonly known as the ``wet-foot,
dry-foot policy,'' declared that those Cubans picked up at sea
would be returned to Cuba, while those who touched US land could
apply for residency. Cuba, for its part, would try to restrain its
citizens from leaving.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the two countries meet every six months to discuss
immigration policy. The next meeting is scheduled for Monday in
Havana. But many Cuba analysts say they expect Castro to cancel the
meetings in protest of the US government's handling of Elian's
case.
</P>
<P>
   Even if Elian is comfortable in Florida, flying his new toy
airplanes through the air or smashing his new Tonka trucks into one
another on national news broadcasts may not matter.
</P>
<P>
   Independent attorneys familiar with the case say, whatever Eli's
wishes, the law will force the boy to return to Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the last analysis, it's not really that complicated,'' said
David Abraham, a law professor who specializes in immigration
issues at the University of Miami Law School. ``He should be
returned to his father. Cuba may be a miserable place, but there's
no way to say that misery equates to the political persecution of a
6 year old.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
