<P>
   Friday, Dec. 10, 1999:
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-CHECHNYA:
</P>
<P>
   After months of bombing, Russia has opened an escape route for
the thousands of civilians trapped in Grozny.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times is offering 9 exclusive photos from Bruno
Stevens taken in and around Grozny. These photos are available for
sale only at the Wieck Photo Database. (http://www.nyt.wieck.com/)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT109) GROZNY, Chechnya -- Dec. 10, 1999 -- RUSSIA-CHECHNYA-9
-- After two months, Grozny's central market is still in ruins
after a scud missile hit it, killing killed 200. The skeleton
remains of the stalls are filled with personal belongings that
fleeing citizens left behind and never retrieved. (Bruno
Stevens/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT108) UNDATED -- Dec. 10, 1999 -- RUSSIA-CHECHNYA-8 -- This
family of refugees from the village of Satoy, south-west of Grozny,
attempt to reach the georgian border through a high mountain gorge.
Many who try to leave find that the greatest danger comes from
gangs of marauders who cruise around the area, brandishing
automatic weapons and stealing food. (Bruno Stevens/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT107) GROZNY, Chechnya -- Dec. 10, 1999 -- RUSSIA-CHECHNYA-7
-- With dwindling food supplies, tables and stalls at the market
are empty making it difficult for those still trying to lie in and
around the city. An estimated 20-30,000 civilians still live in
Grozny, mainly elderly people and women and children. (Bruno
Stevens/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT106) GROZNY, Chechnya -- Dec. 10, 1999 -- RUSSIA-CHECHNYA-6
-- An older man tries to keep warm with a small fire made from wood
debris. Temperatures are getting well below freezing, especially at
night. (Bruno Stevens/The New York Times)
</P>
