<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-10 21:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5636 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-RAC-PINCAY-2TAKES-BOS     12-10 1336
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-PINCAY-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PINCAY'S LONG RIDE FINALLY BRINGS RECORD 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB DUFFY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ His pursuit of history was over but his
workday wasn't. Laffit Pincay Jr. now had the cherished record for
most career victories by a jockey, but he also had two more races
to ride, two more obligations to fulfill.
</P>
<P>
   And nothing _ not the delirious pomp and circumstance that had
just taken place along the Hollywood Park track after the sixth
race Friday afternoon, not the video tributes from a constellation
of fellow jockeys, not the champagne showers, not the spectacular
glass equine trophy and gleaming white Porsche he had received
while the trumpet flourishes of ``The Olympic Theme'' resoundingly
serenaded him in the background _ and most of all, not his 8,834th
career win, which knocked his idol, Bill Shoemaker, out of the
sport's annals _ was i to keep Pincay from his appointed rounds.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he'd considered begging off after bagging the record
with his 2-length win aboard Irish Nip in an otherwise forgettable
1-and-one-16th-mile, $35,000 turf race for maidens 3 years old and
up, Pincay said, ``Not really. I don't want to disappoint anybody.
These guys want me to ride their horses, and I can't let them down.
That's the way I've always been.''
</P>
<P>
   And that's why there was something to this epic moment beyond
mere statistical singularity. That's why Hall of Fame rider Chris
McCarron of Dorchester, Mass., came to the track on his day off,
drove the car that the Southern California tracks presented to
Pincay, and was positively beaming when he``This is the most
exciting thing I've ever been involved with in my life. Everybody
thinks that muc of Laffit Pincay. The guy is an icon. He's a
hero.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, he is as beloved as he is successful. Even
Shoemaker _ who surpassed Johnny Longden's record of 6,032
victories in 1970 and rode his last winner in 1990 _ was rooting
for his challenger. In a wheelchair since a 1991 auto accident
rendered him a quadriplegic, Shoemaker was on hand for the
festivities _ just as he had been the day before when Pincay tied
him aboard I Be Casual. He savored the achievement with Pincay
during the official press conference following the last race, after
Pincay had taken care of business by finishing eighth aboard Storm
Dog in the seventh and eighth on I Gotcha Covered in the eighth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't have any feeling about the record,'' said Shoemaker,
68. ``I had the feeling that Laffit was the guy to do it. He's been
a greafriend, a credit to racing. He's stayed with it through ups
and downs. I'm very proud he did it.''
</P>
<P>
   Pincay's day for the ages got off to an inauspicious start when
he finished last in the first race aboard Demidoll, third on Tart
in the second, and third atop Flying Journey, who pulled up lame
after crossing the finish line in the third.
</P>
<P>
   His major concern at that point was typical.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hate to have everybody come out here to see the show and
have to come back the next day,'' he told the media. ``I didn't
want you to have to keep coming back.''
</P>
<P>
   Not to worry. Wearing the yellow, green, and white silks of
Parfet, Parfet &AMP; Sheffield Farm Inc. and with a red saddlecloth
portentously bearing No. 1 on the 3-year-old bay colt trained by
Richard Mandella, Pincay and Irish Nip engaged in a duel around the
grass oval with Quiet One, Kent Desormeaux up.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the eighth pole, I thought I finally had him,'' said
Pincay.
</P>
<P>
   And when he broke the wire, Pincay said, ``I felt great, like I
just won the Kentucky Derby.''
</P>
<P>
   He's won that, along with just about every other major race, in
a 35-year career that he stubbornly prolonged even when it seemed
some trainers were ready for him to ride off into the sunset a
decade ago. He endured through assorted injuries, unyielding
scales, and the suicide of his first wife almost 15 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   His family _ second wife Jeanine and his three children _ were
there toshare the glory Friday. They watched as he was surrounded
by the Hollywood jockey colony _ whose idle riders had been rooting
for him in the jockeys' room during the sixth _ and accorded video
tributes by the luminous likes of Mcaon, Gary Stevens, Eddie
Delahoussaye, Pat Day, Sandy Hawley, Jerry Bailey, Jorge Velasquez,
Braulio Baeza, Angel Cordero, and the 92-year-old Longden. They
joined a crowd of 5,855 in admiring the bouquet of red roses he
received to go with the blanket of yellow and white flowers that
draped Irish Nip.
</P>
<P>
   And they listened as Pincay said he would celebrate with ``a
piece of steak and maybe a glass of wine'' _ a veritable feast for
this perpetual weight watcher.
</P>
<P>
   But they won't be having him home full-time in the near future.
Pincay, who has ridden 44,649 mounts and at 52 is the oldest jockey
at a major US track, indicated he'll keep going for another year or
two.
</P>
<P>
   By then, he may have set the bar at 9,000 winners.
</P>
<P>
   ``That has a nice ring to it,'' he said. He just as easily could
have been encapsulating his career.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Despite his roots in Panama City, Pincay's long ride to
immortality began almost by default. Laffit Pincay Sr., who
abandoned the family for Venezuela when the boy was 2, was a jockey
and trainer, but neither genetic inheritance nor even osmosis came
into play for his namesake. Laffit Jr.'s passion was baseball. He
aspired to be Mickey Mantle, not Bill Shoemaker.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was a kid playing Little League, that was all I thought
about,'' he recalled Friday in the jockeys' room before post time.
``That was all I wanted to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately for his career aspirations, Pincay topped out at 5
feet 1 inch, and he found no shortage of discouragement.
</P>
<P>
   ``People kept telling me, `Why not be a jockey like your father?
You're too small to be a baseball player,' '' he said. ``After I
kept hearing it, I thought,Why not? Maybe they are right.' ''
</P>
<P>
   One thing was for sure _ he knew his future didn't lay in
scholarly pursuits. ``I didn't have the the patience to sit still
and read,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   So _ why not? _ Pincay began going to the track at age 15. He
encountered one immediate problem, akin to a batter who dreads a
fastball in tight.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was afraid of te horses,'' he said. ``They were big, mean. I
was afraid they might bite.''
</P>
<P>
   But with the resolve that has become his signature, he took a
deep gulp and conquered the anxiety.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew I couldn't be scared if I wanted to be a jockey,'' he
said. ``Little by little, I got over it. I got more used to them.''
</P>
<P>
   So much so that he took a flier at the Panama Jockey School run
by Bolivar Moreno, who imparted one bit of indelible wisdom: ``You
never know when you're going to need your fitness to win a race.''
</P>
<P>
   Pincay has lived by that credo ever since. ``I was always doing
something,'' he said. ``Jogging, running, climbing stairs. All
kinds of things.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, by the time he left Moreno's tutelage, Pincay's ambitions
were hardly extravagant. He merely wanted a steady job to help him
and his mother, Rosario, now 76, escape the poverty of Panama
City's slums.
</P>
<P>
   Then something entirely unexpected and grand happened. Pincay
kept getting to the finish line ahead of the field _ first aboard
Huelen at Panama's Presidente Remon on May 19, 1964. Soon he was
his country's leading apprentice, and his horizons expanded
accordingly.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I started winning a lot in Panama,'' he said, ``I thought
I could come to this country.''
</P>
<P>
   He did in 1966, as a ctract rider for Fred Hooper at Chicago's
Arlington Park. Lo and behold, he found things no different on a
bigger stage. He guided his first US mount, Teacher's Art, to
victory, and the pattern continued.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I kept winning at Arlington, I went to New York,'' he
said. ``Just me and my agent. We didn't know anybody. We started
winning for Frank Martin.''
</P>
<P>
   And he hasn't stopped, on either coast, at any level.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
