<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-10 21:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5643 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-MARKET-1STLD-WRITETHR     12-10 0543
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARKET-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTERNET COMPANY'S STOCK JUMPS 483 PERCENT ON FIRST DAY OF
TRADING 
</HEADLINE>
   (CORRECTS figure to 0.2 percent in 8th graf)  
(rk) 
 By JONATHAN FUERBRINGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Another day, another Internet takeoff.
</P>
<P>
   The stock of FreeMarkets, an online auctioneer for industrial
products, jumped $232, or 483 percent, Friday on its first day of
trading to $280 a share the day after the price of VA Linux Systems
had an eightfold increase, setting the record for the first day of
trading of an initial public offering.
</P>
<P>
   Technology stocks also rallied enough Friday to push the Nasdaq
composite index to another new high, its fifth since Thanksgiving.
The index rose 26.07 points, or 0.73 percent, to 3,620.24. the
index was led higher by Oracle, Global Crossing and Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average, up 89.91 points, or 0.81
percent, to 11,224.70, and the Standard &AMP; Poor's index of 500
stocks, up 8.93 points, or 0.63 percent, to 1,417.04, both closed
just below their recent highs. General Electric led both indexes
higher. Xerox's warning that fourth-quarter profits could be 40
percent below current forecasts came after the close of the New
York Stock Exchange. In after hours trading the stock fell almost
20 percent, to 19~.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are coming into the end of the year, and money managers
want to show that they are fully invested,'' said Timothy M.
Ghriskey, senior portfolio manager at Dreyfus Corp., especially if
they have been holding back cash because of concerns about year
2000 computer problems. So, he said, they are still snapping up the
most popular stocks, including those of technology, media and
communications companies.
</P>
<P>
   He said that he expects trading to slow in the last two weeks of
the year, however, because some firms have told their money
managers to do just that in case year 2000 concerns roil financial
markets near the end of the year. But he expects once the New Year
is under way, the stock rally will continue. ``It's off to the
races,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   While the jump in shares of FreeMarkets was less than of some
other new offerings it in no way diminishes the hot performance of
the Internet offerings this year. According to CommScan LLP, the
average first day gain of 279 initial public offerings this year
has been about 90 percent.
</P>
<P>
   In the bond market, the report that the Producer Price Index for
finished goods rose just 0.2 percent in November helped push bond
prices higher and yields, which move in the opposite direction,
lower. The report showed that the core producer price index for
finished goods, which excludes food and energy prices, was
unchanged.
</P>
<P>
   The price of the 30-year Treasury bond rose 22/32, to 99 16/32.
The yield fell to 6.16 percent from 6.21 percent on Thursday. The
yield on the two-year note, which is more sensitive to the threat
of Federal Reserve interest rate increases, fell to 5.91 percent
from 5.94 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the continued good news on inflation, Federal Reserve
officials have made clear recently that they are likely to raise
interest rates again if the economy does not slow significantly
from an annual rate of growth that could top 4.5 percent in the
fourth quarter.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
