<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991210.0326 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-10 21:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5646 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-BRADLEY-HEART-2NDTAKE     12-10 0762
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRADLEY-HEART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: last week.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Doctors say atrial fibrillation is, in and of itself, usually
not a serious condition and can be kept in check with drugs. It can
be an indication, however, of underlying heart problems and can
lead to an increased risk of strokes. Consequently many people with
the condition take blood thinning drugs to protect against clots.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Dunn said Bradley's doctors have told him that he has no
cardiac problems. She also said he is not taking any anti-coagulant
drugs, an indication that Bradley's doctors think he is at a
minimal risk for a stroke.
</P>
<P>
   President George Bush also suffered from atrial fibrillation,
which came to light in 1991 when he was rushed to a hospital after
feeling heart palpitations while jogging at Camp David, Md. Bush's
condition had been brought on by Graves' disease, which causes the
thyroid gland to produce too much hormone.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, Bradley, a star basketball player with the New
York Knicks between 1967 and 1977, has worked out at least three
times a week, usually on a treadmill or stationary bike, Ms. Dunn
said.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter summarizing a physical Bradley underwent on Dec. 3,
Dr. Robert H. Heissenbuttel of the Columbia-Presbyterian Medical
Center said that other than his irregular heartbeat, Bradley had
``no other health issues.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You have been evaluated and found to have nonstructural heart
disease,'' Heissenbuttel wrote in the letter, which Bradley's
campaign released Friday night. ``When you have atrial
fibrillation, you note an irregular heart beat, but have no other
symptoms. Thus, this rhythm does not, in any way, interfere with
your ability to function.''
</P>
<P>
   Heissenbuttel also wrote that Bradley's heart irregularities had
no known cause.
</P>
<P>
   The letter said that Bradley's blood pressure was regular and
that he had passed a stress test. The letter also disclosed that a
``small benign polyp'' had been removed from Bradley's colon in
April. It said there was no evidence of colon cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Dunn said Bradley first began to notice the most recent
palpitations on Thursday night after a day of campaigning in Los
Angeles. But one of his cardiologists, Dr. Edward Anderson of Palo
Alto, told him to wait 24 hours to see if the arrhythmia would
correct itself before seeking treatment. So he decided to continue
on to Sacramento and conduct his full day of campaigning Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Friday morning, he went to a fund-raiser in Sacramento, followed
by a press conference, an editorial board meeting at The Sacramento
Bee, then drove to Berkeley for another fund-raiser. But by early
Friday afternoon, the palpitations were continuing.
</P>
<P>
   So at around 3 p.m., Bradley went to Sequoia Hospital in Redwood
City where he was met by Anderson. But before any treatment could
be performed, the palpitations stopped, Ms. Dunn said. He remained
in the hospital for at least an hour longer under the observation
of Anderson.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley also canceled two fund-raisers in the bay area. And he
will miss a campaign trip to Seattle on Saturday, where he was to
hold a rally with Mayor Paul Schell, a supporter.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Dunn refused to disclose where Bradley was staying
overnight, saying she wanted to protect his privacy.
</P>
<P>
   The treatment for an attack of irregular heartbeat is a mild
electrical shock known as a cardioversion. Between 1996 and 1998,
Bradley had four episodes of atrial fibrillation and received
cardioversions twice.
</P>
<P>
   In May 1998, he began taking the drug Procanbid to keep his
heart beat regular, Ms. Dunn said. Since then he has had three
bouts of fibrillation, including Friday's, none requiring shock
treatment.
</P>
<P>
   In his letter, Heissenbuttel said, ``the medication has been
effective in preventing or shortening the duration of episodes and
has been well tolerated with no side effects.''
</P>
<P>
   Procanbid can cause nausea, vomiting and allergic reactions,
including rash.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Dunn said Bradley's wife, Ernestine, was in Iowa Friday
night campaigning and had no plans to go to California to be with
her husband. She said that Mrs. Bradley would continue with a full
day of campaigning in Iowa on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, Bradley is scheduled to address the annual convention
of the Florida Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Dunn sought to convey a mood of relaxed assurance during a
phone interview from Bradley headquarters in West Orange, N.J.,
cracking a few jokes about the flood of phone calls the office had
received. She said she had been long aware of Bradley's condition,
calling it ``no big deal.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
