r s BC-BOX-AYALA-LADN     12-10 0804
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-AYALA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER TROUBLED PAST, AYALA TRIES FOR COMEBACK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MICHAEL ROSENTHAL  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Tony Ayala feels 36.
</P>
<P>
   It's the aches and pains he must endure after a fight or
workout, his body's way of telling him he's not the same man who
could once stay out all night drinking and then spar 10 rounds the
next day with no problem.
</P>
<P>
   He's not the 19-year-old who went away to a New Jersey prison in
1983.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, he feels good, much better than most boxers
his age because he has experienced no wear and tear in the ring
over the past 16 years and doesn't abuse drugs or alcohol as he
once did.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, Ayala is both realistic and optimistic as he heads into
the third fight of his improbable comeback: He faces journeyman
Tony Menefee tonight in his hometown of San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   The bout will be on pay-per-view television.
</P>
<P>
   ``The truth is that those who expect me to be like I was when I
was 19 will be disappointed,'' said Ayala, who was the No. 1 junior
middleweight contender when he was convicted of rape and went to
prison. ``I'll probably never be like that again. I'm a different
fighter now, smarter, more conscious of defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``My goals, my motivation are the same, though. That hasn't
changed.''
</P>
<P>
   Ayala, 20 pounds over his fighting weight at the time, left
prison on April 20 of this year and began training two days later.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't easy at first. After 16 years without physical
contact, getting hit by sparring partners was like getting hit by
an angry ram with a full head of steam. As Ayala put it, ``It was
discouraging to say the least.''
</P>
<P>
   However, he's determined. It's how he's always been. He also
knows this is his best chance to make big money, to set his family
up for life, and he wants to give himself every chance to succeed.
</P>
<P>
   So he works hard on his skills and conditioning.
</P>
<P>
   The punching power and innate aggression were there the moment
Ayala stepped back into the ring. That's not the case with his
reflexes, quickness, footwork and timing, which come more slowly _
if ever _ after a layoff.
</P>
<P>
   His conditioning, a liability when he began training eight
months ago, is now a strength. He surprises himself sometimes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went running with him yesterday,'' said psychologist Brian
Raditz, who treated Ayala in prison and now serves as his manager.
``We finished running for an hour and he looked at me and said, `I
can't believe how good I feel. I'm not even breathing hard. I don't
understand it.'
</P>
<P>
   ``He's just working very hard.''
</P>
<P>
   In his two victories, consensus is that he looked ``pretty
good.''
</P>
<P>
   He stopped Manuel Esparza in the third round on Aug. 20 in his
first fight back and then knocked out Robert Koon in four rounds on
Sept. 24. However, Esparza and Koon are club-level fighters, making
it difficult to gauge exactly what the two wins mean.
</P>
<P>
   Ayala admits he's not ready for the Oscar De La Hoyas or Felix
Trinidads, although he doesn't believe he's too far away.
</P>
<P>
   Raditiz said he expects Ayala to get a world-title fight within
a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't expect to be back in form for a couple more fights,''
he said. ``. .. But I'm at a point where I'll give anybody a damn
good fight. Name anyone out there and the fans will say afterward
that they weren't cheated out of their money.
</P>
<P>
   ``If things go good, maybe I'll fight a guy like (former
champion Yory Boy) Campas in my next few fights.''
</P>
<P>
   Raditz is almost certain Ayala will make history.
</P>
<P>
   It's the fighter's determination, his passion, and the fact he's
not a typical fighter even if his stretch in prison is not
considered.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to understand something: Tony's always done unique
things,'' Raditz said. ``When he was in the fifth, sixth grade, he
built his own car and drove it to school. When he was 11, he fought
the Mexican Golden Gloves champ, who was 22, and Tony knocked him
out.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he was 14, he sparred with hard-punching former champion
Pipino Cuevas and gave him all he could handle. He's always done
things like that and it's no different now.''
</P>
<P>
   And if he fails? No biggie.
</P>
<P>
   Boxing is not his obsession. Life as a free man is.
</P>
<P>
   He's made peace with himself in regard to the rape of a neighbor
in Patterson, N.J., while high on heroin and alcohol. He has
expressed remorse for his act and says he's now a ``normal''
person.
</P>
<P>
   His primary objective is keep it that way. Whatever he's able to
accomplish in boxing is a bonus.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never expected to be in the position I'm in now,'' Ayala
said. ``For 14 years, I never expected to fight again. So when you
expect nothing and get a lot, it's a blessing. That's how I feel
now.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not the same fighter I was and I'm not the same person I
was.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
