</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EU-TURKEY-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TURKEY IS INVITED TO APPLY FOR SEAT IN EUROPEAN UNION
</HEADLINE>
  (ADDS 10 grafs at end with details of conference) 
 (With EU-TURKEY-REACT) 
(rk) 
 By WARREN HOGE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HELSINKI, Finland _ The European Union Friday accepted Turkey as
a candidate for membership, reversing a thumbs-down vote two years
ago, which was based mainly on Turkey's human rights record.
</P>
<P>
   Membership, which is probably many years down the road, would
mark the entry of the first Muslim country to the European Union.
Turkey, which has long sought closer ties to Europe, is already a
member of NATO.
</P>
<P>
   The economic and political union also agreed to a plan to bring
in more of the formerly communist nations of Eastern and Central
Europe, in the latest step to expand to the borders of Russia.
</P>
<P>
   Alarm over Russian moves in Chechnya colored the summit
conference of the 15-nation bloc in Helsinki. The national leaders
put out a statement condemning the bombardment of cities in the
territory as ``totally unacceptable'' and threatening to cut
assistance to Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   The statement said the European Union would review its common
strategy on Russia, apply trade terms more strictly, suspend some
provisions of a partnership agreement and shift funds from a
technical program to ``humanitarian needs'' created by the crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Turkey readily welcomed the European offer. ``There might be
details we find hard to accept,'' Prime Minister Bulent Ecevit said
in Ankara, ``but in general the acceptance of our candidate status
on equal conditions is a great success for Turkey.''
</P>
<P>
   Though Turkey has pursued European validation for years, it
balked at some of the terms for its admittance Friday, and Javier
Solana, the union's new foreign policy chief, was sent to Ankara to
clarify them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going there just to explain what has been agreed by the
E.U. summit,'' he said on leaving Helsinki.
</P>
<P>
   To join, Turkey will have to make sweeping political and
economic reforms and abolish its death penalty. Its neighbor Greece
lately indicated its willingness to reconsider allowing Turkey to
join it in the European Union.
</P>
<P>
   Paavo Lipponen, the prime minister of Finland, current holder of
the organization's rotating presidency, expressed hopes for a
positive response and said Ecevit had been invited to the
concluding lunch of the summit conference here on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Bulgaria, Latvia, Lithuania, Romania, Slovakia and Malta were
the countries gaining preliminary consideration for membership
Friday. They fall into line behind six others already negotiating
entry _ Cyprus, the Czech Republic, Estonia, Hungary, Poland and
Slovenia.
</P>
<P>
   It will be at least three years before the first of them become
full members, and it may be decades before all of them do. Under
the new plan, the E.U. will expand to 28 member states by 2025,
representing a population of 500 million people.
</P>
<P>
   While the requirement to improve its human rights record and
enact social and political reforms is likely to make Turkey one of
the later entrants, Friday's decision is considered significant for
symbolizing a break with a long history of stereotyping of Turks as
un-European.
</P>
<P>
   The United States criticized the Europeans for spurning Turkey,
a strategically located Muslim NATO ally, at the European Union's
summit meeting in Luxembourg in 1997. President Clinton called on
the leaders to undo the offense when he visited Greece and Turkey
last month.
</P>
<P>
   It appeared that conditions sought by Greece might have given
Ankara pause in accepting the invitation. Of particular concern to
the Greeks was a provision under consideration saying the two
countries should steer their Aegean border disputes to the
International Court of Justice.
</P>
<P>
   The overall mood of the conference, once envisioned as a
conclusive, forward-looking pre-millennial gathering, was soured by
disputes over France's defiance of the European Commission's
lifting of the ban on British beef and Britain's objections to a 20
percent withholding tax on offshore investments favored by the
other members.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has been some tough talk,'' Lipponen said in a grim news
conference Friday evening. ``Our discussions were not at all
diplomatic in their language.''
</P>
<P>
   Barely mentioned in Friday's account of the meeting's
accomplishments was the approval of the new European rapid reaction
force that was once considered a centerpiece of the gathering. A
European Security and Defense Initiative calling for such a force
was adopted after a brief debate and some minor changes to the
program put together by the alliance's principal military powers,
Britain and France.
</P>
<P>
   Washington, which at the beginning of the decade expressed
interest in Europe's taking on military responsibility for regional
conflicts, more recently expressed anxiety at a European force's
potential to overlap with and detract from NATO.
</P>
<P>
   Trying to address that concern, but leaving the matter vague,
the summit declaration said, ``The objective is for the union to
have the autonomous capacity to take decisions and, where NATO as a
whole is not engaged, to launch and then to conduct E.U.-led
military operations in response to international crises.''
</P>
<P>
   The 60,000-strong crisis response force is supposed to be ready
by 2003. The plan also calls for a separate military staff and a
permanent political and security committee.
</P>
<P>
   There has been a growing consensus _ especially since the war in
Kosovo _ that Europe needs to restructure its military and build up
its muscle. But many of the same nations have been cutting their
own military outlays.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
