<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-10 21:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5658 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-INVEST-EMERGING-MARKE     12-10 0767
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVEST-EMERGING-MARKETS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-$ADV12-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FINDING THE SOURCE OF A FIZZLED GOLD RALLY 
</HEADLINE>
   (Subs for some updated figures and refinement)  
 (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, DEC. 12)  
 (af)  
 By JONATHAN FUERBRINGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The gold market has just gone through a derivative burnout, not
a new awakening that signals the end of long a bear market.
</P>
<P>
   As the price surged from $253.70 to $326 an ounce in an
August-to-October rally, burnout seems to have been a key element.
In time, though, the rally may give desperate gold bulls some small
hope.
</P>
<P>
   They could not have been happier on Sunday, Sept. 26, when 15
European central banks said they would limit their annual gold
sales to 400 metric tons (almost 13 million ounces) for five years
and promised to restrict their gold lending to current levels.
</P>
<P>
   That statement was the spark needed for a rally, even though the
permitted gold sales would be well above the annual average of 297
tons during the 1990s. It removed the threat of a huge increase in
central bank sales, a worry that had been depressing gold prices
for years. And the restriction on central bank gold lending would
make bets against gold by speculators and hedging by producers less
attractive.
</P>
<P>
   Haruko Fukuda, executive director of the World Gold Council,
felt that the gold market environment had changed so much that she
declared in a speech Oct. 18 that ``a new era dawned for gold''
that Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   But with the price of gold back down to $281 an ounce, the bulls
are wondering.
</P>
<P>
   George Milling-Stanley, manager of gold market analysis at the
gold council, acknowledges that something big has to happen to get
the price up.
</P>
<P>
   The derivative turmoil was not on the scale _ nor did it get the
headlines _ that came with the near-collapse of Long Term Capital
Management, the hedge fund that was rescued in the fall of 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Ashanti Goldfields Co. of Ghana and Cambior Inc. of
Canada are both reeling because of their gold hedging programs,
which depend on derivatives. And like Long Term Capital, the two
companies underestimated the risk of a sharp market move against
them, in this case a surge in the price of gold.
</P>
<P>
   In a market where the price of gold had fallen for the last four
years, bets against gold were understandable. And hedging _ which
allows gold producers to sell their production in the future at
prices above current levels _ enabled many companies to be
profitable while the price was declining.
</P>
<P>
   But this appears to be a case of two companies going too far in
their derivative plays: both are now struggling to survive because
their hedges turned against them.
</P>
<P>
   Ashanti, which had 10 million ounces of gold, or 38 percent of
its reserves, hedged on Sept. 30, had to give its bullion dealers
the option to buy 15 percent of the company to avoid being forced
to meet a margin call against potential hedge losses that analysts
said were around $270 million.
</P>
<P>
   Ashanti said the margin call threatened its solvency. Cambior
quickly bought one million ounces of gold and closed out positions
totaling 300,000 ounces, resulting in a net after-tax charge to
earnings of $28.2 million in the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Cambior is now trying to sell off some of its gold and base
metal assets. Both companies have agreements with their bullion
dealers that give them time to work out their problems.
</P>
<P>
   The fear of the unwinding of these hedge positions _ which could
have required the purchase of millions of ounces of gold _ was a
driving force behind the panic gold buying in late September and
early October. Investors who had bet on a gold price decline
scurried to buy the metal back, while producers bought to limit
their hedging losses.
</P>
<P>
   ``That put a great deal of fuel into the rally,'' said Philip
Klapwijk, managing director of Gold Fields Mineral Services, a
London-based precious metals research firm.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the derivative burnout might still redound to the benefit of
the gold price if it changes the attitude of speculators and gold
producers, who have assumed that the price will stay where it is or
fall further.
</P>
<P>
   ``Investors have seen that this market can move both ways, up
and down,'' said Bruce D. Hansen, chief financial officer of the
Newmont Mining Corp. If that lesson takes hold, speculators won't
be as eager to bet on further declines and producers will hedge
less. And that would provide gold some headroom.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
