<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991210.0340 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-10 22:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5664 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-FBC-HEISMAN-COLUMN-NY     12-10 0955
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-HEISMAN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORTHY FIELD HITS WIRE IN HEISMAN RACE 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By JOE DRAPE    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Last spring, two very good college football players
decided to skip the National Football League draft, return for
their senior year to graduate and put themselves in position to
pick up some postseason hardware. One of them, Wisconsin running
back Ron Dayne, will probably be awarded the Heisman Trophy
Saturday night at the Downtown Athletic Club.
</P>
<P>
   The other, Florida State wide receiver Peter Warrick, is nowhere
near New York Saturday and that, unfortunately, continues to
generate too much discussion. He didn't get enough votes on the 921
ballots to make the trip here _ quarterbacks Joe Hamilton of
Georgia Tech, Michael Vick of Virginia Tech, Drew Brees of Purdue
and Chad Pennington of Marshall were the other players who did.
</P>
<P>
   Warrick went from Heisman front-runner to outsider when he was
suspended from two midseason games because of his involvement in a
shopping mall scam. Whether that is fair or not, whether an
off-field incident blinded voters to his game-day brilliance,
shouldn't matter. The five finalists had splendid seasons and
should be the focus of this once-in-a-lifetime day _ especially
Dayne.
</P>
<P>
   The 254-pound Dayne also battled perception problems over the
course of a record-breaking season. He broke the former Texas
running back Ricky Williams' year-old Division I-A career rushing
record, with 6,397 yards. This season, he rolled to 1,834 yards,
averaged 6.1 yards a carry and scored 19 touchdowns to help
Wisconsin (9-2) return to the Rose Bowl for the second consecutive
year.
</P>
<P>
   But throughout the season, reporters, and schools with competing
Heisman candidates, floated theories on why Dayne wasn't the best
player. It prompted the Wisconsin athletic department to post a
treatise about Dayne, on the university's Web site, titled:
``What's Myth and What's Fact.''
</P>
<P>
   The treatise is pretty convincing. Here's a sample:
</P>
<P>
   Myth: Ron Dayne hasn't gained yardage versus quality opposition.
</P>
<P>
   Facts: Dayne and the Badgers have faced nationally ranked foes
15 times since 1996. His average rushing yards per game in those
contests is 114.9 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Myth: Ron Dayne turns the ball over.
</P>
<P>
   Facts: In 1,159 carries, Dayne has suffered just nine fumbles
lost. That is one miscue for every 128.8 carries. Dayne has fumbled
on just 0.77 percent of his career carries. Williams, by
comparison, lost 12 fumbles during his Heisman Trophy-winning
season.
</P>
<P>
   And on it goes. The problem, really, has been that neither
Dayne's bruising running nor his succinct speaking style has awed
or inspired.
</P>
<P>
   But these facts should: He stayed in school to be a father to
his 2-year-old daughter, Jada; a mate to his longtime girlfriend,
Alia Lester; and a big brother to his sister, Onya, a freshman
track athlete at Wisconsin. He will finish the 12 hours needed for
his degree this spring and finds being a role model sobering. ``I
take everything seriously,'' he said. ``You have somebody looking
up to you at all times, watching what you're doing, even trying to
copy what you're doing.''
</P>
<P>
   His fellow finalists also deserve their places on the Heisman
dais.
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton, the likely runner-up, returned Georgia Tech (8-3) to
national prominence and won the Davey O'Brien award as the nation's
outstanding quarterback. Hamilton passed, completing 203 of 305
passes for 3,060 yards and 29 touchdowns. He ran, rushing for 730
yards and 6 touchdowns. He also kept a cool head as the leader of a
young, mistake-prone team.
</P>
<P>
   Another senior, Marshall's Pennington, is an academic
all-American who won the National Football Foundation's Vincent
dePaul Draddy award as the nation's top scholar-athlete. He led the
nation this season with 37 touchdown passes, and completed 275 of
405 passes for 3,799 yards with only 11 interceptions. His team,
the Thundering Herd, is 12-0 and will play Brigham Young in the
Motor City Bowl. Just being here is enough for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just happy to get to go,'' he said. ``I was hoping to be
invited so I could talk about how successful a program we have at
Marshall.''
</P>
<P>
   Rounding out the finalists are two underclassmen who will be
early co-favorites to win the award next year: Vick and Brees.
</P>
<P>
   A red-shirt freshman at Virginia Tech, Vick seemingly came from
nowhere to lead the No. 2-ranked Hokies (11-0) to a national-title
game against Florida State in the Sugar Bowl. A quick-footed
left-hander, he completed 90 of 153 passes for 1,840 yards with 12
touchdowns while rushing for 580 yards on 110 carries. He also
became the first freshman to lead Division I-A in passing
efficiency, with a 180.4 rating.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one had him on the list when the season started,'' said his
coach, Frank Beamer.
</P>
<P>
   Vick will most likely shoot it out next year with Brees, who
announced early this season that he would return to Purdue for his
senior year. The Boilermaker triggered one of the nation's most
potent offenses, completing 301 of 494 passes for 3,531 yards and
21 touchdowns. Brees knows who should receive this year's Heisman _
Dayne.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's kind of been their team for the last four years,'' said
the quarterback who will take Purdue (7-4) to the Outback Bowl
against Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   So forget about Florida State's Warrick _ the college game is
well represented here. Warrick made a mistake; it doesn't make him
a bad guy.
</P>
<P>
   It may or may not have cost him a trip to New York. But he, too,
is on schedule to graduate this spring. He, too, has a big day
ahead of him, just not Saturday. He can pick up some hardware on
Jan. 4, when the Seminoles play for the national title. And that is
fair enough. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
