<HEADER>
A5668 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-BRADLEY-HEART-MEDICAL     12-10 0616
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRADLEY-HEART-MEDICAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A COMMON HEART CONDITION, OF AN UNKNOWN CAUSE, BUT TREATABLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (With BRADLEY-HEART)  
(mcd) 
 By DENISE GRADY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bill Bradley is one of 2.2 million Americans who suffer from
atrial fibrillation, a very rapid, erratic beating in the atria,
the upper chambers of the heart. President George Bush also
suffered from the condition in 1991; in his case it was brought on
by a thyroid disorder.
</P>
<P>
   People who have atrial fibrillation often feel it as a heartbeat
that races one moment and feels sluggish the next. If the
fibrillation is severe enough to interfere with the heart's pumping
ability, other symptoms like dizziness, faintness, shortness of
breath and fatigue can result.
</P>
<P>
   The condition itself is not an emergency, and it does not signal
an impending heart attack. Its cause is often unclear. Dr. Robert
H. Heissenbuttel, who examined the Democratic presidential
candidate on Dec. 3, said in a letter dated Dec. 9 and made public
Friday by the Bradley campaign, ``In 1996, you were found to have
atrial fibrillation with no precipitating cause, nor any cardiac
disease identified.''
</P>
<P>
   Doctors may treat the fibrillation with drugs or an electrical
shock, called cardioversion, to restore normal rhythm. In Bradley's
case, according to Heissenbuttel, he received cardioversion in
1996, when the condition was first diagnosed; he had four episodes
of fibrillation over the next two years, and in 1998 received two
cardioversions.
</P>
<P>
   In May 1998, the doctor said in his letter, Bradley began
receiving the drug Procanbid; since that time the candidate had
``had two brief episodes of atrial fibrillation,'' which converted
to normal rhythm by themselves.
</P>
<P>
   The drug, Heissenbuttel continued, ``has been effective in
preventing or shortening the duration of episodes and has been well
tolerated with no side effects.''
</P>
<P>
   He also said that in the Dec. 3 examination Bradley's heart
function was normal. ``Other than the arrhythmia, you have no other
health issues,'' Heissenbuttel said.
</P>
<P>
   While fibrillation is not life-threatening in itself, when it is
not fully corrected it can cause blood to pool in the atria,
increasing the likelihood of clots and the risk of stroke. The odds
of stroke are practically nonexistent in young people and minimal
in middle age, but the risk greatly increases in the elderly. For
that reason, older people are strongly urged to take a
blood-thinning drug to prevent blood clots and ward off a stroke.
The most commonly used blood thinner is the drug warfarin, also
known as coumadin.
</P>
<P>
   The atria are the upper chambers of the heart. One collects
oxygen-rich blood from the lungs and the other collects
oxygen-poor, used blood from the rest of the body. The atria pump
their blood into the ventricles below. The right ventricle sends
blood to the lungs to pick up oxygen, and the left ventricle pumps
oxygen-rich blood to the body and the brain. Normally, the atria
contract just before the ventricles do, in a strong, synchronized
fashion.
</P>
<P>
   In atrial fibrillation, the atrial rhythm becomes rapid and
irregular, and the abnormal rhythms can disrupt the beating of the
ventricles, causing an irregular or racing pulse.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors cannot always tell why a patient develops atrial
fibrillation. In some cases it is caused by some other form of
underlying heart disease, including coronary artery disease, a
heart attack or diseased heart valves. Lung disease, thyroid
disorders, diabetes and high blood pressure can also bring on the
condition. But in many cases, including Bradley's, it is
``idiopathic,'' meaning that doctors cannot figure out what caused
it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
