<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IPO-IPO_ </SLUG>
 SF CHRON  
 Another Tech IPO Soars, But Market Can Be Fickle  &HT;     By David Lazarus 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
Just a day after Sunnyvale's VA Linux Systems posted a record 697
percent surge in its initial public offering, an Internet company
called FreeMarkets showed some razzle-dazzle of its own, soaring
483 percent in its market debut yesterday.
<P>
   Lest anyone forget, these two IPOs followed Tuesday's 252
percent advance by an outfit named Andover.net.
</P>
<P>
   What do the three firms have in common? Simply put, each
represents a hot-button technology of the moment that Wall Street
thinks can do no wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street, as has been shown in a number of past IPOs, is
frequently mistaken.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a market that takes newcomers in particular niches and
embraces them and kisses them on both cheeks,'' said Ulric Weil, an
analyst with Friedman, Billings, Ramsey in Arlington, Va.
</P>
<P>
   ``And then, when they are through, the investors say, `Next!'''
</P>
<P>
   Today's trend can be tomorrow's turkey. Like a schoolboy with
overactive hormones, Wall Street falls into and out of crushes as
quickly as it encounters a pretty face.
</P>
<P>
   And in today's Internet-powered, warp-speed world, that's mighty
quick indeed. This week's market action was a perfect case in
point.
</P>
<P>
   FreeMarkets, which counts prominent Silicon Valley venture
capitalist John Doerr among its board members, serves up two of
Wall Street's currently favorite fads: business-to-business
e-commerce and online auctions.
</P>
<P>
   The company provides a venue for suppliers to bid on supply
contracts. Unlike traditional auctions, though, in this case the
prices go lower as the bidding proceeds, with the lowest bidder
winning the contract.
</P>
<P>
   It's a nifty idea, but it isn't profitable. In the nine months
ended September 30, FreeMarkets said it had sales of $13 million
but a loss of $13.5 million. It expects to keep losing money for
the foreseeable future.
</P>
<P>
   However, as is already well known, a solid bottom line is of
only passing concern to today's gimme-gimme investors. FreeMarkets'
stock rose $232 yesterday to close at $280.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have themes in the IPO market that people are going
bananas about,'' Weil said.
</P>
<P>
   Along with business-to-business and auctions, another theme du
jour is Linux, the free-to-all operating system touted as a viable
alternative to Microsoft's Windows.
</P>
<P>
   Although nobody owns the Linux source code, a bunch of companies
are rushing to market with their own variations of the recipe.
</P>
<P>
   VA Linux nailed investor sentiment dead on the nose Thursday
when its stock zoomed from an opening price of $30 to end its first
trading day at a whopping $239.25.
</P>
<P>
   ``These guys had it all,'' said Arthur Hogan, chief market
analyst with Jefferies &AMP; Co. in Boston. ``They called themselves
`Linux,' their ticker symbol is LNUX.
</P>
<P>
   ``They might as well be called Dot-com.com.''
</P>
<P>
   Never mind that VA Linux has been bleeding money in its six
years of operation, losing nearly $30 million. And never mind that
the company's IPO filing says it ``expects to continue to incur net
losses for at least the foreseeable future.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Investors don't look beyond the name and symbol,'' said Bill
Meehan, chief market analyst with Cantor Fitzgerald in New York.
``This is what happened with VA Linux.''
</P>
<P>
   It's also what happened earlier in the week when Andover.net,
which runs Web sites aimed at Linux programmers, climbed in its
trading debut from $18 to $63.38 _ and this despite the ``Dutch
auction'' system that was intended to forestall huge first-day
pops.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's money to be made, providing that Linux turns out to be
a worthy competitor to Microsoft,'' Meehan said. ``It's not clear
if that's going to be the case, but it's not beyond the realm of
possibility.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, Wall Street loves Linux not because of what it
is, but because of what it could be.
</P>
<P>
   The same logic applied a year ago to TheGlobe.com, an online
``community'' provider that skyrocketed more than 605 percent to
$63.50 in its IPO _ the record until VA Linux came along.
</P>
<P>
   TheGlobe has lost quite a bit of steam since then. It closed
yesterday at $10.25.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody talks much about online communities anymore. Just as the
buzz has all but vanished for other formerly hot trends like
bandwidth-clogging push technology and the 3-D VRML programming
language.
</P>
<P>
   Investors used to say that content is king on the Net. That's
why MarketWatch.com, a financial news site, jumped more than 473
percent in its IPO earlier this year to $97.50. The company's stock
finished yesterday at $40.88 after trading below $30e a few
months ago.
</P>
<P>
   And despite the hype over online shopping this season, even
e-commerce _ the golden ticket to IPO riches just a few months back
_ has lost its luster.
</P>
<P>
   While VA Linux was grabbing all the headlines Thursday, Redwood
City's Fogdog, an online sports retailer, climbed a mere 19 percent
to $13.13 in its first day of trading.
</P>
<P>
   Investors apparently had a hard time getting excited about a
company that, well, just sells stuff on the Net.
</P>
<P>
   ``The key is not to confuse investors with traders,'' said Shaun
Andrikopoulos, an analyst with Deutsche Bank Alex. Brown in San
Francisco. ``Traders can be very fickle.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the long haul, he added, it's the long-term investor who
will usually come out ahead.
</P>
<P>
   ``Trading is a difficult way to make money,'' Andrikopoulos
said. ``It's not investing. It's gambling.''
</P>
<P>
   It's also hard to forecast. Analysts say it's almost impossible
to predict the Next Big Thing that will catch the market's fancy
before the hype actually takes root.
</P>
<P>
   Jefferies' Hogan said that in today's hyperactive market,
investors' enthusiasm for a particular trend can run from hot to
tepid virtually overnight.
</P>
<P>
   The ones who make the real money when a new stock goes ballistic
are the institutional heavyweights and the pack of day traders
yapping at their heels, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Individual investors, if they're lucky, get no more than table
scraps, and usually at a much higher price than paid by the
institutional big boys. For this reason, Hogan observed, it's the
little guy who frequently gets burned when a company goes public.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you can get in on a deal,'' he advised, ``you really don't
want it. If you really believe in a technology, let it come back
down before you buy.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
