<SLUG> BC-GIFTFINDER-GIFTFINDER </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Internet Services Help E-shoppers Who Are Stumped About What
to  Give 
 &HT;     By Carol Emert 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
I'm an avid e-shopper. I would far rather type my credit card
number into a computer than wait in a checkout line, and I love
letting the UPS guy lug my packages home for me.
<P>
   But can the Web help me find the perfect gift for my Aunt Irene,
Aunt Florence and Aunt Willadine in the Midwest? And what about my
3- three-  &LR; and 5-year-old nephews, Alex and Miles, who live in
Germany?
</P>
<P>
   Perusing my Christmas list this year, these were the relatives
who had me stumped. The aunts are all in their 70s. They live in
small towns in Ohio and don't have any of the interests _ like golf
or wine collecting or Zen Buddhism or day trading _ that seem to
dominate the American zeitgeist these days.
</P>
<P>
   As for Miles and Alex, I don't know what children enjoy other
than Pokemon, and I wasn't about to jump on that bandwagon. Because
the boys live abroad (their mother, my sister-in-law, is in the
Foreign Service), I haven't seen them in a while and don't have a
good handle on their tastes.
</P>
<P>
   I decided to ask the Web for help. Many sites these days have
gift-recommendation services that allow surfers to plug in the
amount they want to spend and characteristics of the recipient such
as age, gender and interests. Voila, a finely tailored list of gift
ideas appears. Theoretically.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, e-tailers' ability to offer ``smart'' services like
gift finding has import far beyond whether Auntie Flo likes her
Christmas present this year.
</P>
<P>
   A good gift finder can convert confused surfers into happy
shoppers _ meaning more revenue for the site. That's not chump
change  &LR;   &LR; when, according to Forrester Research, an estimated 8.6
million American households will spend $4 billion online this
holiday season.
</P>
<P>
   Value-added services like gift finding also give digital
merchants a compelling edge over their brick-and-mortar rivals, and
business economics favor the cyber set. Instead of having to hire a
fleet of sales associates to advise shoppers, an e-tailer need
merely install the appropriate software.
</P>
<P>
   Giftspot.com was the first place I looked for auntie ideas. The
site specializes in gift certificates but also has the simplest
kind of recommendation service _ a handful of ideas in the
categories of Women, Men, Kids and Teens, Romance, Office and Hard
to Buy For.
</P>
<P>
   I thought I had struck gold in my very first try when I clicked
``Women'' and up popped a cunning leopard-spotted handbag. ``Why
give my aunties something they might buy themselves?'' I reasoned,
imagining the appreciative murmur as Aunt Irene took her seat in
church clutching the spotted bag.
</P>
<P>
   But the photo was playing tricks on me. When I clicked on the
purse and got whisked away to Ebags.com, I discovered the tote was
only 8 eight  &LR; inches high. My aunties would never dream of carrying
a purse that can't hold at least a cubic foot of coupons, tissues
and lipstick.
</P>
<P>
   Next I tried RedEnvelope.com, an attractive site that offered 10
``recipient'' choices, from Him to Pet; 13 occasions, from Birthday
to Just Because; and 16 areas of interest such as Entertaining.
Oddly, Christmas was not an occasion option, so I chose Anniversary
for Aunt Florence and Gardening as an interest, plus Her and the $0
to $50 price range.
</P>
<P>
   Gardening at Red Envelope, as it turns out, is a vastly
different undertaking than in Ohio, where gardening involves things
like flower bulbs and watering cans. Red Envelope's recommendations
included two desktop Zen sand gardens, a bonsai, a wreath, vases
and a candle holder.
</P>
<P>
   I typed in different occasions (Birthday, Just Because) and
areas of interest (Spa and Relaxation, Entertaining), but kept
pulling up the same yuppie tchotchkes and overpriced food
(chocolate-covered Oreos for $25. Hello! They're Oreos!).
</P>
<P>
   The most absurd was a 5-inch box of scented stones that cost
$30. Aunt Willadine would think I'd gone barking mad if I tried
slipping that under the Christmas tree. Briefly, I considered
starting my own Web site: Midwesternauntie.com, which would carry
large, sensible purses and garden trowels.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, though, I noticed a button that allowed me to shop by
recipient, avoiding the finer slicing and dicing that didn't seem
to be getting me anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   This one had a Grandmother option, which I chose because my
aunties are grandmother age. Finally, I spotted a gift that was
reasonably priced and perfect for Aunt Irene and Aunt Florence:
paper-white bulbs in a pretty glass vase for $25. Done.
</P>
<P>
   Aunt Willadine was on my mind as I tried MySimon.com. MySimon
offered gift ideas in 16 categories like books, sports and toys. I
clicked on a couple of fun options _ bath beads shaped like bees,
chocolates with brandy centers. But MySimon was difficult to
negotiate; it kept linking me to other sites but not letting me
backtrack to MySimon. Eventually I gave up.
</P>
<P>
   Next stop: Gifts.com, which told me in a pop-up popup  &LR; window
that shipping would be free if I ordered THAT DAY ONLY! I decided
to make an effort to find something for Aunt Willadine here, even
though the ad reappeared and I had to close it down each time I
revisited the home page, which was annoying.
</P>
<P>
   Gifts.com had a wealth of categories: 14 areas of interests, 18
occasions and 16 recipient profiles. Once again, I was creative
with the categories. There was no Aunt, so I plugged in Mother. I
chose Birthday because Christmas or Holiday was not an option. (It
was available under a dedicated button, but not part of the
recommendation service.)
</P>
<P>
   And there it was: a crystal bud vase for $25 that seemed made
just for Aunt Willadine's jonquils. Done.
</P>
<P>
   Alex and Miles were next on the agenda. Their mother advised me
that Miles, 5, is discovering science and might like a chemistry
kit. I was impressed with her zest for adventure.
</P>
<P>
   My first stop was eToys, which I found to be well organized and
easy to use, with many different search options. Using the
ToySearch mechanism, I plugged in 4 to 5 Years Old and Science and
Nature to find something for Miles.
</P>
<P>
   All kinds of cool stuff popped up, including several bug farms
that I immediately dismissed since I want to stay on my in-laws'
good side.
</P>
<P>
   Then I noticed a Scubascope Subsurface Viewer that kids can use
to look underwater while bathing or swimming. It linked to a whole
page of scopes, and soon I was checking out periscopes, zoomscopes,
megascopes and other snooping mechanisms _ all excellent training
tools for a young reporter-to-be, I couldn't help but think.
</P>
<P>
   I fell hard for the MegaScope, a combination telescope and
microscope, after reading this testimonial from Darren, 10, of
Urbana, Ill.: ``I can look at stars and I can look at bugs with it.
I can look at my other toys, too. Thank you, Mom.''
</P>
<P>
   At $19.99, it was cheaper than chocolate-covered Oreos from Red
Envelope! The MegaScope went right into my shopping cart.
</P>
<P>
   I also noticed that the MegaScope had won an award from a
parents organization, so I decided to check out other recommended
toys. EToys lists award winners for different ages, a great service
for gift givers who don't know much about kid stuff.
</P>
<P>
   I questioned the awards' credibility a bit when I came across a
McDonald's Happy Meal Playshop that lets children make
cheeseburgers out of Play-Doh. What are we trying to teach our
children about nutrition, anyway? Still, I did find a very cool
walkie-talkie set for Alex.
</P>
<P>
   As I checked out, I found that EToys even ships abroad, which is
unusual among e-tailers. And the checkout service offered to
include batteries for the walkie-talkie and the scope, in the
appropriate wattage and number, in my order. I happily approved the
batteries.
</P>
<P>
   Even though my shopping was done, I decided to take a look at
ToysRUs.com for the sake of comparison.
</P>
<P>
   ToysRUs did not offer an award-winner category, so I tried the
EZ ToyFinder search mechanism. It didn't seem to be working. I
plugged in 3 to 4 Years Old and $10 to $25, but it came up empty
twice.
</P>
<P>
   As I clicked around in the 2-to-4-Years-Old category I found
myself wading through acres and acres of Barbies and baby dolls.
WNBA Barbie was interesting but not appropriate. I decided to end
my search there.
</P>
<P>
   Conclusion: Like so many other aspects of the infant Web, some
gift-recommendation services work well and some don't. But if my
experience is any example, the site that offers good
recommendations in well-organized categories is the one that will
win the loyalty of e-shoppers.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
