<SLUG> BC-BUSH-SMILE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE GEORGE W SMILE: IS THAT SIMPER FINITE A CAUSE FOR CHAGRIN?
</HEADLINE>
 
(EDS: Rsesnding to restore dropped word in hed) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LIZ STEVENS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's not easy to read George W.'s lips.
</P>
<P>
   Somewhere between the Cheshire cat's toothy grin and the Mona
Lisa's coy simper are the curiously curved lips of the Texas
governor and front-running Republican presidential candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Some call it a smirk, others a smile. Some say it makes George
W. Bush appear cocky and condescending; others say it's friendly
and frank. Whatever it is _ that pursed-lipped grin often
accompanied by raised eyebrows _ it has prompted comment from
C-Span viewers, online magazines and Kansas farmers.
</P>
<P>
   It has also become a topic on local and national talk radio.
</P>
<P>
   But does facial expression really make a difference in a
presidential campaign? Perhaps.
</P>
<P>
   People expect their presidents to be ``cheerful and optimistic
and on the other hand, serious,'' said Jack Pitney, a political
analyst at Claremont McKenna College in California. To that extent,
he said, facial expressions ``can make a difference for some
voters.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Richard Nixon, in spite of his famous scowl, was twice
elected president, Pitney pointed out.
</P>
<P>
   ``We also elected Jimmy Carter, whose humorless grin got old
very fast,'' Pitney said.
</P>
<P>
   Buzz over Bush's mug began in the national news media.
</P>
<P>
   Detroit News columnist and conservative Fox News commentator
Tony Snow referred to the Bush expression as ``The Smirk'' in a
recent syndicated column. The s-word has popped up in the online
``Slate'' and ``Talk'' magazines; other journalists have called the
expression a ``jaunty grin,'' ``bemused smile'' and ``half-smile.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bush campaign classifies his expression as perfectly
affable.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, it is a smile,'' said Mark McKinnon, Bush's media
consultant. ``It's a bemused smile. I would describe it as
charming.''
</P>
<P>
   The look appears most often when the governor is in listening
mode: listening to a potential constituent on the campaign trail,
listening to an interviewer pose a question, listening to CNN's
John King toss him his first question of the Arizona debate Monday.
</P>
<P>
   As Bush's TV appearances have accelerated, commentators and
viewers have keyed on his enigmatic grin. In September, a ``Talk''
magazine writer described Bush as ``smirking'' throughout a
conversation about the execution of Karla Faye Tucker.
</P>
<P>
   C-Span viewers made the grin a topic of conversation on a
call-in show after Bush's mid-November foreign policy address.
``The Wall Street Journal'' ran a story on ``the alleged smirk''
this month.
</P>
<P>
   Texans tend to cut their governor a little more slack than the
nation does.
</P>
<P>
   Bush ``is a person who, by all accounts, has a wonderful sense
of humor,'' said James Riddlesperger, a Texas Christian University
professor of political science. He said that sometimes when you see
the look, ``It's almost a pained expression because he'd really
like to throw out a one-liner but knows he can't. He has a smirk,
but his eyes are dancing.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush isn't the first presidential candidate whose mug has
prompted discussion. Think back to Nixon, ``who was thought to look
shifty-eyed and who perspired a lot'' on televised debates, said
Alan Schroeder, a professor in the School of Journalism at
Northeastern University in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Or, he said, recall Dan Quayle, ``who had this kind of
frightened look in his eye that the camera exaggerated.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem with television is that it perpetuates these
visual stereotypes, but whether they're valid or not is anybody's
guess,'' said Schroeder, author of ``Presidential Debates: Forty
Years of High-Risk TV,'' which is scheduled for publication next
summer.
</P>
<P>
   All the couch-potato grin analysis has Paul King slightly
annoyed. King, an associate professor of speech communications at
TCU, has some news for would-be face readers: ``There's really no
such thing as body language,'' he said, adding that pundits who try
to read a candidate's kisser ``irritate me endlessly.''
</P>
<P>
   Diana Carlin, a professor of communication studies at the
University of Kansas, said members of the Kansas Agricultural Rural
Leadership Program happened to be discussing Bush's expression at a
recent meeting.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were talking about just this issue _ they had all noticed
it, too,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``In fairness, every one of us has things we do that we're
totally unaware of,'' added Carlin, who admits to raising her
eyebrows a lot. ``That's the reason people don't like to watch
themselves on a video.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
