<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-AIRPORTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER PLANE CRASH, RENEWED CALLS TO LIMIT AIR TRAFFIC  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.J., N.Y.)  By MARIA NEWMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HASBROUCK HEIGHTS, N.J. _ Residents of this town, where a plane
crashed on Thursday, killing all four people aboard, have been
trying for years to limit air traffic at nearby Teterboro Airport
amid increasing worries about noise and safety.
</P>
<P>
   The crash, the second time in three weeks that a plane has
plummeted into a residential neighborhood in New Jersey, is causing
widespread concern. Air traffic at small airports in the nation's
busiest air corridor is increasing along with residential
development.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at Teterboro Airport, a mile east of the crash site,
say that air traffic is safe and that there has not been a
significant increase in overall air traffic over the last 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   But the crash of a twin-engine plane Thursday, prompted an
immediate outcry from residents and elected officials that the Port
Authority of New York and New Jersey, which owns Teterboro, should
limit air traffic there. It has highlighted the growing tension
between residents of suburban communities surrounding New York City
and the directors of smaller regional airports trying to meet the
demand for more air traffic.
</P>
<P>
   ``The commerce and business that Teterboro provides is
important, but it should not supersede the quality of life of these
neighborhoods,'' said Rep. Steven R. Rothman, who visited the
accident site Friday with other officials.
</P>
<P>
   The airport, located seven miles from Manhattan on 400 acres in
Teterboro and Moonachie has become a haven for private jets
transporting celebrities and business executives. Teterboro handled
198,466 general aviation takeoffs and landings in 1998, a 10
percent increase from 1997, according to the Federal Aviation
Authority.
</P>
<P>
   Rothman, along with Sen. Robert Torricelli and others have been
calling for a flight curfew to keep planes from flying in and out
of the airport at night.
</P>
<P>
   Port Authority officials said they would work with investigators
from the National Transportation Safety Board to see whether
changes are needed in airport operations.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are concerned and saddened by yesterday's tragedy,'' said
Peter Yearkes, a spokesman for the Port Authority, which also
operates LaGuardia, Kennedy and Newark International Airports. ``We
will cooperate in every way possible with the NTSB investigation.
There are a number of issues that will be examined as a result of
this.''
</P>
<P>
   But he said there were limits to what the airport could do to
accommodate residents without hurting business. In every community
that has tried to impose restrictions on when aircraft could take
off or land, the courts have sided with the airports and declared
that curfews would be an unfair imposition on commerce, Yearkes
said. Some airports, however, have voluntary curfews.
</P>
<P>
   Residents and officials say the noise level has risen so sharply
in the last few years that some limits are urgently needed. The
number of jets flying out of Teterboro has increased to 81,766 in
1997 from 53,009 in 1987, according to the Port Authority. The
mayor of Hasbrouck Heights, William Torre, said such increases
could inevitably lead to more accidents like the one on Thursday,
and he renewed his plea for restrictions from federal aviation
officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``Please, help us minimize the risk so this doesn't happen again
in our town or the surrounding towns and the region,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Frank R. Lautenberg, who was also at the crash site, called
on the FAA to conduct an emergency 60-day study to determine why
there have been an inordinate number of crashes in New Jersey this
year.
</P>
<P>
   He pointed out that New Jersey is the most densely populated
state in the nation, so that airports, like Teterboro and Essex
County Airport in Fairfield, where John F. Kennedy Jr. took off
from on his fatal crash, and even Newark Airport, naturally present
more risk to residents.
</P>
<P>
   The number of fatalities in air crashes has gone down
nationally, to 621 in 1998 from 800 in 1988, the FAA said. But
crashes in densely populated areas that receive considerable news
media attention make people believe they are more common than ever,
said Warren Morningstar, a spokesman for the Aircraft Owners and
Pilots Association, a Frederick, Md., group that represents 355,000
pilots.
</P>
<P>
   In New York State, residents near the Westchester County
Airport, have also been complaining about the growing noise and
pollution. Westchester has the highest number of private aircraft
of any airport in the country, according to FAA reports, with
1,003.
</P>
<P>
   Ron Bianchi, mayor and supervisor of Harrison, said that the
airport's parking lots, which were expanded during last airport
renovation, are already too small. But he said he would oppose
attempts to further expand them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want to turn it into JFK or LaGuardia,'' he said.
``Then they'll start flying in goods, warehouses will crop up
around the airport, and the whole complexion of suburbia will
absolutely change.''
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Spano, the Westchester County executive, recently ordered
a review of the airport's new noise monitoring system, said Susan
Tolchin, his communications director. She said that the county has
no plans to allow an expansion, but that the complaints about noise
have come mostly from neighbors closest to the airport, who say
many pilots ignore a voluntary curfew of midnight to 6:30 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   The numbers of flights have increased in recent years, though
not by as much as at Teterboro. Westchester officials said that in
1998, there were 106,136 general aviation landings and takeoffs,
and 44,060 corporate ones. In 1989, there were 116,600 general
aviation landings and takeoffs, and 39,824 corporate ones.
</P>
<P>
   At Long Islands MacArthur Airport in Islip, N.J., which is owned
by the Town of Islip, air traffic increased since Southwest
Airlines began service last March with 12 daily nonstop flights.
</P>
<P>
   The number of passengers using the airport has more than doubled
from last year, according to town officials, increasing to more
than 200,000 in August, up from less than 92,000 the previous year.
So have complaints about the noise from nearby residents in an area
that is increasingly more populated.
</P>
<P>
   Residents say much of the noise is caused by the small private
jets that seem to land or take off late at night or early in the
morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those Lear Jets are loud,'' said Deborah Slinkosky of
Haolbrook, the chairwoman of Citizens for Enforcement of MacArthur
Airport Controls. ``They are flying these CEOs around, taking off
at 4:30 in the morning and coming in at 2:30 in the morning, and
besides being noisy, that could be extremely dangerous if anything
happens.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
