<HEADLINE>
IN SOCCER SEMIFINALS, SANTA CLARA DEFEATS CONNECTICUT IN 4TH
OVERTIME 
</HEADLINE>
  (mcd) 
 By ALEX YANNIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHARLOTTE, N.C., _ Santa Clara, the most experienced among the
four men's teams remaining for the national championship of college
soccer, went into the semifinals with six overtime victories in its
last eight games. Two of the overtime victories had come in the
National Collegiate Athletic Association tournament, against
Stanford in the first round and Alabama-Birmingham in the
quarterfinals.
</P>
<P>
   So there was little surprise for the Broncos Friday when their
semifinal against Connecticut could not be decided in regulation
time.
</P>
<P>
   But there was plenty of joy for Santa Clara when Shawn Percell,
in the fourth overtime, scored his second goal of the game to give
the Broncos a 2-1 triumph over the Huskies.
</P>
<P>
   The victory, which took 138 minutes 50 seconds to achieve, not
only ended Connecticut's best season since it won the title in
1981, but it also put the Broncos in Sunday's championship game at
Ericsson Stadium against either UCLA or Indiana.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA, the winner two years ago, played Friday's other semifinal
against Indiana, the defending champion, which eliminated Santa
Clara by 4-0 in last year's semifinals.
</P>
<P>
   The winning goal against Connecticut was Percell's fourth in the
tournament and it came from close range on a shot that went just
past Matt Chavlovich, the Connecticut goalkeeper, who left his near
post unprotected.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their goalie cheated a little space in the near post,''
Percell said, ``and I took advantage. I struggled early in the
season, but the coach told me goals come in waves.''
</P>
<P>
   Coach Mitch Murray, who has been with Santa Clara since 1989, is
again within reach of a national title.
</P>
<P>
   Santa Clara (16-3-3) lost the championship game in 1991 to
Virginia on penalty kicks and shared the title with Virginia in
1989 in frozen Rutgers Stadium. The icy conditions for that
championship game prompted the NCAA to put future tournaments in
warm climates.
</P>
<P>
   The loss was Connecticut's first in the last 13 games. The
Huskies, who ended the season at 19-5-0, made their first
appearance in the semifinals since 1983.
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut was more technical in this game, but Santa Clara was
more practical. The Huskies tried to find their way through Santa
Clara's defense with short passes, quickness and speed as Santa
Clara employed more of a direct route with long passes.
</P>
<P>
   Percell scored his first goal in the 20th minute of regulation
when he stepped into an unguarded space and used his head to flick
home a free kick from the right side by Ari Rodopoulos to the far
post. It was his sixth goal of the season and third in the
tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Darin Lewis tied the score for Connecticut with a brilliant
individual effort and a blistering shot from 25 yards in the 56th
minute. The teams went back and forth without a goal after that
until Percell's winner 3:50 into the fourth sudden-death overtime.
</P>
<P>
   ``We expended so much energy getting back their first goal,''
said Ray Reid, Connecticut's third-year coach. ``I thought that for
our first time here our guys did a good job.''
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut maintained possession for the most part, waiting for
the right opening, but Santa Clara's defense rarely allowed
Connecticut to threaten near its goal. The best chances for
Connecticut came on long shots.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
