<DOCNO> NYT19991210.0356 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-10 22:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5684 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-UTAH-SURVIVAL-2TAKES-     12-10 1010
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UTAH-SURVIVAL-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEEP IN THE WILDERNESS, A GROWTH INDUSTRY IS BLOOMING 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Calif., Ariz.)  (mk) 
 By MICHAEL JANOFSKY with BARRY MEIER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERYL, Utah _ For parents like Mitchell and Jill Friedman of
Great Neck, N.Y., the decision to enroll a child in a wilderness
program for troubled teenagers is born of desperation, a last
chance to rescue a life endangered by drugs, crime or simply
aimlessness. In the Friedmans' case, the outcome was worth the
anguish.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's wonderful _ I'm crying,'' Friedman said this week at the
graduation of his son, Jeffrey, from the Redcliff Ascent Outdoor
Therapy Program. ``The last year has been hell. Every day he was
out of school, on the streets, somewhere, we were terrified. When
we got him here, we finally breathed easier.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeffrey had just spent 83 days in the desert here in
southwestern Utah, in a minimalist world without music, television
or cellular phones. Like other wilderness therapy programs,
Redcliff tries to strip away bad habits, build character and
restore self-esteem by forcing teenagers to fend for themselves and
one another through a daily routine of hiking, campfire-building,
food preparation and latrine-digging, as well as high school course
work. Counselors lead the participants through quiet periods of
introspection each day, and psychiatrists and psychologists visit
once a week to measure progress.
</P>
<P>
   The satisfaction of people like the Friedmans notwithstanding,
wilderness therapy has not been entirely trouble-free. In a widely
publicized episode last Saturday, eight Redcliff boys accosted two
counselors and fled into the desert. And over the last 10 years, at
least four teenagers have died in such programs. Further, some
experts question whether the approach provides any long-lasting
benefits to wayward youths, contending that the results of
``shocking'' them with outdoor hardships quickly wear off when they
return to their homes and, frequently, renew old habits with old
friends.
</P>
<P>
   But the successes have apparently been common enough to make
this a growth industry. While the concept of wilderness therapy is
hardly new _ the Dallas Salesmanship Club opened one of the first
such camps for troubled youth 51 years ago _ it has exploded in
recent years. Where there were once just a few scattered operations
around the country, there are now hundreds of companies, most of
them in Western states.
</P>
<P>
   In large measure, the experts say, the programs' popularity
stems from a growing inability of public schools to deal with
severe behavioral problems or to identify signs of alienation that
lead to drug use or violence. More families are seeking alternative
solutions, and the robust national economy has enabled many to
afford them. (Redcliff charges as much as $350 a day, and some
teenagers stay for two months or more.) State and local courts also
use the programs, as an alternative to jail.
</P>
<P>
   No one knows the precise number of such programs, or the
industry's rate of success. So many of the programs are new, their
services are provided in varied settings, and no scientific survey
has ever tried to measure their effectiveness.
</P>
<P>
   But Mark Sklarow, executive director of the Independent
Educational Consultants Association, a nonprofit company in
Fairfax, Va., that helps families find solutions for their troubled
children, said the number of programs had grown to ``several
hundred,'' compared with fewer than 25 less than a decade ago.
</P>
<P>
   Typically, a camp's population has swollen as well. Mitch Cole,
manager of the Redcliff administrative office here, said that as
recently as five years ago, only 16 teenagers were enrolled in the
program on any given day. Now as many as 64 are participating.
</P>
<P>
   ``Working with children at risk is really a growth industry,''
said Helene Reynolds, an educational consultant in Princeton, N.J.,
who has recommended wilderness therapy programs, including
Redcliff, to her clients. (One of those clients, she said, was the
family of a boy involved in the assault on the counselors last
Saturday.)
</P>
<P>
   The rapid growth has brought a hodgepodge of oversight. There is
no national regulation of the industry, and regulation by the
states varies widely. Two industry organizations are engaged in
accrediting or monitoring therapeutic wilderness programs for
health, safety and program content, but one, the Association of
Experiential Education, a trade group in Boulder, Colo., has
accredited only seven of the 165 of its members that offer some
form of therapy. And the other, the National Association of
Therapeutic Schools and Programs, in Savannah, Ga., which was
formed in January, has yet to develop any standards, although it is
working with 67 programs in 26 states.
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Wells, executive director of the Koch Crime Institute, a
research organization in Topeka, Kan., said that while the outward
appearances were different, the underlying philosophy of wilderness
programs was the same as that of military-style boot camps.
</P>
<P>
   ``The basic premise is that the lack of discipline and structure
in their life has led them to bad decisions,'' Wells said of the
participants. ``Therefore, if you provide them with the structure,
it will lead them to better decisions.''
</P>
<P>
   Cole, of Redcliff, conceded that wilderness programs were once
typically run by people who had more of a military background than
experience in therapy work. It was not uncommon, he said, to hear
stories of youths' being treated as if they were attending boot
camp.
</P>
<P>
   But now, he said, Utah and most other states have strict health
and safety regulations against the use of physical force, hazing or
food deprivation as a means of discipline. A misbehaving Redcliff
teenager who violates the rules by cursing will most likely be
punished by having to carry a small rock on the next hike.
</P>
<P>
   ``That way, there's a constant reminder of breaking the rule,''
Cole said. ``It also teaches you that there are consequences to
your actions.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, in the last decade four teenagers, three of them in
Utah, have died at wilderness camps because of mistreatment or
abuse, said Bob MacDougall, who licenses the programs for the Utah
Department of Human Services. The last of the Utah deaths occurred
in 1994, he added, and all three companies involved in those deaths
are now out of business.
</P>
<P>
   Catherine Sutton of Ripon, Calif., whose daughter, Michelle,
died nine years ago after a week in a defunct Utah wilderness
program called Summit Quest, said counselors had accused Michelle
of faking flulike symptoms. Her death was attributed to
dehydration.
</P>
<P>
   And after Nicholaus Contreraz, 16, died of a lung infection last
year at the Arizona Boys Ranch in Oracle, Ariz., his family won a
$1 million settlement of a wrongful-death lawsuit that claimed he
had been a victim of physical abuse at the hands of his counselors.
</P>
<P>
   Like many other wilderness programs, Redcliff teaches its
lessons of respect, compassion and self-esteem against a tableau of
uninterrupted weeks, or even months, of hiking and camping through
580 square miles of rugged desert in southwestern Utah, where
nighttime temperatures in winter routinely fall below 10 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   The campers are sent out with only necessities: Clothes
appropriate for the time of year, sleeping gear and food, which
they prepare for themselves and consume with utensils they carve
out of tree branches. They dig their own latrines.
</P>
<P>
   A Walkman? A portable radio? Forget it. Not even a wristwatch is
allowed.
</P>
<P>
   Rules are strictly enforced, and they include taboos against
cursing, sarcasm and any questions about time beyond the present.
</P>
<P>
   Program officials say they have found that the spartan regimen,
which stresses teamwork over individualism and provides time for
intense personal introspection through individual and group
therapy, is the most direct way to save a wayward life.
</P>
<P>
   Cole said that through follow-up interviews with parents six
months after graduation, Redcliff officials estimated their success
rate at 70 to 80 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Jeffrey Friedman, who acknowledged that before he entered the
program his life in Great Neck had collapsed into daily use of
marijuana and indifference toward school, said he now easily
recognized the parallel between working with a group in the wild
and getting along with his parents and two older sisters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I learned a lot more about how things I did affected the
group, like they affected my family,'' he said. ``In the group, you
have to work together. I realized that at home I was acting
selfishly, and it brought down the whole family.''
</P>
<P>
   Todd Chavin of Evanston, Ill., also graduated this week. His
parents, Scott and Judy Chavin, stared at him in near-disbelief
when he said, ``I don't feel like Todd anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I've truly changed,'' he added. ``I feel totally different.
I'm happy again. I don't want to go home and smoke dope with my
friends. I want to move on with my life and become a man.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
