<HEADLINE>
PINCAY PASSES SHOEMAKER WITH WIN NO. 8,834  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By KEN GURNICK  
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ One day after tying the legendary Bill
Shoemaker, Laffit Pincay Jr. raced past him Friday, becoming the
winningest jockey in thoroughbred history by picking up victory No.
8,834 in his 44,647th ride.
</P>
<P>
   Shoemaker had held the distinction of being the winningest
jockey for 29 years, but Pincay, who turns 53 on Dec. 29, took it
over by going virtually wire to wire aboard Irish Nip, a 3-year-old
maidshowed a liking for the Hollywood Park turf as well as
the champagne that Pincay's fellow jockeys sprayed in all
directions during a wild winner's circle celebration.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like I won the Kentucky Derby all over again,'' said a
beaming Pincay, who won that classic once, in 1984 on Swale.
</P>
<P>
   Irish Nip, a son of Irish River, was making his second career
start and was sent off as the 5-2 favorite in the 1 1/16-mile race.
He dueled for the lead with Laps n'Bounds down the backstretch,
inched clear turning into the stretch and won by two lengths,
paying $7.60 for a $2 bet to win. Pincay waved his fist in triumph
as he crossed the wire.
</P>
<P>
   ``Laffit has conducted himself with dignity all through his
career, he's had ups and downs and he never gave up,'' said
Shoemaker, who watched the race in the jockeys room in his
wheelchair. ``He's ridden in rain and sleet and snow and never took
off a mount. I'm very proud of him.''
</P>
<P>
   Pincay said, ``Thank you, Shoe.''
</P>
<P>
   The celebration included the presentation to Pincay of a white
Porsche, driven into the winner's circle by his fellow Hall of Fame
jockey Chris McCarron. The car was a gift from four Southern
California race tracks, in appreciation of Pincay, who decided two
years ago to shoot for the record on the tough local circuit rather
than move to the softer competition of northern California.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to thank the trainers and owners who supported me my
whole career,'' Pincay said. ``And I want to thank Hooper, who gave
me the opportunity to come to this country and ride for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Pincay was referring to Fred Hooper, now 102, who brought Pincay
to the United States from Panama in 1966 and launched his American
career at Arlington Park outside Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   In typical Pincay fashion, the jockey cut short a postrace
interview to ride his next scheduled mount _ Storm Dog _ who ended
up ninth in a 10-horse race.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't want to disappoint anybody,'' Pincay said.
</P>
<P>
   The winning trainer, Richard Mandella, teamed with Pincay and
Lazy Lode to win the $400,000 Grade I Hollywood Turf Cup last
weekend. ``I didn't realize how special this would be until he got
to the eighth pole,'' Mandella said. ``I was cussing him when he
took him to the lead. But I was riding along with him down the
stretch.''
</P>
<P>
   The ceremony included video tributes by several Hall of Fame
jockeys, including John Longden, who held the record that Shoemaker
broke in 1970, and 46-year-old Pat Day, who is next in line with
7,614 victories.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he keeps going, Pat Day has a good chance to break Laffit's
record,'' McCarron said. ``You've got to have the dedication and
work ethic that Laffit has. Laffit could ride until he's 60. He
could win 10,000.''
</P>
<P>
   Pincay is one victory behind Pat Valenzuela for the current meet
lead at Hollywood Park with eight racing days left. A riding title
would be his 13th at Hollywood and first anywhere since 1991.
</P>
<P>
   Pincay said he hoped to ride ``one or two more years'' and did
not know what he would do after retiring. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The record-breaker capped a remarkable comeback for Pincay, who
overcame the suicide of his first wife in 1985 only to be abandoned
by trainers once he turned 50. At the time, it was believed that
age and years of virtual starvation to make riding weight had
robbed him of his talents.
</P>
<P>
   But sticking religiously to an 850-calorie daily diet, Pincay
rededicated himself to chase Shoemaker. The mounts and victories
picked up, and the pace accelerated this summer.  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
