<HEADLINE>
IRAQ RULES OUT A VISIT BY THE POPE; POLITICAL FACTORS ARE CITED
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By ALESSANDRA STANLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME _ In the first major setback to Pope John Paul II's
ambitious travel plans for the millennium, the Vatican said Friday
that Iraq had ruled out a planned papal visit.
</P>
<P>
   The 79-year-old Roman Catholic leader, who has long dreamed of
visiting major biblical sites in 2000, had badly wanted to stop in
Ur, an ancient city in Iraq believed to be the birthplace of
Abraham.
</P>
<P>
   But Vatican diplomats were unable to reach an agreement with
Iraqi officials over a visit that the pope viewed as a strictly
religious pilgrimage, but that was fraught with political overtones
for both President Saddam Hussein and the United States, which had
lobbied against a papal visit, fearing it could lend legitimacy to
the Iraqi leader.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps in the hope that a visit to Ur could yet be resurrected,
Vatican officials gave a carefully neutral explanation Friday of
how their diplomacy with Baghdad broke down.
</P>
<P>
   ``Iraqi authorities have informed the secretariat of state that
the abnormal conditions in which Iraq finds itself due to the
embargo and the no-flight zone, as well as the general situation in
the region, do not permit a visit by the Holy Father to Ur to be
organized properly,'' the Vatican spokesman, Joaquin Navarro-Valls,
said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   The United Nations imposed the embargo in 1990 after Iraq's
invasion of Kuwait. American and British planes have patrolled
no-flight zones in north and south Iraq since 1991.
</P>
<P>
   Before Friday's announcement, a senior Vatican official
explained privately that the Iraqis appeared preoccupied with the
idea that the pope, by asking the United Nations to permit his
plane to fly into Iraq, would in some way legitimize the sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   The Vatican official said its envoys in Baghdad had explained
that the pope would not ask for permission, but would merely inform
the United Nations of his travel plans. But even though the pope
has often condemned the sanctions, that argument failed to reassure
Iraqi officials.
</P>
<P>
   The Iraqi government may also have feared that during his trip,
the pope would preach about human rights, as he does in almost
every country he visits. Baghdad gave a strong hint of its concerns
last fall, in a letter by Iraqi intellectuals published by the
state news agency, which lectured the pope on what he should say
during his visit, and expressed reservations about his message to
Christians in a predominantly Muslim culture.
</P>
<P>
   Vatican officials let it be known that they were offended by the
letter.
</P>
<P>
   American and British official visitors to the Vatican had
lobbied against the trip, fearing that a papal meeting with Hussein
would break the isolation imposed on Iraq. But the Vatican, which
rejected those overtures as unwarranted interference in its
affairs, was ultimately unable to overcome Baghdad's misgivings.
</P>
<P>
   But in Iraq, where preparations for the visit to Ur had already
begun, Catholic officials expressed their belief that the trip had
only been postponed, not canceled.
</P>
<P>
   Patriarch Raphael I Bidawid of the Chaldean Church told the
Vatican's missionary news service, Fides, that concerns about the
pope's security had put off the visit.
</P>
<P>
   The pope plans to visit the Holy Land in March, but there are
lingering questions about his trip to Nazareth, where the Catholic
Church is opposed to the building of a mosque next to the city's
main Catholic shrine.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
