u s BC-BBO-WINTER-MEETING-NY     12-10 0938
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-WINTER-MEETING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OROSCO RETURNS TO METS AS WINTER MEETINGS BEGIN 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By MURRAY CHASS    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Less than an hour after he arrived on the
scene, Steve Phillips struck. The general manager who a year ago
brought the Mets Robin Ventura, Armando Benitez and Roger Cedeno
pulled off the first trade of baseball's winter meetings Friday.
But Jesse Orosco will not replace the offensive production that
John Olerud took to Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, Jesse Orosco is coming home. The Mets, with whom the
42-year-old relief pitcher began life as a major-leaguer, got him
back by trading Chuck McElroy to the Baltimore Orioles. But the
swap will not rival the one that will send Ken Griffey Jr. closer
to home. Wherever that is, whenever that happens.
</P>
<P>
   This was an exchange of left-handed relievers who have had
better seasons than they had last season. Orosco had a 5.34 earned
run average in 65 games and walked 20 batters in 32 innings, but he
also struck out 35. McElroy, whom the Mets obtained from Colorado
last July 31, had a 5.50 ERA in 56 games, though he was better with
the Mets, at 3.38 in 15 appearances.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be different,'' Orosco said in a conference
call, commenting on his return to the Mets 12 years after they
traded him to Los Angeles. Referring to an interleague game at Shea
Stadium, he added: ``When I went there two years ago, it was
tingling. I was nervous. This will be different. I'll be in a Mets
uniform.''
</P>
<P>
   Orosco, who gained a career-high 31 saves in a Mets uniform in
1984 and was a postseason hero in 1986, had to approve the trade as
a player who has 10 years in the majors, including the last five
with the same team. He said he approved it because he liked the
makeup of the Mets. But he also approved it because he did not want
to pitch for the Orioles' new manager, Mike Hargrove, who was
Orosco's manager in Cleveland nearly a decade ago.
</P>
<P>
   After Phillips announced the trade, he was asked _ jokingly _ if
his work at the meetings was done. ``Obviously,'' he said,
laughing, ``we have a lot to do. We're going to be very busy
here.''
</P>
<P>
   Phillips' primary goals are to replace Olerud at first base and
to add hitting. While at the five-day meetings, he will talk to
agents for several free agents, including first basemen David Segui
and David Nilsson and outfielder Greg Vaughn.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn's agent said Thursday that the Mets were seriously
interested in his client, who hit 95 home runs the past two
seasons, but that the Mets had not made an offer. They are waiting
to see what other teams might vigorously pursue Vaughn.
</P>
<P>
   One player the Mets will not acquire is Carlos Delgado. The
Toronto Blue Jays signed Delgado, their first baseman, Friday,
giving him $36 million for three years. He had rejected their
previous offer of $12 million a year for five years, and they had
rejected his request for $38.25 million for three years.
</P>
<P>
   Delgado, who last season hit 44 home runs and drove in 134 runs,
accepted less money because the Blue Jays added a provision that
will allow him to demand a trade after next season. If he makes
such a demand and the Blue Jays do not trade him by the following
Feb. 15, he can become a free agent.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest name hovering over the meetings is Griffey. The Mets
are among a very few teams that will at least talk with the Seattle
Mariners about the possibility of a trade.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to talk to everybody,'' Phillips said when asked
specifically about his interest in Griffey. ``We'll see how we fit
with those teams. Seattle is one of those teams.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners have never told the Mets which of their players
they would want, and an executive familiar with the talks between
the teams said the Mets had not made an offer for Griffey.
</P>
<P>
   The Cincinnati Reds continue to be considered the team most
likely to acquire the superstar center fielder. Jim Bowden, their
general manager, is scheduled to meet with Pat Gillick, the
Mariners' general manager, on Saturday morning. They have talked
many times by telephone the past few weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Some baseball people believe the only thing blocking a trade is
Pokey Reese, the Reds' second baseman. The Mariners want him; the
Reds do not want to trade him.
</P>
<P>
   ``No question you'd love to have the other guy, but I don't want
to move Pokey,'' said Jack McKeon, the Reds' manager, who
acknowledged that he had no say in the talks. ``Pokey's a great
kid. I love him. But I don't have any control over it. They'll do
what they think is best for the club.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mets acquired Orosco because, Phillips said, he is better at
getting left-handers out than John Franco and Dennis Cook, the
other two left-handers in their bullpen. ``Jesse gives us better
balance in the bullpen with situational left-handers,'' Phillips
said.
</P>
<P>
   In the four seasons before 1999, Orosco held left-handed batters
to a .166 average. But he was not as effective last season. They
hit .270 against him.
</P>
<P>
   There is not much difference economically in the trade. McElroy
has two years left on his contract at salaries of $1.35 million and
$1.45 million. Orosco will have a $1.1 million salary next season,
and the Mets have an option in 2001 for $1.3 million. But the
option will become guaranteed if Orosco pitches in 55 games next
season. The last time he didn't pitch in that many games in a full
season was 1991.
</P>
<P>
   Orosco was asked Friday how much longer he plans to play. He
said his agent and his wife were conspiring to get him to pitch to
age 50. ``I was laughing at it,'' he said. ``Now it's starting to
scare me.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
