<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRADLEY-HEART-TEXT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXT OF LETTER FROM BRADLEY'S DOCTOR 
</HEADLINE>
  (With BRADLEY-HEART) 
(js) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Following is a letter to former Sen. Bill Bradley of New Jersey
from his doctor, Robert H. Heissenbutel. The letter, which was
dated Thursday, was made public Friday by Bradley's presidential
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   I am writing to inform you about the results of your examination
on Dec. 3, 1999. At that time you were feeling well with no
complaints.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, you were found to have atrial fibrillation with no
precipitating cause, nor any cardiac disease identified. You were
cardioverted to regular sinus rhythm. Over the next two years you
had four episodes, and in 1998 you had two cardioversions. Since
May of 1998, after your third and last cardioversion, you have been
treated with Procanbid. Over this year-and-one-half you have had
two brief episodes of atrial fibrillation, which converted
spontaneously. The medication has been effective in preventing or
shortening the duration of episodes and has been well tolerated
with no side effects.
</P>
<P>
   On examination your blood pressure was 118/68, pulse 55 _
regular. The physical examination was normal.
</P>
<P>
   In April of 1999 you had a routine colonoscopy with removal of a
small benign polyp. At that time your PSA was normal.
</P>
<P>
   Your recent laboratory studies included a normal CBC and
differential, urinalysis, ESR, glucose, liver function, kidney
function studies. Lipid profile: total cholesterol 161,
triglycerides 58, HDL cholesterol 58, LDL cholesterol 91
(excellent). Electrocardiogram; regular sinus rhythm, unchanged
from May 28, 1999.
</P>
<P>
   On 12/3/99 you had stress echocardiography performed. Your
exercise tolerance was excellent and you had no symptoms at 91
percent of predicated maximal heart rate. There was no indication
of ischemia and your heart function was normal.
</P>
<P>
   In summary you have had, over the past three years, episodes of
atrial fibrillation, treated for the past year-and-one-half with
Procan, during which time you had only two short episodes, which
spontaneously reverted to regular rhythm. You have been evaluated
and found to have no structural heart disease. When you have atrial
fibrillation, you note an irregular heart beat but have no other
symptoms. Thus, this rhythm does not, in any way, interfere with
your ability to function. Other than the arrhythmia you have no
other health issues.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years you have enjoyed maintaining a high level of
physical conditioning, which I would encourage you to continue.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
