u a BC-OBIT-TUCCI-NYT &LR;      12-10 1014
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-TUCCI-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NICCOLO TUCCI, 91, AUTHOR WHO WROTE OF CHILDHOOD  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Italy, Russia, Mass., Calif.)   By DINITIA SMITH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Niccolo Tucci, an author best known for his
autobiographical fiction evoking a European childhood and a
wonderful and monstrous Russian grandmother, died Friday at his
home in Manhattan. He was 91.
</P>
<P>
   Tucci, the author of four books in English and three in Italian,
was a colorful, romantic figure with somewhat long hair, a silk
foulard and handmade suits from Huntsman &AMP; Sons of London.
</P>
<P>
   ``He does resemble an actor,'' his friend Mary McCarthy wrote in
an introduction to Tucci's book ``The Rain Came Last and Other
Stories.'' ``But he is also an opera singer, a conductor, a painter
of the old school. In any case, a maestro, a virtuoso.'' For many
years he was also a contributor to The New Yorker.
</P>
<P>
   In his writing Tucci tried to recapture the lost world of
childhood, and a lost patrimony. He was born in Lugano,
Switzerland, in 1908. His father, Leonardo, was a doctor. His
mother, Mary, came from a Russian banking family that had lost its
fortune during the Bolshevik Revolution. His parents, Tucci once
wrote, were ``fit to have children, not to tend them.''
</P>
<P>
   When he was a child, the family moved to a home outside Florence
where Tucci received his early education. He was, he said,
``precociously illiterate.'' Initially, he wanted to be a
psychiatrist, but his father wanted him to study law. He managed to
learn six languages and spent a year in 1931 at Amherst College as
an exchange student.
</P>
<P>
   He enrolled in a doctoral program at the University of
California at Berkeley, but he was, he said, converted to Fascism
by the writings of Giovanni Gentile and he returned to Italy.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually he received a doctorate in political science from the
University of Florence, writing a thesis in defense of Mussolini's
doctrine, and then worked for Mussolini's propaganda ministry,
becoming head of a German-language radio station. He translated
Mussolini's speeches into German, and was rebuked in 1936 because
he had altered one of the texts.
</P>
<P>
   In 1937 Tucci traveled to New York as ``a Fascist
propagandist,'' as he put it, and lectured on Dante for the
Italy-American Society. He became disillusioned with Fascism and
moved to New York permanently in 1938 with his wife, Laura Rusconi,
and their infant son, Vieri. The family settled on Cabrini
Boulevard in Washington Heights, and Tucci devoted himself to
anti-Fascist propaganda, translating and ghostwriting.
</P>
<P>
   In 1941 Tucci took a job in Washington working on Latin American
policy for Nelson Rockefeller and writing anti-Fascist articles.
But he was disappointed by American politics, too, and left
Washington. He later wrote of his disenchantment in the
anarchist-leaning magazine ``Politics,'' edited by Dwight
Macdonald.
</P>
<P>
   When Tucci applied for naturalization as an American citizen, he
was turned down because of his early Fascist sympathies and because
of his leftist political views. The historian Gaetano Salvemini
drew attention to his case, and after an eight-year lawsuit,
citizenship was granted in 1953 in a decision by Judge Jerome Frank
of the Circuit Court of New York, who called Tucci ``a greater
friend of Plato than of himself.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1962 Tucci published his first novel in English, ``Before My
Time.'' ``I was born before my time,'' he wrote. ``When my time
came, the place was occupied by someone else; all the good things
of life for which I was now fit had suddenly become unfit. It was
always too early or too late.''
</P>
<P>
   At the center of the book is Tucci's Russian grandmother, known
as Grossmamachen, the tyrannical matriarch of a Russian family.
Portrayed by Tucci as both life-giver and destroyer, she travels
with an extensive entourage of servants, including a French
master-chef, a German butler, an administrator and her family
portraits and icons.
</P>
<P>
   Helene Cantarella, writing in The New York Times, said ``After a
brilliant first chapter which pinpoints with deft if uncharitable
wit its cast of characters, the book unfolds with almost Proustian
involution.'' She called the novel a ``genuine spellbinder.''
</P>
<P>
   Next came Tucci's ``Unfinished Funeral,'' the story of a
matriarch named Ermelinda, Duchess of Combon de Triton, Countess of
Villa Deati, who ensnares her family in a web of emotional guilt.
</P>
<P>
   In 1971 ``The Sun and the Moon,'' a semi-autobiographical work
about his parents' courtship and marriage, was published. In that
book, Tucci's father is nearly driven mad by his mother-in-law's
ways. All three books were edited by Tucci's son-in-law, Robert
Gottlieb, who was an editor at Simon &AMP; Schuster and Alfred A.
Knopf.
</P>
<P>
   ``He insisted I marry his editor,'' the writer's daughter, the
actress Maria Tucci, said Friday. The books have been reissued by
Moyer Bell Ltd.
</P>
<P>
   Tucci also recounted his childhood years and those of his own
children in his short stories for The New Yorker, which is how
Gottlieb came to know his future wife, called Bimba in the stories.
Along with stories and books, Tucci wrote a play, ``Posterity for
Sale,'' which was produced at the American Place Theater in 1967.
</P>
<P>
   Tucci's wife died in 1989. In addition to his son and daughter,
he is survived by two grandchildren and his companion, Deborah
Pease, all of New York.
</P>
<P>
   Tucci won the prestigious Viareggio prize for his collection of
stories ``Il Segreto'' (``The Secret''), which were written in
Italian. But when he was asked to list his awards for the
Contemporary Authors series, he refused to name the conventional
sort. Instead he gave as his ``honors' ``A letter from James Joyce
in 1924, praising me for my Italian fairy tales, a letter from E.B.
White to William Shawn in 1956, saying: ``One Tucci piece a year,
and The New Yorker is in the clear.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``First learn to write as if you were already dead,'' Tucci once
wrote in a piece of advice to young writers, ``and then you will
discover that you can write as if you were still alive.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-10-99 2247EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991210.0366 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-10 22:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5708 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-XEROX-EARNINGS-NYT &LR;      12-10 0690
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-XEROX-EARNINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
XEROX ANNOUNCES 4TH QUARTER EARNINGS WILL BE 40 PERCENT LOWER THAN
EXPECTED  
</HEADLINE>
  (mcd) 
 By DAVID LEONHARDT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Xerox Corp. stunned investors Friday by announcing
after the market closed that its fourth-quarter earnings would be
about 40 percent lower than analysts had expected.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Xerox closed at $24.6875 but skidded almost 20 percent
to as low as $19.875 in after-hours trading.
</P>
<P>
   The company's chief executive, G. Richard Thoman, blamed the
disappointment on a range of problems, including Year 200 computer
fears that have caused customers to suspend capital investments, an
internal reorganization that Xerox has struggled with and economic
troubles in Brazil. The combination, he told analysts Friday, ``has
surprised us.''
</P>
<P>
   More broadly, the announcement by the company, which is based in
Stamford, Conn., raises concerns about Xerox's attempt to transform
itself from a company making freestanding copiers into one that
sells digital printers connected to computer networks. Doing so
requires that Xerox reorganize to focus more on service and
outsourcing and that it compete against both longtime rivals like
Canon _ which is now doing well _ and new ones like
Hewlett-Packard.
</P>
<P>
   So far, observers said, the company has failed to accomplish
everything at once.
</P>
<P>
   ``It obviously seems like there are some very severe problems
within the company,'' said Benjamin A. Reitzes, an analyst at
PaineWebber. Over the last year, Xerox's shares have lost more than
two-thirds of their value, falling from a high of $63.9375 on May
3.
</P>
<P>
   Friday's announcement comes on the heels of a poor third quarter
in which Xerox's net profits declined by 11 percent, to $339
million, and analysts lowered their expectations for fourth-quarter
earnings to 66 cents a share, from an original high of 92 cents.
Thoman now thinks the company will earn closer to 40 cents per
share in the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   In recent months, Reitzes said, ``Every problem seems to have
gotten worse.''
</P>
<P>
   The trouble is not likely to end with this century, either.
``The first quarter won't be a lot better than what we now see,''
Thoman said, noting that many of the problems will linger. He
added, however, that Xerox's profits should start to recover in the
second quarter and continue to do so throughout 2000.
</P>
<P>
   By their very nature, Year 2000 worries will soon end. Many
economists believe Brazil will begin to recover as well, and Thoman
said the company's reorganized structure will soon begin to
overcome its initial problems.
</P>
<P>
   But analysts seemed unwilling to give Thoman and his management
much benefit of the doubt. During Friday's conference call,
analysts chastised Thoman for not coming clean about Xerox's
problems sooner, wondered whether the future would hold more
unpleasant surprises and complained that he does not talk to Wall
Street often enough.
</P>
<P>
   Thoman took over the top job in April, after leaving IBM in 1997
to become Xerox's heir apparent to Paul A. Allaire, its chairman.
</P>
<P>
   About 20 percent of the earnings shortfall will come from
higher-than-expected costs from the company's consolidation of its
36 administrative centers into just three, Thoman said. Because
Xerox did not dedicate enough people to handling the change, sales
people _ who are also in the midst of their own shift from covering
a geographic area to covering specific industries _ have spent too
much time dealing with internal matters.
</P>
<P>
   Xerox is now making ``a full-court press'' to fix the
administrative problems, Thoman said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the company is trying to shift toward
businesses that are growing by at least 10 percent a year, such as
the outsourcing of managing documents. Twenty-five percent of
Xerox's revenue now comes from such industries; by the end of 2000,
the portion should rise to 45 percent, the company said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the problems, Thoman said Xerox had little choice but to
attempt such wide-ranging changes. ``The market is moving
quickly,'' he told analysts. ``Customers are not going to wait for
us.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
