</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-YUGO-AID-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHINA TO GIVE YUGOSLAVIA MONEY FOR RECONSTRUCTION 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By CARLOTTA GALL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELGRADE, Yugoslavia _ China has signed a deal to advance the
Belgrade government about $300 million in cash and credits to aid
the reconstruction of Yugoslavia after the NATO bombing this year,
according to Yugoslav officials.
</P>
<P>
   They said that the agreement was reached last week and that the
money would be spent on rebuilding and on buying electricity.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond helping the staggering economy, the Chinese decision was
welcomed here as a sign of international support for Belgrade and
defiance of Western efforts to isolate the government of President
Slobodan Milosevic, which has been under sanctions since 1992.
</P>
<P>
   China has frequently sided with Serbia in its dispute with the
West, and it opposed the NATO bombing, particularly after the
Chinese Embassy in Belgrade had been severely damaged by NATO
missiles and three of its citizens had been killed.
</P>
<P>
   Newspapers here quoted government officials as saying the
Chinese agreed to offer the money after having taken a 10-day trip
to see the bomb damage and on the condition that it be used solely
for reconstruction.
</P>
<P>
   The $300 million will double Yugoslavia's foreign currency
reserves, said Mladjan Dinkic, chief coordinator for the opposition
G-17 group of independent economists. He suggested that the
government could also use the money to prop up the Yugoslav dinar,
which fell again this week, as well as to pay for electricity from
Slovakia.
</P>
<P>
   Belgrade is showing signs of being desperately short of foreign
currency. Imports have shrunk, and lines for basic staples like
milk and cooking oil are an everyday sight. The dinar trades on the
black market for one-third its official exchange rate.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
