<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-10 22:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5711 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-WALMART-AOL-NYT &LR;      12-10 0661
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WALMART-AOL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMERICA ONLINE AND WAL-MART IN TALKS TO CREATE MARKET ALLIANCE,
REPORT SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mcd) 
 By LESLIE KAUFMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The world's biggest retailer and the nation's top Internet
access provider are in talks about forming a far-reaching alliance
to market each others' products and services, according to people
who have been briefed on the discussions.
</P>
<P>
   Wal-Mart Stores, which is scheduled to introduce its redesigned
Web site in January, is looking for a partner that could send a
steady stream of traffic to bolster what has been a disappointing
trial on the Web, these people said. America Online, meanwhile,
sees in Wal-Mart access to a large pool of potential users for its
Web service, and a big stream of revenue if the retailer grows to
dominate the Web as it dominates conventional retailing. The terms
of the plan are sketchy, and both companies declined to comment
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Speculation about such a deal has gained currency for about a
month, but after a prominent stock analyst predicted Friday morning
that an announcement was imminent, stocks of both companies rose to
52-week highs.
</P>
<P>
   One possible wrench in the deal is Microsoft, whose MSN access
service is a competitor to American Online and is still pursuing
Wal-Mart, according to one of those who had been briefed. America
Online and MSN competed head-to-head for a smaller contract with
Tandy Corp., which owns Radio Shack shops.
</P>
<P>
   The issuer of Friday's report, Richard L. Church, a stock
analyst with Salomon Smith Barney, suggested two possibilities. The
first is a simple cross-promotion deal in which America Online,
which has roughly 20 million subscribers, advertises Wal-Mart's
products on its site and, in return, Wal-Mart promotes AOL's
service at kiosks in its 2,465 stores. Wal-Mart is experimenting
with kiosks in several locations.
</P>
<P>
   The other possibility, confirmed by people briefed on the talks,
is a broader deal under which AOL would develop an Internet service
brand with Wal-Mart using the Wal-Mart name. Wal-Mart could even
offer a low-cost computer that would allow users access to the
Internet but not perform other functions.
</P>
<P>
   Wal-Mart stores attract some 100 milion consumers a week, with
an average family income of approximately $25,000. This is a large
pool of people, many of whom do not have online serivce and could
be looking for a service provider. Presumably, a Wal-Mart branded
site, with America Online handling the back end, would be ideally
positioned to gain the trust and business of such consumers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The significance of this announcement is that Internet
penetration, particularly in the mass market, could increase
significantly,'' Church wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Burt Flickinger III, the managing director of Reach Marketing,
expects an arrangement to emerge in which Wal-Mart becomes a
branded Internet service provider. Along with gaining access to
Wal-Mart's customers through such a portal and through the stores,
he said, America Online might gain access to the retailer's
extensive credit card databases.
</P>
<P>
   Several recent deals between Internet service providers and
retailers provide an example of what the Wal-Mart partnership might
look like, though the analysts indicated that these arrangements
were far smaller than the one being discussed by America Online and
Wal-Mart.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, the giant electronics retailer Circuit City
announced that it would give consumers $400 toward the purchase of
any products in return for signing up with Compuserve, an AOL
brand, for three years. The service costs $21.95 a month, and at
the end of three years the total cost would be $790.20.
</P>
<P>
   The Tandy agreement with Microsoft, which won out over America
Online, provides for Microsoft to set up boutiques in Radio Shack's
700 stores to promote its MSN service. In return, the software
company will provide $100 million to help the electronics retailer
build its Web presence.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
