<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
 (HLW)
</HEADLINE>
  c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NASDAQ COMPOSITE INDEX REACHES YET ANOTHER HIGH
</P>
<P>
   Technology stocks rallied to send the Nasdaq composite index to
another high, its fifth since Thanksgiving. The index rose 26.06
points, or 0.73 percent, to 3,620.23. The Dow Jones industrial
average, increased 89.91 points, or 0.81 percent, to 11,224.70, and
the Standard &AMP; Poor's index of 500 stocks, climbed 8.93 points, or
0.63 percent, to 1,417.04.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of FreeMarkets, an online auctioneer for industrial
products, jumped 483 percent from its initial price of $48, to
$280, on its first day of trading. This was just a day after the
price of VA Linux Systems had an eightfold increase, setting the
record for the first day of trading of an initial public offering.
</P>
<P>
   TELEPHONE MERGER TALKS IN JAPAN
</P>
<P>
   KDD, Japan's largest international telephone service company,
said it was in talks with its faltering competitor DDI, and IDO, a
cellular phone operator, over a possible merger that would create
Japan's second-largest telephone company and intensify the
realignment of the country's telecommunications industry.
</P>
<P>
   HIGHER DAY-TRADING MARGINS SOUGHT
</P>
<P>
   Responding to concerns raised by stock clearing firms and
regulators, the New York Stock Exchange and the National
Association of Securities Dealers said they had approved proposals
to raise margin requirements for day traders to $25,000 from
$2,000.
</P>
<P>
   WHOLESALE INFLATION REMAINS TAME
</P>
<P>
   Inflation at the wholesale level edged up 0.1 percent in
November, pushed higher by the biggest jump in natural gas prices
in two years, the Labor Department said in its monthly report on
producer prices.
</P>
<P>
   LAWSUITS A CLICK AWAY ON INTERNET
</P>
<P>
   Internet sites are sending users to other sites in record
numbers because they earn commissions if any of their users click
on them and then buy something. But this week those sites suddenly
found themselves at risk of violating a patent just granted to a
New York company, LinkShare. That patent gives LinkShare the right
to block anyone from using such an arrangement. LinkShare will not
say how it plans to enforce its patent rights. And in recent months
a number of other Internet companies have filed patent-related
lawsuits on other matters. Jerry Yang, the co-founder of Yahoo,
said: ``People are getting patents on things that are too general.
It's not healthy for patents to be used to stop other people from
doing business.''
</P>
<P>
   AOL'S BRAZILIAN OUTLOOK CLOUDED
</P>
<P>
   America Online seemed to have a promising start in Brazil with
customers there logging more Internet time than expected. But then
the president of AOL Brazil resigned amid differences with other
executives. And consumer protection authorities are reported to be
weighing the possibility of fining America Online as much as 3
million reais, or about $1.4 million, after numerous complaints
over the alteration of online browsing systems by the company's
installation software. Both of these moves have clouded the outlook
for the company in Brazil.
</P>
<P>
   JOHN HANCOCK SETS OFFERING PRICE
</P>
<P>
   John Hancock Financial Services, the insurance and investment
services company, set its initial public offering at 102 million
shares to sell for $15 to $25 each. This will raise $1.9 billion
after expenses for the Boston-based concern, which recently won
approval to convert to a stock company from a policyholder-owned
entity. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SHARES OF FRANCE TELECOM TUMBLE
</P>
<P>
   Shares of France Telecom fell 8 percent after the company's
expansion plans in Germany's profitable wireless phone market were
thwarted by a competing bid for the German cell phone provider
E-Plus Mobilfunk. The rival bid was a joint offer from BellSouth
and the Dutch phone company Royal KPN.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-10-99 2251EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
