u a BC-NY-BABY-LEFTALONE-NYT     12-10 0844
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-BABY-LEFTALONE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOTHER WHO LEFT BABY OUTSIDE IS PUT ON DEFENSIVE IN COURT 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By BENJAMIN WEISER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Two years ago, when a woman was arrested for leaving
her baby daughter outside a Manhattan restaurant while she had a
drink inside, she set off a trans-Atlantic debate about proper
parenting by contending that such behavior was accepted in her
native Denmark.
</P>
<P>
   The charges were dropped, and the woman, Anette Sorensen, later
filed a civil rights lawsuit against New York City over her arrest.
Friday, in a stormy court session, she found herself on the
defensive as she explained her actions. In the climax of a weeklong
trial, Ms. Sorensen, 32, told a jury she had always been able to
see her daughter, Liv, through a restaurant window as the baby
slept on that night in May 1997.
</P>
<P>
   But she said that she had gone into the restaurant in the East
Village with the baby's father for a drink because it was too
chilly. They left the baby asleep and bundled her up in blankets in
the stroller just outside.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Sorensen, weeping at times, testified in federal district
court in Manhattan that she felt only despair after being arrested,
separated from Liv, then taken to a jail cell and strip-searched.
``It's the worst thing I ever experienced,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   In a blistering cross-examination, a lawyer for New York City
contended that Ms. Sorensen had been drunk that night, that the
baby's father had been belligerent toward the police, and that both
had neglected the child.
</P>
<P>
   The city's lawyer, Patricia Miller, asked, ``Isn't it a fact
that a waiter came up to your table and told you it was too cold
for the baby to be outside?''
</P>
<P>
   ``That is not correct,'' Ms. Sorensen said.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Miller persisted. ``Isn't it a fact that a waiter came up to
you and told you that it was too noisy in the restaurant for you to
hear your baby outside?''
</P>
<P>
   Again, the woman said no.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Sorensen and the baby's father, Exavier Wardlaw, a
playwright from Brooklyn, are each seeking tens of millions of
dollars from the city for its handling of the incident, which began
when a restaurant patron called 911 after seeing the child
unattended.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the trial, Ms. Sorensen's lawyer, Michael Q. Carey,
has tried to elicit testimony supporting the notion that his
client's decision to leave her child asleep in the stroller
outside, which might have seemed foolish to a New Yorker, was
perfectly acceptable conduct in Ms. Sorensen's homeland.
</P>
<P>
   ``I assume you are not familiar with the customs in Denmark,''
Carey told the jury on Monday. During the week, there was testimony
from a police officer that Ms. Sorensen had mentioned the Danish
custom to the police at the time of her arrest.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for the city have challenged this notion at every turn,
noting that Ms. Sorensen had spent a great deal of time in New York
in a series of visits, and that Wardlaw, 52, is a citizen of the
United States and a longtime resident of New York.
</P>
<P>
   When Carey asked Ms. Sorensen Friday to comment on the custom
``in Denmark with respect to leaving children outdoors to sleep in
a carriage,'' the city objected and Judge Harold Baer Jr. blocked
her from answering, saying the issue had been dealt with enough.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Ms. Sorensen nor Wardlaw would comment outside the court
about the case, which is expected to go to the jury on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   In her testimony, Ms. Sorensen tried to recreate the trauma she
said she felt on the evening of her arrest and in the following
four days of separation from Liv, who was 14 months old and placed
briefly in foster care by the city.
</P>
<P>
   But Ms. Miller tried to undermine Ms. Sorensen's account,
suggesting in her questions that the mother had been more
interested in talking with reporters after her release than in
checking on her baby. At one point, Ms. Miller cited earlier
statements by Ms. Sorensen that she took Liv out in the stroller
``because otherwise I couldn't go anywhere. I had to be home every
night.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Miller also showed the jury a large goblet, saying it was
like the one Ms. Sorensen drank from that night in the East Village
restaurant, the Dallas BBQ on Second Avenue near St. Marks Place.
Ms. Sorensen had testified that she and Wardlaw had each had a
margarita and a shot of tequila there and had earlier had
margaritas at a cafe.
</P>
<P>
   ``Isn't it a fact,'' Ms. Miller asked, ``that on May 10, 1997,
by the time the police officers arrived at the Dallas BBQ, you were
drunk?''
</P>
<P>
   ``No, that is not correct,'' Ms. Sorensen replied, looking
shaken.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Sorensen, responding to questions from her own lawyer, said
she was a good mother and had been extremely worried about the
effect of the incident on Liv, who is now almost 4.
</P>
<P>
   A psychologist had advised her to talk about it with the child,
she told the jury, and she did, as if she were telling her a fairy
tale about a princess. She said she kept the stories ``very
short.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was good,'' she said. ``I have done that several times.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
