<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-10 22:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5717 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-FLA-AFFIRMATIVE11-COX     12-10 0452
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLA-AFFIRMATIVE11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Affirmative action will end in 2001, Fla. regents agree
 &HT;    By Stephen Kiehl
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ The end of racial preferences in
university admissions will be phased in over two years, the Board
of Regents decided Friday, and private high schools may be allowed
to take part in the One Florida program.
</P>
<P>
   Racial preferences will not be used in undergraduate admissions
beginning with the fall 2000 freshman class, but the preferences
won't be eliminated from graduate and professional school
admissions until fall 2001, according to a set of rules the regents
unanimously approved in a telephone conference call.
</P>
<P>
   Although it ends affirmative action based on race, Gov. Jeb
Bush's One Florida plan guarantees students in the top 20 percent
of their public high school classes admission to one of the state's
10 universities. On Friday, several regents suggested extending
that guarantee to the top fifth of private and parochial school
students.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're discriminating against students in private high
schools,'' said Regent James Heekin of Orlando.
</P>
<P>
   State University Chancellor Adam Herbert said he would research
the idea and present a recommendation to the board at its Jan. 21
meeting, when the regents will give final approval to Bush's plan.
</P>
<P>
   Herbert said, however, that it is probably too late to include
private schools for fall 2000 implementation. The chancellor also
suggested the racial makeup of private schools may not help reach
the One Florida goal of bringing more minorities into state
universities.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to make sure we don't do something inadvertently that
would make it more difficult to achieve diversity,'' Herbert said.
</P>
<P>
   He says the plan would bring an additional 400 minorities into
state colleges and it would allow admissions officers to look at
race-correlated factors _ such as the hometowns, high schools and
economic status of applicants _ when admitting students to preserve
diversity. Also Friday, Herbert said he is considering waiving the
additional tuition paid by graduate students from outside Florida.
A significant number of minorities in state graduate schools come
from out of state, and giving them an additional incentive to come
to Florida may help diversity efforts, Herbert said.
</P>
<P>
   The cost would be $16.4 million a year.
</P>
<P>
   Concerns have been raised that One Florida would reduce the
number of blacks and Hispanics in graduate and professional
schools. Implementation was put off for a year in part to give
universities time to come up with alternatives to racial
preferences.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
