<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-10 22:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5718 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-BKN-KNICKS-SIXERS-NYT     12-10 0962
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-SIXERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EWING HAS WINNING RETURN, AS KNICKS DEFEAT SIXERS 85-78  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Just as the buzz in the building was building in
anticipation, just after Latrell Sprewell went crashing into bodies
along the gantlet of Knicks upon his introduction, out walked a
solemn Patrick Ewing Friday night, bathed in a raucous ovation at
Madison Square Garden.
</P>
<P>
   He was back. Ewing walked out to join the circle of Knicks as
the starting center for the first time since June 1. He was focused
and unfazed by the deafening cheers.
</P>
<P>
   All the controversy surrounding Ewing _ from his standoffish
behavior with teammates to the $20,000 in fines he collected for
his inaccessibility with the news media this week _ was blocked out
by the Knicks' 37-year-old superstar. It was time to play.
</P>
<P>
   Play he did, although not to great effect, scoring seven points,
all from the foul line, and grabbing 10 rebounds in an 85-78 Knicks
victory over the Philadelphia 76ers.
</P>
<P>
   It was a performance that bordered on clumsy _ as in a wild
turn-around jumper against a double team that missed by 2 feet high
off the glass _ but it did not lack for effort.
</P>
<P>
   After Friday night's tip-off, the euphoria of the opening
moments soon evaporated and Ewing was left for inspection. How
would he blend in with Sprewell and Allan Houston? How much could
be expected? Would he try too hard to be the old Ewing?
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope he does well,'' Van Gundy said before the game, even as
Ewing fell back into his pregame routine, headphones on his head,
not saying a word as he bounced a basketball on the blue carpet in
the locker room. ``He deserves to do well. I hope he has immediate
success but the coach in me knows that's going to be very
difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   The seven months without real-game action showed in Ewing's
languid reactions, oxygen-deprived gasps and somewhat pedestrian
defense as the game wore on. But considering his layoff and the
string of injuries that left him to play in just 79 of the team's
last 182 games, Ewing did a decent job. He struggled, but had some
contributing moments on the floor in some early defensive stands.
</P>
<P>
   His teammates, for the most part, were not daunted by Ewing's
presence _ especially Sprewell. He sizzled along at his own pace,
and scored 20 of his 31 points in the first half. The only Knick
who seemed unsettled on the night was Houston, who shot 3 for 15
and finished with six points. The Knick with the most minutes to
lose upon Ewing's return, Marcus Camby, had spurts in which he took
over the game when Ewing went to the bench.
</P>
<P>
   But nothing happened Friday night to put an end to the questions
surrounding Ewing's estranged demeanor around the team this season.
Throughar, he has appeared angry at the organization, seemed
to feel unappreciated by his teammates and grumbled at members of
the team for commenting on his progress in returning from an
injury.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there is a lot of underlying tension,'' Van Gundy said
before the game. ``Some of it we created ourselves, some
externally.''
</P>
<P>
   The issues are not past. With Ewing's return, inherent problems
tag right along. The more Ewing gets comfortable with his game, the
more minutes he will play and the bigger the squeeze placed on the
players who stepped into his place when he partly tore his
Achilles' tendon on June 1 during Game 2 of the Eastern Conference
finals.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, Camby.
</P>
<P>
   Camby was the force Indiana coach Larry Bird called the most
valuable player of the series when the Knicks eliminated the Pacers
and advanced to the league finals last season. With injuries to
Larry Johnson and then Ewing, Camby was the X factor throughout the
playoffs, finally getting his chance after weathering limited
minutes and a strained relationship with Van Gundy.
</P>
<P>
   Now with Ewing back on the floor, Camby wonders once again what
his place is on the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to know,'' Camby said before the game. ``Guys are
coming back off injuries and coming into the starting lineup. I got
hurt, came back and played, and I'm coming off the bench. Minutes
are going to be scarce. It's all about sacrifice. I just want to
play.''
</P>
<P>
   He'll take any position, from small forward to center. Camby was
asked if there was a chance that Van Gundy would go big up front
and play him next to Ewing for heavy minutes. It's a theory that
has been batted around.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jeff said the same thing about the big guards in the backcourt
in the past,'' Camby said. ``And it never happened.''
</P>
<P>
   There was an obvious tone of irritation in Camby's voice, and he
acknowledged that the unknown bothered him.
</P>
<P>
   ``A little bit,'' Camby said. ``Just have to see how it all
works out. Yeah, Patrick deserves the benefit of the doubt for what
he's done for the organization. I don't know how it's all going to
pan out. It remains to be seen. I never want to rehash what went on
last year. I want to play.''
</P>
<P>
   Ewing's arrival has not been easy on anyone, including his
coach. Van Gundy has had to step delicately around Ewing, let him
make his decision to return in his own time and still tend to the
egos on the rest of the team. After 11 years with Ewing, Van Gundy
does not see a high-maintenance superstar who has been unresponsive
to the media. He sees a player who wonders when he is ever going to
get the respect he deserves.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is private,'' Van Gundy said. ``I don't think there is any
doubt. I just think he believes that the scrutiny about his role
and how he affects the team has been unfair and that very few other
great players have had their value to the team questioned as much
as he has. He is a great, great player and wants to be treated with
respect, and he deserves that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-10-99 2256EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
