<HEADLINE>
PLANE WAS OFF COURSE BEFORE FATAL CRASH 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Va.) (lh) 
 By ROBERT HANLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HASBROUCK HEIGHTS, N.J. _ The twin-engine plane that plunged
into a backyard here Thursday evening, killing its pilot and three
passengers, was off course and approaching Teterboro Airport from
the wrong direction when it crashed, a federal investigator said
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pilot was not following the instructions of the air
traffic controller,'' said Robert Hancock, the National
Transportation Safety Board's lead investigator in the crash. ``He
was not where he was supposed to have been. He was coming at the
runway from the opposite side.''
</P>
<P>
   Why the plane was off course, in generally clear weather, is
still unclear, Hancock said. ``He was given instruction,'' he said
of the pilot, who was flying into Teterboro from a small airport in
Virginia. ``The question is why that was not followed.'' Officials
said they were looking into a number of possible causes for the
crash, including a mechanical failure.
</P>
<P>
   During the pilot's approach to Teterboro, which is about a mile
east of the densely populated neighborhood where the crash
occurred, the pilot did not mention any problems with the plane or
its instruments to controllers, Hancock said.
</P>
<P>
   And, he added, the pilot did not suggest that he was puzzled by
the landing instructions from the air traffic controller. Hancock
said the pilot did not make any radio calls of distress or
emergency on his approach to Teterboro and did not exhibit any
``elevated level of concern'' in his last seconds of communication
with the controller.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities said Friday that they had not officially identified
the victims. But friends and family confirmed that they were four
Virginia residents: Paul A. Pedersen Jr., 37, a pilot and the
president of the Virginia aviation company that used the plane for
charter flights; Elaine Moses, 35, the company's office manager;
Chip Brierre, 41, and Cary Brierre, 40, a couple from Richmond, Va.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Aviation Administration said Friday it was unable to
confirm that the plane, a six-passenger Beech Baron 58TC, was being
flown by Pedersen, who was the president of Sundance Aviation Co.,
an air charter company that operates the Hanover County Airport in
Ashland, Va.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the agency, James Peters, reported that the FAA
suspended Pedersen's pilot's license for 45 days in late 1997 after
a plane he was flying on Oct. 18, 1996, ran out of fuel and
crash-landed at night in Pasadena, Md. Pedersen suffered minor
injuries in that crash.
</P>
<P>
   The plane involved in that incident, a Cessna 310Q, was flying a
cargo of film from Virginia to Baltimore-Washington International
Airport, the FAA said.
</P>
<P>
   After an investigation, the safety board said the probable cause
of the 1996 crash was Pedersen's inadequate preflight planning and
inadequate management of the plane's fuel supply. In suspending
Pedersen's license, the FAA cited him for four violations,
including carelessly operating the plane and not having enough fuel
to fly to an alternate destination.
</P>
<P>
   Hancock said there was no indication the plane that crashed here
about 5:30 p.m. Thursday had run out of fuel. He said there was an
odor of aviation fuel at the crash site, and he pointed out that
the plane burned for several minutes after the crash and then
exploded.
</P>
<P>
   The plane had left Hanover County Airport about 4 p.m. for the
90-minute flight to Teterboro. Hancock said there was nothing out
of the ordinary with the flight.
</P>
<P>
   As the plane approached Teterboro from the west, the controller
instructed the pilot to fly over the airport at 1,500 feet and
then, when east of the airport, to make a left turn to the north
and, a bit later, another left turn to approach Runway 19.
</P>
<P>
   The plane never flew over the airport, Hancock said. Instead, he
said, the pilot started approaching Runway 19 from the northwest
and started to make a right turn toward the runway. Hancock said
the controller repeated the instructions to fly over the airport.
Moments later, he said, apparently in response to that instruction,
the pilot made a very abrupt left turn, apparently to loop around
and approach the airport again from the west.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after that turn, the plane crashed. Hancock said his
staff would study radar data to determine the plane's altitude when
it made the sharp left turn.
</P>
<P>
   National safety board technicians began examining the plane's
two engines Friday for any signs of malfunction. Other than the
engines and their propellers, the tips of each wing, both tires and
a piece of the tail assembly, little of the plane's wreckage
remained after the intense fire, Hancock said.
</P>
<P>
   The crash also injured three people on the ground and set a
garage on fire. Before it crashed, the plane clipped the side of a
house at 18 Central Ave., then exploded next to two large oak trees
in the backyard of the house behind it, at 21 Washington Place.
</P>
<P>
   Nancy Riordan, who lives at 17 Washington Place, said she
thought the trees had stopped the plane from slamming into her
home.
</P>
<P>
   ``We complain about all the leaves when they come down in the
fall, but if those trees weren't there ...'' Mrs. Riordan said, her
voice trailing off. ``They probably saved our lives. It was
horrible for the people on the plane. But God was looking over us.
This was our blessing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
