<HEADLINE>
DOCTOR FAULTS STUDY SHOWING THAT THOUSANDS DIE FROM MEDICAL
MISTAKES 
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-BUSINESS-KAN   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY HEASTER  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. -- A Kansas City area physician says recent
claims that hospital medical errors kill 44,000 to 98,000 patients
a year is the result of suspect research.
</P>
<P>
   James Ruhlen, an internist practicing in Olathe, Kan., since
1975, related in a recent letter how the figures were so at odds
with his own experience he decided to review the research.
</P>
<P>
   The Institute of Medicine report attributed massive numbers of
deaths to medical malpractice, which has prompted the National
Academy of Sciences to urge creation of a federal agency to monitor
medical safety.
</P>
<P>
   One of the institute's most puzzling charges was that health
care is significantly behind other high-risk industries in its
attention to safety issues. For most who have had recent experience
with America's health-care system, this revelation must certainly
have been as shocking as it was surprising. The occasional
anecdotal horror story aside, the general level of safety in the
U.S. health-care system has been widely perceived as the standard
by which systems throughout the world are measured.
</P>
<P>
   Meantime, as a matter of fairness, it also seems anyone trying
to quantify malpractice deaths should also try to quantify lives
saved. It's possible, after all, that physicians in the U.S. are
victims of too much success. Life-saving procedures considered
miracles a generation ago have become routine. Americans are living
longer lives of higher quality because physicians and their
hospital support staffs are better trained and their equipment is
more advanced.
</P>
<P>
   Ruhlen criticizes the two studies as too few and too narrowly
based. Moreover, he says, they weren't based on random selection as
claimed. Therefore, the results appear to be extrapolations from
higher-risk patient samples.
</P>
<P>
   Ruhlen said that because one study selected only 31,000 of a
pool of 2.6 million records, the overweighting of high-risk
patients hugely amplified the potential for the sort of negative
numbers the research produced. In the other study, a similar
exclusion of lower-risk subjects ``tended to enrich the pool for
adverse outcomes.''
</P>
<P>
   What calls the project's motivation into question was the swift
call for creation of more government oversight, particularly the
proposed mandate to report and publicly disclose medical errors.
This may sound reasonable, but it might put physicians in a box
that would diminish the quality of care.
</P>
<P>
   The danger of Big Brother looking over everyone's shoulder is
how it would further encourage defensive medicine of the sort that
proliferating lawsuits already promote. The less willing physicians
are to treat serious ailments aggressively, the more such
reluctance might be to the patient's detriment.
</P>
<P>
   Ruhlen's bottom-line contention is that the study vastly
overstated the problem because statistics from the Institute of
Medicine itself already showed a 50 percent reduction in
preventable deaths from 1984-92.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Congress does feel a need to do more,'' Ruhlen suggests,
``funding a truly random study of adverse events in hospital
admissions in 2001 might be a good place to start, to see if
another 50 percent reduction in preventable deaths and injuries has
already taken place, as I suspect (any such) study would show.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
