<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEAT-SAFETY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDGE GIVES MEAT PLANT A REPRIEVE FROM CLOSING 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By MARIAN BURROS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   A federal judge in Texas issued a preliminary injunction Friday
prohibiting the Agriculture Department from shutting down a meat
plant that failed inspections, ruling that he needed to decide
whether the government had the authority to enforce new hygienic
standards.
</P>
<P>
   In the ruling, Judge, A. Joe Fish of U.S. District Court in
Dallas, said meat from the plant had not caused any outbreaks of
food poisoning and that if the company was shut down, it would be
out of business.
</P>
<P>
   The decision means inspectors for the government would not be
able to enforce its new food-safety program, which includes
bacterial tests, at the plant and could be forced to return to the
old poke-and-sniff method to detect spoiled meat.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the judge's ruling, the agency said it would continue to
enforce the new standards in other plants.
</P>
<P>
   But Caroline Smith DeWaal, director of food safety for the
Center for Science in the Public Interest, a consumer advocacy
group in Washington that filed a brief supporting the government,
said: ``This is a devastating setback for the new meat and poultry
program, which has shown significant improvement in salmonella
rates. It's unfortunate if one bad actor can ring down such a
successful program.''
</P>
<P>
   Steven F. Spiritas, president and chief executive officer of the
Texas company, Supreme Beef Processors Inc., said he was pleased
with the decision because ``the department had no justification to
take action against our company when we are producing safe and
wholesome meat products.''
</P>
<P>
   Supreme Beef, which until the government's action supplied as
much as 45 percent of the ground beef used in the national school
lunch program, is the only meat processing plant that the
Agriculture Department has tried to close under the new standards.
The plant failed three inspections for salmonella contamination
over 12 months.
</P>
<P>
   An Agriculture Department spokesman, Andrew Solomon, said the
government ``intends to pursue the matter fully because the
science-based food safety inspection system has proven effective.''
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, the Supreme Beef plant in Dallas will continue
to operate with an Agriculture Department seal of approval for
wholesomeness, even though the department says its meat may be
injurious to public health. On Nov. 30 the department tried to
close the plant by withdrawing inspectors, which are legally
required for meat to be sold interstate, after the company had
failed the tests. But Fish issued a temporary restraining order
that day, pending the hearing Friday that resulted in the
injunction.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one thinks that salmonella in meat is a good thing,'' Fish
said. ``The question is whether the Department of Agriculture had
the authority to do what it did.''
</P>
<P>
   The company's slaughtering plant has also failed three
inspections, but the government has not decided if it will try to
close that plant, too. The slaughtering plant supplies one-third of
the beef that is ground at the processing plant.
</P>
<P>
   The new safety program requires companies to adopt the Pathogen
Reduction and Hazard Analysis Critical Control Points method of
inspection. They must identify critical control points in the
production process where contamination is likely to occur and
implement plans to prevent contamination. They are required to
perform microbial tests for the presence of salmonella,
disease-causing bacteria that cause mild to severe gastrointestinal
distress and, in some, even death. The tests for salmonella
contamination are the government's only check to ensure that the
plan is actually controlling food hazards in the plants.
</P>
<P>
   The Centers for Disease Control and Prevention says salmonella
is responsible for nearly 10 percent of illnesses and 30 percent of
deaths cause by food-borne disease. The agency estimates that there
are 553 deaths and 1.3 million illnesses from salmonella.
Statistics from the agency indicate that the level of salmonella
poisoning has been dropping since the new program went into effect.
</P>
<P>
   But in its suit, the company called the testing program
``arbitrary and capricious'' and said the Agriculture Department
lacked authority to regulate salmonella, arguing that because
``salmonella is not an adulterant and because salmonella is
destroyed during normal cooking, the presence of salmonella is not
a public safety issue.''
</P>
<P>
   The national school lunch program canceled its contract with
Supreme Beef on Nov. 30.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
