<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TURKEY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TURKEY WILL JOIN EUROPEAN UNION DESPITE STRINGS ATTACHED TO THE
INVITATION  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By STEPHEN KINZER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ISTANBUL _ With neither side sure what lies ahead, Turkey shook
Europe's outstretched hand Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can tell you that your country is a candidate member of the
European Union,'' a smiling Javier Solana, the European Union
representative for foreign affairs and security, said as he emerged
late Friday night from a meeting with Turkish leaders in Ankara.
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``We are very, very happy, and I think your country is
also very happy.''
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Bulent Ecevit responded to the European offer by
saying, ``There may be details that are hard for us to digest, but
in general the acceptance of our candidacy on equal terms is a
great success for Turkey.''
</P>
<P>
   That might be going too far. Since Turkey and the rest of Europe
have mistrusted each other for centuries, it was perhaps inevitable
that even a gesture of friendship like the one the European Union
offered in Helsinki earlier in the day would be viewed with
suspicion.
</P>
<P>
   By opening the way for Turkey's eventual membership in the
European Union, the European leaders meeting in Helsinki brought
Turkey a step closer to realizing one of its most cherished dreams.
</P>
<P>
   But the conditions that seemed to be attached to the invitation
puzzled some people here. They might require Turkey to change its
approach to contentious issues like Cyprus and contested islands in
the Aegean.
</P>
<P>
   Turks seemed disposed to put the best face on this outcome and
claim it as a victory. Still, there was no jubilation here. What
might have been a moment for triumph and the blossoming of
friendship has turned out to be only semisweet.
</P>
<P>
   After the text of Europe's invitation was made public, there was
a surge of discomfort among Turkish diplomats and politicians. The
Turkish reaction registered in Helsinki, and European leaders
decided to send Solana immediately to Ankara.
</P>
<P>
   His task was to ensure that Ecevit would fly to Helsinki for a
ceremony on Saturday that would formally open the way for Turkey's
possible entrance into the European Union.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton and Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder of Germany,
both of whom visited Turkey last month, telephoned Ecevit Friday to
congratulate him on the European invitation and, not incidentally,
to encourage him to go to Helsinki.
</P>
<P>
   Ecevit agreed.
</P>
<P>
   If Turkish cabinet ministers had any doubts about accepting
Europe's offer, they did not betray them. All seemed relaxed and
jovial as they left a special meeting Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Their tone reflected what seems to be the government's decision:
to accept the European Union's offer and to suppress impulsive
anger at conditions attached to it.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the end it's take it or leave it, and I can't believe
they'll leave it,'' said Soli Ozel, a professor of international
relations at Bilgi University in Istanbul. ``Among other things, it
would be a slap at Clinton. It would be telling him, `You came here
and offered us all these things, but we just will not budge.'''
</P>
<P>
   As distasteful as details of the European offer are to some
Turks, rejecting it would have been even less attractive. Such a
step could widen a deep historic breach that has only begun to
heal.
</P>
<P>
   Many Turks, including senior government leaders, appeared to
share this concern. If they accepted Europe's offer, it might be
not because they liked it, but because they feared the alternative.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-10-99 2341EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
