<HEADER>
A5841 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-WORLD-BRIEFS-NYT &LR;      12-10 0849
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORLD-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   VATICAN: IRAQ CALLS OFF PAPAL VISIT
</P>
<P>
   In a major setback to Pope John Paul II's plans for the
millennium, the Vatican said a papal visit to the city of Ur,
believed to be Abraham's birthplace, had been called off by Iraq.
The Vatican could not reach an agreement over a visit that the
Pope, 79, viewed as a pilgrimage but that was fraught with
political overtones for Saddam Hussein, and also for Washington.
The United States lobbied against the visit, fearing it could lend
legitimacy to the Iraqi government.
</P>
<P>
   ITALY: RAMP WORK TO CONTINUE
</P>
<P>
   Overriding concerns that archeological ruins could be destroyed,
the government announced it would go ahead with a ramp to a Vatican
parking lot that was halted after workers stumbled on ancient Roman
frescoes. The ramp is not expected to be finished in time for
Vatican millennium celebrations on Christmas Eve. City officials
say it may be ready for Easter.
</P>
<P>
   NORTHERN IRELAND: OPTIMISM ON ARMS
</P>
<P>
   After a meeting with the Ulster Freedom Fighters, the main
Protestant rebel group, a Canadian general overseeing disarmament
efforts expressed optimism that guerrillas would begin handing in
their weapons. Gen. John de Chastelain, who has met with the IRA,
said the rebels should set a disarmament timetable but that, if
necessary, the commission he heads would propose a schedule.
</P>
<P>
   NORTHERN IRELAND: CALL FOR INQUIRY
</P>
<P>
   Six rights groups, including Amnesty International, called for
an independent inquiry into the car-bomb killing in March of
Rosemary Nelson, a lawyer known for defending Irish republicans.
The groups said the mainly Protestant Ulster police failed to
protect her and said Britain bore some responsibility. The Northern
Ireland secretary, Peter Mandelson, said the killing was being
investigated and that he was confident British authorities would be
exonerated.
</P>
<P>
   SPAIN: BASQUE EXTRADITION SOUGHT
</P>
<P>
   Spain said it would seek the extradition from France of a
suspected leader of the Basque separatist group ETA who authorities
say represented the rebels at failed peace talks with the
government last May. The suspect, Belen Gonzalez Penalva, wanted on
terrorism charges, was arrested in October, before the rebels ended
their 14-month-old cease-fire, blaming Madrid for undermining peace
prospects.
</P>
<P>
   THE AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   CANADA: QUEBEC VOTE RULES
</P>
<P>
   Seeking to set rules for any future separatist vote in Quebec,
Prime Minister Jean Chretien introduced a bill giving Parliament
the power to decide whether an independence question was clearly
worded, and, in the event of a separatist victory, whether the
margin was large enough to justify breaking up Canada. Separatist
forces almost won the last referendum, in 1995, in part, Chretien
has said, because the independence question was vaguely worded.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO: CRITICIZED ON RIGHTS
</P>
<P>
   A report criticized Mexico for paying only lip service to human
rights. Prominent politicians have blamed human rights defenders
for a nationwide crime wave, said the report, issued by Human
Rights Watch, and the government deserves special censure for
ignoring recommendations offered by the United Nations and other
international monitors.
</P>
<P>
   ARGENTINA: PRESIDENT SWORN IN
</P>
<P>
   Fernando de la Rua was inaugurated as the new president,
promising to lead a more transparent, austere government in an
effort to construct ``a new society based on ethics.'' The
62-year-old centrist implicitly criticized the outgoing president,
Carlos Saul Menem, for leaving a gaping deficit, adding, ``They
should have handed over power with the books in order.''
</P>
<P>
   ASIA
</P>
<P>
   MALAYSIA: MAHATHIR'S LAST LAP
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad, 73, re-elected last month after
18 years in office, said this would be his last term, ``although
there are who have been telling me that I should continue
forever.'' He said the key members of his Cabinet would retain
their posts.
</P>
<P>
   INDONESIA: RELEASE OF POLITICAL PRISONERS
</P>
<P>
   The government said it was freeing most of the political
prisoners still being held after the 32-year rule of former
President Suharto. They include East Timorese independence figures
and six men who were jailed because they belonged to a Communist
group.
</P>
<P>
   MIDDLE EAST
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL, SYRIA: DATE FOR TALKS
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration's Middle East negotiator, Dennis
Ross, said the talks between Syria and Israel would take place in
Washington next Wednesday and Thursday. The Israeli delegation will
be led by Prime Minister Ehud Barak, and the Syrian president,
Hafez al-Assad, will be represented by his foreign minister, Farouk
al-Shara, Ross said.
</P>
<P>
   PACIFIC
</P>
<P>
   NEW ZEALAND: PREMIER TAKES OFFICE
</P>
<P>
   Helen Clark, the leader of the Labor Party, was sworn in as
prime minister, leading a minority center-left coalition
government. The coalition includes the Green Party, whose policies
include the legalization of marijuana and the banning of
genetically engineered foods.
</P>
</TEXT>
