<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-UCLA-RUSH-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UCLA SUSPENDS FORWARD RUSH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ UCLA has suspended reserve forward JaRon Rush
indefinitely for a possible violation of NCAA rules, the school
announced Friday. It gave no timetable for Rush's return, but
indicated the situation probably will not violate its NCAA
probation.
</P>
<P>
   According to Rush's grandmother, Jeanette Jacobs, the situation
involves Rush's former summer-league coach, Myron Piggie, whom she
claims has been a bad influence on Rush and is one of the reasons
she encouraged Rush to leave his hometown of Kansas City, Mo., for
college.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is exactly why I wanted him in college in Los Angeles,''
Jacobs said. ``But the Piggie situation has followed him there.''
</P>
<P>
   Rush, a sophomore, was excused from several practices last month
to testify in a trial involving Piggie. That situation is related
to the possible NCAA infraction, said a source close to Rush.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA's basketball program is on NCAA probation until April 2001
for violations committed by former coach Jim Harrick.
</P>
<P>
   If a major infraction occurs during probation _ i.e.:
premeditated violations by coaches or the dreaded ``lack of
institutional control'' _ the Bruins could be subject to the death
penalty. However, UCLA athletic director Peter Dalis said Rush's
situation involves only himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it's that kind of thing,'' Dalis said when asked
about the death penalty. ``This has nothing to do with the team.
It's an individual matter regarding NCAA rules.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know for a fact no member of the coaching staff knew about
it. The coaching staff found out about it from me.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Pac-10 commissioner Tom Hansen: ``If the university did not
know about the student-athlete's activity, then that's not an
institutional problem and it doesn't involve the death penalty.''
</P>
<P>
   Dalis learned of the situation Thursday from a non-UCLA source.
He informed the Pacific-10 and the NCAA, then interviewed Rush for
30 minutes as part of an internal investigation. He indicated Rush
probably will miss a minimum of two games.
</P>
<P>
   ``It all depends on how lucky we get (with interviews),'' Dalis
said. ``If I decide to include the Pac-10, then I can't predict how
long it will go.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if the situation could threaten Rush's status with the
team, Dalis said: ``It's possible.''
</P>
<P>
   The Pac-10 and/or NCAA will join the investigation only if Dalis
needs help interviewing and fact-finding. At the conclusion of his
investigation, he'll forward the information to the Pac-10.
</P>
<P>
   Dalis described Rush as ``forthcoming but distraught'' during
the interview, which included UCLA faculty representative Donald
Morrison. Rush, who was not available for comment, will not
practice during the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   His absence _ combined with Matt Barnes' academic suspension _
leaves the Bruins with nine scholarship players and just three
frontliners: center Dan Gadzuric and power forwards Jerome Moiso
and Sean Farnham.
</P>
<P>
   Barnes, who failed a summer school class, is eligible to return
after fall-quarter exams (next week) if he passes four classes.
</P>
<P>
   ``His return is critical for our frontline depth,'' Bruins coach
Steve Lavin said.
</P>
<P>
   Sophomore guard Ray Young probably will absorb Rush's playing
time (19 minutes per game). Young missed several weeks with a
partially torn thumb ligament, but played well against Iona and
Morgan State.
</P>
<P>
   Rush, who hasn't started a game, is UCLA's fourth-leading scorer
(11.3 points) and second-leading rebounder (4.7).
</P>
<P>
   ``What we'll miss from a basketball standpoint is ... his
overall energy, aggressiveness and toughness,'' Lavin said. ``There
are more minutes to go around because we have a shorter bench and a
smaller rotation.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
