<SLUG> BC-KC-VICKY-BUSINESS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AREA WOMAN IS BEST-SELLING ARTIST IN DECORATIVE PRODUCTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JILIAN MINCER  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. -- When Vicky Howard was in third grade, her
teacher recognized her talent and encouraged her to become an
artist.
</P>
<P>
   Howard took that advice, and today the Overland Park, Kan.,
woman oversees a growing decorative-products business that
generates about $35 million in sales annually.
</P>
<P>
   Her artwork, known for its detail, rich colors and whimsy, now
appears around the world on a variety of products, including a
throw with a bird she designed, which hangs in her third-grade
teacher's living room in Arkansas City, Kan.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's one of the best-selling artists on gift and decorative
products today,'' said Rick Yearick, who with his wife is Howard's
licensing agent.
</P>
<P>
   Many of Howard's products can be found under her own label, the
Vicky Howard Collection.
</P>
<P>
   Howard's snowmen, Victorian-styled gardens and holiday scenes
appear on some of the nation's best-selling giftwraps, paper
products, throws and clothing.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's one of our top sellers for Christmas items,'' said Jeff
Roach, a senior designer for C.R. Gibson, which produces decorative
paper products.
</P>
<P>
   He said her work has been so well-received that the company has
made the unusual move of featuring her Christmas tableware design
for the third year in a row.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gives you a very warm feeling when you look at her art,''
he said. ``You can relate to it. It reminds you of your
childhood.''
</P>
<P>
   Howard, who has been creating her own products for about 13
years, gets the inspiration for her watercolor designs from
childhood memories, Victorian postcards and her own back yard. She
lives in Overland Park in a reproduction of a Victorian home that
was built at the turn of the century for an Olathe pharmacist.
</P>
<P>
   Howard often photographs the butterflies, flowers, birds and
wildlife in her wooded garden before spending hours painting them
with tiny brushes to capture every detail.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no shortage of ideas,'' she said. ``There is just a
shortage of time to get these designs on paper.''
</P>
<P>
   In painting the snowmen, flowers and birds that have become her
trademark, Howard applies the watercolors in layers to make the
colors more brilliant.
</P>
<P>
   When the paintings are complete, her husband, Rex Howard, an
artist and computer designer, scans them into their computer.
</P>
<P>
   The designs are then reproduced on products for companies,
including Creative Papers by C.R. Gibson, the Manual Woodworkers
and Weavers, and Dimensions craft designs.
</P>
<P>
   Howard soon will be launching a line of T-shirts and jewelry.
</P>
<P>
   ``She is one of our top five artists, and we have a worldwide
distribution,'' said Robin Nobling, licensing coordinator for
Manual Woodworkers and Weavers, which sells items including throws,
wall hangings, table runners and place mats. ``She's built up a
reputation through her style and images.''
</P>
<P>
   For the holidays, Howard especially enjoys painting traditional
themes such as snowmen, Santas and nature scenes. But she adds her
special touches, like robins wearing tiny scarves and earmuffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``You find a different way to do a snowman,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   One of her newest designs is of a snowwoman dressed in a green
hat, scarf, jacket and skirt, and carrying a basket with a
gingerbread man.
</P>
<P>
   After receiving a degree in fine arts at the University of
Kansas, Howard worked as a graphic designer and art director at an
advertising agency in Topeka.
</P>
<P>
   When her company relocated, she began to design her own line of
greeting cards, notepads and other products out of her Lenexa home.
</P>
<P>
   She recalled seeing the first popcorn tins she designed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anytime I would go into a popcorn shop, I would say, `That's
my artwork,' '' said Howard.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Art Makers International represents Howard's designs and
sells them to vendors who produce different products. Howard's work
appears in gift shops, department stores and catalogs.
</P>
<P>
   The designs come at an opportune time because of the boom in the
home-furnishing market.
</P>
<P>
   There's a trend toward cocooning, said Howard. As the pace of
life has become faster and more technological, people have
responded by making their homes more peaceful.
</P>
<P>
   ``They want to surround themselves with things that are
comfortable,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   When Howard isn't painting, she likes to visit small-town
antique stores, where she adds to her large collection.
</P>
<P>
   She smiles when she talks about her work and how much she loves
what she does.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do what I loved to do as a child,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
