<HEADLINE>
ASSAD'S ASSENT TO PEACE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The world has learned to be wary of pronouncements about a
breakthrough for peace in the Middle East. But if ever a true
turning point appeared to loom on the horizon, it was in the news
that Syria's brutal but prudent dictator, Hafez Assad, has told
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright and President Clinton that he
is ready to resume peace talks with Israel at the highest level.
</P>
<P>
   Assad himself will not be coming to Washington next week to meet
with Israel's Prime Minister Ehud Barak because his health does not
permit him to travel. All parties understand, however, that having
Assad's foreign minister, Farouk Sharaa, stand in for him at the
Washington rendezvous with Barak is tantamount to Assad being there
himself. Until this week the Syrian ruler had insisted on a formula
for negotiations that would entail negotiations by lower-level
``professionals'' and a meeting of the political leaders only after
a final peace treaty had been signed.
</P>
<P>
   Because Assad has acquired a well-deserved reputation for
knowing exactly what he wants, negotiating stubbornly to get it,
and then honoring agreed-upon red lines, his decision to accept the
offered conditions for a resumption of peace talks should be taken
seriously.
</P>
<P>
   He needs to negotiate a peace treaty now so the decks will be
cleared for his son, Bashar, to succeed him. Only Assad the elder,
with his impeccable Arab nationalist credentials, can make the
necessary compromises with Israel and also oblige Tehran to
tolerate a Syrian guarantee of Israeli security on its northern
border _ a commitment that will require disarming the
Iranian-backed Hezbollah guerrillas who operate in southern
Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   Assad also needs to act before the next American elections and
while Barak has a mandate to return captured Syrian territory. If
the shrewd master of Damascus seizes his opportunity, he will pass
to his successor a state at peace, one in the same American orbit
as Israel, Jordan, and Egypt. May the ailing tyrant have enough
time left to complete his historic pirouette.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
