<HEADLINE>
BUSH LEADS PRESIDENTIAL FUND-RAISERS IN MISSOURI, KANSAS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE KRASKE  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. -- Republican George W. Bush, who remains the
runaway fund-raising leader among all presidential candidates, is
way ahead in Missouri and Kansas, too.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas governor pulled in $932,210 from individual donors in
Missouri through Sept. 30, more than three times as much money as
the second-place fund-raiser.
</P>
<P>
   In Kansas, Bush was out front with $299,650, almost twice as
much as the runner-up.
</P>
<P>
   Coming in second in both states was Bill Bradley, a Democrat who
hails from Crystal City, Mo. Bradley can take consolation in
knowing that his totals far out-distanced his Democratic rival for
the nomination, Vice President Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley raised $306,700 in Missouri compared to Gore's $106,601.
In Kansas, Bradley raised $169,900 to Gore's $16,900.
</P>
<P>
   The figures, which cover individual donations of $200 or more,
were compiled by the Center for Responsive Politics, a nonpartisan
group that monitors the presidential money race.
</P>
<P>
   The figures represent money raised only in 1999. Contributions
from political committees that represent special interests were not
included.
</P>
<P>
   In the Kansas City area, Bush topped Bradley, but by a narrower
margin. Bush, the GOP front-runner, attracted $329,100 to Bradley's
$250,700. Gore came in third with $20,450.
</P>
<P>
   In the St. Louis area, where Bush's uncle, Bucky Bush, oversees
his statewide campaign, Bush raised the biggest portion of his
Missouri money: $596,610 to Bradley's $206,150. Gore was third with
$97,650.
</P>
<P>
   Bush ``has a lot of good connections in the state of Missouri,''
said Missouri GOP spokesman Daryl Duwe. ``He has family here.''
</P>
<P>
   Another advantage: One of Bush's chief fund-raisers, Jack
Oliver, worked for years on Missouri Sen. John Ashcroft's staff.
</P>
<P>
   Bush led in money-raising in the St. Joseph area with $13,750;
in Springfield with $76,750; in Columbia with $11,500; and in
Joplin with $15,750.
</P>
<P>
   The governor also led in each of Kansas' major metropolitan
areas. He pulled $59,700 out of Wichita; $16,250 from Topeka; and
$2,500 from Lawrence.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley spokesman Tony Wyche acknowledged that the former New
Jersey senator's close ties to Missouri helped. He said the
region's appreciation of blunt-speaking politicians such as Harry
S. Truman was another factor.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people of Missouri and Kansas like people who speak
plainly and directly about what they want to do,'' Wyche said.
``Whether they agree with (Bradley) on any specific issues, they
appreciate the candor and honesty they are getting from that
candidate.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley led Gore in every metropolitan area in the two states
except Springfield and Topeka.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Missouri nor Kansas ranked in the top five fund-raising
states for any of the nine presidential candidates. Bush, for
example, is drawing most of his individual money from his home
state of Texas, where he bankrolled $12.3 million.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley's top state was California where he brought in $3.3
million. Gore's leading state also was California, where he has
raised slightly more than $3 million.
</P>
<P>
   GOP hopeful Sen. John McCain looked to his home state of Arizona
for $927,300, his top total from any state.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
