A5852 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k BC-EDITORIAL-PARENTS-BOS     12-10 0739
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-PARENTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE PARENT TRAP 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, December 12, 1999)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   We're not Ozzie and Harriet, some folks will say, implying that
they've come a long way. But working parents are starved for the
kind of revolutionary progress that has turbocharged technology.
Parents face a Year 2000 economy hamstrung by decades-old
assumptions.
</P>
<P>
   It's simple arithmetic gone awry, according to the Alfred P.
Sloan Foundation. In the past, families had two jobs: Fathers did
paid work, and mothers did the unpaid work of caring for home,
children, and community. Today there are three jobs _ dad's paid
job, mom's paid job, and the work at home _ but still only two
parents.
</P>
<P>
   Where is the third pair of helping hands? Typically, mothers do
double duty on the home and work shifts. But the real problem, says
Kathleen E. Christensen, director of Sloan's Dual-Career
Middle-Class Working Families program, is that it can still be too
much work no matter who's doing it _ even if dads always rushed
home to make dinner and start the laundry.
</P>
<P>
   Searching for innovations, the failies program gave out $million
in grants this year. It is premature to outline a master plan, but
the Sloan Foundation is studying change in three areas: at work, in
the design of homes and communities, and in federal and state laws.
</P>
<P>
   Take the distinction between full- and part-time work. It's a
1930s concept, Christensen says, that we haven't gone much beyond.
As for the self-employment, it can help parents cope, but
employment laws dating back to the 1930s and '40s don't always
protect them. They lack safety, health, and pension safeguards, for
example.
</P>
<P>
   Sloan is also looking at how to devise architectural and
community plans that lighten the physical and emotional load of
housework.
</P>
<P>
   Shaking off the paradigms of the past, the Radcliffe Public
Policy Center used a Sloan grant to look at the biotechnology
industry. Its newly released study points to good news: Biotech
appears to offer women scientists more equitable opportunities than
other careers. But there are also missed opportunities. As in other
industries, job flexibility is often overlooked or remains a
benefit that savvy individuals negotiate for rather than a common
workplace option.
</P>
<P>
   Many other issues deserve attention:
</P>
<P>
   --Flexible schedules. It's an old idea struggling to fly.
Flexibility benefits parents of young children and older workers
who would rather work a reduced number of hours than retire.
Instead of being part-timers, workers could have annual contracts
that spell out the number of hours to be worked a year, allowing
for day-to-day variations.
</P>
<P>
   --Make sure policies trickle down through the ranks. Radcliffe's
study quotes a human resources director as saying: ``Onlyhe top 10
people in the company are allowed to work at home. Below that, it
is not permitted.''
</P>
<P>
   -Update assumptions about productivity. Earlier this year, a
Boston Bar Association report pointed out that ``merit is usually
couched in terms of legal skills, client responsiveness, commitment
to the firm, and teamwork, but at least three of those four
attributes are, from the perspective of associates and many
partners, correlated with long hours and sacrifices of personal and
family time.'' No home-by-sixers need apply.
</P>
<P>
   --Analyze _ and learn from _ different industries across the
country. In addition to biotech, Sloan-funded projects are looking
at Silicon Valley workers, teachers, medical and computer
professionals, and engineers.
</P>
<P>
   --Look at the bottom line. Studies should continue to consider
how family-work changes affect profit and productivity so companies
can see where their healthy self-interest overlaps with employees'
needs.
</P>
<P>
   --Innovate. Sixty years from now, paid maternity or day care for
sick children could seem as ordinary as the two-day weekend _ but
only if experiments are conducted and studied now.
</P>
<P>
   --Encourage community ties. From coaching soccer to singing in
choirs, working parents enrich their communities. As the Radcliffe
report points out, future studies of the biotech industry could
reveal how employers can better support ``a complex web of
community-based connections.''
</P>
<P>
   The case can't be overstated. Families await the benevolent
earthquake that will help the world of work make 21st-century
changes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
